   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EU-QUICKREACT (Paris) _ By deciding to equip itself to send up
to 60,000 troops to a crisis zone like Bosnia or Kosovo, the
European Union aims to become a strategic player on the world scene
that the United States and other countries will have to reckon
with. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL (Panama City, Panama) _ Preparations are underway
for the handover of the canal to Panama. But there are lingering
doubts here about whether the government, and Panamanians
themselves, can handle the responsibility. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Kavkaz Checkpoint, Russia) _ As elections near,
Russian politicians exploit a popular war. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT4) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-POLITICS (Zagreb) _ Many of those mourning Franjo
Tudjman say that although they loved their president, who died last
week, they will nevertheless vote for the opposition in upcoming
elections. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   LAGOS-URBAN-MIGRANTS (Lagos, Nigeria) _ Tens of thousands of
people live in the shadows of Lagos, Nigeria's biggest city,
squatting on bridgeless islands or, sometimes, on Lagos lagoon
itself inside huts built on stilts. If the ever widening ripples
from Lagos and other cities are changing the rhythm of traditional
rural life in Africa, the inhabitants of the lagoon must surely
rank among the most singular of urban migrants. By Norimitsu
Onishi.
</P>
