<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-CHARGERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGERS STUN SLUMPING SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Seahawks took another step backward Sunday in
their quest to become a playoff team, and another stumble in the
opposite direction from trying to look like one.
</P>
<P>
   When Todd Peterson's 38-yard field goal attempt doinked off the
left upright and dropped into the end zone with 70 seconds to play
at the Kingdome, the Seahawks had lost their third consecutive
game, a 19-16 decision to the San Diego Chargers, to see their
once-seemingly insurmountable three-game lead in the AFC West
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Chiefs pulled into a share of the division lead
with the Seahawks last night by beating the Minnesota Vikings,
31-28.
</P>
<P>
   That makes the rematch between the Seahawks and Chiefs at the
Kingdome on Dec. 26 even bigger. The winner of that game probably
wins the division, if the Seahawks can find a way to rediscover
their winning ways next week in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a thin line,'' coach Mike Holmgren said when asked the
difference between the Seahawks team that had won five consecutive
games and now has dropped three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very painful right now,'' he added. ``We can't seem to
catch a break we need to get us over the hump to win one of these
games. We have to roll up our sleeves. We have three games left.
... And it is hugely important.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to blame this loss on Peterson, who ran his
string of consecutive field goals to a club-record 15 by hitting
three in a row in the first half before missing three in a row in
the final 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were huge kicks,'' Peterson said of coming up short from
48 and 52 yards, then slapping what would have been a game-tying
kick off the upright. ``We needed to have those kicks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks also needed other things on this day when their
performance before another sold-out crowd was as dreary as the
weather.
</P>
<P>
   The defense too often was befuddled by the Chargers' no-huddle
offense, which created confusion and mismatches as Jim Harbaugh
completed 20 of 35 passes for 229 yards and was sacked only once.
</P>
<P>
   The offense again was more miss than hit, scoring just one
touchdown and blowing other opportunities as Jon Kitna misread the
Chargers coverage on a pass to Joey Galloway that was intercepted
at the San Diego 12-yard line and Galloway and Sean Dawkins could
not hold passes in the end zone after having their hands on them.
</P>
<P>
   That's the biggest problem with the Seahawks' slide from 8-2 and
a three-game division lead to being 8-5 and fit to be tied: It's
not one thing, it's everything. And in different weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the loss to Tampa Bay two weeks ago, Kitna turned the ball
over six times to waste the best effort of the season by the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   In the loss at Oakland last week, the defense was pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, it was missed field goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hope to make the playoffs at all this year, we want to
be on a roll when we go in,'' guard Brian Habib said. ``We were on
a roll there for five games and now we're struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   It begs the question: Does any team that gets swept by the
Chargers even deserve to go to the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps better yet: Can any team that has been swept by the
Chargers have enough confidence left to do what it will take to get
to the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been nowhere, we haven't done anything,''
cornerback Shawn Springs said, a reference to the Seahawks not
having had a winning season since 1990 to go with their
league-worst 10-year playoff drought. ``We don't know about success
or failure. We just play.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was there to be taken by the team that made plays at
the most opportune times. Again, the Chargers came out winners in
that matchup.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was John Carney, the Seahawks' perpetual pain in
the you-know-where. He kicked four field goals, including a
41-yarder that proved to be the game-winner with 3:19 left to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the kind of games we have been playing lately, he's just
invaluable,'' Chargers rookie coach Mike Riley said of his veteran
kicker. ``He proved how valuable he was today.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Junior Seau, the Chargers' whirling dervish of a
linebacker. In addition to finishing with nine solo tackles, he got
a hand on two Kitna passes. A completion on either one could have
provided a different ending to this game.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays before Peterson's last kick, Seau blitzed and rejected
a Kitna pass with enough force that it landed several yards behind
the line of scrimmage. Kitna was going to Dawkins, who was open ing
across the middle inside the Chargers 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior made a great play that last drive,'' Kitna said. ``We
had a touchdown. Sean could have walked into the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Seau also made another great play earlier in the quarter. Kitna
had running back Ricky Watters open over the middle on third-and-4.
The pass was there, as was the yardage needed for the first down.
But so was Seau, who reached in to flick the ball away. Peterson
then came up short on his 48-yard attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were trying to go one-on-one with me with my
injury,'' said Seau, who missed the Chargers' last game with a
strained abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, meanwhile, handed the credit where credit was due.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my gosh, what a big play on pass defense,'' Riley said of
Seau tipping away the pass to Watters, although he could just as
easily have been talking about the rejection of Kitna's pass. ``We
see him on the run defense all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks will be seeing Seau, too. In their nightmares.
Carney will be there. And Peterson. And those Kitna passes that
Galloway and Dawkins couldn't hold in the end zone. And that
no-huddle offense that stumped the Seahawks defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach was trying to dwell on the positive,'' linebacker Chad
Brown said when asked about Holmgren's demeanor after the game.
``Which is tough after dropping three games which you really feel
like you should have won.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
