<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR TIME TO BE SAME OLD SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Swept by the Chargers?
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, swept by the Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   (begin bold italic) Swept by the Chargers! (end bold italic)
</P>
<P>
   Neither English punctuation nor modern typography has sufficient
ordnance to convey the sporting embarrassment that was visited upon
the Seahawks Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Chargers were a broken, shamed outfit led by a
rookie coach who relied on plays never seen outside schoolyard
dirt. Losers of six of their last seven games, they went with a
no-huddle offense most of the game because, really, what was there
to discuss?
</P>
<P>
   These misfits beat the Seahawks 19-16 Sunday. They won in the
hostile Kingdome, in December, against a division leader. The day
was a Buster Douglas in cleats _ times two, no less, since in
October the Chargers won 13-10 in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The only way it could have been worse for the locals was if Ryan
Leaf had thrown a touchdown pass, slapped Mike Holmgren and walked
out on his bar tab at the Metropolitan Grill.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Seahawks must be credited with having a sense of the
times, since shame is the prevailing civic feeling this holiday
season in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``To beat the AFC West leader was not part of anyone's plan,
except ours,'' said Junior Seau, the Chargers linebacker who was
his usual aggravation to the Seahawks. ``It shows we haven't given
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking reward for not quitting, especially when one is paid
millions, is some sad coin in the modern realm of pro sports. But
Seau is right: The Chargers, who brought nothing to the game except
the look of a cheap doormat, played as if the game meant something
to them.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks, on the other hand, mysteriously failed to conjure
the wherewithal required for an NFL December game for a
playoff-bound franchise. It was team-wide: offense, defense,
special teams, coaching.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the Seahawks' worst game _ that was probably the first
meeting with the Chargers, when they lost under circumstances not
unlike Sunday. But Sunday was the worst time this season for
bonehead moments, since they came after two straight losses and
against an eminently beatable 10-point underdog at home.
</P>
<P>
   This should have been as easy as December games get for
contenders. Which removes it from the realm of the recent
on-any-given-Sunday defeats to adequate opposition in Tampa Bay and
Oakland. This was a defeat that gives body to the ghosts that
Holmgren has been so desperate to exorcise the last couple of
weeks:
</P>
<P>
   The same old Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   This was a defeat from the Tom Flores/Dennis Erickson tradition.
Not a blowout, not a butchery, just an absence of well-planned,
well-executed plays at a few critical junctures.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way that team should beat us,'' wide receiver Mike
Pritchard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way they're better than us.''
</P>
<P>
   Pritchard knew the Chargers could be had.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a feel for a team's attitude before a game,'' he said.
``They were real loose, they had nothing to lose. If we could get
up on them quickly ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Chargers, with no-huddle hustle and
desperate-looking wide-receiver screens, took the opening drive 73
yards for a touchdown. Instantly, what figured to be a revival game
for the Seahawks became a survival game.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Seahawks rallied to take a 16-13 lead into the
fourth quarter, they were never in command, never mustering the
authority that sparked their road wins in Kansas City and Green
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Although Todd Peterson's three missed field goals in the final
nine minutes were the obvious blunders, the Seahawks were so much
better and healthier than the Chargers that Peterson's sudden
whiffs shouldn't have been decisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you guys are blaming the kicker, but I
wouldn't,'' Pritchard said. ``To make the playoffs, you shouldn't
be worried about just making a field goal to get to overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't know by now what it takes to make the playoffs ...
well, that's the big question.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for the first time in Holmgren's initial season, there
is legitimate doubt that he and his staff have managed to convey
the requirements for contention.
</P>
<P>
   Heady as was the 8-2 start, no one, including Holmgren, didn't
figure the Seahawks were in for two or three more losses. But
suddenly losing three in a row, including Sunday's desultory
affair, leaves three hard games while injuries make each week more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the Seahawks look like the worst division leader
since the John Candy character in the movie ``Volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to spring a little realism when when we were 8-2
and feeling good about it,'' Holmgren said. ``But we're not there
yet. Now we're fighting for our (postseason) lives a little bit,
and learning a lot about each other and how we handle this
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   What was learned was not pleasant for Seahawks fans. After
witnessing a Chargers sweep, they learned the bandwagon they jumped
on a few weeks ago still hasn't cleared its axles of some
decade-old mud.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
