<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-RUSH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S RUSH IN NO HURRY TO GO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Suspended UCLA forward JaRon Rush is in good
spirits and has no plans to leave school unless forced to, his
grandmother said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's OK, and he wants to stay there,'' said Jeanette Jacobs,
who dined with Rush on Saturday night. ``He doesn't want to leave,
he doesn't want to transfer. He likes it there. He's staying until
it gets resolved, and (if Rush is declared ineligible), then we'll
deal with it. Otherwise, he's staying.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush, a sophomore from Kansas City, was suspended indefinitely
Friday for a possible violation of NCAA rules. UCLA athletic
director Peter Dalis said Rush's future at the school could be in
jeopardy, depending on the results of an internal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``JaRon doesn't know what's going to happen,'' Jacobs said.
``He's a good kid who does silly things. Hopefully, this will be a
learning experience.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two issues involved, according to sources: Rush's
relationship with his former AAU coach, Myron Piggie, and his
dealings with a Southern California sports agent with ties to
Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   If UCLA, the Pacific-10 or the NCAA determine Rush received
improper benefits from Piggie or the agent, Rush could be suspended
and forced to make restitution _ or he could be declared
ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   Rush missed several practices last month to testify about Piggie
before a grand jury in Kansas City, according to a source close to
Rush.
</P>
<P>
   His future might depend on how the NCAA interprets his
relationship with Piggie _ whether they had a pre-existing
relationship or whether it was a direct result of Rush's status as
a high-profile athlete, which would render improper any benefits
Piggie gave to Rush.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury is investigating Piggie on suspicion of income
tax evasion, fraud and money laundering, according to the Orange
County Register. Last week, an FBI representative informed Dalis
that Rush may have admitted to breaking NCAA rules during the
testimony, the paper reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 0023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
