<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7069 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-HOUSTON-DIMEL-HNS     12-13 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOUSTON-DIMEL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
So eager was Dana Dimel, the Houston Cougars' new football coach,
to dig into his upcoming job that he checked into his downtown
hotel, then returned to his future office Sunday night to watch
film of his future players.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dimel, who arrived Sunday afternoon via a UH private plane, will
be introduced today at a 3 p.m. news conference at the
Athletics/Alumni Center on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to throw the ball around and do our best to score
points,'' Dimel said in a brief meeting outside his future office
Sunday night, accompanied by his wife, Julie. ``I've already
watched some film on Jason McKinley (the Cougars' returning senior
quarterback) and his receivers, and I can't wait to start working
with them. We'll put Jason in the shotgun with a controlled passing
game and try to balance it with a strong running game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimel, 37, who already had visited the UH facilities, expects to
bring four or five assistants with him from Wyoming, where the
Cowboys were 23-12 in his only three years as a head coach. In
1997, he became at age 34 the youngest head coach of a Division I-A
program when Wyoming hired him to succeed Joe Tiller after Tiller
went to Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   The financial terms of Dimel's contract were not immediately
disclosed. His base salary at Wyoming was $110,000 with a total
package of about $250,000 a year, with two years remaining.
Estimates of his multiyear deal with UH range from $550,000 to
$650,000 annually, possibly higher depending on bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   In its past, Wyoming has lost several notable coaches who went
on to higher-level programs, including Bob Devaney (to Nebraska),
Bill Lewis (East Carolina and Georgia Tech), Dennis Erickson
(Washington State and Miami), Fred Akers (Texas) and Pat Dye
(Auburn).
</P>
<P>
   Dimel is a former offensive lineman at Kansas State who served
as an assistant there for 10 years, including the time when head
coach Bill Snyder rebuilt the program. He said Sunday night he will
hire quarterbacks coach Phil Davis of Nevada to be the Cougars'
offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ranked in the top three nationally in passing in each of
the last five years, and that's what we have in mind,'' Dimel said
of Nevada. ``We intend to play an exciting game to bring fans from
the city of Houston to our stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Manny Matsakis, Wyoming's offensive coordinator, is joining the
staff of new Texas Tech coach Mike Leach. Wyoming assistant head
coach Sheahon Zenger may be considered as Dimel's successor.
</P>
<P>
   Dimel, whose name was part of earlier speculation regarding
vacancies at Texas Tech and North Carolina State, noted Wyoming has
18 Texans on its roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can recruit Texas kids to Laramie, you should certainly
be able to recruit them to the University of Houston,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his first year in coaching as a Kansas State graduate
assistant in 1987, Dimel said, ``My first day of recruiting I spent
in Austin. I've recruited in San Antonio, Dallas-Fort Worth, Waco,
Killeen, all over the state. I think I have some pretty good ties
with Texas high school coaches, and they are going to be seeing a
lot of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Based in a state with a population of about 430,000, Dimel and
his Wyoming staff had to range far and wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my years of recruiting Texas, I had always aspired to be
the head coach of a school in this state,'' Dimel said in a
prepared statement. ``This has been a career goal of mine, and now
I have my chance. I know Houston is on the verge of being a great
football program once again, and there is no reason why we can't
keep great players in this state and city at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really fired up about this opportunity. I look forward to
bringing a high-powered and high-scoring offense to the fans of
Houston and in the process pack the stadium for our home games.
This is going to be a lot of fun for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming averaged 400 yards and nearly 30 points per game in
1999, finishing 7-4 and losing out on a share of the Mountain West
championship via a 39-7 loss to San Diego State in the final game.
Wyoming was 8-3 in 1998 and 8-5 in '97, when the Cowboys' defense
was second nationally in sacks, sixth in pass defense, 17th in
scoring defense and 23rd in total defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe our community will truly enjoy the incredible
enthusiasm Dana brings to Houston,'' UH athletic director Chet
Gladchuk said in a prepared statement. ``As a proven Division I-A
coach who has enjoyed unquestioned success at Wyoming and did a
remarkable job assisting in the building of Kansas State's program,
I believe we can expect to win at Houston, both in the classroom
and on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dana has a clear vision for the future of the program and an
intelligence for football that rivals some of the best coaches in
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Said UH chancellor/president Arthur K. Smith: ``Dana Dimel
brings extraordinary energy and an outstanding background of
football leadership and success to our program. He has exactly the
right blend of coaching skills, personal integrity and commitment
to the academic success of student-athletes that will carry Cougar
football to high national standing and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years as a graduate assistant at Kansas State, Dimel
was promoted to offensive line coach in 1989 when Snyder was hired
as head coach. Four years later, Dimel was put in charge of both
the running game and offensive line, then spent 1995 and '96 as
offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   While with the Wildcats, Dimel coached 11 offensive linemen who
went on to the NFL. Ten of his Wyoming players signed NFL
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   While Snyder is known for holding a tight rein over media
contacts, player interviews and accessibility, Dimel sounds like
the exact opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most cooperative coach, media-wise, I have ever dealt
with,'' said Kevin McKinney, Wyoming's sports information director,
who has been through 11 coaching changes. ``He would talk with
anybody at any time. He was always the same, win or lose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
