</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-EAGLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' OFFENSE SHOWS SIGNS OF LIFE IN VICTORY OVER EAGLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys made a statement Sunday for
the offensively challenged.
</P>
<P>
   In a 20-10 victory against the Philadelphia Eagles at Texas
Stadium, the Cowboys threw the ball downfield _ six pass plays of
16 or more yards _ and scored two offensive touchdowns in a game
for the first time in four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys managed to accomplish all this with Troy Aikman
playing while he had the flu and Emmitt Smith being sidelined after
the first play because of a groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   After the victory, a relatively reserved Cowboys locker room
showed no signs of back-slapping, chest-thumping or wild
predictions. The players obviously see the bigger picture.
</P>
<P>
   They probably have to win their division to make the playoffs,
and they don't control their destiny at this point. And they have
to do it without defensive end Greg Ellis, the team's sack leader,
who was lost for the season with a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   With three games remaining, the 7-6 Cowboys trail NFC East
Division-leading Washington (8-5) by one game and are tied with the
New York Giants. All three teams won Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   So what did Sunday's game mean to the Cowboys? Pretty much the
same to anyone who was asked.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Dave Campo: ``It means we've got a chance,
and that's all it means. It keeps us in the hunt. It's just one
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chan Gailey: ``We're on a mission. I think our guys
understand exactly where we are and what our mission is ... we're
glad to win, but we have more ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle Erik Williams: ``We're 1-0 so far in the
stretch drive. We need to win three more games ... and that's not
necessarily going to be easy since we haven't put together a
four-game winning streak since (November 1998).''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who finished with his most passing yardage (242) since
the 38-20 victory against Washington on Oct. 24, was still wearing
his football pants and a T-shirt when he turned his attention to
the New York Jets, the Cowboys' opponent next Sunday at Texas
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we've got to focus on beating the Jets,'' Aikman
said. ``We haven't put back-to-back victories together since the
third week of the season when we started out 3-0. The Jets ...
that's where my focus is.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Cowboys didn't put on a laser show Sunday, they did
take a lively step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Eagles are very aggressive, and so you have to try to
(counter) that somehow,'' Aikman said. ``We hoped to be able to
take some shots downfield. We watched film and saw that the teams
that moved the ball against Philadelphia were able to make some big
plays in the passing game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' six longest receptions went to Rocket Ismail (26
and 17 yards), tight end David LaFleur (25 yards), running back
Chris Warren (24 yards _ mostly on the run after the catch), wide
receiver Jason Tucker (19 yards) and tight end Eric Bjornson (16
yards).
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence in these guys,'' Aikman said of his
ever-changing cast of receivers. ``It's just a matter of getting
some playing time with them, and that's been hard to come by. We're
playing with a lot of different guys. We're just trying to go with
the guys who are healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we never seem to know, from one week to the next _
literally, from one series to the next _ who that's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   On defensive, the Cowboys kept rookie quarterback Donovan McNabb
corralled and eventually knocked him out of the game late in the
third quarter with a knee sprain.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys failed to score first for only the second time this
season. Also for the second consecutive week.
</P>
<P>
   After Cowboys newcomer Eddie Murray, who was 2-for-4 Sunday in
field-goal tries, missed a 49-yarder on the Cowboys' first
possession, the Eagles capitalized on the good field position to
drive 34 yards in nine plays before settling for a 44-yard Norm
Johnson field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who had scored only four offensive touchdowns in
their previous 18 quarters, responded by driving 60 yards in eight
plays, with Chris Warren scoring on a 4-yard burst behind Flozell
Adams and Solomon Page on the left side.
</P>
<P>
   Passes of 25 and 10 yards to LaFleur and fullback Robert Thomas,
respectively, set up the touchdown run by Warren, who was playing
with a bruised right leg. He finished with 92 yards on 25 carries,
both season highs.
</P>
<P>
   Passes of 26 and 16 yards to Ismail and Bjornson, respectively,
led to the Cowboys' second touchdown drive capped by an 8-yard pass
from Aikman to LaFleur that made the score 20-3 in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cowboys squandered a late first-quarter Darren Hambrick
interception of a McNabb pass and could get only three points after
being set up on a 24-yard Sean Landeta punt in the second quarter.
They added nine penalties for 55 yards to their NFL-leading totals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some costly penalties again that we have to
eliminate,'' Gailey said. ``And we still have to pass the ball more
consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   This could be defined as a start.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
