u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COLTS-BO     12-13 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COLTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS RUN OUT OF GAS AT INDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It was, for all intents and purposes, the last
lap at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' possibilities of making the playoffs became
minuscule Sunday following a 20-15 loss to the Colts in which they
held the high-powered Indianapolis offense to two touchdowns and
two field goals but struggled on offense in the red zone.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the stunned Patriots said the ``right things'' after the
game, others told it like it really was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one of the highest payrolls in the NFL,'' said New
England quarterback Drew Bledsoe, who completed 31 of 44 passes for
379 yards, with one touchdown and one interception. ``To need help
from other teams to get into the playoffs is unacceptable. I want
to apologize to Mr. Kraft because it's unacceptable. We're all
accountable for this.''
</P>
<P>
   The 7-6 Patriots could win out and not make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the last drive I really thought we were going to pull it
out,'' said tight end Ben Coates. ``We had enough time. We were
moving the ball. But we just couldn't get it done. That was the
case all day. On chances we had to score touchdowns, we scored
field goals. Our defense did a great job keeping us in it. It's
very frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustration? Offensive lineman Bruce Armstrong oozed it. He had
to come out of the game in the fourth quarter when he twisted his
left knee. He watched the Patriots march down the field near the
end of the game, but on fourth and 13 from the Indianapolis 31,
Bledsoe couldn't connect with Shawn Jefferson for the first down.
The game was over and the very loud RCA Dome crowd exploded as the
Patriots departed for the locker room in silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, when we need to make a play, we're not doing it,''
said Armstrong. ``We're practicing well, but once we get into the
game situation we're not scoring points. You like to think we can
get better, but right now we're stagnant. That's the worst part.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair or not, that will be blamed on coach Pete Carroll. Carroll
said he and the players ``felt sick'' after this one because they
could have won it. The Patriots outgained the Colts, 401 yards to
287. Bledsoe had 379 yards in the air to Peyton Manning's 186. But
the Patriots were a woeful 3 for 13 (23 percent) on third-down
opportunities to the Colts' 3 for 10.
</P>
<P>
   The defense kept the team in it despite cornerback Ty Law
playing with a broken hand, cornerback Steve Israel leaving early
with a sprained left ankle, and safety Chris Carter leaving in the
third quarter with a hamstring pull. On offense, running back Kevin
Faulk suffered a low ankle fracture on his right leg similar to the
one Terry Glenn had a year ago and will be lost for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood in this locker room is that of a team that hasn't
quit,'' said defensive tackle Chad Eaton. ``No way will we quit on
this season. We were all over them all day. We just didn't make the
plays when we had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Embattled offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese certainly tried.
He again came up with different looks, using the backs as dumpoff
receivers for Bledsoe, who still was sacked five times.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots shot themselves in the foot with 12 penalties for
85 yards. Twice Willie McGinest jumped offsides. On a key
third-quarter drive, on a fourth and goal from the 3, right tackle
Zefross Moss was called for a false start just before Bledsoe hit
Lamont Warren for a 3-yard TD that would have made it 20-13.
Instead Adam Vinatieri kicked a 26-yard field to make it 20-9. An
earlier false start had pushed the Patriots from the Colts 3 to the
8.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were moving again early in the fourth quarter as
Bledsoe nailed Glenn (nine catches, 148 yards) with a 35-yard
completion to the Colts 25. But Bledsoe was sacked by Chad Bratzke
for an 8-yard loss, then threw an interception to Tyrone Poole, who
had a monster game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Patriots weren't done. They marched 57 yards on six
plays, capping the drive with a 10-yard pass from Bledsoe to
Jefferson with 3:07 remaining in the third, making it 20-15. The
2-point attempt failed as Bledsoe threw it away.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots got a break with 2:10 remaining when the Colts were
running down the clock as Manning fumbled the snap. Lawyer Milloy
emerged from the pile with the ball at the Patriots 33. Two catches
by Troy Brown, one a beauty on which he leaped to snare the ball
between two defenders for a 28-yard gain to the Colts 27, gave the
Patriots a first down with 1:48 left.
</P>
<P>
   But from there the Colts tightened, forcing Bledsoe to run for 5
yards, then sacking him when Mike Peterson came untouched up the
middle. That forced the fourth and 13, and Bledsoe's overthrow to
Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts took a 7-0 lead on their first possession when Marvin
Harrison broke away from Law for a 52-yard gain to the Colts 20. An
offside penalty on McGinest hurt, and Manning eventually found
tight end Marcus Pollard, who lunged over the goal line on a 5-yard
pass with linebacker Ted Johnson tugging on his legs.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots countered when Vinatieri nailed a 34-yard field
goal. His 28-yarder with 5:39 left in the second made it 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the half, the Colts connected on two long passes to
Harrison, for 22 and 27 yards. That culminated in a TD on a 2-yard
shovel pass from Manning to Edgerrin James. Two third-quarter field
goals made it 20-6, Colts. But there was time.
</P>
<P>
   In another time, the Patriots would have overtaken their foe on
that final lap at Indy. But not this time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
