r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ANALYSIS-     12-13 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ANALYSIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGRESSIVE ATTITUDE REPLACES THE GAILEY GRIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys coach Chan Gailey promised
changes on offense.
</P>
<P>
   And he delivered in Sunday's 20-10 victory against the
Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Deion Sanders' contributions at wide receiver had an
impact on what seemed to be a breakout performance by the Cowboys'
offense, which reached the end zone only twice in the previous
three games but accounted for two touchdowns Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest difference for the Cowboys was in attitude.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the conservative, ``let's let the defense win it
for us'' group of recent weeks. Gailey's offense was bold and
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman, who completed 22 of 40 passes for 242
yards, took shots down the field and not to the flat. He threw the
ball past the first-down marker and not underneath. Aikman's passes
resulted in drive-extending first downs 12 times.
</P>
<P>
   Both Aikman and Gailey said the difference had a lot to do with
the Eagles' blitzing style of play. Teams have had success going
downfield against them all season. The Cowboys were no different.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were loading up to stop the run and blitzing secondary
people,'' Gailey said. ``That leaves the corners out there, and we
were able to get the ball down the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' new-found aggression was evident three plays into
the game, when Aikman aired one down the middle to Jason Tucker,
who had a step on Eagles cornerback Troy Vincent. The pass was
incomplete, but Vincent was called for pass interference.
</P>
<P>
   The play also demonstrated that Aikman was not going to be shy
about throwing to receivers other than Raghib Ismail, which was
imperative, considering injuries have continued to deplete the
receiver corps. Rookie Wane McGarity joined Michael Irvin and James
McKnight on the injured reserve list Thursday. And veteran Ernie
Mills missed his second consecutive game because of a strained
quadriceps.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Sanders' move to offense. It put first-year free
agent Tucker in the starting lineup for the first time. Chris
Brazzell, another first-year receiver who was signed from the
practice squad last week, played in a game for the first time. And
backup tight end Eric Bjornson saw time as a backup receiver.
</P>
<P>
   That the Eagles decided to double Ismail and Sanders as much as
they could made it even more crucial that Aikman spread it around.
Tucker and company rewarded Aikman's confidence by making plays.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail led the way with four receptions for 52 yards, but Aikman
completed passes to eight players. Tight end David LaFleur and
running back Chris Warren each caught four passes. Tucker caught
three. Bjornson, Sanders and fullback Robert Thomas caught two. And
Brazzell caught one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough because we've been relying on guys we haven't spent
a lot of time playing with,'' Aikman said. ``That's been the
biggest challenge for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Aikman, who came into the game battling the flu, was
up for the challenge against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a different group is on the field every week,''
Gailey said. ``He's done a good job adjusting to who is on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   One guy Aikman and Gailey want to see on the field more with the
regular offense is Sanders. He was in on 11 offensive snaps to go
along with the 72 snaps he played on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said that because the Eagles rolled coverages toward
Sanders, it opened up things in the running game and opened up the
middle for LaFleur.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman said he would like to expand what the Cowboys did with
Sanders, especially when he's on the field with Ismail.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
