<HEADER>
A7075 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     12-13 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUTION FLAGS WERE IGNORED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ One loud expletive boomed out of the corner of
the loser's locker room Sunday and then all was silent. Frankly,
there was nothing else to say.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but what has been said before about these New England
Patriots. Nothing but they aren't as good as they think they are
and they aren't as good as their fans hoped they'd be and tey
aren't anything special anymore in enough places to win against the
top teams.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but to point out once again that they aren't going
anywhere this year and if something big doesn't change they w't be
going anywhere but home for a while because their time is growing
short and their window of opportunity to do big things as a team is
closing fast.
</P>
<P>
   It closed a bit more Sunday after a 20-15 loss to the
Indianapolis Colts dropped their record to 7-6 and brought them one
step closer to elimination from playoff contention even though the
Buffalo Bills helped their cause by losing themselves. That is what
it has come to these days for the Patriots: The only chance they
have left is a mathematician's.
</P>
<P>
   How can that be on a day when they held the powerful Colts
offense to two touchdowns and two field goals and outgained them by
more than 100 yards?
</P>
<P>
   How can they score only one touchdown when they average 5.8
yards a play and quarterback Drew Bledsoe goes 31 for 44 for 379
yards and is incredibly enough the team's No. 2 rusher as well,
averaging 4.5 yards on four scrambles?
</P>
<P>
   How can that be when they are paid tons of money at so many
positions by an owner who has paid the price and then some, and has
had to look out on the field and too often see his players
scrambling around at the last instant like ants in a maze before
the ball is snapped as if they have no clue what is expected of
them?
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Patriots made enough stupid mistakes to beat
themselves twice. They committed a dozen penalties, including one
in the third quarter that took 7 points off the board when a
touchdown pass to Lamont Warren was called back because Zefross
Moss couldn't keep himself from flinching on the snap count. When
you are having the trouble New England is scoring, you can't afford
to take points down once they've beenput up because chances are
they won't return . . . which they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   You have a first down at the Colt 27 with 88 seconds to play in
a 5-point game. You would seem to be in good shape until your
receivers all wander downfield aimlessly on first down and none get
close to open. In a situation where there is no room for waste, you
waste a play.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, on third and 5 at the 22, you are outguessed by
the Colts' defense and do not have enough blockers in to keep out
the extra blitzer and Bledsoe is nailed for an 8-yard loss. You
wasted a second play.
</P>
<P>
   Two wasted plays out of three and then what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it's fourth down and forever,'' Bledsoe said. He didn't
have to point out that forever never came.
</P>
<P>
   No one should blame Ernie Zampese for this. New England's
offensive coordinator called a sharp game that got Terry Glenn free
numerous times for big gains and kept the ball moving all
afternoon. Zampese called plays that produced gains of 52, 35, 28,
and 21 yards. He called plays that produced 401 yards of total
offense. He called plays that put his team in first-down situations
on the Colt 3, 8, 10, 11, and 17. Out of those opportunities the
Patriots scored one touchdown, so stop blaming the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme is moving the ball. It's the players who are moving
the ball backward by their consistent inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've wasted so many opportunities all season,'' tired and
hurting left tackle Bruce Armstrong said. ``Eventually you run out
of opportunities. You can only go to the well so many times. We all
know that.''
</P>
<P>
   This group has been going to the well since the second year Bill
Parcells was here and the well is running dry. It has been four
years now since their Super Bowl run of 1996 nd each year they have
produced just a little less than the previous season.
</P>
<P>
   One point from the AFC Championship Game in 1997. One game and
out of the playoffs in 1998. Probably one game short of making the
playoffs in 1999. Down, down, down. Slowly but steadily. The same
way they lost the game Sunday. Slowly but steadily.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the defense is tiring of the offense's
ineptitude at theonly thing that counts _ scoring points. Sunday
that defense righted itself after some early problems and held the
Colts down, allowing only two field goals in the second half while
recovering a critical fumble two plays after the Patriots finally
scored a touchdown with 2:11 to play to cut the lead to 5.
</P>
<P>
   That recovery by Lawyer Milloy of Peyton Manning's mishandled
snap might have been a turning point in other years. It was the
kind of opportunity Bledsoe craved, and he got it, but he got no
more points because his teammates didn't get open when he needed
them to and got him sacked when he needed them not to.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean Bledsoe is blameless in the dissolution of
the team's offense. At times he has been way off rhythm. But that
was not the case Sunday. Sunday it was others who exhibited the
rhythm of Don Knotts at a disco and the result was predictable.
Just enough mistakes to get beat.
</P>
<P>
   When you do that often enough, as this collection of players has
all season against good teams, it is no longer an accident.
</P>
<P>
   It's who they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can do is give them as many chances as possible,''
Milloy would say carefully after he had seen his team's offense
come up short once again. ``We did that. nthe end, we had a chance
to win the game. That's all we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it's all these Patriots seem able to do, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
