<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX MAKE PUSH 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-OS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Red Sox made a major push Sunday at the
winter meetings to acquire a middle-of-the-lineup hitter in a
proposed trade with Houston for switch-hitting center fielder arl
Evertt. According to sources, the deal was contingent on Boston
general manager Dan Duquette agreeing with Everett's agent on a
contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were prepared to accept the Red Sox' offer of
shortstop prospect Adam Everett (no relation) and a pitching
prospect from the lower minors in exchange for Everett, who had the
best season of his career last season, when he batted .325 with 25
home runs and 108 RBIs in 123 games.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who was paid $2.4 million last season, is in position
to double that amount in arbitration this winter, but more
important to the Sox is the fact that he is eligible for free
agency after the 2000 season. Duquette, according to sources, has
had conversations with Everett's agent, Larry Reynolds. Also, any
long-term financial commitment would undoubtedly require CEO John
Harrington to sign off on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   There also was some question whether Harrington might be
reluctant to OK a deal because of a situation involving Everett
when he was with the Mets in 1997. In August of that year,
Everett's two children were taken into custody by New York City
officials after a Shea Stadium child-care worker noticed bruises on
his 6-year-old daughter, Shawna. Charges of child abuse
subsequently were dropped by a Family Court judge, who ruled tha
Everett's wife, Linda, inflicted ``excessive corporal punishment''
on their children and the player did little to op her.
</P>
<P>
   In a later court ruling, the couple, who underwent counseling,
regained custody of their son but lost custody of their daughter.
The Mets traded Everett after the '97 season to Houston for
reliever John Hudek, and in his two seasons with the Astros, he has
been regarded as a model citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who has a strong arm, also can play right field. He had
10 assists from center field last season; Sox center fielder Darren
Lewis had one. Picking up Everett would seem to leave the Sox in a
position of needing to move an outfielder. Lewis has $5.1 million
remaining on a contract that carries him through the 2001 season
and has given the Sox Gold Glove-caliber defense. Rookie Trot Nixon
platooned last season in right, and the Sox after the season picked
up Jermaine Allensworth, who was expected to compete with Michael
Coleman to be Damon Buford's replacement in a platoon with Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   In a media briefing late Sunday, Duquette made no reference to
his talks with Houston. Meanwhile, Astros officials, who had met
with Duquette early Sunday morning, were waiting to hear back from
the Sox GM n Everett. Houston has a surplus of outfielders. Moises
Alou has a no-trade clause, Richard Hidalgo is their star of the
future, and teams have little interest in Derek Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Having just signed Craig Biggio to a long-term extension and
facing free agency with slugger Jeff Bagwell, the Astros need to
move some salary. If the Sox did not move on the deal, Houston was
prepared to talk with other clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Duquee insisted the Sox' priority remained adding
pitching. As of early Sunday &UR;  &LR; night Boston had not made an offer
for lefthanded free agent Chuck Finley, who had received three-year
proposals from three teams, the Mariners, Indians, and Orioles. All
of those offers were believed to be in the $22 million to $23
million range. Finley's agent, Tim Shannon, said that no team had
yet met the salary the 37-year-old would like.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette was vague about whether the Sox would make a proposal,
saying the team is also looking at other free agent possibilities
as well as trades. Talks with San Diego about lefthander Sterling
Hitchcock did not seem to be progressing.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had talked to the Dodgers about righthander Ismael
Valdes, who Sunday was traded along with second baseman Eric Young
to the Cubs for reliever Terry Adams in what Dodgers GM Kevin
Malone acknowledged was a salary dump. Duquette said the Dodgers
had had interest in Boston talent, but the Cubs' willingness to
take both Valdes and Young, who had played for new Cubs manager Don
Baylor in Colorado, was a dealmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets Saturday night signed Todd Zeile, who's topped 90 RBIs
in each of the last four seasons, as a replacement at first base
for John Olerud, even though Zeile has played just 76 games at
first in his major league career.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, word of a proposed four-team trade, a
throwback to the days when deals were much less money-driven than
they are now, circulated. Montreal would trade catcher Chris Widger
to the Brewers. Milwaukee would deal third baseman Jeff Cirillo to
the Rockies. Colorado would ship third baseman Vinny Castilla t the
Devil Rays, and Tampa Bay would send pitcher Rolando Arrojo to the
Expos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
