<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG AMERICA KNOCKS SELF OUT OF CUP SEMIS 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For whatever sports analogies are worth, it might be said that
this weekend was as dismal for the Young America sailing team of
the New York Yacht Club as it was for the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Each team saw its hopes for playoff competition fade to black in
an afternoon that capped a season of sputtering performances. For
the Patriots, the executioner was the Colts, although the seeds of
destruction have been in their own hands all season.
</P>
<P>
   Same with Young America, which was mathematically eliminated
from the semifinals Sunsday when Dawn Riley opted not to sail
America True against France's LeDefi BTT, thus handing the French
the 9 points they needed to sew up sixth place in semifinals that
begin in early January.
</P>
<P>
   And the analogy goes deeper. Both the Patriots and Young America
started the season as highly touted, top-rated teams. Both were
expected to go deep into the elimination rounds and possibly end up
in the ultimate showdown _ Super Bowl for the Patriots, and the
America's Cup finals for Young America.
</P>
<P>
   Each team began the season with good records _ 6-2 for the
Patriots, 8-2 for Young America _ before taking dazzling and
inexplicable noedives in midseason.
</P>
<P>
   The many critics of Riley's America True and perhaps even Paul
Cayard's AmericaOne (which was also accused of throwing a race to
the French Saturday) will argue that the end was unsportsmanlike,
that the two US rivals from San Francisco should have played out
the series and given Young America its fair shot at making the
semis.
</P>
<P>
   But again, like the Patriots, Young America blew so many
opportunities to save itself that in the end it's hard to see them
as victims. Merely, and very surprisingly, as losers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking a lot about it,'' said Young America
president John Marshall by phone from Auckland Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, ``and
the obvious question to me is how could a team with so much
potential fall so short? It's hard to find a single factor. But the
program as a whole undererformed and we couldn't put the brakes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we look at races lost, they were lost for a variety of
reasons _ some trivial mechanical breakdowns, several attributable
to the massive failure of US 53 (the first boat that broke up),
some due to simply being on the wrong side of windshifts, and at
least one race lost through a serious tactical mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is one single answer, Marshall goes back to a decision
to start construction of the two boats about three months later
than planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope was we could turn that time into significant
differences in boat speed,'' said Marshall. ``But the price we paid
was the opportunity to sail in Newport in 1999 (with the new
boats). We might have had two or three months of sailing if we had
not made that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall believes the Young America program suffered fm not
having enough sailing time. ``We never gave the sailing team enough
time on the water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to predict the first-leg windshifts _ a critical
moment in most races _ never developed well enough in his
afterguard, Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the things you need to do to race well began to fall
apart as we dealt with more and more days lost to sailing because
of weather or because of breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, we just weren't sailing well enough or
fast enough to make the cut. That's my best perception.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the cataclysmic moment in Young America's campaign
came just over a month ago when the first hull, US 53, cracked in
half and nearly sank. Moving quickly into their newer boat, hull
58, skipper Ed Baird and his team never quite got their sailing
smoothed out.
</P>
<P>
   Then, early in round-robin 3, leading Italy's Prada late in the
race, Baird made a major tactical error of not covering a trailing
boat, and let Prada through for the win. Had it been a victory, the
series might have been different.
</P>
<P>
   After that, a combination of shifty winds and choosing the wrong
side of windshifts doomed the campaign, which is headquartered in
Portland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   As Young America emerged as one of the preseason favorites, much
talk centered around the possibility of the America's Cup returning
to the waters of Newport.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat of Young America is hauntingly similar to the New
York Yacht Club's last campaign to get the Cup back from the
Australians in 1987. With a well-heeled team in Fremantle, two
hulls, and a seemingly top sailing team under skipper Jo Kolius,
the effort failed to make the four-boat semifinals. Their nemesis
13 years ago: France's Frnch Kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the last-ditch desperation measurfor Young America on
Saturday was to deliver a palate-load of Sam Adams beer by forklift
to Riley's America True compound. ``That diplomacy,'' said Marshall
with a chuckle, ``did not seem to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley's explanation for not racing the French Sunday is that
with just one boat, America True did not want to risk it in a
nonessential race, especially one held in rough weather.
</P>
<P>
   So the top six boats entering the semifinals are Prada, America
True (Cayard), AmericaOne (Riley), Nippon, Stars &AMP; Stripes (Dennis
Conner), and Le Defi Francais.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 0103EST &QL; 
