<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7080 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     12-13 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
YOU pause to admire the speed and dispatch of Chet Gladchuk, the
University of Houston athletic director, who has just hired his
second head football coach in four days.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Marshall's Bob Pruett handed the Cougars a lemon, giving
back on Friday a job he had accepted Thursday, Chet went to Wyoming
for his lemonade. He hired Dana Dimel to replace the reluctant
Pruett, the original first choice to succeed Kim Helton, who was
cashiered 21 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars announced their new man Sunday and will present him
to a curious public today at 3 p.m. In moving briskly through a
process fraught with risk, the Cougars seemed to take their motto
from the submarine service: Run silent, run deep. In doing so, they
kept to a minimum any stigma from being jilted by Pruett.
</P>
<P>
   For a fellow who did not have a losing season in his three years
at Wyoming, Dimel is something of a blank page. His name never
surfaced as a candidate at Houston, although clearly he was near
the top of Gladchuk's list. He had been mentioned in connection
with the vacancies at Texas Tech and North Carolina State but
didn't interview for either position.
</P>
<P>
   So quickly did recent events unwind and reopen that Dimel was on
the road recruiting for Wyoming until a day or so before he
committed to the Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   At 37, blond and burly, he spent 10 seasons as an assistant
coach at Kansas State, his alma mater, the last two as Bill
Snyder's offensive coordinator. The Wildcats finished with records
of 10-2 in 1995 and 9-3 in '96, and Dimel began to attract notice
outside the Big 12. Wyoming came calling, and he rewarded the
Cowboys with 23 wins against 12 losses, sending 10 of his players
to the NFL from his first two squads.
</P>
<P>
   He was Wyoming's 28th head coach, reflecting the school's status
as a steppingstone for those with higher ambitions, including Bob
Devaney, Dennis Erickson, Fred Akers and Joe Tiller.
</P>
<P>
   In your everyday study of the coaching science, you realize the
Cougars still lack the experience in this area of Wyoming, LSU or
Notre Dame. Dimel will be introduced Monday as the school's ninth
and youngest head coach, counting only those who actually signed a
contract.
</P>
<P>
   But he brings to the task an interesting personal history. He
was an offensive lineman who won awards as a weightlifter,
suggesting he isn't someone the players can push around. He and his
wife, Julie, have a 4-year-old son, Winston, who was born on
Dimel's birthday, Oct. 9. This may indicate nice timing, a sense of
order or a harmless coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   There will be plenty of time in the weeks and months to come to
probe the personality of Dana Dimel. If he doesn't have one,
Cougars fans can overlook it if he continues to enhance his
reputation as a winner. He certainly hasn't known much adversity in
his coaching career, although the Houston job has in the past
filled any shortages in this area.
</P>
<P>
   The line began with hometown products Jewell Wallace and Clyde
Lee, men of quiet dignity who got the program off the ground. Bill
Meek and Hal Lahar were the first two coaches hired away from other
schools; Lahar had played under Bud Wilkinson at Oklahoma and made
his ``name'' at Colgate. Bill Yeoman had a 25-year run that saw the
Cougars achieve national recognition, and he brought with him a
load of enthusiasm and invention.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Pardee, who had been an All-America fullback under Bear
Bryant at Texas A&AMP;M and an All-Pro linebacker, was a modest,
soft-spoken type who had been the NFL's Coach of the Year with the
Bears. He finished his NFL career with the Oilers, as many coaches
did. John Jenkins coached the run-and-shoot offense under Pardee,
helped turn Andre Ware into a Heisman Trophy winner and instilled a
sense of abandon and fun in the team before he ran afoul of the
NCAA sleuths.
</P>
<P>
   Helton was a gruff, grizzled veteran of both the college and pro
games, and his honesty won him the loyalty of those who knew him.
But winning games, not friends, was the bottom line. It still is,
which brings us back to Dana Dimel, who is not without Texas roots.
</P>
<P>
   His coach his junior year at Kansas State was Jimmy Dickey, a
former Cougars quarterback and assistant coach and a high school
legend at Galena Park. When Dickey was fired, Dana finished the
season under Lee Moon, who later, as the athletic director at
Wyoming, gave him his first head coaching chance.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Cougars hope he will turn out teams that produce
offensive fireworks, he brought to Wyoming a swarming defense that
ranked second in the nation in sacks in 1997 and sixth against the
pass.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's announcement, out of the office of UH chancellor
Arthur K. Smith, it was noted that the '99 Cowboys beat two
bowl-bound teams, Utah and Brigham Young, back-to-back. Dimel's
record also includes wins over Rice, SMU and TCU.
</P>
<P>
   One conclusion we can already draw about Dimel is that he moves
fast. He had already hired an offensive coordinator Sunday, Phil
Davis, from Nevada. He had lost his guy to the new staff at Texas
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Football historians would probably point out that Dimel is the
first football coach named Dana to work in this state since Dana X.
Bible was building a national power at Texas (and who had won big
earlier at Nebraska and Texas A&AMP;M). This could be a good omen, and
the Cougars will take all they can get.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
