<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNS'S MIND RUNNING ON BRUINS SOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pat Burns was up to 50 minutes on the treadmill Sunday
when it first occurred to him he was tired. The Bruins' coach was
so distracted by his team's six-game winless streak (0-3-3) that he
hadn't been monitoring his workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually run about 35 or 40 minutes and all of a sudden I
realized I'd been running for 50 minutes,'' said Burns after his
club's skate at the FleetCenter. ``I was lost in thought about
things to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he's not panicking and he doesn't want his team to
panic. But with four games this week, beginning Monday night with
the Phoenix Coyotes, it's not going to get any easier.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's loss to the Red Wings, Burns said he needs more
from his top players _ namely Jason Allison _ and other players
have approached the coach about doing more on their own, including
goalie Byron Dafoe and right wing Joe Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he thinks part of the problem might be that players
are focused on individual goals rather than team ones. The club
plays its 30th game Sunday night, which means more than a third of
the season is over, and Burns said that at this time of year, some
players start doing the math to figure out where they'll be come
season's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a coach's nightmare to have that,'' he said. ``When I
first came into the league there was none of that. You're trying to
get a team ensmble going and all of sudden one guy goes, `I've got
to get going, I've got a big bonus for 20 goals or 30goals.' All of
a sudden things change. I think it's become a part of the game that
coaches have no control over. It's not management's fault. They
have them up against the wall. I hate the whole structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said one player he really needs going is Allison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned about his game,'' said the coach. ``I've
never seen him play like this. I've never seen the falling and
trying to draw penalties and the lack of fight. That concerns me a
lot. I've talked to him, I've done a lot of things with him. Sooner
or later, it's got to come from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Since returning from a wrist/forearm injury that caused him to
miss two games early last month, Allison has four goals and nine
points in 14 games. His linemate, Dave Andreychuk, after scoring 13
goals in 17 games, has two goals and four points in his last 12
games.
</P>
<P>
   Allison sounded frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going as good as I can, I know that,'' he said. ``I
don't think that's why we're not winning. We haven't played well.
If I don't play well and the team plays well, we still win,
although it helps, obviously, if I'm playing good.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said his inability to take faceoffs because of his
injury has resulted in reduced ice time and in turn has reduced his
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a couple the other night because (Andreychuk) got
kicked out and I felt fine, but other things I can't do still, so I
don't know if I should be pushing to do that when I can't do other
simple things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he thought Allison wasn't playing with his usual
confidence and Allison agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of things _ being hurt a little bi and not
having my confidence and (seeing) a little less ice,'' he said.
``Since I've been back, I'l be sitting on the bench thinking, `Am I
going to get out now?' That's part of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he thinks Burns has less confidence in him now,
Allison nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' he said, ``and maybe deservedly so. Even when I
think I'm playing good and skating good, as a line we're not doing
nothing. I don't think we have too many even-strength goals in the
last 10 games and it's not just our line. I haven't had the
confidence myself, the team hasn't been playing as well, and maybe
him having a lack of confidence in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Dafoe was making heroic saves in the first period
until his teammates found their game. So far this year, Dafoe isn't
playing badly, but the team is giving up early goals and having to
battle back from deficits it didn't face a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say there aren't a lot of goals that have gone
in that have been bad goals,'' Dafoe said, ``but I look at last
year and I was making a lot of the big saves early to keep us in
the game until we got going. We were notorious last year for
starting slow, as we are this year. The difference is (other teams
are) scoring this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
