<HEADLINE>
RELAXED EDDIE MURRAY GLAD TO BE KICKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ At 43, playing football is still better than
talking about it. Kicker Eddie Murray left his job as sideline
reporter for the Detroit Lions radio broadcast team to rejoin the
Dallas Cowboys last week and in his first game in almost two
seasons made field goals from 30 and 34 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really pleasantly surprised with my emotions,'' Murray
said after his 2-for-4 performance Sunday in the Cowboys' 20-10
victory against the Philadelphia Eagles. ``I thought I would be a
lot more nervous. I was anxious during the week. It felt like this
game would never get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Murray, his first game since the 1997 season
didn't come down to a field goal. He barely missed his first
attempt, a 50-yarder that bounced off the right upright. He also
missed wide right on a 33-yarder, but connected on two
second-quarter field goals to give the Cowboys a 13-3 halftime
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed with the short one,'' he said. ``I fully
expect to kick much better. I felt I had a good rhythm going. It's
a timing factor. I am a little off.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite missing twice, Murray has a renewed faith in the kicking
game, coach Chan Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, he kicked the ball solid,'' Gailey said. ``Like
everyone else, he needs to get out there and play.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
