<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS, DEFENSE WORTH SHOUTING ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The Patriots found out Sunday what all the
``noise'' is all about in Indianapolis, and they couldn't deal with
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were back on their heels most of the day,'' said Colts
defensive end Chad Bratzke, who had a monster game. ``There were
times at the end of the game that the crowd was the loudest I've
ever heard it in here. And it helped a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The raucous, or was it ``rock us,'' crowd in the RCA Dome
cowered the Patriots' offensive line so badly it took New England
right out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some stats for New England's offensive line:
</P>
<P>
   Six false start penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Two ineligible men downfield penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Five sacks allowed.
</P>
<P>
   And, at the minimum, another five hurries on quarterback Drew
Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd had a big impact,'' said Colts general manager Bill
Polian. ``The noise bothered the New England offense. You could see
it, and it helped our defense at the same time. That was the best
job our defensive front has done coming off the ball all year, and
our crowd had something to do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, coming to play in the dome was like a vacation. The
Colts weren't very good, the games didn't sell out, and the crowd
didn't seem to care what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year is the first time we got the crowd to where it is a
homefield advantage,'' Polian said. ``It didn't start out that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``After our first home game this year, I called our marketing
people in and said, `Listen, we've got to do a better job of
getting our crowd into the game. Put those signs up on the
scoreboard. Let them know that they are supposed to be quiet when
we come to the line on offense, and noisy as hell when the other
team gets over the ball.' We've finally got it right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots played an excellent game on defense. This was only
the third time in 13 games that the Indianapolis offense has been
held to 20 points or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played us tough,'' said Colts quarterback Peyton Manning.
``They did some nice things against us with their defense. They
kept changing it up. And we had to keep adjusting. In the first
half we made some big plays to get us those two touchdowns, but the
second half, we missed some key plays that stopped drives, and we
had to take field goals. Their defense played very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts were much better on the line of scrimmage than the
Patriots. Indianapolis consistently got pressure on Bledsoe rushing
four men, and didn't blitz as often as it normally does.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to cover them more today rather than bringing
pressure,'' said Colts defensive coordinator Vic Fangio. ``We
wanted to keep everything in front of our defensive backs. We
didn't want to let Bledsoe beat us deep. We gave up a lot of yards,
but we did the job near the goal line and kept them out of the end
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had no running game whatsoever. The Colts shut that
down early, and concentrated on getting to Bledsoe after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got up on them we knew they weren't going to hurt us
anymore on the run,'' said Polian. ``Bratzke made a couple of great
plays against the run. Terry Allen looked like he was going to
break it for some yardage a couple of times in important
situations, and Bratzke closed right down the line of scrimmage to
make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were out of it until the Colts made their only
turnover in the game, when they appeared to have everything under
control. ``My guard was pulling out and he knocked the ball out of
my hand,'' said Manning, explaining the fumble, recovered by Lawyer
Milloy, that gave the Patriots the ball in the final two minutes,
trailing just 20-15, with a chance to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to suck it up right there,'' said Colts coach Jim Mora,
``and our guys handled it on defense. We had some adversity, and we
overcame it.''
</P>
<P>
   The key play in the game, and the Patriots' season to date, came
with 1:17 left. The Colts had the 5-point lead, but the Patriots
had the ball at the Indianapolis 22, third and 5.
</P>
<P>
   Fangio called a blitz, with Mike Peterson coming up the middle
to sack Bledsoe, forcing a fourth and 13 on which Bledsoe had no
chance the way he was pressured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ellis Johnson made the big play on that blitz,'' said Bratzke.
``He tied up two of their offensive linemen inside and the guy that
was supposed to block our blitzer couldn't block (Peterson) and he
came free to make the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the play, the crowd was the loudest ever. They sensed what
was at stake. Bledsoe was in the shotgun. They had a silent count.
He couldn't try to call the signals because it was so loud his
linemen wouldn't have heard him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were keying on the center. We watched Bledsoe lift his leg
to tell the center to snap it, so we knew when he put his head down
to look between his legs, he was going to snap it. The offensive
linemen were back on their heels, and we had a great chance to get
off with the snap.''
</P>
<P>
   Another critical point came in the third period, with the Colts
leading, 20-6, and the Patriots on the Indianapolis 1, with third
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used a defense on that play that we hadn't used all year,''
said Fangio. ``We noticed in their films that they had a play on
the goal line that they had run with success, something similar to
what our offense does. We changed up a little, and had our
defensive linemen pinch down toward the middle, and when it
happened, Allen couldn't go off tackle (where the play was supposed
to go) and we had the stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had to settle for a field goal, a 4-point swing,
and ended up with a loss, even with Bledsoe throwing for 172 yards
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 0122EST &QL; 
