<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-EAGLES-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
INJURY TO McNABB THROWS SCARE INTO EAGLES 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The present is ugly for the Philadelphia Eagles,
which is why it was so disturbing for them to see their future
limping off the field Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the third quarter of the Eagles' 20-10 loss to the
Dallas Cowboys at Texas Stadium, Cowboys defensive tackle Leon Lett
timed the snap, leaped over Eagles center Steve Everitt and slammed
into rookie quarterback Donovan McNabb. McNabb fumbled and Dallas'
Brandon Noble recovered, but more importantly, Philadelphia's top
draft choice and quarterback of the future was knocked out of
action with a sprained left medial collateral ligament.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb, who made his fifth consecutive start since replacing
Doug Pederson, is scheduled for a magnetic resonance imaging test
today to determine the extent of his injury. But he was encouraged
by the fact he was able to walk and predicted a return for next
Sunday's game against New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very anxious to get back out there,'' McNabb said. ``We
were starting to get things going on offense, starting to get some
chemistry in our passing game and our running game. It was going
the right way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it looks like it's nothing serious. I'm trying to
stay positive and focus on the best, and that means being out there
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb said he told coach Andy Reid he wanted to stay in the
game, but Reid vetoed that idea and finished the game with
Pederson. Pederson had better statistics than McNabb, completing 8
of 12 passes for 108 yards with one touchdown and no interceptions.
McNabb was 7-of-17 for 49 yards with an interception and no scores.
He was sacked three times. Pederson was not sacked.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Reid said the quarterback situation is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Donovan can go, he'll go,'' he said. STILL GOING...
</P>
<P>
   Norm Johnson made his only extra-point attempt to extend his NFL
record conversion streak to 293. Johnson, who is fourth on the
all-time NFL scoring list and fifth on the career field goal list,
hasn't missed an extra point since Sept. 29, 1991, when he played
for Atlanta against New Orleans. His 630 career conversions rank
third all-time behind George Blanda (943) and Lou Groza (641).
DON'T LEAVE HOME...
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles have lost 13 consecutive NFC East road games. Their
most recent division victory away from Veterans Stadium was on Nov.
3, 1996, when they beat the Cowboys at Texas Stadium. Since a road
victory against the New York Jets on Dec. 14, 1996, Philadelphia is
1-23-1 on the road, including a 19-game winless streak that was
broken with a victory at Chicago on Oct. 17. BACKED UP
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles didn't put together much offense _ only 233 total
yards _ but part of the problem was the poor field position they
were stuck with most of the day. Indeed, they got the ball at their
20 or deeper on seven consecutive possessions, a span that
encompassed the entire second and third quarters. In those seven
series, the Eagles failed to make a first down four times, had only
one first down on two possessions and fumbled on the third play of
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that makes it harder, but it's not like you can't drive
the ball from there,'' quarterback Donovan McNabb said. ``We've
done it in the last couple of weeks. But when you go three-and-out,
three-and-out, it becomes hard to get a rhythm going.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
