<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS PLAY GAME OF FIELD POSITION TO PERFECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys punter Toby Gowin provided the
defense the perfect opportunity to play an aggressive, attacking
style against Philadelphia Eagles rookie quarterback Donovan
McNabb.
</P>
<P>
   Gowin tied the team record by landing five punts inside the
Eagles' 20-yard line, the second time Gowin has pulled off the feat
and only the fourth time in team history it has been accomplished.
Gowin continually kept the Eagles' lethargic offense stuck in
horrible field position.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's huge,'' defensive coordinator Dave Campo said. ``Any
time you start with field position in your favor, it's big.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Eagles started at the Cowboys' 36-yard line with 33
seconds remaining in the first quarter _ a drive that ended with a
Darren Hambrick interception of a McNabb pass on the first play _
the Eagles' starting field position on their next eight drives went
like this: own 10, own 17, own 16, own 18, own 16, own 20, own 11,
and own 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was key,'' safety George Teague said. ``Whenever you get
somebody back inside their 20 for half the game, we can do a lot of
different things and be very aggressive.'' ELLIS LOST FOR THE
SEASON
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys got the victory, but the barrage injuries they've
suffered this season continued.
</P>
<P>
   The most crucial was to defensive end Greg Ellis, who suffered a
season-ending fractured left tibia in the first quarter when
defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman fell on his leg. Ellis, the team's
sack leader with 7.5, was replaced by rookies Peppi Zellner and
Ebenezer Ekuban. He underwent surgery to repair the fracture last
night.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis is the 13th Cowboys player to suffer a season-ending
injury in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Kevin Mathis could also miss the final three games
after suffering a sprained left knee. CORYATT RETURNS
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Coryatt, expected to be the starting strongside
linebacker before he unexpectedly opted to leave the Cowboys before
the season opener, returned to the field for the first time since
1997 when he was with the Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt, who said the combination of a shoulder injury and an
Achilles' tendon injury forced him to take the first 12 weeks off
to rehabilitate, saw action on about 10 plays and combined on one
tackle. He said he is clearly not in football shape, but should be
in time for the playoffs. FIRST SACK
</P>
<P>
   Rookie defensive end Ebenezar Ekuban recorded his first career
sack and then added a second as he received extended playing time
after Greg Ellis suffered a fractured left tibia early in the first
quarter. Ekuban finished with three tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely feels great when you finally get an opportunity
to play,'' Ekuban said. ``Unfortunately, it came through the wrong
way because someone got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban's two sacks are the most by a Dallas rookie since Russell
Maryland recorded two against Pittsburgh on Nov. 28, 1991. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Wide receiver Chris Brazzell, who was signed off the practice
squad on Friday when Wane McGarity was placed on injured reserve,
caught one pass, a third-down, 12-yard reception for a first down
in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Troy Aikman's 8-yard touchdown pass to David LaFleur in the
third quarter marked Aikman's 153rd career touchdown pass, tying
him for second place in team history with Roger Staubach. The
franchise leader? Danny White with 155. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
