<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YOUTH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS OWNER HICKS WILL ACCEPT YOUTH MOVEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Rangers will have a younger team next
year, younger perhaps than they expected going into the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Spurned by Todd Zeile and aghast at the asking price of starting
pitching, the Rangers are bracing themselves for a team that not
only has Ruben Mateo in center and Gabe Kapler in right but also
Mike Lamb at third base and Matt Perisho in the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Tom Hicks said he's willing to do that and go through a
potentially painful transition period rather than spend recklessly
for free-agent pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a decision that we couldn't win the World Series with
last year's roster,'' Hicks said yesterday. ``You have to find a
way to get there. We don't have to get there next year. It would be
great if we did and if we improve our starting pitching, we might
have a better chance than last year. But if we have to be more
patient, we will.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin seems to be leaning that way as the
Rangers regrouped at the winter meetings the day after losing Zeile
to the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we were a little bit older, a little slower and
not as athletic,'' Melvin said. ``I get very excited about young
players. When we're talking about Ruben Mateo, Gabe Kapler, Mike
Lamb and Francisco Cordero, we're talking about young guys who are
highly respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said the Rangers are not looking for a front-line third
baseman. They will not pursue Colorado's Vinny Castilla or
Milwaukee's Jeff Cirillo _ both are available _ and it's unlikely
they will pursue Tony Fernandez or Ed Sprague, the best of the
remaining free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely they'll discuss a veteran who could help Lamb with
the transition from Double A. They talked with agents yesterday for
Gary Gaetti, Shawon Dunston and Tom Evans. Giants utility infielder
F.P. Santangelo remains another possibility, through a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching remains the Rangers' top priority, but an expensive
waiting game has developed all through the industry.
Representatives for the available free-agent pitchers are looking
for three- to four-year contracts for at least $9 million to $10
million a year while clubs aren't willing to spend more than $7
million to $8 million per annum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a gap or you'd have more signings,'' Indians general
manager John Hart said. ``A lot of it is the expectations that are
out there and the reality some clubs have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have offered Aaron Sele a four-year contract worth
$28 million, and they met with agent Scott Boras yesterday
concerning Kenny Rogers. But Melvin said the Rangers have yet to
make an offer to Rogers and remains reluctant to overpay for the
pitching available.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't think they'll take you to the next level,''
Melvin said. ``If you tie up those kind of dollars, you could be in
trouble for the next three or four years. It could be expensive
going through a whole rebuilding program if it fails.''
</P>
<P>
   Most baseball officials believe Chuck Finley will be the next
starting pitcher to sign, thereby setting the market for Sele,
Rogers and others. The Indians, Seattle Mariners and Baltimore
Orioles have made offers but have yet to meet agent Tim Shannon's
asking price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a figure in mind,'' Shannon said. ``I've told them, the
first team that hits that number, I'm going to put that in front of
Chuck, and he'll say yes or no. We're not trying to set any records
or break anybody's bank.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers have seen the kind of money that pitchers are
asking for, and they're holding back. It's just one reason why
youth could be served next year at The Ballpark in Arlington.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
