<HEADLINE>
ORDERING BLITZ PROVED SOUND CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ On first down from the Colts 27 with 1:28 left in
the game and many of their futures riding on what happened, the
Patriots squandered play Sunday. None of the receivers seemed to
know where they were supposed to go.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Drew Bledsoe had to throw the ball away, and on
second down that oh-so-familiar sight of New England receivers
heading deep and toward the sidelines reappeared like a ghost from
games past and chances lost. Bledsoe, again finding no one open,
had to scramble and picked up 5 yards. And now came third down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches made a good call on that down,'' said Indianapolis
linebacker Mike Peterson. ``We caught 'em by surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of the fourth quarter, as the Patriots tried to come
back, the Colts often had rushed only three linemen and played a
prevent defense. But, said Peterson, ``I'm an aggressive player and
I like it when we're aggressive.'' On that third down, the Colts
went aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots ``didn't have enough blockers when we came,'' said
Cornelius Bennett, the old man of the football wars who also came
with Peterson on the blitz. ``They tried to pick me up because I'm
the one who does most of the blitzing, but they didn't pick up the
other guy (Peterson).''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, at the Colts' hotel, Bennt had gathered his
teammates around him ``and gave a really good motivational
speech,'' said Indianapolis coach Jim Mora. ``He talked to the club
about a lot of things and he showed why he's one of our leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, of course, has been to four Super Bowls with the Bills,
was with the Falcons in the last Super Bowl, and said, ever
modestly, ``I love football and football loves me. And wherever I
go, I win. And I'm still playing good for an old fart.'' The
linebacker is now 37 and in his 14th season, ``and I'm not going to
count myself out until the fat lady sings and she's nowhere to be
found right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in training camp, Bennett could only practice once a day
``and I remember telling (defensive back) Jason Belser because I
had a lot of chances to stand back and look, `We've got a chance to
be a special football team.' From my knowledge of football, and
being around as long as I've been, I just saw the way these young
guys were busting their butts in practice. And now we've come
together real fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett was asked if these ``young guys,'' who have helped the
Colts clinch a playoff spot, have made him feel younger or if he
has made them play older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably a little bit of both,'' Bennett said. ``You know, I
feel that, at my age, I can't let these young pups outdo me. And
they probably feel they can't let this old dog outperform them.
I'll probably keep playing another five years if we keep winning
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was that third down that so symbolized the demise of the
Patriots, the ``young pup'' _ Michael Peterson _ and the ``old
dog'' _ the ever-emotional and vrtalkative Cornelius Bennett _
teamed up to totally surprise the New England offense.
</P>
<P>
   As Peterson recalled the blitz, ``we had practiced it all week
and we hadn't run it the whole game. Then we called it at a good
time. Give all the credit to the coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson came right up the middle ``and the look we gave then
made them think of something else, a great disguise we had,''
Bennett said. ``It was all the coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts' defense ``was sucking air at that point,'' said
Peterson, ``and I kind of looked off the center (the Patriots'
Damien Woody) and I kind of looked like I was going somewhere else.
But, at that last moment, I kind of hit it and I came free. They
never even got a piece of me. That's the way it's supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson sacked Bledsoe for an 8-yard loss. The Patriots were
done, their fall continuing. The Colts were ecstatic, their rise
quickening.
</P>
<P>
   And, Bennett said, ``This team is making this old dog feel like
a young pup again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
