<SLUG> BC-BBO-ZEILE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' APPEAL FOR ZEILE: BETTER SHOT AT WINNING SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Todd Zeile believes the New York Mets have a
more realistic chance of winning the World Series than the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he spurned the Rangers and agreed to a three-year,
$18 million contract with the New York Mets late Saturday night.
Zeile will play first base for the Mets, replacing John Olerud, who
signed with the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets have a more realistic possibility of (winning the
Series) during what I consider the remaining term of my career,''
Zeile said. ``There were more question marks and uncertainty with
the Rangers than the Mets.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile's decision stunned Rangers general manager Doug Melvin,
who met with Zeile's agent, Seth Levinson, late Friday night and
went to bed believing that a deal was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we did everything they asked us to do,'' said
Melvin, who now has to decide if he'll go with rookie Mike Lamb at
third base or make a run at aging free-agent veterans Tony
Fernandez or Ed Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin and Levinson had agreed on the terms of a three-year, $16
million contract that included a complete no-trade clause for the
first two years. In the last year of the deal, Zeile would have
been able to designate 15 teams that he couldn't be traded to by
the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seth told me that's (a deal) he could convince Todd of,''
Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't. Instead Mets catcher Mike Piazza, a former teammate
with the Dodgers and Marlins, convinced Zeile that New York was the
place to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Piazza must have done a good job,'' Melvin said. ``He should
be an agent when he's done playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile met with Melvin on Saturday night before making a decision
and expressed two concerns. Zeile said he wasn't happy the Rangers
had taken too long to offer a three-year contract and was concerned
about their chances of winning.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile was worried the Rangers had yet to re-sign pitcher Aaron
Sele, and they were going with young players, most notably center
fielder Ruben Mateo and right fielder Gabe Kapler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd did have some concerns about our club being younger,''
Melvin said. ``But I get a little tired of veteran players talking
about younger players. They were once young, too. But I give Todd
credit. He came in and expressed his concerns to me face-to-face.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin also pointed out, ``Our payroll is going to be higher
than 25 other teams. We're just distributing the money
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile said the pace of the negotiations ``to some degree left me
a little frustrated. They knew from the beginning of the off-season
I expressed serious interest in getting it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers started the process early in November by offering a
two-year contract plus a club option for a third year. Levinson
countered that with a four-year proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile, who lives in the Los Angeles area, had purchased a house
in the Metroplex, contingent on the Rangers' re-signing him by Nov.
15. When that date passed, he started to get irritated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it can get done quickly if you just give the player
what he's asking for,'' Melvin said. ``We had a lot of things going
on, and we were reluctant to go three years.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Rangers were concerned about how much it
would take to sign free-agent pitching. The Rangers didn't offer a
three-year contract to Zeile until last week. By then, the Mets had
lost Olerud, and general manager Steve Phillips was pursuing other
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if things had moved sooner, it would have been done
before I got a chance to talk with Steve,'' Zeile said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
