<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-TRADES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS ACQUIRE PITCHER VALDES, INFIELDER YOUNG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN and SIMON GONZALEZ c.1999 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Before taking the job as Chicago Cubs manager,
Don Baylor wanted to know if the team was willing to do what it
takes to put a winning team on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``My interview process, that was something that we talked about,
the baseball people and the Tribune Company,'' Baylor said. ``I was
looking for commitment, and they promised that.''
</P>
<P>
   Management made good on its promise yesterday. The Cubs were
able to trade reliever Terry Adams and two minor-leaguers to the
Los Angeles Dodgers for starting pitcher Ismael Valdes and second
baseman Eric Young because ownership was willing to take on about
$10 million in salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here to accomplish some things right away, and we've
done that with the backing and blessing of the company,'' Baylor
said.
</P>
<P>
   There are questions about Young's defense and attitude but
Baylor, who managed him in Colorado, wanted him in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very exciting player for me in Colorado,'' Baylor
said. ``He brings to us something that this club needed, a leadoff
hitter with speed. Fifty-two stolen bases was probably more than
our entire club had last year.'' Protecting Palmeiro Signing Rafael
Palmeiro last year gave the Rangers some protection for Juan
Gonzalez in the middle of their order. The departure of Gonzalez
and third baseman Todd Zeile now leaves manager Johnny Oates
wondering who will protect Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find a way a way to make them pitch to Raffy,''
Oates said. ``The key is not so much protecting the young kids
\RRuben Mateo, Gabe Kapler\S but protecting Raffy so they'll pitch
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said one solution is to have the designated hitter platoon
of Lee Stevens and Mike Simms in the fifth spot. One result of
Zeile signing with the Mets on Saturday is the Rangers aren't
likely to trade Stevens, who is arbitration eligible, as a
cost-cutting measure.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said he has no idea what his Opening Day lineup will be,
but he is leaning toward Rusty Greer as his leadoff hitter, Luis
Alicea batting second, Ivan Rodriguez third and Palmeiro in the
cleanup spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said he was sorry to see Zeile and Mark McLemore _ two of
his favorites _ leave but added, ``I've lost a lot of good players
in my career. But life goes on. Everybody has decisions to make.
Nobody is bigger than the game.'' Palmeiro wins DH award Rafael
Palmerio has been named the American League's Outstanding
Designated Hitter for 1999. He is the first Rangers player to win
the award since it's inception in 1973. He is also the first player
to win that award and the Gold Glove as a first baseman in the same
season. Briefly Cubs pitcher Kerry Wood, coming off major elbow
surgery, is expected to throw off a mound today. The Grand Prairie
High School graduate might be ready for the start of the season,
but manager Don Baylor won't rush him. ``I'm going to baby him as
much as I can, try to keep him away from throwing a lot of
pitches,'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, in need of a catcher after losing Brent Mayne and
Scott Servais to free agency, traded right-handed pitcher Chris
Brock to the Phillies for Bobby Estalella. Estalella, 25, who a
.218 average with 14 home runs and 34 runs batted in in 76 career
big-league games, is considered a good defensive catcher. Brock,
29, was 6-8 with a 5.48 earned-run average in 19 starts for the
Giants last season.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay general manager Chuck LaMar confirmed interest in free
agent slugger Greg Vaughn. The Indians and Mets also want Vaughn,
who hit 45 home runs and drove in 118 runs for the Reds last
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are interested in Indians right fielder Manny Ramirez
as well as Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. They are dangling closer
Armando Benitez, starting pitcher Octavio Dotel and outfielder
Roger Cedeno.
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox would rather see a Mets lineup with
Todd Zeile at first base than departed free agent John Olerud. ``I
was really glad to see Olerud leave,'' Cox said. ``I think he's one
of the best hitters in the game. I like Zeile, don't get me wrong,
but I love Olerud. He's got one of the best swings I've ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Womack, the National League's stolen base leader in his
first three full major-league seasons, agreed to a $17 million,
four-year contract with the Arizona Diamondbacks, The Associated
Press reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
