<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-KRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT SHOULD GET DOWN TO BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Many of them appeared to be as sad as this
droopy-eyed city's nightlife. They began Sunday living on their
own, simply needing to win the rest of their games to get into the
playoffs. But their 20-15 loss to the Colts changed everything. Now
the Patriots have to do the NFL equivalent of moving in with the
folks to get what they want. They are highly paid dependents. They
need outside help and they don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   That was the surface reason for a football team's sadness Sunday
at RCA Dome, but sadness is usually deeper than what appears on the
surface. You would have to conduct a private organizational poll to
find out what each Patriot believes is the definitive problem (or
problems) on a 7-6 team.
</P>
<P>
   I have not conducted a poll, but I am sure my summary would
include a line like this: The problem is that not many people can
agree on what the problem is. I also would add: This certainly is
not a divided team and organization, but it is not seamlessly
united, either.
</P>
<P>
   Three consecutive wins or losses to end the season will not
change what ails the Patriots. Only one man can do that. He is the
same man who was headed toward a private plane as one of his
employees was sending a message to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just say that I apologize to Mr. Kraft,'' quarterback
Drew Bledsoe said after passing for more than twice as many yards
(379) as winning quarterback Peyton Manning. Bledsoe mentioned that
the Patriots have ``one of the highest payrolls in the NFL'' and
that ``(Kraft) spends a lot of money for the players he has on this
team'' for it to be in a situation where ``it needs help getting
into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   People react to apologies in different ways; I would love to
hear Robert Kraft's initial reaction to Bledsoe's. Does the owner
believe that he has invested too much money in a team that wins
slightly more often than it loses? Is he thinking of reshuffling
some of the players who hold the weighty salaries and/or the people
who signed them to those contracts? He is a rich man, but does he
have the same feeling that a lot of us have after excessive
spending doesn't bring satisfaction? You know, the feeling that he
has wasted his money?
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, money might be a Patriot problem. But then, some don't
think it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to talk to Big Money,'' Lawyer Milloy said,
referring to Bledsoe. ``That's not football. Money doesn't have
anything to do with it. Because, we weren't the highest-paid team
out there when we had a whole bunch of role players and ended up in
the Super Bowl. So, you can't bring up money. We're still that same
team. We're just not producing.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are tough words coming from the team's most ferocious
hitter. But the more you listen to him, you realize he is
frustrated as much as he is afraid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious that we need help (getting into the playoffs),''
he said. ``It's obvious. We could still end up with 10 wins. But
the way the AFC is and the way our division is, those 10 wins might
not get us in. So right now the feeling is . . . it's a scary
thought. To think that we could possibly go home early this year is
scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, there is only one man in the organization with the
power to finger the nonproduction problem and fix it. Ultimately,
Kraft will have to determine if offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese
is ineffective or if the problem is with the players he is given to
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Zampese's schemes were good enough Sunday for Bledsoe to pick
the Colts defense apart at times. Bledsoe said the Colts did
nothing to confuse him, and no one mentioned anything about the
receivers not being able to get open. The chain-smoking
coordinator's offense was good enough for Terry Glenn to produce
nine catches and 148 yards. In fact, Zampese's offense seems to
work for Glenn when the Patriots play 150 miles or fewer from
Glenn's hometown of Columbus, Ohio. He had 22 catches for 362 yards
in games against Cleveland and Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   But who was at fault for the major mistake at the end of the
third quarter? The Patriots trailed, 13-6, and had a third and goal
from the 1. Coach Pete Carroll said the call for Terry Allen was an
off tackle play. Well, either it was a bad call, bad block, or bad
run because it turned into a 2-yard loss and eventual field goal.
These things have been happening to the Patriots often enough this
season for their record to be an uneasy 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft also will have to analyze his last few drafts and ask
himself if he is happy with what they have produced. In 1998,
Kraft's Bobby Grier-led personnel team sat with him in the team's
war room and told him that they liked a great athlete who was a
risky pick. But, they said, since the team had two first-rounders
it was a risk the team could afford. The player, of course, was
Tebucky Jones. I see the man and think ``safety,'' but I don't
coach nor sign checks. As Bledsoe pointed out, Kraft does sign a
lot of checks and endorses the hiring and firing of coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Kraft may have pleasant conversations about Carroll's
performance, but publicly he has done classic Michael Jackson
moonwalks away from his coach the past couple weeks. After Sunday's
game, he was as noiseless as the tumbleweed rolling through the
prairie that is this city's downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Kraft is silent because he doesn't want anyone to feel he
is looking over a shoulder. I can respect that. But no matter what
the Patriots do in the next few weeks, Kraft will have to do some
deep thinking in 2000. That process may involve admitting that he
was wrong on some of his previous football decisions.
</P>
<P>
   This organization definitely needs something new _ either new
management, new coaching or new players. Kraft has a tough job: He
has to find the problems before they find him. If not, the
second-most important part of his business (winning) will be a
memory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
