<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE AIRS IT OUT AFTER THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ He was seething, but he tried not to show it.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe is not often a captive of his
emotions, but Sunday, after the offense he leads had done
everything it could to self-destruct at the most critical of
moments, he was ready to pop his cork.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe silently has grown weary of blown assignments, receivers
covered like they were wrapped in flypaper, and penalties that take
points off the board or cause his team to go backward just when it
is beginning to go forward.
</P>
<P>
   He is tired of seeing offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese blamed
for the wrongs of his players, tired of seeing himself and his
teammates make just enough mistakes that Zampese is always starting
over when he tries to call a game rather than starting to set
something up.
</P>
<P>
   So on a day in which he completed 31 of 44 passes for 379 yards
and threw two touchdown passes but was credited for only one
because the other was wiped out by an illegal procedure call,
Bledsoe was steaming. So angry he refused to speak for a long time.
A long, long time.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he did, his true emotions were masked by a blank
look, a calm voice, and a personal decision to admit what has been
obvious to some for quite a while now.
</P>
<P>
   ``On behalf of myself and the team I really want to apologize to
Mr. (Robert) Kraft (the Patriots' owner),'' Bledsoe said an hour
after that team had lost to the Indianapolis Colts, 20-15, to fall
to 7-6 and register its fourth loss in the last five games. ``He's
paying us a lot of money and not getting his money's worth. To be
in a position where we need help to get into the playoffs is
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he got it out of Bledsoe, who completed eight passes
of 16 yards or longer and three for gains of more than 25 yards
(28, 35, and 52). He was accurate and on time with his throws and
four times ran away from pass rushes for gains when in the recent
past he might have been sacked.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in the end, all Bledsoe had to show for this effort was
more frustration, more anger, and a need to apologize for the kind
of game most quarterbacks never have in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a very good game,'' Patriots coach Pete Carroll said of
his downcast quarterback. ``He was alive the whole time. I thought
he was whipping the ball around and was in control of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took advantage of the opportunities that were there. I
thought he played very, very well in this game. It's unfortunate he
didn't get to finish it. I know he's dead sick about not finishing
it. It's the kind of situation he looks forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   What Bledsoe looks forward to is having the ball handed back to
him with just over two minutes to play and the game on the line.
His team trailed by 5 points by then, but he had the ball and more
than enough time to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   When he found Troy Brown for a 28-yard completion to the Colts
27 with 88 seconds still on the clock, he knew, just knew, he would
get his team in the end zone this time.
</P>
<P>
   He knew it.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came up too little, too late at the end,'' Bledsoe said
after he was forced to throw the ball away on the next play when no
one was close to being open and was sacked for an 8-yard loss on a
blitz two plays later to put the ball back on the 30, making it
``fourth down and forever,'' according to Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense did as good a job as they've done all year,''
Bledsoe said. ``They did everything they could, including turn the
ball over to us late (when Lawyer Milloy recovered Peyton Manning's
fumbled snap).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job to get the ball to the end zone at the end of the
game and I didn't get it done. For the most part we were able to
move on them but you have to score touchdowns. Field goals aren't
going to win for you against a team like this. I knew it was a
problem for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a problem Drew Bledsoe could not solve Sunday and so he
seethed instead. Seethed until he composed himself and did the only
other thing he could think to do for his team.
</P>
<P>
   He apologized for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
