A7131 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKNOTES-LADN     12-13 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARIYA SAYS KOHN'S FIGHT WAS KEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Playing on a team with heavyweights Stu
Grimson and Jim McKenzie, 5-foot-11, 192-pound winger Ladislav Kohn
doesn't figure to make much of an impact with his fighting skills.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Paul Kariya, it was Kohn's willingness to
defend himself against Atlanta's Kelly Buchberger that turned
Sunday's game in favor of the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that was the biggest play of the game,'' said Kariya of
the Kohn's fight at 1:14 of the second period. ``He stood up for
himself and got us going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't believe it,'' joked Teemu Selanne. ``We thought
`what is he doing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Kohn, who was hit high by Buchberger after the Ducks winger had
checked Atlanta's Patrik Stefan, said it was all in a night's work
on the fourth line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was answering the bell, facing the music,'' he said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   But Kohn got rewarded for his efforts shortly after leaving the
penalty box when he converted Kariya's two-on-one pass into his
second goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A goal and a fight ... if you had told me that before the
game, I'd have taken it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __Even Dominic Roussel was involved in some rough stuff. The
Ducks goalie, who won his first game since Oct. 27, got a a
roughing penalty for pushing Ray Ferraro after the Atlanta pest got
in his face and bumped him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of like it,'' said Roussel. ``With the new rules you've
got let them know who is boss (in the goal crease).''
</P>
<P>
   Roussel's win came in his first appearance since he lost a 6-3
decision in Detroit on Nov. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he played very well,'' said Ducks coach Craig
Hartsburg. ``We kind of left him alone at times in the third
period.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks outshot the Thrashers 36-28, but Atlanta had the edge,
16-12, in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stapleton's shot bent the cage on Roussel's mask and had
him ``seeing stars'' just seconds before Dean Sylvester scored the
Thrashers' goal at at 8:11 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   __The Ducks had scored three or more goals in only four of their
previous 14 games. Anaheim has topped the three-goal mark only
eight times in the first 31 games.
</P>
<P>
   __Ferraro, an ex-King, considered retirement after Los Angeles
did not re-sign him last summer, but the center was selected by
Atlanta in the expansion draft and is getting more playing time
than he has in recent years. Ferraro leads the Thrashers' forwards
in ice time (16:23 a game) and is second in scoring (5-11-16).
Andrew Burnette leads Atlanta with 13 goals and 26 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 0143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7140 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PISTONS-LA     12-13 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PISTONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX, O'NEAL LIFT LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ That wasn't some bad Vegas lounge performer
playing ventriloquist on the Staples Center floor Sunday night. It
just looked that way.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the part of the dummy _ the Detroit Pistons. Displaying
the latest technique for denying Shaquille O'Neal the ball, Piston
after Piston planted himself in O'Neal's large lap as he took
position outside the paint.
</P>
<P>
   It worked, to a point, but O'Neal came up with 22 points anyway.
And the Los Angeles Lakers shooters, led by Rick Fox's 20 points,
took advantage of the added space to roam to take the 101-93
victory.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal also pulled down a season-high 24 rebounds and blocked
four shots, but was limited by foul trouble and a constant crowd of
Piston defenders. Coach Phil Jackson said O'Neal would have done
much more damage if not for the officiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (referee) Steve Javie is the only one who could stop
Shaq because of the way he played,'' Jackson said. ``He was
dominating _ so much so that they conceded our outside shot and
gave us whatever we wanted, and kept us at bay because we have such
a predictable type of orientation toward going inside. The first
quarter took us a long time to build a rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that was a consequence of losing Glen Rice for the
evening. With Rice nursing a 100-degree fever at home, the Lakers
lacked an outside shooting threat to keep the Pistons' guards from
sagging into O'Neal's lap.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Fox filled that role instead. Coming off the bench
to play a season-high 37 minutes, Fox had his best statistical game
of the season. He hit 9 of 18 shots, and his points and rebounds
(eight) were both season highs. He also dished out four assists and
blocked a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Things were going so well for Fox, he even made plays when he
wasn't looking. Early in the fourth quarter, Robert Horry saved the
ball from going out of bounds, and his quick toss caromed off Fox's
head before landing back in Horry's hands. The possession was
saved, and Fox eventually dished to Brian Shaw for a layup that
gave the Lakers an 89-71 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was the perfect encore to Fox's breakout-type performance the
day before against Vancouver. After a month and a half of
struggling to find a shooting groove in Jackson's offense, Fox
wasn't about to declare he'd found a comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``How dare I speak so soon,'' he quipped. ``No, I always enjoyed
playing this offense and am comfortable in knowing it gets
opportunities for everyone. But being a perfectionist and liking to
see things happen the same way every night, I'd like to have the
shots go down a lot more consistently. And I'm probably harder on
myself than anyone else is going to be. It will only get better if
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last two games, it has, and Fox is encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely reminds me that I'm not stealing money from the
Lakers,'' he said. ``It allows me to feel good about a contribution
to the team, especially when we miss one of our superstars.''
</P>
<P>
   With Fox firing, O'Neal rebounding and Kobe Bryant slashing for
a team-high 26 points, the Lakers took a double-digit lead in the
third quarter and were on their way to a rout when they extended
the margin to 20 points in the fourth. But a shaky outing from the
Laker reserves let the Pistons knock the lead down to eight late in
the game before the Lakers sealed the win, their ninth in the last
10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' said Pistons coach Alvin Gentry, ``is you
have to find so much time and energy trying to figure out what you
are going to do with Shaq ... that he breaks your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson knows that axiom well enough, having coached against
O'Neal. ``It's probably why I'm coaching here now,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   The game featured the top two scorers in the NBA, and both
league leader O'Neal (averaging 28.3 points) and Grant Hill (27.5)
set the tone for their teams in the first half, with 16 points
each. But the Lakers got the better supporting effort to take a
58-51 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, despite leading the Pistons with 25 points and 12
rebounds, struggled with his shot, finishing 7 of 19, and had four
turnovers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 0157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7141 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-TRADE-LAD     12-13 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-TRADE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS TRADE VALDES, YOUNG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It became apparent midway through the
tumultuous 1999 season that the Dodgers wanted to trade
right-hander Ismael Valdes and second baseman Eric Young. Finding a
club to absorb the cost was another subject.
</P>
<P>
   After months of trying and numerous talks, the Los Angeles
Dodgers found a match in the Chicago Cubs. Sunday the two teams
pulled off the first big trade of the winter meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes and Young went to the Cubs, while the Dodgers, in
addition to cutting $14 million of payroll, received right-handed
reliever Terry Adams, minor-league pitcher Chad Ricketts and
another minor-league player to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, 26, is 19-26 with a 4.03 ERA and 37 saves in four-plus
seasons with the Cubs. Ricketts, 24, had 80 strikeouts in 67
innings at Double-A West Tennessee. The Dodgers project him out to
be a set-up guy for the 2001 or 2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who made $736,000 last year, is eligible for salary
arbitration and expected to earn approximately $1.3 million next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't an option, a legitimate option, moving (Valdes)
solely by himself,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said.
``We have to look at the bigger picture. You probably could have
gotten a little more talent, but reality is this is more than a
talent issue. The reality of this is there were economic issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic issues was a mandate by Dodgers managing general
partner, chairman and CEO Robert Daly to move payroll. The Dodgers,
who had an $83 million payroll last season, cut their current
payroll to approximately $80 million after the trade.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is being criticized throughout the industry because the
Dodgers traded two starters for a relief pitcher and two
minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers thought Valdes was expendable after his agent,
Jim Bronner, said the Mexico native wouldn't sign a multi-year
contract before the season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Valdes, who has a career 61-54 mark with a 3.38 ERA,
wants to test the free-agent waters after the 2000 season. Valdes
is considered one of the top pitching talents in baseball, but his
toughness is questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hate giving up players, and we especially hate giving up a
Valdes,'' Daly said. ``You hate to lose Valdes, but, again, he was
going to be a free agent.''
</P>
<P>
   It leaves the Dodgers without a leadoff hitter or second
baseman, though more moves are expected. In the interim, Malone
said rookies Eric Gagne, Jeff Williams and Mike Judd would battle
for a starting spot, while a number of options are being considered
for second base.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Vizcaino, Alex Cora and Juan Castro are among those
considerations, as is a platoon involving Craig Counsell. Malone
also said publicly for the first time it was possible shortstop
Mark Grudzielanek could move to second base.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson said Grudzielanek could bat leadoff, which
he did in Montreal. If the Dodgers somehow retain third baseman
Adrian Beltre, he could bat second, Johnson said. Last season
Grudzielanek became the first Dodgers shortstop to hit more than
.300 since 1963. He batted .326, mostly from the second spot.
</P>
<P>
   The trade also means the feud between Young and manager Davey
Johnson, which escalated as the season wore on, won't infiltrate
the clubhouse again. The relationship between the two took a
drastic turn in July, when Young failed to turn a double play ball
on a routine grounder and team officials considered Young a
defensively liability.
</P>
<P>
   It was further strained when Young wanted to go on the disabled
list because of an ankle injury but the Dodgers didn't oblige
because they wanted to trade him before the July 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very relieved and at peace right now because I know I'll
be going to a situation where I feel wanted,'' Young, 32, said.
``There was too much finger-pointing going on in our locker room,
and it wasn't only the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin Malone was great to me over there, but I think he has a
lot to overcome in doing his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, he had people working against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Young was third in the National League with 51 stolen bases,
though he was caught 22 times. He batted .281 with 24 doubles and
41 RBI, but was roundly criticized by scouts for hitting too many
pop flies. Some teammates quietly questioned Young as well,
wondering why he didn't work more on his defense in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a bad relationship with Eric,'' Johnson said.
``He played the first half of the season hurt, but after he was
healthy he played well. One of the things we wanted to do was get
more balance, and we started doing that (with Shawn Green) and get
bullpen help. And Terry Adams is still young, and he can be a good
set-up guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Trading Young has been a major point of emphasis since last
offseason. But the Angels, Colorado Rockies and St. Louis Cardinals
each shunned a possible trade because of Young's contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs were willing to take on Young's salary to fill holes.
General manager Ed Lynch, whose job is on the line, came to the
winter meetings looking for a No. 2 or No.3 starter and a second
baseman/leadoff hitter. Both gaps were filled with this move.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Young reunited with former Rockies manager Don
Baylor, but also with former infield instructor Gene Glynn, who
Young credits with helping his fielding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings us something this club needed with a leadoff hitter,
one with speed,'' Baylor said. ``Fifty-two stolen bases is probably
more than our entire club had last season. Valdes, a quality young
starting pitcher was one of our objectives this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
