</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY'S REVENGE? STAYING, WINNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Now is a good time for all citizens of Marinerville to
start thinking World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   As of now, the Mariners have John Olerud, Edgar Martinez and
Alex Rodriguez _ three former batting champs _ anchoring their
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mariners have Ken Griffey Jr. _ Player of the Decade,
All-Century Team selection, Seattle's own ... still.
</P>
<P>
   Championship teams are built for one-year crusades these days.
Why not try and win the 2000 World Series without a care as to what
value you get in a timely, sensible trade of the best player of his
generation?
</P>
<P>
   Why not the Mariners?
</P>
<P>
   Why not consider Griffey sticking it out by sticking it to the
M's as a golden opportunity for Marinerville to exult in one year
of glory?
</P>
<P>
   A-Rod. Griffey. Martinez. Olerud.
</P>
<P>
   Right. Left. Right. Left.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner March ... all the way to October.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is eating yourself alive with anger,
frustration, boredom and assorted other feelings about why the
Mariners and Griffey can't part company in a timely and fruitful
manner, like we had all hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, through his good-guy agent Brian Goldberg, Griffey
announced that unless the Mariners can work a deal with the Reds _
the only team to which Griffey is now willing to accept a trade _
Griffey will be back in Seattle for the final year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the scenario anyone had hoped for, although the
potential for such back-firing was in the cards.
</P>
<P>
   Remember last season when Griffey vowed that his status as a
10-year veteran with five years of service with one team let him
hold the ultimate hammer?
</P>
<P>
   For a man who thrives on trying to control a very uncontrollable
and, at times, overwhelming circus surrounding a big-time sports
star, Griffey takes great comfort in knowing that ultimately, at
least in this deal, his grip is tightest on the hammer.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Mariners are beginning to feel it coming down.
</P>
<P>
   Why such a hard line by Griffey two months before the start of
spring training?
</P>
<P>
   Because Griffey keeps reading newspaper stories that quote new
general manager Pat Gillick saying Griffey changes his mind as
often and with the same inexplicable fluidity as the way sand dunes
shift shape.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Gillick was not briefed on how to do business with
Junior _ the politics and poetics of what you should and should not
say. So that would be an error on Mr. Gillick.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to committing the sin of inadvertently insulting
Griffey, Griffey believes the Mariners have betrayed his word on
what teams to which he would be willing to consider a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey gave the Mariners a list, but instead of sticking to the
list, Gillick went back to Goldberg and Griffey with deals from
teams not on the list.
</P>
<P>
   This would be another way of testing Griffey's patience _
another no-no.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Griffey narrowed his focus to the Reds, because
no other teams he was interested in were biting. But the Mariners
have refused to make a deal with the Reds, all because of a guy
name Pokey Reese, whom the M's insist on getting in any deal.
</P>
<P>
   So Griffey is so frustrated with the Mariners that he is
apparently more than prepared to exact his most delicious revenge.
His plan?
</P>
<P>
   He will come back to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He will play hard _ harder than he did last August and September
when the Mariners depleted the team around him by trading David
Segui and Butch Huskey.
</P>
<P>
   He will hit homers and win a Gold Glove.
</P>
<P>
   He will produce one of his best seasons ever.
</P>
<P>
   He may even help take the Mariners to the postseason, because
with Griffey, Olerud and A-Rod (or whoever they get for A-Rod), the
M's will be the team to beat in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   And after all this, Griffey will walk away from Seattle after
next season saying: ``I told you so. You should have traded me to
the Reds, like I wanted, when you had a chance to get something in
return.''
</P>
<P>
   What's odd about all this is that the Mariners said they learned
everything they needed to know about handling a superstar
free-agent-to-be who wants out of Seattle. One season with a sullen
and suffering Randy Johnson was all the Mariners needed to declare
they would move expeditiously the next time around.
</P>
<P>
   So, never again. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe wrong _ enough to lead the faithful but restless
citizens of Marinerville to serious worrying and hand-wringing.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you take the opposite approach.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you say that with Griffey, who will be out to prove he is
no Randy Johnson, the Mariners are a pretty darn good club _ even
for just one year. Sometimes, one year of glory is all you get
anyway, so why not visualize World Series?
</P>
<P>
   Why not choose sanity over insanity, which is the only place all
this Griffey stuff leads you anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back, Junior. You hold the hammer and the key. The world
will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
