<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS OR NOTHING FOR GRIFFEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Ken Griffey Jr. will return to the Mariners
next season unless the Cincinnati Reds resume trade talks for the
star center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Brian Goldberg confirmed Sunday that Griffey, who has veto
power over trades, has narrowed his list to one team, the Reds.
With Cincinnati emphatically withdrawing from talks on Saturday,
the Mariners have no team to which they can deal him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason Junior's list has narrowed really is because
the Mariners are pursuing us constantly about teams and situations
not on the original list,'' Goldberg said. ``(Griffey) doesn't like
the misleading and the game-playing, so he decided to shut it down.
The last two weeks, the Mariners have known their only option was
Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners general manager Pat Gillick continues to talk to teams
about Griffey, who told the Mariners last month that he did not
want to re-sign with them, effectively requesting a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving at the winter meetings here Friday night, Gillick
has talked with five teams, and he received offers from at least
two. The M's met with the New York Mets about Griffey last night.
</P>
<P>
   But for those talks to mean anything, Griffey has to change his
mind and approve a deal to a team other than the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to change his mind quite often,'' Gillick said. ``So
I think there's a possible chance he'll change his mind (again).''
</P>
<P>
   Through Goldberg, Griffey declined comment. But he talked Sunday
to friend and former teammate Harold Reynolds, an ESPN analyst, and
Reynolds stressed that Griffey controls the situation. Because he
has 10 years in the majors and the past five with the same team,
Griffey must approve a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior's 10 and 5,'' Reynolds said. ``If the only place he
wants to go to is Cincinnati, then who's to say Cincinnati won't
sign him next year? Big deal; let's not forget who's got the power.
...
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to get in a war, they're going to lose and get
two draft picks. He's got too much power in this, and that's the
right of a player. I call him the silent assassin. Everyone's
shooting all these big bullets, and he's saying, `You know what?
I've got my finger on the button that counts.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds' ``bullets'' analogy was in reference to the
characterization of Griffey as a person who constantly changes his
mind. Even so, the main motivation for Griffey's Reds-only stance
is the fact that the Mariners talked trade with teams he would not
play for.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners started doing that sometime after the GM meetings
in mid-November, when they were unable to make a deal with
Griffey's preferred clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey has long said he would never play for the New York
Yankees _ who may have made an offer _ and has no interest in
resurrecting the Pittsburgh Pirates in the same manner he helped
build the Mariners franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ticks me off, as much as it does Junior, that they had the
audacity to try to trade him to the Pirates,'' Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners do not want to lose Griffey to free agency after
next season and receive only compensatory draft picks. They also
want to avoid a repeat of 1998, when Randy Johnson wanted out and
the distraction helped ruin the Mariners' season.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how he believed Griffey would respond to playing out
a lame-duck season in Seattle, Gillick said he was confident
Griffey would handle it well.
</P>
<P>
   ``For certain players, if there's a distraction off the field,
once they cross the white lines they're professional and they have
a certain pride and a certain passion for the game _ and I think he
has that,'' Gillick said. ``There might be times that, off the
field, he might not be happy to be with the Mariners. But I think
on the field he'll be a professional.''
</P>
<P>
   After the All-Star break last year, with the Mariners depleted
and out of contention, Griffey batted .255 and appeared to play
without his usual joy. He was often irritable on the topic of his
future, which he raised periodically without being prompted.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffey could use the controversy over his future as
motivation during a farewell season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope is if he goes back to Seattle, the media will allow
him to concentrate on his job,'' Goldberg said. ``I don't worry
about Junior and I don't worry about the Mariners. Those two
parties are fine with each other, and if people think otherwise,
they're just dead wrong. I can only hope that outside influences
such as the media will not create the circus atmosphere they did
two years ago with Randy Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillick said that if Griffey and Goldberg decided to re-open
negotiations on a contract extension, he would take that request to
ownership. But there probably will be no need.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never say never,'' Goldberg said. ``(But) I sincerely
doubt it. I don't want to ever mislead anybody, but I sincerely
doubt it. It's not a knock on anything about Seattle. People should
not forget that most of the reasons Junior wanted to play in
Cincinnati were the same reasons why John Olerud came to Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gillick did not appear totally convinced the Reds
wouldn't re-enter trade talks, Goldberg has reason to speak of
Cincinnati in the past tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out of it,'' Bowden reiterated to Cincinnati reporters
Sunday. ``There will be no further discussions. The issue is behind
us. We are going forward with the team we have.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, most likely, are the Mariners, who probably will have
Griffey for one more year.
</P>
<P>
   FREE AGENT TALKS: The Mariners made their first offer to
Japanese closer Kazuhiro Sasaki Sunday, which could be an
indication they believe Bowden when he said trade talks are off
with the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki, the all-time saves leader in Japan, will probably sign
somewhere by the middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``All offers are in the eye of the beholder,'' agent Tony
Attanasio said of the Sasaki offer. ``I'm sure they viewed it as
very reasonable, and I viewed it as a very reasonable first
offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Attanasio also represents former Texas infielder/outfielder Mark
McLemore, and the clubs traded proposals Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The M's also met with the agent for former Anaheim starter Chuck
Finley Sunday. Seattle is one of seven teams bidding for Finley,
according to agent Tim Shannon; Baltimore, Boston, Cleveland, both
New York teams and Texas are the others.
</P>
<P>
   Finley and Shannon are seeking a three-year deal, possibly for
$27-$30 million.
</P>
<P>
   TRAINERS HONORED: Mariners trainers Rick Griffin and Tom Newberg
were named the Major League Baseball's outstanding trainers for
1999 by the Professional Baseball Athletic Society.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
