<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-TENNIS-BURBANK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY MAMIIT REIGNS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC ERWIN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ He began 1999 with a bang, beating Andre
Agassi and reaching the Sybase Open final. He ended it with
another, beating Alex O'Brien 7-5, 6-3 on Sunday to defend his
title at the drkoop.com Tennis Championships of Burbank at the
Burbank Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Cecil Mamiit, the 1997 NCAA champion while at USC
who is now ranked No. 105 in the world, battled himself and his
knee. It was not a battle he frequently won.
</P>
<P>
   Hampered by nagging injuries throughout the year, Mamiit
struggled to regain the form he showed at Burbank last year and
early this year in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been real up and down,'' said Mamiit, who won $7,200. ``I
was playing great at the beginning of the year, then I kind of got
injured. It's been nagging injuries, so I'd do well for awhile then
not so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Mamiit said he finally started feeling good again around the
U.S. Open, and he won his first-round match in New York. Now, he's
finally back to full-strength, and it showed against O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   Although O'Brien was in control through much of the first set,
Mamiit showed a few glimpses his knee was sound, hustling for balls
O'Brien believed he had put away. Two times, Mamiit chased them
down and flicked backhand winners past a stunned O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``I relaxed, and you can't relax against a guy as fast as he
is,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, O'Brien closed out his early service games with ease
while Mamiit struggled just to hold. O'Brien broke to take a 5-4
lead but seemed to tense up when serving for the set. He mis-hit a
forehand volley three inches long, then double-faulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truthfully, I was serving for the first set, and I just played
a bad game and let him back into the match,'' said O'Brien, ranked
No.160 in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Mamiit said he started feeling more comfortable against
O'Brien's serve, and he certainly appreciated the unforced errors.
Down love-40, O'Brien hit two big serves to make it 30-40, but
Mamitt hit a crisp return on the next point to earn the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mix,'' Mamiit said. ``I started getting a rhythm.
Things change so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Mamiit held to go up 6-5, then broke O'Brien again to win the
set _ but not without controversy.
</P>
<P>
   On his serve, O'Brien hit a clean winner down the line at 15-15,
but the chair umpire overruled and called it wide. Instead of
taking command of the game, O'Brien got flustered and Mamiit broke
to win the first set.
</P>
<P>
   Another service break at the beginning of the second set gave
Mamiit a quick 3-0 lead, and he cruised from there.
</P>
<P>
   After that, O'Brien, one of the top doubles players in the world
who won the U.S. Open and the world doubles championship this year,
questioned several line calls and wasn't shy about arguing with the
umpire. He earned two code violations costing him a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always get bad calls _ that's just part of the game,'' he
said. ``But they were all going against me for awhile there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mamiit said he just tried to ignore the argument delays and
concentrate on his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to be quiet,'' the Eagle Rock native said. ``Last
year I was really rowdy, dancing around and everything. I just
wanted to keep my cool.''
</P>
<P>
   And he'd like to keep his momentum going into 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really looking forward to getting ready for the Australian
Open,'' Mamiit said. ``And staying healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mamiit wasn't able to pull off a sweep, however, as he and
partner Scott Humphries fell to brothers _ and former Camarillo
High standouts _ Bob and Mike Bryan 7-6 (7-5), 5-7, 6-1 in the
doubles final.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 0208EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
