<SLUG> BC-GEN-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW FANS, BIG WINS FOR NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's the easiest ticket in town.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 1,000 fans showed up last week when the Cal State
Northridge men's basketball team easily beat Oral Roberts. The
Matadors were playing at home for the first time since beating
Fresno State on Nov.30. Only a few hundred saw the tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   The next night, only 183 fans came to see the CSUN women, last
season's Big Sky Conference champion, roll to an 26-point win over
UC Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN athletic director Dick Dull isn't pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of apathy, from the (San Fernando Valley) to
the student community, as well,'' Dull said. ``Our basketball
programs are best-kept secrets. People need to be alerted to the
fact there is quality Division I basketball being played here.''
</P>
<P>
   The men's basketball team, which had another quality road win
Saturday night, 79-77 at Oregon, doesn't play at home again until
Dec.28. The Matadors were dead last in home attendance in the Big
Sky last year, averaging 823 fans per game. The women also were
last, averaging only 379 in an arena which seats 1,600.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find a way to generate enthusiasm,'' Dull said.
</P>
<P>
   Moving on: Brooke Michelle resigned as the athletic department's
director of marketing and promotions last month to take a marketing
position with WinStar Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle is the fourth high-ranking department employee to leave
this year, following Brian Swanson (assistant athletic
director/external affairs), Michael Rehm (assistant athletic
director/development) and Kathy Heitzman (director of compliance).
</P>
<P>
   Dull combined Swanson and Rehm's positions _ and salaries _ to
attract experienced candidates for the crucial task of fund-raising
for the department. He said the job will be filled in the next
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be somebody that has the ability to interact
with the (university's) development office,'' said Dull, who added
his preferred priorities for the new person should be ``developing
a plan and doing research.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect the person to be out on the street the first
day, asking for money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Skeleton crew: The new director of compliance will be announced
this week, as early as today. Tom Shannon, the athletic
department's faculty representative, has been in charge of
compliance since Heitzman left last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon hasn't been the only employee taking on more work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here is doing more than one job,'' Dull said. ``It's
extended everybody. It's not been easy.''
</P>
<P>
   And the winners are ...: Michael Preis, a senior men's soccer
player, and junior women's swimmer Lisa Andrade were selected as
CSUN's athletes of the month for November.
</P>
<P>
   Preis, a forward, scored two goals, his 10th and 11th of the
season in the season finale, against Loyola Marymount on Nov.7. He
finished sixth on the school's career chart for goals (35), fifth
in assists (27) and sixth in points (97).
</P>
<P>
   Andrade, a transfer from Riverside Community College, went
undefeated in November and won the 100 and 200 breaststrokes at the
Malibu Invitational on Nov. 19-20.
</P>
<P>
   Difficult circumstances: Tara Harrington, an assistant women's
basketball coach at CSUN last season who took a similar position at
Montana State in the summer, was elevated to the Bobcats' top
assistant job last week.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, a Stanford graduate, was hired at Northridge 1{
years ago by then-head coach Michael Abraham, who resigned last
year after he was arrested for cocaine trafficking. Harrington's
new boss, MSU head coach Tracey Sheehan, was fired in November for
alleged NCAA violations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
