u e BC-R-BESTSELLERS-PAPER-S     12-13 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BESTSELLERS-PAPER-S-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Dec. 19)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Dec. 4 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE,
</P>
<P>
   by J.K. Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   2. JEWELS OF THE SUN, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   An American woman, studying folklore in Ireland,
</P>
<P>
   unexpectedly finds romance.
</P>
<P>
   3. VINEGAR HILL, by A. Manette Ansay. (Avon, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman moves with her children and unemployed husband
</P>
<P>
   to live with his loveless family.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE GREEN MILE, by Stephen King. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A six-part thriller set on death row at Cold Mountain
</P>
<P>
   Penitentiary.
</P>
<P>
   5. TOM CLANCY'S POWER PLAYS: Shadow Watch, created by
</P>
<P>
   Tom Clancy and Martin Greenberg. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Terrorists target a space station project in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   6. MIRROR IMAGE, by Danielle Steel. (Dell, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Identical twin sisters experience dissimilar lives
</P>
<P>
   in New York and France early in this century.
</P>
<P>
   7. SEIZE THE NIGHT, by Dean Koontz. (Bantam, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Snow seeks to discover why children in
</P>
<P>
   his hometown keep disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE HAMMER OF EDEN, by Ken Follett. (Fawcett, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   An FBI agent finds herself on the trail of terrorists
</P>
<P>
   planning a man-made earthquake in California.
</P>
<P>
   9. INTO THE GARDEN, by V.C. Andrews. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Four troubled teen-age girls, subjects of the Wildflowers
</P>
<P>
   series, stage a revealing reunion.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE SIMPLE TRUTH, by David Baldacci. (Warner,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) An appeal by a man serving a life sentence
</P>
<P>
   for murder creates chaos in Washington's legal
</P>
<P>
   community.
</P>
<P>
   11. POKEMON: Mewtwo Strikes Back and Pikachu's Vacation,
</P>
<P>
   adapted by Tracey West. (Scholastic, $4.99 and $4.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated adaptations of ``Pokemon'' stories.
</P>
<P>
   12. POKEMON: Nos. 1-4, by Tracey West. (Scholastic,
</P>
<P>
   $4.50 each.) Stories about the characters currently
</P>
<P>
   popular with children.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE PRESENT, by Johanna Lindsey. (Avon, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected arrival of an old journal changes the
</P>
<P>
   life of everyone attending a Malory family Christmas
</P>
<P>
   reunion.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE POISONWOOD BIBLE, by Barbara Kingsolver. (Harper/
</P>
<P>
   Perennial, $14.) Five female characters narrate a novel
</P>
<P>
   set in the Belgian Congo during that country's fight
</P>
<P>
   for independence.
</P>
<P>
   15. LEFT BEHIND, by Tim LaHaye and Jerry B. Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Tyndale, $13.99.) Life as lived by those who survive
</P>
<P>
   a global cataclysm. (b)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer recalls his childhood
</P>
<P>
   amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   2. BLIND MAN'S BLUFF, by Sherry Sontag and Christopher
</P>
<P>
   Drew with Annette Lawrence Drew. (HarperPaperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) American espionage by submarine, from the
</P>
<P>
   Cold War to the present.
</P>
<P>
   3. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a single
</P>
<P>
   crew.
</P>
<P>
   5.(x) THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $13.) How a murderer helped James
</P>
<P>
   Murray compile the Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   6. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man
</P>
<P>
   who survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   7. OUR DUMB CENTURY, edited by Scott Dikkers. (Three
</P>
<P>
   Rivers, $15.) Newspaper headlines making fun of the great
</P>
<P>
   events of the past century.
</P>
<P>
   8.(x) THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $10.95.) The author of ``A Child
</P>
<P>
   Called `It''' recalls his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   9. GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance to
</P>
<P>
   geographical advantages. (b)
</P>
<P>
   10.(x) INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest season in
</P>
<P>
   history.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   12. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   13. OPHELIA SPEAKS, by Sara Shandler. (HarperPerennial,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) Adolescent girls discuss their feelings about
</P>
<P>
   themselves and about life.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) MIDNIGHT IN THE GARDEN OF GOOD AND EVIL, by John
</P>
<P>
   Berendt. (Vintage, $12.) The mysterious death of a young
</P>
<P>
   man in Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) THE GIFTS OF THE JEWS, by Thomas Cahill. (Talese/
</P>
<P>
   Anchor/Doubleday, $14.) What Western civilization owes
</P>
<P>
   an ancient nomadic tribe.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) PERFECT MURDER, PERFECT TOWN, by Lawrence Schiller.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPaperbacks, $7.99.) The death of JonBenet Ramsey
</P>
<P>
   and its effect on the city of Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE OFFICIAL POKEMON HANDBOOK, by Maria S. Barbo.
</P>
<P>
   (Scholastic, $9.99.) A guide to the characters currently
</P>
<P>
   popular in the movie and television show and as collectible
</P>
<P>
   toys.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE CARBOHYDRATE ADDICT'S DIET, by Rachael F. Heller
</P>
<P>
   and Richard F. Heller. (Signet, $6.99.) A program for
</P>
<P>
   weight loss. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14 and $6.99.) Ways to lose weight and achieve
</P>
<P>
   a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. THE CARBOHYDRATE ADDICT'S LIFESPAN PROGRAM, by Richard
</P>
<P>
   F. Heller and Rachael F. Heller. (Plume, $15.95.) How to lose
</P>
<P>
   weight and become fit in middle age. (b)
