<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 08:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7204 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TA     12-13 1679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anonymous vs. Anonymous, Or Poor Little Rich Girl  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F. Scott Fitzgerald wrote 75 years ago about trying to economize
in his magazine article, ``How to Live on Practically Nothing a
Year.'' A $100-a-month governess offered to work for $40 a month
``and do the baby's washing.'' Patricia Duff, the most recent
ex-wife of the billionaire Ronald Perelman, may be looking for such
a governess. Justice Franklin Weissberg of New York state Supreme
Court rejected her request for as much as $132,000 a month in child
support, ordering Perelman to pay $12,825 a month for the couple's
4-year-old daughter, Caleigh.
</P>
<P>
   In his 22-page decision, the judge, who takes a brown-bag lunch
to court every day and who showed signs of impatience with Ms. Duff
during hearings in September, dismissed Ms. Duff's demands for more
money with words like ``absurd'' and ``rubbish.''
</P>
<P>
   He also seemed intent on seeing that state child-support
guidelines were not used to redistribute wealth. Perelman's income
ranges from $40 million to $60 million yearly, the judge said,
while Ms. Duff's is about $2.4 million yearly. Her lawyers argued
that having a mere millionaire for a mother would hurt Caleigh
psychologically. ``There is not a shred of evidence in the record
to support these conclusions,'' the judge said. ``There are far
more important things in the life of a young child than private
jets, yachts, obsequious staffs and pandering guests. The reality
is that Caleigh will never suffer a shortage of material
comforts.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES BARRON
</P>
<P>
   Peaceful Clash of Symbols &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While decorating a Christmas tree or lighting the candles of the
Hanukkah menorah are joyous activities in most households, many
interfaith couples find December holidays a source of angst.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, couples, especially Christians and Jews, would
forgo one holiday or display all the symbols together. But as the
rate of religious intermarriage increases in America _ today some
50 percent of Jews marry outside their faith, up sharply from
previous decades _ many families have developed an alternative:
religious syncretism, or the blending of two different, dissimilar
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The marketplace has responded by producing dual-faith
decorations: tree ornaments painted with menorahs or Kwanzaa
lights; angels with wings, halos and dreidel-print dresses; and
Christmas lights that have Stars of David.
</P>
<P>
   The devout deplore such melding. ``It is a terrible sign of
intellectual and religious confusion,'' says Elliott Abrams, who
wrote ``Faith or Fear: How Jews Can Survive in a Christian America
(Free Press, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   But to many, the ornaments are peacemakers. Susan Greenberg, a
Jew who has two children with a husband who was raised Christian,
says, ``It is our way of carving out our own particular family
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LESLIE KAUFMAN
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear Engineer Charged With Stealing Data  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in New Mexico indicted a nuclear engineer
on 59 counts of stealing highly classified nuclear data from secure
computers at the Los Alamos weapons lab where he worked. The
engineer, Wen Ho Lee, whose case has been furiously debated within
the cloistered worlds of counterintelligence, law enforcement and
nuclear energy, was not charged with espionage although
investigators have unsuccessfully tried to determine whether he
passed secrets to China. The crime Lee is charged with is
punishable by a maximum sentence of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Lost: Large Spacecraft
</P>
<P>
   The eagle did not land.
</P>
<P>
   That was NASA's conclusion after the $165 million Mars Polar
Lander failed to signal home. The agency promised a thorough
investigation of the causes and implications behind the
spacecraft's disappearance and a ``major rethinking'' of the
strategy for the entire Mars exploration program. In September the
lander's companion craft, Mars Climate Orbiter, which cost $125
million, was lost as it approached the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Death and a Bid for Attention
</P>
<P>
   At first, police believed they were looking for two hooded
assailants who tried to gain entry to Edmond Safra's lavish Monte
Carlo penthouse and then set a fire that killed the billionaire
banker and one of his nurses as they huddled for safety in a
bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   But now investigators said another of Safra's nurses, Ted Maher,
has confessed to making the whole story up. There never were any
masked men brandishing knives in the predawn hours of Dec. 3. Maher
admitted that he had concocted the story, slashed his own leg and
started the fire himself, so he could be seen as a hero.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SUZANNE DALEY
</P>
<P>
   Ruling for Another View
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one years after the assassination of the Rev. Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr., a jury in Memphis, Tenn., held someone
accountable. After an odd four-week trial in a civil case brought
by King's family, the jury found that Loyd Jowers, 73, was liable
for the civil rights leader's wrongful death. The Kings' lawyer,
who once represented James Earl Ray, argued that Jowers acted as
part of a sweeping government and Mafia conspiracy. Jowers, who did
not testify, has claimed to have been a middleman between a
mob-connected grocer and the now-deceased Memphis police officer
who he has named as the gunman.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEVIN SACK
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: KEVIN SACK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Errors and Patients' Rights  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Acting on recommendations from the Institute of Medicine,
President Clinton ordered federal agencies to find ways to reduce
medical errors that injure and kill tens of thousands of patients
each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insuring patient safety is not about fixing blame,'' Clinton
said in announcing his initiative. ``It's about fixing problems in
an increasingly complex system, about creating a culture of safety
and an environment where medical errors are not tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Health care providers promised to support the effort, but
emphasized that it must not expose them to any increase in lawsuits
or liability.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT PEAR
</P>
<P>
   A Paper Trail in Switzerland  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Testifying in front of Congress in 1996, representatives of
Swiss banks said they knew exactly how many dormant Nazi-era
accounts were still on their books: 775. As the controversy over
how these banks handled Jews in particular intensified, the figure
rose to the thousands. Last week, former Federal Reserve Chairman
Paul Volcker said a three-year audit he supervised put the figure
closer to 54,000. Some banks, he said, issued ``deliberately
misleading statements'' to keep Jews from recovering their assets.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Latest Casualty  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The protests in Seattle may have calmed down since the World
Trade Organization talks ended, but turmoil continues. The police
chief announced his resignation, saying he wanted to
``de-politicize'' investigations into how his force handled
demonstrators. More than 600 people were arrested, and the police
used tear gas and rubber bullets to disperse some crowds, while
vandals went unchecked elsewhere. Irate protesters, merchants and
bystanders jammed the first City Council meeting focusing on the
debacle.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK
</P>
<P>
   Shots Ring Out, Again  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 13-year-old boy described by friends as pleasant and friendly
opened fire at his middle school in rural Fort Gibson, Okla.,
injuring five students and leaving investigators baffled.
Prosecutors are expected to file charges, accusing the boy of
shooting his father's 9-millimeter handgun into a crowd of students
waiting outside Fort Gibson Middle School before the morning bell.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JIM YARDLEY
</P>
<P>
   Not All Cell Phones Are Safe Calls  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two Israeli researchers say they have cracked a cell phone code
that protects private conversations and data transmissions. The
encryption method is part of the Groupe Speciale Mobile, or GSM,
wireless phone standard, the most widely used system in the world.
The researchers' method may make widespread eavesdropping possible.
Most cell phones in America, however, are based on other wireless
technologies, but companies like Pacific Bell and Omnipoint Corp.
use the GSM standard.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SARA ROBINSON
</P>
<P>
   Less a Benefit at Exxon  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Angering gay rights advocates, Exxon Mobil revoked a policy at
Mobil, which Exxon acquired last month, to offer health benefits to
partners of newly hired gay employees. Though five of six large
companies still do not offer such benefits, the trend, which has
been driven by a tight job market and changing attitudes, has been
to provide them.. Some municipalities also have ordinances that
prevent companies that do not offer the benefits from getting city
business.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Hope for Hemophiliacs  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have successfully used gene therapy to treat a form of
hemophilia. The results, which produced a blood-clotting protein
without adverse side effects, were reported in research connected
with hemophilia B, which affects about 5,000 Americans, or 20
percent of all hemophiliacs in America.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRENCE M. FISHER
</P>
<P>
   Hazardous to Flying  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors claimed a victory when an aircraft
maintenance company was found guilty of improperly handling
hazardous materials that investigators said caused the crash of
ValuJet Flight 592 and the deaths of 110 people. A fine is expected
to be set later.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICK BRAGG
</P>
<P>
   It Was a Very Bad Year  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a move that stunned the business world, Coca-Cola's chairman
and chief executive announced he would step down in April. The
52-year-old CEO, M. Douglas Ivester, who had been in the job barely
two years, said he was retiring after a past year in which
Coca-Cola ran into regulatory problems in Europe, faced the biggest
product recall in its history and saw its profits fall worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CONSTANCE L. HAYS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 0816EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
