<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 08:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7205 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-SCHOOLS-CHEATING-RE     12-13 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCHOOLS-CHEATING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEATING ON TESTS: THE HIGHER THE STAKES, THE GREATER THE
TEMPTATION? 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, investigators in New York City said they had
uncovered the most widespread public-school cheating scandal in the
nation, encompassing 32 schools, dozens of teachers and two
principals. The methods _ from teachers using palm cards to
overzealous test coaching _ were so varied and so widespread that
they might only be the tip of the iceberg, investigators contended.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same sort of thing occurred recently in Texas, where
school officials and politicians like Gov. George W. Bush were
brandishing the results of a standardized test to claim victory
over ignorance. There, too, a cheating scandal has erupted which
calls some of the achievement into doubt.
</P>
<P>
   While officials trumpet higher scores, it also appears that an
old staple of education is gaining ground: cheating. And it is not
just students who are the culprits, but adults: the teachers,
principals, superintendents and other administrators charged with
watching over them.
</P>
<P>
   This rash of dishonesty has spread at the same time that
superintendents and politicians across the country have set tough
new test-score targets for their school systems. A ``standards''
revolution is sweeping through the classroom, tying promotion and
graduation of students and even cash bonuses for everyone from
principals to cafeteria workers to measurable achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The current scandals have emboldened critics who question the
validity of standardized testing, in particular high-stakes,
high-pressure tests tied to promotion and graduation. And they have
sharpened the argument over whether it is possible to have
accountability without some form of testing.
</P>
<P>
   At one end of the spectrum are organizations like Fair Test,
based in Boston, a group that monitors testing abuses and has been
a staunch critic of the testing industry. They see the new
accountability measures _ from publishing test scores in local
newspapers to state takeovers of failing schools _ as a way of
encouraging abuses. ``It's sort of like the Soviet Union; everybody
ends up lying,'' said Monty Neill, executive director of Fair Test.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-test groups oppose even the newest tests, which require
children to organize their ideas into a coherent essay and, in
math, ask them to explain their reasoning, not just present
answers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the fence are educators and scholars like
Diane Ravitch, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, who
passionately defends testing. ``To say that tests create cheating
is wrong,'' Dr. Ravitch said. ``What creates cheating is people who
cheat. If we spent as much time teaching kids as showing them the
answer, they might have learned to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of standards, tests and stark consequences for
failing to meet them _ like withholding high school diplomas _ say
that for too long, an officially sanctioned system of low
expectations has consigned many poor and disadvantaged children to
a second-class education.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about how hard it is to raise test scores, it
sounds like you are defending current practice,'' says Seymour
Fliegel, president of the Center for Educational Innovation in New
York City. New tests that require 9-year-olds to write essays with
correct spelling, grammar and punctuation are a far cry from the
multiple choice bubbles of the past, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the idea that kids should be able to find a main idea;
that they should know how to find supporting details; how to draw
an inference, vocabulary,'' Fliegel said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is evidence that testing has always encouraged
cheating, at least where the stakes were high enough.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Haney, a professor at the Center for the Study of Testing
at Boston College, points out that the current debate is following
a pattern established in 19th century England. A program called
``Payment by Results'' reigned in English and Welsh elementary
schools from 1862 to 1897. Every student was examined annually by a
royal inspector, and teachers received government grants if their
students performed well. Among the results were that teachers
school-hopped, looking for positions that would pay better.
</P>
<P>
   There were also complaints that teachers tried to get copies of
arithmetic questions used in other schools, and then drilled their
students in them, in the hope of raising test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Test preparation is one of those ethical gray areas, where the
line between what is legitimate and illegitimate may be ill
defined. In fact, many school districts not only sanction test
preparation but spend large portions of their budgets paying for
it.
</P>
<P>
   The public schools have embarked on a new mission _ or at least
begun a new fad. Suddenly, teachers and students are expected to
produce results. But the reality is that real change and real
progress in the schools is hard to produce and takes time. Cheating
may be one of the unintended consequences of the increasing
reliance on standardized tests and the pressure to perform better,
fast.
</P>
<P>
   That is one motivation behind the accusations in New York and
Texas. Last January, the Texas Education Agency sent letters to
Houston and 10 other school districts saying that an analysis of
test results showed that unusually high numbers of wrong answers
had been erased and replaced with correct ones. In April, the
county attorney in Austin charged the city's school district and a
top administrator with test tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials have publicized statistics showing a narrowing
achievement gap between white students, who typically score higher,
and blacks and Hispanics. But in a legal challenge to the tests, an
expert witness has testified that 10th-grade test scores among
black and Hispanic children have been inflated by holding back
those who are failing, so they are not counted in the results.
</P>
<P>
   Even when tests are conducted honestly and scores do go up
sharply, it is often for reasons that have little to do with
improvements in teaching or learning. More commonly, the big jumps
_ what statisticians call statistical outliers _ betray something
more insidious at work: a new magnet program that attracts more
affluent or gifted students, perhaps, or test preparation mania.
Ultimately, standardized tests are probably most useful in
measuring the improvement, or decline, of an educational system
over an extended period of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 0817EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
