character of Boris, a Russian hacker, who fulfilled a
double-villain quotient by combining a Cold War bad guy with a
cyber world one. Not only does Boris betray his best friend, but he
also has the obnoxious habit of screaming ``I am invincible!'' (To
the contrary, he is frozen by a plume of liquid hydrogen.)
</P>
<P>
   Hacker advocates complained to Miramax Films last year about the
early version of a screenplay of ``Takedown,'' which is based on
the 1996 book by Tsutomu Shimomura with John Markoff of The New
York Times about the capture of Kevin Mitnick, who pleaded guilty
in March to computer fraud and wire fraud and was sentenced to 46
months. They were concerned about a scene in which the Mitnick
character attacked a pursuer with a garbage can lid and several
others they say were invented. Emmanuel Goldstein, who publishes
2600, a hacker magazine, called the initial depiction of Mitnick a
``low blow'' but added that the film company had been receptive to
the hackers' complaints and made changes in the script. Miramax
spokesman Andrew Stengel had no comment on the film, which is in
post-production.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein and others who cover the hacker world say negative
depictions are part of the media's and the public's limited grasp
of what computers _ and the people who master them _ can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has a tendency to vilify what they don't
understand,'' said Luke Reiter, a reporter for the interactive
cable channel ZDTV, which covers the Internet. ``And there's a
certain amount of unknown about what happens with a hacker: who he
is, what he looks like. People simply don't know what that person
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Wellen, who also covers the hacker community for ZDTV,
pointed out that while hackers often work in positive ways _
testing computer security and tracking down child pornography
rings, for example _ much of the news the public gets is bad. Last
week, a New Jersey hacker, David Lee Smith, pleaded guilty to
creating the ``Melissa'' virus, the most widely spread, disruptive
and costly computer virus in history.
</P>
<P>
   The daily annoyances of the computer age perhaps contribute to
the artist's distrust of those who glibly navigate cyberspace. The
demise of the hero in ``Y2K'' was inspired by an actual incident in
which Kopit's hard drive crashed while he was writing the play.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe computer bad guys are just more fun to watch, Wellen said.
``Portraying someone as a villain is much more interesting than
someone who can recognize a security flaw in a computer system,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always like this. Take ``War Games,'' the 1983 movie
that is arguably the parent of all hacker movies, plays or
television shows. The film starred Matthew Broderick as David
Lightman, a nerdy but nice computer enthusiast whose idea of making
trouble was changing a chemistry grade. Granted, he nearly starts
World War III looking for free video games, but in the end he
outsmarts a supercomputer to avert a global thermonuclear
catastrophe and teach us a valuable lesson about the futility of
armed conflict. (``The only way to win is not to play.'')
</P>
<P>
   The cinematic watershed seemed to occur around 1995, which
brought not only ``The Net'' and ``Goldeneye,'' but also
``Hackers,'' a B-movie about a gang of high school computer
whizzes. But it wasn't the subject matter that was important, it
was the lifestyle. The hackers in ``Hackers'' smoked. They listened
to techno music. They had sex. They were, well, hip.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Keanu Reeves (``The Matrix'') and Tom Cruise
(``Mission: Impossible'') were playing characters who hack. Things
would never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the growing pantheon of characters matches the
reality is an open question. ``There really are no absolutes in
personality, style or viewpoint in the hacker community,'' said
Reiter. ``I mean, some wear leather jackets, some wear Armani
suits.''
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the character is still open for writers. Hackers in
bikinis? Why not? Hackers in love? Let the writing begin.
</P>
<P>
   All of which seems to support the credo of Kopit's beleaguered
hero in ``Y2K.'' Quoting Gustave Flaubert, he says, ``Everything
you invent is true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 0819EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
