<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 08:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7238 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-TOBACCO-GUNS-REVIEW     12-13 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TOBACCO-GUNS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT JUST LOOKS LIKE A SMOKING GUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the past year, 28 cities have filed suits against firearms
manufacturers seeking monetary damages and changes in the ways guns
are sold in the United States. Two states, New York and
Connecticut, have threatened to sue, and last week federal
officials announced that they would help public housing authorities
nationwide file suit to force gun makers to sell safer firearms and
do more to keep them out of criminal hands.
</P>
<P>
   To many, it appears the fight against guns is a sequel to the
tobacco war _ a struggle against products that kill, and against
industries that have dodged or defeated change in Congress. And now
gun makers, like tobacco producers who paid $246 billion and agreed
to change marketing practices to settle state lawsuits, are facing
a reckoning in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The gun industry, with about $1.5 billion in annual U.S. sales,
is tiny relative to the domestic tobacco business, with sales of
$45 billion. So money will not loom nearly so large as it has in
the tobacco settlements. Nonetheless, as with the anti-tobacco
campaign, gun control advocates are using the specter of ruinous
monetary awards to force the gun manufacturers to change the way
they do business. Specifically, they are being asked to place
additional safeguards on guns to prevent accidental shootings, and
to restrict sales to dealers whose guns frequently turn up in the
commission of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But the parallels between guns and tobacco may be overdrawn, and
the success of the tobacco lawsuits may be harder to achieve in a
different industry.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike tobacco, which is harmful when used as intended, guns
have multiple safe and proper uses, from target practice to
collecting to hunting. As a result, legal experts say, the gun
lawsuits appear to be weaker than the anti-tobacco claims.
</P>
<P>
   Cities such as New Orleans, Chicago and Detroit want to be
reimbursed for expenses incurred treating gunshot victims. These
suits are modeled on the cigarette cases, in which states sought to
recover public funds spent treating smoking-related illnesses by
arguing that cigarette makers had not properly disclosed the risks
of smoking. That novel legal theory was never resolved because all
the cases were settled before verdict.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephen Gillers, a professor at New York University Law
School, said the cause-and-effect legal claim that underpins the
gun cases appears far weaker than in the tobacco lawsuits.
Manufacturers have little control over what owners do with their
guns. In addition, the expenses that public agencies might have the
right to recover are also unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Public housing authorities, for example, might claim they are
owed money because one person shot another on their premises. But,
Gillers said, ``There is an extra beat because an individual is
involved. The direct causation was more obvious in tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, that may not matter. Gillers and others note
that some manufacturers have already begun to seek compromise at
the bargaining table, faced with their opponents' strategy of legal
attrition. By contrast, it took years before tobacco makers entered
such talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the type of industry that is going to be able to
mount the type of long-term resistance that cigarette producers
were able to do,'' said Peter Schuck, a professor of law at Yale
University.
</P>
<P>
   While cigarette producers are multinational titans, the gun
industry includes only a few sizeable companies like Colt
Manufacturing and Smith &AMP; Wesson, and dozens of small ones.
Moreover, the industry is not unified; some producers have entered
settlement talks, others have shunned them.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, even if gun opponents falter in court, they may
still win their war. Already four smaller manufacturers, citing the
growing litigation, have filed for bankruptcy protection. Colt
Manufacturing, fearful of growing legal costs, has held initial
settlement talks, while other large manufacturers are working on
codes of conduct for dealers, hoping to slow indiscriminate sales.
</P>
<P>
   John Lott, a law professor at the University of Chicago who has
written about the value of guns as a crime deterrent, said that the
lawsuits are simply an effort by public officials to strong arm a
weak industry into submission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy is to maximize the legal costs on the industry so
it will fold,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who are sympathetic to the lawsuits tend to agree.
``That is the way our legal system works,'' said Robert Rabin, a
law professor at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   There are no guarantees that settlement talks will be
successful, even in the event of a broad agreement. That's because
the decentralized nature of the gun industry might frustrate its
effective implementation. Once again, the tobacco industry offers a
useful contrast. Tobacco sales are controlled by only a few
companies, but negotiators still had to carefully construct a deal
that prevented smaller companies or new ones from ignoring
settlement-imposed price hikes and marketing restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The gun industry includes any number of small companies, some of
them based overseas, a large market in used guns, and a national
gun show circuit, all of which may be difficult to monitor and
control.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some gun supporters like Lott believe that
gun control efforts will prove effective, but only in those parts
of the market where guns don't pose a serious risk. Lott sees the
lawsuits as a well-meaning but misguided attempt at social
engineering, which will only make it harder for honest people,
particularly poor ones, to buy guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only see bad things coming out of it,'' he said. ``There is
so much consciousness about the bad things that guns do that people
do not think about the defensive use of guns.''
</P>
<P>
   But others, like Timothy Lytton, a professor at New York Law
School, said that the gun industry found itself on the defensive
because gun control advocates successfully changed the terms of the
debate from the right to bear arms to public health. And, just as
with tobacco, once the debate was reframed to emphasize the cost to
society, the roadblocks to industry regulation began to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to solve all gun crimes,'' Lytton said.
``But if it is true that a significant number of guns are being
sold irresponsibly then changing the practices of manufacturers can
change that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 0826EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
