<P>
   In addition, he has a great deal to say about what happens in
Lebanon, which ended its civil war in the 1980s only by turning to
Syria as a power broker and inviting in its army. Lebanon remains a
base for guerrilla attacks on Israel, which keeps control of a
tense buffer zone that is the scene of frequent bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, for more than a decade, one of the biggest
questions in the Middle East has been when Assad might see
advantage in aggressively seeking a deal. With the surprise
announcement last week that he was ready to send his foreign
minister to Washington to meet with Israel's prime minister, a new
question looms: Might this really be the moment?
</P>
<P>
   There is good reason to think so, and not just because of the
small shift in his stance that opened the way toward peace talks
when Secretary of State Madeleine Albright visited Damascus early
in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Behind that shift lies a broader sense not only of new
opportunity, but of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   Until early this year, Assad had always carried himself as if
time did not matter. He had prided himself on his refusal to
compromise; to win peace, Israel would have to withdraw from every
inch of the Golan Heights. In recent months, his government had
gone further, saying that even to restart talks, Israel would have
to publicly commit itself to borders that existed before the 1967
war, something Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak, would not do.
</P>
<P>
   But Assad is 69 now and clearly ill. Since early this year, he
has seemed preoccupied by a need to cement the position of his son,
Bashar, 34, as his heir apparent, and his decision to return to the
talks without such a public Israeli commitment suggests a further
recognition that it would be foolhardy to wait too long.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Assad feels peace with Israel would guarantee his place
in history. But perhaps more important, it could transform Syria's
domestic environment to his son's advantage. The younger Assad is a
staff colonel, but he has little military experience and lacks the
confidence of the former Baath Party bosses and long-serving
generals. His strength is his close ties with Syria's business
community. So it seems logical that a Syria at peace, with an eye
on prosperity rather than security, would be a far easier place in
which to establish himself in power.
</P>
<P>
   To Syrian ears, another clock has begun to tick more loudly than
ever _ the one marking progress toward a final Israeli-Palestinian
peace. With the Israelis and Palestinians now pledging to wind up
their final peace talks by late next year, Assad does not want to
find himself shut completely out of the circle of peace _ including
decisions to be made on the fate of Palestinian refugees, more than
500,000 of whom now live in Syria or Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The winding down of President Clinton's last term is yet another
ticking clock, this one measuring how long the White House might be
willing to put pressure on Israel to cement Clinton's own legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, of course, has been here before. The talks in Washington
are to begin ``at the point where they left off'' nearly four years
ago, when Israel walked out after Islamic militants launched a
bus-bombing campaign in Israel, soon to be followed by an all-out
conflict in southern Lebanon between Israeli forces and the
Syrian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   That history shows how easily peace can be sidetracked by
violence. But this time, as Assad clearly recognizes, changes in
the Middle East have presented Syria with better opportunities _
particularly in Lebanon _ to untangle itself from its conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-R-MIDEAST-SYRIA-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BEIRUT: its conflicts. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As one price for peace, Israel has made clear its demand that
Syria rein in Hezbollah, the Lebanese guerrillas whose attacks on
Israeli forces and towns have been used by Damascus to put pressure
on Israel. But doing that is not like turning off a tap.
</P>
<P>
   Armed by Iran and fueled by Iranian-inspired ardor, the
guerrillas are subject only to indirect Syrian control. Four years
ago, a Syrian attempt to shut them down almost surely would have
been met with open rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not the Lebanon of four years ago, in part because
Iran, too, has changed. The Revolutionary Guards who once trained
militants in the art of terror in Lebanon's lawless Bekaa Valley
have long since departed. And since Mohammed Khatami assumed Iran's
presidency in 1997, he has been trying to put an end to Iran's
isolation, even though he still faces opposition on that score from
very powerful conservatives. That power struggle in Tehran
presumably gives Assad some room to maneuver if he wants to curb
the militants.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Assad's government warned Palestinian militants
based in Syria that if peace were to come, it would be time to find
a new line of work. Through Bashar Assad, Syria later sent the same
message to Hezbollah. Among diplomats in Lebanon, the betting is
that if peace were to come soon, the message would be heeded.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even if the new road leads to peace, the path is
unlikely to be straight. Syria and Israel have been enemies for 50
years, and much distrust still lies between them. Many skeptics in
Israel and the United States think Assad's opening was just a
sucker bid, intended to lure Israel into a big concession or,
perhaps, to persuade the United States to end sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Assad's associates say he frowns on the theatrics that have come
to be associated with Middle East peacemaking. Still, simply by
dispatching Farouk al-Sharaa, his foreign minister and closest
adviser, to Washington this week, Assad knows that he is sending a
new signal; never before has so a high-ranking a Syrian official
held direct talks with an Israeli delegation.
</P>
<P>
   If Assad himself joins any talks, diplomats here guess, it will
not be until the final moments, when a deal is ready to be signed.
But for the first time in memory, the diplomats say, that prospect
now seems more real than fanciful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
