 &HT;     (EDS: Repeating for all needing)    U.S. AND RUSSIA WORK TO
PREVENT THE ULTIMATE Y2K PROBLEM    (For use by New York Times News
Service clients.)    By ERIC ROSENBERG    c.1999 Hearst
<TEXT>
Newspapers &LR;  &QC;  WASHINGTON _ A small group of U.S. and Russian
military officers won't be doing much New Year's Eve cork-popping
as the millennium arrives at midnight on Dec. 31. Instead, they
will be guarding against the end of the world. Their concern is the
ultimate Y2K catastrophe: Computer glitches causing the launch of
nuclear-tipped ballistic missiles. The U.S. and Russian governments
have been working to fix the potential Y2K glitches in their
missile systems and early warning defense equipment. And officials
from both countries stress that the likelihood of a mistaken Y2K
missile launch is extremely remote. But to reassure a jittery world
public and further cut the risk of a Y2K accident, the governments
of the two nuclear superpowers have set up a joint command center
at Peterson Air Force Base at Colorado Springs, Colo., to help
protect against such an accident. The year 2000 problem, commonly
called Y2K, refers to the possibility that computers programmed to
read only the last two digits of a year might interpret the change
from 1999 to 2000 as going from 1999 to 1900. This could cause the
computers to crash; interfering with utility services, banking,
aviation and any other sector that relies computers. While most
essential civilian and military computers in the United States have
been deemed ``Y2K-compliant,'' other countries, including Russia,
are having difficulties. In fact, the State Department is so
worried about computer troubles there and in three former Soviet
republics that it is withdrawing hundreds of employees through the
New Year period. But the ultimate Y2K mishap would be nuclear war.
That's why, for three weeks starting Dec. 22, some 33 Russian and
U.S. military officers will stand around-the-clock vigils over
consoles and computer screens that would alert them to missile
launches around most of the world. Their information will be
collected from a network of radars and satellites operated by the
nearby Cheyenne Moun
 &Cx1f; .Arsjm4Xm9%
</TEXT>
