<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 09:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7258 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-BOOKS-HOLIDAY-4TAKES-     12-13 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-HOLIDAY-4TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUT THE WORLD IN SOMEONE'S HANDS WITH THESE HOLIDAY BOOKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By FRITZ LANHAM 
and LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's another reason to give books this holiday season: They're
Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Give them with the confidence that they won't blow up on Jan. 1.
Of course, recipients may have to read them by candlelight, but
that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   Even in this dot-com-crazy era, books remain among the most
appreciated of presents. But the bookstores are bulging. What to
buy?
</P>
<P>
   As we do every year, we have scouted the terrain and put
together some suggestions. Most of these books fall into the
category of oversized, coffee-table tomes. But in every case we've
sought out books that engage the mind as well as please the eye.
</P>
<P>
   We've also tried to cast a wide net. You'll find books here on a
score of subjects, from art and fashion to history and travel, to
sport, religion, science and literature.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone want to guess the most common word on gift-book covers
this year?
</P>
<P>
   ``Century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Century in ...'' politics, photographs, sports. You get
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the best of these looking-back books, along with a list
of also-rans.
</P>
<P>
   Doorstop-of-the-season honors go to ``Century'' (Phaidon,
$49.95), a 1,120-page collection of photographs edited by Bruce
Bernard.
</P>
<P>
   This monster weighs in at 12.7 pounds, contains more than 1,100
photos and comes encased in a box with a handle. Don't give this
one to your uncle with the bad back.
</P>
<P>
   Subtitled ``100 Years of Human Progress, Regression, Suffering
and Hope, 1899-1999,'' this selection is arranged chronologically.
The emphasis is on politics and war _ the ``regression'' and
``suffering'' of the subtitle _ although entertainment and social
trends also receive attention.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard, a longtime photo editor for British newspapers, made a
deliberate decision to avoid photos we've seen over and over.
Together with its superb production values and reasonable price,
that sets this book apart.
</P>
<P>
   The title ``Letters of the Century: America 1900-1999'' (Dial,
$35) may elicit yawns. But make no mistake, this 741-page
collection of letters from people famous and obscure, edited by
Lisa Grunwald and Stephen J. Adler, is a very entertaining book.
</P>
<P>
   Dip in at random and come across Groucho Marx's hilarious
missives describing the plot of ``A Night in Casablanca'' to a
suspicious Warner Bros. legal department, Gen. George Patton's 1940
letter to then-Maj. Dwight Eisenhower promising him a job (``Hoping
we are together in a long and BLOODY war''), and Janis Joplin's
letter to her parents announcing she'd run off to San Francisco to
be a rock star.
</P>
<P>
   In tone and subject, the letters range from the intimate to the
officious, from the foaming to the fawning, from the profound to
the puerile. This is history on a human scale.
</P>
<P>
   Many ``Century'' books suffer from bland, lackluster prose. Here
are two exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People of the Century'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $35), a joint
project of Time magazine and CBS News, profiles ``100 men and women
who shaped the last 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The selectees are the usual suspects. Fortunately, the profilers
are name writers and journalists who treat their subjects with
sympathy but, for the most part, without awe. You get Salman
Rushdie on Mohandas Gandhi; crime novelist Edna Buchanan on Mafia
don Lucky Luciano; Molly Ivins on Willis Carrier, the man who
invented air conditioning; and Henry Kissinger on soccer star Pele.
</P>
<P>
   The profiles are brief, three to four pages long, and
complemented with well-chosen photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``ESPN SportsCentury,`` edited by Michael MacCambridge
(Hyperion, $40), also assembles an all-star cast of contributors,
whose efforts are longer and more essayistic.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Carol Oates takes the measure of Muhammad Ali; Roy Blount
Jr. compares the achievements of Joe DiMaggio and Ted Williams;
Thomas Boswell delivers a tough-minded assessment of Pete Rose's
success on the field and moral failings off the field; and Nelson
George writes about Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Shorter profiles of other sports figures are shoehorned around
these longer pieces, making for an attractive and satisfying book.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are these:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Century of Country: An Illustrated History of Country
Music,'' by Robert K. Oermann (TV Books, $39.95). This is the
companion volume to The Nashville Network's 13-hour documentary
series.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Life: Our Century in Pictures,'' edited by Richard B.
Stolley (Bullfinch, $60). If it wasn't pictured in Life magazine,
it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York Times Century of Business,'' edited by Floyd
Norris and Christine Bockelmann (McGraw-Hill, $29.95). Reprinted
Times articles form the basis of this history.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``National Geographic Eyewitness to the 20th
Century''(National Geographic Books, $40). Nice design, with more
text than you find in many surveys.
</P>
<P>
   For the literary-minded, the season brings good tidings: a
wonderful new edition of ``The Oxford Book of English Verse.''
First published at the dawn of the century, ``The Oxford Book of
English Verse, 1250-1900,'' edited by Arthur Quiller-Couch, quickly
established itself as the most popular and influential such
anthology in the language, selling nearly a half million copies
over the next 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   By midcentury, a new edition was needed, and in 1972 Helen
Gardner's ``The New Oxford Book of English Verse, 1250-1950,''
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Now Christopher Ricks has brought the collection up to date with
``The Oxford Book of English Verse'' (Oxford, $39.95), which
includes such postwar figures as Philip Larkin, Ted Hughes and
Seamus Heaney.
</P>
<P>
   Ricks also has broadened the coverage somewhat, including more
women (such as Charlotte Bronte) and Scottish poets. He's added
nursery rhymes and a larger helping of dramatic verse. Altogether,
Ricks has assembled some 800 poems covering nearly eight centuries
of British literary history.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of anthologies and textbooks over the years
perhaps has made ``The Oxford Book'' less essential than it once
was. But it remains a richly rewarding assemblage and a handsome,
convenient volume.
</P>
<P>
   If American poetry holds more appeal, consider ``The Poems of
Emily Dickinson,'' edited by R.W. Franklin (Harvard University
Press, $29.95), or ``Walt Whitman: Selected Poems, 1855-1892,''
edited by Gary Schmidgall (St. Martin's Press, $32.50).
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson and Whitman are the godmother and godfather of
American poetry, and there's no shortage of collections of their
work. So what sets these apart?
</P>
<P>
   Franklin's book is the ``reading edition'' of the three-volume
Variorum Edition published in 1998, in which he sorted through the
multiple versions of Dickinson's poems and numerous manuscripts she
left at her death to come up with versions that represent her final
wishes.
</P>
<P>
   The new book includes the largest number of Dickinson poems ever
assembled (1,789) and preserves her idiosyncratic spelling,
punctuation and capitalization. Well-printed and attractively
bound, this book is a good value.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of his long career, Whitman kept revising the
poems that make up his masterpiece, ``Leaves of Grass.'' Scholars
have long argued that this tinkering marred rather than made the
work _ that the later versions were tamer and more ``refined,''
less vital and exuberant, and that the older Whitman engaged in
what amounted to self-censorship.
</P>
<P>
   For this new edition, Schmidgall has assembled more than 200 of
Whitman's finest poems in their earliest published forms,
emphasizing works he wrote early in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Two short-story collections would make great gifts. ``The Best
Short Stories of the Century,'' edited by John Updike (Houghton
Mifflin, $28), was published earlier this year but has a new,
festive red cover for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   For this 768-page anthology, Updike selected the ``best''
stories from the annual ``Best American Short Stories'' volumes.
Started in 1915, that series is still going strong today.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to think of a major American writer who isn't here,
beginning with Ring Lardner, Ernest Hemingway and Katherine Anne
Porter and concluding with Alice Munro, Thom Jones and E. Annie
Proulx. This is a meeting of the giants.
</P>
<P>
   If Updike's book seems a bit fusty and predictable in its
selections, pick up ``The Art of the Story: An International
Anthology of Contemporary Short Stories,'' edited by Daniel Halpern
(Viking, $40). Halpern limited himself to authors born between 1938
and 1970 but considers writers from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   So you'll find familiar names such as Margaret Atwood, Raymond
Carver and Salman Rushdie, along with fine writers who are hardly
household names in the U.S.: Renaldo Arenas from Cuba, Patrick
Chamoiseau from Martinique and Tatyana Tolstaya from Russia, to
name three of the 78 contributors from 35 countries.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good book for fiction readers who want to broaden
their horizons.
</P>
<P>
   If a picture is worth a thousand words, a map may be worth
10,000. Every household should have a good atlas. There are plenty
on the market. ``The Hammond World Atlas, Third Edition'' ($69.95)
is first-rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This 11-by-14 1/4-inch book, with 312 pages, has large, crisply
rendered maps and a 100,000-entry master index. Complementing the
political maps are new digitized relief maps of the continents and
thematic maps on such topics as population growth, climate and
languages.
</P>
<P>
   This atlas gives us the world as it is today. To get a sense of
how we got here, nothing beats a good historical atlas. ``Atlas of
World History'' (Oxford University Press, $85) is pricey but
up-to-date and truly global in its treatment. The maps are not as
large as those in the ``Times Atlas of World History,'' for
example, but they are clear.
</P>
<P>
   Together with the heavy dose of text, they make up a course in
world history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three beautiful coffee-table books may fit the bill if you want
a Texas-flavored gift.
</P>
<P>
   First, from the University of Texas Press, there's the
spectacular ``Great Texas Birds,'' edited by Suzanne Winkler and
featuring 48 full-page, full-color paintings by artist John O'Neill
($34.95).
</P>
<P>
   Texas has some 600 species of birds, more than any other state.
O'Neill, who lives in Louisiana, here has limned some of our most
handsome, from the Harris's hawk to the roseate spoonbill to the
yellow-breasted chat. His paintings are highly detailed; the color
printing is first-rate.
</P>
<P>
   Writers and birders from around the state provide brief essays
to accompany the paintings. John Graves, Stephen Harrigan, and John
and Gloria Tveten are among the contributors. Some pieces emphasize
science, others personal experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great Texas Birds'' is one of those books you pick up and
can't put down.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer nature below your feet to nature above your head,
consider Blair Pittman's ``Texas Caves'' (Texas A&AMP;M University
Press, $34.95).
</P>
<P>
   In color photographs and text, Pittman covers the basics of
Texas caves and cave formations. His goal, he writes, is to reveal
the glories both of ``show'' caves, which are open to the public,
and of ``wild'' caves, which are not.
</P>
<P>
   Third, photographer Peter Brown's award-winning ``On the
Plains'' (Norton, $39.95) captures with sympathy the American
Plains, that flat landscape stretching from Texas to Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Brown turns his camera on people, cattle, buildings, the big
land, the bigger sky. His crisp, cleanly rendered color images
suggest less the harshness of the region than its quiet beauty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two remarkable books about Africa deserve note.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Louis Gates Jr.'s ``Wonders of the African World'' (Knopf,
$40) was written to accompany a PBS television series, but it's
important in its own right.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, who chairs Afro-American studies at Harvard University,
is one of the country's most insightful commentators on the black
American experience.
</P>
<P>
   His well-illustrated book is based on visits to five areas _
Ethiopia, Zimbabwe, northern Sudan and Egypt, East Africa and West
Africa _ to explore the little-understood and underappreciated
cultural achievements of Africans.
</P>
<P>
   Part history, part travelogue, ``Wonders of the African World''
is well-written and intellectually honest. While trumpeting
Africa's past greatness _ the Muslim scholars who gathered in
Timbuktu, the towers of Great Zimbabwe _ Gates doesn't engage in
mere cheerleading; for example, he wrestles throughout his visit
with the role Africans played in the slave trade.
</P>
<P>
   This is an excellent starting point for anyone who wants to
learn about Africa's past.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most massive new books of the holiday season is
``African Ceremonies,'' a two-volume slipcased set from Abrams
($150). It's much different from Gates' book, recording a world
more rural and traditional.
</P>
<P>
   Photographers Carol Beckwith and Angela Fisher have spent 30
years traveling and shooting pictures in Africa. Their book
contains nearly 850 color photographs of ceremonies attached to key
moments in human life: birth and death, courtship and marriage,
royal coronations, seasonal rituals. Many of these ceremonies are
dying out.
</P>
<P>
   Another companion book to an acclaimed PBS series is Ric Burns'
``New York: An Illustrated History'' (Knopf, $60). This 578-page
book, filled with arresting photos, is popular history at its best.
</P>
<P>
   For lovers of science and nature on your list, consider these:
</P>
<P>
   ``Snake'' by Chris Mattison (DK, $29.95) is a gorgeous book.
Like many from this publisher, it combines imaginative design with
bite-size bits of text.
</P>
<P>
   Get up close with the boomslang of southern Africa (favorite
food: chameleon). Discover why snake charmers like the monocled
cobra. Learn your chances of survival if bitten by the West African
green mamba (not good).
</P>
<P>
   From the same publisher comes the ``DK Great Dinosaur Atlas''
($19.95) by William Lindsay, illustrated by Giuliano Fornari.
Readers _ intended to be kids ages 8 and up _ come away with a
vivid sense of the variety of dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   For older readers, there's ``The Simon &AMP; Schuster Encyclopedia
of Dinosaurs and Prehistoric Creatures: A Visual Who's Who of
Prehistoric Life,'' revised by Douglas Parker ($40).
</P>
<P>
   Originally published in 1988, this reference work for the
serious student combines succinct scientific descriptions with
superbly rendered color illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``John James Audubon: Writings and Drawings,'' edited by
Christoph Irmscher ($40), is a volume in the acclaimed Library of
America series. Audubon, the 19th-century artist-naturalist best
known for his ``The Birds of America'' lithographs, was also a
prolific writer. This 942-page book includes 45 sketches from his
massive ``Ornithological Biography'' and excerpts from his journals
and letters. Sixty-four color plates give a sampling of his
illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   Both birds and machines are the subjects of ``The Miracle of
Flight'' (Firefly, $40). Author-photographer Stephen Dalton
explains in pictures and words exactly how it works.
</P>
<P>
   For real high flyers, there's ``The Planets'' by David McNab and
James Younger (Yale University Press, $35). The companion volume to
an A&AMP;E television series, it describes the birth and evolution of
each planet in our solar system and records efforts by astronomers
to learn more about them.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, ``Landmarks in Western Science: From Prehistory to the
Atomic Age'' by Peter Whitfield (Routledge, $35) is a useful survey
of the history of Western scientific developments. The book is
well-illustrated if somewhat dryly written.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford University Press has given us an ``Oxford Companion'' to
many a human activity. The latest addition to the list: ``The
Oxford Companion to Food'' by Alan Davidson ($60).
</P>
<P>
   Not a cookbook but a reference work, this 892-page book has more
than 2,600 entries covering almost every conceivable topic, from
Bedouin diet to offal and octopus, to Spam and Spanish mackerel, to
why we call the Mexican dish ``refried beans'' when the beans are
fried only once. The connoisseur will find this tasty, ample fare.
</P>
<P>
   This book joins ``The Oxford Companion to Wine,'' edited by
Jancis Robinson ($65). Similar in format, it has just been released
in an updated second edition.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer impressive new art books seem to be in stores this year.
One notable exception is ``Victorian Painting'' by Lionel Lambourne
(Phaidon, $59.95).
</P>
<P>
   Long viewed with condescension, Victorian painting has been
attracting more attention in recent years. Lambourne, former head
of paintings at the Victoria and Albert Museum in London, aims to
defend it from the charge of sentimentality and to persuade us to
look at it with a fresh eye.
</P>
<P>
   More than 600 color illustrations make this 512-page book
pleasing as well as educational.
</P>
<P>
   Victorian imagery filtered through a surrealist sensibility
animates the art of Philip C. Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   Now 92, Curtis has a limited reputation outside Phoenix, where
he's lived since 1947. His strange, evocative paintings have been
described as surrealism ``without the snarl and terror'' of Max
Ernst and Salvador Dali.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Dreamer: The Art of Philip C. Curtis'' (Hudson Hills,
$45), a project of the Phoenix Art Museum, is the place to make his
acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of strange, the Getty Museum has combined the lyrics of
Bob Dylan's 1965 downer ``Desolation Row'' with details of Belgian
artist James Ensor's ``Christ's Entry Into Brussels in 1889'' to
create ``The Superhuman Crew'' (J. Paul Getty Museum Publications,
$24).
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't know quite what to make of this, but the book comes
with a CD of Dylan's song, which holds up very well after 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   For more charm, there's ``Fay'' (Hyperion, $26.95), in which
photographer William Wegman pays tribute to his Weimaraner Fay Ray,
who succeeded his first dog, Man Ray, as the subject of his funny,
deadpan photographs. Fay died in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Many photographs will be familiar to those who have followed
Wegman over the years, but the book is an endearing homage.
</P>
<P>
   An inordinate number of books this season deal with France,
yesterday and today.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's because France, especially Paris, captured that
midcentury longing for a return to romanticism after the harsh
reality of war. It is a longing that has never quite deserted the
American psyche.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Paris lays claim to even a tiny part of someone's heart,
Peter Miller's ``The First Time I Saw Paris'' (Times Books, $30) is
the perfect not-so-big book. When he made his first trip to the
City of Light in the summer of 1954, Miller was a
wet-behind-the-ears 20-year-old from Vermont acting as an assistant
to portrait photographer Yousuf Karsh.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's involvement with photography was almost an accident;
he'd bought his first camera with an insurance check covering the
theft of his hunting rifles.
</P>
<P>
   Miller returned to Paris several years later as an Army Signal
Corps photographer. Over the next 2 1/2 years, during times he
could sneak away from his Army tasks, Miller took the photographs
that became the basis of this book _ photos on the Rue de la
Huchette in the Latin Quarter and on Rue Mouffetard, steps from
where Ernest Hemingway had lived.
</P>
<P>
   There are photos of pimps and prostitutes on Rue Saint-Denis,
Christian Dior models and homeless ``clochards'' showing off their
tattoos. This was a romantic time in Paris, after World War II,
when the French were still recovering from war and rebuilding their
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   These photos and Miller's picturesque words also trace the
coming of age of a man who would go on to become a reporter for
Life magazine, a respected journalist and author.
</P>
<P>
   A look at France today comes through the images of four
photographers and the words of Marie-France Boyer, Paris editor for
the World of Interiors magazine. In ``Village Voices: French
Country Life'' (Thames &AMP; Hudson, $24.95), Boyer takes us to small
towns in rural France, where there are televisions in the
barbershop and plenty of packaged foods at the grocers. But there
is also a charm strictly French, and Francophiles will relate to
this midsize book.
</P>
<P>
   Another thin-volume picture book is Don Krohn's ``In the South
of France'' (Godine, $45), in which he provides both photographs
and text. While Krohn has taught photography, lectured on law and
traveled extensively in Nepal, Ireland and France, this is his
first book. Color photographs range from grand vistas to the single
doorway, crowds to a cafe table of friends.
</P>
<P>
   In a continuing series, James Bentley dishes up ``The Most
Beautiful Villages of Brittany'' (Thames &AMP; Hudson, $40). A
coffee-table compendium of 251 color photographs by Hugh Palmer,
this book delves into that northwestern peninsula of France that
was home to the Celts and the magical Merlin and the seat of the
Breton language.
</P>
<P>
   Complete with a traveler's guide, the book moves from the craggy
coast and seafood caches to the piety of local churches, to the
park at Chateau de Caradeuc, sometimes called the ``Versailles of
Brittany.''
</P>
<P>
   A fine connection is made here between French Brittany and
English Britain, and there is much to remind one of Ireland as
well.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Desert: The Mojave and Death Valley'' (Abrams, $49.50),
photographer Jack Dykinga shows us a close-up of the drying blades
of a yucca in which one might see the whorls of a bird's-eye maple,
the rings of a cut redwood or the aridness of Mars. But it is only
a yucca.
</P>
<P>
   The image is representative of how Dykinga and writer Janice
Emily Bowers relate the need to preserve and protect the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after passage of the Desert Protection Act, 4 million
people live within 35,000 square miles surrounding the Mojave
Desert, a tough-looking but fragile ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   For an armchair traveler, ``Desert'' is a comfortable way to see
the legendary Joshua tree, the crystallized salt formations of
Death Valley and the carved-looking red sandstone of Red Rock
Canyon National Conservation Area in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   And for the desert-bound, its stark, almost surreal photos are a
fine initiation to the harshness that is the desert's reality.
</P>
<P>
   For less arid holiday reading, consider the lushness of
``Equator'' (Taschen, $29.99). Milan-born Gian Paolo Barbieri made
his name with his 1960s fashion photographs for Italian Vogue and
has since been ranked among the world's best fashion photographers.
</P>
<P>
   In these images from the Seychelles, islands off the east coast
of Africa, Barbieri combines sex, shape, sea, sky and sun into a
sensual and sometimes erotic study.
</P>
<P>
   As in the cover image of a muscular young man, nude, hoisting a
freshly caught shark above his head, these photos combine nature
with a certain naivete. Nude studies are interspersed with juicy
fruits and fishes that make one think of Erica Jong's
fruits-and-vegetables poetry. Surely the half dozen entwined sea
creatures are merely displayed by the fishmonger, not having an
orgy.
</P>
<P>
   Another book of island observations is ``Archipelago: The
Islands of Indonesia'' (University of California Press, $45), by
Gavan Daws and Marty Fujita. Unlike Barbieri's titillating picture
book, this is a scholarly history of the islands from their
19th-century dissection by field biologist Alfred Russell Wallace
to the 21st-century fate of the area's forests and reefs.
</P>
<P>
   The book, published in cooperation with the Nature Conservancy,
includes maps, archival materials and more than 200 color
photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The name Wallace may not ring a bell, overshadowed as he was by
Charles Darwin, but working independently, he also enunciated the
theory of evolution by natural selection.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, an explorer and a prodigious collector, was the first
to bring living birds of paradise to the West. From his first
tentative collections of beetles to his adventures in the wilds of
Borneo, his was a scholarly yet exciting life.
</P>
<P>
   Today we know that the 17,500 or so Indonesian islands are home
to some 10,000 species of trees as well as one-sixth of all bird,
one-eighth of all mammal and about one-third of all fish species.
Can such biodiversity be preserved with a human population that
will reach 300 million in the next 50 years?
</P>
<P>
   ``Penguin'' (Taschen, $24.99), Frans Lanting's land, sea and ice
brush with this most unusual of creatures, is a natural-science
book to treasure, almost as loving a look at these birds as the
children's book ``Mr. Popper's Penguins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dutchman Lanting has been hailed as one of the best nature
photographers of our time. For ``Penguin,'' he collaborated with
Christine Eckstrom.
</P>
<P>
   From the boisterous rockhoppers of the Falkland Islands to the
king penguins of South Georgia to the emperor penguins of
Antarctica, Lanting and Eckstrom got up close and personal with
their subjects, making this less a natural-history project than an
attempt at getting acquainted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earth From Above'' (Abrams, $65) is a big, millennium-perfect
coffee-table book. Aerial photographer Yann Arthus-Bertrand worked
for more than five years above 60 countries to record the state of
the world's environment at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   His 170 color photographs are accompanied by essays from
specialists in history, economics, sociology, environmental
science, geography, demography, zoology and anthropology.
</P>
<P>
   Arthus-Bertrand soars so high that the brown-and-white African
landscape looks like sugar frosting on a cinnamon bun, and he
swoops low enough to capture smiles. With the latitude and
longitude of each photograph provided, this is a wonderful keepsake
for generations to come.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the Atlantic, ``The Houses of Old Cuba'' (Thames &AMP;
Hudson, $45) offers glimpses of a Cuban architectural heritage many
outsiders never see. Author Llilian Llanes, chief curator at the
Museo Wilfredo Lam in Havana, and Caribbean-based photographer
Jean-Luc de Laguarigue show us Cuba's homes, from cabins to
mansions.
</P>
<P>
   They look at the Creole oligarchy of the inland regions, the
dominance of Havana and the details of daily life, customs and
pastimes that surround both. There are no rusting hulks of vintage
cars among these 168 color photos, or diatribes against communism,
merely memories of what was and still is the grandeur of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mayfield and the editors of Southern Accents magazine are
the authors of ``Southern Style'' (Bulfinch Press, $45), a 208-page
book that looks not only at the charming interiors and architecture
of this U.S. region but also at its influence nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   While comfort and elegance may have been sacrificed elsewhere,
in the South they continue to reign with graciousness from the
gardens to the garrets.
</P>
<P>
   Southern style frequently borrows from other cultures _ Chinese
porcelain, French antiques, English-style gardens, and accents from
Latin America, Africa and the Far East _ but puts the pieces
together in a way that recalls an American history.
</P>
<P>
   John Loring, long known as the design director of Tiffany &AMP; Co.,
has published perhaps his best, most beautiful book. ``Tiffany
Jewels'' (Abrams, $60) is the first complete history of Tiffany's
renowned jewels.
</P>
<P>
   From its founding as a stationery and fancy-goods emporium in
1837 by Charles Lewis Tiffany, the store has become one of the
world's premier jewelers. With 361 illustrations, most in color,
this book profiles the company's great designers, including Edward
C. Moore, Louis Comfort Tiffany (son of the founder) and Paulding
Farnham.
</P>
<P>
   It follows fine jewelry design through the store's 20th-century
stars _ Jean Schlumberger, Elsa Peretti and Paloma Picasso. There
are newly discovered designs and anecdotes, first lady Eleanor
Roosevelt's Tiffany solitaire diamond engagement ring and Peretti's
``Diamonds-by-the-Yard'' necklace.
</P>
<P>
   This is a book for anyone who loves fine jewelry or likes to
window-shop and dream of dressing like a princess _ or at least
like Elizabeth Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Serious observers of fashion will appreciate two new books, each
more words than pictures. ``A Dedicated Follower of Fashion''
(Phaidon, $29.95) is by Holly Brubach, former style editor of the
New York Times Magazine. Now working for Prada in Italy, Brubach
chronicles 20 years in the international fashion world.
</P>
<P>
   In 27 essays published in the '80s and '90s in the New Yorker,
the Atlantic Monthly and the New York Times Magazine, she ranges
from famous designers to designer sunglasses, the Chanel suit to
what she perceives as the recent decline of elegance. Brubach sees
herself as a fashion anthropologist, trying to make sense of it
all.
</P>
<P>
   So does Teri Agins, author of ``The End of Fashion: The Mass
Marketing of the Clothing Business'' (Morrow, $25). To Agins'
credit, she pursues a more businesslike route in investigating this
multibillion-dollar industry _ but then she has, for 10 years,
covered fashion as senior special writer for the Wall Street
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   One of Agins' hard-hitting accusations is that the fashion press
is subsidized by the industry it covers, with magazines such as
Vogue and Harper's Bazaar and industry newspapers such as
Fairchild's WWD dependent on advertising revenues.
</P>
<P>
   She dishes the dirt on key players, including Giorgio Armani,
Calvin Klein, Ralph Lauren, Donna Karan, Bill Blass, Tommy Hilfiger
and Emanuel Ungaro.
</P>
<P>
   Then she looks at possibilities for the future _ the Gap, J.
Crew, Banana Republic and Zoran, the designer of luxury understated
clothing. (You must read the book to find out how journalist Cathy
Horyn, now fashion critic for The New York Times, ended up riding a
garbage truck back to her hotel _ as a birthday present.)
</P>
<P>
   A defining name of the 20th century is Andy Warhol, documentor
and icon of pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   With and without his Dynel fright wig, Warhol stood behind and
in front of the camera, for portraitists or in cramped photo
booths, for Leicas owned by world-renowned photographers or for his
own Polaroid camera.
</P>
<P>
   As a gawky child, he had shunned photographs, but before his
death in 1987, he would become one of the world's most photographed
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy Warhol Photography'' (Andy Warhol Museum and Hamburg
Kunsthalle, Edition Stemmle, $75) is the first book to look at the
whole of Warhol's photographic work. This is not a book for the
faint of heart or the casual consumer of culture, but it will be a
welcome edition to the library of any student of 20th-century art.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Warhol's photography (including nudity and sexual
content), it contains photos of the artist by Richard Avedon,
Robert Mapplethorpe, Cecile Beaton and others, as well as
interviews with Warhol associates and essays by art historians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sixties'' (Random House, $75), an interesting history of
people who shaped one of the century's most formative decades, is
the product of a 30-year collaboration between photographer Richard
Avedon and writer/interviewer Doon Arbus.
</P>
<P>
   Subjects include John Lennon, Abbie Hoffman, Tennessee Williams,
Tom Hayden, Dr. Benjamin Spock, civil-rights lawyer Florynce
Kennedy, Janis Joplin, Buckminster Fuller, Vietnam War soldiers,
anti-war activists, politicians, people with Hansen's disease and
victims of napalm attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Leibovitz, as honored in photography circles as Avedon, is
known for her decisive portraits in such magazines as Rolling
Stone, Vanity Fair and Vogue. In ``Women'' (Random House, $75) she
teams with writer Susan Sontag, who translates Leibovitz's images
into word pictures of women at the end of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Among their subjects are coal miners, dancers, athletes,
military officers, an astronaut, the Kilgore College Rangerettes
and even three Houston socialites _ Pat Breen, Lynn Wyatt and
Caroline Wiess Law.
</P>
<P>
   Sontag and Leibovitz conclude that all is not well with women;
they bemoan that there are countries ``where men have been
mobilized for a veritable war against women'' and where women
scarcely appear at all, in photographs or in public.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Brandt (1904-1983) was among the most inventive
photographers of the 20th century. He grew up in Germany and
Switzerland, was an assistant to Man Ray at the height of his
surrealist period, and worked in Paris at the time of Brassai and
Andre Kertesz.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s and '40s, his photojournalistic essays covered the
plight of England's coal miners and industrial workers, then London
during the blitz.
</P>
<P>
   A portraitist for magazines such as Harper's Bazaar, Brandt went
on to experiment with poetic images of the English landscape and
with nudes, photographing the human body as if in abstract.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Brandt: The Photography of Bill Brandt'' (Abrams, $75),
Bill Jay and Nigel Warburton gather and reproduce in duotone 378
photographs, grouping them by theme and pairing them with
quotations from Brandt. A survey of Brandt's career and a
discussion of his printing styles complete the book.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Edward Steichen: The Early Years'' (Princeton University
Press and Metropolitan Museum of Art, $60), Joel Smith examines the
career of the painterly photographer from the late 1890s to World
War I.
</P>
<P>
   Praised by Alfred Stieglitz and Auguste Rodin, Steichen at an
early age became a sought-after portraitist of the elite, both in
the United States and abroad. He is known to many for his twilight
views of New York's Flatiron Building and his sequence of moonlight
photographs of the Rodin's sculpture ``Balzac.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be overlooked are his erotic nudes and his energetic
portraits of figures such as Richard Strauss and J.P. Morgan. With
much of Steichen's early work, one will find it difficult to
believe that the shadowy, tinted results are indeed photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Dreadlocks garner attention anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Dreads'' (Artisan, $35), photographers Francesco Mastalia
and Alfonse Pagano display the modern diversity in this style of
knotted, ropelike locks dating back to the fifth century.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``dreadlocks'' refers not to a hairstyle but to a lack
of hairstyling. In the West, dreads gained popularity with the
Black Power movement, but most cultures recognize the adoption of
dreadlocks as a denunciation of vanity and a sign of the pursuit of
spiritualism.
</P>
<P>
   Mastalia and Pagano traveled to Jamaica, Japan, New Zealand,
Kenya, Namibia, Ethiopia, Angola, Senegal, India and the United
States. In words and photos, they explore the sacred rites of the
natural hair revolution by Rastafarians, Rasta-Buddhists, Maori
warriors, African-Americans, Sadhus, Sikhs and Sinhalese.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Walker, author of ``The Color Purple,'' writes in an
introduction that it was musician Bob Marley who taught her to
trust the universe enough to respect her hair.
</P>
<P>
   She saw Marley perform and wondered what it would be like to
have his ropes of hair or to make love with someone who had them.
Walker went 10 years without combing her hair and learned that,
left to itself, her hair would weave itself into a flat or rounded
pattern shortly after leaving her scalp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art of the Boot'' (Gibbs Smith, $39.95) is a book for anyone
who ever loved a pair of boots. Texan Tyler Beard, author of ``The
Cowboy Boot Book'' and ``100 Years of Western Wear,'' here examines
the boot as an art form, by no means dying.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in luxury goods and handcrafted leathers, including
boots, is running high. Boots, Beard writes, can be a narcotic for
cowboy wannabes, who see the footgear as the soul of the West,
regardless of whether it descended from Attila the Hun and Genghis
Khan.
</P>
<P>
   The first American cowboys probably wore Wellingtons or Hessian
boots. By 1870, John Cubine of Coffeyville, Kan., had combined the
Wellington and military-style boots for Texas cowboys, adding
leather pull straps, low Cuban heels and slightly rounded square
toes, although no example of a decorated boot in this style exists.
</P>
<P>
   Decorative stitching and high heels emerged in the 1880s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art of the Boot'' takes off with the highly decorated boots of
the 1930s and '40s, soon standard wear for rhinestone cowboys and
cowgirls. Now artist-designed boots are made for entertainers,
presidents and kings. Learn the names of the great boot designers,
from the Blucher Boot Co. to Tres Outlaws.
</P>
<P>
   Not often do you find a book designed primarily for adults that
is a riot of fun. The afternoon Gary Greenberg's ``The Pop-Up Book
of Phobias'' (Morrow, $24.95) arrived in our office, a half dozen
editors hooted, hollered, ughed and oh-nooooed over it like kids.
And we were kids again, remembering all the things that scared the
britches off us in childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Take snakes, dentist visits, filthy public toilets ... please!
Ugh. Ick. Phooey. Greenberg takes his short chronicle of phobias
seriously _ as seriously as is possible for a stand-up comedian and
author of the book ``Self-Helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   With the aid of illustrator Balvis Rubess, pop-up whiz Matthew
Reinhart makes your worst nightmares jump up and out of the book.
The dental drill of dentophobics. The pit of vipers that
ophidiophobics imagine with every step in the woods. Even the evil
clown of coulrophobics, who can usually trace their phobia to a bad
circus experience in early childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Short, delightfully evil and oh-so-much fun, this big pop-up
book makes a great gag gift, or a serious one for the phobia-laced
relative whose estate you hope to inherit sooner rather than later.
Merry Christmas, Addams Family. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
