<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GARDEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GARDEN OF GOOD READING FOR THE HOLIDAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As garden books poured in from publishing houses these
past months, those by Texans and for Texans began to add up.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a short stack, compiled after reading through
dozens of 1999 first editions, home-grown and from across the
country, that might hold something to please the gardener on your
holiday list.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Wild Orchids of Texas'' by Joe Liggio and Ann Orto Liggio
(University of Texas Press, $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   We treasure our wildflowers and native plants. But what about
our orchids? They're natives, too. Chances are that few of us
realize that 54 types of orchids grow in various habitats in Texas.
These orchids are terrestrials; their roots grow right in the
various soils of this diverse state. They're not epiphytes like the
majority of orchids in the tropics. Ours may not be as showy, but
they're as beautiful. They possess fascinating forms _ acquired to
attract pollinators. And most come with easy-to-remember common
names so they're less intimidating. The chatterbox orchid, for
example, has a hinged lip that flaps in a breeze. It's found on the
Edwards Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pleasure being introduced to our native orchids through
Ann Orto Liggio's text and Joe Liggio's outstanding photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Their book, apparently a first on the subject, fills a gap in
our plant library. Not all Texas orchid habitats are as plentiful
as they once were, and the authors encourage preservation of orchid
habitats to ensure the survival of these treasures. The impressive
Southern lady's slipper (Cypripedium kentuckiense), with its pale
yellow, pouchlike lip; three birds orchid (Triphora trianthophora);
and green adder's mouth (Malaxis unifolia), all found in the moist
pine-hardwood forests of East Texas, are much rarer now.
</P>
<P>
   Discovering these orchids in the Liggios' book is a treat that
could only be overshadowed by spotting one in its natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Texas Wildscapes: Gardening for Wildlife'' by Noreen Damude
and Kelly Conrad Bender (Texas Parks and Wildlife Press, $24.95,
distributed by University of Texas Press).
</P>
<P>
   More gardeners are transforming traditional landscapes into
wildscapes that will provide a habitat for wildlife squeezed out by
urban development. In doing so, they also enjoy a livelier garden
filled with flowers and berries.
</P>
<P>
   This guide is useful to those who would like to offer wildlife
food, cover and water. Its thorough approach includes design
illustrations, a wealth of information on plants native to Texas'
10 ecological regions, chapters on Texas birds and other critters,
a glossary and a list of resources.
</P>
<P>
   For those who would like recognition for creating a wildscape
that attracts and supports wildlife, there's an application form to
become an Official Texas Wildscape Site, a program offered by Texas
Parks and Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The American Lawn,'' edited by Georges Teyssot, Princeton
Architectural Press, $52.95.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're bent on creating a wildscape, this collection of
essays on the American lawn, that great patch of green that lies at
the heart of our culture, is thoughtful, carefully researched and
entertaining. In this below-the-surface presentation, architects,
historians and theorists clue us in to the political, historical,
psychological, literary and artistic significances of our turf.
</P>
<P>
   We learn of our mowing ancestors and how the lawn came to
symbolize the self-sufficient American's dream of control. How the
lawn, the green plot that connects individual to community, became
the great equalizer. There are governmental lawns, palace lawns,
suburban lawns.
</P>
<P>
   We read how we have used the lawn not only as a domesticized
extension of our home _ our outdoor carpet _ but as an element of
pastoral romanticism in parks, and, thanks to renowned landscape
architect Frederick Law Olmsted, as therapeutic grassy surfaces. We
use green, velvety surfaces in cemeteries and outdoor theaters and
on tennis courts, bowling greens, polo fields, football fields and
golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, one essayist tells us, the front lawn was
the face of the nation _ keeping up the front lawn meant keeping up
the morale of those at home and in the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the image of the American male pouring his heart and soul
into the greening of his lawn may be fading as we raise the flag of
low-maintenance gardening. But the lawn is a living key to our
collective psyche.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't believe it, check out the failure-to-cut-the-grass
court cases, along with a pair of 3-D glasses, in the back of the
book.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Gardens of the Imagination: A Literary Anthology,'' edited
by Sophie Biriotti and illustrated by Peter Malone (Chronicle
Books, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   In this collection of prose and poetry, with some of the most
fascinating illustrations out there today, we find Lewis Carroll's
Alice talking to Tiger-lily, Daisy and Rose in the Garden of Live
Flowers. In most gardens, we learn, ``they make the beds too soft,
so that the flowers are always asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   We hear Mary Lennox's voice breaking the years-old stillness in
an excerpt from Frances Hodgson Burnett's ``The Secret Garden.'' We
see Vita Sackville-West visualizing a garden of white pansies,
peonies and irises.
</P>
<P>
   We disappear into the mystical images of the hanging Gardens of
Babylon and Kubla Khan's Xanadu as we wander through gardens of
paradise, love and temptation.
</P>
<P>
   This exquisite book is a gift for either literary or gardening
types.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Beautiful American Rose Gardens'' by Mary Tonetti Dorra
(Clarkson Potter/Publishers, $40).
</P>
<P>
   Two Texans are included among the 24 rose enthusiasts in this
coast-to-coast look at rose gardens. Houston artist David Caton has
a thing for Texas natives _ and old roses. The fragrant, persistent
bloomers are beautiful elements in his paintings and complementary
partners to the graceful grasses and succulents that grow in this
rose rustler's atypical, colorful and abundant suburban garden.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth philanthropist Anne Bass' intense interest in
horticulture is reflected in her sumptuous landscape, which was
designed by the late Russell Page. The vast grounds were his only
Texas creation. Bass was not initially interested in roses, but
once she discovered the blooms, she worked with Page to gather a
great collection of roses that could withstand the Texas climate.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to these vastly different Texas rose gardens; to a Los
Angeles garden created by Dan Kiley, the ``dean of American
landscape architecture''; to those of the South, is an inspiration
to any gardener. The authors include design plans, gardeners' tips
and a source list to reinforce that inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Clutius Botanical Watercolors: Plants and Flowers of the
Renaissance'' by Claudia Swan, (Harry N. Abrams, Inc. Publishers,
$45).
</P>
<P>
   The botanical watercolors reproduced in this book offer a
stunning short course in botany. Such late-16th-century paintings
were not just pretty pictures but teaching aids in the medical
field. Plants were used to soothe headaches, colds and more serious
ailments, and visual identification was crucial. Renderings of
roots, foliage, flowers and seeds are presented in exquisite
detail.
</P>
<P>
   The images include plants found in a pleasure garden, the
kitchen garden and in the wild and are selected from some 1,800
watercolors included in a multivolume account of the plant world,
``Libri picturati,'' used by Netherlands pharmacist Theodorus
Clutius while employed at Leiden University during the last decade
of the 1500s.
</P>
<P>
   The opening pages are a written account of Clutius' painted
herbarium. Those that follow are so pretty you'll be tempted to
tear them out and frame them.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Tranquil Garden: Creating Peaceful Spaces Outdoors,''
from the editors of County Living Gardener, text by Kay Fairfax,
photography by Clive Nichols (Hearst Books, $30).
</P>
<P>
   Just looking at the cover of this book is calming.
</P>
<P>
   Gardeners have a long list of choices in creating a refuge _ a
formal garden, a romantic garden, perhaps a water garden. This book
helps assess spaces and needs, then guides the gardener through
such aspects of gardening as composition, color and balance to
successfully create that choice. The third section of the book is a
look at the details of a garden _ arbors, walls, statuary, lighting
and containers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Better Homes and Gardens ``New Junior Garden Book'' by Felder
Rushing (Meredith Books, $15.95).
</P>
<P>
   Felder Rushing is known to many adult gardeners through his
books and lectures. He also gardens with his two children in
Mississippi, and many of the cool projects in this
not-for-kids-only book are found on the Rushing home front. The
Jurassic Jungle _ a garden in a sweater box complete with moss,
ferns and toy dinosaurs _ is a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Soil, tools, safety, a plant-related glossary, worms and other
critters, recycling and all the fun things about gardening keep
this book jumping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other notable Texas-based garden books published this year:
</P>
<P>
   _ The paperback edition of ``Edible and Useful Plants of Texas
and the Southwest'' by Delena Tull (University of Texas Press,
$24.95) is a good choice as well. Give the book and a jar of
prickly pear or persimmon jelly _ just follow the recipes in the
book.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lowe's ``Texas Gardening Handbook'' by Dale Groom (Integra
Color Press, $19.95). The year-round guide is available at Lowe's
Home Improvement Warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Great Garden Sources for Texans'' by Nan Booth Simpson and
Patricia Scott McHargue (Eakin Press, $17.95). This is a useful
compilation of sources _ from inspiration to tools to plants to
public gardens.
</P>
<P>
