<HEADER>
A7264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN15-CO     12-13 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A cornucopia of other people's stuff
 &HT;    (For release Dec. 15, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be that to have a memento from a famous or infamous
person was to have something rare; a conversation piece. In this
last decade of the 1900s, however, it is rare that someone isn't
collecting mementos _ either for prestige, nostalgia or money.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, more than 350 people turned out in San Diego to
bid for the possessions of the members of the Heaven's Gate cult
whose 39 in-house fanatics did away with themselves in a mass
suicide. The most alluring relic: the bedframes from the beds in
which the bodies were found.
</P>
<P>
   There also was the Las Vegas Elvis auction in October in which
someone paid $8,000 for Presley's sixth-grade report card. Why do
you figure Elvis saved that card _ D's in math and geography, A in
music?
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, neither me nor my closest friends salted away the
baseball cards that came inside a pack of bubble gum. Instead, we
swapped and/or gambled them. But to put them into a protective
plastic sleeve with the thought of future sales never dawned on us.
</P>
<P>
   What's that old Honus Wagner baseball card worth today? About a
quarter-million dollars to collectors who would, upon getting it,
hide it in some safe deposit box until such time as it is sold to
another investor for even more money and put in someone else's
safety deposit box.
</P>
<P>
   I once had a business-sized card signed by Babe Ruth; have no
idea what happened to it. I also wonder what my Goose Goslin
first-ever fielder's glove would fetch today, if still it existed.
Likely little because few can recall the old Washington
Senators/Detroit Tigers outfielder who played his last major-league
game in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   When WWII ended, a returning relative bestowed upon me a German
officer's bayonet and helmet. My mother had no reverence for
mementos or anything else lying around the house. While I was in
the service, she got rid of them as horrible reminders of Nazi
atrocity. In doing that, she also dumped my 1891 Spalding Baseball
Guide; arghh!
</P>
<P>
   In New York tomorrow (Thursday) night, some of Princess Diana's
jewelry is to be auctioned. Who it is that put the jewels _ a
necklace and matching earrings _ up for sale is unknown to me but
there is an interesting footnote to an advertisement for the event:
``Proceeds in part to support UNICEF.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the same with the Elvis auction. Proceeds from that were
to go toward building housing for Memphis's homeless. And the
proceeds from the Heaven's Gate auction were designated to repay
the families of the cult members for their burial expenses.
</P>
<P>
   One can investigate which percentages actually went to the
designees but that's not what I'm into right now. What intrigues me
is our penchant to pay for, to possess, to frame or otherwise
display, mementos of people we've never met.
</P>
<P>
   As I look around my den at home, everything on the walls _ and
there is much there _ is something I associate with: A 1948 Boston
Braves banner (I'm a longtime Braves fan), two military discharges,
caps of my favorite sports teams, a couple of awards I won and a
framed poster of the 1988 Calgary Winter Olympics, which I
attended.
</P>
<P>
   There is no room for Elvis's sixth-grade report card on my
walls, or a Heaven's Gate bed in my guest bedroom. And there isn't
money enough to buy Diana's necklace for my wife.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of prints of great and not-so-great paintings, our
hallway walls are covered with photos of our children, our
grandchildren, our parents and grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, I'm into collecting, but only as the nostalgia is
directed inward.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder about the guy who bought the Heaven's Gate bed frame.
He told the media he would put it in his guest bedroom. When he was
asked if ever he would sleep in it, he answered: ``Absolutely
not!''
</P>
<P>
   How do you think he'll handle the guest? Will he tell him that
the bed he's going to sleep in was one in which a Heaven's Gate
member committed suicide, or will he keep it to himself as he
sardonically chuckles off to his own bed, maybe one in which an
aging George Washington might have had a continence problem?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
