<HEADER>
A7265 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN15-COX     12-13 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A man, a plan, a canal _ communists!
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Chinese communists are coming! The Chinese communists are
coming!
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long dry spell, but finally there's a juicy new
lunatic right-wing conspiracy theory to entertain us, and just in
time to add to the general hilarity and joy kicked up by the sundry
agitated millennial hysterias.
</P>
<P>
   The chicoms, it seems, are about to take over the Panama Canal.
Once there, they will, of course, install nuclear missiles and
attack us. Indeed, there are already reports _ Reports! no less _
that Chinese military personnel have been sneaked into the
Panamanian population. Panamanians apparently are unable to tell
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   All this goes back to the decision by that traitor, President
Jimmy Carter, to give the canal away. Never mind that our overt
colonialism in the canal zone had become untenable in a sharply
changed world, that the concession to Panama was a graceful
substitute for the otherwise inevitable turmoil that would have had
the same outcome or that by making the gesture, Carter vitalized
our deteriorating relations with much of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The harumphing opponents of the treaty have never reconciled to
Panamanian control of the canal and now are running about and
shouting ``I told you so.''
</P>
<P>
   The excuse for these antics is the contract Panama awarded a
Hong Kong company, Hutchinson-Whampoa Ltd., to operate the canal's
port facilities. The John Birch Society, which has been seeing
communists under the bed since the four-poster was invented, a few
retired military throwbacks and a handful of off-the-chart
Republicans in Congress say the company is cover for the Chinese
government, which you can tell just by looking at billionaire Li
Ka-shing, who heads the company and is actually Chinese, so there
you are.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Hutchinson-Whampoa is a well-established international
company, publicly traded, with operations in 24 countries,
including contracts to run Britain's three largest ports. It won
the Panama contract in competitive bidding. Its top manager in
Panama is British, his No. 2 is American and none of the 500
employees is Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Into the bargain, Panamanians, not Hutchinson, will be running
the canal, as for all practical purposes they have for the past 10
years. And thanks to Carter's foresight, Washington retains the
right to act militarily to protect the canal, a grant that probably
would have been denied if we had had to cede control under
political siege conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, proving the left yields nothing to the right in
paranoia, a Memphis jury wasted no time, just three hours after a
loosey-goosey civil trial, in deciding that because he opposed the
Vietnam War, Martin Luther King Jr. was killed by a conspiracy
involving a bunch of local marginals, some Memphis cops, the FBI,
the Mafia and the U.S. military. And maybe the Tooth Fairy.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but let's just bank that one for now. We can pull it out for
comfort when the next shortage of loopiness hits.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
