u e BC-FILM-MAGUIRE-PROFILE-     12-13 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MAGUIRE-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBEY MAGUIRE HAS BECOME AN ACTOR TO WATCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: An odiaeresis , or two dots, is needed over o in Hallstrom) 
 
By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Who is this Tobey Maguire?
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Hollywood will roll out several big, expensive,
prestigious holiday films, and two of them star a 24-year-old actor
many moviegoers don't know yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rules,'' a warm and thoughtful adaptation of
John Irving's best seller directed by Lasse Hallstrom (``My Life as
a Dog''), stars Maguire as Homer Wells, a naive young man who
leaves the orphanage of his youth to discover joy and pain in the
outside world. Maguire gets support from co-stars such as Michael
Caine, Kate Nelligan and Jane Alexander. He even gets to romance
Charlize Theron.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Ride With the Devil,'' a Civil War epic told from a
youthful perspective, stars Maguire as Jake Roedel, a Southern teen
who joins a guerrilla band for four cruel years of fighting. Ang
Lee (``Sense and Sensibility'') directed a cast that includes Skeet
Ulrich, Jeffrey Wright, James Caviezel, Jonathan Rhys-Meyers and
Jonathan Brandis. The leading lady in this one is singer Jewel, in
her feature-film debut.
</P>
<P>
   Both are expensive productions built around Maguire's
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire, a native of Santa Monica, Calif., is not a newcomer. He
started acting when he was 13, and his long list of films includes
Lee's ``The Ice Storm'' and Woody Allen's ``Deconstructing Harry.''
Last year he had a breakout lead in ``Pleasantville,'' playing a
modern teen transported into a black-and-white 1950s TV-sitcom
world.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire showed up for Toronto International Film Festival
interviews dressed in a black T-shirt, black jeans and sneakers,
yawning and looking like a kid who'd been up all night. Maybe he
had: He certainly had reason to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rules'' and ``Ride With the Devil'' are films
of the kind young actors pray for: big productions with good casts
and top directors.
</P>
<P>
   On the screen, Maguire has a low-key presence. But he also
conveys perception, even wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   He's much the same in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great insight into human psychology,'' Hallstrom said
of his ``Cider House'' star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost intimidating, the way he sees through you.''
</P>
<P>
   Maguire is also, at times, reticent. When asked what
characteristic or talent made important directors want him in their
films, his answer was simple:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged to elaborate, Maguire interrupted, not impolitely but
firmly: ``Look, really, I'm just not going to answer that question,
because I don't know and I wouldn't want to speculate on that. Who
knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Hallstrom does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobey has this combination of childish innocence and a very
old soul,'' the director said during a recent visit to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Pleasantville,'' ``The Cider House Rules'' and ``Ride
With the Devil'' are vastly different from one another, Maguire's
characters in them show important similarities. All are
inexperienced young men thrust into new worlds whose events they
observe and absorb rather than shape.
</P>
<P>
   When a Maguire character does take control of a situation _ as
in ``Ride With the Devil'' when Roedel stops his fellow guerrillas
from murdering innocent citizens _ it comes as a surprise and a
relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do what the part requires,'' Maguire said. ``It would make
sense to say that, but it's much more complicated in my head.''
</P>
<P>
   If Maguire is reluctant to talk about his screen persona,
Hallstrom is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobey's main interest is the understated performance, which is
something I really appreciate,'' Hallstrom said. ``As an actor, he
works on being emotionally present, so he can respond. He really
works hard on experiencing the proper emotion of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't manipulate what kind of expression comes from that.
He trusts that if he is emotionally present in the moment, that
will convey enough for him to make the right choices in the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he portrays Homer (in ''The Cider House Rules``), he's
lived an isolated life in the orphanage. When he goes out into the
world, it's like a new planet for him, but he doesn't want to
reveal what kind of wonderment he is feeling and experiencing.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the restraint seen in these films, and in this interview, a
matter of acting choices or just the way he is?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see,'' Maguire said, as though he had a secret. ``I
don't want to put any limitations on myself. I look forward to
challenges in my life and career and want to do my best to surprise
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Realizing he had been less than forthcoming, Maguire smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to challenge you,'' he teased. ``It's strange for me,
talking to journalists. I think there tends to be so many labels
for things, and I don't think that way, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Maguire was more talkative about his attitude toward work. He
likes acting ... sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm a kid, and half of me doesn't want to be working
anyway. What young person really wants to go to work every day? And
it's really a lot of responsibility. You have to show up. I've been
dead sick where, if it was some other kind of job, I would take the
day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``On `Ride With the Devil,' there was this day where they would
yell `Cut' and I would jump off the horse, lay with my face in the
dirt,'' he said, adding a convincing moan. ``And they'd say, `Mount
up.' People would help me up and get me on the horse and
`Yahaahhh!' for days in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me would prefer to be just hanging out, doing other
things. I'm a single guy, I don't have children to support, I don't
have a high cost of living. So now's the time to take my time and
choose wisely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to work, particularly early in my career, I want
to work with people I am going to learn from. I want to be involved
in movies that really make me want to show up for work.''
</P>
<P>
   He cringed at the suggestion that his choices have been
calculated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is somewhat calculated, but I hate to create that
perception. I think about it. I want longevity. I want to work with
great people. I want to be regarded as, you know, at least a decent
actor with a decent body of work 20 or 30 years from now. But most
of all I want to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   In making ``Ride With the Devil,'' much of what Maguire learned
was how miserable it would have been to be a Civil War guerrilla.
It was a long, rough shoot, much of it spent in the saddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were out there,'' he said. ``There were no trailers. We
were in the mud, on horses. We were all dirty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions were better than the real (Civil War) guys. I
mean, I still went back to a house at the end of the night and ate
some food. But it's a great thing to get as close to something as
you can.''
</P>
<P>
   What he really liked was learning to ride. At first he was
intimidated by horses, but he soon learned to love them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the great thing about acting _ you get to learn about
things and experience things. Like learn how to pick apples and how
to make cider for ''The Cider House Rules.`` Learn a little bit
about the psychology of hand-to-hand combat (for ''Ride With the
Devil``).''
</P>
<P>
   Another bonus is getting screen romances with Jewel and Theron.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire grinned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that way,'' he said. ``I get to experience the
perception that I made love to Charlize Theron.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
