<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PARKS PLAN A NATURAL LEGACY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ From Caddo Lake to the Guadalupe Mountains, Texas' 122
marvelously diverse state parks and 50 wildlife management areas
are envied nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   And yet during the past decade, even as millions of visitors
enjoyed a wealth of outdoor pursuits and historical treasures,
Texas Parks and Wildlife Executive Director Andrew Sansom says,
``We've barely been able to keep up with what we've got. We've
spent much of our efforts fixing toilets and sewer systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to figures that show Texas ranks 49th among the 50
states in public spending to operate parks ($1.79 per person
compared with a national average of $4.81), Sansom says, ``It's a
credit to Texas that it can produce the kind of resources and
venues it does from that amount of support. But as proud as we are,
it shouldn't be interpreted that we don't need help. We do. Our
people are desperately stretched. Some parks are underfunded.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BLUEPRINT FOR MILLENNIUM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the inspiration for Lone Star Legacy _ a blueprint for the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest program we've ever undertaken,'' Sansom says
of an endeavor _ begun last year and now taking firm shape _ that
combines public and private funds and spreads to every corner of
the state. The initial campaign (a partnership between Texas Parks
and Wildlife and the private, nonprofit Parks and Wildlife
Foundation of Texas) hopes to raise $25 million on behalf of more
than 200 parks, wildlife management areas, fish hatcheries and
educational facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas Legislature has led the way with recent
appropriations,'' Sansom says. ``Now it's time to reach out to
Texans who care about preserving and enhancing our natural and
cultural resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond providing assistance to existing sites, the program
focuses on five new projects, including Austin's Woods Habitat
Area, steeped in history and a primary stopover for migratory birds
in Brazoria County.
</P>
<P>
   Also planned:
</P>
<P>
   _ The World Birding Center in the Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Texas Rivers Center in San Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   _ Government Canyon State Natural Area near San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   _ Re-establishment of the Texas State Bison Herd _ now numbering
only about 30 animals _ at Caprock Canyons State Park near
Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SAVING AUSTIN'S WOODS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The prototype is the George Bush Gallery of the National Museum
of the Pacific War, which opened in June as part of the Admiral
Nimitz Museum and Historical Center in Fredericksburg. ``It's the
perfect model,'' Sansom says, ``in that public and private funding
were combined to develop an outstanding facility.''
</P>
<P>
   At Austin's Woods _ so named because Stephen F. Austin founded
his colony there in 1820 _ the restoration of a cabin built from
native cedar in 1826 already is under way. ``It's probably the
oldest Anglo structure in the state,'' Sansom says.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Austin's Woods will combine the Nannie M.
Stringfellow Wildlife Management Area (along County Road 316 south
of Sweeney) and Peach Point Wildlife Management Area (south of
Texas 6 and east of Freeport) and encompass 6,745 acres of
bottomland hardwood forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dense, old-growth forest that occurs nowhere else
but Wharton, Matagorda, Brazoria and Fort Bend counties,'' Sansom
says. ``And, of course, that's where most of this area's population
growth is concentrated. Of all the (endangered) habitat in Texas,
I'm most alarmed by the Austin's Woods area.''
</P>
<P>
   Preservation measures are ongoing, and Sansom says, ``We are
also creating a living history and interpretation program there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate that 460 million individual birds fly through this
region every year. I'd like to see us build aerial boardwalks where
visitors can walk at tree-top level and best see the birds. Texas
has nothing like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ambitious project, the World Birding Center, is touted
as the first of its kind in the nation and dedicated to providing
world-class viewing, innovative environmental education, habitat
conservation and regional economic development of sustainable
nature tourism.
</P>
<P>
   A 15,000- to 20,000-square-foot visitors facility adjacent to
Bentsen-Rio Grande State Park near Mission is scheduled to open in
2002. Also planned are interpretive centers at Brownsville and
Weslaco; welcome centers in Edinburg and Harlingen; and at least
five satellite locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In time, we anticipate satellite locations operating on both
sides of the (U.S.-Mexico) border,'' Sansom says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what we are calling satellites may be as simple as a
beautiful wetland and kiosk.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other aspect of nature or outdoor travel has expanded as
much in the last decade as birding. Texas is now the largest
birding destination in the world. We've got the greatest bird
diversity, and it's easily accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Birding's economic impact on some of Texas' poorest counties
can't be understated either, Sansom says. For each 10,000 visitors
attracted to the region through the World Birding Center, an
estimated $8.5 million boost to the local economy is projected.
</P>
<P>
   A prime goal, too, is generating more interest in outdoor
activities among the predominantly Hispanic residents of this
region and among Hispanics, African-Americans and other minorities
throughout Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to see studies that show Texas diversifying so
much in the next century,'' Sansom says. ``Our concern is that
Hispanics and African-Americans tend to be among the lowest
segments of the population in participation in outdoor activities,
and we need to work hard to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sansom cites urbanization and economics among factors but says,
``We need to do a better job of interpreting Hispanic and
African-American history at our sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Direct minority involvement also is being stressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all the leadership in the World Birding Center is
Hispanic,'' Sansom says. ``And by its economic impact, the birding
center will attract the attention of people who wouldn't otherwise
be involved.''
</P>
<P>
   For information about how to participate in the Lone Star Legacy
program, write to the Parks and Wildlife Foundation of Texas, P.O.
Box 15097, Dallas, Texas 75201-0097; call 214-720-1478; or access
www.tpwd.state.tx.us on the Internet. Tax-deductible donations can
be made for individual sites or to a general fund. For information
about state parks, call 800-792-1112. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
