<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTS ON POINSETTIAS SHOW PLANTS ARE SAFE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: Is the poinsettia poisonous? Can I cut the flowers
and use in a vase? How do I stop the stem from bleeding?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to many toxicity tests, there is no evidence that
ingestion of any part of the poinsettia causes death or even
serious injury, and in 1975 the Consumer Product Safety Commission
declared the plant nontoxic.
</P>
<P>
   The poinsettia, of course, is not grown for food, and being a
nonfood product, it may cause minor discomfort if eaten, according
to the Society of American Florists, a group that has launched its
own study of possible poinsettia toxicity. The group refers to the
Poinsindex Information Service, used by poison control centers
nationwide, a 50-pound child would have to ingest 500 poinsettia
bracts to surpass experimental doses, which were not toxic at those
levels.
</P>
<P>
   You can cut the ``flowers'' and use them in a vase, but most
have found the colorful bracts won't last much longer than a day or
two.
</P>
<P>
   You can stop the milky sap from oozing from the end of a freshly
cut poinsettia stem by touching it with a flame or inserting it
into fine sand.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please help me out on a bird of paradise. This plant was
given to me, and I know nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not sure which bird of paradise you have, and since two
other gardeners have recently asked about bird of paradise, here's
a little information on plants commonly called bird of paradise:
</P>
<P>
   ``Strelitzia reginae'' is a tropical plant with bananalike
foliage and exotic orange, blue and white flowers that resemble
birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caesalpinia gilliesii'' is a shrub or small tree that grows
quickly to about 10 feet and has light-yellow flowers with 3- to
5-inch red stamens and feathery blue-green foliage. Butterflies
love this plant, and I understand the stamens have been used as a
saffron substitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``S. reginae'' is native to South Africa, grows to 4 or 5 feet
in height and prefers a well-draining, fertile soil. It likes
moisture during the growing season but drier conditions while
dormant. Give it sun to light shade.
</P>
<P>
   This bird of paradise will not bloom until it's mature and has
formed a large clump, which may take a few years. To encourage
flowering when the plant is more mature, regularly apply a
fertilizer low in nitrogen and high in phosphorus and potassium.
Cool winter temperatures are said to help flowering once a plant is
mature. Dense, crowded plants bloom best, and container plants
flower best if somewhat root-bound. While ``S. reginae'' may
survive a dip to the mid-20s, it's best to protect it during
freezing weather.
</P>
<P>
   Note: The less commonly seen ``S. nicolai'' is the giant or
white bird of paradise and may reach 30 feet. The 5- to 10-foot
bananalike leaves are displayed fanwise on the trunks.
</P>
<P>
   ``C. gilliesii'' is easy to grow and likes sun and a
well-draining soil. You might apply a little fertilizer twice
during the growing season, but otherwise this plant needs little
care. If problems arise, it's likely the plant is receiving too
much shade or moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Native to Argentina, it has now made parts of Texas and Mexico
home. Mulch heavily, and the tender ``C. gilliesii'' is likely to
return from the roots after a cold winter.
</P>
<P>
   Those seeking a source for ``C. gilliesii'' might ask a local
nursery that carries native plants when supplies will be available.
Seed can be ordered from J.L. Hudson, Seedsman, Star Route 2, Box
337, La Honda, Calif. 94020. The catalog is $1.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I thought gardenias bloomed only once a year, but mine has
new buds. Isn't this unusual?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are many gardenia selections, and while some bloom in
late spring, others flower in summer, some spring to fall, even
during a mild winter.
</P>
<P>
   I recently saw potted ``Gardenia jasminoides'' `Veitchii,' a 3-
to 4-foot compact shrub, in bloom. The double flowers are 1 to 2
inches across. G. jasminoides radicans `Daisy' is another compact
repeat bloomer. It's highly fragrant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. The bulk of mail prevents
individual replies to each unpublished letter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
