<HEADLINE>
MORE DEBATE EXPOSURE COULD HELP BUSH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the game of lowered expectations that we call
presidential ``debates,'' Gov. George W. Bush survived his first
two challenges, and his supporters breathed huge sighs of relief.
</P>
<P>
   His performances would have earned him a ``C-minus'' or worse
from many high school speech teachers, but his White House campaign
is still alive and well because he didn't say or do anything
stupid.
</P>
<P>
   How's that for building confidence in the process by which
Americans will select the next leader of the Free World?
</P>
<P>
   In all fairness, none of the Republican contenders have been
oratorical superstars in their joint appearances _ except for Alan
Keyes, a professional radio talk show host and professional
presidential candidate, whose campaign is going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   But the spotlight was on Bush, the perceived front-runner who
had skipped three earlier forums with his five Republican opponents
before finally joining them in recent days for two nationally
televised appearances from New Hampshire and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   A third forum that also will include Bush is scheduled this week
in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his advisers took advantage of the Texas governor's
strong leads in public opinion polls and fund raising to skip the
earlier events.
</P>
<P>
   They obviously wanted to avoid, as long as possible, a
high-profile setting in which Bush could be flustered or duped by
one of his opponents into committing a campaign-crippling gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   And a second reason may have been to avoid or postpone exactly
what has happened in the wake of the governor's first two debate
appearances, a spate of speculation in the media that Bush isn't
experienced enough or intellectual enough to be president of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation, fanned by Bush's opponents, spun off from the
governor's lackluster debate performances, including his moments of
discomfort in the spontaneous setting and his tendency to recite
well-worn passages from his campaign stump speech as if he were
afraid _ or unable _ to depart from his basic script.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates mostly stuck to their basic messages as well,
but expectations were higher for the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Bush generally kept his poise as he parried numerous challenges
from his opponents, but he definitely needs more practice as a
debater.
</P>
<P>
   Before launching his presidential campaign, he had participated
in only two political debates, one each in his 1994 and 1998
gubernatorial races.
</P>
<P>
   It it not entirely fair to judge a presidential candidate's
intellect and leadership abilities by his performance on the debate
stage. But presidents must be able to make sound decisions under
pressure, and voters deserve an opportunity to view and hear
would-be presidents facing off in a setting that is more-or-less
spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   It is as close to spontaneous as we're going to get, anyway,
even though any real debate among major contenders is disrupted by
a restricted format and the inclusion of minor candidates who don't
have a chance of winning election to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush may have been better off participating in the debates from
the very beginning.
</P>
<P>
   That would have given him more practice and maybe reduced some
of the anticipation _ and expectations _ that seemed to build each
time the governor was a no-show.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, who is giving Bush a tough fight for the Feb.
1 New Hampshire primary, was pretty flat in the first joint
appearance of the Republican candidates in the Granite State in
late October. Bush missed that forum, which was televised only in
the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Three debates later, McCain was much more relaxed and confident.
And he performed much better than Bush, who was making his first
joint appearance with his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally with Bush's first two debate appearances, new
polls showed McCain overtaking Bush among Republican voters in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's debate performances may not be the main reason he has
lost ground in that key nominating state, because McCain also has
been campaigning harder than Bush there. Bush is trying to run a
national campaign, while McCain has been more selectively picking
his targets.
</P>
<P>
   But the debates most likely were a factor in Bush's slippage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is still clearly the candidate to beat for the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   He still leads in financial resources and national polls, and
McCain has all but ceded Iowa, another key, early nominating state,
to the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   But the post-debate fallout could be a wake-up call for Bush, if
he needs one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
