<HEADLINE>
COSMETIC SURGERY SPEEDS THE EMOTIONAL HEALING IN BREAST
RECONSTRUCTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photo and graphic available on NYT database) 
 
By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Kathy Park and her daughter were drinking a glass of
wine at a restaurant recently while waiting for a table. A man
struck up a conversation with Park and mentioned that he'd recently
lost his brother to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Park confided that she had been diagnosed with cancer as well.
In 1998, she told him, she had a double mastectomy, followed by
breast reconstruction. Park saw the man's gaze shift down to her
sweater, and then he said, ``I know you don't know me, and I don't
know you, but if I can say one thing _ they did a very good job.''
</P>
<P>
   In different circumstances, Park, 47, might have been offended,
but in this case, she just laughed. ``Cancer makes you appreciate
life a lot more,'' she says. ``When you find out you have the
disease, you feel like your life might be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have the mastectomy and you come out looking close to
what you looked like before, it makes you very thankful that
medical technology is what it is today. A long time ago, women
didn't have this choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, women devastated by a cancer diagnosis came out
of surgery feeling even more discouraged, with one breast or both
replaced by a jagged scar.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more and more women go into the operating room for a
mastectomy and wake up with the beginnings of a new breast,
fashioned entirely from their own tissue or with implants. An
increasing number of surgeons are becoming comfortable with
immediate reconstruction. In the past, reconstruction was completed
only after chemotherapy and radiation. Breast cancer survivors say
reconstructive surgery is a major step forward in the healing
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to get there faster if you look normal,'' says
Carrie Wood, 41, a breast cancer survivor who volunteers at
University of Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston.
``That's what the reconstructive surgeons do. They give you back
what you lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Several breast-reconstruction procedures are commonly offered by
plastic surgeons. In Texas, health insurance companies have been
required to pay for breast reconstruction for mastectomy patients
since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Park had what is known as a ``free TRAM flap.'' This is a highly
technical procedure in which a football-shaped section of skin, fat
and muscle is taken from the lower abdomen and relocated to the
breast area. (TRAM stands for Transverse Rectus Abdominus
Musculocutaneous.) In Park's case, the tissue was augmented by
implants to match her former size.
</P>
<P>
   Flaps also may be taken from the buttock or the back. When taken
from the back or abdomen, the surgeon can leave the flap attached
to its blood supply and create a passageway beneath the skin to
allow the tissue to be passed to its new location. Or, as in Park's
case, the flap can be detached, then reattached to a new blood
supply through microsurgery.
</P>
<P>
   One M.D. Anderson nurse calls this free flap operation ``the
Cadillac of breast reconstruction,'' providing a softer, more
realistic breast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our most common technique. We're really committed to it.
For most patients, it provides the most natural result,'' says M.D.
Anderson plastic surgeon and researcher Dr. Michael Miller.
</P>
<P>
   When a woman doesn't have enough tissue to spare for a TRAM
flap, as in Wood's case, a balloon-like tissue expander is placed
under the pectoral muscle where the breast is to be reconstructed.
Over a period of several weeks, it is gradually filled with saline,
or salt water, through an injection port until the breast is the
correct size. In most patients, the expander is removed and
replaced by a silicone-gel or saline implant.
</P>
<P>
   Although silicone-gel implants have been at the center of highly
publicized lawsuits, with women claiming the implants have caused a
range of health problems, most doctors consider the implants safe.
In June, a panel of 13 scientists, convened by the Institute of
Medicine at the request of Congress, released a report in which it
concluded that silicone breast implants do not cause lupus,
rheumatoid arthritis or any other systemic disease.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the biggest drawback of all implants is that, as
medical devices, they have a limited lifespan and may need to be
replaced in 10 to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Several months after reconstruction, doctors add the final
touches. A new nipple is made from skin on the surface of the
reconstructed breast, sutured to simulate a nipple once it heals.
Tattooing adds realistic skin tones.
</P>
<P>
   Although numbers vary, the tissue flap technique accounts for
almost half of breast reconstructions nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Friedman, a plastic surgeon with Baylor College of
Medicine in Houston, said that for many years, doctors were
reluctant to reconstruct patients' breasts for fear of not being
able to detect a recurrence of cancer. They also were concerned
that if the reconstructed area didn't heal quickly, chemotherapy
might have to be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   However, studies have shown that if cancer recurs, it is nearly
always detectable, even if the patient has had breast
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complication rate of reconstructions are no different than
the mastectomies themselves,'' Friedman says. ``It's a very
reliable technique that doesn't create more problems that will
inhibit patient treatment. People look good, they do well, so it's
becoming more common.''
</P>
<P>
   Reconstruction is still postponed for patients who need
radiation to treat their disease. Reconstruction makes it more
difficult to deliver the right dose of radiation to the skin and
chest wall.
</P>
<P>
   The procedures are not without risks and downsides. Women who
get the TRAM flap may get a tummy tuck as a bonus, but as with
other abdominal surgeries, recovery is painful and takes several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Although women have some feeling in the reconstructed breast,
``the sensation you get back is never like it was before the
surgery,'' Miller says. In addition, there is a small risk that
some of the transferred tissue and fat won't survive in its new
location, making further surgery necessary. Areas of scarring also
can form.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, one of Miller's patients, is affectionately known as a
``flasher.'' She talks to women scheduled for mastectomies and
reconstruction and answers questions like, ``Will it hurt?'' ``What
does it feel like?'' and ``What will I look like?''
</P>
<P>
   After shooing the husband from the room, Wood lifts her blouse.
Most women are expecting the worst and invariably, they say, ``Oh!
Wow!'', amazed at how natural Wood's reconstruction looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you're inducted in this cruel sorority, we're all in this
together,'' Wood says, explaining why she sets aside her usual
modesty for her role as educator. ``You want to help people over
the hump, if you can. If it helps them to know they're going to
look OK, they feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
