<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANAMA READY FOR A NEW ERA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Canizales) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ Near the banks of the Panama Canal, a huge
digital clock counts the hours, minutes and seconds remaining
before what could be called this nation's true independence day.
</P>
<P>
   At noon on Dec. 31, the United States will surrender control of
the 85-year-old canal to Panama, marking the final stage of the
U.S. withdrawal from the isthmus. Because of scheduling conflicts
and concerns about the Y2K computer problem, a symbolic hand-over
ceremony will be held Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It will mark the start of a new era for Panamanians, who at long
last will run the waterway and control every inch of their national
territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most important moment in Panama's history,'' said
former Panamanian President Nicolas Ardito Barletta.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ceremony will be held at Miraflores Locks, near the
Pacific entrance to the canal. Former President Carter, who signed
the Panama Canal treaties in 1977, will head the U.S. delegation. A
second ceremony, a mostly Panamanian affair, will be held on Dec.
31, when the actual transfer takes place.
</P>
<P>
   On that date, the Panama Canal Commission, the U.S. government
agency that ran the canal, will be dissolved. It will be replaced
by the Panama Canal Authority, an autonomous Panamanian board made
up of business executives and canal veterans.
</P>
<P>
   The turnover of the waterway, which connects the Atlantic and
Pacific oceans, ``represents a big historic change,'' said Peter
Romero, the acting assistant secretary of state for Western
hemisphere affairs. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Even so, there are few indications in Panama City or Washington
that something momentous is afoot.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, top U.S. officials are largely ignoring the
event. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who had been
scheduled to attend Tuesday's ceremony, canceled her Panama trip
because of peace talks between Israel and Syria that will be held
in Washington this week.
</P>
<P>
   Neither President Clinton nor Vice President Al Gore will attend
the Panama ceremony. Analysts say they worry that Republicans
during the 2000 campaign will accuse Democrats of ``giving away''
the canal and damage Gore's run for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in such calculations is that the canal treaties were an
important break from the ``big stick'' policies of the past and did
much to improve U.S.-Latin American relations, according to Adam
Isacson of the Center for International Policy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Returning the canal to Panama ``was the right policy, but it was
never popular'' in the United States, Isacson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has tried to do the sales job lately on why it was
necessary to give the canal back,'' he said. ``People forget, and
they wonder why we are giving away this canal to this little
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panamanians are also taking a low-key approach, but for
different reasons: To them, the hand-over is largely a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   The transition to Panamanian control has been going on for 20
years. The process has helped reduce the fervent nationalism that
U.S. dominance of the canal once provoked.
</P>
<P>
   The 1977 canal treaties, for example, eliminated the Canal Zone,
a 10-mile-wide, U.S.-controlled strip of land straddling the
waterway that had an American governor and police force. Parts of
the zone were fenced off from the rest of Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Omar Torrijos, the Panamanian military ruler who signed the
treaties with Carter, often referred to the zone as a ``colonialist
tumor.''
</P>
<P>
   The treaties also mandated the gradual withdrawal of 10,000 U.S.
troops and the closure of all American military bases.
</P>
<P>
   Today, only about 120 U.S. soldiers remain in Panama, and they
will be gone by the end of the year. Panamanians now make up 97
percent of the canal's 9,000-member work force. A Panamanian has
served as the canal's top manager for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Many Panamanians are too young to remember the anti-American
riots that broke out in 1964 at the beginning of their tiny
nation's struggle to gain control over its own territory.
</P>
<P>
   Panama won independence from Colombia in 1903 through a
U.S.-backed uprising. Immediately afterward, Panama signed a treaty
authorizing the United States to build and operate a canal
connecting the Atlantic and Pacific. The treaty granted the United
States the use, occupation and control of the Canal Zone in
perpetuity. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``The great cause of dissatisfaction no longer exists,'' said
Fernando Manfredo, a former Canal Commission administrator. ``It's
like if you watch a baseball game knowing ahead of time who won.
There is no longer much emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   For many Panamanian teen-agers, the main attraction this Dec. 31
will be the free New Year's Eve concert by salsa star Ruben Blades.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is hardly any historic memory here,'' said Raul Leis of
CEASPA, a Panamanian research center. ``But nationalism is no
longer the main objective. We are now in an era of globalization.''
</P>
<P>
   Panamanian officials already are negotiating contracts with
dozens of foreign businesses to set up factories, assembly plants,
hotels and shopping malls on about 500 square miles of former Canal
Zone properties.
</P>
<P>
   Development is essential to make up for the U.S. pullout. The
American bases pumped about $300 million annually into the
country's economy and provided thousands of well-paying jobs to
Panamanians.
</P>
<P>
   Economic concerns are the main reason why many people here are
sad to see the Americans leave. Newspaper polls have consistently
shown that a majority of Panamanians prefer some kind of U.S.
presence.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries talked for years about setting up a regional
anti-drug center in Panama, but the negotiations broke down.
President Mireya Moscoso, who took office in August, said she has
no plans to reopen talks.
</P>
<P>
   There are also concerns about whether Panama is up to the task
of running the canal. Some fear that the new administrators will
cut corners in an effort to squeeze larger profits from the canal.
</P>
<P>
   As she sat on a bench overlooking the canal last week, Teresa
Canizales compared the American exit to the breakup of a long
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a divorce. You feel a little disoriented,'' she
said. ``It's not the same thing as having a supportive spouse.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jaime Bocanegra, who heads the Canal Commission's Transition
Management Office, points out that the canal has been under mostly
Panamanian control for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic has risen steadily. Last year, 14,244 ships passed
through the canal, paying $525 million in tolls. Bocanegra said
that alternative routes, such as ship-to-rail land bridges, mean
that the canal must run smoothly and safely to stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to destroy what generates so much riches for
the country. That would be shooting ourselves in the foot,'' he
said. ``The Panama Canal doesn't just respond to Panama's reality.
It responds to the international reality, so there is pressure to
provide good service and prices.''
</P>
<P>
   The canal's two-lane locks raise vessels 85 feet, allowing them
to cross the narrowest section of Panama across an artificial lake,
then lower them back down to sea level. Because of growing traffic,
a third lane may have to be added to the locks within the next
decade, Bocanegra said.
</P>
<P>
   The approach of the hand-over date has rekindled passions in the
United States about the waterway, which opened in 1914 and remains
a powerful icon of progress and American know-how.
</P>
<P>
   During two days of hearings last week, Republican members of
Congress reiterated many of the warnings issued when the canal
treaties were ratified by the Senate in a narrow 1978 vote.
</P>
<P>
   They accused the Panamanian government of corruption and warned
that as the Americans leave, leftist rebels in neighboring Colombia
could sabotage the canal. They also claimed that China could wrest
control of the waterway from Panama through a Hong Kong-based
company that won a contract to administer ports at both ends of the
canal.
</P>
<P>
   Panamanian officials point out that the firm, Hutchison Whampoa
Ltd., is one of the biggest shipping companies in the world and won
a competitive bid. They add that the Panama Canal Authority will
control ship traffic and that the treaties guarantee neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   Romero, the assistant secretary of state, said that the
hand-over of the canal does not mean Washington intends to ``turn
off the lights and shut the door and forget about Panama.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite to the contrary,'' he said, ``we've established a very
good basis with this new government for cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
