<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-FARMERS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK FARMERS' DISCRIMINATION SETTLEMENT MAY NOT EASE YEARS OF
PAIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELZONI, Miss. _ A fat check for $50,000. For the nation's
dwindling number of black farmers, the check in the mail hinted at
possible salvation, like a lottery win but potentially more
satisfying because of the wrongs it might wipe clean and the way of
life it might preserve.
</P>
<P>
   The money was the fruit of a class-action settlement this year
intended to amend decades of discrimination in the federal farm
lending program.
</P>
<P>
   But many are finding that it provides little to ensure their
survival, fails to compensate for their bitterness and lost
opportunity, and comes at a time when the U.S. Department of
Agriculture may soon phase out its lending programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't wash away the sin and it doesn't cover up the abuse
that they did to the black farmer,'' said Rodalton Hart, who farms
near Lexington, Miss., in Holmes County.
</P>
<P>
   Under the April 14 class-action settlement, farmers will receive
$50,000 each. An additional $12,000 will be paid directly to the
Internal Revenue Service to cover the taxes on the payment. Also,
any farmer whose claim involved an outstanding or defaulted loan
from the USDA will get that debt written off.
</P>
<P>
   To some, little is better than nothing. To others, no amount is
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Davis, 71, standing under a gaping hole in the ceiling
over her dining table, said her $50,000, cash-free payment was
already spent before it arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we pay the bills, there won't be anything,'' said
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was intended &UR;  &LR; to remedy discrimination against
black farmers who for decades had been turned down for farm loans
or received loans too late to plant a profitable crop. The
discrimination led to foreclosures and the loss of a way of life
that had existed for generations.
</P>
<P>
   There are fewer than 19,000 black farmers in the United States.
There were 925,000 in 1920. Less than 1 percent of U.S. farmers are
black, and they are abandoning farming at three times the rate of
whites, according to U.S. Census Bureau figures.
</P>
<P>
   Black farmers say the USDA's Farm Service Agency has been more
foe than friend. They recall having loan applications stowed away
in desk drawers for months and FSA officials telling them to remove
their hats upon entering FSA offices to show respect.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents are particularly damning considering that for
black farmers turned away by commercial banks and other lending
institutions, the USDA was the lender of last resort.
</P>
<P>
   In a Feb. 28, 1997, policy statement, Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman said that discrimination would not be tolerated. The
comment came shortly after a civil rights action team report
concluded that minority farmers lost their farms and potential farm
income as a result of discrimination by FSA programs.
</P>
<P>
   The report listed 92 recommendations to be implemented within
six months. Priority was given to ensure accountability at the
county level by converting nonfederal county positions to federal
positions.
</P>
<P>
   In the predominantly black Mississippi Delta counties far
removed from the lofty rhetoric of Washington, D.C., black farmers
claim they still must contend with predominantly white Farm Service
Agency committees that decide who gets farm loans.
</P>
<P>
   In the Southeastern United States, blacks account for 1.1
percent of all county committees and office employees. The
committees and employees are 97.5 percent white, according to 1996
USDA figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of these members of county committees, they don't work
for the USDA, they're not county employees, so there's no
enforcement mechanism. You can't penalize them, you can't fire
them, so a lot of them do what they want to do,'' said Mike Espy,
former secretary of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   For Sarah Davis, the settlement will ease the burden of her
debt, nothing more. Fellow Belzoni farmer Edmond Clark, after
having been denied a share of the settlement, clings to a shred of
hope that his appeal will save his farm.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Ross, a plaintiff in the discrimination lawsuit, sees his
school-age daughter's future guaranteed by the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he could count on one hand the number of black
farmers still farming around Belzoni. In his eyes, black farmers,
including himself, in rural Mississippi are systematically being
forced into extinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to lose the land eventually; unless some miracle
happens I'm gonna lose the land,'' Clark said. ``And when I lose
the land I know where it's going. It's going away from a black
farmer and never to return again.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a black farmer who is an exception to the crisis, it
is Eddie Ross, a Warren County cotton farmer who led a
demonstration outside the White House on Dec. 12, 1996, protesting
unfair loan treatment.
</P>
<P>
   His family had farmed outside Vicksburg, Miss., since the 1940s
when his grandfather, Robert Wyatt, bought 120 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Ross applied for his first government loan in 1988 to lease 50
acres of cotton. He applied for three additional loans from 1991 to
1993 to lease more than 700 acres. In those three years, he was
given a loan too late to plant, was turned down for another and
received one on time only to have funding stopped in midseason.
</P>
<P>
   He filed discrimination complaints that received favorable
rulings, but was never compensated for his losses. After obtaining
a copy of the USDA civil rights report, he and five other farmers
sued the USDA in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At a pretrial hearing, Judge Paul L. Friedman of the U.S.
District Court for the District of Columbia rejected the argument
to dismiss the lawsuit on the grounds that farmers could not sue
the federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he said that, all of us, we all just applauded in the
courtroom. We all were so excited,'' Ross said. ``From that point
on we felt confident we were going to get this thing settled.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross would only say his settlement was a seven-figure award that
included his government loan debt payoff. His settlement was
separate from the class-action award.
</P>
<P>
   He said the the class-action award gives farmers a clean slate
by clearing their debt and obtaining new credit to buy equipment
and land.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that money will do, it will give them an opportunity to
compete in their local market. It will give them a chance to go get
quality feed. It will give them a chance to upgrade their farm
equipment,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   Black farmers have never held an edge. In 1920, there were about
925,000 black farms, mainly in the South, representing 14 percent
of all farms. The number has dropped to 18,451, according to the
1997 census figures.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanization and black migration to northern factories cut
deeply into black farming, historically small operations big enough
to sustain families, but too small to generate profitable yields.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at black farmers today as a subset of small
farmers and small farmers as a subset of all farmers, it's clear
that as we move into the new century that the small-family farmer
is dying away,'' Espy said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of U.S. farms fell to 1.93 million in 1992 from 2.24
million in 1982, a 14 percent drop. The number of black-operated
farms dropped 44 percent during the same period, from 33,300 in
1982 to 18,800 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, less than 1 percent of all U.S. farms were owned by
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Further evidence in the dramatic decline in black farm
operations is the disparity in FSA loans to black farmers.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1999 ending Sept. 30, white farmers received 18,687,
or 85 percent, of the 21,900 loans issued by the FSA. Black farmers
received 893 loans, or 4 percent. Of the $1.3 billion loan total,
white farmers received $1.1 billion compared with $32.4 million for
black farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The black farmer also is getting older: Their average age was
58.7 in 1992. Younger generations, witnessing firsthand the
struggle and hard work of keeping a farm alive, have chosen
different careers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But for some, options are a luxury they cannot afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people live at the poverty level. I know because I was
one of them,'' said Ross. ``These people can't afford an education.
These people that come right out of high school have to work to
help support their families, help their mothers and fathers support
their families and can't go to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although they had the grades to go they couldn't go, they had
to go work. That's the life of the Mississippi Delta,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, Edmond Clark was throwing water on a
smoldering module of cotton as a friend picked through the burnt
fibers with a broken broomstick. The module, valued at about
$6,000, was one of two Clark had scheduled for pickup that morning.
It also was the second in as many weeks intentionally set on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Clark speculated the fire was set by a competitor. A handful of
people who lived nearby looked on as Clark and a friend worked to
salvage the module. But in the group was a &UR;  &LR; teen-ager who confessed
to starting the fire out of boredom.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been a good year for Clark. He planted his cotton
late this year and was among the last in a three-county region to
harvest, guaranteeing low prices for his yield.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark understands hardship. His family was reared on a
49-acre farm bought by his father in the early 1940s. Clark
remembers the family sustaining itself on what was raised and
canned on the farm. When he and his three brothers began farming,
the four had to share their father's tractor.
</P>
<P>
   The Clark brothers still live on the land, but the family may
soon lose the farm, which was used as loan collateral.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at that point now,'' said Clark, whose land is still
owned by the FSA. ``We're in the process of trying to get the debt
written off so it can go back to the family.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 22, a court adjudicator rejected Clark's settlement
claim, saying he had not suffered racial discrimination and had
received emergency or operating loans every year from 1981 through
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Clark argued that he could not get loans to buy equipment, and
that when he managed to obtain a loan to lease land and pay
planting costs, it always came too late to harvest a profitable
yield. Other than his father's tractor, the only equipment on hand
was an ordinary garden tiller.
</P>
<P>
   He also was humiliated by county FSA officials who tried to
persuade him to abandon his farm, the only work he had ever known.
</P>
<P>
   Clark hasn't received a loan since 1996, and with the government
debt hanging over him, he doesn't plan on getting any help from
commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``These four years, actually when I look back and see how I made
it, I really don't know. It's just been with the grace of God that
I've done made it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I get up every day not knowing what I'm going to have
to deal with, not knowing how I'm going to be able to buy my seed,
not knowing how I'm going to be able to buy fertilizer, not knowing
how I'm going to pay these notes on this equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Poorman Douglas, the firm contracted to process
settlement claims, announced that 2,412 farmers were mailed checks
from the settlement. Since Sept. 15, the firm has received 19,191
claims from 20 states. The majority of the claims, however, are
from Mississippi, Arkansas, Georgia and Tennessee. The firm expects
to finish processing all claims in early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Under the class-action settlement, farmers must prove that they
were victims of racial discrimination in a USDA credit or benefit
program between Jan. 1, 1981, and Dec. 31, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As of Dec. 1, court adjudicators had decided 4,969 claims. Of
those, 3,083, or 62 percent, favored of the claimant and 1,886 were
denied. Attorneys for the farmers expect a large percentage of the
denials will be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Pires, a lead attorney in the lawsuit, said the
settlement payments are expected to total about $1 billion, making
it the largest class-action civil rights settlement in U.S.
history. In addition to the $50,000 cash payments, debt write-offs
are averaging $30,000 to $40,000 per claimant.
</P>
<P>
   Pires said a lot of farmers are upset because the claims have
taken so long to process or have been denied. He said fingers are
being pointed everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're suspicious,'' he said, ``not only of the government,
they're suspicious of their own lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Sweet, a Jackson, Miss., attorney, said a lot of the
frustration comes from farmers learning that their claims were
denied because they improperly outlined their charges of
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   He said many farmers did not document their problems with the
FSA or were not advised on how to prepare their affidavits. Also,
some attorneys claimed 40 percent of a claimant's settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the settlement is done and done the way they said it will
be done, it will save a lot of farmers,'' Sweet said.
</P>
<P>
   However, former Agriculture Secretary Espy believes little hope
exists for the small farmer if he continues as he has for decades,
plowing away a meager living on small operations. The surviving
farms are the large operations and corporate farms. He said the
black farmer lacks the capital and technical expertise to survive.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, time is running out for the small farmer who
depends on government loans to stay afloat from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   Under a farm bill passed in 1996 that ends farm subsidies by
2002, USDA announced its plans to get out of the lending business
for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For reasons of generational disenchantment, for reasons of the
economies of scale, for reasons of just the risk of the occupation
itself and now the government not providing a helping hand, I think
farmers are wasting away. Black farmers are going to be nonexistent
in the near future,'' Espy said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodalton Hart has known the hard years. He remembers growing up
during the Depression in Holmes County when black farmers pooled
their cotton to earn 5 cents a pound. That amount fed their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Hart said he has never regretted his decision to continue the
family farm, although it has meant a life full of inconvenience and
hardships. He owned land, but he enjoyed few of the luxuries that
came with land ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had the opportunity to enjoy life, take vacations
or have extra spending money to do things that other people do.
That's the only downside, that we have to work all the time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   All the money, he said, went back into the farm.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Sweet said it is farmers such as Hart and Ross who will
survive and are the source of his faith in the black farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have survived in the face of the worst obstacles,'' Sweet
said. ``The sad part of it is that people just want to work. Every
black farmer is not going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Underlining the crisis, he said, is the land, some of which has
remained in black hands since the post-Civil War period of
Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the settlement will save a lot of black farmers. You
can take the black farmer and give him some debt forgiveness and he
will survive. Most of these farmers are not trying to get rich from
the settlement, just debt relief. All they're asking for is a
little debt relief and a promise they'll be treated fairly in the
future,'' Sweet said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get treated fair, the serious black farmers, they'll
stay around.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
