<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A couple of my friends could use some `nanners'
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Many years ago when my son Kristofor was
still a short shadow in the sandbox, I overheard him telling his
best buddy Chuck that he had good ``nanners'' in his house. Chuck
assumed he meant bananas and said that was cool _ could he have
one.
</P>
<P>
   It took a bit of doing but we straightened it out. As I handed
each of them a banana, Kristofor tried to explain to another
confused 3-year-old. ``I said `nanners' not `nanas'.'' Chuck,
caring little for semantics, nodded and munched on.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, ``nanners'' became a byword around our house. I
remember shoving clean socks into his backpack for a sleepover at
Chuck's house and instructing him to mind his ``nanners.'' When he
grew tall and acquired his first set of car keys and a date all in
the same year, I would follow him to the door, reminding him to be
polite.
</P>
<P>
   I'm happy to say it worked. The kid, now 32, married, and quite
tall, hasn't forgotten his pleases and thank yous, and always
remembers to pull out my chair at dinner. Of course, he also finds
it amusing to haul me around under one arm like a 40-pound sack of
birdseed _ but that's a tale for another day.
</P>
<P>
   This gross story is about two friends I ran into the other day
in the cafe uptown. Cal and Amos are somewhere in their mid-70s and
I like them a lot. We often bump into each other for morning coffee
but today they're in for lunch because their wives are Christmas
shopping. They asked me to join them, and that's how I came to be
sitting between two guys _ one loudly slurping the dregs of his
soda through a straw, and the other blowing his nose in a napkin
(at least it was paper).
</P>
<P>
   My eyes widened, I'm sure, but I politely avoided an instinctive
response which would have been to jump up, flail my arms like an
infuriated palm tree, and screech at the top of my lungs:
``Yaaaack!'' (local slang for ``You guys are enough to gag a
grub!'') But I minded my ``nanners.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the racket had died down, and my gorge had slunk back where
it belonged, the boys and I got down to some good conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Cal's all mad at first lady Hillary. ``I never thought I'd live
to see the day when a president's wife moved out of the White House
a year ahead of her husband,'' he's huffing like this has been on
his mind a while. Cal couldn't imagine living anywhere without his
wife. ``I'll tell you what,'' he says, ``Bess Truman was my
favorite first lady and I sure can't picture her ever leaving Harry
on his own while she went off to `find' herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Amos nods and admits he's been wondering about that too, only
his concern comes with dollar signs. ``I want to know who's paying
for those extra Secret Service guys.'' He tells us in no uncertain
terms that it is not his intention to contribute to Clinton's
wife's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Cal allows he can understand why Hillary would want to get out
of the house and cut herself loose from her philandering husband's
crummy coattails, but he thinks the mess she's getting herself into
with her run for the Senate could be nastier than Monicagate.
``That Giuliani is going to chew her up and spit her out,'' he says
looking not too unhappy at the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   I accuse them both of being chauvinists. Cal gives me his best
impish grin and tells me I'm just jealous because I don't have a
husband as wonderful as either one of them. I assure them that's
it. Amos says his wife is all the time saying what a handsome devil
he is.
</P>
<P>
   This happy foolishness lasts through coffee, homemade apple pie,
and on into toothpicks. That's when it gets messy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta' go now,'' I mutter as I reach for my check, ``before I
have to watch you guys eat your lunch twice.'' Cal just grins and
studies a piece of meatloaf he's liberated from behind his bridge.
Amos plays like I've hurt his feelings, but I know I haven't. We
have this ``nanners'' conversation at least once a week. They say
they miss it when I'm gone.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
