<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sneak in some Santana when the kids ask what you want from Santa
 &HT;    Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Give your teens a shock this Christmas. When
they ask you what gift you would like, don't give them the stock,
``All I want is for us to be together and happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell 'em you want ``The Best of Santana'' CD. Then watch 'em
keel over in shock.
</P>
<P>
   If you stopped listening to Casey Kasem decades ago, you might
not know that Carlos Santana, one of the masters of Jurassic Rock,
otherwise known as our music of the '60s and '70s, has the current
No. 1 song on the charts.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``Smooth'' and the kids love it. What they most
likely don't know is that we, their parents, have loved Santana for
almost 30 years. I bought the ``Hits'' CD last week, passing up the
new one because I know the kids will buy it. I'm here to tell you
that the benefits of the old album go beyond just hearing some
terrific music.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Santana is a hit with today's young people gives
me hope. See, my kids and their friends might think I'm just a
little bit cool because I know who he is. Not only that, I saw him
in concert with several other groups like ZZ Top in a memorable
event at what was then Memorial Stadium at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Most kids won't know the group even made music before this
current hit. They will be forced to admit we know at least one
thing they don't. For that, you may want to purchase the album
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   I'm also thinking that for effect, we parents could drive around
listening to the ``Greatest Hits'' CD. Maybe make a drag on the
Loop and crank up ``Soul Sacrifice.'' On spotting a car full of
teens, turn up the bass all the way, roll down the windows and just
jam. That is, if you remember how and are careful not to strain
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how cool you will be, not only knowing the artist but
the words, to such classics as ``Evil Ways'' and ``Black Magic
Woman.'' It's true. My daughters and their cousin were shocked when
my younger sister took them to see ``Wayne's World,'' the movie,
and knew all the words to ``Bohemian Rhapsody'' by Queen. Oh, was
Aunt Patty cool after that.
</P>
<P>
   Those parents who want to stay home with Santana but who still
feel adventuresome could drag out the black lights and the Hendrix
poster. What would the young 'uns think then? It should be fun to
find out.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not up for all that effort, just plug ``Samba Pa Ti''
into the CD player and slow dance with your main squeeze in the
living room. That's guaranteed to send the resident teens through
the roof, or maybe just out of the room. Ah, but you will be
``Smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that doesn't work, turn up the volume and let Santana
keep playing. You can depend on hearing words you thought you never
would out of the mouths of your babes: ``Could you turn that
down?''
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal. E-mail: awalker(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
