<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A Christmas lament
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ This year, retailers had the plastic Christmas
trees out next to the Halloween jack-o-lanterns. Thanksgiving,
after all, isn't very consumer-oriented (other than in the grocery
store), so let's not waste too much time on this no-profit holiday.
Let's just forgo the thanks and get straight to the giving.
</P>
<P>
   I don't like to rush through autumn, though. It is my last deep,
cleansing breath of the season before Christmas mania begins. As I
think ahead to another season of gift-giving and gift receiving, I
take stock of how we have taught our children to experience
Christmas. It's one thing I wish I could ``do over'' as a parent.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, I realize we trained them _ more carefully than we
ever taught them to say ``thank you'' or to chew food with their
mouths closed _ to experience Christmas almost soley as a time of
``getting.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the Thanksgiving turkey was off the table, we would
ask our children what they wanted for Christmas. If they couldn't
think of anything, we had them watch Saturday morning cartoons,
filled as they were with commercials for every conceivable toy in
the world. Or we'd look through toy catalogs. ``Make us a list,''
we urged.
</P>
<P>
   We hung Christmas stockings, built up the excitement about Santa
coming and, in every other imaginable way, filled them with
anticipation about the plethora of goodies they would awaken to on
Christmas morning.
</P>
<P>
   My wisdom has come late, but I offer it to other mothers of
young children.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of mountains of Fisher-Price and Tonka and Nintendo and
Hilfiger, give your children gifts that will hold their interest
much longer than just the two weeks of Christmas vacation. Teach
them to think more about what they can give than what they might
receive. Begin a tradition of saving nickels and dimes all through
the year to buy toys to give to others. Teach them to take time and
patience and thought to make gifts for others that truly will be
treasured for decades to come. Go each year to serve dinner to
homeless people, or make blankets to donate to the Salvation Army,
or simply go door to door in your neighborhood caroling the Good
News. Yes, in our family we did a sprinkling of such things
throughout the years, but it was always a tacked-on event, never
the main event.
</P>
<P>
   With the best of intentions, and in the finest traditions of how
we ourselves were reared, we passed onto our children a legacy of
materialism. Witness the early Christmas morning call to friends:
``What did you get?''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, we taught our children to think primarily of themselves
and their own desires. For the most part, they learned their lesson
well. I'm not sure you can just ``un-train'' them. Our instruction
and indoctrination was too thorough.
</P>
<P>
   We gave lip service to the ``real meaning'' of Christmas, but it
did not translate into meaningful action, a serious shift of
priorities or the establishment of new traditions. And I'm not sure
we're all that different from many families
</P>
<P>
   My hope is that it's still not too late to teach them that ``to
whom much is given, much is expected.'' It would be the best gift
we could ever give them.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
