<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celebrating Y2K with a Y1.8K story
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ There's always an implied sneer when
critics talk about cult movies, cult rock bands and most of all
cult fiction. It is media that doesn't get to sit at the big
people's table. Putting the adjective ``cult'' in front of a noun
is a way of saying, ``get a load of those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet cult movies are played at midnight on college campuses to a
front row that has memorized the best lines. The touring schedules
of cult bands are passed eagerly from hard-drive to hard-drive all
along the Internet. And cult fiction has a community of readers who
confound the expectations of marketing departments, defy
tastemakers and generally aren't supposed to exist.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick O'Brian creates cult fiction. Like with many cult works,
critics are either contemptuously baffled or get all mushy.
Disclaimer: I am a cult member.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brian writes about something we can all identify with _ life
on smaller British warships in the Napoleonic wars. He has written
a series of 20 novels. The latest one has just appeared on
bookstore shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Although each book purports to be a complete novel, none of them
truly stand alone. They are one very long, 20-volume novel. Serial
fiction with a new installment every two years.
</P>
<P>
   The author is now 85, writes in longhand, and says when prodded
into a rare interview that his health is not the best. That a new
volume in the series appeared at all this year is a gift to his
readers. And I would urge you not to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue at the Mizzen'' is a new reason to go back to book one,
``Master and Commander.'' (The title is not as grandiose as it
sounds. It is the rank of someone who commands a ship too small to
be run by a full captain.) To start with the new book would be like
tuning into the last 15 minutes of the program. Don't be tempted.
</P>
<P>
   So why as we head into Y2K would a narrative that begins at
Y1.8K gain cult status?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not because they throw any light on our time.
</P>
<P>
   The hero of the novels, John ``Lucky Jack'' Aubrey, Post
Captain, R.N., is not coping too well with the onset of 19th
century, much less providing us any help understanding the 21st. He
knows only the sea and resents the first stirrings of everything
that would come
</P>
<P>
   to define the world 200 years later. He is a disaster in
business and legal dealings. He distrusts industrialism,
businessmen, the stock market, lawyers, Whigs, utilitarians,
small-d democrats, political reformers, naval modernization,
Methodists, tea-sippers
</P>
<P>
   and Frenchmen.
</P>
<P>
   Historical fiction is overpopulated with 20th century types
stranded in other worlds. Capt. Aubrey is not among them. He is
overadapted to the 19th century sailing ship and a problem
everywhere else he goes. His particular friend (a charming, antique
phrase resurrected by O'Brian in place of our bland ``best friend''
or overly '70s ``main man''), Stephen Maturin, is also solidly a
person of his own time, although more comfortable on its
intellectual fringes. Maturin is the ship's surgeon, natural
philosopher, spy, Catholic among Anglicans, duelist, cellist and
ornithologist. He can trephine a seaman's skull on a swaying main
deck, joke in Latin or plug a Frenchman at 100 yards.
</P>
<P>
   More plausible, subtle and researched than the Horatio
Hornblower books to which they are thoughtlessly compared,
O'Brian's books recreate the Napoleonic era as a complete
alternative universe. Not, like so many other historical novels, as
people with 20th century attitudes unaccountably costumed in Jane
Austin drag.
</P>
<P>
   Are these mere guy-books? Do they cross the line from cult
fiction to full-fledged nerd fiction? The critics are divided. ``A
sort of Hardy Boys for smart, literate men'' condescended the Los
Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is ready-the-carronades-and-strike-the-stuns'l
writing. But it's the best
ready-the-carronades-and-strike-the-stuns'ls writing around. Each
book packed with the vocabulary, objects, sights, smells, tastes
(spotted dog tonight!) and sounds of 200 years ago. Not because
these things teach us anything at all about our own pallid age, but
because they have some value in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy Boys, indeed. Amazingly, for one more volume, the cult
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.) News-
</P>
<P>
   Journal. E-mail: marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
