<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gamers get ready: The toys are back in town
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With the marching out of ``Toy Story 2,'' kids
everywhere are waiting with bated breath for the game. Wait no
longer! Activision's Toy Story 2 ($50 for Playstation and $60 for
Nintendo, www.activision.com) is on the shelf and is sure to be a
hot one for the holiday season. The game follows the movie in that
Woody, the cowboy doll, is stolen, and Buzz Lightyear and friends
take on the task to find him. In the game, you can earn rocket
boots, grappling hooks and other accessories to help in your quest.
If you're more into the sinister battle of new toys vs. old toys,
then Sega's Toy Commander ($50, www.sega.com) is for you. In this
game, you take on the role of Andrew, whose older toys have
rebelled against the newer ones. You must prove yourself a Toy
Commander and bring the toys under your control. Fantastic graphics
are the high point of this one.
</P>
<P>
   CALL ME LI'L BWANA
</P>
<P>
   Grolier Interactive's Virtual Serengeti ($30,
www.gi.grolier.com, for PC and Mac) is as loaded as an elephant gun
with enough live-action video to turn even the most sedentary young
joystick jockey into a big-game hunter. Players take on the persona
of a research assistant for a nature documentary, sent to Africa to
study animal behavior and collect video. Virtual explorers navigate
more than 50 360-degree panoramic environments and seven virtual
Serengeti locations, storing information in an interactive journal.
Along the way, players use the collected information and Grolier
Multimedia Encyclopedia online articles to answer questions about
animals they've spotted. Installation is a snap, and on-screen
video of Nature TV host George Page is available to help wee
adventurers who get stuck. The documentation says the game is for
ages 9 and up, but our test 7-year-old installed and played for
hours on his own. Virtual Serengeti is not your father's Sunday
afternoon nature film.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
