 &HT;    A multitalented mini
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ We all want to make a ``Blair Witch Project.''
After all, the garage movie made $200 million _ and that would be a
nice chunk of change in anyone's pocket. Likewise, it would be nice
to have a digital camera that could record family events on video
and also take still photos. That's why you should pick up the
palm-sized Canon Elura MiniDV Camcorder ($1,800, www.canondv.com).
This bad boy offers high-resolution video, a still-photo mode and a
digital motor drive (which takes high-resolution pictures at 30
frames a second). The Elura boasts 380k pixels so the user can get
premium quality video and stills. The camera is also equipped with
a 48x digital zoom, a variety of digital effects and a color LCD
viewing screen. And for the budding auteur, Canon was nice enough
to bundle a trial version of Digital Origin's EditDV, digital
editing software.
</P>
