<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech breakthroughs evoke memories of holidays past
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shopping for the holidays used to be something I
complained about, but _ like finding just the right Christmas tree
and drinking eggnog _ turns out that it was an important part of
the ritual.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny how memory repaints some of my old Christmas
adventures. The hassles seem good now, even the memories of the
year that I got caught in a dense fog in Oregon and called home to
say I might not find my way back until New Year's Eve. Looking
back, I remember how the fog painted little rainbow halos around
the Christmas lights. And it was cold, hard work dragging a
Christmas tree out of the woods, towing it on cross-country skis.
But, when I think of Christmas now, I remember how the dry snow
squeaked under my skis.
</P>
<P>
   The skis are in the basement now. I'm pretty sure the next time
I ski it'll be with the aid of a joystick, not my old-fashioned
bamboo poles.
</P>
<P>
   I miss Christmas this time of the year. I wonder if, 30 years
from now, people will reminisce about a terrific holiday Web page
they found, or a nifty electronic Christmas card they got. Probably
so. Times change. Maybe your family will remember this as the year
you got a digital camera, or a faster processor.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe like me, you shopped in a different way this year, too.
</P>
<P>
   I've finished my Christmas shopping and I avoided the crowds,
didn't hear the corny department store recordings of carols. I
shopped online. It was efficient and easy and colder emotionally
than a February morning in North Dakota. It reminded me that for
everything technology gives us, it takes something away.
</P>
<P>
   I won't need any wrapping paper or ribbon this year. No one will
make fun of my clumsy attempts to tie a bow, and my cat won't have
the pleasure of sitting smack dab in the middle of the gift I'm
trying to wrap. Instead, someone else _ someone I've never seen _
will wrap up the present, pack it securely away and mail it for me.
So I won't be standing in line at the post office this year either.
</P>
<P>
   Like I said, I miss Christmas. But I think we've automated and
computerized it to the point where my grandparents wouldn't
recognize it. There won't be carolers in my neighborhood, but I
have a string of Christmas tree lights that play ``Silent Night''
with a plinky electronic sound.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the really bad part. I am as seduced by the convenience
of a high-tech Christmas as the next person. I sure had a choice
about where to spend my gift money, and I made it. That's the real
trouble with the changes technology makes in our lives: It's not
something _ unless you plan to move to a cabin out in the woods _
that you can tune out or ignore. It becomes part of your life.
</P>
<P>
   Probably I'm giving this advice to me as much as to you, but I
keep thinking that it may still be possible to turn off some of the
technology this holiday season. Think of it as a way of having a
Y2K-proof Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   If your Christmas tree crashes, it'll be the cat, not a fluke in
programming. So instead of gathering around the computer to read
holiday cards that arrived at the speed of of 43k bps, you could go
out and buy some of the paper ones and address them. And if you sat
at the kitchen table and hummed a Christmas song while you did it,
that would be fine.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but all that sounds good. I'm going to
go home tonight and take off that strand of computerized tree
lights. ``Silent Night'' is too beautiful a song to sound like it
is being played by elves who need a drug test.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this year, on Christmas Eve, you and your family will
gather around the light from a fireplace instead of a flickering
computer monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
