A7361 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-DECK-THE-HALLS-LIFEBE     12-13 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DECK-THE-HALLS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETHING DIFFERENT TO DECK THE HALLS
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color photos of a rosemary topiary and the designer) 
 By AMY SCHLEIN 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever feel like you don't want to bother with decorating an
8-foot evergreen tree _ but you don't want to be a Scrooge, either?
</P>
<P>
   There are other Christmas tree options, some easier, others more
stylistic, says Jerry Bolduan of Green Valley Growers in
Sebastopol, Calif. Bolduan, who frequently contributes to Martha
Stewart Living magazine, offers some alternatives. ''The basic
thing is that you don't have to have the basic conical shaped
tree,'' he says, ''although it can be achieved using other
materials.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of his ideas for holiday decorating:
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)Oak: Using the branches of classic native oak trees that
have lichen or moss growing in them can be really beautiful with
tiny white lights, says Bolduan.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) Topiaries: Bolduan says topiaries are a bit sensitive,
but make a beautiful presentation. ''Rosemary topiaries can be used
as a good alternative to a classic Christmas tree. Not only are
they fragrant, like a Christmas tree, but they can be grown in a
pot or in the ground and used from year to year, both for
decoration and cooking,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Topiaries can range in size from a a pretty little 2-foot-tall
tree made of ivy to sheared evergreens as tall as 6 feet, Bolduan
notes. One of the benefits of using these is that they can become a
decoration for the front entry of your home when the holiday season
is over.
</P>
<P>
   Topiaries typically are not happy indoors. If you want a topiary
as part of your permanent decorating scheme, you really need to
have three of them to rotate, Bolduan explains. Two can remain
outside for two weeks, while one spends the week inside with you.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) Make your own artificial tree: Get a conical shaped
wire frame used for a topiary, put it directly , then mount it on
top of a pot set on a table or on the floor. Make a natural
garland, or use artificial garland, and wind it around the frame in
coil-like fashion to give it that Christmas-tree look, Bolduan
says.
</P>
<P>
   When using cut and wired fresh materials in a garland, remember
they're no longer in water, Bolduan says. He suggests choosing
materials that, once they're cut, will hold their shape and color
and won't fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best red berry that will not shrivel is called nandina, or
heavenly bamboo. A blue berry that will not shrivel is a vibernum
berry. The drier the berry is when put it in your decoration, the
longer it will last. For example, the nandina berry is a beautiful
red berry, and one year later, that berry will look just like it
did when you used it.''
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) Magnolia: Bolduan recommends a variety that has a brown
velvet surface on the back of the leaf. ''That magnolia works
extremely well for wreath making,'' he says. ''I did a book with
Martha Stewart about the wreaths of every state in the union, and
we did a magnolia wreath, using brown ribbon as an accent that
matched the reverse of the leaf perfectly. It's probably one of the
most popular in the whole book.''
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) Japanese maple: ''Japanese maple is especially
beautiful,'' he says. He suggests that you always buy this as a
plant, never as a cutting. ''At Christmastime, it will no longer
have any leaves, but the delicate nature of it going up umbrella
fashion, and coming down, with very fine branching structure, could
make a really dramatic decoration, especially on a table. And it
would hold ornaments extremely well.
</P>
<P>
   ''The double advantage is after you use it for the holidays, you
can plant it outdoors either in the ground or in a container.''
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)Display items: Finally, Bolduan says remember that many
things beyond plants and trees will work as a focal point for a
display, especially if it particularly evokes memories and feelings
of the holidays for you.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't have to be a tree. I used to use an old sled and
old metal truck from when I was a boy, one of the ones that you
actually got inside and pedaled,'' he says. Anything that reminds
you of the holidays, especially ones past, offers great
possibilities for decorating, he says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Amy Schlein writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
