<HEADER>
A7371 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NETWATCH14-COX     12-13 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amazon.com applying lessons of '98
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jeff Bezos is a happy guy.
</P>
<P>
   In person, the founder and chief executive of Amazon.com laughs
a lot, drinks a lot of coffee and talks excitedly about the bright
future of his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon is one of the most successful online retailers, selling
everything from best-selling books to power tools and nearly
everything in between. In the race for holiday shoppers and their
dollars, Amazon is turning up at the top of nearly every list of
most-visited shopping sites.
</P>
<P>
   The great online shopping stampede of 1998 taught Amazon a few
lessons, and this year it is ready with not only a one-click
ordering system but gift-wrapping services and wish lists shoppers
can fill out and mail to prospective gift-givers.
</P>
<P>
   Bezos says one secret to his success is thinking of ways to make
the online shopping experience more fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers should not and do not spend time in the shower
thinking up new technologies for Amazon,'' he said during a visit
to Atlanta last week, laughing the kind of laugh you can only have
when the world is spinning just the way you want it to spin.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead into the 21st century, Bezos sees nothing but
fleets of UPS trucks speeding CDs, DVD players and power saws to
happy shoppers all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Bezos started out selling books, but not because of his love of
the printed word. ``We made a list of 20 products you could sell
online that you could not sell from mail-order companies,'' he says
of Amazon's humble beginnings. ``There weren't many mail-order book
companies, because if you tried to create a print catalog, it would
be the size of several Manhattan phone books.
</P>
<P>
   ``The realization I had was that one of the great things about
the Web is that you can build something online that you cannot do
in a physical store. We didn't know if it would work,'' he says.
``Frankly, I'm the most surprised person in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Bezos says that's one of the great things about the Web: It's
possible to use the Internet to sell as many books as you can keep
in warehouses. To make the process even easier for power shoppers,
the Web can add search functions and gift registries and recommend
other products in order to eliminate aimless browsing. You want a
book? Type in the title and order it. Simple. Easy. Profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Or it would be if Amazon didn't keep expanding to one product
category after another. ``We are a famously unprofitable company,''
Bezos says, flashing a ``What, me worry?'' smile.
</P>
<P>
   Bezos says Amazon is making money on the products it sells, but
that those profits are going to marketing and adding new product
categories like electronics and home improvement items.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to build a place where customers can come to buy
anything online,'' he says. But to do that he'll need the help of
third-party product providers, many of which are already on board
in the Web site's ZShops area.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do a good job in one area,'' he says, ``your customers
will ask you to do more. One of our challenges is to let people
know we sell all these different things.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to do that is through Amazon's series of TV ads
featuring a chorus harmonizing about the many products available on
Amazon.com and how many tons of toys Amazon has. ``Every ton weighs
2,000 pounds,'' they sing. ``That's a lot of toys.'' Some find the
campaign kitschy and cute; others say it's just annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Are the ads working? Bezos isn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody famous once quipped, `I know half my advertising is
working, I just don't know which half.''' He laughs that big,
booming laugh before getting serious again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense to heavy up during the holiday season. There
are lots of shoppers and lots of first-time shoppers. We have to
try and motivate people to shop online for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you are going to drive even more people to an already
enormously popular site, you had better make sure that if you
promise a book in three to seven working days, it turns up in that
time.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows this better than Bezos, who admits he just scraped
by last Christmas and isn't about to let any kind of fulfillment
disaster ruin his holidays. He knows there's way too much at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to invest in the back end of your business,'' he says
simply. ``We think it's important to ship things to people. In real
estate they say it's location, location, location. In the online
world it's technology, technology, technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tarnish your online reputation with bad customer
service,'' he says. ``The Internet is unforgiving for companies who
don't fulfill customer expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's no laughing matter for Bezos _ or any of his
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
