<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Accessing of groups can ease info hunt
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What image comes to mind when someone says Internet?
Nowadays, for most people, it's the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Web has become (other than e-mail) the most
popular way to use that giant pipeline for information called the
Internet, it's not always the best way to get information.
</P>
<P>
   Long before there was a Web, there were newsgroups. Unlike the
highly graphical Web, these are basically message areas. You post a
message, usually a question or a comment, and all the other members
of that newsgroup can see it and comment.
</P>
<P>
   Using the newsgroups is easy with the right software, and you'll
find out today how to get the news reader programs you need. For
highly specialized topics, newsgroups are still the place to find
the real expertise on the Web. Newsgroups are organized according
to topics and _ no matter what your interest _ you'll probably find
it there. Parents, however, should be warned. The newsgroups also
include some topic areas that would be offensively sexual or
obscene, even for the most liberal.
</P>
<P>
   While your Web browser offers the ability to read and create
newsgroup postings, a dedicated news reader works best. The best
place to find that reader is www.tucows.com. Whether you use a PC
running Windows or favor the Macintosh, or even an Amiga or a
machine running Linux, you'll find a reader here.
</P>
<P>
   Simply select the operating system using the pull-down menus and
then type in the search word ``newsgroups'' ... without the quote
marks. You'll be zapped to a page describing the news readers for
your particular operating system. There's a description of how each
works so you can select the one that suits your fancy. Keep in mind
that the listing usually will have both shareware readers (which
means that you are supposed to pay for it if you decide to keep it
and that some features may be disabled until you do pay) and
freeware readers (no payment is ever made).
</P>
<P>
   If you're new to newsgroups, you may have a difficult time
finding the ones you're most interested in. Things are still sort
of nerdlike out there. All newsgroup readers will _ the first time
you use them _ load in the names of the newsgroups available to
you. You can then use search terms to find the groups that you care
about.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to get an exact hit to find the right newsgroup
this way. For instance, if you want to find a newsgroup that sells
amateur radio equipment and you use the term ``ham'' ... as in ham
radio ... you won't get a hit if the newsgroup's proper name uses
the word ``amateur'' instead of ``ham.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a way around this. And we'll get back to the Web for
that. A search engine called Deja.com (www.deja.com/) does an
excellent job of searching the newsgroups. Just like the search
engines you use to find Web sites, you type in the search term and
Deja will ferret out the newsgroups where that topic is discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Using the search engine is an excellent way to find the sort of
newsgroups you'd enjoy. Just type in search words, make note of the
newsgroups where the term appears and try them out. You can click
on the links that Deja brings up to check them out, too.
</P>
<P>
   One last newsgroup tip: Be aware that if you do post a message,
your e-mail address appears. Some people choose to use one of the
free e-mail services such as Hot Mail or Yahoo to avoid getting
both junk mail to your main account and revealing your main e-mail
address to the casual newsgroup browser.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
