</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Graphire program more refined than mere drawing with a mouse
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I am no different from the average user in my
resistance to change. Whatever I'm accustomed to, regardless of how
antediluvian it may be, is almost always going to be better than
anything else, no matter how new and wonderful it really is.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, I believe I have become smitten with a new input
system.
</P>
<P>
   Wacom has long been in the business of making computer drawing
tablets for graphic artists. Being no artist, I never bothered to
try one until the company came out with its Graphire system.
</P>
<P>
   This consists of a stiff tablet about the size of an ordinary
mouse pad, a mouse and a pen, or pencil, as you wish. The pen and
the mouse are cordless; the cord is connected to the tablet.
</P>
<P>
   The one I'm using plugs into the USB port for Windows 98
systems. There is a serial port version for Windows 95 interfaces.
</P>
<P>
   I'm enjoying this outfit a great deal; it's an excellent system
for those who must have a mouse, but occasionally get involved in
graphics programs in which something more exact would be useful.
</P>
<P>
   I was somewhat put off initially by the lack of heft in the
mouse. However, it is a rollerless type and, once it is applied to
its tablet, this feeling goes away. The shape is only slightly
different from the standard Microsoft mouse and, like that standby,
it has two buttons divided by a wheel.
</P>
<P>
   It is, for me, just as comfortable to use.
</P>
<P>
   The pen takes some getting used to, of course. It is a simple
plastic tool, shaped like a pen, with an oblong button near the
tip. There is a blue protrusion on the back end which looks like an
eraser and indeed, in some applications, serves as an eraser.
</P>
<P>
   The software that comes with the Graphire system is quite good.
The mouse and pen are customizable, both for your entire system or
for individual applications. Even the mouse buttons and the wheel
can be reprogrammed, although it's hard to imagine anyone wanting
to do that.
</P>
<P>
   The harder you press with the pen, the stronger and darker the
line. The pressure needed to get the sort of line you ordinarily
want can be set up through the control software. Clicking on
whatever needs to be clicked is accomplished by tapping with the
tip of the pen.
</P>
<P>
   There is a penholder at the top of the pad to keep the
instrument and prevent damage to its tip. There is a clear plastic
overlay on top of the working portion of the pad. You can slip a
drawing or whatever under the overlay, and then trace it out into
the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Outlined on the main section of the pad is a rectangle that
represents the computer screen. You can set up the pen so that
where it works on the pad corresponds exactly to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if you open up a graphics program, take the pen
and make squiggles on the upper left corner of the tablet
rectangle, that's where you'll make them on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse can be made to work this way, too, but that gets very
confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Using the pen comfortably takes practice, but, if you'll recall,
so did using the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The pen ordinarily won't work in a word processor, but there's
an accompanying program that will allow you to use the pen to mark
up copy. There's also a nice paint program, although a drawing
program would seem more useful.
</P>
<P>
   The printed manual is very skimpy, but the online manual is
outstanding. For $99.95, Graphire is very hard to resist. More
information is available at www.wacom.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
