<HEADER>
A7381 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A14-COX     12-13 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: Could you print the current cost of items in
``The Twelve Days of Christmas'' song?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ann Wright
</P>
<P>
   A: Glad the folks at PNC Bank do the calculations every year.
Does your true love have a high Visa limit? The total for all the
gifts listed in the song (364 separate items because each
dayrepeats the prior days' gifts) is $59,719.33. Economizing?
Purchase each item once, lowering the total to $14,940.17. So which
items rose in cost? Pear tree prices were affected by a drought.
Labor costs for the drummers and lords rose. Want the full
breakdown? Visit www.pncbank.com./12days/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have found feathers on our property. I would like to know
how to sanitize them. _ John Oliver
</P>
<P>
   A: Better leave those feathers on the ground. ``Collecting any
feathers from nongame birds such as bluebirds and cardinals is a
violation of the National Migratory Bird Treaty Act,'' says Paul
Sunby, of SWCA, an environmental consulting firm. Collecting
feathers from threatened or endangered birds (e.g., bald eagles)
violates the Endangered Species Act. Yikes! Why? No way for the
authorities to tell if you found the feather or killed the bird to
get it. But you probably have duck feathers from birds you were
licensed to shoot, correct? In that case, the advice of Martinez
Brothers Taxidermists' Alex Martinez applies: Wash the feathers in
dishwashing soap and water. Rinse in clear water, then soak in
Coleman fuel (yes, as in lantern) while wearing a mask in a
well-ventilated area. Blow-dry. Next, dust with a mixture of half
cornmeal and half borax. Toss until dry. Remove the dusting
solution with a hair dryer and soft cloth, and arrange the
feather's barbs.
</P>
<P>
   This process rids the feathers of blood, dirt and fat. To
protect from bugs and other critters, Martinez uses a powdered
insecticide.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several co-workers and I received an electronic message about
an ill girl, Amy Bruce, and Make-A-Wish Foundation. I thought it
was a scam. Others swear this is an honest message. Who is right? _
M.K.
</P>
<P>
   A: You are right. This bogus electronic chain letter has
prompted inquiries to various Make-A-Wish offices, which are not
connected to the plea. The Make-A-Wish Foundation has identified
the person who started the chain letter and has contacted the
individual's Internet service provider to pursue the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I found what looks like WWII ammunition while cleaning out a
shed behind my grandparent's farmhouse in East Texas. (My late
uncle served combat duty in WWII.) The ammunition is in a metal box
painted army green. Inside there are about 10-12 small cardboard
boxes labeled ``50 cartridges, Carbine, Caliber .30 M1, Ammunition
Lot PG26258, Kings Mills Ordnance Plant.'' Is it legal to possess
this? Does it have value in a collectors market? How do I sell it
or dispose of it safely? _ M.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, it is legal and no, there is no collectors market I
could find. As for the hunter's market? There is no way to know if
the ammunition has been properly stored all these years. Did it
ever get wet and stay wet? It may not be in any condition to be
fired safely. Please do not toss the ammunition in the trash or
bury it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We recently purchased a car and were charged $50 for a
vehicle inventory tax although the car will not be on the dealer's
lot when the annual inventory is taken. Is this legal? If every car
sold during the year is charged this tax, how does that figure for
the amount of tax paid to the state by the dealer? Who gets the
excess cash?
</P>
<P>
   _ Nancy Ulland
</P>
<P>
   A: The automobile inventory tax officially changed January 1994
to a property tax _ even though some dealers still refer to it as
the vehicle inventory tax. Dealers are charged property tax on
their vehicles based on a complex mathematical formula, says Sheila
Clancy of the State Comptroller's office. So yes, the charge is
legal. All collected tax goes to local property tax jurisdictions _
the county, AISD, ACC, etc. Clancy reminds consumers this is a
property tax paid by the dealer so you might try negotiating it out
of your car deal. More questions? Call the comptroller's office at
(800) 252-9121.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter wet the mattress recently and it doesn't have any
type of protective covering. How can I clean the mattress? It is
soaked. _ L.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Turn the mattress on its side and position a towel beneath
the stain. Sponge the spot with a mixture of one part vinegar and
one part water. If you have a wet vacuum, use it. Blot excess with
clean towels. Final sponging should be with clean water. Repeat as
necessary. Dry with a hair dryer or, if possible, in the sun. Use a
disinfectant spray. And buy a protective cover so you do not have
to repeat the process. Q: I have always wondered about Santa's
reindeer. Are they males or females? _ M.W.
</P>
<P>
   A: Females _ one and all. Both male and female reindeer sport
antlers. According to John Dinon of Michigan's Binder Park Zoo,
male reindeer shed their antlers at the end of November or the
beginning of December; females keep them until spring. So Santa's
Dec. 25th antlered reindeer must all be females. The females keep
the antlers to compete successfully with the larger males for food
during the winter and, after giving birth, to protect the fawns.
</P>
<P>
   Dinon adds that the clicking of the reindeer hooves heard ``up
on the housetop'' is accurate. Reindeer walking on any surface make
a clicking sound. Remember the names of the reindeer that Rudolph
led? Dasher, Dancer, Prancer, Vixen, Comet, Cupid, Donder and
Blitzen. You read that right _ Donder, not Donner, is what Clement
Moore wrote in ``A Visit from St. Nicholas.'' Donder is Dutch for
thunder.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have visited the Elisabet Ney Museum. They have a corner
stone that says, ``sursum 1892 _ 1902.'' I suppose that's Latin.
What does it mean?
</P>
<P>
   _ James G.
</P>
<P>
   A: The studio was built in 1892, and the tower as well as the
east wing were added in 1902. ``Sursum corda'' is a term that
German-born sculptor Elisabet Ney embraced, which means ``uplift
your heart'' _ to yearn, to aspire, to seek. ``Sursum'' (upwards)
is the title of a Ney sculpture. ``That cornerstone refers to Ney's
ideals _ to aspire with unfaltering zeal,'' says Mary Collins
Blackmon, museum curator. The Elisabet Ney Museum, 304 E. 44th St.,
houses her marble and plaster statuary.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a very special friend that is a big Chicago Cubs fan.
I would like to get her a button down jersey with her name on the
back. Any suggestions? Perhaps a phone number for the Pro Shop at
their baseball park (Wrigley Field?). _ G.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Contact Chicago Cubs Souvenirs at (800) 248-9467 to place an
order. But you are too late to have the jersey monogrammed if this
is a Christmas present. A custom job takes 3-6 weeks. Order a plain
jersey and have her name put on locally.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
