<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-PANDAVISIT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A field trip to learn about Atlanta's pandas
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A few weeks ago, News for Kids asked you to call in
with your best question about Zoo Atlanta's giant pandas. NFK took
the best five questioners out of nearly 300 to the zoo to see the
rare bears and to meet the head panda keeper.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what 6-year-old Morgan Bonham of Madison, Ga., 8-year old
Anna Perling of Dunwoody, Ga., 9-year-old Kendall Harris of
Sharpsburg, Ga., 10-year-old Kyle Mancini of Alpharetta, Ga., and
12-year-old Billy Townsend of Ben Hill, Ga., learned:
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's hottest new couple start their day around 7 a.m., but
it takes more than a clock radio to rouse Lun Lun and Yang Yang. It
takes the zoo keepers, a bamboo appetizer and the promise of a bowl
of high-protein porridge.
</P>
<P>
   While they're eating, the keepers ``check their poop,'' get a
urine sample and weigh the ``little'' critters to make sure they're
healthy. The pair sit on platform scales while they eat, says
assistant curator for large mammals Rich Sartor.
</P>
<P>
   The male, Yang Yang, is the lightweight for now, tipping the
scales at about 185 pounds. His female buddy, Lun Lun, weighs in
around 205 pounds. Sartor says Yang Yang will most likely end up
the heavyweight. Yang Yang lost weight last summer in China when he
was sick.
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast, the pandas head out to their day rooms or to
their caves to play, sleep, wrestle, explore and, as our five
winners observed, scratch. All the while, researchers study the
animals' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   So what did NFK's winners really want to know? Here's a sample:
</P>
<P>
   Anna: We read in this animal book that pandas were members of
the raccoon family and they weren't really bears.
</P>
<P>
   Rich (the panda keeper): People weren't really sure what to do
with them when they were trying to put them in a taxonomic family.
Some people thought the best place to put them was the raccoon
family. But they've been doing biochemistry work, and the
biochemistry work puts them in the bear group. (So you can say
panda bear now.)
</P>
<P>
   Billy: I saw on TV when the pandas were in China that the
veterinarians and staff were speaking to the pandas in Chinese. Is
the staff in Atlanta going to communicate with the pandas in
English or Chinese?
</P>
<P>
   Rich: We'll be talking to them in English because we don't speak
Chinese. So the pandas will be learning a new language. They can
pick it up pretty quickly as they get to know their keepers; they
see their keepers every day. Their keepers are the source of good
things, so they like their keepers and pay attention to them.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle: Do the keepers have contact with them?
</P>
<P>
   Rich: We don't go into the habitat with our pandas, we don't
actually step in there. But we can touch them through the bars,
particularly if they lean up against it with their backside. We can
get a good scratch in as long as everyone's being careful. As
placid, as calm as they seem to be ... nobody wants to be a panda
toy. You could get hurt or even killed, and they may not even mean
to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan: How do they play?
</P>
<P>
   Rich: Rough and tumble. They like to wrestle, roll around on
each other, do somersaults. They like to climb and drape themselves
over the logs. They're pretty silly actually.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall: How do they communicate with each other?
</P>
<P>
   Rich: They can see each other, so they can read each other's
behavior. ... And they make some sounds. They growl; they huff;
they bleat like a sheep. That's something to hear, and it really
does sound like a sheep or a goat. ... They can kind of bark like a
dog. That's an angry one. And they can roar like a bear.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
