<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The booster advantage
 &HT;    By Mike Fish and David A. Milliron
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACON, Ga. _ When Westside High School opened three years ago,
the view from the back showed acres of barren fields. This fall,
those fields are adorned with athletics facilities befitting a
small college campus. They are appraised at more than $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   It is the work of wildly energetic, well-meaning boosters. They
have built baseball and football stadiums for their sons and
renovated a country house to function as the supporters'
headquarters on 52 acres adjoining school property, all owned by
the private, nonprofit Westside Boosters Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The generosity might have placed the school afoul of a federal
gender-equity law, which principal Pat Coxsey knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I believe under Title IX we're supposed to have the same
facilities (for boys and girls),'' Coxsey said, weighing her words.
``It concerns the parents of softball girls. Those parents are,
like, `We don't have bathrooms over here, and we don't have the
same things the guys do.' They're absolutely right. I can't say
they do, because they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   School administrators throughout Georgia walk a precarious line
in dealing with booster clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Title IX law requires schools to afford equitable treatment of
male and female athletes. That means if somebody donates to the
boys program, it is the school's responsibility either to provide
or find a donor for comparable facilities for the girls, federal
officials say. Administrators cannot get off with, ``Oh, the
booster club did it; we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Many public high schools rely on booster groups _ often geared
toward football _ to build stadiums, augment the salaries of
coaches and secure vehicles and other perks for them.
</P>
<P>
   Westside football coach and athletics director Robert Davis
serves on the executive committee of the Georgia High School
Association, which governs extracurricular activities at member
public and private schools. Westside boosters provide Davis with a
Ford pickup, outfitted in the school's garnet and gold colors. They
also pay to send his Seminoles to preseason camp on Jekyll Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all illegal (on the part of the school),'' said lawyer
Kristen Galles, a Title IX specialist, because the same benefits
are not showered on girls coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The clubs often go unregulated by schools, even as many generate
thousands of dollars annually. The U.S. Department of Education's
Office for Civil Rights, which investigates discrimination
complaints, has not paid much attention, because it focuses on
colleges, with their scholarships and immense athletics budgets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's an issue here (at Westside), it's going to be an issue
at every high school,'' said Coxsey, principal at the Macon high
school. ``It really is a state problem. No one monitors it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because few districts can spare funds for athletics, partly by
law, a booster club subculture has been created that induces
parents to hustle for money. It accentuates the disparity between
schools attended by children from affluent families and those
attended by children of less affluent families.
</P>
<P>
   The clubs also complicate efforts to bring schools into
compliance with federal gender-equity laws.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATE SOURCES PAY WHEN STATE DOESN'T
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it being part of a problem,'' said Lamar Daniel, a
former investigator for the U.S. Department of Education's Office
for Civil Rights. ``If you had state funds involved, then maybe
you'd be closer to state monitoring (for compliance). By not having
state funds, the state says, `Well, we have no interest in how you
raise the money or how your booster club pays for these sports.'''
</P>
<P>
   So, other sources are cultivated.
</P>
<P>
   At Lassiter High in east Cobb, the football stadium has three
cell-phone towers _ the steel monoliths for wireless communication
_ rising above banks of lights. The lease agreement has brought the
school about $100,000 during the past three years, according to
principal Charles Lea, with half of it helping to pay down the
stadium debt and the other half going to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter has received additional funding from the Cobb Electric
Membership Corp. It donated $1.6 million to the county school board
in June, with the understanding that $600,000 be used for a
football field house at the school. The corporation directed that
the rest go to pay stadium debts at Pope and Harrison high schools
and assist in stadium construction at two new schools.
</P>
<P>
   The corporation's chief executive officer, Dwight Brown, is
president of Lassiter's football booster club.
</P>
<P>
   The school district formed a tax-exempt charitable body, the
Cobb County Schools Education Foundation, to handle that and other
donations. It is directed by Stan Wise, chairman of the state
Public Service Commission _ and leader of the Lassiter baseball
booster club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally want to make sure that this goes beyond just
athletics,'' Wise said. ``You say, `Well, yeah, right, but $1.6
million just went to athletics.' I say it went to programs where
kids, moms and dads are going to be active in football and
baseball, and we're going to have to come up with that money one
way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether the Cobb foundation also will fund girls
programs. Its officials say more funding is being sought for other
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the responsibility of the district administration to
ensure that the girls do not receive second-class treatment,
period,'' said Mary Francis O'Shea, Title IX coordinator of the
Office for Civil Rights, ``that you provide equitable opportunities
in athletics for your girls as well as for your boys, no matter
where you get the money. That is really not complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   `A FACILITY PROBLEM'
</P>
<P>
   When Coxsey opened Westside, she was greeted by the booster club
from heaven. The school was in need of everything, and there was no
turning the boosters down. Last year, they raised $980,000 toward
paying off debt on their Sports and Fine Arts Complex.
</P>
<P>
   No principal would reject them, Coxsey said. Besides, the Bibb
County School District, not her, had final say over booster
projects.
</P>
<P>
   The potential gender-equity violation is most graphically
illustrated with comparisons between the softball and baseball
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball field is a mini-stadium, spectacularly manicured,
with a Wrigley Field-like brick backstop behind home plate. The
softball site is a bare-bones field, enclosed by chain-link
fencing.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball field has 50 box seats behind home plate and 550
bleacher seats. The softball field has six rows of temporary
bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball field has brick dugouts with lights and brick
concession stands and offices. The softball field has open dugouts
topped with Fiberglas sheets and a former football ticket booth for
a concession stand.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball field has lights. The softball field does not.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball field has permanent restrooms. The softball field
has two foul-smelling portable toilets.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel, the former OCR investigator, said, ``It sounds like
they've got a facility problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Coxsey said that worries her. In one breath, the principal can
say that at least Westside has a field, which isn't true of other
Bibb County schools. But if a complaint should bring federal
investigators on campus, the school district would be hard-pressed
to explain away the disparities in its treatment of boys and girls
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you're supposed to have (equity),'' Coxsey said. ``At
the same time, if the system says we don't have (the money), I
don't know where you go from that point except to try and get your
boosters to help. I think eventually they will help the softball
girls, but I don't know where it is on the list of their
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I assume if (OCR) pushes it, something is going to have to
be done. They don't really care if you have the money or not.
You're going to cut instruction or cut something, if they put you
under the gun to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Pruett, booster club director, said his group isn't to
blame, because the softball field is on school property and the
baseball stadium is on private grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try to help (the softball team) as much as we can, but
we're waiting for the school board to do something,'' he said. ``We
can't go on school property and build buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Pruett said the club has helped girls sports at Westside, such
as paying for a storage shed and portable toilets on the softball
site.
</P>
<P>
   Coxsey said that the two-tiered treatment of girls and boys
sports long has been accepted in Georgia education and that
districts have managed to get by, as long as no one raised a
ruckus. If boosters kicked in money for football, rarely has equal
funding been sought for softball or volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   Coxsey said, ``It does send out a message, absolutely _ (girls),
you're kind of second-class here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
