<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7388 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-EQUITY-PORKBARREL14-C     12-13 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EQUITY-PORKBARREL14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Legislators find ways to get state funds to school sports
despite laws against it
 &HT;    By Mike Fish and David A. Milliron
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEZUMA, Ga. _ As the afternoon sun reflects off the metal
bleachers, George Hooks surveys the work needed to spruce up the
Macon County High School football stadium. The South Georgia native
is talking championships, Friday night football, entertainment for
an entire town.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real need here,'' Hooks says.
</P>
<P>
   Money is on its way, he promises. And it is, a state check for
$100,000, thanks to the Democratic senator from Americus, who is
chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   With few exceptions, it is illegal for school districts in
Georgia to spend state tax dollars on athletics, but every year
legislators skirt the law by practicing old-fashioned pork-barrel
politics to move teams into larger stadiums or fancier uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Since fiscal 1996, lawmakers have doled out $2.8 million for
high school football stadiums, field houses, stadium lighting and
sports equipment, according to a computer analysis by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution of grants dispersed by the state Department of
Community Affairs. Less than 10 percent has been awarded by the
governor's office, with the remainder handed out by the General
Assembly in the form of local assistance grants.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-1990s, money for legislators' pet projects was
included in the Department of Education budget, even though it was
not requested by the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stadium things come through Community Affairs because
they're not supposed to be funded, period,'' state school
Superintendent Linda Schrenko said. ``Somebody of influence like a
George Hooks gets extra money in the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general's office said the practice is
suspicious, but it has not been asked an opinion of whether the
grants violate state law. ``Those kind of expenses would certainly
raise questions,'' deputy counsel Daryl Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia lawmakers seem to violate the spirit, if not the letter,
of the federal Title IX law by allocating more than 85 percent of
grants to projects aiding boys sports.
</P>
<P>
   When the Legislature appropriated $15,000 last session for Bryan
County High School in Pembroke, the bulk went to purchase football
uniforms. Cheerleading _ which the federal government does not
recognize as a sport under Title IX _ got $2,000 for outfits.
</P>
<P>
   The pork-barrel projects reach to junior high schools, with
North Clayton Middle School receiving $5,000 last year, mostly for
boys sports.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators trade their votes on the budget for inclusion of
sports projects that benefit their districts. Some say they act on
the neediest of requests from back home. Hooks said he pushed for
$100,000 for Macon County because, with the 1996 state champions
moving up in classification to Class AA, seating capacity would
have to be doubled to 4,000 for the school to host playoff games.
The school is in the midst of a $225,000 expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Macon County High School ranks among the worst schools in the
state for complying with Title IX, according to a
Journal-Constitution analysis. Boys make up 70 percent of its
athletes. The school sponsors eight boys sports and six girls
sports, excluding cheerleading. The school pays supplements of
$40,850 to its 13 coaches of boys sports and $13,850 to the six
coaches of girls sports. Yet, the disparity widened when the grant
money was spent on football.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real need, in an absolute sense,'' Hooks said. ``It
helps athletics, gets kids to school and encourages them to stay in
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooks also helped Lee County High in Leesburg get a $25,000
grant to install a sprinkler system on its baseball and
football/soccer field.
</P>
<P>
   Hooks is hardly the only lawmaker playing the game. The practice
reaches to the top of the ladder at the state Capitol, with Speaker
Tom Murphy (D-Bremen) assisting athletics in his district. Even the
governor chips in.
</P>
<P>
   In the budget, the Legislature annually sets aside money for the
governor's emergency fund, which totaled $3 million this year.
Local groups apply for grants, and the governor decides which
requests to fund.
</P>
<P>
   State documents from 1996 show that then-Gov. Zell Miller helped
booster clubs pay three stadium debts in Gwinnett _ Meadowcreek
($20,000), South Gwinnett ($15,000) and Collins Hill ($10,000). In
1998, Miller approved $5,000 for weight-lifting equipment at East
Paulding High School.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes, then a state representative in the middle of
his 1998 gubernatorial campaign, helped secure a $75,000 grant to
build a football field house at his alma mater, South Cobb High,
which his three children also attended. In 1994, South Cobb
received $40,000 for athletics facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disgusting that your tax money is being spent like
this,'' said Betty Jo Williams, who retired last year after 20
years in the Legislature. ``If the state is going to give so much
money ... for the state's athletic programs, then it should be done
out in the open.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, $850,000 found its way into the budget for high
school sports from the Legislature and the governor. Schools and
sports teams get rewarded for no specific reasons, other than
because of connections to powerful lawmakers or legislators willing
to trade votes on the budget for some pork, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only criteria is how much influence you have,'' said
Williams, a former House Appropriations Committee member. ``Urban
school districts tend to be left out, either because their
representatives are not positioned to deal or they're focused on
other community needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Former state School Superintendent Werner Rogers distanced
himself from the process when his department was being used,
contrary to state law, to dispense funds for athletics. Rogers
asked that the governor find another department to dole them out.
Community Affairs was assigned the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were being put in the education budget that we were
just passing through to local school systems that we had not
requested,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Hooks defended the practice of selectively sharing the wealth
with athletics programs even though his rural district, which spans
from Albany to the Alabama line, seemingly has more immediate
needs. The district contains almost 400 miles of dirt roads and
lacks the tax base of metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Educators lobbied him after Douglas High consolidated with Macon
County, increasing the school's enrollment to Class AA size. They
sought money to expand the football stadium. In Montezuma and many
other small towns, it is considered a pressing need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football serves as a sense of community pride, bringing people
together,'' said Tommy Moore, the school's athletics director and
assistant principal. ``Macon County football has been
ultra-successful in the '90s, the most successful in the state. We
wouldn't appeal to these gentlemen (in the Legislature) if we
didn't have a need. Understand, there'd be no playoff games at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
