<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7389 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEW-FAITH14-COX     12-13 2122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-FAITH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More Christians seeing religion in a different light
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Cheryl Wahlgren rises early and by 5 a.m. is
quietly settled in front of a windowsill adorned with stones,
crystals, flowers, plants, oils and feathers _ a personal altar
she's created in her Sunset Valley home.
</P>
<P>
   While her husband and children sleep, she balances her female
and male sides through the Chinese meditation practice Qui Gong.
She honors God by turning to the four directions of the Earth, and
she burns sage, a Native American cleansing practice. The pieces on
her altar are reminders of the natural bounty given by God.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of gets you ready for the day,'' said Wahlgren, 48, a
cardiac nurse at Seton Medical Center. ``The other thing I do is
ask God to show me how to make his presence known in everything I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Raised as a Lutheran and Catholic, Wahlgren also prays the
rosary each evening.
</P>
<P>
   David George, 48, was brought up in the Church of Christ and
goes to services whenever he visits his parents near Marble Falls.
On Wednesday nights, he studies with a yoga master.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty eclectic in my belief system,'' he said. ``I take
the gold wherever I find it.''
</P>
<P>
   From fundamentalist to mainline Christians, the words
``religion'' and ``religious,'' which many believe synonymous with
a church institution, are being cast aside in favor of personalized
spirituality. It's a dramatic shift, one of the biggest of the
millennium, according to some theologians and scholars.
</P>
<P>
   What has evolved, mostly in recent decades, is a new perspective
on how faith can be practiced, leading to declining membership in
mainline denominations, religion hopping and a freestyle approach
to faith that shows no signs of letting up.
</P>
<P>
   The search for spiritual growth has reached an all-time high in
the United States. A recent Gallup Poll reports that 82 percent of
the people in the United States (88 percent in the South, which
includes Texas) feel the need to experience spiritual growth. In a
1994 survey, Newsweek reported that 58 percent of the population
wanted to grow spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   The Gallup Organization, a leading source for statistical
information on America's religious beliefs, will release a book
today that chronicles how the practice of faith has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spiritual frontier for this country has expanded and
incorporated diverse foreign ideologies and philosophies throughout
the 20th century,'' according to the book, ``Surveying the
Religious Landscape: Trends in U.S. Beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   ''People in the U.S. favor a faith that meets numerous spiritual
beliefs and tenets.''
</P>
<P>
   In their search for a customized faith, it is not unusual to
hear people describe themselves as being on a ``faith journey'' or
``spiritual path'' or seeking a ``personal relationship with Jesus
Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Their thirst to understand and relate to the personal spiritual
journeys of others has books by both the Dalai Llama and the Rev.
Billy Graham flying off bookstore shelves and onto The New York
Times' best-sellers list.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of studies that show in the past decade
some 30 to 40 percent of Americans are switching their faith,''
said the Rev. Scotty McClennan, chaplain at Tufts University and
author of the new book ``Finding Your Religion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I find many students say: `I'm spiritual but not religious,'
meaning they are not looking for a religious home but mixing and
matching different religions.''
</P>
<P>
   INTERFAITH MARRIAGES
</P>
<P>
   A millennium ago, there was one dominant Christian faith: Roman
Catholicism. An Orthodox schism in 1054 and the Protestant
Reformation in 1517 splintered Christianity into numerous sects.
People were born, raised and expected to marry in the same
religion.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually, some people from different Protestant faiths
began marrying. Then Protestants began marrying Catholics. Later,
it became common for Jews and Christians to marry, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of fragmentation and a lot of new
development of individual consciousness rather than collective
consciousness,'' notes A.J. ``Chip'' Conyers, a theology professor
at Baylor University's Truett Seminary. ``The philosophical grounds
for religion being a private individual matter were laid in the
17th century, but there has been a great leap in modern times.''
</P>
<P>
   Conyers credits philosophers John Locke, an Anglican from
England, and Pierre Bayle, a Huguenot _ a French Calvinist _ with
introducing the concepts of religious tolerance and private
theology.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, those ideas were manifested in the
constitutional separation of church and state. Yet America remained
almost exclusively a Christian nation. The Christian faith
permeated the public domain _ requiring Christian prayers in many
public schools, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   America's changing religious landscape has led to an increase in
legal changes, said Terry Muck, a professor of comparative religion
at Austin Presbyterian Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1940, only six cases dealing with religious liberty went
before the Supreme Court, which at the time was the only court that
could hear such cases, according to the First Liberty Institute.
Since then, hundreds of cases have popped up in state and federal
courts, and more than 90 opinions have come down.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars agree the man most responsible for the surge in the
country's religious diversity was President Lyndon B. Johnson, who
signed the Immigration Act of 1965 that led to a wave of
non-Christian immigrants, including Buddhists, Hindus and Muslims.
The Vietnam War and baby boomers' rejection of ``the
establishment'' or anything connected with institutionalism _
including religious denominations _ along with the sexual
revolution sparked many Americans to re-examine their religious
beliefs and drop out of congregational life.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, ``the age of Aquarius dawned on us,'' Conyers
said. ``Religion becomes ... privately chosen and no longer the
realm of the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Membership in mainline denominations also began to dive during
the 1970s feminist movement, as some women began to reject what
they perceived as patriarchal religious institutions. They also
entered the work force in droves _ out of financial necessity or to
pursue careers.
</P>
<P>
   Long work hours, hectic schedules and competing interests _
sports, entertainment, leisure activities _ meant that churchmoved
down on some people's list of priorities.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Gallup pollsters, 14 percent of Americans
identified themselves as Methodist in 1967. Three decades later,
that number slipped to 9 percent. The number of people who claimed
their denomination as Presbyterian fell by half from 1967 to 1998,
from 6 percent to 3 percent, while Lutherans dropped from 7 percent
to 5 percent and Episcopalians from 3 percent to 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many Americans, church moved from the mainline to the
sideline,'' said D. Michael Lindsay, Gallup's consultant for
theology, religion and culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several decades ago, the majority of church affiliation in the
United States involved mainline Protestant denominations. Today,
the religious landscape is much more diverse.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one in four American adults have switched denominations
since their childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who used to affiliate with mainline denominations
have moved toward evangelical or nondenominational churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are also seeing an emergence of nontraditional churches
that have dual-alignment or are aligned with more than one
denomination, as well as you have the emergence of churches that
have loosened their denominational allegiances,'' Lindsay said.
</P>
<P>
   ON THEIR OWN TERMS
</P>
<P>
   Religion is far from out of the American psyche; 95 percent
reported to Gallup that they believe in God or a universal spirit,
a number that has remained relatively unchanged in 50 years. Today,
many just want to practice their beliefs a new way.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay, who co-authored the book with George Gallup Jr., said
it shows how people also are seeking out small groups as spiritual
support systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 100 million Americans involved in small groups, and
over half are spiritual small groups that range from prayer groups
to support groups for single parents to Alcoholics Anonymous, and
they are all meeting in church,'' Lindsay said.
</P>
<P>
   But, as one scholar noted, some Christians also are busily
mixing religious ideologies. ``Even if you are raised in those
(mainstream) faiths, that is not an encompassing reality anymore.
It's just one part of your life,'' said Ray Pickett, a New
Testament professor at the Lutheran Seminary in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is eclectically creating their own faith or
theology,'' he added. ``It's almost comical.''
</P>
<P>
   The rise in spirituality comes from the baby boomers who earlier
stopped practicing their faith. As they grow older, they begin
searching for life's meaning beyond their careers, triggering a
spiritual awakening that brings them back to family and religion.
They adopt a more holistic approach, including trying relaxation
techniques, such as yoga, that are rooted in Eastern religious
philosophies. They also parlay environmental concerns into a
spiritual tenet, borrowed from Native American and pagan faiths,
that the Earth is sacred.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't put this together theologically,'' Muck said. But
the average person doesn't see it that way, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``People measure religion and religious truth differently these
days,'' he said. ``They measure it by pragmatism.'' In other words,
they simply ask: ``Does this work for me?''
</P>
<P>
   Even among Roman Catholics, whose numbers have held steady as a
quarter of the nation's population for more than 30 years, there is
room for other religious traditions to feed the spirit. Buddhist
practices have taken off in Roman Catholicism. Two nuns run a Zen
meditation center near Baltimore, Md., and the popularity of
Buddhist traditions among Catholics was a cover story this month in
the National Catholic Reporter newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Mary Rose McPhee, executive director of Seton Cove in
Austin, offers yoga as part of the Catholic spirituality center's
stress reduction classes. The center, which attracts people of all
faiths, teaches a holistic approach that incorporates the human
experience and personal spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is beautiful about it being integrated in a program with
a spiritual focus is they can appreciate the whole connection of
mind, body and spirit in this era of high-tech,'' she said. ``Our
interest is really trying to make a difference in people's whole
perspective of themselves. ... They have to have that connection of
that inner spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   BECOMING BORN-AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   The holistic approach has not been lost on fundamentalist and
conservative Christians, who are buying books on how to incorporate
Scripture into everything, including weight loss, personal
finances, healing, parenting and education. The CBA, formerly known
as the Christian Booksellers Association, reported this year that
Christian retailers are doing more than $3 billion in sales, three
times what they were in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentalism is a strange mixture of individualism and
retrenchment,'' Pickett said.
</P>
<P>
   It is completely Bible-based, but it's a religious experience
people seek for themselves. Fundamentalism and Pentecostalism are
anchored in a personal relationship with Jesus Christ, giving
higher priority to that relationship than a particular dogma or
doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelical leaders such as Graham, who emphasize Christian
conversion as the pivotal faith experience, have drawn followers
from traditional faiths that stress doctrine and dogma as central
to religious practice.
</P>
<P>
   Today, two of five Americans claim they are born-again
Christians, Lindsay said. ``You see Methodists, Baptists ...
Catholics who say they are born-again,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   People who are born again believe they are transformed by
knowing Jesus Christ as their personal savior.
</P>
<P>
   While people are choosing a litany of different ways to practice
their faith today, Lindsay, the Gallup consultant, said the
majority are committed to organized religion, even though they
might not be a member of the church they claim as their religious
preference.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we approach the millennium event, people have a new
commitment to exploring their faith,'' he said. ``The entire 20th
century has been spent exploring the extent of human progress. We
have been pushing ourselves to outer space, and the data seems to
suggest people are now turned to exploring inner space.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
