<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Dec. 13, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6320.
    (All sluglines end with ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NEW-BREASTS (Houston) _ More and more women go into the
operating room for a mastectomy and wake up with the beginnings of
a new breast fashioned entirely from their own tissue or with
implants. An increasing number of surgeons are becoming comfortable
with immediate reconstruction, and breast cancer survivors say
reconstructive surgery is a major step forward in the healing
process. By LEIGH HOPPER.(Photo and graphic available on NYT
database.)
</P>
<P>
   S.F.-MAYORAL (San Francisco) _ If Mayor Willie Brown wins
reelection in Tuesday's runoff here, it will end a long spell of
one-term mayors in San Francisco and signal a major change. Brown,
who couldn't run again because of voter-approved term limits, could
take a damn-the-people attitude in a second term. Or, he could
concentrate on his legacy without worrying about going back before
the voters. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   MARS-MAN (Hemphill, Texas) _ Besides NASA's disappointing
failure in getting its Mars Polar Lander to phone home last week,
the space agency also could be trespassing. At least that's how
Thomas Budnick sees things. The 52-year-old former social worker
from Ludlow, Mass., has spent the past two decades in relative
obscurity, mailing his official claims to land and mineral rights
on Mars and elsewhere in outer space to the Sabine County Clerk's
Office in this quiet East Texas town. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-FARMERS (Belzoni, Miss.) _ When the federal government
caved in the face of a class-action lawsuit and agreed to pay cash
to amend decades of discrimination in the farm lending program,
black farmers envisioned salvation. But many are finding that the
settlement provides little to ensure their survival, has failed to
compensate for their feelings of bitterness and comes at a time
when the Agriculture Department may soon phase out its farm lending
programs. By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA. (Photo available on NYT
database.)
</P>
<P>
   NICARAGUANS-RESIDENCY (San Francisco) _ Like a salesman,
Nicaraguan Ambassador Francisco X. Aguiree Sacasa is trying to sway
those from his homeland not to miss an opportunity of a lifetime.
With phrases like ``time is running out,'' he is preaching to
natives from his country about a law that allows Nicaraguan
nationals to apply for permanent residency in the United States. By
JUSTINO AGUILA.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL (Panama City) _ Because of Y2K computer concerns, a
symbolic handover of the Panama Canal will occur Tuesday between
the United States and Panama. At noon Dec. 31, the United States
will actually will surrender control of the 85-year-old Panama
Canal. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-PROFILE (Sunapee, N.H.) _ Steve Forbes, heir to a
multimillion-dollar family fortune, is running for the Republican
presidential nomination as a Washington outsider, someone who
repeatedly decries the ``disconnect'' that he sees between the
political culture of the nation's capital and the ``potential
greatness'' of the American people. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ Even as it operated what many consider
the
</P>
<P>
   best system of state parks in the nation, Texas Parks &AMP; Wildlife
was so strapped for cash during the `90s that the main priority was
keeping bathrooms clean. Now, a major step forward: Through Lone
Star Legacy, a multimillion public-private funding program, a new
World Birding Center and several other huge projects are in the
works. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader asks, ``Is the poinsettia
poisonous? Can I cut the flowers and use in a vase? How do I stop
the stem from bleeding?'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-CHILDREN (Undated) _ Books that would make good holiday
gifts for children. By JANE P. MARSHALL.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-BOOKS (Undated) _ Books always make great gifts. Here's
a laundry list of suggestions on subjects ranging from photography
to fashion, art to science. By FRITZ LANHAM and LINDA GILLAN
GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-GARDEN (Houston) _ A look at books by Texans and for
Texans that hold something to please the gardener on your holiday
list. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MAQUIRE-PROFILE (Toronto) _ Toby Maguire talks about the
two films he has opening Friday: the adaptation of John Irving's
``Cider House Rules'' and ``Ride With the Devil,'' a Civil War
flick co-starring Jewel. By the Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RAIDERS (San Francisco) _ And now, for their next act, the
Raiders pray for losses. All kinds of losses. Buffalo losses.
Seattle losses. New England losses. Kansas City losses. The Raiders
pray for losses all around. Which tells you something about the
Raiders' current predicament. By BRIAN MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   SOCCER-WOMEN (San Jose, Calif.) _ The U.S. Women's World Cup
team made a Victory Tour stop here last weekend, but much of the
talk after the match against a World Stars team was about a loss
that is now looming out there in the land of the international
soccer hierarchy. The sport's governing body announced a few days
ago that it planned to move the next Women's World Cup from 2003 to
2002, the same year that the men's World Cup will be contested. To
a woman, the members of the U.S. team think that's a bad idea. By
DWIGHT CHAPIN.
</P>
