<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAMELA-ANDERSON-LEE-IN-VIP-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `V.I.P.' TREATMENT: PAMELA ANDERSON LEE BOUNCES BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Pamela Anderson Lee with Leah Lail,
Molly Culver, Natalie Raitano and Shaun Baker in a scene from
``V.I.P.'') 
 By BRIAN HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 Not for release in Canada until Dec. 19. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chatting with Pamela Anderson Lee during a break from filming
her hit action series ``V.I.P.,'' one thing is clear: She doesn't
mind being candid, even outspoken on the record.
</P>
<P>
   It's surprising, given the reams of bad press she's received
about her life, her, ahem, physical attributes, that infamous home
video and her on-again-off-again relationship, now on again, with
her ex-husband and current fiance, rocker Tommy Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, many people would shy away from anyone
with a camera or a notebook, but Anderson Lee never has.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a sense of humor about yourself,'' she says,
``and also you have to realize that you're not really in control of
what the press writes about you. You can only live your life in a
positive way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to build you up and tear you down,'' she adds.
``You get a People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals award, and
then someone writes that they saw you eating chicken fingers in the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually very funny, very amusing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's good that she thinks so, because everything the 33-year-old
native of Victoria, British Columbia, does _ whether in front of or
behind the camera _ seems fair game for the tabloids. But instead
of shunning the attention, Anderson Lee has capitalized on it _
most notably in the year-old syndicated series ``V.I.P.,'' which
parallels her own life in the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot episode opens with a dumb-luck incident in which her
character, Vallery Irons, accidentally saves an actor from an
attacker. Caught on camera, the bit of derring-do makes Vallery an
overnight sensation and leads a Los Angeles bodyguard agency to
sign her on as a figurehead.
</P>
<P>
   The real-life story of Pamela Denise Anderson Lee is almost as
whimsical. Her rise to fame started when she was captured on a
giant Jumbotron television screen at a 1989 Canadian Football,
cheering on her team and wearing not much more than a Labatt's
T-shirt and a smile.
</P>
<P>
   From that brief glimpse came a beer-commercial contract, a
Playboy spread and a regular role on Tim Allen's comedy series
``Home Improvement,'' where she spent four seasons as the comely
Tool Time Girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quite a bit of myself and my experience on this
show,'' says Anderson Lee, who also executive-produces ``V.I.P.''
``The whole concept came from what I've gone through in my life to
get here _ a girl comes from a small town and is thrown into this
Hollywood life and goes through things a little naively, but she
finds her way through and things come out good in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Her life contains enough material for two or three series, at
most. There's her 1995 marriage to heavy-metal drummer Lee, their
sordid _ and stolen _ sex video and the births of their children,
Dillon and Brandon. There was the violent incident with Lee which
led to their divorce, the much-publicized removal of her breast
implants and, recently, a reconciliation with her ex-husband and
plans for a second wedding.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy being an actress, producer, celebrity, wife and
mother, Anderson Lee says, but as she goes along it gets easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult,'' she says, ``but I've really learned how to
structure my life for my family, which is my priority, and my
extended family, and it seems to be running pretty smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I wish there were 10 of me, but I'm figuring it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, one or both of her boys can be found on the
set. But don't expect her to push them in front of a camera:
Anderson Lee disapproves of children _ hers or anyone else's _
getting involved in acting until they're old enough to make their
own decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even say that about children working on the set,'' she says.
``If you can't choose to be in the business, then I don't think
it's right. So I don't allow children to work on the show. I don't
believe in parents making that decision for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping keep the family together, Anderson Lee has arranged for
two recent guest shots by Tommy Lee. The actress/producer says she
looked forward to his days on the set, because of the chance it
offered for him to understand her work better.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she admits, she enjoyed watching the usually
ultraconfident musician flounder around, out of his element.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really funny,'' she recalls, ``because he's never done
anything like that. He was saying `Where do I pick up the gun?
Where do I put down my cigarette? When do I say the line?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally he said, `This is way too difficult, somebody give me
a drum!'''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, in her husband's defense, Anderson Lee admits that
he had it particularly difficult, because his wife was serving not
only as producer and star but also, on these episodes, as director
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cool,'' she says, ``but it was horrible because I was
being the total director ... I was way too controlling.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson Lee takes her role as executive producer seriously. She
insisted on it before agreeing to sign on for ``V.I.P.,'' and has a
hand in everything from casting to performing regular production
duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't do it any other way now,'' she says. ``I don't
think I would do another project if I couldn't be a producer. I
have a lot of input in everything I do.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress has no illusions that she's doing Shakespeare here,
but as a producer she takes pride in the fact that the audience is
not, as most observers had predicted, made up entirely of teen-age
boys and football-loving men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studio really thought `V.I.P.' would appeal to a huge male
demographic,'' Anderson Lee says. ``But when the numbers came in,
they discovered that the audience was 40 percent women. So ... girl
power! But I've always known that a lot of my fans were women and
young girls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``V.I.P.'' is an unquestioned hit _ it's the No. 1 weekly
syndicated, hour-long show in the world, and has already been
renewed through 2002 _ and Anderson Lee realizes that she's
something as a role model to young women around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Which is fine with her, actually, but only up to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that every actor, everyone in the public eye should be
a role model of some kind,'' she says. ``But, you know, people
shouldn't really base their positions in life on what people do in
the public eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Good advice, coming from someone who's been there.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Brian Hartigan is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ont.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``V.I.P.,'' consult the official
Website at www.spe.sony.com/tv/shows/vip. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
