<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7416 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-JIM-CARREY-IN-MAN-ON-     12-13 1473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JIM-CARREY-IN-MAN-ON-THE-MOON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING IT SURREAL: JIM CARREY VISITS ANDY KAUFMAN'S WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jim Carrey with Danny DeVito in a scene
from ``Man on the Moon.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    His name is Jim Carrey, and this is his press conference.
 &HT;    Or is it?
 &HT;    Time: Dec. 4, 1999 _ afternoon.
 &HT;    Place: The ballroom of Los Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel.
 &HT;    Cast of characters: Jim Carrey, star of Milos Forman's ``Man on
the Moon'' _ an Andy Kaufman biopic opening Dec. 22 _ and more than
75 journalists.
 &HT;    Theme: You don't have to know Andy Kaufman to like ``Man on the
Moon.''
 &HT;    ``The reaction has been kind of cool,'' Carrey says. ``A lot of
people, especially the European press _ who have no idea who
Kaufman is _ screened the film and seem wild about it. Maybe you're
better off.
 &HT;    ``It's (appealing) just on the basis of a very interesting
artist, a person who challenges people's beliefs,'' the comedian
says. ``I think there's enough of that to make it a good movie and
a good story.''
 &HT;    Kaufman, if you've forgotten _ or never knew _ was a stand-up
comic who dared to not tell jokes and deliberately antagonize
audiences. The sitcom ``Taxi'' made Kaufman a star, and he played
it to the hilt, wrestling women, clashing with a male wrestler on
``Letterman'' and unleashing Tony Clifton, an arrogant, talentless
lounge singer _ played by his friend and writing partner, Bob Zmuda
_ who would heckle Kaufman at live appearances.
 &HT;    By the time Kaufman died of cancer in 1984, the public was so
used to his stunts that some people didn't buy it. In fact,
Kaufmaniacs think he's alive and planning a comeback in the wake of
``Man in the Moon.''
 &HT;    Bad news: He's really dead.
 &HT;    On the other hand, Carrey _ once best known for talking through
his butt cheeks _ provides so uncanny an impersonation that pundits
are predicting an Oscar nomination.
 &HT;    ``The experience itself was so incredible,'' Carrey says softly.
``To this day I sit up and go, `This is never going to happen again
in that way.'
 &HT;    ``It was an odyssey for everybody,'' he says. ``It was like Andy
was around and Andy was directing. Every decision was made on that
basis.''
 &HT;    As for his Oscar chances, he claims to be indifferent.
 &HT;    ``The whole project was such a thrill that, if something like
that happened on top of it, I'd have a heart attack,'' he says.
``It would be ungrateful to sit here and expect something else to
come my way from this.''
 &HT;    Carrey pauses.
 &HT;    ``It would be a wonderful thing,'' he adds, smiling. ``No
question about it.''
 &HT;    Playing Kaufman consumed him, says Carrey _ who, like Kaufman,
was born on Jan. 17 _ to the extent that he lived in character on
and off camera, only twice showing up on the set as Jim Carrey.
 &HT;    ``I really didn't exist,'' he says. ``I went to bed as Andy, and
it was strange and wonderful. I'd wake up in the morning and jump
into his shoes.''
 &HT;    Further obscuring the line between fact and fiction, several
figures from Kaufman's life appear in the film. The ``Taxi'' cast
pretty much play themselves, for example, while ``Taxi'' co-star
Danny DeVito portrays Kaufman's manager, George Shapiro. And the
real Shapiro cameos as the first club owner to fire Kaufman.
 &HT;    A typical press-conference question follows: Would today's
audiences better appreciate Kaufman than people did back then?
 &HT;    ``That's interesting,'' Carrey says. ``I think he'd probably ...
Oh, God. Oh, my God.''
 &HT;    Carrey's eyes open wide as he looks to the back of the ballroom.
There stands Bob Zmuda _ or, rather, Tony Clifton, a homely man in
a devastatingly ugly tuxedo, with a bimbo on each arm and puffing
on a cigarette.
 &HT;    ``I'll tell you, ladies and gentleman, I am Tony Clifton, the
star of this motion picture,'' he rants. ``These people from
Universal tried to keep me out of here, and I know why. Because the
gentleman sitting up here, who has a lot of power, doesn't want me
here. His name _ and I'm going to point him out _ is Drew Carey.''
 &HT;    Apparently thrown off-balance, Carrey interrupts.
 &HT;    ``Let me just say I worked very hard on this character, OK,'' he
says. ``This is a guy who was very jealous, very envious of Andy.
Andy tried to help him.''
 &HT;    Clifton doesn't seem to like that idea.
 &HT;    ``I'll tell you what,'' he shouts. ``He's in shock! He didn't
know this was going to happen. He's trying to figure this out right
now, and he's not doing a very good job at it.
 &HT;    ``He does not want me here for one reason and one reason
alone,'' he adds. ``It's called the Oscar. It is so obvious I blow
his a-- off that screen.''
 &HT;    ``The Oscar is not everything,'' Carrey shoots back.
 &HT;    ``Don't make it sound like you don't want that Oscar,'' Clifton
yells. ``You've got Oscar-wannabe all over your face.''
 &HT;    ``Oh, come on,'' Carrey says. ``You're desperate, you're
desperate.''
 &HT;    ``Don't get me started, man,'' Clifton warns.
 &HT;    ``And you're a drunk,'' Carrey adds.
 &HT;    Clifton pulls out a can of spray paint and proceeds to write the
words ``Man on the Moon'' on the ballroom door, as the assembled
journalists laugh and try to figure out what's going on. Carrey
feigns an inability to make out Clifton's handwriting.
 &HT;    ``Mandingo?'' he hazards, drawing another chuckle from the
reporters.
 &HT;    Clifton seems to snap, lunging at Carrey and hollering ``I'll
spray you!'' The two men grapple. Carrey dumps a pitcher of water
on Clifton and then storms out, but not before swiping his arm
across the table that holds the journalists' tape recorders.
 &HT;    The recorders crash to the ground, as the paint drips down the
door and Clifton's cigarette burns a hole in the carpeting.
 &HT;    ``OK, I did my dirt,'' Clifton says smugly. ``I just want to
say, folks, it's been a pleasure talking to you. Vote for me. If I
made one person happy, it's all been worth it.
 &HT;    ``Thank you. Good night.''
 &HT;    And out the door he goes.
 &HT;    It's half an hour before Universal publicists, scrambling for
damage control, can get Carrey back. In the meantime, the
journalists retrieve their recorders, some broken beyond repair,
and hotel employees do their best to clean up the mess.
 &HT;    ``You kind of get sucked into this thing,'' Carrey says, ``and
it's hard to know what's real and what isn't anymore. Bob Zmuda,
who was playing Tony, has been writing books and doing the
character everywhere.
 &HT;    ``I was not approving,'' he says, seeming a bit disoriented. ``I
think the press should be handled within the confines of the movie.
He seems to want to step out and ... be Andy, I don't know. This
whole thing is so blurred.''
 &HT;    Carrey, who insists the episode wasn't a put-up job, offers to
pay for the broken recorders.
 &HT;    ``We're all working toward the same end here, and Zmuda ... ''
he pauses. ``I just think it's time for him to move on.''
 &HT;    Carrey himself is moving on, to new films that include the
Farrelly brothers' ``Me, Myself and Irene'' and Ron Howard's
live-action version of ``How the Grinch Stole Christmas.''
 &HT;    As for Andy Kaufman, Carrey thinks that ``Man in the Moon''
sheds light on the talented, troubled comic, but it's not the final
word.
 &HT;    ``I don't think he needs an explanation,'' Carrey says. ``If you
explain Andy, you've killed him.
 &HT;    ``That's the triumph of his life _ he beat death, because he
can't be explained,'' he concludes. ``Nobody knows if it's for real
or not, and in that way he's immortal.
 &HT;    ``If I ever did win an Oscar, I wish he'd come up and grab it
out of my hands.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Man in the Moon,'' consult the
official Website at www.man-on-the-moon.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
