<HEADER>
A7417 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-JODIE-FOSTER-IN-ANNA-     12-13 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JODIE-FOSTER-IN-ANNA-AND-THE-KING-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANNA'-LYTIC: WELCOME TO THE WELL-THOUGHT-OUT WORLD OF JODIE
FOSTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jodie Foster in a scene from ``Anna and
the King.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``Getting to Know You'' has never been her theme song.
 &HT;    But Jodie Foster, one of Hollywood's most notoriously private
actresses, is finally talking about what goes on behind the palace
doors _ at least as far as it relates to her pride and joy,
16-month-old Charles Foster.
 &HT;    Foster makes her postpregnancy return to the screen in the
holiday film ``Anna and the King,'' but everything else about her
life has changed.
 &HT;    ``I'm not a big fan of TV, but I love the Teletubbies now,''
confesses the Yale grad and two-time Oscar winner who, despite her
rep as the smartest woman in Hollywood, now spends her afternoons
with Tinky Winky and Po.
 &HT;    ``Teletubbies are very serene, not too overstimulating and
almost hypnotic,'' she says thoughtfully _ and then giggles like
any new mother. ``OK, so they're also adorable.''
 &HT;    If that doesn't sound like the sharp-as-a-tack Foster Hollywood
knows and loves, it's no wonder.
 &HT;    ``Motherhood has really affected my ambition _ I have none of my
ambition left,'' the 37-year-old actress says over breakfast at
Beverly Hills' chic L'Ermitage hotel. ``I already didn't have a
competitive streak in me in the few years before my son was born.
With the baby, I have absolutely no competitive streak left in me
at all.''
 &HT;    Dressed down in black jeans, a T-shirt and a worn leather
jacket, Foster still has the porcelain skin and shiny blonde hair _
currently in a pageboy _ that made her the luminous star of 33
films in 34 years, but she doesn't feel like that woman these days.
 &HT;    ``My identity is not wrapped up in the movie business anymore,''
she says matter-of-factly. ``Let's face it, I've already
accomplished so many of the abstract goals in my career. So it's
not, `Will I make money anymore? Will people like me?'
 &HT;    ``I have only one pure question left when it comes to work,
which is `Do I feel passionate enough to tell this story?'''
 &HT;    Andy Tennant, who directed ``Anna and the King'' _ a nonmusical
version of the book that inspired ``The King and I'' _ has
predicted that Foster may retire from the screen in not too long.
The actress begs to differ.
 &HT;    ``I can't imagine giving up acting,'' she says. ``I love making
movies.''
 &HT;    Those expecting to see Foster sing or dance in her latest movie
will be disappointed. ``Anna and the King,'' which will open Dec.
17 nationwide, may tell the story first recounted by real-life
royal governess Anna Leonowens in ``Anna and the King of Siam,''
but it tells it much differently than Rodgers &AMP; Hammerstein did.
 &HT;    ``First of all, I've loved the musical my entire life,'' she
says. ``But I wanted to say something completely different. I
wanted to talk about Asia from the Asian perspective.''
 &HT;    Making the film involved spending weeks on a set in Malaysia
with temperatures lingering around 120 degrees, only six months
after she'd given birth _ but Foster says it wasn't really that
bad.
 &HT;    ``I never sweat,'' she says, ``which is one reason the makeup
people loved me. I mean, I'm standing there in a hoop skirt, a
bonnet, crinolines, leather boots and gloves, looking pretty
cool.''
 &HT;    Better yet, little Charlie also kept his cool.
 &HT;    ``He was only 6 months, and I had him on a flight that lasted 23
1/2 hours,'' the proud mother marvels. ``He was really a trouper.
He talked to the other passengers. He crawled up and down the
aisles. He smiled at people. He took food off their plates.''
 &HT;    She pauses.
 &HT;    ``What I couldn't believe,'' she adds, ``is that, after the
movie wrapped, I took him on a two-hour flight and I was like, `Oh
my God!' He was a different child. Everything was, `No, no, no!'
People were staring at me like, `Get this kid away from me!'''
 &HT;    So, will little Charlie be getting any brothers or sisters
anytime soon?
 &HT;    ``Suuurre,'' Foster says slowly, smiling wearily. ``Just not
right this week.''
 &HT;    Just don't ask her why she decided on single motherhood in the
first place.
 &HT;    ``You know,'' she says warmly but firmly, ``I try not to comment
on that stuff. Everybody's decision to have a child is personal.''
 &HT;    Besides, she says, it's not so hard if you're banking some of
the biggest paychecks of any Hollywood actress.
 &HT;    ``I mean, my mom had four kids,'' she says. ``With no money. I
don't know how she did it.''
 &HT;    Well, Foster herself helped a little. At age 3 she was a
Coppertone tot in a print ad. She went on to become one of the most
successful child stars ever, supporting her mother, sisters and
brother by the time she was 10. And then, to almost everyone's
surprise, she did the near-impossible by reinventing herself as a
top adult star, beginning with her Oscar-winning turn as a rape
victim in ``The Accused'' (1988).
 &HT;    And, yes, it's true that only moments before winning the award,
Foster called it ``one of the worst performances of my life.''
 &HT;    ``Yes, I said at the time I thought it was absolutely one of the
worst performances I had ever given,'' she admits. ``Basically, I
was so uncomfortable because this performance came completely from
instinct. And when I saw it, I thought, `Wow, she's brash. She's
tough. Uneducated. And she's not nice at all.'
 &HT;    ``Now I think she's a hero.''
 &HT;    Actually, Foster says, she never enjoys seeing her own movies.
 &HT;    ``This is my moviegoing experience,'' she says: ```We could have
had a sunset shot, but it clouded over at the last minute.' `Oh,
that's where one of the actors couldn't remember his lines.'
 &HT;    ``Even years later,'' she admits with a laugh, ``I'm looking at
a movie and screaming, `We shouldn't have cut from here to there.'
I see the mistakes.
 &HT;    ``By the way,'' she adds, ``it's not a negative thing. It's just
the perfectionist in me.''
 &HT;    Foster pulled out of ``Double Jeopardy'' when she found out she
was pregnant. The movie went on to make Ashley Judd into a
bona-fide movie star, but Foster says she has no regrets.
 &HT;    ``Obviously, I don't regret that it was a huge hit,'' she says.
``I'm happy for them.''
 &HT;    Foster has had some huge hits of her own, of course, most
notably the multiple-Oscar-winning ``The Silence of the Lambs''
(1991).
 &HT;    Rumor has it that she's been offered $20 million to reprise her
role as Clarice Starling in a movie version of ``Hannibal,'' Thomas
Harris' best-selling sequel to ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' and
though she won't confirm the rumors, Foster won't deny them either.
 &HT;    ``I would love to do it,'' she says, ``but first I have to see a
script.''
 &HT;    If she were to nix the sequel script, though, she admits that it
would bother her to see someone else play Agent Starling of the
FBI.
 &HT;    ``I don't feel like I own her, but I do feel possessive of
her,'' Foster says. ``I feel like I know what Clarice would do and
not do. I know everything about her _ she is the most specific
character I've ever played.''
 &HT;    But that's one character little Charlie won't meet for some
time. He hasn't seen any of his mother's movies, and won't for a
while yet.
 &HT;    ``Maybe I'll show him `Bugsy Malone' (1976),'' she says after a
moment's thought. ``It's one big fantasy, which I think is an
important part of childhood.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Anna and the King,'' consult
the official Website at www.annaandtheking.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
