<SLUG> BC-PAMELA-ANDERSON-LEE-IN-VIP-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `V.I.P.' TREATMENT: PAMELA ANDERSON LEE BOUNCES BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Pamela Anderson Lee with Leah Lail,
Molly Culver, Natalie Raitano and Shaun Baker in a scene from
``V.I.P.'') 
 By BRIAN HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 Not for release in Canada until Dec. 19. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chatting with Pamela Anderson Lee during a break from filming
her hit action series ``V.I.P.,'' one thing is clear: She doesn't
mind being candid, even outspoken on the record.
</P>
<P>
   It's surprising, given the reams of bad press she's received
about her life, her, ahem, physical attributes, that infamous home
video and her on-again-off-again relationship, now on again, with
her ex-husband and current fiance, rocker Tommy Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, many people would shy away from anyone
with a camera or a notebook, but Anderson Lee never has.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a sense of humor about yourself,'' she says,
``and also you have to realize that you're not really in control of
what the press writes about you. You can only live your life in a
positive way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to build you up and tear you down,'' she adds.
``You get a People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals award, and
then someone writes that they saw you eating chicken fingers in the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually very funny, very amusing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's good that she thinks so, because everything the 33-year-old
native of Victoria, British Columbia, does _ whether in front of or
behind the camera _ seems fair game for the tabloids. But instead
of shunning the attention, Anderson Lee has capitalized on it _
most notably in the year-old syndicated series ``V.I.P.,'' which
parallels her own life in the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot episode opens with a dumb-luck incident in which her
character, Vallery Irons, accidentally saves an actor from an
attacker. Caught on camera, the bit of derring-do makes Vallery an
overnight sensation and leads a Los Angeles bodyguard agency to
sign her on as a figurehead.
</P>
<P>
   The real-life story of Pamela Denise Anderson Lee is almost as
whimsical. Her rise to fame started when she was captured on a
giant Jumbotron television screen at a 1989 Canadian Football,
cheering on her team and wearing not much more than a Labatt's
T-shirt and a smile.
</P>
<P>
   From that brief glimpse came a beer-commercial contract, a
Playboy spread and a regular role on Tim Allen's comedy series
``Home Improvement,'' where she spent four seasons as the comely
Tool Time Girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quite a bit of myself and my experience on this
show,'' says Anderson Lee, who also executive-produces ``V.I.P.''
``The whole concept came from what I've gone through in my life to
get here _ a girl comes from a small town and is thrown into this
Hollywood life and goes through things a little naively, but she
finds her way through and things come out good in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Her life contains enough material for two or three series, at
most. There's her 1995 marriage to heavy-metal drummer Lee, their
sordid _ and stolen _ sex video and the births of their children,
Dillon and Brandon. There was the violent incident with Lee which
led to their divorce, the much-publicized removal of her breast
implants and, recently, a reconciliation with her ex-husband and
plans for a second wedding.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy being an actress, producer, celebrity, wife and
mother, Anderson Lee says, but as she goes along it gets easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult,'' she says, ``but I've really learned how to
structure my life for my family, which is my priority, and my
extended family, and it seems to be running pretty smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I wish there were 10 of me, but I'm figuring it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, one or both of her boys can be found on the
set. But don't expect her to push them in front of a camera:
Anderson Lee disapproves of children _ hers or anyone else's _
getting involved in acting until they're old enough to make their
own decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even say that about children working on the set,'' she says.
``If you can't choose to be in the business, then I don't think
it's right. So I don't allow children to work on the show. I don't
believe in parents making that decision for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping keep the family together, Anderson Lee has arranged for
two recent guest shots by Tommy Lee. The actress/producer says she
looked forward to his days on the set, because of the chance it
offered for him to understand her work better.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she admits, she enjoyed watching the usually
ultraconfident musician flounder around, out of his element.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really funny,'' she recalls, ``because he's never done
anything like that. He was saying `Where do I pick up the gun?
Where do I put down my cigarette? When do I say the line?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally he said, `This is way too difficult, somebody give me
a drum!'''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, in her husband's defense, Anderson Lee admits that
he had it particularly difficult, because his wife was serving not
only as producer and star but also, on these episodes, as director
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cool,'' she says, ``but it was horrible because I was
being the total director ... I was way too controlling.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson Lee takes her role as executive producer seriously. She
insisted on it before agreeing to sign on for ``V.I.P.,'' and has a
hand in everything from casting to performing regular production
duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't do it any other way now,'' she says. ``I don't
think I would do another project if I couldn't be a producer. I
have a lot of input in everything I do.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress has no illusions that she's doing Shakespeare here,
but as a producer she takes pride in the fact that the audience is
not, as most observers had predicted, made up entirely of teen-age
boys and football-loving men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studio really thought `V.I.P.' would appeal to a huge male
demographic,'' Anderson Lee says. ``But when the numbers came in,
they discovered that the audience was 40 percent women. So ... girl
power! But I've always known that a lot of my fans were women and
young girls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``V.I.P.'' is an unquestioned hit _ it's the No. 1 weekly
syndicated, hour-long show in the world, and has already been
renewed through 2002 _ and Anderson Lee realizes that she's
something as a role model to young women around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Which is fine with her, actually, but only up to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that every actor, everyone in the public eye should be
a role model of some kind,'' she says. ``But, you know, people
shouldn't really base their positions in life on what people do in
the public eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Good advice, coming from someone who's been there.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Brian Hartigan is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ont.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``V.I.P.,'' consult the official
Website at www.spe.sony.com/tv/shows/vip. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7419 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-CROSBY-STILLS-NASH-AN     12-13 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROSBY-STILLS-NASH-AND-YOUNG-RETURN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MUSIC IS BACK FOR CROSBY, STILLS, NASH &AMP; YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of David Crosby, Stephen Stills, Graham
Nash and Neal Young.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    During the opening moments of their new album, ``Looking
Forward,'' a harmonizing Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP; Young sing _
perhaps to each other as much as to the listener _ ``We do belong
together ... and it's going to last forever.''
 &HT;    Those are pretty optimistic words for four musicians who,
despite their 30-year association, have managed only three studio
albums and haven't toured together since 1974.
 &HT;    But, all four contend, these are better times. Past arguments
and ego battles have been set aside, replaced by warmer feelings
for each other and a greater appreciation for the music they make
together. The results: ``Looking Forward,'' their first album
together since 1988, and the ``CSNY2K'' tour, which will kick off
Jan. 24 in suburban Detroit.
 &HT;    ``There's a lot of unfinished business,'' Neil Young says. ``I
don't think we really reached our potential, and so we have a lot
of things to show and a lot of things to do. There are things that
we started doing on the record that show us the future.''
 &HT;    David Crosby agrees.
 &HT;    ``I think Neil's right,'' he says. ``There's almost no limit to
what this band can do when we get out there and start playing. All
of us are better at what we do than we ever have been _ I caught
glimpses of it when we were playing and singing in the studio. I'm
dying to explore the potential.''
 &HT;    The creative promise seemed enormous when CSN&AMP;Y first came
together in 1969. Each of the members had established himself in
highly regarded bands _ Crosby with the Byrds, Young and Stephen
Stills in Buffalo Springfield, Graham Nash with the Hollies.
Crosby, Stills &AMP; Nash had already come together and released
``Crosby, Stills and Nash,'' an album widely considered the
launching pad for the 1970s singer/songwriter movement, combining
pointed social and political commentary with a sound marked by rich
harmonies.
 &HT;    Young, who had begun a successful solo career, was recruited to
flesh out the live sound. The quartet's second performance was at
the original Woodstock festival, and by that time, Nash says, CSN&AMP;Y
had cheerfully embraced its supergroup billing.
 &HT;    ``We knew who we were,'' the 58-year-old Nash recalls. ``We knew
nobody in the world was doing what we were doing. No one had four
guys writing those kind of songs that were also that good as
musicians, all at the same time _ there was nobody like us.
 &HT;    ``So we were a little punkish about it,'' he says. ``We thought
we were kings of the world, so it was exciting to us.''
 &HT;    ``Deja Vu'' (1970), the quartet's first album, delivered on that
potential, yielding songs that became immediately popular and _ in
the case of ``Teach Your Children'' and ``Our House'' _ graduated
to musical immortality as campfire singalongs.
 &HT;    CSN&AMP;Y, it seemed, was a band for the ages.
 &HT;    But this was an admittedly volatile group of creative
personalities, stoked by ambition, arguments and drugs. The
58-year-old Crosby likens the partnership to ``juggling four
bottles of nitroglycerin,'' and they exploded more than a few times
in the intervening decades, during which CSN&AMP;Y performed in varying
incarnations but seldom as a single unit.
 &HT;    ``We're more than friends,'' says Nash, who spent nearly three
months in a wheelchair after breaking both legs in a Hawaii boating
accident shortly before the new album's release. ``We're brothers.
And, unfortunately, brothers fight occasionally. But it's been 30
years _ something's going on.''
 &HT;    The 55-year-old Stills credits the band with increased maturity.
 &HT;    ``Some of the ridiculous little kid games we used to play with
each other ... were really ridiculous and just beyond belief,'' he
says. ``This time there was a lot more listening going on than
ever, since the first record. No agendas, no tricks.''
 &HT;    It was Young, who has had the most high-profile and commercially
successful solo career of the four, who nonetheless brought the
group back together. He'd done so once before, in fact, spurring
``American Dream'' (1988) with a promise that he'd record with the
other three again if Crosby would kick the debilitating drug habit
that had landed him in a Texas prison during the mid-1980s.
 &HT;    Young had been working on a Buffalo Springfield box set, and
reached a point at which he needed Stills to come to his
northern-California ranch to hear what he'd compiled.
 &HT;    The two old friends ``laughed, cried and hugged each other,''
Young says, and their visits culminated with Stills playing a new
song that Young not only liked but agreed to record with Crosby,
Stills &AMP; Nash.
 &HT;    And when he drove down to Los Angeles, he was impressed to find
that his compatriots had left their longtime label, Atlantic
Records, and were financing their new album themselves.
 &HT;    ``It was just a good feeling again _ it was three guys who have
been making music for 30 years together, and they still want to do
it enough to go in and do it out of their own pockets,'' the
54-year-old Young says. ``That's a fantastic testimony right there
to why someone would want to be involved in that energy. It was all
positive, and the music was really great.''
 &HT;    After recording some of the other musicians' songs, Young then
offered up a few he'd written for his own album _ an
acoustic-oriented effort called ``Silver and Gold'' _ telling them
to ``take the best ones you think we can do the best job on.''
 &HT;    But throughout the process, Crosby says, the four refused to
acknowledge that they were making an album, instead taking a ``one
tune at a time'' approach.
 &HT;    ``We just didn't talk about what was going to happen or where it
was going,'' Crosby says. ``We didn't have expectations, which are
real dangerous things. What felt good was to just do the music that
was on our plate at that second and stay focused on that, and it
kept the right vibe going.''
 &HT;    They've fought to sustain that vibe even after the album's
release. The group insisted that a piano and guitar be available
even during promotional interviews for ``Looking Forward,'' and
during breaks they'd drift there to show each other new ideas.
 &HT;    And then there's ``CSNY2K,'' a three-month tour _ though it
could easily be extended _ that will feature songs from ``Looking
Forward,'' other CSN&AMP;Y favorites and music from their previous
bands, as well as new songs.
 &HT;    After that? Well, despite their history of stop-and-go dynamics,
all four band members speak hopefully of continuing their
collaboration with more consistency than they have in the past.
 &HT;    All have ongoing individual projects they're working on, ranging
from Crosby's upcoming film about music activism, ``Stand and Be
Counted,'' to Young's ``Silver and Gold'' and his continued
archival project. Those projects will inescapably make demands on
their time.
 &HT;    But the four are also conscious of how much time they've wasted
along the way, and have made a conscious commitment to what they
clearly feel is a good thing to have going.
 &HT;    ``None of the other stuff stops,'' Nash says, ``but the emphasis
shifts to what we feel right now is most important and what we
believe is most important, which _ you can ask the other guys _ is
this present piece of music that we have created, and the tour.
That takes precedence over anything.''
 &HT;    ``We have an occasion here,'' Young adds, ``and an opportunity.
We just have to keep the doors open.''
 c.1999 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Looking Forward,'' consult the
official CSN Website at www.crosbystillsnash.com. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
