<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7440 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-CELEBRITY-PC-INVESTIN     12-13 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBRITY-PC-INVESTING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFIT CARING  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By SHARON EDELSON 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Believe it or not, when Leonardo DiCaprio gets on his soap box
about saving the planet, he's not just blowing hot air. DiCaprio,
along with Cameron Diaz, Aidan Quinn and Alanis Morissettamong the socially and environmentally enlightened entertainers who
are putting their money where their conscience is.
</P>
<P>
   They, like many investors, have created portfolios filled with
the stocks of companies with sound environmental policies, fair
employment practices and other traits beyond profit and loss.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, they've discovered that it's possible to do well
while also doing good.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can make a huge difference by checking to see where
their money is going,'' affirms actress Susan Sarandon, while the
designer Diane Von Furstenberg, who avoids companies dealing in
arms, adds, ``It's a good thing to invest in products and services
that help. That's the elevating side of the American capitalist.''
</P>
<P>
   Long seen as the purview of the Birkenstock set, such so-called
PC investing has been gaining mainstream acceptance. And now, if
picking stocks isn't your thing, there are certain mutual funds and
indexes that avoid ``sin'' industries such as tobacco, alcohol and
gaming and that screen for ethical concerns like union busting and
workplace discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Ethical investing is taking off in part because the army of
newly minted dot-com millionaires, who were in junior high school
when a greed-is-good philosophy swept over the '80s, don't want to
manage their money the way their parents did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pendulum of unethical behavior swung so far during the
Michael Milken era,'' says Patrick McVeigh of financial management
firm Trillium. ``People are saying, `We don't want to invest that
way.'''
</P>
<P>
   And legal restrictions governing pension funds are no longer an
obstacle since the Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration
ruled that selection of socially conscious investments is not
inconsistent with fiduciary standards governing such plans.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most compelling is the fact that the performance of
some PC mutual funds and indexes has been good enough to make evil
capitalists green with envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are outperforming most other funds in our category,
regardless of whether they are socially responsible or not,'' says
Chris Brown, co-portfolio manager of the socially and
environmentally conscious Pax World balance fund, which invests in
stocks, bonds, cash and equivalents.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar, the Consumer Reports of the mutual-fund world,
identifies over 60 funds that specifically target social concerns,
including Dreyfus Third Century, Calvert Social Equity, Citizens
Emerging Growth, Green Century Equity, Meyers Sheppard Pride and
Women's Equity Mutual.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are many definitions of socially responsible
investing _ and plenty of loopholes and rationales should an
investor wish to include a questionable company in his or her
portfolio. After all, good deeds are no guarantee of good returns _
although performance was more of an issue when people were avoiding
South African investments to protest apartheid and tobacco and
firearms companies were driving the Standard &AMP; Poors 500.
</P>
<P>
   Today, performance and ethics seem more closely interwined.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the companies that are proactive in doing good are
performing better,'' says Dana Giacchetto, president of Cassandra
Group, the trendy financial management company that counts DiCaprio
and Diaz among its youthful Hollywood clients. ``General Electric
has shed a lot of defense and chemical units, while companies like
Philip Morris have been hurt. There are not a lot of people who
want to start pounding the table about why cigarettes are good for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   But while many ethically enlightened firms are now doing well,
some investors still want to goose their profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People put together a portfolio they consider to be socially
or environmentally responsible and enhance their returns by using
futures on the market itself _ S&AMP;P futures,'' says Andrew Malloy, a
partner in Tag Associates, which managed the money of the late Time
Warner chairman Steve Ross. ``To the extent that the market pushes
well ahead of the companies in the portfolio, you have a side door
exposure to the market itself. There are a lot of sneaky ways to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, PC investing offers protesters a voice where it
really counts: in the boardroom. Two cases in point: The Domini
Social Equity Fund has been urging Johnson &AMP; Johnson to improve
standards at its Mexican factories while Trillium believes its
vocal objection to Home Depot's practice of buying timber from old
growth forests persuaded the company to change its position.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sharon Edelson is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
