<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO EASY ANSWERS IN THE SAN FRANCISCO RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayors have a tough job. They have to set a tone
for a city at the same time they set parking fines. They have to
symbolize a city while they make sure the streets are swept.
</P>
<P>
   That's particularly hard in San Francisco, a city where nowadays
some leave their hearts but more leave their waste.
</P>
<P>
   Mayors have to represent all the people, no matter their
politics, while sitting in an office where petty political types
constantly arrive wanting something. Mayors have to take unending
guff from everyone.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1997 U.S. Mayor's Conference demonstrators chanting
for higher workfare pay surrounded Mayor Willie Brown. Mayor Thomas
Menino of Boston turned to me and said, ``Congressmen don't have
this. Senators don't have this. We have this.''
</P>
<P>
   We, in turn, have to live with mayors, ride their buses and step
over their failed social policies in the streets. That's why we're
so picky about mayors.
</P>
<P>
   San Franciscans are facing two less than perfect choices for
mayor, even though they come on strong as symbols. The following
are a few questions to focus voters' minds before Tuesday's
election.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who do you want as mayor if there's an earthquake? There's
going to be an earthquake. It's just a matter of when.
</P>
<P>
   When asked who he wanted as mayor when the Earth moves, a friend
said, ``Er, Dianne Feinstein?''
</P>
<P>
   I thought of Art Agnos attending to the nouveaux homeless at the
Marina Middle School. The 1989 earthquake was Agnos' finest moment
as mayor. San Francisco wasn't well prepared for the quake, but
afterward Agnos and his wife, Sherry, were all over town pitching
in. Later Agnos successfully twisted the arm of the Red Cross to
hand over the millions it collected in the name of San Francisco
but stashed in its general fund.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not advocating either Willie Brown or Tom Ammiano, the
president of the governing Board of Supervisors, as the better
choice for earthquake preparedness, as if they were different
brands of batteries. I'm just saying think about it, because no
poll will tell you when the Big One will hit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who do you want as mayor when the recession hits?
</P>
<P>
   Some of the dot-commers probably aren't old enough to remember
recessions, but we had one way back when Windows 3 was challenging
the Macintosh SE and Bill Clinton was a governor of a backwater
state.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a recession, kids. Stocks do not eternally go up,
e-commerce is just a big Sears catalog and San Francisco is not
always flush with money.
</P>
<P>
   The big issue in the 1991 run-off election between Agnos and
Frank Jordan was the city's budget deficit and what Agnos was going
to do about it. Recall that Agnos was the one who took a bath in
that election.
</P>
<P>
   Is Willie Brown or Tom Ammiano the man to have in City Hall when
programs, jobs and pay have to be cut? That's a tough question. Is
either the man to raise taxes? That's a somewhat easier question.
</P>
<P>
   The Brown administration has been blessed with budget surpluses,
much of which went into new city employees who'll have to be paid
when San Francisco goes broke _ or has a ``budget shortfall,'' as
mayors in free fall call them.
</P>
<P>
   It might be fun to see Brown do some unspending. Otherwise
recessions are no fun. You may lose your job. You get fewer
services. And even with a slumped economy the price of San
Francisco housing doesn't go down.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's your choice of symbol? Sure, we shouldn't care about
mayors as symbols. They're in the pothole business. But they are
symbols, and this election is loaded with symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano's workers are calling new voters and asking them if they
want to make history. There's a feeling of crusade to Ammiano's
campaign that's invigorating in a city where bohemians are being
pushed out by newcomers in cars from Bavaria, and the demand for
social change has been replaced by a demand for spare change.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is a living symbol of a certain stylish San Francisco,
whether you love him or hate him. And the farther away you get, the
better he looks. When he heard that Brown had been forced into a
runoff, my dad back East said, ``You're not getting rid of your
mayor, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   You have to answer those questions yourself, while you sort
though all those well-chewed questions about housing, leadership
and cronyism, and ask your pocketbook the obvious question of
whether Ammiano or Brown will do it the least damage.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the election will come down to the economic issues
of jobs, pay, rents and taxes. This election may be between two men
the rest of the nation would consider Bolsheviks, but the old
Reagan question still applies. Are you better off now than you were
four years ago?
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano and Brown have added one more question to Reagan's,
though: Do you fear what will happen to you in the next four years?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
