<HEADER>
A7505 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      12-13 1511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S TIME TO CATCH UP AFTER A LATE INVESTING START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I started my investing late in life. I am a 49-year-old woman
who sells real estate and my income can vary quite a bit from year
to year. My net income usually falls between $80,000 and $110,000
at this point in my career. I now have a savings program that
includes $200 a month to Fidelity Asset Manager fund, where I have
$19,461, and $200 a month to Fidelity Fund, where the balance is
$6,084. I have SEP-IRAs of $6,782 in Fidelity Equity Income and
$8,049 in Fidelity Spartan Market Index. I add $5,000 a year to the
SEP-IRAs. I don't necessarily picture myself retiring at age 65,
but I would like to have the financial resources to slow down if I
so chose. In some articles, you seem to lean toward Vanguard funds.
As you can see, I am invested in Fidelity funds. Should I diversify
into different funds, or do all the companies offer similar
packages? I honestly don't know what you mean by large-cap and
mid-cap etc., but would like to have an evaluation of my financial
status. I like to keep liquid funds in an asset-manager-type fund
for easy access since my income fluctuates.
</P>
<P>
   J.J., Lake Oswego, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Since you started investing le, you need to concentrate more
intensely on building these accounts, which will probably b the
bedrock of your financial stability whenever you retire.
</P>
<P>
   At your current savings rate (and presuming there are no
withdrawals from the Asset Manager account) you would have an
accumulation of $553,990 at age 65.
</P>
<P>
   Without even factoring in the effects of inflation on that pool,
it will clearly be inadequate to support a comfortable retirement,
given your current income levels. The main thing you need to do is
save more.
</P>
<P>
   One suggestion that frequently works for people such as yourself
who hve variable income streams is to set a certain point as your
expected annual earnings, and then contribute a heavier percentage
of your income to savings during the years when you pass that
benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose, for example, you budgeted yourself so you could live on
$90,000 a year, including the current $9,800 that goes into
savings. You might then decide that a certain percentage _ or all _
of the earnings that you make in excess of that level go into
savings.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have any particular argument with your fund choices,
although the portfolio could certainly be more diverse.
</P>
<P>
   First, I suggest that since you are using the Asset Manager
account more or less as an emergency pool, I would move to a more
conservative sibling of this fund, which is the Asset Manager
Income fund.
</P>
<P>
   Like Asset Manager, this fund spreads its investments among
stocks, bonds, and cash, but Asset Manager Income puts about 80
percent of its assets in cash and bonds, compared with about 47
percent for Asset Manager.
</P>
<P>
   Second, I sugest you look at your historical earnings trend and
decide what might be a prudent level at which this account could be
topped out.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if the level is $25,000, I'd continue with the
current contributions util you reach that level, and then transfer
the $200 monthly contributions to the Fidelity Fund account, or
another mutual fund holding. If a bad sales season subsequently
causes the Asset Manager Income balance to fall below $25,000 or
whatever target you have set, you could then resume contributions
until you get back to the benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   The terms large-cap, mid-cap, and so forth refer to he size of
the companies that dominate a funds portfolio. For example, all of
the funds you hold have large-cap portfolios. Cap here refers to
market capitalization, which is the value of all of the shares of a
company's stock that are outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   If this value exceeds $5 billion, it's considered a large-cap
company; if the market value of all of a company's shares fall
between $1 billion and $5 billion, it's considered a mid-cap
company; if the total value of all shares is below $1 billion, it's
a small-cap company.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the large-cap market has been the place to be.
But the stock markets go through various cycles, and the common
wisdom is that the mid- and small-cap categories will have their
day and catch up, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a well-diversified portfolio is usually dominated by the
relatively stable large-cap companies, but also holds smaller
positions in the mid- and small-cap sectors. Staying within
Fidelity, for example, you might look at Fidelity Mid-Cap Stock
fund or Fidelity OTC fund to give y some exposure to that sector.
The first is solid and more cautions; the second more aggessive,
and thus far has rewarded its owners more lavishly.
</P>
<P>
   In the small-cap arena, Fidelity isn't particularly attractive.
Two nice funds, Fidelity Low-Priced Stock and Fidelity Small-Cap
Stock, are closed to new investors. Fidelity Small Cap Selector
seems to be proving little but that the small-cap arena does not
lend itself well to computer-aided stock picking.
</P>
<P>
   I guess I do tend to favor Vanguard funds, but that is basically
a reflection of my cautious approach to investing. Vanguard's
strong points are very low expenses and plain-vanilla approaches to
building portfolios, most clearly demonstrated in its wide array of
index funds.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, on the other hand, prides itself on the
stock-selecting prowess of its many talented portfolio managers.
Recent years have been kind to the index approach, but many believe
that as markets get choppier the most talented and prescient fund
managers will return to the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason to believe that with Fidelity you are going
any waybut first class _ and the same can be said for many other
fund families.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We are 63 and 64 years old and retired. We have $55,557
invested in these American mutual funds _ New Perspective, American
Mutual, Capital World Growth and Income, and Washington Mutual. We
also have $10,000 in a Nuveen fund, $50,000 in n annuity, and
$20,000 in deferred compensation that will be paid out next year.
We recently sold a property in Colorado and need to invest
approximately $30,000. My husband wants to add to the American
Funds portfolio. I think we need to try another fund. Our bank
account has more than $100,000 in it, so we are in a hurry to t it
down. Can you help us make a decision? We also own our own home,
with a $40,00 mortgage balance. Our combined monthly income is
$4,000.
</P>
<P>
   M.S., Carlsbad, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I tend to agree with your husband. You certainly could do a
lot worse than adding to the American Funds portfolio, which is
entirely made up of solid, fairly conservatively managed funds with
good long-term records.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to diversify, you might consider two American
offerings that are much riskier than the funds you hold. They are
American Century Heritage and American Century Vista.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have quite poor records over most ofthe last half
of this decade, new managers have posted very strong 1999 results.
Heritage is up 34.29 percent year to date, while Vista has produced
an eye-popping 81.22 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   Both seem attractive candidates at this point, although if you
were to add $30,000 to the American Funds portfolio, I'd put no
more than $5,000 of it in one or both of these.
</P>
<P>
   With all of that cash loafing at the bank, why not pay off your
mortgage? With such a cash surplus, your income probably exceeds
your expenses. By prepaying the mortgage, you could then take the
amount you were formerly paying to the bank and begin a
dollar-cost-averaging program into the American Funds portfolio,
building it still further to protect you against inflation in the
later years of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 42-year-old woman. Last year I opened a 403(b)
account, which now is worth $1,400, all invested in Fidelity Blue
Chip Growth fund. I contribute $150 biweekly. I would like to
retire at age 65. Is ving all of my money in one fund a good idea?
Should I diversify? Is my contribution eough?
</P>
<P>
   H.I., Randolph, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Fidelity Blue Chip Growth is certainly a first-rate fund,
with a long and enviable track record. But you should diversify so
that you have small percentages of your money in other market
sectors. If you send me a list of the options open to you through
the 403(b), I'll be happy to make some suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   You will have to calculate whether you are saving enough. Your
retirement savings represent 9.75 percent of your earnings, which
is a pretty typical level. If your investments earned 10 percent
average annual returns for the next 23 years and you continued
contributing at the current level, you would have $336,982 by age
65.
</P>
<P>
   You will have to combine that with your husband's retirement
assets to determine if you will have a satisfactory level of
savings at that point.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
