<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   11 1/2 ``Deuce Bigalow: Male Gigolo'' ``Saturday Night Live''
alum Rob Schneider stars as a hapless, mild-mannered fish-tank
cleaner whom fate forces to moonlight as a gigolo. A smorgasbord of
bizarre dates and gross-out humor ensues _ a web of bathroom jokes
and stock antics along the lines of executive-producer Adam
Sandler's usual fare. But thanks to sprint-like pacing and
Schneider's likability, this 85-minute film is as short and sweet
as it is stupid. (R) (Joan Anderman) &QL; 
 &QL; 
111 ``The Green Mile'' ``Shawshank Redemption'' writer-director
Frank Darabont goes back to prison with Stephen King and scores
again with an involving story about supernatural happenings shaking
up the grisly routine on a Louisiana prison death row in 1935. Tom
Hanks's humane guard reacts with increasing awe to Michael Clarke
Duncan's saintly giant, whom Hanks just can't believe is a killer.
(R)
</P>
<P>
   (FR) 111 ``Liberty Heights'' As he did in ``Diner,'' ``Tin
Men,'' and ``Avalon,'' Barry Levinson returns to the 1950s
Baltimore of his youth, this time with more focus on societal
context and currents. The characters thus seem more like historical
markers and in some ways less idiosyncratic than in his earlier
films, but Levinson's canvas is broader and more deeply evocative
of time and place than ever, which is the most moving thing about
the film. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
111 1/2 ``Tumbleweeds'' A fresh, exhilarating mother-daughter story
starring Janet McTeer as a mom whose reflexive coquettishness keeps
getting her in trouble, but never so much so that she leaves her
daughter feeling unloved; a spunky performance by Kimberly J. Brown
creates a daughter who believably wonders when they're going to
stop fleeing her mom's soured romances. (PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
