<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASHMINA'S STARTING TO GET HER GOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is ashmina all it's cracked up to be, the rarest of rare
fabrics, harvested only from the chins and bellies of a particular
kind of scarce Himalayan goat that lives at very high altitudes? Or
is pashmina merely cashmere by another name?
</P>
<P>
   It's a question that's been keeping me up nights, wondering and
worrying. I don't move in pashmina circles, but I just hate it when
anybody tries to pull the wool, or whatever, over the eyes of the
cashmere class.
</P>
<P>
   Where will the pashmina controversy end?
</P>
<P>
   That was a rhetorical question, but I wouldn't be surprised to
pick up a shopping circular one of these Sundays and read: ``Who
Wants to Look Like a Millionaire? Warm and Fashionable Pashmina 80
Percent Off Upscale Store Prices . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Pashmina is cashmere, period. That's the official word from the
Boston-based Cashmre and Camel Hair Manufacturer's Institute. That
organization has issued a press release stating that pashmina isn't
``necessarily finer than other types of cashmere, nor does it have
any distinguishing characteristics other than those normally
associated with cashmere.''
</P>
<P>
   Pashmina, the release continued, is a term derived from an
Indian word for cashmere. Pashmina is not a legally recognized term
for describing fabric content. ``In its current usage, this is
marketing terminology intended apparently to capitalize on a fad.''
</P>
<P>
   Fad or not, pashmina marches on, into American closets. It
emerged as a fashion status symbol last Christmas. Pashmina shawls
were harder to score than a Furby. Pash-mania was rampant in
Europe. Fashion magazines were full of beautiful people wrapped in
cash-mina, as some called it. The fabric was touted as finer,
softer, and warmer than cashmere, and also rarer, presumably
because of all the hairs from those goats' chinny-chin-chins, thus
pricier.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, fashion fans on this side of the Atlantic coveted
pashmina shawls, two or three of them in various colors. Money was
no object, and a good thing, too, because pashmina shawls were
going for as much as $1,000, if you could find any.
</P>
<P>
   This season, pashmina seems to have peaked as a status symbol.
It's now available to the masses, those who can afford to shell out
$200 to $800 for a shawl, and in these economically robust times
there are masses of those masses. Pashmina is everywhere,
advertised in magazines and catalogs and Internet shopping sites,
over the counter in Neiman Marcus, Saks Fifth Avenue, Filene's, and
other stores greatnd small.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much pashmina now that I've been worrying about the
welfare of those bare-chinned, bald-bellied goats wandering around
in their chilly Himalayan pastures. Karl Spilhaus, president of the
cashmere institute, put my fears to rest. Cashmere is harvested
from the soft undercoat of the cashmere goat, the whole goat, he
said. The pashmina story _ the special goats, the chin and belly
hair _ is just that, a story, a marketing ploy.
</P>
<P>
   Having seen pashmina close up, and felt it, too, I wonder what
all the fuss is about. It's nice, but no nicer than cashmere. But
then, it is cashmere. Recently the Wall Street Journal asked Dr.
Kenneth D. Langley, a professor of textile sciences at the
University of Massachusetts at Dartmouth to put pashmina under a
microscope. He did, and pronounced it ``good ol' cashmere, nothing
special.'' Tell that to the goats.
</P>
<P>
   A word to the wealthy. Spilhaus says this is a good year to buy
cashmere (or whatever you call it). Prices are comparativelylow
because of last year's Asian economic crisis. They're still not low
enough for some of us. If you're looking for me, I'll be airing out
my old woolies and watching those shopping circulars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
