u a BC-MEDICAL-ERRORS-BOS &LR;      12-13 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-ERRORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL-ERRORS ISSUE GOT HIGH-PROFILE PUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happened back when he was playing tight end for Harvard. A
teammate's knee got mangled, then a prominent Boston surgeon
bungled te operation, cutting open the wrong knee before he finally
went to work on the right one. It's an experience that still haunts
the aging pass catcher, Senator Edward M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   US Senator Joseph Lieberman suspec he was a victim of medical
sloppiness 26 years ago, when he served in the Connecticut
Legislature. He was convalescing after having his appendix out when
an infection set in that kept him bedridden for three weeks. The
senator said he thinks the surgeon may not have washed his hands
thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Wakefield found herself touched by medical errors even as
she was preparing a report on the topic for the prestigious
Institute of Medicine. Her 83-year-old mother was having an
operation on her left hand. Three hours later, Wakefield got a
subdued voice mail from the surgeon confessing that he had operated
on the wrong hand.
</P>
<P>
   These incidents suggest how common medical mistakes are, as well
as how disturbing the consequences can be. And the fact that they
are happening not just to some amorphous public, but to policy
makers, helps explain how the issue recently became America's most
talked about health-care crisis. Two weeks ago the institute issued
a blockbuster report that madeeadlines nationwide, last week
President Clinton ballyhooed it, and now legislators are tripping
over one another to hold hearings and claim credit even as they get
ready to head home for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at the institute looking at research and data on
medical errors,at abstract issues, on Monday and Tuesday that week
of my mother's surgery,'' said Wakefield, who runs the Centerfor
Health Policy and Ethics at George Mason University. ``Then on
Thursday I'm experiencing them firsthand. It showed me how simple
(wrong-site surgery is) to prevent; you just put a mark on the
patients hnd.''
</P>
<P>
   Medical mistakes have been happening ever since doctors began
treating patients, although any discussion generally has taken
place behind the closed doors of doctors' conference rooms.
Understanding how the issue has been propelled into the spotlight
also can help explain how public opinion and public policy are
formulated in America today, especially when it comes to medicine
and science.
</P>
<P>
   The groundwork was quietly laid in the last five years. Studies
at Harvard University and elsewhere showed that as many as 100,000
Americans die each year from hospital-related errors, more than
from motor vehicle accidents, breast cancer, or suicide. And there
were highly publicized cases of people dying from errors, most
notably the fatal overdose of cancer-fighting chemicals that
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute gave in 1994 to Boston Globe health
columnist Betsy Lehman. As noted in the Boston Globe series titled
``Patients at Risk'' published earlier this year, hospitals have
been working to root out mistakes nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   A broader movement is also under way across America in which
patients have been exercising their right to know about treatments
they were getting, to have a say in those therapies, and, most
important, to ensure they were not given the wrong dose of drugs,
that the correct joint was operated on, and they would not be
subjected to other common errors.
</P>
<P>
   What about the special interests that nip so many other budding
reforms?
</P>
<P>
   Reformers masterfully framed the issue to move it away from
blaming individual hospitals, doctors, and nurses, instead pointing
to flaws in the health system, such as having doctors write
prescriptions by hand when computers are available with built-in
errordetectors. The result: powerful organizations representing
doctors, nurses, and hospitals are sponsring error-reduction
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   All those developments made the issue ripe, but it needed a
boost to distinguish it from other issues competing for the
attention of the president and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the Institute of Medicine, the nation's most prestigious
assemblage of doctors. Two weeks ago it issued a 223-page report
that gave policy makers everything they needed: a clear statement
of how widespread and deadly medical errors are and relatively easy
and inexpensive ways to cut the death rate in half over five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Institute of Medicine has clout, people have to genuflect
to it,'' said Dr. Lucian Leape, the Harvard researcher whose 1994
study showed for the first time how widespread hospital errors are
and who was one of the authors of the Institute report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Institute didn't say anything a lot of us haven't been
saying for a long time. It wasn't what the report said, but who
said it,'' Leape said.
</P>
<P>
   When it was said also was key. The Institute report came out on
a slow enough news day, and it became the lead story in the New
York Times, the Washington Post, and USA Today, as well as on the
NBC and ABC evening news, and was featured on three networks'
morning news shows.
</P>
<P>
   All that attention was not lost on Clinton, who political
analysts said was eager to find a domestic issue where he could
grab the spotlight. He held a news conference last week announcing
that he was ordering federal agencies to do all they cn to end
medical errors. The day before that the president signed a bill
ordering the Agency for Healhcare Research and Quality to do
precisely the sort of research on medical errors called for by the
Institute of Medicine, and the following day, he again raised the
errors issue, this time during a news conference called to talk
about renewed peace negotiations between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Key membes of Congress, were also eager to participate,
especially since several of them had been pushing the issue long
before it caught the White House's attention and many had had
personal experience with medical mistakes. Senator Arlen Specter,
Republican of Pennsylvania, is holding a hearing on medical errors,
Senator James M. Jeffords, Republican of Vermont, hopes to hold one
in January, and Democratic Senators Kennedy and Lieberman have
echoed the calls for quick action.
</P>
<P>
   One question raised by the recent flurry of activity is why, if
the problem is pandemic and the fixes are so straightforward, has
it taken five years to move from evidence to action?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that is half the 10 years it normally takes for health
problems to be addressed, said John Eisenberg, who runs the Agency
for Healthcare Research and Quality.
</P>
<P>
   What is critical, those involved with the issue said, is whether
the imperative to fix the problem will persist after the fervor
dies down. Eisenberg said he is committed to getting results,
although he added that while the Institute of Medicine recommended
that the US government spend $100 million a year on error
reduction, Congress in its recent budget increased that funding by
just $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Senar Bill Frist, Republican of Tennessee, who has been
pushing the issue longer than anyone on Capitol Hill and is the
only doctor in the Senate, said he is confident the momentum will
last ``now that we have the bully pulpit out behind it.'' And he
vowed to stick with it as long as it takes, in part because he
regrets how easy-to-prevent medical errors often undermined the
work he and his colleagues did in saving lives with
state-of-the-art heart and lung transplants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1342EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
