<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7514 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-LUDWIG-BOS &LR;      12-13 1698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LUDWIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTA LUDWIG'S LIFE BECOMES AN OPEN BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christa Ludwig was one of the greatest singers of this century.
The mezzo-soprano sang her final performance in Vienna in 1994 _
her New England farewell was a Tanglewood recital in 1991. Now she
has written a book, ``In My Own Voice'' (Limelight Editions, $30),
one of the few diva memoirs fully worthy of the career it records.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Ludwig was in America to promote the book, and spoke
cheerfully on the phone about her career and her life in
retirement. ``The most terrible thing,'' she says decisively, ``is
when some singers say that when they are not singing any more, they
are not living any more. It is so sad when a singer simply
disappears after her career _ I think of Lisa Della Casa; nobody
knows where she is now, where she is living, and that is a real
pity. I think my life started when I didn't sing any more and I
could begin to live like a normal person.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Russian soprano Galina Vishnevskaya, author of another
remarkable musical autobiography, Ludwig wrote her book herself and
didn't rely on a ghostwriter's bag of tricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started writing when I was still singing _ in fact, when I
had a big vocal crash during the Salzburg Festival in 1975 when I
couldn't sing so well. I was sitting at home, staring into the air,
and then I rmembered a book from Marlene Dietrich, and I thought,
`Ja, perhaps I could do this.' Then I forgot about it for several
years until I got an offer to write a book, and then I started,
whenever I was on the plane or sittig in the hotel. I wrote it as
how I speak, not the way a writer would, and I worked very closely
with Regina Domeraski, who made the translation into English. In
France, there was a very iterary translation, and this was not the
right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig always had a very secure sense of her own abilities. When
she was in Boston to sing and record Klytemnestra in Richard
Strauss's ``Elektra'' with Seiji Ozawa and the Boston Symphony, she
announced she would not remain an extra day for the ``patch''
session to repair any problems from the live performances. ``In my
case,'' she said firmly, ``this will not be necessary.'' Ozawa
remembers this fondly. ``It wasn't,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   She admired other performers who shared a comparable work ethic.
There is very little in her book about her singing with Maria
Callas on a recording of ``Norma,'' but on the phone she said,
``Callas was a hard worker, very precise. I can't say much about
her other than that; the only thing she told me was that I should
imitate her in the duets. I had no idea of the style of Bellini,
which was not my cup of tea. What I remember more from that
recording was the tenor, Franco Corelli _ who was not working as
hard as Callas. We had the sessions beginning at 10 o'clock in the
morning, and always his wife was calling to tell us that Corelli
couldn't come.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A sense of her strengts &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At one time there was a lot of talk about Ludwig taking on
soprano roles. She did sing and record Leonore in Beethoven's
``Fidelio'' and the Marschallin in Strauss's ``Der Rosenkavalier,''
but resisted entreaties to sing Isolde and Bruennhilde, although
she did learn the role of Isolde.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strauss's `Ariadne auf Naxos' I sang in only one season,''
Ludwig recalls, ``in Salzburg, in 1964. I thought this part needed
a more silvery tone than I had. Singing it, I got tired with the
vocal cords, and when they wanted me to sing it the next year, I
said no. The conductor Karl Boehm called me and tried to talk me
into it, and he didn't believe it when I told him it made me tired
_ if you tell people the truth, they will not believe you. But my
friend, the soprano Hilde Gueden, told me, you can never afford to
have some problem with the voice; if you have cancer, they will
hire you again, but if you have a vocal problem, it is over.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the people who strongly advised Ludwig not to sing Isolde
after hearing her sing the par straight through with piano was the
great Croatian soprano of an earlier generation, Zinka Milanov.
``For the beauty of the voice, hers was my favorite,'' says Ludwig.
``Her recording of `Pace, pace' from `La Forza del Destino' is
absolutely incredible. Conductors were asking me to sing Lady
Macbeth, and I didn't know what to do; my mother was not with me,
and she was my best vocal adviser. I bought a record with Leonie
Rysanek, but I couldn't listen to it because Leonie had such a
special voice that no one could imitate her. So I asked Zinka to do
with me Lady Macbeth. She told me, `First you have to sing it, and
not to push it.' It may not have en the singing as Verdi wanted it;
he said he wanted an ugly voice. But I sang it in the bel canto
style, in Vienna, with Sherrill Milnes, who was fantastic. There
was one high note I could only scream, and not sing in pianissimo,
which is why I never sang it in Italy, although I was asked to. I
thought people would boo me. In those days not everyone sang
difficult music in lower keys _ the way Domingo does.'' Ludwig
laughs, more merrily than wickedly. Lady Macbeth was one of the
triumphs of her career, and the performance has been preserved on
CD.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig was onstage as a teenager, and even sang Ulrica in
Verdi's ``Un Ballo in Maschera'' at 18 _ ``only once,'' she laughs,
``because it was terrible.'' Because she herself started her
professional career so young, Ludwig was recently shocked, when
judging a singing competition in Oslo, to discover that many
contestants were over 30. ``This I cannot understand; they should
be making their careers by now.'' Ludwig repeatedly credits her
mother, who had once sung Elektra under Karajan, for the security
of her own technique. ``I was never booed in my entire career,
although in the beginning I had some very mixed critics. I had no
high notes, and I had to learn this; at the beginning the high
notes cracked always, but my mother told me not to worry about the
critics, who did not understand that I was so young.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she would choose to sing if she could go onstage one
last time, in prime form, Ludwig does not hesitate. ``Kundry in
`Parsifal.' I love this part, ja.'' One of Ludwig's performances of
Kdry under Karajan has recently appeared on CD. ``But you know, on
the records, some of the performance is not ours. Elisabeth Hoengen
sang Kundry in Act I in Vienna, and on the records, it is Martha
Moedl. Apparently the first 18 minutes of the opera is not Karajan
because they could not find it, so they used a Bayreuth performance
conducted by Knappertsbusch. When this was discovered, it made a
big scandal! Of all the roles I never sang, the one I coveted was
Elektra; this was my wish, my dream, but it was not possible. I was
8 or something when I heard my mother sing it, but I wasn't afraid
_ I knew when the screams were going to come!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Stories and ideas &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig says she did not want her book to be boring. ``I wanted
not to write where I sang such-and-such that was a huge success,''
she says. Her book is a chronological narrative until she
establishes her career; then it changes direction to become a
series of essays about different aspects of a singer's life. She
scarcely mentions her first marriage to the baritone Walter Berry,
but does speak with great pride of their son, Wolfgang, who
contributes a brief, affectionate chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today Wolfi is a composer, for musicals. I think he had too
much classical music in the house when he was growing up. He had a
voice like his father and he asked me if he could make a career and
I told him, ``I don't know _ you smoke, you live.' But his
musicality runs in another direction. He has had two musicals come
out already in Germany, although the big success was not there yet.
I like his music. Now I am one time a grandmother, and the
littlene, Kevin, is 7. He attends the American International School
in Vienna, like his parents; the wholefamily speaks English like
New Yorkers!''
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Ludwig speaks about the least favorite of her many
recordings, the mother in Offenbach's ``Les Contes d'Hoffmann'' _ a
recording that was conducted by Seiji Ozawa, although Ludwig never
met him during the sessions. Her voice was tracked in later on,
when the original singer was judged unsatisfactory. ``Seiji never
saw me, and I am so ashamed of the record. It was not my fault, but
nobody was there, except for me in the headphones, trying to sing
in a trio with other singers who weren't there. They recorded my
voice without overtones, so I sounded terrible. The engineer told
me he would fix it, but when I heard it, he fixed it really fine!
This, unfortunately, is the modern way of making records.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig does love a few of her recordings. ``The record of
Mahler's `Des Knaben Wunderhorn,' with Leonard Bernstein, this I
love very much. And there is also a live recording of a recital
from the Salzburg Festival with Erich Werba which is very good. I
do not like so much making the Lieder in the recording studio _ it
is so difficult when you do not have the audience; you cannot get
the feeling in it. Of the operas, `Fidelio' with Otto Klemperer _
that is really good. Just now I start sometimes to listen to my old
recordings, and I think to myself, especially with the records I
made in the 1960s, `You know, Christa, you really sang very well.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Today Ludwig lives with her husband, the actor and stage
director Paul-Emile Deiber, near Cannes. ``I am not teacng, at
least not too much, because I am too lazy. For too many years I was
the whole time on the road, and always living in the hotel, and
what I liked was to be at home. Finally an live with my husband, my
dog, and my cat. Sometimes young singers will come to me when they
want to learn something for a recital or run through an operatic
role; theystay for a week and I show them how to phrase. This I
like very much because I do not have to go away to do it. Who would
want to go away from the south of France? I am happy to have
friends I can speak to now, and cook for! I like my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
