<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7517 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-KRAFT-BO     12-13 1983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-KRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'GRATEFUL' KRAFT SAYS HIS JOURNEY IS OVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Robert Kraft's long, strange stadium odyssey began five
years ago, with camera crews jockeying for a shot of the proud new
owner of the New England Patriots. After purchasing the team for a
record-setting $172 million, a jubilant Kraft thrilled local fans
by announcing the franchise wouldn't be moving to St. Louis after
all.
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots stadium saga finally ended late Monday night,
Kraft was alone at his Brookline home, with no cameras in sight.
</P>
<P>
   After returning home from a late business meeting and dinner
with his eldest son and confidant, Jonathan, Kraft had just turned
on the Monday night football game when the phone call he'd spent
years waiting for came.
</P>
<P>
   It was Patriots chief operating officer Andrew Wasynczuk calling
fro oxborough High School, where he was tracking the critical town
meeting vote on the team's proposed new $275 million stadium.
Wasynczuk, who spent the last seven months quarterbacking the
team's stadium drive, gave Kraft the good news. Foxborough
residents had just approved the new stadium, by a margin of more
than nine to one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very emotional moment,'' Kraft said as he reflected
upon the stadium struggle in an interview this week. ``This wasn't
a normal business deal. It was the stadium problems that hung up
the Patriots' prior owners. So this was about the future of the
team and the love of a community.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was the community of Foxborough, Kraft insisted, that
ensured the Patriots would remain in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got such a vote of support from hard-working people
who were willing to come out on a rainy night and listen to hours
and hours of boring discussion, well, it felt like it was my family
saying welcome home,'' Kraft said, his voice choked with emotion.
``It was a long journey that ended up back where we began. But it's
where the Patriots should be. We're very grateful to the people of
Foxborough and the state who made it possible, and we're going to
build something special that they'll be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his office 34 floors above State Street with
Jonathan, Kraft conceded that he purposely kept a low profile
during the stadium debate. Noting his tendency to ``become a
lightning rod'' for criticism, both Krafts repeatedly credited the
team's stadium success to Wasynczuk and other Patriots officials
who negotited the team's agreement and met with Foxborough
officials and residents on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned that when I get involved it changes the dynamic
so it becomes more a personality issue rather than a substantive
one,'' Robert Kraft said as Jonathan nodded in agreement.
``Luckily, we had a really great team of people. We let them run
with the ball, and clearly that faith was rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   After repeated requests, Kraft reluctantly agreed to discuss the
Patriots stadium struggles late last week, marking his first
extensive interview since he walked away from a publicly financed
$1 billion stadium deal with Connecticut eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of two hours, Kraft and his son readily
acknowledged that over the past five years they stumbled badly as
they struggled to find a new home for the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   But while both men made it clear they have moved beyond their
earlier missteps, including the team's costly failed id to build a
new stadium in South Boston, they were far less serene about the
team's aborted move Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel badly about it, I really do,'' Robert Kraft said after
drawing a deep breath. ``The governor of Connecticut and the
Legislature made herculean efforts for us. And the reception we got
from the people of Connecticut was incredible.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it just couldn't be done on schedule. And in the end, they
acknowledged that. But I feel very bad about it because while some
people in Connecticut may be happy they aren't spending all that
money, we really were moved by thir passion and support.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it would ready in 2001 and then 2002,'' Jonathan
Kraft said. ``But after a thorough review, it was clear it might be
2003, or 4 or 2005. And to compete with other teams, we needed a
stadium before that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kraft purchased the Patriots, the team ranked dead last in
terms of payroll. Now the team has one of the highest payrolls in
the league. Since 28-year-old Foxboro Stadium lacks the luxury and
club seats that generate the cash to pay for star players, the
Krafts have subsidized the team by using profits from their paper
business. That couldn't continue, Kraft said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's extraordinary publicly subsidized stadium offer
came after the Patriots had spent years trying _ and failing _ to
get a new stadium in Massachusetts. The last straw came when House
Speaker Thomas M. Finneran rejected a plan by Senate President
Thomas F. Birmingham to provide infrastructure assistance for a new
Foxboro Stadium that the Krafts would pay for and build on land
they already owned.
</P>
<P>
   The day Kraft signed the contract to move to Hartford, his body
language made it clear he did not want to leave Massachusetts. But
when he agreed to move the team to Hartford, it was with the best
of intentions, Kraft said. He adamantly denied the claim now made
by critics in Connecticut that he signed the Hartford deal simply
to entice Massachusetts into making a counteroffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had tried so hard for so long but we had come to the
realization that we couldn't do anythin in Massachusetts,'' Kraft
said. ``There was nothing in the works up here, and after ll we'd
been through, we believed nothing would ever change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we had three options: Move to Connecticut, where the people
really wanted us. Sell the team. Or move it out of New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``And while there were plenty of very, very lucrative offers to
move the team to L.A. and a few other cities, I had a personal
commitment to keep the team in New England. I knew I would never
move the team out of this area. That just wasn't something I was
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But five months after signing the agreement to move to Hartford,
the team walked away from the deal. Kraft says he left because the
state could not clean up the polluted stadium site and deliver it
in time for the promised 2001 opening date. Because Jonathan Kraft
was concerned from the outset that the site might have problems,
the Krafts had insisted that Connecticut's contract specify the
Patriots had the right to terminate the agreement with no penalty
prior to May 2.
</P>
<P>
   Citing delays in the site assembly and cleanup efforts, the
Patriots shocked many sports analysts by canceling the $1 billion
Hartford stadium agreement on April 30, two days before the penalty
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a record-breaking deal, so if we were driven by money
we would have held onto it and waited for however many years it
took until they got the site ready or moved us to a new location,''
Kraft said. ``But it was never about money. And people who think
that, don't really understand us. For us, your legacy iat you do
for your family and your community.''
</P>
<P>
   So if it wasn't about money, what was the lure of Connecticut's
$1 billion contract? Kraft says it was the chance for his family to
be involved in ``a greater social good'' beyond a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real kicker for us was the idea that the stadium could act
as a catalyst to help the state redevelop downtown Hartford,''
Kraft said. ``The sacrifice of leaving Massachusetts, which it was
clear to everyone all along I never really wanted to do, was that
we could make a real difference in a struggling city ripe for
redevelopment. That's what turned me on.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly nine months later, Connecticut is still reeling from the
Patriots' sudden departure. And there are lingering threats of a
lawsuit, though given the various exit clauses included in the
Patriots' contract, it's unclear on what grounds the state could
sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can look you or anyone else in the eye and say we did
nothing improper'' Kraft declares in steely tone. ``We worked with
Connecticut in good faith, and it simply didn't work out the way
anyone hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the 58-year-old Kraft's voice softens, and he looks
down at the gleaming mahogany tabletop in front of him. ``Still I
hope somehow we can try to make it up to the good people of
Connecticut and to the political leaders down there who
unfortunately took the heat for it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years earlier, it was Kraft and his son who took the heat,
and not local politicans. Led by then-governor William Weld and
aide Steve Tocco, the Patriots proposed a ne tadium in South Boston
as part of a combined sports and convention center development or
``megaplex.'' Furious that the team hadn't consulted them first,
South Boston leaders errupted, and both Krafts were vilified.
Today, both men say they made mistakes and regret hurt caused by
their plans and off-the-cuff comments. Clearly chastened, they've
both been more wary of public comment ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the bitter disappointment, the Krafts are determined
to slough off critics who labeled them ``whiners'' and worse. Both
blame the South Boston debacle on their own ``naivete'' and
declined to criticize political leaders like Weld and Tocco, who
encouraged the Krafts to spend millions on developing a plan for a
South Boston stadium then abruptly abandoned them when local
leaders howled in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will the Krafts take on their former nemesis, Finneran, who
nearly singlehandely drove the team into Connecticut's arms and
once sarcastically referred to an NFL owner as a ``fat-assed
millionaire.'' Finneran later said he was speaking about another
team owner, but most listeners thought he was needling Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'm one of those things,'' Kraft said with a smile when
asked about the comments. Turning serious, he said no ill feelings
linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's history,'' the elder Kraft declared. ``There were a lot
of big-picture people who felt that the new stadium belonged in
Boston. And I think many South Boston residents, if left on their
own and allowed to hear things objectively, might have thought it
was better than some of the alternatives.Bt I don't dwell on it
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft continues to enjoy what he calls ``the privilege of owning
the Patriots'' and still ``gets pumped'' by the team's loyal fan
base, frequently engaging fans in the parking lot or near the field
before games. But he's also been stung by the ferocity of his
critics, who used to point to his golf-cart spins around the
stadium shaking hands with fans as evidence of either a
major-league ego or a man longing to be loved.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft says his high profile was dictated by necessity. ``When I
first bought the team I think I made 70 speeches in 90 days, but I
did it because we had to pay the bills,'' he said. ``This was a
team that had three owners in the previous four years and was in
disastrous financial shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Personal identification with fans, Jonthan Kraft said, was
essential to ``branding'' the team and marketing it to season
ticket holders and corporate patrons. ``It was a way of reassuring
potential fans that if you invest your money, time, and passion in
this team now, you won't be sorry. My dad did that, and we sold out
before the season started. That had never happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Krafts grow more animated when discussing their plans for
the team's new, 68,000-seat stadium. ``It's a great plan in the
right place at the right time,'' Jonathan Kraft said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a signature piece for our family, our team,
and for Massachusetts, and I'm very excited about it,'' Robert
Kraft said. After a pause he added: ``All's well that ends well. I
couldn't ay it any better than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
