<HEADLINE>
ENVOY URGES NICARAGUANS TO TAKE ADVANTAGE OF RESIDENCY LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUSTINO AGUILA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Acting like a salesman, the Nicaraguan
ambassador to the United States encourages those from his homeland
not to miss an opportunity of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   With phrases like ``time is running out,'' and ``take advantage
of,'' the well-dressed man captivates his audiences _ often
plugging a toll-free number, 877-478-8472.
</P>
<P>
   But Ambassador Francisco X. Aguiree Sacasa is not trying to make
a buck here in San Francisco. Rather he is preaching to people from
his country about the Nicaraguan Adjustment and Central American
</P>
<P>
   Relief Act (NACARA).
</P>
<P>
   Under NACARA, Nicaraguan nationals are able to apply for
permanent residency in the United States as long as they can
provide proof that they have not committed any felonies and that
they have lived in the United States since before December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are running out of time,'' Sacasa told his audience of more
than 50 Nicaraguans on Sunday at the Ira and Leonore S. Gershwin
Theater. ``We need to make this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the turnout was low on Sunday, Sacasa is asking
Nicaraguans in the San Francisco Bay Area this week to spread the
message about the March 31 deadline when the application
</P>
<P>
   period under NACARA ends.
</P>
<P>
   Of an estimated 150,000 Nicaraguans living in the United States,
</P>
<P>
   slightly more than 40,000 have applied for permanent residency,
the ambassador said, and added that many of those who have not are
scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's fear that they'll be deported, but if they don't file
now, they'll have no one to blame but themselves,'' Sacasa said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimate that about 25,000 Nicaraguans live in
Northern California, but some believe there are more. Attorney
Thomas L. Hiester has helped 300 people file for permanent
residency under the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought anything like this would ever pass,'' said the
Daly City lawyer who attended Sunday's gathering. ``It's so
generous. It comes down to being an amnesty for Nicaraguans.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's always that easy. Nicaraguan native Esteban
Gonzalez, 45, applied for permanent residency more than a year
</P>
<P>
   ago. Even though he has followed procedures, he said, he has yet
</P>
<P>
   to hear about his status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been frustrating,'' said Gonzalez, who lives in Oakland.
``I've been patient, but I have not heard anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador emphasized that only about a dozen government
employees are screening thousands of NACARA applications. Sacasa
said he was trying to improve relations with U.S. immigration
</P>
<P>
   officials. ``It can be a bureaucratic system. Patience is
important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
