<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MAO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLENDER `MAO' STUFFED WITH LAYERS OF CONTEXT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MAO ZEDONG 
By Jonathan Spence 
Lipper/Viking, 188 pp., $19.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When China celebrated the 50th anniversary of its revolution in
October, most observers, Chinese and Western both, noted that while
the China of today was far removed from the People's Republic
proclaimed by Mao Zedong in 1949, it still had to be defined by
reference to Mao.
</P>
<P>
   A common observation illustrating this point was that the
instability _ and idealism _ of Mao's permanent revolution had ben
replaced by a stability precariously balanced between a stodgy
enshrinement of Communist ideology and an enthusiastic embrace of
Western capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   But if Mao provides only a point of reference for considering
what China is today, he remains among the most intriguing of
20th-century nation-builders. And he is _ as Jonathan Spence makes
clear in this tightly drawn study, another in the ``Penguin Lives''
series of brief ographies _ a world figure about whom the
ambiguities and contradictions are at least as interesting as the
momentous accomplishments and the equally momentous horror.
</P>
<P>
   Spence teaches at Yale, and his previous books on Chinese
history have been noted for their scholarship as well as the charm
of their writing. These qualities are everywhere evident in this
volume for general readers.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than focusing on the major events in which Mao was
involved and telling his story through them _ a conventional
historian's approach _ Spence has attempted, very largely
succeeding, to discover and explore the factors that shaped Mao's
thinking and actions.
</P>
<P>
   The series of upheavals that Mao launched in 1957 led up to the
Cultural Revolution. As they played out over the following years,
they alternately mystified, transfixed, and horrified Chinese and
Western observers _ and they still are not wholly understood.
</P>
<P>
   During the previous year, Spence writes, ``various tracks
converged in Mao's mind: the ability of the nobodies of China to
transform their society, the obstructionism of the Communist
Party's own new establishment, the possibilities of vast economic
strides forward if those with `bound feet' would get out of the
way, the need to deepen the channels of criticism and the flow of
information and to keep the brightest flames of socialism
burning.''
</P>
<P>
   That is pretty solid analysis _ and a pretty fair framework for
understanding the events that were to follow. It is an analysis
most readers would be willing to take on faith, as it were, from a
scholar of Spence's standing. But what makes thisook so fine an
accomplishment _ especially considering its length _ is that Spence
provides supporting evidence about Mao's thinking, mainly from a
``curious'' four-hour speech to party leaders on the subject of
``contradictions.'' There were ``antagonistic'' contradictions
between ``the enemy (landlords, imperialist elements, and the like)
and ourselves'' and ``non-antagonistic'' ones ``among the people''
and within the party, and these were to be resolved through a
``process of unity-criticism-unity.''
</P>
<P>
   One interesting element of Mao's life is his personal relations
with his successive wives, his children, and his old revolutionary
comrades. It is surprising to find it even mentioned in so
compressed a study as this, but it is one that Spence draws upon
effectively. In the early 1950s, Spence notes, Mao received many
letters from such people, conveying news from ``across space and
decades,'' which ``gave him an intimate view of how the revolution
was affecting individuals he knew well, and enabled him to place
the larger national criteria in a smaller-scale series of
contexts.''
</P>
<P>
   As a historian rather than a political scientist, Spence is
interested in placing Mao in the context of Chinese cultural
history and philosophy. Several times he cites Mao's poetry as
something he used to define his place in a Chinese pantheon.
Curiously, however, Spence ignores an even more important cultural
element, calligraphy, which Mao _ like the emperors before him _
deliberately exploited to project power and establish his
legitimacy to rule.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, Spence notes that ancient Chinese
philosophers ``loved the paradoxes of status reversed . . . the
dizzying possibilities inhren in turning things upside down.'' They
were ``natural dialecticians,'' he writes, for whom ``te aspects of
misrule were always embodied within the concept of order.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be ``Mao's terrile accomplishment,'' Spence writes, to
meld such insights with Western socialist thought into ``a
long-drawn-out adventure in upheaval.'' And it is that kind of
assessment, well argued and well documented throughout, that makes
Spence's slender book on ``Mao'' a necessity even on shelves that
sport _ or flaunt _ the five volumes of Mao's collected writings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
