<HEADER>
A7526 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRELAND-STREETS-BOS &LR;      12-13 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-STREETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE AMID INFLEXIBILITY IN ULSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROSSMAGLEN, Northern Ireland _ Sitting in Paddy Short's pub, a
neglected pint of Guinness in front of him, the IRA man didn't
hesitate when asked what the chances were of his organization
turning in some weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a chance in hell,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   The political progress achieved in Northern Ireland over the
past month has been predicated mostly on the premise that the Irish
Republican Army will begin disarming, but there is no appetite for
doing so here in the republican heartland of South Armagh.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA still runs this hilly, rural corner of Northern Ireland.
Through most of the Troubles, the British Army has been forced to
operate by helicopter here, so dangerous are the narrow roads lined
with hedgerows that hide bombs and assassins.
</P>
<P>
   That there seems no evidence that the IRA's most hardline
disciples are willing, or have been prepared, to countenance the
handing in of weapons would lead one to despair for the future of
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Ulster Unionists, Northern Ireland's largest
party, have said they will withdraw their support and force the
collapse of the power-sharing government that took office this
month, unless the IRA begins to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics say that the last government that sought to share power
between Protestant Unionists and Catholic Republicans lasted six
months before collapsing in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will fail, just as other attempts to sell out the loyal
people of Ulster will fail,'' the Rev. Ian Paisley, leader of the
Democratic Unionists and a bloc of Protestants who want the
government to fall, said recently.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the defiant republicans in Paddy Short's pub, and
the uncompromising unionists at Stormont, there are important
differences between today and 1974 that bode well for the future,
according to historians and political analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have moved beyond the failed policies of the past,'' said
Sinn Fein's leader, Gerry Adams, who in 1974 was an IRA commander
but who has since persuaded the IRA to let politics replace the
``armed struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny Morrison, a former IRA figure who is now a writer but who
is still close to senior IRA leaders, says he believes the IRA will
put weapons ``beyond use.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, only the mainstream parties were committed to
power-sharing, and moderate unionists were even more divided than
they are today. And, crucially, the main paramilitary groups on
both sides were violently opposed to the idea of a compromise
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA was convinced in 1974 that it was winning its campaign
to end British control of Northern Ireland. The loyalist
paramilitary groups, appalled at the thought of sharing power with
Catholic nationalists, used their own power to shut Northern
Ireland down with a general strike that brought the collapse of the
government.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, despite the IRA's misgivings about turning in
weapons, its allies in Sinn Fein are part of the government. The
IRA and its loyalist counterparts, the Ulster Defense Association
and the Ulster Volunteer Force, are openly in favor of a political
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   While dissidents on both sides of the divide remain committed to
wrecking the Good Friday Agreement of April 1998, their ability to
inflict anything but sporadic violence is limited, according to
security officials on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a noticeable momentum in Ireland. On an island
where history weighs heavily, the word ``historic'' tends to be
overused here. But it is hard to find another word to describe what
has happened over the past month.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of political paralysis that followed the
endorsement by voters, both north and south, of the Good Friday
Agreement, there has been a burst of progress in implementing the
provisions of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   First, the former US senator from Maine, George Mitchell, spent
three months persuading the Ulster Unionists and Sinn Fein not to
allow the failure of the agreement he brokered. Mitchell's efforts
at trust-building were rewarded when the Ulster Unionists dropped
their demand that the IRA begin disarming before they formed a
government with Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare pledge of tolerance by an Ulster Unionist leader,
David Trimble acknowledged the legitimacy of nationalists seeking a
united Ireland by peaceful means, and vowed to treat Catholics as
equals.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein's Adams responded by unequivocally rejecting violence
and by pledging to work in partnership with unionists to create a
more egalitarian society. The IRA completed the jigsaw carefully
choreographed by Mitchell with a statement reversing its refusal to
consider disarming.
</P>
<P>
   All this set the stage for the dramatic developments of this
month. In the space of two days, the British Parliament returned
governing power to the Northern Ireland Assembly. On Dec. 2, the
Irish government formally dropped its constitutional claim to the
territory of Northern Ireland; Britain and Ireland signed a new
treaty governing their relationship; and the first-ever meeting of
a power-sharing government that included unionists and republicans
took place at Stormont castle.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most remarkable was the appointment of Martin
McGuinness, once the IRA's chief of staff, as the education
minister in the new government. McGuinness acknowledged that the
eyes of his former comrades-in-arms will be on him and he will have
to prove that, as he put it, ``politics provides a real alternative
to conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the optimism generated by the return of an elected
government here for the first time in 25 years, it remains true
that this experiment in power-sharing could collapse as the last
one did in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   But much has happened since then. Many of the grievances of
Catholics, such as the housing discrimination that catalyzed the
civil rights movement whose suppression touched off the conflict,
have been addressed _ at least with legislation that provides
redress to anyone who feels discriminated against.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the importance of British and Irish sovereignty has been
diminished by the increasing power of the European Union, the
15-nation bloc to which both countries belong that has taken over
many responsibilities that used to be the domain of national
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Britain and Ireland, historic foes, have never been closer. In
1974, few Irish people were willing to drop their claim to Northern
Ireland. Last year, 95 percent voted to do so and to enshrine the
principle of consent: that Northern Ireland will remain part of the
United Kingdom until a majority living there say otherwise. In
1974, Britain saw Dublin's interest in Northern Ireland as
interference; now the two governments are partners, with the new
treaty enshrining cross-border, and cross-island, cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The other big difference is that between 1974 and today some
2,000 people have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just want a bit of peace,'' said Ann Carr, who staged
peace vigils for years to encourage the Ulster Unionists to
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Many people remain doubtful that the IRA will turn in, or
destroy, any of its weapons. But Brian Feeney, a political analyst
and former nationalist politician in Belfast, says there is great
incentive for the IRA to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about the north anymore,'' he said. ``It's about
the south, too.''
</P>
<P>
   At the next general election in the Irish Republic, which could
be held as soon as next year, Sinn Fein stands to gain three or
four seats in the Irish parliament. Feeney says that would probably
make them kingmakers, holding the balance of power to create a
coalition government. But Feeney says that scenario can occur only
if the IRA does its part and turns in some weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Weapons retain a mythical importance to the IRA. But political
power, which its allies in Sinn Fein now hold in the north and
could soon gain in the south, is a tradeoff that the leaders of the
most resilient guerrilla movement of the 20th century have to
consider as the century comes to a close.
</P>
<P>
   As even the wary IRA man at Paddy Short's pub acknowledged,
``I've seen things this week I never thought I'd see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7527 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-WEST-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     12-13 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-WEST-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... is black.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But West's rhetoric has been far more incendiary than Bradley's
to date. West writes hopefully of the need for racial unity, but he
criticized Clinton's vaunted dialogue on race as little more than
``chitchat.''
</P>
<P>
   He is a harsh critic of government in general, writing of the
police and prison systems as mechanisms of state violence against
minorities, and of the FBI and CIA as more subtle forms of that
vioence, ``whose actions threaten personal liberties, and remain
beyond public scrutiny and accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is not the grand paradox of American democracy at its
inception that the people are distrusted and contained, their power
dispersed and diluted so that elites may prosper at the expense of
workers' power, women's power, and especially black, brown, yellow
and red power?'' West wrote in the introduction to his latest book,
``The Cornel West Reader.''
</P>
<P>
   He criticizes ``multinational corporate capitalism, with its
bankrupt and authoritarian-like state,'' persecuting the ``black
and brown, and working poor and underclass,'' attacking women's
reproductive rights, and making lesbians and gays ``cultural
scapegoats.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes that white fear of a black sexuality is ``a basic
ingredient of white aism.''
</P>
<P>
   He has criticized today's black middle class as ``more deficient
and more decadent' than in previous decades, their selfishness a
prime reason for what he sees as a crisis in black leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most present-day black leaders seem too hungry for status to
be angry, too eager for acceptance to be bold, too self-invested in
advancement to be defiant,'' he wrote in his bestseller, ``Race
Matters.''
</P>
<P>
   West's association with Sharpton, who has a reputation for
widening the racial divide, and his qualified sympathy for Minister
Louis Farrakhan and the Nation of Islam reinforce his image as a
radical.
</P>
<P>
   His links to Sharpton and Farrakhan, especially, will not fly on
a national political stage, said analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has some rather bizarre ideas,'' said Steele, of Stanford.
``That children should be able to vote, that government should take
care of everybody. He's socialistic in that bent. Overall, those
ideas would be dangerous for Bradley politically because the public
would identify him with the far, almost exotic, left.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Abigail Thernstrom, the coauthor of ``America in Black and
White: One Nation, Indivisible'': ``I do not think Cornel West's
ideas or Bradley's ideas, which are very `two nations, separate and
unequal,' (are) reality in 1999, and I think the American public
knows that. The average voter will say, `Give me a break.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Voters will not respond well to claims that ``all whites are
racist, and that there has been no black progress that is
meaningful,'' said Thernstrom, who knows both Bradley and West. ``I
don't think his voice swhere the American public is, I really do
not.''
</P>
<P>
   The American public has never responded well to calls for a
redistribution of wealth, even during the Great Depression, said
Karlyn Bowman, a resident fellow and public opinion specialist at
the American Enterprise Institute.
</P>
<P>
   She cited a 1993 survey, which found that even 51 percent of
people who earned less than $15,000 a year believe Aericans should
be able to accumulate as much wealth as possible even if others
live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are voters likely to respond well to West's criticism of
welfare reform, Bowman said. In a mid-November Los Angeles Times
poll, which asked respondents what opinions would make them likely
to vote against a candidate, 59 percent of respondents were less
likely to vote for someone who opposed the welfare reform bill, as
Bradley did. Of the many issues surveyed, that position elicited
the strongest negative sentiment, Bowman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bradley rejects the suggestion that he might be
called upon to answer for West's views.
</P>
<P>
   ``My positions on race are formed out of my own experience and
my own life,'' he said. ``Cornel's a friend and he's an admired
friend. I don't know all the positions he's ever taken on all the
issues. I don't think they'll be liabilities because Cornel is
speaking to who I am as a person. I'm not worried, because I speak
for myself as to what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, many observers, especially those who know Bradley,
warn against overestimating West's sway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would doubt that Cornel West has a lot of influence on
him,'' said Walters, who was Bradley's colle when the former
senator taught for a short time at the University of Maryland. ``I
don't think anybody has that much influence over Bill Bradley. (He)
has proven he's his own man. That's precisely the attraction he has
for a lot of voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley does not brook attempts to hold him responsible for the
people with whom he associates: he defended his August visit to
Sharpton in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was the first Democratic politician in a primary
campaign to go to Harlem since 1968,'' Bradley said. ``I don't
agree with Al Sharpton on all the issues. But I recognized that it
was an opportunity to speak to a community that doesn't often have
presidential candidates come speak to them.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite Bradley's determination to remain solely responsible
for his public views, Walters said, West's presence in the campaign
might pull Bradley's image farther left.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is that view that Bradley is more liberal than he really
is, because he has surrounded himself with people like West,''
Walters said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Bradley and West will be bound together even more
closely in coming weeks, during their tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a very highly respected voice in the
African-American community,'' the candidate says of West. ``He's a
friend of mine who's known me for many years, and he can speak
about me in ways other people can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Added West: ``It's just to push him over the top. We'd go
everywhere, especially through the South. We'd be going to churches
and synagogues and trade union centers, barber shops and beauty
salons, the full court press.''
</P>
<P>
   They face a difficult battle. In the South, where most black
Democratic voters live, Gore's approval rating is at 74 percent,
whil,according to an August survey, 42 percent of voters still did
not know who Bradley was. And West is a complete unknown outside
intellectual circles in the Northeast, said David Bositis, senior
political analyst at the Joint Center for Political and Economic
studies, who conducted the survey.
</P>
<P>
   The whole trip might backfire, turning off black voters, Steele
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bradley is making a very serious mistake,'' Steele
said. ``If he's working through Cornel West, he does not understand
the black American community. He needs to reach out in a much
broader way.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele called West's ``aggressive support of racial preferences
very out of step with broader America,'' including a half of black
Americans. ``Bradley is placing himself in the far left of black
community,'' Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   West, however, is unlikely to abandon his position as a liberal
crusader against institutional power _ even if he succeeds in
helping his friend make it to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Then, West said, ``I'll become his loving and friendly critic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
