<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7528 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-13 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENSE IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- It took President Clinton, spouting Third Way
nostrums that go beyond petty politics, to finally clear away the
tear gas and the polysyllabic fog from the bizarre goings-on inside
and outside the hall at the World Trade Organization's battle in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The president's contributions were two: explaining why the trade
meeting was a flop only in a short-term sense, and declaring that
the truly big issue ahead is the looming vote in Congress on
establishing normal trade relations with China _ our end of the
bargain in getting the world's most populous nation into a system
that can guide its development to the world's benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that a more open world continues to work the same
economic wonders that have been occuring ever since the basic
system was erected after World War II. Tre are, and always have
been, adjustment problems and abuses, but grown-up people can and
must deal withtem, and their track record is more than good.
</P>
<P>
   The oter reality is that a more open trading world is a vital
security concern as well as the engine of economic growth. The
president was correct in noting that the world's hot spots after
the Cold War are distinguished by too little, not too much, contact
with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Theconventional political babble declared the WTO gathering a
disaster because Clinton went out there to cave in to labor and
environmental groups for the benefit of the Democratic Party and Al
Gore next year. That may work for entertainment on cable channels,
but it doesn't stand up to analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that the president went West to declare that any
new round of global trade negotiations has to include the topics of
labor and environmental standards on its agenda. The developing
nations resisted, and so the talks were inconclusive _ but only for
now.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks that is a new position for Clinton has been
asleep for the last eight years
</P>
<P>
   It was in October '92 at North Carolina State that he first
articulated his ``Yes, but'' philosophy, using the North American
Free Trade Agreement with Canada and Mexico as his takeoff point.
As negotiated by President Bush, NAFTA was unratifiable at that
point. By insisting on side agreements regarding labor and
environmental rules and by actually negotiating them in the early
months of his presidency, Clinton made ratification possible.
Applying these principles worldwide was a position first stated on
behalf of the administration in spring '94 by Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Then and now, Clinton's notion was hardly that wages in other
countries should be similar to ours or that a Third World factory
need to follow American EPA rules. Instead, he introduced the
principles that extreme violations of human rights and of the
environment should be addressed and that races to the bottom for
trading advantage should be avoided. Later, Clinton negotiated
deals that recognized countries' rights to guard against sudden,
massive surges in imports following market-opening deals. That's
not protectionist; it's common sense.
</P>
<P>
   As he noted, it has often happened that concepts initially
considered alien to trade become central with time. Few thought
there were ways to begin protecting intellectual property rights in
commerce, but it turned out there were.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the break-up for now of talks about starting a new round
of world-wide trade talks necessarily disastrous. As Clinton
pointed out, it took four years, from 1982-86, to get the Uruguay
round started, and it didn't conclude until 1996. The preliminaries
to Seattle started two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody needs something to happen. The United States wants
more access for farm and other products as well as formal talks on
labor and environmental standards; the Europeans and Japanese don't
like our tough antidumping laws; the Third World wants more access
for its farm and textile goods. The only way everybody can get some
satisfaction is to deal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the real issue before the United States is China, and
a push is on for a congressional vote on trade relations by the
spring. Economically, the issue should be a slam dunk. US companies
and farmers will have market cess beyond their recent dreams; and
China has agreed to tough rules and safeguards on import surges
that are similarly sound.
</P>
<P>
   But the hidden issue is security. Rejecting trade relations is
almost certain to mean the demise of China's relatively
outward-looking government. In its place will come the thugs who
have Tiananmen Square, anti-economic reform, anti-Americanism, and
truculence toward Taiwan on their resumes. Stability in Asia is at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's business allies need to cut him enough slack to
realize he is not caving to their labor and environmental
antagonists. And his friends on the left need to recognize that in
the politics of 2000, control of Congress will be decided in swing
districts where the president's approach is the popular one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
