<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7531 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-AUSTIN-CITYLIMITS-250     12-13 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-CITYLIMITS-2500(4TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTV, VH1 PREDECESSOR STILL GOING STRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Garth Brooks walks up the aisle, grabs his belly
contentedly _ this is clearly a man who loves to eat _ and laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you stretch video? Can you? I am stuffed,'' he says as
more and more heads swivel his way and the activity on the drafty
soundstage stops.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Garth is in the house _ full as a tick and an hour late,
but ready, at last, to work. It's just a shade before 2 p.m. on
Wednesday, Nov. 3, and the biggest country star in history has come
to the sixth-floor studio of the University of Texas' KLRU-TV to do
a sound check before the taping of the first show of the 25th year
of ``Austin City Limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the night is over, he will do a full career retrospective
_ all the hits with his regular group, and a brief set of Chris
Gaines material with a second band. The reward will be playing for
just 450 people and a mere $500 _ union scale.
</P>
<P>
   Makes no sense? Makes perfect sense. Brooks _ who has compared a
spot on ``ACL'' to playing in the World Series _ loves the small
venue, the enthusiasm of the Austin fans, the whole, well, vibe of
the joint and the staff and the program. And he knows that his
``ACL'' show will reach, when aired Feb. 5, ]a country full of
serious music fans.
</P>
<P>
   And he is only one of many who know this. It's easier to list
who hasn't played ``ACL'' than who has. Suffice to say that just
about any American musician of note, from darned near every genre,
has passed through these doors and stood on this stage. B.B. King.
Sheryl Crow. Joe Ely. The Dixie Chicks. Johnny Cash. Tom Waits.
Lyle Lovett. The Allman Brothers. The late, great Doug Sahm. Neil
Young. George Jones. Ruth Brown. Los Lobos. Merle. Waylon. Stevie
Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Videos on VH1 (when you can actually find them) may resemble
fashion shows, playa fantasies or soft porn; but here, all is right
with the world, and everybody, as Brooks will say before tearing
into ``We're Two of a Kind, Workin' on a Full House,'' ``is in it
for one thing, and that's the music.''
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, ``ACL'' hasn't changed a whit since 1974, when
Willie Nelson taped the pilot (which aired in 1975) before the
program even had a name.
</P>
<P>
   Today ``ACL'' is shown on 300 PBS stations nationwide, which
means it gets to 90 percent of all U.S. markets. Thus, on a
national scale, it provides a safe, homey, often very funky oasis
of lived-in blues, jazz, rock, Tejano, bluegrass, folk, country,
zydeco and soul in a world where it seems a new teen-age pop star
reaches supernova status every five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``ACL'' is celebrating its anniversary with ``Austin City
Limits: 25 Years of American Music,'' (Billboard Books, $35
hardcover) a handsome, photo-filled tome detailing the show's
history, and a companion video of the same name. But really the
celebration is just in the doing, the program's continuing ability
to bring some of the best names in roots music to this drafty
little studio just a stone's throw from the trendy shops and hordes
of roving UT students on Guadalupe Street.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why there's so little hubbub surrounding Garth's
taping. Despite his lateness and the fact that the show will start
an hour late due to the scheduling of another event on the sixth
floor, nobody panics, nobody frets or complains (well, not very
loudly, anyway); everybody just gets his or her job done.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of it all is Terry Lickona, a slim,
unassuming-looking man who has been producing the show since its
fourth season, in 1979. He's the first person Brooks shakes hands
with when he enters the studio, he's going to be one of the last
people out of the building after the show wraps around 11:30 p.m.,
and he is clearly in quiet control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of it is pretty simple _ the emphasis has always been on
straightforward presentations of music with no gimmicks,'' he says,
sitting in a corridor, the sound of Garth's drummer going a sound
test getting resounding from down the hall. ``My vision has always
been to have a broad cross section of American roots music _ people
with a unique voice _ but also as a sort of window on Austin to the
rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Lickona is obviously pleased that Brooks is here, as much as he
is still unhappy that Linda Ronstadt blew off an appearance on the
show just a few days earlier, despite the fact that she and Emmylou
Harris had played a show in Austin the night before the scheduled
``ACL'' date.
</P>
<P>
   The show had already been publicized in ``TV Guide,'' and
Lickona had reacted with highly uncharacteristic anger for such a
low-key, amiable man, at one point comparing Ronstadt with Jabba
the Hutt.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't want to focus on that now, other than to say he's
still honked off, but one could hardly fault him. The Ronstadt
no-show, like Brooks' appearance, highlights just how demanding his
job is. Lickona must nail down the acts for the 13 new shows that
air during an ``ACL'' season, which is February through May. As
taping is typically done between August and January, this means
that he usually sits down in late spring with a wish list of acts
he'd like to have for the next season.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is, he's having to balance numerous factors: Who is
touring? Who is coming through Texas, or who can be persuaded to
make a detour through Austin? How many male and female acts are
there? Newbies and superstars? Austin and Texas performers and
national acts? People who have appeared on the show before and
those who never have? Bluesmen and jazzers? Veteran rockers and old
R&AMP;B singers?
</P>
<P>
   Add to all this Lickona's own Holy Grail performers, which
presently include Dolly Parton, Bob Dylan and Bruce Springsteen.
Lickona has been working on snagging these folks (and Ronstadt and
Brooks) for about a decade.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases he's come close (Parton, he says, is a probable
for sometime in 2000) and others, such as the Boss, he admits, have
never given him any response. But he keeps on plugging; getting
somebody like Brooks to give one day of his life to ``ACL'' can
mean literally years of phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   But when it happens, it often happens fast: After five years of
work, ``ACL'' had 10 days' notice that Brooks would do the show.
This is the way ``ACL'' works: Shows are filmed based on artist
availability, not on a set show schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden we'll have a windfall,'' Lickona says. ``And
frankly, sometimes I prefer less lead time _ it means the date is
less likely to change. I never give up. Persistence pays off.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the historical thing that's interesting is that `ACL' is
something a whole generation of artists have grown up with. When
Alan Jackson was here, he made the comment that when he was growing
up, this was the closest thing he had to seeing a live show. Seeing
George Jones here made an impression on him because he couldn't, in
the little town in Georgia where he grew up.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Way back in 1974, though, there was not a whole lot of vision,
just a bunch of guys at KLRU who loved the progressive/outlaw
country music so in vogue in the city at that time and who wanted
to get it on television. The three were Bill Arhos, Paul Bosner and
Bruce Scafe, and when PBS started its common market in 1973, they
decided to try to get some Austin music broadcast around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote a proposal and got $13,000 to do a pilot,'' says
Arhos, who is still the show's executive producer. ``The Armadillo
World Headquarters was bringing in all these musicians, and we got
B.W. (Stevenson) and Willie. B.W. was actually bigger, at the time,
with `My Maria.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't draw as well in Austin; 600 people showed up for
his taping, while Willie drew 1,000. They went with Willie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had it in the can and didn't even have a name yet,'' Arhos
says. ``We went to a programming meeting in Washington, D.C., and I
took a break and sat in the park and ``Macon County Line'' was
playing across the street. It really had a good ring to it and I
told Paul, and he said, `Well, instead of ``Travis County Line''
how about ``Austin City Limits?'' ' ''
</P>
<P>
   The show was played during a PBS pledge drive and drew well;
Arhos had a selling point and got the nod to do the first season,
whose first show premiered Jan. 7, 1976. The first year it was all
Austin bands _ Alvin Crow, Steve Fromholz, Marcia Ball _ with a few
San Antonio ringers, such as Flaco Jimenez and Charlie Daniels,
thrown in for spice.
</P>
<P>
   But just as ``ACL'' was trying to make a name for itself, the
outlaw country scene was dwindling. The next few years, Arhos says,
were tough. There were times when he had to get on the radio and
beg people to attend the tapings _ during the show's third season,
only 300 people showed up to see Merle Travis.
</P>
<P>
   The show had several aces in the hole, though. One was the lack
of other outlets for musicians on television; these, remember, were
the days before MTV and VCRs, and save for one band doing two shows
per week on ``Saturday Night Live'' and a few others, there was no
way to see bands on the tube _ and certainly not guys like Willie,
John Prine, Jerry Jeff Walker or Gatemouth Brown. Another was UT
football coach Darrell Royal, who coaxed his old pal Merle Haggard
to play the show's third season.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
