<HEADLINE>
FOR QUEEN, PROOF IS IN THE PUDDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It is said that revenge is a dish best served cold, but
Queen Elizabeth II apparently has decided that the royal family's
answer to Mohamed Al Fayed and his conspiracy theories will be a
nice, hot pudding _ 1,411 of them, to be precise.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since August 1997, when his son Dodi died with Diana,
Princess of Wales, in a car crash in Paris, Fayed, the owner of
Harrods, London's most famous department store, has been claiming
that the couple was assassinated by British secret agents.
</P>
<P>
   Fayed insists that the British establishment could not stomach
the idea of Diana, mother to the heir of the throne, marrying Dodi
and bearing Muslim children.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the couple had only started dating, that there
were no wedding plans, and that a French judge has ruled that one
of Fayed's employees, the couple's chauffeur, killed the couple and
himself while driving drunk as he sp ay from paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
   Fayed has produced no evidence to support his claims. But last
month, wile testifying in a slander case brought against him by a
former politician whom he said he had paid for favors, Fayed
expounded on his conspiracy theory. He said that Prince Philip, the
queen's husband, was the brains behind the assassination plot.
</P>
<P>
   Even Prince Philip's detractors rose to his defense, though
their assertion that he was not bright enough to carry out such an
elaborate conspiracy was a classic case of damning with faint
praise.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers and serious commentators here have treated Fayed's
accusations with derision. Some say the Egyptian-born Fayed's
frustration over failing to get British citizenship is at the root
of his claims.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the royal family turns the other cheek when its
members are libeled or slandered. It is considered bad form to do
otherwise. But this time, the Buckingham Palace crowd did not get
mad, they got even. They hit Fayed where it really hurts: the cash
register.
</P>
<P>
   There is, it turns out, a price to be paid for peddling
conspiracy theories. In Fayed's case, that price is about $40,000
worth of traditional Christmas puddings that the queen buys as
presents for her household staff.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the queen has treated her staff to the Super Luxury
Christmas Pudding from Harrods, at about $30 a pop. But at the
urging of Andrew Farquharson, assistant to the Master of the Royal
Household, the queen recently tasted the matured Cristmas pudding
from Tesco, a British supermarket chain. The queen was suitably
impressed, and next week 1,411 of the Tesco puddings will be
distributedo the staff at the royal family's various residences.
</P>
<P>
   While no one would ever confuse the luxurious Harrods store in
Kensington with the ubiquitous Tesco supermarkets that are spread
across Britain, the Tesco pudding recipe has upscale roots. It was
prepared by Anton Edelmann, head chef at the Savoy Hotel, one of
London's finest.
</P>
<P>
   At Buckingham Palace, a spokeswoman denies that the change in
puddings has anything to do with Fayed's attacks on the royal
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't react to allegations,'' insisted Clare Sillars, the
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Poppycock, say other palace insiders, who are delighted by the
queen's ability to simultaneously snub Fayed and score points with
the masses who shop at Tesco. The Tesco 2-pound pudding costs less
than half of Harrods' 3-pounder. Since Diana's death, the queen has
been keen to make gestures that make the royal family more
accessible and relevant to the public.
</P>
<P>
   There are some at the palace who hope the royal family goes the
next step and strips Harrods of its royal warrant. Harrods is one
of about 800 businesses whose supplying of goods and services to
the royal family has earned them a royal warrant, a prestigious
seal of quality. The warrants are reviewed every five years, and
Harrods' is under scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   While turning the other cheek has its merits, and the quality of
Harrods' merchandise is undisputed, there are some at the palace
who believe it is outrageous for the royal household to patronize
the business of someone who routinely slanders the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the queen's genersy is not boundless. One man who worked
for the palace for half the year, walking the queen's dogs, willnot
be getting a pudding. He was caught plying the queen's corgis with
gin.
</P>
<P>
   But that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen is chief of The Globe's London bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
