<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7535 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-AUSTIN-CITYLIMITS-3rd     12-13 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-CITYLIMITS-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
AUSTIN, Texas: third season. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But it was Willie Nelson who really saved the day. His ``Red
Headed Stranger'' LP was slowly gaining ground, making him a
country legend and attracting attention among rock critics, and
thanks to his debut show and other appearance, he (and his
mystique) became associated with the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``After his show, `Stranger' came back on the charts and stayed
there 48 weeks,'' Arhos says. ``Pat Metheny's LP went from No. 12
to No. 2 on the jazz charts after he played. So we had a selling
point for musicians and booking agents. We didn't make people a
star, but if they had label support, it certainly did help people
become stars.''
</P>
<P>
   This is called momentum, and suddenly ``ACL'' had it. The fourth
season saw Tom Waits and the Neville Brothers stop in, and the
fifth season featured a songwriter's special, with Willie, Hank
Cochran, Ray Price and others. (The Austin-skyline backdrop,
incidentally, wasn't put in place until the seventh season, in
1982).
</P>
<P>
   And right from the first few seasons, ``ACL'' proved to be an
important vehicle for performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show allowed people to experience music on TV like they
never had before, with artists really relating to the audience,''
says Bobby Bridger, who appeared on the show's first and third
seasons. ``And they were concerned with good music, not who had a
record deal or who had been on the Carson show the night before.
The show solidified me in Texas, that I was part of the Texas music
scene and that I was there to stay. It meant the world to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Roundtable _ or theme _ shows have become one of ``ACL's''
signatures; it gives numerous performers exposure and continues to
focus on the show's folk/country roots.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the genre, though, there has been no question for some
time now that ``ACL'' gets results, from better bookings to a
better showing on the charts. For smaller labels, it is one of the
best ways _ if not the best _ of getting their music to a national
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the primary vehicle for promoting roots music _ that's
it,'' says Barry Poss, president of North Carolina's Sugar Hill
Records. Numerous Sugar Hill artists, from Guy Clark to the late
Townes Van Zandt to Doc Watson, have appeared on the show, and
every time one does, Poss says, there's a spike in interest and
sales.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, though, ``there's the prestige factor,'' says
Poss. ``It means an artist has arrived, that you're at the top of
your game. And the fact that it's so performance-driven means it's
the perfect artist vehicle. Basically, you have the premier club of
American roots music in your living room every week. There's
something magical about those performances.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin favorite Joe Ely, who has appeared on the show seven
times, calls it ``the David Letterman show of Texas. The first time
I did it (in 1980) I was scared to death _ it was a really big
deal. All my favorite songwriters had been on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first did it and went out on tour, I was surprised how
broad an audience it had in America. People always told me they had
seen me on the show, and they still do. It's a great scene _
there's no place like it for a good sound, a great stage. They do
everything right there.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Back in the studio, the drummer's endless whacking has,
mercifully, been replaced by Brooks and company doing ``Rodeo.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk of the past leads to talk of the present and the future.
Lickona says he wants, someday, to double the long-standing
schedule of 13 shows per year, ``and still do the Texas artists and
the Tom Waitses and the Leonard Cohens.''
</P>
<P>
   The show has lasted for so long for a number of reasons, not
least of which is that it's never had a celebrity host, which meant
its star was never hitched to any one person's career.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Lickona says, being on PBS frees the show of the pressure
to get ratings that it would have encountered on a commercial
network. It also means the finished product won't be broken up by
commercials, which detract from the flow of what's happening
onstage: On a good night, ``ACL'' can still feel like a peek into
the concert of your dreams.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Lickona says he feels little competition with VH1
because few ``ACL'' artists would ever be seen there anyway. The
show, he says, can both stand solidly outside music trends and be a
reflection of them.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
