r e BC-AUSTIN-CITYLIMITS-4th     12-13 0262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-CITYLIMITS-4thTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
AUSTIN, Texas: of them. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``In the first five years, we had four female artists and two of
them were Marcia Ball,'' he says, laughing. ``Last year, the
majority of our artists were women. That's a reflection of what's
happening, as is having the Dixie Chicks and some of the newer
bluegrass artists.''
</P>
<P>
   He also says that there are plans afoot to sell individual
previous episodes in 2000, although there's no hard-and-fast
information about release dates or specific shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep everything, so we have full performances of Roy
Orbison and Stevie Ray Vaughan, for example,'' he says. ``And we
may do compilations, such as the best of Merle Haggard or Lyle or
Willie. My ultimate dream is that some day people will be able to
download a song or an entire show.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's for later. Right now, there are camera angles to look
at and a thousand-and-one details before the crowd outside can be
let in, partake of the free beer in the studio lobby and get
settled for more than two hours of all that is Garth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I've met people and gotten to talking, and when I
told them I was from Austin, the first thing they asked was if I
knew about `Austin City Limits,' '' he says. ``That's the first
thing they think of when they think of Austin. It's like we're
stuck in a happy time warp _ we still do what we do almost exactly
the same way as we always have.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' he adds, ``I never have to negotiate money.''
</P>
