<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7541 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CANDLE-TIPS-TEX     12-13 0193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANDLE-TIPS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDLE SAFETY TIPS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-CANDLE-CONTROVERSY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Don't let a candle smoke. Keep it out of drafts and keep the
wick trimmed to about 1/4 inch or less. Keep matches and wick
debris out of the candle. Otherwise, you may be inhaling unburned
particles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Candles with all-cotton or all-paper wicks are the safest bet,
at least until the controversy is settled over metal-core wicks.
</P>
<P>
   _ To test wicks for heavy lead content: A major U.S. wick
manufacturer recommends snipping off a small piece of wick. Strip
it of wax and soot, then rub the small metal wire against a sheet
of white paper. If it's mostly lead content, it will leave dark
marks on the paper, says Jeb Head, president of wick maker Atkins &AMP;
Pearce, Covington, Ky. However, the test will not reveal trace
amounts of lead, which can be harmful, depending on how many are
burned and for how long.
</P>
<P>
   _ Large numbers of candles are best burned in the fireplace, so
emissions can escape.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
