<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONA-JOURNALBOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S FLASHY, IT'S SPLASHY, IT'S ALL VEGAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Perhaps only in Las Vegas could there be a theater
show featuring a 1.5 million-gallon water tank in which the cast
dives, swims, or dances on a hydraulically lifted floor that moves
up and down in pieces _ allowing dancing on one part and diving on
another _ while transporting fiberglass horses from their
underwater berths.
</P>
<P>
   It's an engineering spectacle raised to high art _ and it's the
theme of the mind-blowing, $70 million Cirque du Soleil show called
``O'' (adapted from the French word for water, ``eau'') now playing
at the 1,800-seat Bellagio Theatre, which was built expressly for
this production.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas has always lured gamblers to its casinos, but the new
game in town is to lure theatergoers looking for spectacular,
post-Broadway thrills.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Cirque du Soleil's ``O,'' which has sold out weeks in
advance and is considered the hottest ticket in Vegas (at $100 and
$90 each), is not your father's Broadway show. Nor is it something
that will ever tour _ hence its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shows like this are taking the place of the old feather shows
with the dancing girls,'' said Las Vegas Review-Journal
entertainment reporter Mike Weatherford. ``And you can't do these
on Broadway, because Broadway theaters are ancient. You can't put a
water pool into a Broadway theater.''
</P>
<P>
   No, you can't, certainly not a 1.5 million gallon pool, as
conceived by the Montreal-based Cirque du Soleil production team,
which worked for two years to build the Bellagio Theatre. It's
designed to be an avant-garde version of the Paris Opera House, but
with a pool that is 25 feet deep, measures 150 by 100 feet, and has
108 incandescent underwater lights.
</P>
<P>
   The ``O'' show, which is running indefinitely, features
synchronized swimmers and sultry alien creatures in waterproof
makeup, along with bungee jumpers, contortionists, trapeze acts,
and gymnasts who do aerial acrobatics on parallel bars attached to
a hoisted, stainless-steel boat. The boat is raised by a ceiling
carousel with four winches that can lift 1,000 pounds each.
</P>
<P>
   It's an awesome spectacle by any definition, enhanced by upwards
of 4 million watts of light. It even makes most stadium-sized rock
'n' roll productions look like amateur hours.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas has another Cirque du Soleil show, ``Mystere,''
playing at the Treasure Island Hotel. While ``O'' has been running
for just a year, ``Mystere,'' which has a more human element and
includes taiko drummers, has been going for six years and has drawn
3 million patrons.
</P>
<P>
   There are now seven different Cirque du Soleil productions
playing on four continents.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the Cirque shows the only mega-productions in this city
in the desert. The MGM Grand has ``EFX.'' And the new Mandalay Bay
has the Broadway-style ``Chicago.'' All have done a brisk business
and given Las Vegas a new cachet in the theater world.
</P>
<P>
   These long-running shows cost a fortune to produce, but are
based on the theory that the money will be made back once the
tourists start to roll in. And if they stop, there always seems to
be more money to try something new.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Las Vegas Hilton. Once known for booking Elvis Presley,
its entertainment center changed five years ago from a concert room
with chandeliers and tables to the ``Starlight Express,'' starring
performers on rollerskates racing around extended ramps to the
music of Andrew Lloyd Webber. Then last year it was changed back to
a concert venue, at enormous expense.
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure what will happen to the Bellagio Theatre once
``O'' finishes, but there's no need to worry about that at the
moment. Whether it's Mom and Dad coming to Vegas for the weekend,
or corporate expense-account types coming for a convention, all
seem eager to see the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the Bellagio one afternoon and I couldn't believe how
many people were standing in a waiting line to see if they could
pick up any canceled tickets for that evening's show,'' said
Weatherford. ``In Vegas, you hear a lot about how shows are sold
out, when really, the casinos always pull tickets so they can give
them away to gamblers and VIPs. But `O' seems to be seriously sold
out all of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And, really, is it any wonder? How many blackjack tables can a
visitor stand? How many slot machines? Vegas is trying to make sure
that if the city's core vices don't sell, then at least people can
get some unforgettable theater for their dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Take that, Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Morse covers pop music for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
