<SLUG> BC-INTERVIEW-SILBER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL BOSTON UNIVERSITY LEADER STICKS TO GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The poet Robert Penn Warren was once described as a man
who looked as if he was about to throw you off his land. The same
can still be said of John Silber.
</P>
<P>
   The former president of Boston University has not gone gently
into that good night. At 73, he remains all edge. Silber is still
the bantam who slashes at intellectual opposition the way
Confederate General Nathan Bedford Forrest savaged Union lines.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his failed gubernatorial bid in 1990, politics still
interests him _ he abhors life at the margins. And he focuses on
the issues central to any presidential campaign: education, foreign
policy, and the military.
</P>
<P>
   While he has three books to finish, the man chafes at the
thought of a contemplative pace. Chancellor of the institution
since he retired as BU president in 1996, Silber maintains two
shifts of secretaries to arrange his peripatetic schedule of
speeches and fund-raising across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Decades before John McCain's temper became an issue in this
presidential campaign, John Silber's dander was on parade. During
the long arc of his years in academe and politics, it shaped his
public persona, endearing him to some while appalling others. Love
Silber or hate him, Boston seemed a richer place when he was in the
fray.
</P>
<P>
   He is hard on himself and everyone around him, yet he claims to
have no idea why he scares friend and foe alike. For all of his
acute perceptions about others, he fails to recognize his own
shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I suppose because there are a lot of people who
don't ever want to be challenged with the truth,'' he offered as
explanation for the fear he generates. ``I think anybody who leads
people and has ideas is going to scare some people who don't want
to work or who don't have any aspirations. It goes with the
territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily. Ronald Reagan never scared people to achieve
what he wanted. Nor did Franklin Roosevelt. And one is hard-pressed
to name a university leader who has generated the tumult this man
has. But Silber is uncomfortable with routine, not anger, and it is
through this emotion that he finds comforting links with larger
figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Truman had one hell of a temper,'' he said from his
grand office overlooking the Charles River. ``They'd say, `Give 'em
hell Harry,' and Harry would say, `I don't give them hell. I just
tell the truth and they think it's hell.' That's the same thing I'd
say about myself on a smaller scale. And that's what I'd say about
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's problem isn't his temper. It's money. If he had
two-thirds the money that Bush has, I think he'd be doing very
well. Most people greatly admire the man's integrity. I wouldn't
have the gall to challenge the character of John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Silber scoffs at the notion that he smells fear in others and
exploits it mercilessly. ``That's a lot of crap,'' he said.
``That's the kind of cheap psychology you have to put up with
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   And he denies that he holds a grudge, even against Channel 5's
Natalie Jacobson for her interview with him in which he lost his
temper a few days before Election Day in 1990. ``If I had been a
more experienced candidate, she would have been in my house for 15
minutes, not two hours,'' he said. ``That's not Natalie's fault. I
don't blame Natalie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a hater,'' he maintained. ``I have too much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Silber has always considered himself a liberal and seems
flummoxed by the perception that he is a conservative. He addressed
this in an article about liberalism in May in the journal The New
Criterion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I face the issue baffled, and my bafflement is personal as
well as conceptual,'' he wrote. ``I have almost always thought of
myself as a liberal, yet in the marketplace of ideas I am almost
always called a conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Silber argues that his strong record on civil rights, his
opposition to the death penalty, and his defense of First Amendment
rights at the University of Texas and Boston University secure his
liberal credentials. He blames attacks from the left on its
penchant to eat its own. ``One is not liberal but an ideologue if
one joins the thought police to enforce political correctness in
society and especially in academe,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   One suspects that his vilification warms the contrarian in
Silber. He cannot operate in a vacuum. He adores the idea that BU
marches to its own drummer. ``What I am proudest of is that this is
a major university and it is probably the least politically correct
university in the country,'' he said in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Silber remains an unreconstructed meritocrat. He champions
access over outcome. Nothing sends him ballistic faster than what
he terms ideological demands for equality of achievement rather
than equality of opportunity. The former, he believes, diminish the
struggle he deems essential in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time you have equality of achievement is if you cut
everybody down to the lowest common denominator,'' he said. ``We'll
all get down to the level of Down syndrome. Is that what you want?
That's equality? Or maybe it has to be worse than that. Maybe it
has to be the equality of Alzheimer's.''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath this dyspeptic carapace lies a tender pride that often
has been punctured over the years, and a yearning for acceptance
that has never come to him. Boston has never embraced Silber or his
institution. He is oblivious to the possibility that he may have
had something to do with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this hostility to Boston University that is
unrelenting,'' he said. ``This is the thing that has disappointed
me most: the political hostility to a university that has played
the game and done more for this city relative to its strengths than
any other institution around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Silber's bile toward Harvard, and the ``cream-puff articles'' he
finds in The Boston Globe, is pungent. ``Harvard has done nothing
for the community compared to Boston University,'' he said. ``We
could itemize that very easily in terms of scholarships we give,
the services we provide, the work we do in Chelsea. You have these
sweetheart articles on Northeastern, on Boston College, on Harvard.
You don't get them on Boston University.''
</P>
<P>
   His bitterness has not clouded his bead on the Yankee culture
here and its differences from his native Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of energy and civic enterprise is far greater in
Texas than it is in Boston,'' he said. Exhibit A is the city's
travails over the years to fund a convention center. ``They would
have put that together in about two months in Houston, about four
months in Dallas and maybe six months in San Antonio,'' he said.
``This is like Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a Democrat, Silber has kind words for Republican and
fellow Texan George W. Bush, as well as for McCain. ``He's got
about as effective an educational reform movement going as anybody
in the country,'' Silber said about Bush.
</P>
<P>
   And he swats away criticism that Bush is unprepared to occupy
the Oval Office. ``He is so far better qualified than many of the
people who have held this office it's not funny,'' he said. Like
who? ``Well, Carter, for example. George W. Bush would be a much
better president than Carter. He's got the administrative sense of
what his role is. His role is that of keeping his eye on the whole
forest and not the individual trees.''
</P>
<P>
   On foreign policy, Silber expects Bush would learn on the job,
as do countless other presidents. ``When Harry Truman went in,
everyone said, `Harry Truman's totally incompetent _ a minor little
senator from Missouri. What the hell does he know about anything?'
''
</P>
<P>
   Silber offers perfunctory praise for Democrats Al Gore and Bill
Bradley. He is particularly guarded about Bradley, whose public
reserve is foreign to him. ``He's cool _ and they talk about the
importance of being cool _ in the sense of TV cool,'' he said in a
timbre that reflected a disdain for the concept. ``The guy doesn't
get angry. If having a temper is supposed to be a disadvantage to
McCain, then being cool has got to be an advantage for Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   John Silber doesn't like that one bit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1407EST &QL; 
