<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7555 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-13 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTENTION MUST BE PAID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We honor them when they die. The rest of the time, we hold up
their contracts, question their overtime pay, and grouse about
their soft duty in an era when serious fires are on the decline.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing false in our grief at the tragic deaths of Paul
Brotherton, Timothy Jackson, Jeremiah Lucey, James Lyons, Joseph
McGuirk, and Thomas Spencer, the six firefighters killed in the
conflagration in that vacant Worcester warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   There is something disingenuous, however, about all of or
rhetorical tributes to our firefighting forces, something strained
and nostalgic about the homage we are paying to this corps of
selfless public servants.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a week, we have been honoring the sacrifice of
these fallen firefighters, their parents, their widows, and their
17 fatherless children _ families who were willing to live every
day with the possibility of sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a week, we have been telling ourselves and our
children that these are the men we most admire, men who were
willing to do what most of us cannot even imagine ourselves doing:
enter a burning building with the full knowledge that they might
not come out alive.
</P>
<P>
   That's what we say, but what do we do?
</P>
<P>
   Did weall the firefighters in Brookline heroes last summer when
Local 950 of the International Association of Fire Fighters had to
throw up picket lines outside the Longwood Cricket Club, site of
the Davis Cup tennis tournament, and outside The Country Club, host
of the Ryder Cup golf tournament, to pressure the town to seriously
negotiate a new contract?
</P>
<P>
   Was that how we viewed Local 1795 of the same union when we let
the firefighters of Wellesley work without a contract, or a pay
raise, for four years running?
</P>
<P>
   We act toward our firefighters the same way we do toward our
police officers and our public school teachers, paying lip service
to their honorable professions while shortchanging them of
everything but our resentment on payday.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Commonwealth, throughout the nation, municipal fire
departments are in the midst of a major reassessment of their
public safety mission. In Boston, the number of fires has declined
by more than half in the last decade. Because of advances in fire
prevention and more stringent building codes, that trend can be
seen in small towns as well as big cities everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The transition to a broader role in their communities is not
without obstacles. In cities and towns across Massachusetts, turf
battles are raging between local fire departments and private
for-profit ambulance companies that compete to provide emergency
medical services. The Boston Fire Department has been struggling
all year to sort out its relationship with the paramedics of
Emergency Medical Services. The EMS handles most medical calls but
firefighters respond to more than 30,000 emergency medical cal
year.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the problems in the department are unique to Boston _
how many other big-city fire commissioners have firefighters
available to walk their golden retriever? _ but other issues
confront every firehouse in Massachusetts. How many uniformed women
and people of color marched into the Worcester Centrum last week as
full-fledged members of ``the brotherhood'' we heard so much about?
Of those who did, how many have any rank of note?
</P>
<P>
   The best managed fire departments are reinventing themselves,
scaling back firefighting units that are no longer needed and
recruiting firefighters as diverse as their communities. The
worst-managed _ Boston comes to mind _ are plagued by patronage
appointments, mired in the past, and resistant to change.
</P>
<P>
   Former state public safety secretary Kathleen M. O'Toole is
expected to issue a report any day now on management problems in
the Boston Fire Department. When she does, will we focus only on
union contracts, overtime pay, and light duty in one city? Will we
forget the heroism of Brotherton, Jackson, Lucey, Lyons, McGuirk,
and Spencer in another? Can we hold two conflicting images in our
minds simultaneously or must every firefighter be either a hero or
a goat?
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident that our children want to grow up to be Bill
Gates, not the town fire chief, or Officer Friendly or Mr. Chips.
Children watch what we do as carefully as they listen to what we
say. Maybe the memory of the stirring speeches of these last
difficult days in Worcester will alter their thinking. But when the
smoke has cleared and the funerals are behind us, will it have
altered ours?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNama's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
