<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7557 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-13 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING CONSPIRACY FINDING SHEDS WELCOME LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week a jury in Memphis found what the family of the
Reverend Martin Luther King Jr., as well as many other Americans,
have long been looking for _ a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   A Memphis jury hearing a lawsuit filed by King's family found
Wednesday that the civil rights leader was the victim of a murder
conspiracy, not of a lone assassin. The family's lawyer claimed
that the FBI, CIA, the Mafia and the military were involved.
</P>
<P>
   When the King family filed the wrongful death civil lawsuit
against Lloyd Jower, a retired businessman who said six years ago
he paid someone other than James Earl Ray to kill King, they were
not interested in a big settlement. They were asking for a token
payment, such as the $100 they were awarded last week.
</P>
<P>
   What the King family truly wanted, and may get as a result of
the verdict, is a new investigation into King's death _ one that
takes the conspiracy theory seriously. What the family also wants
is to have the history books re-written to reflect the truth of
what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Attorney General Janet Reno ordered a limited
investigation by the US Justice Department into two alleged
conspiraces in the King assassination. One involved Jowrs' claim of
paying someone else to kill King, and the other involved a
statement by former FBI agent Donald Wilson that he found papers in
Ray's car that may support a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   But the King family wants is a full and complete new
investigation that will prove what their lawyer outlined in his
conspiracy presentation at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Dexter King, the slain civil rights leader's son, talked
with Ray, who was serving a life term after being convicted of
killing King. Ray was quoted as saying, ``I had nothing to do with
shooting your father.'' And Dexter said ``I believe you and my
family believes you.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the Memphis jury of six blacks an six whites
did not address that issue of whether Ray was involved. Instead, it
backed the argument by the King family's attorney, William Pepper,
that more than one person was involved in the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper told jurors that Jowers was part of a vast conspiracy
that included agents of the federal government and the Mafia. he
argued that King was targeted for assassinatuon because of his
opposition to the Vietnam War and plans for a massive civil rights
march in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He further argued that there was a coverup after King's murder
in Memphis that involved the FBI, CIA, the media, Army intelligence
and state and city officials. Pepper, who wrote a book about his
conspiracy theory in the King case, told and apparently convinced
the jury to send a message ``to all of those in power that you
cannot get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The juy concluded that Jowers was part of that conspiracy and
ordered him to pay the family $100 in keeping with the family's
request of a token payment in the verdict. Expressing what many
Americans _ and most African-Americans _ believed, King's widow,
Coretta Scott King, said last month as a withness in the trial, ``I
always felt that somehow the truth would be known and I would live
to see it.'' No doubt that's how she felt after the verdict came
in.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are critics of the verdict who argue that the trial
didn't prove anything, nor changed their view that Ray was the lone
gunman in the slaying. One of them, Shelby County prosecutor John
Campbell, who investigated the assassination several years ago but
was not involved in the Jowers trial, said that Jowers' claim that
he paid someone other than Ray to kill King, and that there was a
conspiracy, has no merit.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he looked at this off and on for five years ``and
I've still seen nothing that would change my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Others argu that the trial was tilted in favor of a conspiracy
because Pepper was also the lawyer for Ray during his trial on
charges of killing King. Nonetheless, the jury's verdict did
accomplish one goal of the King family: to find a way to open a new
full investigation into King's death.
</P>
<P>
   And the trial also raised again the question of how Ray managed
to get a room across from the Lorraine Hotel, kill King with a
single shot, and escape from the neighborhood, and the city,
without being stopped and arrested.
</P>
<P>
   What one juror, David Murphy, said was what many other skeptics
felt about Ray being the lone gunman. Theassassination was far too
complex to have been carried out by one person. And that contention
becomes even stronger given that Ray, a prison escapee from
Missouri, could not have carried out the killing and go out of town
without a lot of help.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jowers' attorney, Lewis Garrison, said in last week's trial
that while the jury could conclude that King was the victim of a
conspiracy, Jowers at best played only a minor role.
</P>
<P>
   Jowers had owned a small restaurant, Jim's Grill, across the
street from the Lorraine Motel. Ray, under an assumed name, rented
a room in a rooming house above Jower's restaurant. Garrison may
have helped the jury reach its conclusion when he said at the trial
that it was hard to believe that the ``owner of a greasy spoon and
an escaped convict'' could by themselves have pulled off the King
assassination.'
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the verdict in Memphis last week raised the volume
in the call for a new investigation. It also raised conspiracy
advocates' call for an investigation into President Kennedy's
assassination, and the possibility that Lee Harvey Oswald did not
act alone, and may not even have been involved, in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that the trial occurred three decades after
King's death, and after Ray himself had died in prison, the volumes
of testimony that was examined by the jury does give the jurors
enough credibility to render a vedict in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   And since the verdict supported the arguements that there was a
conspiracy in the killing of King, the King family should have the
opportunity to see a new investigation _ one that would find the
truth, once and for all. After all, the King family, having endured
the personal pain of the assassination for more than 30 years, has
arned its right to bring closure to America's tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
