<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, Dec. 14,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-GOLAN _ JERUSALEM _ Early signals look like Israelis will
be prepared to give back the Golan Heights if that's what it takes
to make a real peace with Syria. Ehud Barak addressed the Israeli
parliament Monday before flying to Washington for his meeting with
the Syrian foreign minister Wednesday. His message: This generation
must pay the price in land for the next generation's peace. The
parliament is expected to endorse his trip to Washington with a
vote that could indicate the mood of the country. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GOP-DEBATE _ DES MOINES, Iowa _ Coverage of GOP debate from Des
Moines. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ Commentary on tonight's GOP debate in Des
Moines. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CITIES _ WASHINGTON _ WASHINGTON _ While most new homes are
still built in the suburbs, the 1990s has seen a trend toward more
housing construction in large cities, the Brookings Institution
reported Monday. (Dart, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   With CITIES-DATA _ Chart material.
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL-HEALTH _ WASHINGTON _ Surgeon General David Satcher
issues a report urging better treatment policies for mental
illnesses. (Nesmith, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Also moving in (l) Lifestyle category with sidebars.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO _ The Campaign for Tobacco Free Kids, an advocacy group
out of Washington, on Tuesday will release a report _ in
conjunction with the American Cancer Society and the American Heart
Association _ that criticizes Big Tobacco for shabby treatment of
tobacco growers. The unlikely alliance of public health interests
and tobacco growers was forged when the groups got together and got
money from Big Tobacco to compensate growers for decreased demand.
The report will detail what Big Tobacco has done to hurt domestic
growers, things like culitivating foreign markets and foreign
growers. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
