A7572 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-SOC-WOMEN-HNS &LR;      12-13 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCCER CHAMPS OPPOSE MOVING WOMEN'S WORLD CUP TO 2002
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) 
 By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Members of the U.S. Women's World Cup team
say they strongly oppose a plan by the sport's governing body to
move the next women's championship from 2003 to 2002, the same the
same year that the men's World Cup will be contested.
</P>
<P>
   To a woman, the members of the U.S. team think the proposal by
FIFA is a very bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insane,'' said veteran midfielder Julie Foudy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we proved at this year's Women's World Cup that it
could be a stand-alone event,'' longtime national team defender
Brandi Chastain said. ``We don't need to move it up.
</P>
<P>
   And I don't think we deserve to have to piggyback on the men's
World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. goalkeeper Tracy Ducar added, ``We don't want to take a
back stage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we don't need to,'' Chastain added.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain said the first she and her teammates heard about FIFA's
``nightmare'' decision ``was when we read about it in the
newspaper. We were all very surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   They then discussed it with Alan Rothenberg, the recently
departed president of the U.S. Soccer Federation and a major mover
in the sport globally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan said FIFA had never discussed it with him, either,''
Chastain said. ``He was as shocked as we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain pointed out that a huge problem with holding both the
men's and women's World Cups in the same year is that media
resources would be stretched so thin that something would probably
be sacrificed in print and electronic coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody (in the U.S. camp) is interested in fighting
this decision,'' Chastain said. ``I don't think it's set in
stone.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team has something else to be concerned about. It is
without a head coach as it nears the start of training for the 2000
Olympics. Tony DiCicco resigned as coach to spend more time with
his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us just want the decision on a new coach to be
made,'' Ducar said, ``so we can move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Ducar, who played in Briana Scurry's shadow in the Women's World
Cup last summer, was the star Saturday as the U.S. team beat the
World squad, 8-5, before a crowd of 10,842 at San Jose Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Ducar was perfect as the U.S. team built a 7-0 halftime lead,
before turning the net over to Scurry, who was under assault
throughout the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Then the U.S. women are off to Australia to begin getting ready
for the Olympics. Their immense triumph over China last summer
already seems a distant echo.
</P>
<P>
   But Chastain and her teammates are still enjoying the good
feelings while they can.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to sum up what the reception on their Victory Tour across
America has been like, Chastain didn't hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open arms,'' she said. ``Open arms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1432EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
