<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR Tuesday AMs  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Financial stories from The New York Times News Service for
newspapers of Tuesday, Dec. 14. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WALLSTREET-PAYDAYS (New York) _ Wall Street is overflowing with
holiday cheer: Investment banks have set aside $13 billion to pay
bonuses, up 20 percent from last year. Pay packages above $10
million are no longer rare. Yet among Wall Street professionals
whose incomes still astound the rest of America, the mood has
changed. One top trader bemoans the ``opportunity cost'' of
remaining a financier in the Internet age. By Joseph P. Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-AUTO-TRENDS (Paris) _ Europeans have been trading up their
midget Fiat Cinquecentos and Renault Twingos to sports utility
vehicles. While clogged cities, astronomical gas prices and a
tradition of compact cars would seem to work against the popularity
of SUV's, their sales surged 26 percent last year. The recent
growth has been fed by the introduction of new models that are
somewhat smaller than their American cousins and and hence better
attuned to European roads. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Daily market roundup. At midday, the Dow is
down 11 and the NASDAQ up 24.
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-ADCOL (Undated) _ Madison Avenue has supported efforts to
curb youth violence by creating public service advertising,
offering the commercials and print campaigns free to the media. One
advertising executive has taken a different approach. Alan Rambam
has started Seeking Harmony In Neighborhoods Everyday, or Shine, a
nonprofit organization dedicated to reducing youth violence. Using
a Web site as its hub, Shine attempts to provide teen-agers a voice
to express themselves through poetry and art about substantive
topics like racism, self-esteem and violence.
</P>
<P>
   COMPANIES (Undated) _ Company news.
</P>
<P>
   KEYRATES (Undated) _ Key interest rate numbers.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other financial
stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic,
Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News,
San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
