 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Tuesday, Dec.
14.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STONEAGE-FASHIONS (Undated) _ According to three
anthropologists, it is time to toss aside the hidebound cliches of
Paleolithic woman. Researchers have found evidence that the women
of the so-called upper Paleolithic era were far more accomplished,
economically powerful and sartorially gifted than previously
believed. By Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   With map-graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-POLIO (Undated) _ It is a turn of events that might have
delighted Dr. Jonas Salk: nearly 40 years after the United States
abandoned his injectable polio vaccine in favor of the oral version
created by his rival, Dr. Albert Sabin, the pendulum has swung back
the other way. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SLOAN-SKY-SURVEY (Undated) _ Using a technique akin to
overlaying thousands of faint X-ray images to create one sharp
picture, astronomers have discovered that typical galaxies may be
twice as large and contain twice as much mass as suggested by
previous measurements. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME (Undated) _ Biologists cannot yet synthesize a living
cell from the appropriate chemicals. But in the light of recent
research findings, the project has at least become conceivable. By
Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Science notes and news: Items on coral
around oil rigs, tiny tweezers and birth of giant planets. By Henry
Fountain.
</P>
<P>
