<P>
   OBIT-HELLER (New York) _ Joseph Heller, the novelist who made
the term ``Catch-22'' a synonym for the tripwires of life, died
Sunday night. He was 76. The Brooklyn-born author was a master of
satire and sardonic humor whose bleakly witty view of the human
condition was expressed in a series of novels that began in 1961
with the phenomenally successful ``Catch-22'' and continued through
``Something Happened'' (1974), ``Good as Gold'' (1979), ``God
Knows'' (1984) and ``Picture This'' (1988). By Herbert Mitgang.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH-FILMS (Paris) _ French filmmakers are angry with French
film critics, who seem to prefer American action movies to their
own. By Alan Riding.
</P>
