<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7618 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-MAMMOTHLAKES-SKISITE-     12-13 2258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAMMOTH </SLUG>
 LAKES-SKI SITE-LADN  
Local ski site undergoing a major tune-up 
Story and photos by Eric Noland, Travel Editor 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAMMOTH LAKES _ There was no grand design, no master plan when
Mammoth Mountain began developing as a ski area a half-century ago.
Rather, its growth mirrored that of many California communities of
the era _ a formless, hurried sprawl, with support enterprises and
improvements springing up here and there as needs arose.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Mammoth has always maintained such a
comfortable, old-boot appeal to Southern Californians: It felt a
lot like home.
</P>
<P>
   Commute up on a Friday night _ a five-hour haul that never felt
any more taxing than a 4 p.m. negotiation of the 10 Freeway. Check
into the Motel 6. Drive around the mountain to the main ski area in
the morning. Drive into the town of Mammoth Lakes for dinner,
perhaps at that place whose sign reads ``Mexican American Italian
Grill.'' Drive to Grumpy's for beer, popcorn and a game of pool.
Gas up. Drive to the motel; huddle around the wall heater. Drive
back to the ski area in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Mammoth is deep in the throes of change, however. Its teeming
prosperity of the mid-1980s _ when visits by winter-sports
enthusiasts reached 1.5 million annually _ began to subside when
the term ``amenity'' began to creep into the ski-resort vernacular.
</P>
<P>
   Customers began to drift away to places like Vail, Colo.; Deer
Valley, Utah; and Whistler, British Columbia; where they would
enthuse over live bands, heated sun decks, four-star cuisine and _
brace yourself here _ a village environment with something called a
pedestrian walkway.
</P>
<P>
   Mammoth is scurrying to catch up with industry trends, so much
so that the place might not even be recognizable in another four
years or so.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, ski area founder Dave McCoy and his family entered into
a partnership with Intrawest, the Vancouver-based developer
that!dlim!established the prototype for the upscale ski resort _
witness its work at Whistler-Blackcomb in British Columbia,
Tremblant in Quebec and Copper Mountain in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Mammoth is about halfway through a five-year, $130 million
upgrade project, and it has even more grandiose schemes on the
boards for the next decade. New for this winter are luxury condos,
another high-speed quad lift, completion of the gondola overhaul,
and a new gondola station that will include a kids' sports center.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the bulldozers are scheduled to converge on the corner
of Main Street and Minaret Road to break ground for ... yep, one of
those ritzy villages.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy, a spry 84, sat in his Main Lodge office recently and
reflected on the days in the 1930s when he rigged a portable rope
tow so he and his friends wouldn't have to sidestep up the face of
the hill. The first chairlift began making the climb on
Thanksgiving Day, 1955.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started, skiers were rough-and-tumble people,'' McCoy
said. ``They didn't care what they had to put up with to ski. Now
it's changed. Now they want hotels and fancy restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our competition isn't just other ski areas. It's the cruise
companies, Disney, Vegas, golf. People want recreation and
relaxation. We see the demand coming on us that we never saw in the
past _ to have amenities and make it easier than it was in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   In the '50s, no one could have predicted the explosive growth of
skiing and its latecoming cousin, snowboarding. And even if someone
had, it's unlikely that Mammoth could have delivered the elaborate
master planning that characterizes some of the West's most lauded
resorts.
</P>
<P>
   The region is a patchwork quilt of land held privately and by
the U.S. Forest Service, the Bureau of Land Management and other
government entities. ``We're kind of a doughnut,'' McCoy said, ``in
the Forest Service land.''
</P>
<P>
   So Mammoth is concentrating its development on four portals
strung out along the mountain's base _ Main Lodge, Canyon Lodge,
the Village at Mammoth and Juniper Springs _ in the hope that each
can eventually accommodate 5,000 people a day. The people might
even find so much to do at each location that they refrain from
spending a third of each day in their cars.
</P>
<P>
   The further hope is that winter-sports folk find the entire
resort so inviting that they plan extended ski vacations here,
supplementing that weekend stampede from Southern California.
Included on the upgrade list is Mammoth's podunk airport, with the
expectation of attracting a major carrier within two years. (An
American Airlines spokesman confirmed that talks have been
conducted between the parties and ``we are definitely interested in
the potential for service there in the future.'')
</P>
<P>
   At Mammoth, they speak grandly of a renaissance. ``We're about a
year away from sharing Mammoth with the whole world,'' said Rusty
Gregory, the ski area's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Such giddy optimism is to be expected when a major player like
Intrawest acquires 58 percent of your company and begins buying
land and launching redevelopment projects.
</P>
<P>
   Five or so years from now? Here's what Mammoth plans to offer:
</P>
<P>
   _The Village at Mammoth will reconfigure the gateway to the ski
area, the corner of Main and Minaret. Imagine an area of boutiques,
restaurants, clubs and top-end lodging, all interspersed with
winding walkways, undoubtedly in some alpine theme of gingerbread
roofs and cobblestones. (Minaret will be routed around it,
according to resort officials.) A gondola will climb through the
trees (and past residences) to Canyon Lodge, linking with a gondola
that ascends Lincoln Mountain. A back trail will enable guests to
ski to the very edge of the village.
</P>
<P>
   _Nearly 300 ski-in, ski-out condos will hug the slope at Juniper
Springs _ the base of what is now Chairs 15 and 24. The Juniper
Springs Lodge opened this summer with 174 upscale units. Just up
the slope, Sunstone Lodge and its 77 units are taking shape _ they
sold out in 36 minutes, according to Gregory _ and a 36-condo
property in the same region, Eagle Run, is to be built when it is
finished. All of these rooms will be serviced by a new gondola and
the Eagle Lodge base facility, both of which are scheduled for
construction next summer.
</P>
<P>
   _New facilities will improve the experience at Mammoth's primary
base area. The renovation of the gondola included construction of a
13,500-square-foot facility, Panorama Station, next to the resort's
distinctive woolly mammoth statue. Woollywood, a kids' sports
center, takes up the entire first floor. On its beginner slope,
Mammoth also spent this off-season replacing Chairs 11 and 27 with
a high-speed quad, the Discovery Chair.
</P>
<P>
   (This base area could do with more extensive improvements _ a
razing of those unsightly 1950s rectangles that pass for lodging,
to begin with _ but any makeover here will have to wait until the
other village is completed.)
</P>
<P>
   _For summer visitors, there will be golf. Intrawest opened
Sierra Star Golf Club, an 18-hole championship course just south of
the Village at Mammoth site, this year. There will be townhouses
along the fairways, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Mammoth can probably institute all of these improvements without
creating a pinch. This mountain resort is true to its name, with
3,500 skiable acres, a rise to 11,053 feet, 150 named trails and 28
lifts. It's one big mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of its recreation has always received high marks. A
Ski magazine readers' poll _ which ranked the resort 17th in
western North America _ returned raves for the quality and
challenge of Mammoth's terrain and for its lifts. However, in the
same survey, the region ranked far down the list in after-ski
diversions.
</P>
<P>
   Intrawest's track record suggests that this will change. This is
not a developer that cuts corners on creature comforts.
</P>
<P>
   For verification, check into the Juniper Springs Lodge this
winter (rooms $210 and up). Its design blends timbers and river
stones, borrowing unapologetically from the distinctive look of
Yosemite's Ahwahnee. Inside, there are many tasteful design
touches: generous use of mountain hemlock as wood accents, Arts and
Crafts lamps outside each room, Morris chairs in sitting areas,
black-and-white photos of the early days of Mammoth's skiing days,
simple baskets of pine cones.
</P>
<P>
   There are also numerous opportunities to unwind after a long day
of downhill exertions. Each room has a fireplace _ alas, they burn
gas, not wood, but the design is so efficient that even the lowest
setting will soon drive you onto the balcony. Rooms are also
equipped with full kitchens and VCRs.
</P>
<P>
   Two outdoor Jacuzzis afford views of the mountain crescent that
shelters the Mammoth Lakes Basin. The pool itself is heated to a
restorative 84 degrees. The pool deck is heated to hasten snow
melt. And there's even a fire pit out there; lodge general manager
Michael Bennett said the open blaze at Mammoth's Mill Cafe, which
opened last year at the base of the Stump Alley Express, was such a
hit that the lodge resolved to build one for its guests.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Mammoth could realize its goal of broadening its appeal
to upscale resort travelers _ people who stay several days,
actually get out of their cars and don't break out in a panicked
sweat when the wild mushroom strudel on the appetizer menu lists
for $12.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, however, Mammoth officials insist they don't
want to forsake their bread and butter: the Southern California
weekenders who tear up Highway 395 on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that bothers me is the price tag you have to
put on the sport to meet the needs of today's skier,'' said McCoy,
perhaps mindful that Mammoth's adult lift ticket inched up 6
percent to $52 this year.
</P>
<P>
   But marketing director Rob Perlman cited the Mammoth Club and
College Club _ reduced-rate programs for frequent visitors _ and
said, ``There will still be the ability for a family of five to
come here, stay in a condo, go to Vons, brown-bag it and have a
great time on the mountain. That's something we don't want to take
away from our loyal skiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``By contrast, there will be the ability for someone to come
here and enjoy the resort experience. It's tough to be all things
to all people, but I think we can have a variety of experiences and
(appeal to different) spending levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The upgrades that have occurred at Mammoth over the past two
years and the sweeping changes that are planned for the next few
years reflect a simple philosophy, really. ``It's a matter of
asking people what they want and giving it to them,'' said Gregory,
the company's CEO.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled slightly and added, ``It started with the rope tow.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO &QL; 
GETTING THERE: Mammoth Lakes is 310 miles north of Los Angeles via
I-5 and highways 14 and 395. It is 289 miles north of San
Bernardino via I-15 and Highway 395.
</P>
<P>
   COSTS: The adult daily lift ticket at Mammoth Mountain Ski Area
is $52. Prices are lower for teens, children and seniors. Multi-day
discounts and frequent-guest programs (Mammoth Club, College Club)
are also available.
</P>
<P>
   LODGING: Juniper Springs Lodge offers comfortable new condos at
the base of Chair Lifts 15 and 24. In winter, they are priced at
$210 for a studio, $310 for one-bedroom units, more for two- and
three-bedroom units. Reservations: (888) 311-1102. Information:
(760) 924-1102. For information on other accommodations overseen by
Mammoth Mountain Ski Area, (800) 228-4947; www.mammothlodging.com
on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   DINING: The Lakefront restaurant at the Tamarack Lodge continues
to offer the finest dining in the area. Chef Frederic Pierrel is a
wizard with mushrooms, and he garnishes main dishes (beef, lamb,
fish, even elk) with numerous fresh vegetables. Main courses are
priced from $17 to $25. Reservations recommended: (760) 934-3534.
Another nice option is Whiskey Creek, (760) 934-2555. Nevados has
also received high marks in guide books, (760) 934-4466. For
breakfast, it's difficult to beat the Stove, (760) 934-2821.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: For Mammoth Mountain Ski Area, call (800) 626-6684.
Web: www.mammothmountain.com.
</P>
<P>
