<SLUG> BC-CITIES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CITIES GAINING ON SUBURBS AS SITE FOR NEW HOMES
 &HT;    With CITIES-DATA.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While most homes are still built in the suburbs,
the 1990s has seen a trend toward more housing construction in
large cities, the Brookings Institution reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The study of new housing construction in America's 39 largest
metropolitan areas over the past 15 years showed that more than 80
percent of home building took place in suburbs. However, between
1991 and 1998, the number of new housing permits more than doubled
in large cities, growing at a faster rate than in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The growth was distributed unevenly. While new home building is
booming in cities such as Seattle, Orlando, Boston, Tampa and
Columbus, Ohio, it continues to stagnate in others, including
Baltimore, Detroit, Philadelphia and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, home building has rebounded from the recession of the
early 1990s and is reaching the levels of the economically roaring
mid-1980s, according to the Brookings study, which was conducted in
collaboration with Harvard's Joint Center for Housing Studies.
</P>
<P>
   The study shows that ``the trend, essentially for the century,
continues,'' said Nic Retsinas, director of the Harvard center.
``For at least 60 years, every generation of Americans has been
more suburban than the previous generation.''
</P>
<P>
   This outward growth has caused problems, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fears that uncontrolled suburban growth will degrade the
environment and engulf the neighboring countryside has made
'suburban sprawl' a national political issue,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1999, Vice President Al Gore announced a federal effort to
control sprawl by encouraging construction within central cities,''
the report said. ``The states of Maryland and Georgia recently
enacted measures aimed at containing urban growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The statistics show some movement in that direction. ``Large
cities' share of metropolitan permits rose from 14.6 percent in
1991 to 17.8 percent in 1998,'' the report said. However, the
percentage has not regained its level of 19.1 percent in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, about 82.2 percent of the housing permits were
issued in the suburbs in 1998, compared to 80.9 percent in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The report focuses on housing permits issued in four years:
1986, a boom year; 1991, a recession year; 1996, a recovery year,
and 1998, the most recent year for which statistics were available.
The researchers examined the 39 largest metropolitan areas, where
over half of all Americans live, focusing on the core city, the
suburbs and the combined area.
</P>
<P>
   The study grouped metropolitan areas by the geographic size of
the central cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorting the cities by their land area distinguishes between
giant cities, such as Phoenix and Dallas, which contain significant
areas of undeveloped land, and small, intensely developed
metropolises such as Hartford and Miami,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
