<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPLE ACTS GO A LONG WAY IN COMFORTING THE BEREAVED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo.)   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a drunken driver left Margaret Kramer a young widow with
four small children, her Minnesota friends and neighbors pitched in
with ready-to-eat meals, took turns mowing the lawn and
baby-sitting and a year or so later surprised her by painting the
outside of her house while she and the children were away on
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   When Frank Crewdson died, a friend said to his widow, Carole,
``Tell me what needs doing,'' then cleaned out her refrigerator,
which had been neglected for the three months her husband had been
ill. Other friends investigated cremation arrangements, brought
frozen packets of homemade soup and took her shopping. When life
quieted down a bit, friends took her out to lunch or to the movies
and even on a short trip to the West Coast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When someone dies, most people know to send the bereaved a card,
note or letter expressing their sorrow and sympathy, letting the
survivors know they are thought of and cared about during this
difficult time. If the note includes a fond memory of the person
who died, all the better.
</P>
<P>
   Sending a memorial gift, planting a tree, donating a book plate
_ all are common gestures always appreciated. Bargemusic, the
concert program in Brooklyn, was thrilled to receive more than
$6,000 in contributions sent in memory of Frank Crewdson, a
Brooklynite who was an accomplished amateur musician.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond writing, calling or sending a memorial gift, many
people feel a little helpless about how best to comfort a friend or
relative who is grieving.
</P>
<P>
   For those who can pay a bereavement call, food is nearly always
a welcome gift either for the grieving family or for the visitors.
If possible, use disposable containers that do not need to be
returned. Keep in mind dietary restrictions and label the packaged
meals as to contents and reheating directions.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Kelly, author of ``Don't Ask for the Dead Man's Golf Clubs:
Advice for Friends When Someone Dies'' ($12.95, Kelly
Communications, 888-401-6602 or 303-740-8278), suggests, ``If you
have expertise in an area where your friends need help, offer it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Crewdson's friends provided invaluable help after Frank
died. A jack-of-all-trades fixed a broken door knob and light
fixture.
</P>
<P>
   An architect developed a list of house repairs that were needed.
A lawyer advised her on legal matters and translated legal
gobbledygook for her. And a stockbroker helped her figure out her
finances and accompanied her when she met with an investment
counselor.
</P>
<P>
   Ask what needs to be done and, if the person is unable to
answer, look around to see how you might help, perhaps by doing
laundry, tending the garden, washing the car or taking it to the
shop for maintenance, cleaning the house, baby-sitting, caring for
pets, helping to start a memorial fund, chauffeuring the children
or taking them for a weekend. Or you might say: ``I can do this,
this, this and this. I would like to help you. Tell me what I can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   If family members are unavailable or unable to handle such
matters, you might offer to help dispose of the deceased person's
clothing and other personal effects. But don't do things without
asking.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kelly recounts the experience of Sam Newton of Englewood,
Colo., whose 7-year-old daughter died in an accident: ``Somebody,
we don't know who, came in right away and cleaned out our little
girl's room and took away all of her things. We really didn't want
that.''
</P>
<P>
   After the initial stages of grief have passed, issue invitations
_ to lunch or dinner, to a movie or concert, to visit a museum or
to take a ride in the country or a walk in the park.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be put off if your friend is unwilling to join you at
any given time. Ms. Kelly advises, ``Hang in there even if your
friend doesn't respond to your first idea, or second, or third.''
</P>
<P>
   Marta Felber, author of ``Grief Expressed: When a Mate Dies,''
(Life Words, 800-789-0100, $19.95), wrote that many people wanted
to keep her busy after the death of her husband, Joe.
</P>
<P>
   But what she wanted most was time alone to grieve. So at first
she said no to invitations to things like pot-luck suppers, bridge
club, a computer class, jazz concert, singles group and a lengthy
trip. (Such activities may be enjoyable after a while.)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Crewdson, too, often vacillated when an invitation was
issued. She said one of the most valued contributions from her
friends was their willingness to ``put up with my mood changes and
sudden changes of plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Holidays, anniversaries, birthdays and other such occasions are
especially difficult for people who are grieving.
</P>
<P>
   Try to make sure the bereaved are not alone at these times, but
be prepared for the possibility that they may refuse company or be
unwilling to celebrate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kelly warns, ``Don't offer to do something if you don't
intend to follow up.'' Joel Bershok of Littleton, Colo., who was 9
when his father died, told her that three men from a volunteer
organization had offered to help him.
</P>
<P>
   The boy poured out his heart to one man, who was never seen
again. ``He just wanted it on his resume,'' Bershok said. The
second volunteer moved away before he could do anything, and the
third never called after the initial contact.
</P>
<P>
   If you say you will invite a bereaved friend to dinner or to the
country for a weekend, do it. If you tell children you will take
them to a ball game or a show, do it. Those who are grieving do not
forget such promises. Failing to fulfill them just reinforces their
feelings of abandonment.
</P>
<P>
   Don't assume that your initial gesture of comfort following a
death is all that is needed by the bereaved. Most appreciated are
the friends who continue to make such gestures.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Felber was touched by a friend who called long-distance
every evening for the first 10 days she was alone. ``I'm just
calling to hear about your day and tuck you into bed,'' the friend
would say. Another would call to say she was going shopping, and
did Ms. Felber want to come along? Still another kept writing notes
long after everyone else had stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Felber said of these little but meaningful gestures, ``I
remember how good each contact felt and the comfort it brought.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, don't try to dictate how a person should be grieving or
for how long. Remember that each person grieves in his or her own
way and there is no time limit to grief. At first it often comes in
waves, perhaps days or weeks apart.
</P>
<P>
   But later it can resurface at any time, triggered by a memory,
by a happy event that the deceased is missing or even by a
beautiful day. Be patient with your friend, provide a shoulder for
the tears, and respect the times he or she wants to be alone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
