<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSISTENT PATHOGENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Can you reinfect yourself with an infectious disease from
which you are recovering, perhaps through exposure to residual
germs on your hands?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``There is no simple answer, but in general, it is very
unlikely,'' said Dr. John R. La Montagne, deputy director of the
National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases. In theory,
such reinfection is conceivable, he said, ``and one cannot say it
could never happen, but it would be very unusual and there are no
documented cases of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility would depend on the organism and how the
person's immune system responded to it, he explained. ``If a
pathogen is on the skin a long time, the person has probably
developed immunity to it,'' he said, ``and the same holds true for
an infection from which a person is recovering, so it is difficult
to `reinfect' yourself unless it is a totally different organism, a
new germ.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with two cases of flu in the same winter, La Montagne said,
the second case would probably involve an unrelated flu virus that
was present at the same time. The same patterns of disease would
appear, so it would be impossible for the patient to distinguish
between the two infections.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by mail to Question,
Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York,
N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to question(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of general interest will be answered in this column,
but requests for medical advice cannot be honored and unpublished
letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1634EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7638 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PERSONAL-TRAINERS     12-13 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PERSONAL-TRAINERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST GYM OFFERING: SHARED TRAINING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa., Canada)  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 7 and 8 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LINDA VILLAROSA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago Rick Ellis of Bordentown, N.J., wanted to hire a
personal trainer to build up what he called his ``98-pound-weakling
body.'' But Ellis, a 47-year-old kindergarten teacher, was not
about to go to the gym near his home and ask about one-on-one
workouts. ``It was much too intimidating,'' he said. (It didn't
help that the gym was called Powerhouse Fitness.)
</P>
<P>
   But once he tapped his reserves of self-esteem and got through
the gym doors, he eased into personal training with a class called
Be Fitt. The hourlong session, a hybrid of an exercise class and a
one-on-one session, consisted of six to 10 clients working out on a
circuit of free weights and machines with three trainers.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Ellis has reduced his body fat from 29 percent to 17
percent, can do squats with 200 pounds and is known as ``Pump Dog''
around Powerhouse. ``The group motivated me, but I was still able
to get the personal attention that I needed from the trainers,''
Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   These days, personal training is often not so personal. Around
the country, growing numbers of trainers are offering the benefits
of one-on-one fitness to small groups of people who would prefer to
sweat together. ``Personal training is on the rise, and there's a
correlation between that increase and the growth of people working
with trainers in groups,'' said Maeve McCaffrey, spokeswoman for
the International Health, Racquet and Sportsclub Association, a
trade organization in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The group estimates that in 1998, 4 million Americans used a
personal trainer. And from 1992 to 1998, the number of health clubs
offering personal training programs increased to 95 percent from 74
percent. ``People who work out in groups are generally those who
thought one-on-one was not possible,'' said Ms. McCaffrey. ``As
more clubs offer group training, the idea of working with a trainer
touches more people and makes it feel more accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   It can also be a bargain. At the Boston Athletic Club, for
example, a one-on-one session costs $50 an hour, while semiprivate
training with two people is $35 per person. Be Fitt at the
Powerhouse gym costs $69 for a package of six classes, while one
personal training session is $45 an hour. ``It's a huge cost
saver,'' said Christopher Carney, the gym owner.
</P>
<P>
   It can also be a time saver. Once a week, Sharyn Pak, a personal
trainer, guides Beth and Ron Clearfield through an hourlong mix of
cardiovascular, strength and toning exercises in their home in
Richboro, Pa. ``We don't have a lot of time to work out,'' said
Mrs. Clearfield, 34. ``My husband is an attorney, and he doesn't
get home until 7 at night. Plus we have three kids under 8. Working
out with Sharyn, we get the benefits of exercise and we get to do
something together.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, the Clearfields make their training sessions a
family affair. ``Sharyn has set up drills for all of us using the
swing set, trampoline or whatever,'' Mrs. Clearfield said. ``We've
all gone out with me pushing my girls in the double stroller and my
husband running down the street doing soccer drills with Sharyn.
Even our dog, Sheba, joined in.''
</P>
<P>
   Many small-group enthusiasts believe camaraderie is the most
important benefit. Mary McArthur and Marlene McDonald work out
together on Mondays and Thursdays with Bjorn Read-Friedmann at
Citadel Health Management Group, a fitness center in Vancouver,
British Columbia. On Thursdays, their friend Collette Storrow joins
them for 20 minutes of aerobic exercise, 20 minutes of weights and
some stretching and toning. ``It's more of a social event with two
or three people,'' said Ms. McArthur, a 61-year-old retired manager
of a medical lab. ``Plus, being with buddies makes you much more
committed to exercising.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all trainers are convinced that small-group workouts are a
good idea. ``There's a move afoot to encourage trainers to work
with more than one client at a time, but I think it's a mistake,''
said Mark Occhipinti, president of American Fitness Professionals
and Associates, a certification and education organization in Ship
Bottom, N.J. He discourages the 17,000 members of his group from
doing it. ``It's like going to a doctor who is seeing three or four
patients at the same time in the same room,'' he went on. ``You
can't pay as close attention with three or four as when you're
working one on one. You lose the one-on-one intimacy between client
and trainer.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep focused, some trainers will not work with more than two
people at a time, while others limit their groups to four. ``With
more than four, you can't give individualized attention,'' said
Read-Friedmann of Citadel.
</P>
<P>
   But even Ms. McArthur says she has never felt a lack of
attention during sessions with her two friends. ``When I've
exercised with a trainer alone, I admit I've worked harder,'' she
said. ``But even with three of us, I still feel like my workout is
designed just for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1635EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7639 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      12-13 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORAL'S STRANGE HOME  
 WORLD'S TINIEST TWEEZERS  
 BIRTH OF GIANT PLANETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Offshore oil rigs are not the most environmentally friendly of
places. As they take oil or gas from the depths, they also spew
chemicals, mud and other contaminants into the water.
</P>
<P>
   So it may come as a surprise to learn that some older rigs in
the North Sea have been found with colonies of an endangered coral
growing on their concrete structures some 100 to 200 feet below the
surface. It is the first appearance in the North Sea of the coral,
Lophelia pertusa, which has been considered by some scientists to
be susceptible to just the kind of contamination found around oil
rigs.
</P>
<P>
   The coral was also found on the Brent Spar, a huge cylindrical
oil storage and loading buoy that was taken out of service and
dismantled after 15 years in the North Sea. The Brent Spar had been
the focus of major environmental protests in Europe because the
original plan was to dump the buoy, with its six contaminated
storage tanks, in deep water in the North Atlantic. (Instead, it
was cut up into sections, cleaned, and used to help build a dock
extension in Norway.)
</P>
<P>
   The finding of the coral, reported by scientists with an
environmental consulting firm in the journal Nature, raises
questions about future dismantling of obsolete oil platforms. The
authors suggest that an option might be to leave some parts of the
structures _ huge concrete footings, for example _in place to
preserve existing colonies of the coral and help it gain more of a
foothold in the North Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Got a splinter? A really tiny splinter? Two Harvard scientists
may have just the thing to help: a pair of ``nanotweezers'' capable
of manipulating objects as small as one-50,000th of an inch wide.
</P>
<P>
   To make the tweezers, the scientists attached nanotubes _
cylindrical molecules of carbon atoms _ to metal electrodes
deposited on the end of a tapered glass pipette that had been
pulled to a very fine tip. The tweezing action was created by
applying a voltage to the electrodes, which caused the nanotube
arms (which themselves are only about one-500,000th of an inch in
diameter) to close on each other.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, describing their work in the journal Science,
used the tweezers to grab and pull clusters of polystyrene
molecules. These clusters are about the size of structures within
cells, so the tweezers may eventually find a use in manipulating
and modifying biological structures.
</P>
<P>
   Since electricity is used to make the tweezers work, they could
also be used to study the electrical properties of the tiny
structures and molecules they grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Astrophysicists have a pretty good idea about how the solar
system's two gas giants, Jupiter and Saturn, came to be. Rocky
cores formed out of the nebular disk of gas and dust swirling
around the young Sun, and then the cores attracted the helium and
hydrogen that form the bulk of the planets' masses.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to explaining how the solar system's other two
giant planets, Uranus and Neptune, were formed, this model has some
flaws. For one thing, the two planets are much farther from the
Sun, and the gas and dust in that part of the nebular disk was not
very dense. So formation of these planets' rocky cores would
probably have taken longer than the age of the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from Canada and the United States, using computer
modeling, have come up with an alternative explanation: that Uranus
and Neptune were formed in the vicinity of Jupiter and Saturn, and
were later kicked out of the neighborhood by the gravitational
interactions of these two planets.
</P>
<P>
   According to the theory, described in Nature, Uranus and Neptune
would have been left in highly chaotic, irregular orbits for a few
hundred thousand years until friction with the nebular disk
produced their final circular orbits.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1639EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7640 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-13 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENSE IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- It took President Clinton, spouting Third Way
nostrums that go beyond petty politics, to finally clear away the
tear gas and the polysyllabic fog from the bizarre goings-on inside
and outside the hall at the World Trad Organization's battle in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The president's contributions were two: explaining why the trade
meeting was a flop only in a short-term sense, and declaring that
the truly big issue ahead is the looming vote in Congress on
establishing normal trade relations with China _ our end of the
bargain in getting the world's most populous nation into a system
that can guide its development to the world's benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that a more open world continues to work the same
economic wonders that have been occuring ever since the basic
system was erected after World War II. There are, and always have
been, adjustment problems and abuses, but grown-up people can and
must deal with them, and their track record is more than good.
</P>
<P>
   The other reality is that a more open trading world is a vital
security concern as well as the engef economic growth. The
president was correct in noting that the world's hot spots after
the Cold War are distinguished by too little, not too much, contact
with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional political babble declared the WTO gathering a
disaster because Clinton went out there to cave in to labor and
environmental groups for the benefit of the Democratic Prty and Al
Gore next year. That may work for entertainment on cable channels,
but it doesn't stand up to analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that the president went West to declare that any
new round of global trade negotiations has to include the topics of
labor and environmental standards on its agenda. The developing
nations resisted, and so the talks were inconclusive _ but only for
now.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks that is a new position for Clinton has been
asleep for the last eight years
</P>
<P>
   It was in October '92 at North Carolina State that he first
articulated his ``Yes, but'' philosophy, using the North American
Free Trade Agreement with Canada and Mexico as his takeoff point.
As negotiated by President Bush, NAFTA was unratifiable at that
point. By insisting on side agreements regarding labor and
environmental rules and by actually negotiating them in the early
months of his presidency, Clinton made ratification possible.
Applying these principles worldwide was a position first stated on
behalf of the administration in spring '94 by Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Then and now, Clinton's notion was hardly that wages in other
countries should be similar to ours or that a Third World factory
need to follow American EPA rules. Instead, he introduced the
principles that extreme violations of human rights d of the
environment should be addressed and that races to the bottom for
trading advantage should be avoided. Later, Clinton negotiated
deals that recognized countries' rights to guard against sudden,
massive surges in imports following market-opening deals. That's
not protectionist; it's common sense.
</P>
<P>
   As he noted, it has often happened that concepts initially
considered alien to trade become central with time. Few thought
there were ways to begin protecting intellectual property rights in
commerce, but it turned out there were.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the break-up for now of talks about starting a new round
of world-wide trade talks necessarily disastrous. As Clinton
pointed out, it took four years, from 1982-86, to get the Uruguay
round started, and it didn't conclude until 1996. The preliminaries
to Seattle started two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody needs something to happen. The United States wants
more access for farm and other products as well as formal talks on
labor and environmental standards; the Europeans and Japanese don't
like our tough antidumping laws; the Third World wants more access
for its farm and textile goods. The only way everybody can get some
satisfaction is to deal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the real issue before the United States is China, and
a push is on for a congressional vote on trade relations by the
spring. Economically, the issue should be a slam dunk. US companies
and farmers will have market access beyond their recent dreams; and
China has agreed to tough rules and safeguards on import surges
that are similarly sound.
</P>
<P>
   But the hidden issue is security. Rejecng trade relations is
almost certain to mean the demise of China's relatively
outward-looking government. In its place will come the thugs who
have Tiananmen Square, anti-economic reform, anti-Americanism, and
truculence toward Taiwan on their resumes. Stability in Asia is at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's business allies need to cut him enough slack to
realize he is not caving to their labor and environmental
antagonists. And his friends on the left need to recognize that in
the politics of 2000, control of Congress will be decided in swing
districts where the president's approach is the popular one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
