<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOORAY FOR HARRY POTTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The three Harry Potter books, rightfully entrenched
at the top of the best-seller lists, are the most imaginative tales
to come along since Alice in Wonderland, fun to read for adults as
well as children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone,'' the first of what
will eventually be a series of seven books, will soon be made into
a movie. The current novels, which take little Harry through his
first three years at wizard school, have sold more than 17 million
copies worldwide, some 5 million in this country alone. Christmas
sales are expected to go through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   When their author, J. F. Rowling, toured America recently,
thousands of excited children and their parents stood in line for
hours to meet her. It is the publishing phenomenon of not just the
season, but the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   The whimsical books have made Rowling fabulously wealthy. More
power to her. She has created a classic young hero who will delight
future generations of children and grandchildren, as he is
delighting us. My husband and I, both writers who read a lot,
cannot remember when we have been as entertained by the printed
page as we were this past week devouring Harry's adventures. Who
says books are dead?
</P>
<P>
   As puzzling as the goings-on at Hogwarts School of Witchcraft
and Wizardry, however, is the outcry from stuffy muggle folk who
contend the books are an evil influence on young minds. Muggles, in
case you haven't read the books, are what Rowling's wizards call
ordinary people who cannot make magic and cannot understand it.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative parents, particularly fundamentalist Christians,
complain that making magic seem like fun promotes the occult and
weird religions like Wicca, which is a tiny sect that indulges in
pagan rites. Evangelist Pat Robertson is in a froth about Wiccans,
but nobody else seems to think they represent a threat to organized
religion or anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Galloping gargoyles, are these book-banners reading the same
elegant prose I just did?
</P>
<P>
   Harry is in the great tradition of our best fairy tales, which
can be scary and filled with danger but always have happy endings
in which good conquers evil. His early childhood as an unwanted
orphan abused by relatives is the Cinderella tale revisited. His
story is a struggle against rejection, hardship and evil forces,
with which we can all identify. The addition of humor and a little
magic dust provides the enchantment that attracts us and keeps us
rooting for him and thrilled when he wins.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter doesn't talk to a supernatural world. He doesn't
pray to ghosts. He and his friends rely on their own wit and
courage. He has odd powers denied muggles, but he is human, lives
in a defined wizard world and makes recognizably human mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   He forgets to wear his invisible cloak and exposes his presence
in places he is not supposed to be. His wand doesn't always work
right. He can't control the broomstick he is riding in a game in
the sky. He almost got picked for the least desirable Hogwarts
dormitory. He flubs the password, which is ``pig snout,'' to get to
his bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   An annoying but harmless ghost named Peeves haunts the student
quarters. The professors know how to turn themselves into animals,
but Harry hasn't learned that trick yet.
</P>
<P>
   A three-headed dog and mountain trolls lurk dangerously.
Centaurs roam the nearby forest. Owls deliver the mail, but Harry
never gets any from his guardians, who are glad to be rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   He takes classes in making mysterious potions, which he is not
very good at. The spine of his book on monsters has to be stroked
to make it stop growling and to open its pages. A rival classmate
bugs the dickens out of him.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the inventive antics, dollops of wisdom fall. The
school's headmaster, explaining a mirror that can show the past and
the future, advises his young charge, ``It does not do to dwell on
dreams and forget to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry is 11 when he goes to Hogwarts, where his murdered parents
had distinguished themselves as outstanding good-guy wizards.
Rowlings says she will take him to adulthood at 18 and then stop. I
sob at the very thought of losing Harry but eagerly anticipate his
next four years as a wizard-in-training.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow-minded, would-be book-banners are missing something
wonderfully special. I feel sorry for them _ and their children.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
