<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7642 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-FORBES-PROFILE-2TAKES     12-13 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-PROFILE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES' POLITICAL FORTUNE YET TO MATERIALIZE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNAPEE, N.H. _ Outside, moonlight glistened off a scenic
mountain lake, and a crispness in the Saturday night air hinted at
the winter that would soon grip this state, presidential candidates
and all.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the community lodge, magazine publisher Steve Forbes
stood before a fire, explaining to 150 people what was wrong with
the politicians in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sort of practice there what you might call the rooster
method of government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, roosters feel that they cock-a-doodle-do and the sun
rises each day. In Washington, they do the same thing. They make
the appropriate noises in the morning, the sun comes up, but unlike
the roosters, they send out press releases, proclaiming what
they've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, fortunately, doesn't have to make a living as a standup
comedian. But the heir to a multimillion-dollar family fortune
clearly is running for the Republican presidential nomination as a
Washington outsider, someone who repeatedly decries the
``disconnect'' that he sees between the political culture of the
nation's capital and the ``potential greatness'' of the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   He has ridiculed Washington politicians as roosters and worse in
countless speeches throughout the country at a time when
anti-Washington feelings are running high among voters.
</P>
<P>
   What is not so clear, however, is why he is running. Until his
surprise entry in the 1996 presidential race, Forbes had never
sought elective office. He created some excitement with his
flat-tax proposal, spent more than $30 million and won two minor
primaries before dropping out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, millions of dollars into his second campaign, he is
advocating tax reform again as well as changes in the health care
system and letting younger Americans invest their Social Security
dollars in their own personalized retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   And he has expanded his message to embrace the priorities of the
social and religious conservatives who helped derail him four years
ago. But he has been able to register only single digits in most
public opinion polls, widely trailing GOP front-runner George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Why does a successful businessman continue to spend so much time
and risk huge chunks of his personal fortune on a seemingly
impossible goal?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the business part of me is willing to take risks,
knowing that any great thing is a long shot,'' Forbes explained on
a recent bus ride through New Hampshire, where he has tirelessly
campaigned for the first-in-the-nation primary Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no sure thing. If you have faith in what you're
doing, you have an obligation to move on that faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the polls, Forbes' wealth makes him a significant factor
in the presidential race, if for no other reason than his deep
pockets and Bush's record fund raising helped narrow the Republican
field early.
</P>
<P>
   Casualties of the money game included former Vice President Dan
Quayle, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and former American
Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole, whose husband, Bob Dole,
accused Forbes of trying to buy the presidency during the 1996
primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers estimate that Forbes may spend as much as $50
million of his own money on this campaign, bringing his personal
outlay for two presidential campaigns to about $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to an analysis by The New York Times, Forbes'
expenditures are exceeding his cash flow, leading the newspaper to
conclude that the publisher has been quietly selling off some of
his shares in family-held Forbes Inc. to his siblings.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the newspaper reported, he has slipped from
being the company's majority shareholder to a major shareholder.
Forbes has declined to say how many shares he has sold or how much
he was paid for them, but he insists he's complied with campaign
finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Many people assume that Forbes is simply hoping that lightning
will strike, that Bush will stumble and that Forbes &UR;  &LR; will suddenly
become a major contender for the Republican prize.
</P>
<P>
   Some political experts believe, moreover, that Forbes is an
ideologue who views a presidential race as an opportunity, win or
lose, to promote ideas that he holds dear. No one, they point out,
gets more publicity than a serious presidential candidate. And any
presidential candidate worth a reported $400 million or more has to
be taken seriously, until the voters have had a chance to prove
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``A presidential candidate gets ink and air time that no
foundation can match,'' said University of Texas at Austin
government professor Bruce Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Some also believe that Forbes may be in the hunt for the long
haul, that he may be building a political base for a third shot at
the White House. At 52, he is young enough, they point out, to run
for president one or two more times.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said he jumped into the presidential race four years ago
and is running a second time because no other Republican candidates
were committed to building upon the legacy of Ronald Reagan, one of
his political heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not one was offering new ideas to take money and power out of
the hands of the Washington politicians and truly put it back in
the hands of the American people,'' he wrote in his book, ``A New
Birth of Freedom,'' published earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The book title is taken from the Gettysburg address of another
Forbes hero, Abraham Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Some people speculate that Malcolm Stevenson Forbes Jr. is
running for president as a symptom of a public midlife change, much
as his late father did before him.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Stevenson Forbes Sr., a tireless promoter of the upscale
business magazine that bears the family name, was in his 50s before
he flamboyantly broadened his interests to include motorcycling,
hot-air ballooning and Elizabeth Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Steve, his decidedly &UR;  &LR; staid eldest son, has taken up running for
president as a different kind of hobby, according to this theory.
</P>
<P>
   But it should be noted that Forbes Sr. also was stricken with
the political bug, although at a younger age than his son. The
elder Forbes was a state senator for eight years in New Jersey and
lost two races for governor of that state in the 1950s, when he was
in his 30s.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Family Business magazine shortly after his
father's death in 1990, Forbes said that his father, at one point,
also wanted to be president of the United States but turned his
energies to the magazine when he realized his political career
wasn't going to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes was only 9 when his father lost his second gubernatorial
race, buried in a landslide by a popular Democratic incumbent, but
some of the memories stuck.
</P>
<P>
   ``You remember the picnics. You remember putting up posters and
bumper stickers and handing out literature and things like that,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I was disappointed he didn't win the general
election, but the campaign was exciting and fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes became president and editor in chief of Forbes magazine
after his father's death and, from that forum, dabbled on the edges
of politics.
</P>
<P>
   President Reagan appointed him to the board that oversaw Radio
Free Europe and Radio Liberty, key weapons in America's Cold War
arsenal. President Bush reappointed him to that post, and Forbes
helped Jack Kemp and Bill Bennett, two members of Reagan's Cabinet,
organize a conservative grass-roots organization called Empower
America.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990 interview with Family Business, however, Forbes
denied that he had political ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I grew up with a politician, I saw that to be serious
about politics, you give up a lot of your privacy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is your boss, every holiday you're working the
events. The phone is always ringing.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked in the same interview if he wanted to be president, Forbes
replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to give it to me, sure, I'll take it. But how many
make it to the Holy Grail?''
</P>
<P>
   But after Kemp and other potential Republican candidates to his
liking decided to sit out the 1996 primaries, Forbes decided to
jump in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jude Wanniski, a supply-side economist and former Wall Street
Journal editorial writer, claims credit for nudging Forbes into
presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motivation came from a good friend of his _ me _ telling
him the roster (of candidates) was incredibly thin,'' Wanniski
said.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote a long memorandum to Forbes, proposing a presidential
race for the publisher four years ago, after Kemp had ruled himself
out. Wanniski and Forbes, who lived a few miles from each other in
New Jersey, had been longtime friends and had often discussed
politics and economics.
</P>
<P>
   But they had a falling-out after Forbes became a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes lost in 1996 because ``he rejected my advice'' and
listened to the wrong people, Wanniski said.
</P>
<P>
   She isn't involved in Forbes' current campaign but has advised
Quayle and Pat Buchanan, who recently jumped from the GOP to seek
the Reform Party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his future may hold, Forbes' interest in politics and
economics began in his childhood in New Jersey, where he still
lives.
</P>
<P>
   He told one interviewer several years ago that he started
reading The New York Times and following the stock market when he
was 12 or 13.
</P>
<P>
   As a son of privilege, Forbes at a young age met a number of
famous and influential people from the worlds of business and
politics.
</P>
<P>
   He and his four siblings helped their father entertain corporate
chiefs during lunch and dinner cruises on the magazine's yacht, the
Highlander.
</P>
<P>
   One of his childhood friends was Christine Todd, now New Jersey
Gov. Christine Todd Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Forbes and Whitman don't always see eye to eye on
politics. Forbes advised Whitman during her first gubernatorial
race in 1993, but they have drifted apart on social issues. Whitman
favors abortion rights, while Forbes, eager to win the support of
social conservatives, has made opposition to abortion an important
part of his current campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just last month, Forbes held a rally in Trenton to support
a bill before the New Jersey Legislature that would require
students to recite a passage from the Declaration of Independence
at the start of each school day. Whitman opposes the bill because
she believes that it has marginal educational value.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman declined to comment on Forbes' presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``She believes that he is a very bright man, but there are some
issues on which they differ,'' the governor's spokeswoman, Jane
O'Connor, said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes was only 17 when he wrote his first article for the
family's magazine. The contribution, which his father carried as
part of his ``Fact and Comment'' column, was a report from the 1964
Republican National Convention in San Francisco, which nominated
Barry Goldwater for an impossible challenge to President Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all the young people around my age were Goldwater
supporters. And they weren't kooks,'' the young Forbes wrote,
without revealing his own preference in candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of them had at least one conspicuous button and when
it came to noisemaking, they were tops.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also published his observations of the 1968
conventions, including what he called the ``fierce Democratic melee
in Chicago.'' Forbes, then a 21-year-old Princeton student, called
legendary Chicago Mayor Richard Daley, who unleashed the city's
police on young anti-war protesters, a ``unique antique.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Princeton with a history degree in 1970
and serving a five-month active duty commitment to the New Jersey
National Guard, he became a fact-checker and researcher in the
magazine's editorial department and quickly worked his way up the
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not the kind of guy who said, `Let's go get a beer.' He
was very awkward socially,'' recalled a former writer for the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The former staffer said he finds Forbes' presidential ambitions
``befuddling.'' But, he added, ``He was always interested in
economic issues, and the stage for it is politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who soon began getting regular column space of his own,
developed a reputation as an able prognosticator of presidential
election results and economic trends. By 1989, he had been a
four-time winner of the prestigious Crystal Owl award, presented
annually to the reporter making the most accurate economic
predictions for the upcoming year.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is not actively involved in running the magazine
during his presidential race, he retains the title of president and
editor in chief and still regularly writes a column.
</P>
<P>
   In one recent column, he criticized the ``inconsistent,
floundering regime'' of German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, and
endorsed an instant video replay as a way to resolve controversial
calls by umpires during Major League Baseball games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he (Forbes) has a very good mind. He just wasn't
blessed with Malcolm's (his father's) gift of gab,'' the former
Forbes staffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has been characterized as stiff and owlish, but his
speaking style on the campaign trail is hardly any worse than
Bush's, Al Gore's or Bill Bradley's. None of the leading contenders
of either major party is golden-throated.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher's one-liners, most of which he says he writes
himself, are generally well-received. ``It makes you wonder what
global warming can do to a man's mind,'' is one of his favorite
digs at Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' gestures during his speeches often are mechanical, but
that doesn't seem to bother supporters like April Carter, 42, an
aircraft engine factory worker from Chichester, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   ``His heart is huge. I just sense it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole, the 1996 Republican presidential nominee, however, may
not agree. Forbes' negative TV ads against Dole during the primary
season are believed to have contributed to the nominee's general
election defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Now, trying to position himself as a viable, conservative
alternative to Bush for Republican voters in 2000, Forbes has
recently gone on the offensive against the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes recently began running a TV spot in New Hampshire,
blasting Bush for suggesting that the Social Security retirement
age could be raised to bolster the troubled system. And he was
quick to criticize Bush's proposal to cut income taxes, rather than
overhaul the system.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes promotes his own tax proposal _ which would impose a 17
percent flat tax on all income above $36,000 for a family of four,
abolish capital gains taxes and eliminate many loopholes and
deductions _ as a boon for middle- and low-income Americans. What
he doesn't often say, however, is that his plan also could be worth
untold millions in tax savings to his own company.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is often joined on the campaign trail by his wife, the
former Sabina Beekman, a minister's daughter whom he met at a New
York debutante party during his senior year at Princeton. They have
five daughters.
</P>
<P>
   No one except Dwight Eisenhower has been elected president in
modern times without first holding a lower elective office. But
Eisenhower was a war hero.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes insists he is not discouraged by history _ or his low
poll numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more real-world executive experience than all of these
other candidates put together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that he has traveled the world extensively and
visited with many foreign leaders as a businessman, journalist and
chairman of the Radio Free Europe board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll match my knowledge of the world with anyone else,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
