<HEADER>
A7646 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BUFFETT-CD14-COX     12-13 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUFFETT-CD14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hospital employees' Parrothead stunt puts fun in fund-raising
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The story of how six physical therapists at Miami
Valley Hospital filled charitable Christmas baskets by dressing up
in food costumes is not so obvious as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't actually fit in the baskets.
</P>
<P>
   It was last summer that the PTs and three friends dressed up as
a picnic meal for their annual trip to see Jimmy Buffett in
Cincinnati. The previous year, they had talked about ``doing
something a little different,'' as Dona Dersarkisian puts it.
Dressing up as the entree and condiments in Buffett's song,
``Cheeseburger in Paradise,'' seemed different enough, so they
spent 20 to 30 hours making costumes for their field trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we were listening to Buffett music as we were making
them,'' Lisa Holscher says.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . I like mine with lettuce and tomato,
</P>
<P>
   Heinz 57 and french-fried potatoes,
</P>
<P>
   Big kosher pickle and a cold draft beer.
</P>
<P>
   Well, good God Almighty, which way do I steer
</P>
<P>
   For my cheeseburger in paradise?''
</P>
<P>
   The walking buffet _ Buffett? _ table caught the eyes of some
photographers in Cincinnati, naturally, and one of them happened to
work for Rolling Stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured we might be in a picture in the magazine,'' said
Holscher, the french fries. ``But the photographer said he showed
the picture to Buffett later in Boston, and Buffett loved the
picture. So he sold it to Buffett.''
</P>
<P>
   The photographer eventually called one of the therapists'
friends to say the picture would be on the cardboard insert for
Buffett's new CD, ``Buffett Live Tuesdays, Thursdays, Saturdays.''
The live collection of classics and new songs came out last month.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to understand at this point in the story that
Miami Valley Hospital, like many companies, gives holiday baskets
to needy families and nursing homes each December. Each department
takes responsibility for raising the money to fill a family's
basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they get a little creative and competitive,''
spokeswoman Julie McEwan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to do something other than just bake sales,'' said
Heather Koch, the lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   They decided to put on their costumes, go to the hospital
cafeteria and autograph their CD pictures for anyone making a
donation. ``Usually it was $2 to $5,'' said Scott Johnson, the
cheeseburger patty. They've signed more than 100 and also raised
more than $150 by raffling off a basket full of Parrothead
paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to Christmas time, the more creative the idea,
the more funds that are raised,'' said Dersarkisian, the kosher
pickle. ``We've probably been the zaniest fund-raiser so far. We've
certainly gotten our share of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The PTs and occupational therapists together are assembling
baskets for two families, one of which the PTs already know. The
family spent a lot of time in therapy after a serious accident
earlier in the year. Families are nominated by hospital employees
and volunteers and then chosen by the holiday basket committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get information about the families and go shopping,''
Dersarkisian said. ``We get them dietary supplies that wouldn't be
covered by food stamps, toys, games, clothes, coats, whatever their
needs happen to be.'' For one of the families this year, that means
kitchen supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital will kick in a ham and some bread, milk and fruit
for each of the 145 baskets, and the departments will deliver their
baskets on Thursday. ``It's nice to see their faces,'' Holscher
said.
</P>
<P>
   The therapists are wondering how they'll follow all this next
year. Fruitcakes? Margarita fixings? ``We're going to have to do
something,'' Holscher said. ``We want to see if we can make it up
on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To contribute to Miami Valley Hospital's holiday basket
committee, contact Patricia Tremblay at (937) 208-2368 or Lisa
Holscher of the cheeseburger and therapy department at (937)
208-3925.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
