<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7647 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-POLIO-ART-NYT &LR;      12-13 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-POLIO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALK, SABIN AND A COMPLEX QUEST TO CONQUER POLIO
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Georges as first name for Brown professor cq.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a turn of events that might have delighted Dr. Jonas Salk.
Nearly 40 years after the United States abandoned his injectable
polio vaccine in favor of the oral version created by his rival,
Dr. Albert Sabin, the pendulum has swung back. Starting in 2000,
the government has declared, the Sabin vaccine will be dropped and
replaced by a series of old-fashioned polio shots that will use a
stronger version of what is essentially the Salk vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   To the public, Salk, who died in 1995, has always been the hero
who conquered polio. Even though his vaccine, licensed in 1955, was
replaced by the Sabin vaccine starting in 1961, it was the Salk
version that halted the frightening epidemics that had gripped the
nation in the 1930s,  &UR; ' &LR; 40s and early  &UR; ' &LR; 50s, killing thousands of
children and leaving many more with lasting paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   The two men clashed personally as well as scientifically, and
Sabin, who died in 1993, never relented in his bitterness toward
Salk. So it is tempting to regard the resurgence of the polio shot
as Jonas Salk's last hurrah, the final proof that he was right
after all.
</P>
<P>
   But the picture is more complicated than that. Researchers say
that both vaccines played important roles, and that it was the
resounding success of the Sabin vaccine in much of the world that
made it possible for the United States to return to the Salk
variety. And that change means that medicine is coming close to a
goal that would delight the fathers of both vaccines: the worldwide
eradication of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the verge of global elimination of polio,'' said Dr.
Georges Peter, a professor of pediatrics at Brown University and
chairman of the national vaccine advisory committee. ``It's one of
the great triumphs of 20th-century medicine. We hope that in the
next 5 to 10 years, polio vaccine will no longer be necessary,
similar to the situation with smallpox.'' But as long as it is
still possible to catch polio somewhere in the world, countries
will continue to vaccinate.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization resolved in 1988 to wipe out polio
by the end of 2000, and officials say it is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have what you guys call a fighting chance to do it
by the end of next year,'' said Dr. Rudi Tangermann, a medical
officer at the health organization's Expanding Immunization Program
in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Governments are already working together to take inventories of
laboratories that have stocks of the polio virus being used for
research, with the goal of making sure that they are either
destroyed or moved to a few secure containment sites like the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta. Although
bioterrorism becomes possible in an unvaccinated world, researchers
say the polio virus is not an ideal weapon: It is neither deadly
enough nor easily enough transmitted to bring about large-scale
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization estimates that there were just
5,000 cases of polio this year, a drop of more than 90 percent
since 1989. The disease has already been eliminated from many parts
of the world. The Western Hemisphere, for instance, was declared
polio-free in 1994. In the United States, isolated cases occurred
in 1986 and in 1993, but they were brought in from other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Polio, however, is still present in parts of Africa, southern
Asia and the Indian subcontinent. (The number of infected people,
who can spread the disease, is higher than the 5,000 known cases of
polio because only a small percentage of those who become infected
actually get sick.)
</P>
<P>
   The elimination strategy consists of broad and repeated
immunization campaigns and intense surveillance to make sure the
disease is gone. Scientists say it is safe to assume that it has
been eradicated when no more cases occur: the virus needs human
hosts _ there is no known animal host _ and once they have all been
immunized, it has no place left to go.
</P>
<P>
   These immunization drives rely on the Sabin vaccine, which is
given orally and uses a live but weakened form of the polio virus
to stimulate immunity. (The Salk vaccine uses killed virus.) It is
much easier to give an oral vaccine than a shot, but that is not
the only reason the Sabin vaccine is favored in areas where polio
still exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``In endemic areas, the oral vaccine is the vaccine of choice,''
said Dr. Rebecca Prevots, an epidemiologist in the National
Immunization Program at the CDC. ``It contains live virus, and it
can spread from a vaccinated person to an unvaccinated person, and
it will confer some immunity to the unvaccinated person. You can
immunize more people than you're actually vaccinating. You get more
bang for the buck.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally important, Prevots said, is that the oral vaccine
creates strong immunity in the intestine, whereas the Salk vaccine
has a weaker effect. Intestinal immunity is of great value because
the polio virus enters the body through the digestive tract and is
shed in stools, which can infect others. If people given the Sabin
vaccine are exposed to polio, the immunity in their gut will stop
them from excreting the live virus. But those given the Salk
vaccine, even though they do not get sick themselves if exposed to
polio, can still shed the virus and pass the disease to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oral vaccine raises intestinal immunity in the whole
population, and it can stop transmission of the wild polio virus
quickly,'' Prevots said.
</P>
<P>
   Once polio has been eliminated, as it has in the United States,
the oral vaccine is no longer needed, and its risks actually begin
to outweigh its benefits. Because it contains live virus, it
carries a small but real risk of causing polio in the child given
the vaccine or an adult exposed to that child: about eight cases a
year in the United States, one for every 2.4 million doses, have
been caused by the vaccine. The Salk vaccine carries no such risk.
</P>
<P>
   It is that risk that has prompted the United States to switch
back to the Salk vaccine, a move that researchers say could have
taken place several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major reason for the reluctance to withdraw the oral
vaccine sooner has been concern about the global village in which
we live,'' said Peter, the chairman of the vaccine advisory panel.
``We're just a few hours by plane from countries where polio is
still circulating.''
</P>
<P>
   If the immunization efforts succeed in eliminating polio by the
end of 2000, researchers say it will take several more years of
careful surveillance to make sure that the last few hot spots are
truly clear of the disease. If they are, the world may be certified
polio-free by 2005, and if that occurs, vaccination may end by
2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that happens, as it did for smallpox, we're going to
start saving a lot of money,'' said Tangermann, of the World Health
Organization. ``The savings will be in the billions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
