<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7652 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-PLAYOFFS     12-13 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-PLAYOFFS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forecast gets gloomier after Dolphins lose in Meadowlands
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Legend has it that Jimmy Hoffa is buried
in one end zone of Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he might have gotten some company.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Dolphins' 34th season isn't dead. Not yet. But a few
weeks from now, Dolphins fans may look at this once-promising year
and say it is planted in the east end zone of the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Keyshawn Johnson caught two fourth-quarter
touchdown passes from Ray Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   That is where safety Otis Stoutmire celebrated after returning a
Dan Marino interception 67 yards.
</P>
<P>
   That is where the Dolphins hopes of bouncing back from what
happened one week earlier _ a loss to Indianapolis in a battle for
first place in the AFC East _ disintegrated into a 28-20 loss to a
team that began the day reeling from a loss to the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were ready to lay down,'' linebacker Zach Thomas said,
sitting in front of his locker, staring at the ground. ``I promise
you that. We just kept letting them hang in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins now have lost their past three games and four of
the past five to fall to 8-5. They began the day clinging to the
sixth, and final AFC East playoff spot. They had a chance to move
past Buffalo when the Bills lost 19-17 to the Giants in an early
game.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, this will be remembered as a day that the Jets, a team
whose roster has been depleted of stars, turned to one that was
still healthy.
</P>
<P>
   They gave Johnson the ball.
</P>
<P>
   He caught a career-high 11 passes for 144 yards. His 26-yard
touchdown catch on the first play of the fourth quarter tied the
score at 13-13. And his 24-yard touchdown with 9:34 remaining gave
the Jets their first lead _ one that they never let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of knew I'd have the opportunity to catch a lot of
balls,'' Johnson said. ``You should be able to beat man-to-man.''
</P>
<P>
   But should Johnson, who Sunday reached the 1,000-yard receiving
mark for the second consecutive season, have man-to-man coverage?
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the many questions Dolphins' fans will be asking
after this loss.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the Dolphins were focused on stopping a
receiver. The other one.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Wayne Chrebet has been the player who burned the
Dolphins. Chrebet began the day with four touchdowns against Miami.
Johnson had three. Plus, as cornerback Sam Madison pointed out, the
tapes they had watched showed the Jets going to Chrebet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keyshawn is their go-to guy, but over the last couple weeks we
saw Chrebet catches more passes and making big plays,'' Madison
said. ``They had been featuring him. We thought they would do that.
But they had a different gameplan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chrebet-or-Johnson emphasis might have been moot if the
Dolphins had been able to stop running back Curtis Martin.
</P>
<P>
   With 11:29 remaining in the fourth quarter and the score tied,
the Jets were faced with a fourth-and-1 at the Dolphins 32-yard
line.
</P>
<P>
   Jets coach Bill Parcells decided to go for it.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time in this season when one would have bet the
Dolphins defense would have made Parcells pay.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing Denver 113 yards on the ground in the season
opener, the Dolphins held their next six opponents to less than 100
yards. They headed into their Nov. 7 game against Tennessee having
allowed an average of 76.7 yards per game. Then they allowed five
consecutive opponents to rush for at least 100 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, they ended that streak. They held the Jets to 95 yards
on 24 carries. But when they really needed a stop, they didn't get
it.
</P>
<P>
   On that fourth-and-1, Martin didn't just get a yard, he got 9.
</P>
<P>
   On the next play, defensive end Daryl Gardener knocked Lucas
woozy with a helmet-to-helmet hit. Lucas was helped off the field.
As Rick Mirer ran one play, handing off to Martin, Lucas convinced
Parcells he was OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked me right in the eye and said, `I'm all right. Don't
worry about it,''' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas trotted back onto the field. The fans roared.
</P>
<P>
   On his next play, he threw deep to Johnson in the left corner of
the east end zone. Johnson broke free from Madison, grabbed the
ball and basically gave the Jets their third consecutive victory
against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Thomas pointed to what happened on fourth down as an
example of what is right with the Jets (5-8) and wrong with the
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a team that can go for it on fourth down because they
have nothing to lose,'' he said. ``I feel like now we should play
like that. Just go all out, man. Let's put it back together. But
it's not going to be that easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   It was just five weeks ago that the Dolphins were 7-1, sitting
atop the NFL. Now they appear to have contracted an
all-too-familiar disease _ December-itis.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins now are 5-8 in December since Jimmy Johnson arrived
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this latest case will be fatal remains to be seen. But
after Sunday's game, Johnson offered a blunt assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't win doing what we're doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Woods writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
E-mail: markwoods(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
