<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7658 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MENTAL-HEALTH14-COX     12-13 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-HEALTH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MENTAL HEALTH GROUPS HAIL SURGEON GENERAL'S REPORT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a report hailed by mental health advocacy
groups, Surgeon General David Satcher warned Monday that most
mentally ill Americans fail to receive treatment despite two
decades of revolutionary advances in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The report, the 51st on national health issues by surgeons
general but the first dealing with mental illness, notes that
diseases such as depression, schizophrenia and eating disorders can
be as disabling and serious as cancer and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``While mental disorders may touch all Americans, either
directly or indirectly, all do not have equal access to treatment
and service,'' Satcher said at a White House news conference. ``We
need to ensure that mental health services are as widely available
as other services in the continuously changing health care delivery
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Safe and effective options are available to treat mental
disorders that affect one in five Americans, Satcher said, yet
nearly half of all Americans with severe mental illness fail to
seek treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the report does not advocate specific policy changes,
it notes that ``the complex and fragmented mental health service
delivery system'' creates barriers to treatment. It also points to
financial barriers such as lack of health insurance ``parity'' for
mental health problems.
</P>
<P>
   The 500-page publication defines mental disorders as diagnosable
conditions that impair thinking, feeling and behavior and interfere
with a person's capacity to be productive and enjoy fulfilling
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The definition encompasses mental and brain problems of varying
severity: depression, schizophrenia, manic depressive (bipolar)
illness, anxiety disorders, Alzheimer's disease, attention deficit
hyperactivity disorder, autism and others.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Satcher in releasing the report were Tipper Gore, wife
of Vice President Al Gore, Health and Human Services Secretary
Donna Shalala and Larry Fricks, a Georgia state Division of Mental
Health official.
</P>
<P>
   Fricks brought a group of about 100 representatives of mental
health advocacy groups to their feet in a standing ovation with a
description of his own recovery from mental illness, as well his
grandmother's unsuccessful effort to cope with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Fricks said the report's ``most important impact'' would be to
help eliminate the stigma of mental disease ``so that people like
my grandmother will not waste their lives in self-imposed
isolation.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said Mrs. Gore, who serves as President Clinton's
adviser on mental health, originally suggested a surgeon general's
report on mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   Mental health groups expressed hope it would stimulate greater
public spending on mental health problems and greater public
awareness of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surgeon general puts mental health where it belongs: as a
cornerstone of public health,'' said Michael Faenza, president of
the National Mental Health Association. ``This historic report
makes clear that mental health is integral to individuals' and the
nation's health and should not be relegated to the sidelines of
health care and public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the report will not be worth the paper it is
printed on if its messages are not put into practice,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Flynn, executive director of the National Alliance for
the Mentally Ill, said the report documented a health crisis but
added that it would be ``waste of taxpayer dollars unless it
becomes a foundation for action. What matters most is deeds, not
words.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Beson, president of the St. Cloud, Minn.-based National
Association for Rural Mental Health, said, ``Our hope is that this
report will raise the level of dialogue throughout the country on a
variety of mental health issues. We hope one of them will be rural
mental health, which is an area that doesn't get a lot of attention
and is extremely lacking in resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Fact sheets about the report can be found at the Department of
Health and Human Services Internet site:
http://www.os.dhhs.gov/news/press.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
