<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYORAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNOUT SEEN AS CRUCIAL FOR BOTH CANDIDATES IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ILENE LELCHUK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Tuesday's mayoral contest between incumbent
Willie Brown and Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano could
hinge on who gets more voters to the polls at a time of year when
people may be thinking more about holiday shopping than politics.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the election lies in a handful of precincts and with
the Chinese-American voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   The polls indicate that Brown is likely to win his second term
as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he is not without weaknesses. The voters in the
neighborhood that gave him the most solid support, Bayview, turned
out in the smallest numbers for the Nov. 2 general election. And
the mayor faces ongoing criticism about his handling of the
troubled public transportation system and chronic homelessness in
one of the city's most prosperous eras.
</P>
<P>
   Brown campaign spokesman P.J. Johnston said interviews with
supporters who did not vote in November revealed that they did not
think Brown needed their help.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people said they thought that Mayor Brown had the
election wrapped up,'' Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown also needs the city's conservative west side and the
Marina district, where voters traditionally flock to the polls but
not in support of Brown.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 2, they went for former Mayor Frank Jordan and
businessman Clint Really, who both failed to win a spot in the
run-off election.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has to convince people in these areas to vote for him,
the more conservative of the two candidates in the run-off, rather
than sit out the election.
</P>
<P>
   The support of Chinese-Americans, who helped Brown in November,
could help boost turnout rates on the west side, said David Lee, a
specialist in demographic politics in San Francisco who heads the
Chinese-American Voter Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asians are really a kind of anchor from Brown's perspective,''
Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brown and Ammiano are Democrats, the incumbent is
viewed as much more friendly to businesses and developers.
</P>
<P>
   Amman's campaign is focusing on newly registered and people who
did not care much for politics before now but are swept up in
Amman's grass-roots movement.
</P>
<P>
   He won the second-place spot on the ballot through an
unprecedented write-in campaign in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winner could be the candidate who turns out the people who
don't normally vote,'' said Robert Barnes, a Brown supporter and
political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Amman's camp is expecting the occasional voters to flood the
polls, as they did for Amman's write-in bid.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign especially targeted the youthful neighborhoods of
Lower Haight and the Mission, where Ammiano carries solid support
in elections. But it also is where voter registration is very low.
</P>
<P>
   In a massive registration drive last month, Amman's campaign
claimed to have signed up more than 10,000 residents. There are
467,295 voters registered now, compared to 453,151 for the Nov. 2
election.
</P>
<P>
   Just under 45 percent of registered voters turned out in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Nishioka, acting director of the city Department of
Elections, predicts that 50 percent of registered voters will cast
ballots in the run-off election, based on the number of absentee
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   In the last-minute blitz to get voters to the polls, the
candidates held rallies over the weekend and sent volunteers
knocking on doors.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Mabel Teng, who supports Brown, held a
get-out-the-vote rally with Chinese-Americans on the steps of City
Hall Friday, and Supervisor Barbara Kaufman recorded a message sent
to phones around the city urging people to vote for Brown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1711EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
