<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7674 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITALS-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      12-13 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITALS-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREATMENTS: ZINC SUPPLEMENTS, FOR THE LIFE OF A CHILD 
PATTERNS: OF RATS, MAZES AND CELLULAR PHONES 
CAUSE AND EFFECT: THE MANY FACES OF HOLIDAY DEPRESSION 
OUTCOMES: WHEN TIME HEALS A DAMAGED HEART
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In America, zinc supplements have mainly been discussed in
recent years as a potential cure for the common cold.
</P>
<P>
   But in developing nations, according to an article published in
the December issue of The Journal of Pediatrics, zinc supplements
could offer the most cost-effective way of reducing the two leading
causes of childhood death: pneumonia and diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   Zinc deficiency is common among the world's poor. Exactly what
role the mineral plays in the body is not clear, but a lack of it
appears to hamper the body's immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the appeal of zinc is that it can be added to diets
relatively inexpensively, for example, by adding it to bread or
other foods. The extra zinc, researcher said, reduced diarrhea,
respiratory illnesses and skin disorders by 56 percent among
Turkish schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   For a broader look at the effect of zinc supplements, members of
the Child Health Research Project _ a collaborative effort by the
World Health Organization, Johns Hopkins University and Harvard _
analyzed data from 10 controlled trials in countries around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   They found that zinc reduced the number of cases of childhood
diarrhea by 25 percent; by comparison, the WHO has estimated that
high-quality improvements in water and sanitation would reduce the
incidence by 27 percent, but at a far greater cost.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on pneumonia was even more striking, reducing cases
by 41 percent, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Michael Hambidge and Dr. Nancy
Krebs of the University of Colorado Health Sciences Center in
Denver noted that zinc deficiencies might be corrected either by
fortifying food during manufacturing or by using plant breeding
techniques to increase the mineral content of grains and legumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enormous appeal of correcting zinc deficiency is that in
normalizing the function of cells in multiple tissues, it enhances
the child's ability to combat disease states and not just single
infectious organisms,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus,'' they added, ``on a worldwide public health level, it
is likely to be more economically feasible than vaccines directed
against specific organisms.''
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: Of Rats, Mazes and Cellular Phones
</P>
<P>
   The question of cell phones and their radiation lingers on. In
1993, an expert panel was to settle the issue, but then left a big
question mark.
</P>
<P>
   The panel rejected heavily publicized claims that cell phones
promoted brain tumors.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it suggested that much remained to be learned
about the effects of radiation emitted by phones on the human
brain.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a rat study has raised the possibility that the radiation
might adversely affect learning and memory.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, to be published in the January issue of the
journal Bioengineering, Dr. Henry Lai, a bioengineering professor
at the University of Washington in Seattle, looked at the effects
of microwave radiation on long-term memory formation.
</P>
<P>
   Lai trained two groups of rats to swim through a tank of water
to a submerged platform. Since the water had been made murky, they
had to first learn, then memorize the location of the platform.
</P>
<P>
   Rats that were exposed for an hour to pulsed microwaves similar
to the radiation emitted by cell phones were ``much slower in
finding the platform during the training sessions,'' Lai said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the platform was removed, and the rats were sent back for
another swim. The rats that were not exposed to the radiation
generally swam around where the platform had been, as if
``scratching their heads, saying `We thought it was here,''' Lai
said.
</P>
<P>
   The rats exposed to radiation swam around more randomly, Lai
said, suggesting that the maps they had made in their heads was not
as clear.
</P>
<P>
   CAUSE AND EFFECT: The Many Faces of Holiday Depression
</P>
<P>
   The thoughts of editors of medical journals apparently turn to
depression around this time of year, when more people are known to
get depressed. A survey of recent research articles and conference
reports found several, including these:
</P>
<P>
   _ Among people over 70, depression increases the risk of
developing a wide range of diseases as much as smoking does, a
University of Michigan study of 6,000 older Americans found. The
results were presented at the annual meeting of the Gerontological
Society of America. Earlier studies had linked depression to higher
rates of cancer and cognitive decline; this research found that
depression lifted overall rates of ``disease burden'' as much as
smoking and more than obesity, though not as much as lack of
physical strength.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of smoking, a Johns Hopkins University study
published in The American Journal of Public Health found that
teenagers who smoked were at greater risk for depression. But, the
study found, depression did not appear to prompt young people to
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   _ For people with Type 1, or juvenile, diabetes, depression is a
better predictor of coronary heart disease than high blood sugar,
according to a University of Pittsburgh study to be published in
the January issue of the journal Atherosclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Another study found this: Teen-age girls care an awful lot about
what other people think of them; teen-age boys, not so much. That
higher rate of what University of New Hampshire researchers call
emotional reliance was found to be associated with higher rates of
depression for young women in a survey of 1,393 people in Toronto.
The results were published last week in The Journal of Health and
Social Behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In 1872, Charles Darwin wrote, ``Infants, when suffering even
slight pain or discomfort, utter violent and prolonged screams.''
The observation, reported recently in the British Medical Journal,
came in connection with a study looking at what clinical trials
could reliably establish about the best ways to calm them down.
</P>
<P>
   Interest has been fueled by the growing number of premature
babies kept alive by intensive _ and often painful treatment in
neonatal units, and by the recent recognition that even very
premature infants can feel pain.
</P>
<P>
   The study by pediatricians at Poissy Hospital in France examined
the analgesic powers of sweet solutions (sucrose and glucose) and
pacifiers compared with placebos.
</P>
<P>
   The solutions and pacifiers were found effective, according to
pain ratings made on the basis of facial expression, limb movements
and crying. But the most effective measure was a pacifier alone.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why pacifiers work is a mystery. But the researchers
speculated that the sensory input from sucking may override or
distract from pain signals, or that infants may be comforted by the
fact that the pacifier gives them some control over what they are
experiencing.
</P>
<P>
   OUTCOMES: When Time Heals a Damaged Heart
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the popular diet drug combination known as fen-phen was
pulled off the market after Mayo Clinic researchers found an
increase in heart valve disease among people taking the
medications. In a follow-up study published last week, researchers
from the clinic concluded that the valve damage appeared to improve
after patients stopped taking the pills.
</P>
<P>
   The new study looked at 30 men and women who had been taking
either fen-phen (fenfluramine and phentermine) or a placebo for an
average of 41 weeks as part of an unrelated study of the diet
drugs. Their hearts were examined by echocardiogram shortly after
they stopped taking the medicines and about six months later.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the patients taking fen-phen were found to have some
sign of heart valve disease, said Dr. Donald Hensrud, a Mayo Clinic
nutrition specialist who led the new study, which was published in
the Mayo Clinic Proceedings. But the researchers found that ``heart
valve disease did not get worse after patients stopped taking the
medications,'' Hensrud said. In fact, all of the patients whose
valves were affected showed improvement in the six-month follow up.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new findings should be reassuring for those Americans
who took fen-phen,'' he said. Hensrud said that the study's patient
pool was too small to allow for sweeping generalizations. But he
said the findings were consistent with patients' reports that they
had fewer symptoms associated with valve disease after the drugs
were withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he urged those who took either drug to consult their
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
