<P>
   FBN-GASOUTHERN _ Georgia Southern fullback Adrian Peterson will
spend the next two days on crutches but probably will be available
for Saturday's Division I-AA national championship game against
Youngstown State. (Reese, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-GARNETT _ Kevin Garnett has had a huge impact on the NBA
during his four short years in the league. When Garnett was
selected by the Timberwolves with the fifth pick of the 1995 draft,
he was the first high schooler to be selected in the draft in 20
years. That opened the door for others, including Kobe Bryant, to
go straight from high school to the NBA. Two years ago, Garnett
signed a $126 million contract which ultimately led to the league
locking out its players in hopes to limiting spiraling salaries. On
the court, he's helped Minnesota develop into one of the league's
top teams and the Timberwolves meet the Hawks tonight at Philips
Arena. (Bunn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-MEETINGS _ News, notes from the baseball winter meetings.
(Stinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EQUITY-BOOSTER _ MACON, Ga. _ When Westside High School opened
three years ago, the view from the back showed acres of barren
fields. This fall, those fields are adorned with athletics
facilities befitting a small college campus. They are appraised at
more than $5 million. It is the work of wildly energetic,
well-meaning boosters. They have built baseball and football
stadiums for their sons and renovated a country house to function
as the supporters' headquarters on 52 acres adjoining school
property, all owned by the private, nonprofit Westside Boosters
Inc. The generosity might have placed the school afoul of a federal
gender-equity law. (Fish/Milliron, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EQUITY-PORKBARREL _ With few exceptions, it is illegal for
school districts in Georgia to spend state tax dollars on
athletics, but every year legislators skirt the law by practicing
old-fashioned pork-barrel politics to move teams into larger
stadiums or fancier uniforms. (Fish/Milliron, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
