<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7721 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-GOLAN-1214-COX     12-13 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GOLAN-1214-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BARAK MAKES PITCH TO ISRAEL ON THE 'HEAVY PRICE' OF PEACE
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Monday urged his
country to prepare for the ``heavy price'' of a peace agreement
with Syria _ a possible withdrawal from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Barak spoke in a special address to the Israeli parliament that
was followed by a 47-to-31 vote of endorsement for peace talks,
which are scheduled for Wednesday and Thursday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first official indication of Israel's openness to
concessions that might be necessary in making peace with Syria, one
of the country's oldest and most important enemies.
</P>
<P>
   With his speech, the vote and the demonstration outside of
several thousand Golan Heights supporters, the debate that some
Israeli newspapers have already dubbed ``The Battle for the Golan''
was underway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peace agreement we want to reach with Syria will be such
that it will put an end to conflict and ensure peace and security
between the two nations,'' Barak told the parliament. ``If we miss
this opportunity, God forbid, it might cost us in blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak denied accusations that he had already promised Syrian or
American mediators that Israel would give up the Golan in the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   He chose to stress instead, the ``historic'' chance the talks
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a revolution in the relationship between Israel and
the Arab countries,'' Barak said. ``Our supreme responsibility is
to act today so that we will not dig new rows of graves tomorrow in
a conflict that could have been ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Though their border has been quiet since the 1973 war, Syria and
Israel have been in an official state of war for decades. Israel
captured the Golan Heights from Syria in 1967, and the return of
the plateau _ on Israel's northeastern edge _ is the key issue in
the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Syria seeks the return of the entire Golan. Israel seeks
assurances that Syria will reign in guerillas who Israel is
fighting in the war in southern Lebanon. It also seeks normal
relations with Syria, a pull back of Syrian troops from the Israeli
border, and international monitors or other ways to insure security
between the countries.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has promised to take any Syrian deal to a public vote.
Opinion polls in recent days have shown Israelis evenly split on
whether to give up the Golan in return for a peace deal. One poll
even showed that a quarter of Golan residents could agree to a
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Before his speech, Barak met with Nadia Cohen, widow of Eli
Cohen, an Israeli spy who was tortured and executed by Syria in
1965. She said she wished Barak well in the talks and said she
hopes they will lead to the return of Eli Cohen's remains.
</P>
<P>
   But, others oppose Barak's efforts and that opposition has
quickly turned ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Police Monday were reportedly investigating the posting of signs
accusing Barak of treason, the same accusation hurled at Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin in the months leading up to his
assassination in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israelis compare the possible evacuation of some 18,000
Jews living in 33 settlements on the Golan to the Nazi practice of
sweeping Jews out of their neighborhoods and countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Golan Heights has supporters beyond those that live there.
While some say the high ground is not strategically important in
these days of missile warfare, others believe it is vital to the
country's security. Still others say a withdrawal would encourage
Arab countries to press for more land.
</P>
<P>
   At a demonstration outside the parliament Monday, several
thousand people chanted, ``No moving from the Golan!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to turn this country upside down,'' said
demonstrator Pircha Lottner, 71, of Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not extremists. We want peace, but there is no way we
want to leave our homes,'' said Golan resident Avner Talmon, 45.
</P>
<P>
   But, one public opinion expert here said the nearly even poll
numbers over a Golan withdrawal, even before a deal is signed,
indicate the odds are in Barak's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak has his trump card. He will tell people that it will end
all the wars,'' said Yehuda Ben Meir, a researcher on Israeli
attitudes about peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
   An actual agreement, which negotiators say could occur within
months, would likely include potent public relations opportunities,
such as a Barak visit to the Syrian capital, Damascus, and a
signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the prime minister's residence Monday night, several
hundred peace activists voiced their support for the talks.
Carrying signs saying, ``Peace with Syria now,'' they invoked the
name of Rabin and offered a preview of the pro-peace referendum
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the Golan is more than a home. It is a lifetime
achievement,'' said Yigal Kipnis, a resident of the Golan for 21
years. ``But we never put our own interests above the interests of
the nation. Real and full peace is the aim.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
