<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7726 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-FORBES-PROFILE-2NDTAK     12-13 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-PROFILE-2NDTAKE-1STLDWRIT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
SUNAPEE, N.H.: to jump in. 
 
(Sub 3rd graf to correct to ``he'' sted of ``she.'') 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jude Wanniski, a supply-side economist and former Wall Street
Journal editorial writer, claims credit for nudging Forbes into
presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motivation came from a good friend of his _ me _ telling
him the roster (of candidates) was incredibly thin,'' Wanniski
said.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote a long memorandum to Forbes, proposing a presidential
race for the publisher four years ago, after Kemp had ruled himself
out. Wanniski and Forbes, who lived a few miles from each other in
New Jersey, had been longtime friends and had often discussed
politics and economics.
</P>
<P>
   But they had a falling-out after Forbes became a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes lost in 1996 because ``he rejected my advice'' and
listened to the wrong people, Wanniski said.
</P>
<P>
   She isn't involved in Forbes' current campaign but has advised
Quayle and Pat Buchanan, who recently jumped from the GOP to seek
the Reform Party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his future may hold, Forbes' interest in politics and
economics began in his childhood in New Jersey, where he still
lives.
</P>
<P>
   He told one interviewer several years ago that he started
reading The New York Times and following the stock market when he
was 12 or 13.
</P>
<P>
   As a son of privilege, Forbes at a young age met a number of
famous and influential people from the worlds of business and
politics.
</P>
<P>
   He and his four siblings helped their father entertain corporate
chiefs during lunch and dinner cruises on the magazine's yacht, the
Highlander.
</P>
<P>
   One of his childhood friends was Christine Todd, now New Jersey
Gov. Christine Todd Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Forbes and Whitman don't always see eye to eye on
politics. Forbes advised Whitman during her first gubernatorial
race in 1993, but they have drifted apart on social issues. Whitman
favors abortion rights, while Forbes, eager to win the support of
social conservatives, has made opposition to abortion an important
part of his current campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just last month, Forbes held a rally in Trenton to support
a bill before the New Jersey Legislature that would require
students to recite a passage from the Declaration of Independence
at the start of each school day. Whitman opposes the bill because
she believes that it has marginal educational value.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman declined to comment on Forbes' presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``She believes that he is a very bright man, but there are some
issues on which they differ,'' the governor's spokeswoman, Jane
O'Connor, said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes was only 17 when he wrote his first article for the
family's magazine. The contribution, which his father carried as
part of his ``Fact and Comment'' column, was a report from the 1964
Republican National Convention in San Francisco, which nominated
Barry Goldwater for an impossible challenge to President Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all the young people around my age were Goldwater
supporters. And they weren't kooks,'' the young Forbes wrote,
without revealing his own preference in candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of them had at least one conspicuous button and when
it came to noisemaking, they were tops.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also published his observations of the 1968
conventions, including what he called the ``fierce Democratic melee
in Chicago.'' Forbes, then a 21-year-old Princeton student, called
legendary Chicago Mayor Richard Daley, who unleashed the city's
police on young anti-war protesters, a ``unique antique.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Princeton with a history degree in 1970
and serving a five-month active duty commitment to the New Jersey
National Guard, he became a fact-checker and researcher in the
magazine's editorial department and quickly worked his way up the
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not the kind of guy who said, `Let's go get a beer.' He
was very awkward socially,'' recalled a former writer for the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The former staffer said he finds Forbes' presidential ambitions
``befuddling.'' But, he added, ``He was always interested in
economic issues, and the stage for it is politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who soon began getting regular column space of his own,
developed a reputation as an able prognosticator of presidential
election results and economic trends. By 1989, he had been a
four-time winner of the prestigious Crystal Owl award, presented
annually to the reporter making the most accurate economic
predictions for the upcoming year.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is not actively involved in running the magazine
during his presidential race, he retains the title of president and
editor in chief and still regularly writes a column.
</P>
<P>
   In one recent column, he criticized the ``inconsistent,
floundering regime'' of German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, and
endorsed an instant video replay as a way to resolve controversial
calls by umpires during Major League Baseball games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he (Forbes) has a very good mind. He just wasn't
blessed with Malcolm's (his father's) gift of gab,'' the former
Forbes staffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has been characterized as stiff and owlish, but his
speaking style on the campaign trail is hardly any worse than
Bush's, Al Gore's or Bill Bradley's. None of the leading contenders
of either major party is golden-throated.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher's one-liners, most of which he says he writes
himself, are generally well-received. ``It makes you wonder what
global warming can do to a man's mind,'' is one of his favorite
digs at Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' gestures during his speeches often are mechanical, but
that doesn't seem to bother supporters like April Carter, 42, an
aircraft engine factory worker from Chichester, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   ``His heart is huge. I just sense it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole, the 1996 Republican presidential nominee, however, may
not agree. Forbes' negative TV ads against Dole during the primary
season are believed to have contributed to the nominee's general
election defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Now, trying to position himself as a viable, conservative
alternative to Bush for Republican voters in 2000, Forbes has
recently gone on the offensive against the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes recently began running a TV spot in New Hampshire,
blasting Bush for suggesting that the Social Security retirement
age could be raised to bolster the troubled system. And he was
quick to criticize Bush's proposal to cut income taxes, rather than
overhaul the system.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes promotes his own tax proposal _ which would impose a 17
percent flat tax on all income above $36,000 for a family of four,
abolish capital gains taxes and eliminate many loopholes and
deductions _ as a boon for middle- and low-income Americans. What
he doesn't often say, however, is that his plan also could be worth
untold millions in tax savings to his own company.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is often joined on the campaign trail by his wife, the
former Sabina Beekman, a minister's daughter whom he met at a New
York debutante party during his senior year at Princeton. They have
five daughters.
</P>
<P>
   No one except Dwight Eisenhower has been elected president in
modern times without first holding a lower elective office. But
Eisenhower was a war hero.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes insists he is not discouraged by history _ or his low
poll numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more real-world executive experience than all of these
other candidates put together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that he has traveled the world extensively and
visited with many foreign leaders as a businessman, journalist and
chairman of the Radio Free Europe board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll match my knowledge of the world with anyone else,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
