<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS ARE HOPING FOR SOME BIG UPSETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRIAN MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ And now, for their next act, the Oakland
Raiders pray for losses.
</P>
<P>
   All kinds of losses. Buffalo losses. Seattle losses. New England
losses. Kansas City losses.
</P>
<P>
   As for the day of Dec.26, when Buffalo plays New England and
Kansas City plays Seattle? The Raiders pray for losses all around.
Four losses for those four teams, if possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess a lot depends on what other teams do now,'' Raiders
fullback Jon Ritchie said. ``I'm not going to lie. It's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's how tough: The Raiders are 6-7 and enjoy a tiebreaker
advantage only over Buffalo, which is 8-4. In other words, for the
Raiders to pass Seattle and Kansas City in the AFC West, those
teams have to finish 8-8. Seattle already has eight wins, and
Kansas City has seven. So is Seattle going to go 0-4 and Kansas
City 1-3, and are the Raiders going to win their last three games,
starting next Sunday against Tampa Bay, a defense that has allowed
the fewest points of any NFC team?
</P>
<P>
   Don't hold your breath.
</P>
<P>
   So the other hope is this: Buffalo goes 1-3 over its last four
games (against the New York Giants, at Arizona, at New England and
against Indianapolis) and the Raiders not only beat Tampa Bay, but
win road games at San Diego and at Kansas City _ oh, and New
England (7-5) flames out, too _ and the Oakland Raiders break a
six-year playoff drought.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about it, Ritchie could barely answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the prognosticator, I'm the player,'' Ritchie said.
``I know one thing, and that's to play and practice hard, and to
continue to improve. There's only one thing I can control, and
that's whether we win or lose.''
</P>
<P>
   How can anyone expect the Raiders to go 3-0 down the stretch
when all they have done all year is show an amazing ability to hurt
themselves, an almost fascinating inconsistency that is so regular,
you'd have to call it consistency?
</P>
<P>
   Never more than two wins in a row. Never more than two losses in
a row. Never a record more than one game above or below .500.
Losses that can be boiled down to one play, every week, losses that
can be boiled down to missed field goals at Denver, against Kansas
City at the Coliseum, and at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Losses that, on average, were only by 4.4 maddening points, and
never by more than a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they face the specter of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers
coming next, a team that makes its very existence thriving off of
other teams' mistakes, a turnover-hungry crew that is still playing
every game for its playoff existence and will be motivated, not
flat, at the Coliseum on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Raiders can look back on this season as the season of
the unforgiving schedule. Maybe if they hadn't had to fly to
Tennessee on a Thursday following a Sunday game, maybe if they
hadn't had to open at Green Bay and then play at Minnesota, Seattle
and Buffalo in four of the first six weeks, their season would have
started better than 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' Ritchie said. ``It's a difficult
schedule. No one can be happy with a schedule like that, but it
shouldn't affect the way we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie made that comment just minutes after the 21-14 loss at
Tennessee, another example of a Raiders game gone awry: a Rich
Gannon fumble at the 7-yard line, a Darrien Gordon muffed punt that
cost the Raiders a comeback try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we could have won the (Tennessee Titans) game, we were
in a position to win it,'' Ritchie said. ``We had to finish out,
and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   A familiar refrain, uttered in locker rooms at Mile High
Stadium, Lambeau Field and the Kingdome. And to think, this is a
Raiders team that has defeated Minnesota on the road, Buffalo on
the road, and beaten probable division winner Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the thoughts that caused Gannon to utter the word
``frustrating'' so many times after the Titans loss, it was as if
it were the only word he could say. Those are the thoughts that eat
away at the Raiders this weekend, as they take a Sunday off and
watch their brethren play around the league.
</P>
<P>
   And root for the Cardinals over the Bills. And root for the
Chargers over the Seahawks. And root for ... ah, you get the idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
