<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Dec. 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A dreary day is expected across New England and the Middle
Atlantic states. A complex storm moving east from Delaware will act
as a pivot for a wedge of very mild, moist air to be lifted over a
dome of chilly air over Quebec. The result will be a cold, soaking
rain from Lake Erie to Cape Cod. As much as three inches of rain
will be blown by onshore gale-force winds. Pockets of colder air
over the higher terrain of northern Pennsylvania and upstate New
York may lead to accumulations of ice or wet snow.
</P>
<P>
   Drier yet cooler air will cover much of the Southeast and Gulf
States with high pressure building across northern Florida. A few
showers will persist in south Florida ahead of a cold front. A flow
of mild air into Texas will cause clouds to develop along the
coast. Low clouds will linger along the west slopes of the
Appalachians from northern Georgia to Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Rain and low clouds are expected into the central Lakes. A push
of polar air into the Plains will produce scattered snow showers in
the Missouri Valley. Low pressure forming over the southwest Plains
will force chilly, moist air to ascend the east slopes of the
southern Rockies leading to a brief period of snow. Colder air will
return to the Rockies on gusty winds.
</P>
<P>
   Fine late-autumn weather will dominate the Southwest, though
canyon winds will still be gusty in southern California. Milder air
from the Pacific will be lifted over the Cascades, allowing snow
levels to rise. Farther inland, residual cold air will promote snow
showers in the higher terrain. Rain and gusty winds will effect the
Northwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Fullest Moon
</P>
<P>
   It may sound like a cheap advertisement, but the full moon next
week will be bigger and brighter than any moon that we have seen
this century. An unusual coincidence of the shape of the lunar
orbit and the winter solstice, which occurs on December 22, will
make the moon appear 14 percent larger and about 7 percent
brighter. Despite the beginning of winter in the northern
hemisphere, the Earth is actually several million miles closer to
the sun at this time of the year and this will add more radiance to
the full moon. Should a strong coastal storm develop, then tidal
flooding could become very serious.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
