<HEADER>
A7742 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MEDICAL-CASES-NYT     12-13 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MEDICAL-CASES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HEALING ARTS, CAST IN SHADES OF GRAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   All the talk about medical errors in Washington these days
leaves the impression that now that the problem is finally
acknowledged, a solution is already in sight. Like an alcoholic at
his first AA meeting, we have finally stood up and said the words
out loud: Bad errors happen in medical practice. There are drugs
with look-alike labels and sound-alike names, there are nurses who
mistake micrograms for milligrams and doctors who mistake left for
right. The message seems to be that once systems like the ones
safeguarding aviation and other high-risk industries are in place,
medical care will become safe at last.
</P>
<P>
   Would that it were so. The truth is that unlike aviation or any
other industry, medicine is a world etched in perilous shades of
gray. Very little is black or white, right or wrong. Once systems
are in place to fix stupid human mistakes, equally dreadful errors
of judgment that are far harder to deflect will endure.
</P>
<P>
   A patient who was admitted to a New York City hospital a month
ago is an instructive case study in medical error, the kind that
will require more than systems analysis and punitive Medicare
sanctions to correct. He is an 80-year-old man with diabetes who
developed diarrhea early this fall. After a week he started to feel
woozy and went to his local hospital _ call it Acme Medical Center
_ to get checked out.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors at Acme did all the right things. The patient was
severely dehydrated, and they gave him some fluid intravenously;
they ran tests to see if an infection was causing the diarrhea and
examined his colon in case a tumor or other anatomic abnormality
was responsible. They found nothing wrong, gave him pills to slow
the diarrhea and sent him home. The diarrhea stopped on its own a
few days later.
</P>
<P>
   A week passed. The patient noticed that his forearm was sore at
the site where his intravenous line had been placed. The pain
worsened and he ran a slight fever. He went back to Acme.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors there could see that he clearly had an infection in
his arm _ a complication of intravenous therapy that occurs in
American hospitals hundreds of thousands of times a year. Most of
the time these infections go away by themselves. Rarely, they
progress, spreading through the bloodstream to cause
life-threatening abscesses in the brain, the bones or the heart.
Anything that impairs the body's immune defenses, like diabetes,
may increase the risk of the infection's spreading.
</P>
<P>
   The Acme doctors put the patient in the hospital and gave him
the most powerful antibiotic they could. At the end of a week, the
arm was fine. The patient was desperate to go home. Usually at
least two weeks of antibiotics are given to make sure these
infections do not progress. Some doctors recommend four weeks to
reduce the small remaining risk still further. But insurers can be
loath to pay for extra hospital days just for a little added
certainty. Furthermore, the antibiotics were now making the
patient's stomach rumble, and he was morbidly afraid his diarrhea
would return. His doctors could have arranged for him to get
another few weeks of antibiotics at home, but he vigorously
protested.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later the patient stumbled in the street, fell down
and couldn't get up. An ambulance took him back to Acme.
</P>
<P>
   He was found to have a high fever and pneumonia. Inexplicably,
he was also having trouble moving his legs. On his third day in the
hospital he suddenly couldn't move them at all. An MRI scan showed
a large infection in his upper spine, with a fist-sized abscess
encasing two vertebrae and pressing down on the spinal cord itself,
paralyzing his legs. He had become a textbook example of one of the
worst and rarest complications of an infected intravenous line.
</P>
<P>
   The patient is still hospitalized. He has been receiving
antibiotics for almost a month now. His fever is gone, but he still
cannot move his legs. Scans show that the abscess in his spine is
getting larger. It is close enough to his heart and lungs that an
operation to drain it would be complicated and very risky. The
hospital surgeons are unwilling to take those risks. But leaving
the abscess undrained is also risky _ it is growing dangerously
close to a big blood vessel in the chest. If it bursts into that
blood vessel, the patient will die.
</P>
<P>
   Sorting out the bad luck from bad systems and bad medical
practice in this dreadful tangle of medical error would take the
wisdom of Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   Can we assign the blame for the whole cascade of events to an
unknown nurse or medical technician who placed the patient's first
intravenous line, deciding that they must not have used good
aseptic technique during the procedure? This is a temptingly simple
solution, but studies have shown that even when intravenous lines
are placed with immaculate technique, a small but finite risk of
infection persists.
</P>
<P>
   Is it better to blame instead the doctors at Acme for not
insisting that the patient get more antibiotics for his arm
infection? They, too, were playing the roulette wheel of medical
risk. The chances were pretty good that their patient's infection
would subside without incident. But more antibiotics would have
made those chances much better _ so do we blame them for failing to
understand important gradations of risk? For understanding them but
not making the patient understand them? For not bullying him into
submission even if he couldn't understand, making him stay when he
wanted to leave?
</P>
<P>
   Do we decide to whirl around and just blame the patient, for
taking unnecessary risks with his own health? Do we instead blame
the philosophy that guides medical practice these days, for giving
him the legal and moral autonomy to do so? Do we blame medical
insurers, for encouraging early hospital discharges, making it so
very difficult nowadays to be careful with patients who need a
little extra care? Do we pass a little blame on to the nursing
profession, for not routinely sending visiting nurses to drop in on
discharged patients, so that trouble is detected sooner rather than
later?
</P>
<P>
   Or do we shake our fists in the air and blame bad karma and
angry gods?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, we have outgrown this last option. But at least we
should be aware that while acknowledging that medical errors occur
is a first step in getting rid of them, the path toward making
medical care a safe haven is likely to be long and winding indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
