<SLUG> BC-BORDER-SHOOTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING CREATES TENSION ACROSS THE RIO GRANDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIUDAD ACUNA, Mexico _ Viewed through Mexican eyes from an
outcropping above the Rio Grande, the Vega Verde subdivision in Del
Rio, Texas, is an isolated bit of American fantasyland of
comfortable homes, satellite dishes, recreational vehicles and
pacing watchdogs.
</P>
<P>
   And when three dirt-poor young Mexicans waded the river last
month to burglarize a secluded home on Vega Verde Road, they were
following in the footsteps of many thieves before them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going over to rob them, but we didn't have any time,''
Martin Cerdo Martinez said. ``We saw the man running out of his
truck. We ran and got out to the middle of the river, and then we
heard the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The three crossed the Rio Grande on Nov. 1, but only two came
back. Eleven days later, the body of the missing youth, Luis
Armando Chavez Vaquera, 16, turned up downriver with a bullet hole
through the left eye.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since, the obscure border incident outside Del Rio
has become a sensitive international issue, prompting high-level
calls by Mexico for intervention from Texas and U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   It has also illustrated the jarring contrasts and inevitable
conflicts between the lives of Mexicans and Americans who are
neighbors here, separated only the modest stream called the Rio
Grande.
</P>
<P>
   ``It involves a youngster, a juvenile of 16 years. We feel it is
a very delicate situation, and we don't want it generalized along
the border,'' said Carlos Sada, Mexico's consul-general in San
Antonio. ``If everyone begins taking justice into their own hands,
then the law of the Wild West comes into the scenario, and that law
is totally abolished.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Mexicans are angered and confused because the man the
would-be burglars accuse in the shooting has not been charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mexico, a suspect would be immediately jailed until he
could demonstrate he is innocent. Some people don't understand
there is a different legal system in the United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The man has denied the shooting. Victor Garcia, the man's
lawyer, said he advised his client to leave Del Rio for safety
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities are awaiting results of DNA testing to confirm
the identity of the badly decomposed body, but have few doubts that
it is that of Chavez Vaquera.
</P>
<P>
   The dead teen's family members feel that authorities on both
sides of the Rio Grande are trying to avoid investigating the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Maria del Carmen Vaquera, the dead boy's mother, said ``what we
want first is justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it would be justified to shoot someone in the home, but
he was shot in the river, on the Mexican side,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But where Mexicans see cold-blooded murder, Americans who live
on the isolated river road and are victims of repeated thefts, see
an act of self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone on this side who knows the situation is sympathetic''
to the gunman, said Tommy Vick, who lives along the river in Del
Rio. ``That's the only thing you can do, stand up to them, or
they'll take everything you have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be the best place in the world to live if that
wasn't Mexico,'' Vick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been broken into numerous times over the last eight to
10 years. I've lost $15,000 to $20,000 in merchandise. We caught a
burglar in our home one time, and after we turned him over to
police, they just turned him loose,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few houses downriver from Vick, Virginia Mohr lives with a
loaded .12-gauge shotgun hung above the inside of the front door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is, but I know how to use it. I think
you'll probably find a shotgun in every house on the river,'' Mohr
said.
</P>
<P>
   The residents along Vega Verde Road say calling the Val Verde
County Sheriff or U.S. Border Patrol to deal with such incidents is
pointless.
</P>
<P>
   With only 10 deputies to patrol a 3,300-square-mile county,
Sheriff D'Wayne Jernigan said responding in time to calls from the
river neighborhood is nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a practical matter, we can't protect them. Usually we have
only one deputy on (road) duty at any time,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
