<HEADER>
A7748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-Y2K-BANKS-COX     12-13 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-BANKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Banks pronounced ready for Jan. 1
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ All of the nation's 10,200 banks, thrift institutions
and credit unions insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
are ready for 2000, federal and state regulators said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts don't expect problems, and depositors' accounts
at FDIC banks are insured up to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Tanoue, president of the FDIC, and Jack Guynn, president
of the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta, said any glitches that
occur Jan. 1 will be minor bumps in the road, not disasters.
</P>
<P>
   The main concern expressed to date _ whether or not consumers
will be able to use automated teller machines as usual _ has been
put to rest, said Ellen Seidman, director of the Office of Thrift
Supervision.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us have been to ATM machines that did not work. It was
not Y2K then, and it won't be Y2K now, if it happens,'' she said.
``Just go up the street to another ATM.''
</P>
<P>
   In a three-year effort that involved thousands of examiners
visiting each bank at least twice, systems have been upgraded,
replaced and tested. Codes have been rewritten when problems
appeared, Tanoue said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has not been a one-shot deal. We have greater reliability
than ever and better contingency systems (for all kinds of power
outages, including those caused by weather),'' Tanoue said.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been an increased demand for cash over 1998,
people have not been withdrawing huge amounts, Guynn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The banks have stockpiled (cash), so it is there if people
want it, but some have even started sending the money back,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most consumers think banks are prepared, according to a Gallup
Poll commissioned by federal bank regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bridges, commissioner of Georgia's Department of Banking
and Finance, said consumers have not been making the wholesale
withdrawals that some banks expected.
</P>
<P>
   According to Seidman, there are no total industry cost estimates
for Y2K preparation. Her agency has spent $100 million. The Federal
Reserve has shelled out $125 million. Some of the money was for
scheduled, non-Y2K-related upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harte writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
