<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-WASHINGTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY GEORGE, GROUP GETS INTO THE SPIRIT OF HONORING WASHINGTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ His picture, similar to the one on dollar bills,
seemed out of place on the local newspaper's obituary page Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But there he was: ``General George Washington,'' dead now for
200 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would catch the eye,'' chuckled Frank Gibson, a
retiree who helped organize a totally serious church service
Tuesday night to commemorate the bicentennial anniversary of
Washington's death in 1799.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the memorial service for the father of the
United States was right there on page 6B of Monday's Austin
American-Statesman, a Cox newspaper with a daily circulation of
about 200,000.
</P>
<P>
   The service is expected to draw some of Washington's distant
relatives, a minister from Houston and Sons of the American
Revolution from around the state and nation, Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Washington is sort of the patron saint of the SAR. He's
our No. 1 man,'' said Gibson, president of the state chapter of the
SAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since it's the 200th anniversary of his death, we decided to
have a memorial service for him,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   The religious observance at Covenant Presbyterian Church will
include hymns, a sermon, a eulogy by former Texas Supreme Court
Justice Jack Hightower, and a remembrance by a descendant of one of
Washington's staff officers and a Daughter of the American
Revolution, Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   Two ``collateral'' descendants of the general, who had no
children, also are expected, said Gibson, an elder at the church.
</P>
<P>
   If the 7 p.m. CST service lasts until 9:30, the
approximate &UR;  &LR; local time of Washington's demise at Mount Vernon,
Va., the church bells will be tolled in his honor, Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was only appropriate that we honor his death,
the same way we honor his birth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington had been retired from public service about two years
when he succumbed to what some historians say was strep throat, a
bacterial infection. On the day before his death, Washington
followed his usual routine of logging weather observations _ it was
near freezing and damp _ riding horseback and doing other chores at
Mount Vernon. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But he failed to remove wet clothes that afternoon and by early
the next morning, his throat had swollen, making it hard to breath,
historians say. Their accounts say Washington ordered an aide to
drain blood in a failed bid to feel better before doctors arrived.
He died several hours later, and the nation remained in mourning
more than two months _ until his Feb. 22 birthday. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; As citizens did then, those honoring Washington on Tuesday will
wear black arm bands, said John Knox, who leads the Austin chapter
of the Sons of the American Revolution. He'll don a Revolutionary
War uniform first thing in the morning to lead a Cub Scout troop's
flag-raising ceremony in the general's honor.
</P>
<P>
   Knox said SAR members in the Dallas suburb of Plano are also
planning ceremonies Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without George Washington taking the steps he took, we
wouldn't be here today,'' Knox said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
