<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANGOGH-MOMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GOGH DRAWING FILLS GAP AT THE MODERN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Museum of Modern Art, which abruptly lost its
only two van Gogh drawings last year, once again has one in its
collection. The museum's chairman, Ronald Lauder bought an
unusually large and turbulent van Gogh drawing of olive trees last
week at Sotheby's in London for $8.5 million, a record price for a
van Gogh drawing.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's director, Glenn D. Lowry, confirmed the gift from
Lauder. The drawing will go on view early in the new year, museum
aides said. The acquisition helped fill, at least in part, a gap
created in the Modern's collection by an unusual stipulation in the
will of Abby Aldrich Rockefeller, one of the museum's founders, who
died in 1948. She bequeathed the Modern two van Gogh drawings
valued together at $40 million: ``Hospital Corridor at St. Remy,''
an 1889 gouache that Vincent van Gogh made for his brother, Theo,
while the artist was a patient there, and ``Streets at Stes.
Maries,'' an 1888 image of a row of cottages along a street leading
to the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   But her will specified that after 50 years, when in her
estimation the drawings would no longer be considered new, the
Modern would have to surrender the two Van Goghs and two works by
Seurat to rival institutions (the van Goghs to the Metropolitan
Museum of Art and the Seurats to the Art Institute of Chicago) that
did not have the same exclusive commitment to art of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew when we gave up the great van Gogh drawings to the
Met, we were going to have to go out and find one or two to replace
them, which wasn't going to be easy,'' Lowry said. He added that
Lauder's gift was ``a complete home run.''
</P>
<P>
   His purchase of the drawing, ``Olive Trees With the Alpilles
Range in the Background'' of 1889, had been planned since the
museum learned it was coming on the market, Lowry said. Officials
at the Modern wanted it not simply because of its extraordinary
penmanship and size (it measures 18{ by 24{ inches), he said, but
also because van Gogh executed the drawing while working on a
painting with the same title that was left to the Modern in March.
The other drawing was bequeathed by Betsy Cushing Roosevelt
Whitney, the New York socialite and philanthropist who with her
husband, John Hay Whitney, the financier, publisher and former
ambassador to Britain, had amassed one of the nation's most
important private art collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drawing has an energy that the painting doesn't,'' said
Lowry. ``It is not a study for the painting but was done at the
same time.''
</P>
<P>
   That drawing had belonged to Max Silberberg, a German
industrialist who was forced by the Nazis to sell it along with 143
other works.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Greta Silberberg, his 85-year-old daughter-in-law,
recovered the painting in a legal case against the German National
Gallery, where it had been hanging. After the drawing was returned
to her, she put it up for sale. Ms. Silberberg said she planned to
use the money partly to finance a search for the other missing
works.
</P>
</TEXT>
