<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FRENCH-FILMS-ART-NYT &LR;      12-13 1699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-FILMS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FRENCH FUME OVER POPULARITY OF U.S. FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ For many French movie directors it is a familiar
problem: how to explain Hollywood's domination of the French box
office without conceding that local moviegoers prefer American
films. In the past they argued that American imports benefited from
better marketing and distribution. Now some are blaming betrayal
closer to home. French film critics, they say, seem bent on killing
off the French movie industry,
</P>
<P>
   That artists resent criticism is hardly exclusive to France or
to cinema. Yet after the first shots were fired at French movie
critics in October, there was something peculiarly French about the
furious battle of words that followed. Where else would major
newspapers dedicate entire pages to covering _ even fomenting _ a
cultural conflict? Isn't a dialectical confrontation between
patriotism and freedom just the stuff of Left Bank cafes?
</P>
<P>
   The respective charges in the dispute seem straightforward
enough. The offended directors say that influential critics at
leading newspapers give ample space and generous reviews to
Hollywood blockbusters while treating many French films with
gratuitous venom.
</P>
<P>
   The critics respond that many French directors are, as one
critic put it, ``spoiled children'' who enjoy government subsidies
and a protected market and expect to be applauded simply because
they are French.
</P>
<P>
   The background to the quarrel, though, is more complex. France
is the only European country where a major movie industry has
survived the American movie offensive of the last two decades.
While film production in Italy, Germany and Britain imploded (the
British industry is now showing some signs of recovery), successive
French governments continued to support filmmaking here, notably by
insisting that 40 percent of movies shown on television be French.
</P>
<P>
   As a legacy of the New Wave movement of the late 1950s and
1960s, cinema in France is still treated more as art than as
business.
</P>
<P>
   Most graduates of France's main film school dream of
intellectual kudos before a share of gross profits. Their likely
role model is Jean-Luc Godard rather than James Cameron. And in a
world where the auteur-director is king (and the producer is his
servant), making films becomes almost a birthright guaranteed by
the government.
</P>
<P>
   Unsurprisingly, then, measured by output, France's record is
good. The number of new releases with total or majority French
financing rose from 97 in 1995 to 148 last year; the number of
French cinema-goers also rose during the same period from 140
million to 170 million. But here's the crunch: The French share of
this market fell from 35 percent in 1995 to 27 percent last year,
while the American share rose from 54 percent to 63 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A closer look at 1998 (1999 statistics are not yet available)
gave further cause for concern. Although running far behind
``Titanic,'' three popular French comedies _ ``Le Diner de Cons''
(``The Dinner Game''), ``Les Visiteurs 2'' and ``Taxi'' _ ranked
second, third and fourth in box-office revenue here. Yet they
accounted for 45 percent of the entire take of 148 French movies,
and only three other new French releases made it into the top 40.
So, while more French films are being made, fewer French are seeing
them.
</P>
<P>
   The need for an explanation _ for a scapegoat, perhaps _ was
evident, but the timing of the directors-critics squabble was
accidental. On Oct. 13, Patrice Leconte, a veteran director, sent a
private letter to fellow members of the Society of Auteurs,
Directors and Producers expressing outrage at the way French films
were treated by the Paris press and suggesting an informal meeting
of directors to debate the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that copies of the letter were mistakenly faxed
to the very newspapers he had in mind. And just one sentence in the
letter sufficed to set off conflict. ``Some reviews, which resemble
premeditated assassinations, send chills down my back,'' Leconte
wrote, ``as if the writers' purpose was to kill off all commercial
French cinema designed for a mass audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Leconte, whose popular comedies include ``Les Bronzes'' and
``Ridicule,'' followed up with an interview in the left-of-center
daily Liberation in which he described Liberation, Le Monde and
Telerama as the ``Bermuda Triangle'' of French cinema. ``Since the
fall, all French films have flopped,'' he said. ``I see this
auguring the collapse of French cinema in its entirety. And in
this, French critics are playing the role of gravediggers.''
</P>
<P>
   Other newspapers and magazines, including those singled out by
Leconte for their reviews, promptly joined the fray. And the
coverage only added to the confusion: Some critics thought that
other critics went too far in their abusive language; some
directors thought critics should be ignored rather than attacked;
everyone agreed that the French movie industry was in trouble;
everyone had a different opinion about why.
</P>
<P>
   The critics who felt criticized, of course, also had a chance to
reply. ``Leconte reproaches us for being more indulgent with the
average American movie,'' Olivier Seguret, Liberation's chief film
critic, noted during a round table of movie critics. ``Perhaps he's
right. Take a film like `There's Something About Mary,' a simple
comedy that made me laugh a lot. Obviously it's not a masterpiece.
But would a similar French film please me as much? It is perhaps a
truth that is unpleasant to hear, but isn't the average American
film better than the average French film?''
</P>
<P>
   Serge Kaganski of Les Inrockuptibles, an alternative magazine,
quickly answered. ``I think that the average American film is far
better than the average French film,'' he said, adding that Leconte
``and his friends'' would be wise to look more closely at their own
films. He nonetheless conceded that French films might be treated
more harshly simply because familiarity breeds, well, irritation.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in Le Nouvel Observateur, Jerome Garcin in turn
demolished Leconte's suggestion that critics consider themselves
partners rather than enemies. ``Partners!'' he explained. ``In
other words, associates. Colleagues. Collaborators. And why not
shareholders who take a share of profits like distributors?''
</P>
<P>
   It did not help that the tiff coincided with a particularly
sensitive moment, when French cultural officials were worrying that
the meeting of the World Trade Organization in Seattle would bring
new pressure on France to abandon its quota system and other
measures protecting its movie industry. As it happens, the meeting
failed to start a new round of trade liberalization, and what is
known as the French ``cultural exception'' survived.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But when some 60 movie directors met here Nov. 4 at Leconte's
suggestion, they were still busily wrapping themselves in the
French flag and eager to denounce critics as fifth columnists.
</P>
<P>
   From the closed-door meeting emerged the idea of a directors'
declaration naming irresponsible critics that would be distributed
to moviegoers outside theaters. Several directors agreed to draft
such a text based on notes prepared by Bertrand Tavernier, a vocal
nationalist on the movie question.
</P>
<P>
   Before the declaration could be approved and signed, it was
published by both Le Monde and Liberation. Its contents caused more
waves. Reflecting the spirit of the Nov. 4 meeting, it stressed
that the unidentified directors did not object to constructive
criticism, but it offered endless examples of what it called ``hate
and scorn'' by critics. ``Criticism is in crisis,'' it said, ``in
crisis of intelligence and competence, bereft of analysis and
enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   The directors suggested a pact of coexistence, but their main
suggestion was tantamount to asking critics to surrender their
freedom in the name of patriotism. ``We would wish that no negative
review of a film be published before the weekend that follows its
theater release,'' the draft declaration said. Since movies are
usually released on Wednesdays in France, the theory was that word
of mouth could neutralize poor reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was not well received. ``The proposal is frightening
and inadmissible,'' Liberation fumed. ``You have read correctly.
They want to prohibit only `negative' reviews. The rest are
welcome.'' All that was missing, the newspaper said, was the
composition of the censorship committee that would decide what was
negative. ``Should we extend this system to sculpture, painting,
literature?'' it asked.
</P>
<P>
   The Society of Auteurs, Directors and Producers quickly
distanced itself from the draft declaration, saying that it would
never have carried the society's letterhead. Even more
embarrassing, a statement denouncing the draft was signed by
another 60 directors, among them Bertrand Blier, Cedric Klapisch,
Yves Robert and Agnes Varda. ``We think this directors-critics
polemic is pointless,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   Only Tavernier was willing to defend the draft. ``Even with its
imperfections and errors, it moves things along,'' he said in an
interview with Liberation early this month. The point, he said, is
that many critics had little inkling of the damage they caused with
what he called ``killer words,'' words that particularly affected
serious directors whose natural audience read reviews. And
newspaper attacks on the French movie industry, he added, only
aided American critics of France's ``cultural exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it seems, the furor is over, presumably until the movie
attendance figures for 1999 are released early next year. And what
was its legacy? It showed that French movie critics could be
vicious in their reviews, but it did not prove that they were
responsible for the crisis in French cinema. Rather, perhaps
unfairly, it created the impression that some French directors
believe their right to make films also includes the right to be
praised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1818EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7753 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MENTAL-CONSUMER14-COX     12-13 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-CONSUMER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Insurers often look askance at mental care
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wayne Fisher, director of the Marcus Behavior Center in Atlanta,
treats youngsters with severe behavioral problems. Some of them _
infants and toddlers _ won't eat. Others, usually adolescents, are
violent. But Fisher has found a therapy, called applied behavior
analysis, that works well for both groups.
</P>
<P>
   It takes about the same length of time. It costs the same. And,
most importantly, it has about the same success rate _ around 80
percent, Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   But when the bills are submitted to health insurance companies,
the similarities end. While insurers accept the cost of the
infants' care in about 90 percent of cases, they approve the price
of the adolescents' care only about 20 percent of the time, Fisher
said.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because the adolescents' problems fall into the murky realm
of mental illness, a field of medicine where routine discrimination
is condoned and defended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is that as people become more aware of the situation,
families who have a mentally ill member can push harder to get the
services they need,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the mentally ill say that, while the U.S. surgeon
general's report issued Monday is a step in the right direction,
it's unlikely to change the daily hassles faced by one in four
American families every year when members need mental health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine how frustrating it is to deal with the
financial and insurance end of things,'' said Suzanne Broder, whose
36-year-old son, Chris Byrd, is diagnosed with schizo-affective
disorder. ``It's an extremely unfair situation.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because most employers and insurers still don't offer
equal benefits, or ``parity,'' when it comes to mental illness.
Although a person might have a $1 million lifetime benefit for
medical bills such as heart surgery or leukemia treatment, it's
rare that he or she would have such a benefit for schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, for example, held private insurance for more than a
decade, but he had no outpatient mental health benefits and a
$10,000 lifetime cap on inpatient services. That was exceeded
during his first hospitalization and, since then, his family has
spent at least another $10,000 on unreimbursed services.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has tried to rectify the problem, with
the passage of the Mental Health Parity Act. And 26 states,
including Georgia, have put parity laws on the books. But the
bottom line is that all these laws, often hard-won in legislative
battles, are narrow in focus and don't mandate much. Most require
only that employers already offering mental health benefits be sure
the benefits are equal to traditional medical policies. And, in a
continuing problem for health consumers, the state laws don't
affect the almost 40 percent of workers who are employed by
companies that are self-insured. Those businesses, often large
corporations, are exempt from state mandates under the Employee
Retirement Income Security Act of 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't made much progress in this area,'' said Lei
Ellingson, assistant director of the Carter Center's mental health
program. ``Although we are finally getting some data to debunk the
theory that (parity) would be astronomically expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurers and employers have maintained for years that adding
mental health mandates would be too costly. The Health Insurance
Association of America has reported that any mental health mandates
would bring dramatic hikes in premiums and a 6 percent increase in
the number of uninsured, because many employers would stop offering
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But other studies, including a 1997 report in The Journal of the
American Medical Association, have concluded that insurance
mandates would increase the number of uninsured by only 0.04
percent and suggested that the cost of mental health benefits has
actually been declining.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly because many workers are still hesitant to take
advantage of mental health benefits through employers, out of
concern that their bosses will find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still worried about confidentiality,'' said Pamela
Greensberg, executive director of the American Managed Behavioral
Healthcare Association. ``I think Congress needs to enact
regulations protecting medical records so everyone can feel a
little more comfortable getting the services they need.''
</P>
<P>
   But, for now, families and the doctors and other therapists who
treat them have to fend for themselves. And experts on all sides
recommend that people comb through their health insurance policies
to find the fairest deal they can in an unfair world. For example:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check out the co-payments and deductibles. If you discover
that you have a $500 deductible for mental health care and a $100
deductible for traditional medical treatment, you probably should
seek out another health care plan. And if your insurance is
employer-based, you should find out whether it complies with parity
laws.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure you can choose the provider you want, rather than be
forced to pick a doctor or therapist from a list. And make sure the
insurer offers a range of mental health providers, such as
psychiatrists, psychologists and social workers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Understand the kind of provider you need. If you rely on
medications, you'll probably need regular contact with a
psychiatrist, who can prescribe drugs. On the other hand, if you're
dealing with grief, a divorce or other issues that don't require
medicine, a social worker or psychologist might be the most
appropriate provider.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you're having problems with your insurance coverage, call
the Georgia Mental Health Insurance Advocacy Center Hotline
(404-978-0316 in metro Atlanta, 1-800-933-9896 elsewhere) or
contact the National Alliance for the Mentally Ill of Georgia
(770-234-0855 or
</P>
<P>
   e-mail to NAMI-GA(at)nami.org).
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1818EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7754 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MENTAL-GEORGIA14-COX     12-13 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-GEORGIA14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mental health care in Georgia: Head goes here on so many
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In six cemeteries at Central State Hospital in
Milledgeville, Ga., _ once known as the Georgia Lunatic Asylum _
almost 30,000 mentally ill patients buried in the first half of
this century finally have achieved equality in death.
</P>
<P>
   They were equally nameless, with only numbered iron stakes and
metal discs marking their graves. Many lost even that distinction
when groundskeepers in the 1960s yanked up the stakes and cast them
into thick underbrush. That made it impossible to identify the
patients, because the hospital failed to keep records of the burial
plots, though it detailed how many sheets were cleaned and how many
beans were harvested in its gardens.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the 1980s that deceased patients merited
headstones in the hospital's newest cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unknown humans, shunned when living, deprived of their very
names in death _ and literally only known to God'' is how Joe
Ingram, the hospital's lead attendant for 50 years, described the
patients in a historical account titled ``But for the Grace of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   For Georgia advocates for the mentally ill, the markers are a
silent reminder of one of modern medicine's darkest corners. As
U.S. Surgeon General David Satcher on Monday unveiled a historic
report on the mental health of Americans, advocates noted that the
status of mentally ill Georgians is much improved from what it once
was, thanks to scientific research, better medical treatment,
bulldog advocacy and strong legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many, many good things have happened recently to help
Georgia's consumers,'' said Cynthia Wainscott, executive director
of the National Mental Health Association of Georgia. ``We are
definitely seeing improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   But people with mental illnesses still encounter plenty of
problems and an abiding social stigma that victims of other
illnesses don't face, advocates note. Public and political
attention to mental health issues has not kept pace with growing
attention to AIDS, cancer, heart disease and other physical
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Georgia Department of Human Resources' budget
for mental health services, which include programs for mental
retardation and substance abuse, has been reduced by 11 percent _ a
total of more than $30 million _ over the past four years. The
state still doesn't offer enough residential and community day
programs, advocates say, with many of the mentally ill simply
landing in homeless shelters, hospitals or jails. And when surveyed
this year, more than 300 Georgia mental health care users and their
family members gave community mental health services an average
grade of ``D'' when asked to rank the quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wonderful thing about the (surgeon general's) report is it
is an answer to our cry for attention,'' said Shannon Scheels, the
Georgia executive director of the National Alliance for the
Mentally Ill. ``Mental illness is real, it can be treated and there
is new hope for the future. If we had any complaints, it would only
be why did this acknowledgement take so long?''
</P>
<P>
   Until this decade, Scheels said, mental illness was not
routinely recognized as a biological condition, but rather
something akin to a character flaw. An abundance of scientific and
medical research in recent decades has challenged that view, with
many studies linking mental illnesses to brain function and
chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   But while science has shown that early diagnosis and treatment,
ranging from drugs to counseling and other therapies, can be very
effective in combating mental illness, the traditional stigma
associated with mental problems persists. And while treatments for
heart disease and cancer are routinely covered by insurers and
government agencies, they rarely pay for mental health care with
the same loosened purse strings.
</P>
<P>
   Significant strides made In recent years, Georgians have made
significant strides in gaining equality in treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Legislature enacted a parity act. Under that
law, if an employer offers mental health benefits, they must be
equal to other medical coverage. For example, if there's a $1
million lifetime benefit for traditional medical coverage, the same
must exist for mental health coverage. But the law is limited: Like
other states' parity acts, it does not apply to companies that are
self-insured, meaning it doesn't protect workers for most large
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Medicaid began to offer its members access to newer
medications, under new federal regulations. Now, doctors who don't
prescribe the latest drugs, which have fewer side effects, must
explain why.
</P>
<P>
   And Georgia is cited as a national model for its ``20 by 2000''
program. The program was designed to get 20 percent of people with
mental illnesses or retardation who attend state-sponsored day
programs into jobs, such as sales representatives, clerks,
receptionists or drivers, said Larry Fricks, director of the Office
of Consumer Relations in the Department of Human Resources' mental
health division. This year, that equals more than 4,000 Georgians
with mental disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Fricks, who himself was diagnosed with bipolar disorder, also
known as manic-depression, in 1989, told his story of struggle with
mental illness in Washington on Monday, as part of the surgeon
general's press conference. ``People used to think if you had a
mental illness, you couldn't work,'' Fricks said. ``We've learned,
with the proper medication, work is a treatment, and you'll have
fewer symptoms and move into crisis less frequently.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, the state also has shifted its resources.
Traditionally, the bulk of state money for mental health has been
spent on hospital care, which served almost 20,000 patients last
year. Now, most funds are being spent on community programs, with
more than 23,000 participating in day programs and almost 24,000
living in state-supported residential programs. Thirteen regional
boards also oversee the 212 community centers' activities, with
half of those boards including consumer advocates and patients'
family members. Problems still abound
</P>
<P>
   But some advocates say that daily life remains a challenge for
Georgians with mental illness and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all looks so much better on paper and in theory than it
sounds when you answer our statewide helpline and hear the problems
on the other end,'' Sheels said.
</P>
<P>
   Treating the mentally ill often involves a complicated network
of caseworkers, medication, therapy and support systems that extend
far beyond clinic walls. Often, agencies and individuals are simply
asked to do too much with too little funding or resources, experts
say. Too often, they say, the mentally ill are discharged from
hospitals too soon or released from jail without any treatment.
Because there is such a scarcity of community programs, those most
in need of care often become homeless or repeatedly return to
hospitals and jails.
</P>
<P>
   Scheels said one indicator of the need is the calls taken at
NAMI's statewide helpline. More than half of callers are seeking
community support. And she points to a NAMI survey about
satisfaction with community mental health services. On nine factors
_ ranging from housing to vocational rehabilitation to case
management _ respondents gave an average score of 1.75 on a 1-to-5
scale, with 1 being the lowest grade.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates say progress is being made, with efforts under way
to fix the wrongs _ even the historic ones. Last week, the
Smithsonian Inst in Washington asked Georgia officials to
let it use one of the iron stakes from Central State Hospital,
along with a description of the person it represents, as part of a
display celebrating the 10th anniversary of the Americans With
Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, the Georgia Mental Health Consumer Network began
tracking down Central State patient names and burial locations _ a
mammoth task considering that not only were numbered markers tossed
aside, but the same numbers were often used and then reused for
different people.
</P>
<P>
   The group also hopes to erect a bronze angel to guard over the
graves. ``And to remind society,'' Fricks said, ``to never, ever
allow something like this to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
