r l BC-MENTAL-LIST16-COX     12-13 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-LIST16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Resources for more information on mental health
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   O R G A N I Z A T I O N S
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  County emergency mental health services hotlines: Most metro
Atlanta counties have emergency mental health crisis telephone
lines; look in the blue pages of the business phone directory for
the number in your county. These hotlines handle mental health
emergencies such as suicide prevention and also can refer callers
to counseling centers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  American Foundation for Suicide Prevention, 120 Wall St., 22nd
Floor, New York, NY 10005; 1-888-333-2377. Provides state-by-state
directories of survivor support groups and information on
prevention.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Anxiety Disorders Association of America, 11900 Parklawn
Drive, 100, Rockville, MD 20852-2624; 301-231-9350. Promotes the
welfare of people diagnosed with anxiety problems; has a newsletter
and other services.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Georgia Parent Support Network, 404-875-6801. Provides mental
health information and help for children and families.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  National Alliance for the Mentally Ill, 2101 Wilson Blvd.,
Suite 302, Arlington, VA 22201; 1-800-950-6264.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  National Association of Anorexia Nervosa and Associated
Disorders Inc., P.O. Box 7, Highland Park, IL 60035; 847-831-3438.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  National Depressive and Manic-Depressive Association, 730 N.
Franklin, 501, Chicago, IL 60610; 1-800-826-3632. Provides support
and information, public education and a quarterly newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  National Mental Health Association of Georgia, 404-527-7175.
Provides free informational booklets and brochures. Among the
topics: ``Depression and African-Americans,'' ``Depression in Later
Life,'' ``Women and Depression,'' ``Diagnosing Depression'' and
``New Treatments.'' Some are available in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mental Health Insurance Hotline, 404-978-0316. Helps people
when they are denied insurance payment for needed mental health
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   B O O K S
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``An Unquiet Mind'' by Kay Redfield Jamison (Vintage Books,
$12). A memoir about coping with manic-depression and its
treatment, written by a respected professor at the Johns Hopkins
University School of Medicine, who also co-authored the standard
medical textbook on manic-depressive illness.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Darkness Visible'' by William Styron (Vintage Books/Random
House, $10). A must-read for those suffering from depression, their
families and friends. In 84 pages, the noted author provides one of
the most succinct and compelling accounts of the descent into
darkness, the black hole of worthlessness and pain into which so
many depressed people fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Helping Someone With Mental Illness: A Compassionate Guide
for Family, Friends and Caregivers'' by Rosalynn Carter with Susan
K. Golant (Times Books $24). This 348-page book covers the science,
social and health care aspects of mental illness, and its symptoms
and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Magic Daughter: A Memoir of Living with Multiple
Personality Disorder'' by Jane Phillips, a pseudonym for a French
college professor (Pengiun Books, $11.95). This memoir, about how
Phillips has learned to live with a fragmented personality, began
as a suicide note attempting to explain the everyday hardships in
her life.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Undoing Depression'' by Richard O'Connor, Ph.D. (Little,
Brown, $12.95). Unlearning the habits of depression is the focus of
this book by the executive director of a mental health clinic in
Connecticut, based on his belief that medication and conventional
psychotherapy don't go far enough in helping a person recover from
depression. Chapters explore five key elements of personality:
feelings, thoughts, behavior, relationships and the self.
</P>
<P>
   I N T E R N E T S I T E S
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mental Health Net provides a mental health directory, chat and
support groups, advice columns, information about therapies and
links for any number of conditions, from anxiety to schizophrenia.
www.mentalhelp.net/.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
