<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7756 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSSTAND14-COX     12-13 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newsweek salutes WWII's ordinary Americans
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a refreshingly unique look back at the century, Newsweek
($3.50) uses quotes and vintage cartoons to pay tribute to the
ordinary Americans who made history. As editor at large Kenneth
Auchincloss notes in his introduction, the greatest heroes of the
last 100 years were the GIs of Bill Mauldin's World War II
cartoons. ``They are definitely not Rough Riders, or Sergeant York,
or John Wayne. Yet Willie and Joe .... became the indelible symbol
of the U.S. war effort.'' Among the other ``ordinary''Americans on
Newsweek's list of heroes are the suffragists, the foot soldiers of
the civil rights movement, the antiwar brigades, the feminists and
the entrepreneurs of Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Highs and lows: Excerpts from Time's ($3.50) exclusive cover
story on the Columbine High School tapes have already been widely
reported, but the entire package should be must reading for any
parent. Also of note are Time's annual lists of the best and worst
in entertainment and sports. Top choices include ``All About My
Mother'' (cinema), ``The Sopranos'' (television), Rage Against the
Machine (music), ``Personal Injuries'' and ``Home Town'' (books),
``The Iceman Cometh'' (theater) and the USA women's soccer team
(sports).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Portrait of a year: Life ($4.99) provides some unforgettable
images of 1999, from the ethnic cleansing of Kosovo and the
shootings at Columbine High School to the women's soccer team's
victory and the retirement of Wayne Gretzky. Accompanying the
photographs are the personal stories of Patrick Ireland, the boy
who flung himself out of the window at Columbine, and 6-year-old
Zyrjete Korqa, who fled Kosovo to find refuge in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The price of prosperity: Maybe it's not our imagination after
all. Americans are working harder and longer, according to U.S.
News &AMP; World Report ($3.50). Studies show that between 1977 and
1997, the average workweek lengthened from 43 to 47 hours and the
number of workers putting in 50 hours or more a week jumped from 24
percent to 37 percent. The upside is that prosperity is at an
all-time high. The downside? Few families are able to sit down to a
quiet, home-cooked dinner.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pulp goddess: Before Danielle Steel and Jackie Collins there
was Jacqueline Susann, the best-selling author of ``Valley of the
Dolls.'' On the eve of a new Bette Midler film about Susann, Vanity
Fair ($3.95) profiles the woman who launched the forerunner of
today's book tour and shamelessly promoted her steamy novels. When
the manuscript for ``Valley of the Dolls'' was submitted to Berney
Geis, the editorial staff marched into his office and begged him
not to publish this ``literary trash.'' His wife overruled them,
however, and told Geis, ``I feel like I picked up the phone and I
was listening in on a conversation of women talking about how their
husbands are in bed. Who would hang up on a conversation like
that?''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Going Hollywood? Speculation already abounds about the
successor to Jack Valenti when he retires as head of the Motion
Picture Association of America. One possibility, according to The
New Yorker ($3), is Bill Clinton. Valenti acknowledges that the job
calls for someone who is adept at politics or diplomacy like Henry
Kissinger _ or Clinton. The president would be ``great,'' Valenti
says, ``but he does bring a little baggage with him.'' The job does
have perks that would appeal to Clinton because, Valenti adds, ``if
you're in the insurance business or run the New York Stock
Exchange, you're not around beautiful women every day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: In an interview with Ebony ($2.50), Puff Daddy,
the head of Bad Boy Entertainment, discusses his new love, Jennifer
Lopez, his new album, ``Forever'' and his new clothing line, Sean
John.... What is it like to be touched by an Oprah? People ($2.99)
talks with the authors whose lives have been changed by the TV
host. North Carolina writer Kaye Gibbons used part of the windfall
from Oprah's Book Club to spend a year and a half just being a
mother to her three girls. Alabama novelist Melinda Haynes, who
initially intended to keep living in her five-room trailer, soon
abandoned that notion when ``Mother of Pearl'' became a best
seller. ``I suddenly wanted a house with a doorbell,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
