<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7758 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-MENTAL-CONSUMER14-COX     12-13 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-CONSUMER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Insurers often look askance at mental care
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wayne Fisher, director of the Marcus Behavior Center in Atlanta,
treats youngsters with severe behavioral problems. Some of them _
infants and toddlers _ won't eat. Others, usually adolescents, are
violent. But Fisher has found a therapy, called applied behavior
analysis, that works well for both groups.
</P>
<P>
   It takes about the same length of time. It costs the same. And,
most importantly, it has about the same success rate _ around 80
percent, Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   But when the bills are submitted to health insurance companies,
the similarities end. While insurers accept the cost of the
infants' care in about 90 percent of cases, they approve the price
of the adolescents' care only about 20 percent of the time, Fisher
said.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because the adolescents' problems fall into the murky realm
of mental illness, a field of medicine where routine discrimination
is condoned and defended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is that as people become more aware of the situation,
families who have a mentally ill member can push harder to get the
services they need,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the mentally ill say that, while the U.S. surgeon
general's report issued Monday is a step in the right direction,
it's unlikely to change the daily hassles faced by one in four
American families every year when members need mental health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine how frustrating it is to deal with the
financial and insurance end of things,'' said Suzanne Broder, whose
36-year-old son, Chris Byrd, is diagnosed with schizo-affective
disorder. ``It's an extremely unfair situation.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because most employers and insurers still don't offer
equal benefits, or ``parity,'' when it comes to mental illness.
Although a person might have a $1 million lifetime benefit for
medical bills such as heart surgery or leukemia treatment, it's
rare that he or she would have such a benefit for schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, for example, held private insurance for more than a
decade, but he had no outpatient mental health benefits and a
$10,000 lifetime cap on inpatient services. That was exceeded
during his first hospitalization and, since then, his family has
spent at least another $10,000 on unreimbursed services.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has tried to rectify the problem, with
the passage of the Mental Health Parity Act. And 26 states,
including Georgia, have put parity laws on the books. But the
bottom line is that all these laws, often hard-won in legislative
battles, are narrow in focus and don't mandate much. Most require
only that employers already offering mental health benefits be sure
the benefits are equal to traditional medical policies. And, in a
continuing problem for health consumers, the state laws don't
affect the almost 40 percent of workers who are employed by
companies that are self-insured. Those businesses, often large
corporations, are exempt from state mandates under the Employee
Retirement Income Security Act of 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't made much progress in this area,'' said Lei
Ellingson, assistant director of the Carter Center's mental health
program. ``Although we are finally getting some data to debunk the
theory that (parity) would be astronomically expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurers and employers have maintained for years that adding
mental health mandates would be too costly. The Health Insurance
Association of America has reported that any mental health mandates
would bring dramatic hikes in premiums and a 6 percent increase in
the number of uninsured, because many employers would stop offering
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But other studies, including a 1997 report in The Journal of the
American Medical Association, have concluded that insurance
mandates would increase the number of uninsured by only 0.04
percent and suggested that the cost of mental health benefits has
actually been declining.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly because many workers are still hesitant to take
advantage of mental health benefits through employers, out of
concern that their bosses will find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still worried about confidentiality,'' said Pamela
Greensberg, executive director of the American Managed Behavioral
Healthcare Association. ``I think Congress needs to enact
regulations protecting medical records so everyone can feel a
little more comfortable getting the services they need.''
</P>
<P>
   But, for now, families and the doctors and other therapists who
treat them have to fend for themselves. And experts on all sides
recommend that people comb through their health insurance policies
to find the fairest deal they can in an unfair world. For example:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check out the co-payments and deductibles. If you discover
that you have a $500 deductible for mental health care and a $100
deductible for traditional medical treatment, you probably should
seek out another health care plan. And if your insurance is
employer-based, you should find out whether it complies with parity
laws.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure you can choose the provider you want, rather than be
forced to pick a doctor or therapist from a list. And make sure the
insurer offers a range of mental health providers, such as
psychiatrists, psychologists and social workers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Understand the kind of provider you need. If you rely on
medications, you'll probably need regular contact with a
psychiatrist, who can prescribe drugs. On the other hand, if you're
dealing with grief, a divorce or other issues that don't require
medicine, a social worker or psychologist might be the most
appropriate provider.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you're having problems with your insurance coverage, call
the Georgia Mental Health Insurance Advocacy Center Hotline
(404-978-0316 in metro Atlanta, 1-800-933-9896 elsewhere) or
contact the National Alliance for the Mentally Ill of Georgia
(770-234-0855 or
</P>
<P>
   e-mail to NAMI-GA(at)nami.org).
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
