<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7759 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-MENTAL-GEORGIA14-COX     12-13 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-GEORGIA14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mental health care in Georgia: Head goes here on so many
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In six cemeteries at Central State Hospital in
Milledgeville, Ga., _ once known as the Georgia Lunatic Asylum _
almost 30,000 mentally ill patients buried in the first half of
this century finally have achieved equality in death.
</P>
<P>
   They were equally nameless, with only numbered iron stakes and
metal discs marking their graves. Many lost even that distinction
when groundskeepers in the 1960s yanked up the stakes and cast them
into thick underbrush. That made it impossible to identify the
patients, because the hospital failed to keep records of the burial
plots, though it detailed how many sheets were cleaned and how many
beans were harvested in its gardens.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the 1980s that deceased patients merited
headstones in the hospital's newest cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unknown humans, shunned when living, deprived of their very
names in death _ and literally only known to God'' is how Joe
Ingram, the hospital's lead attendant for 50 years, described the
patients in a historical account titled ``But for the Grace of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   For Georgia advocates for the mentally ill, the markers are a
silent reminder of one of modern medicine's darkest corners. As
U.S. Surgeon General David Satcher on Monday unveiled a historic
report on the mental health of Americans, advocates noted that the
status of mentally ill Georgians is much improved from what it once
was, thanks to scientific research, better medical treatment,
bulldog advocacy and strong legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many, many good things have happened recently to help
Georgia's consumers,'' said Cynthia Wainscott, executive director
of the National Mental Health Association of Georgia. ``We are
definitely seeing improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   But people with mental illnesses still encounter plenty of
problems and an abiding social stigma that victims of other
illnesses don't face, advocates note. Public and political
attention to mental health issues has not kept pace with growing
attention to AIDS, cancer, heart disease and other physical
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Georgia Department of Human Resources' budget
for mental health services, which include programs for mental
retardation and substance abuse, has been reduced by 11 percent _ a
total of more than $30 million _ over the past four years. The
state still doesn't offer enough residential and community day
programs, advocates say, with many of the mentally ill simply
landing in homeless shelters, hospitals or jails. And when surveyed
this year, more than 300 Georgia mental health care users and their
family members gave community mental health services an average
grade of ``D'' when asked to rank the quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wonderful thing about the (surgeon general's) report is it
is an answer to our cry for attention,'' said Shannon Scheels, the
Georgia executive director of the National Alliance for the
Mentally Ill. ``Mental illness is real, it can be treated and there
is new hope for the future. If we had any complaints, it would only
be why did this acknowledgement take so long?''
</P>
<P>
   Until this decade, Scheels said, mental illness was not
routinely recognized as a biological condition, but rather
something akin to a character flaw. An abundance of scientific and
medical research in recent decades has challenged that view, with
many studies linking mental illnesses to brain function and
chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   But while science has shown that early diagnosis and treatment,
ranging from drugs to counseling and other therapies, can be very
effective in combating mental illness, the traditional stigma
associated with mental problems persists. And while treatments for
heart disease and cancer are routinely covered by insurers and
government agencies, they rarely pay for mental health care with
the same loosened purse strings.
</P>
<P>
   Significant strides made In recent years, Georgians have made
significant strides in gaining equality in treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Legislature enacted a parity act. Under that
law, if an employer offers mental health benefits, they must be
equal to other medical coverage. For example, if there's a $1
million lifetime benefit for traditional medical coverage, the same
must exist for mental health coverage. But the law is limited: Like
other states' parity acts, it does not apply to companies that are
self-insured, meaning it doesn't protect workers for most large
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Medicaid began to offer its members access to newer
medications, under new federal regulations. Now, doctors who don't
prescribe the latest drugs, which have fewer side effects, must
explain why.
</P>
<P>
   And Georgia is cited as a national model for its ``20 by 2000''
program. The program was designed to get 20 percent of people with
mental illnesses or retardation who attend state-sponsored day
programs into jobs, such as sales representatives, clerks,
receptionists or drivers, said Larry Fricks, director of the Office
of Consumer Relations in the Department of Human Resources' mental
health division. This year, that equals more than 4,000 Georgians
with mental disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Fricks, who himself was diagnosed with bipolar disorder, also
known as manic-depression, in 1989, told his story of struggle with
mental illness in Washington on Monday, as part of the surgeon
general's press conference. ``People used to think if you had a
mental illness, you couldn't work,'' Fricks said. ``We've learned,
with the proper medication, work is a treatment, and you'll have
fewer symptoms and move into crisis less frequently.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, the state also has shifted its resources.
Traditionally, the bulk of state money for mental health has been
spent on hospital care, which served almost 20,000 patients last
year. Now, most funds are being spent on community programs, with
more than 23,000 participating in day programs and almost 24,000
living in state-supported residential programs. Thirteen regional
boards also oversee the 212 community centers' activities, with
half of those boards including consumer advocates and patients'
family members. Problems still abound
</P>
<P>
   But some advocates say that daily life remains a challenge for
Georgians with mental illness and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all looks so much better on paper and in theory than it
sounds when you answer our statewide helpline and hear the problems
on the other end,'' Sheels said.
</P>
<P>
   Treating the mentally ill often involves a complicated network
of caseworkers, medication, therapy and support systems that extend
far beyond clinic walls. Often, agencies and individuals are simply
asked to do too much with too little funding or resources, experts
say. Too often, they say, the mentally ill are discharged from
hospitals too soon or released from jail without any treatment.
Because there is such a scarcity of community programs, those most
in need of care often become homeless or repeatedly return to
hospitals and jails.
</P>
<P>
   Scheels said one indicator of the need is the calls taken at
NAMI's statewide helpline. More than half of callers are seeking
community support. And she points to a NAMI survey about
satisfaction with community mental health services. On nine factors
_ ranging from housing to vocational rehabilitation to case
management _ respondents gave an average score of 1.75 on a 1-to-5
scale, with 1 being the lowest grade.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates say progress is being made, with efforts under way
to fix the wrongs _ even the historic ones. Last week, the
Smithsonian Institution in Washington asked Georgia officials to
let it use one of the iron stakes from Central State Hospital,
along with a description of the person it represents, as part of a
display celebrating the 10th anniversary of the Americans With
Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, the Georgia Mental Health Consumer Network began
tracking down Central State patient names and burial locations _ a
mammoth task considering that not only were numbered markers tossed
aside, but the same numbers were often used and then reused for
different people.
</P>
<P>
   The group also hopes to erect a bronze angel to guard over the
graves. ``And to remind society,'' Fricks said, ``to never, ever
allow something like this to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
