<HEADER>
A7771 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      12-13 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (jt) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, Dec. 14. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ After hours of impassioned debate _
and just two days before talks begin in Washington _ Israel's
parliament narrowly endorsed Prime Minister Ehud Barak's quest for
a comprehensive peace settlement with Syria. Israel will pay ``a
heavy territorial price,'' Barak acknowledged in an emotional plea
for parliamentary support Monday. But failure to pursue peace with
Damascus ``could cost us in blood,'' he said. By William A. Orme
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY (Washington) _ Defense Secretary William Cohen
Monday ordered an investigation at military bases to determine
whether homosexuals in uniform are being harassed under a
controversial ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy toward gays in the
armed forces. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   HELLER-OBIT (Undated) _ Joseph Heller, the author of
``Catch-22,'' the darkly comic 1961 novel that became a universal
metaphor not only for the insanity of war, but also for the madness
of life itself, died Sunday night at his home in East Hampton, N.Y.
He was 76. The cause was a heart attack, his wife, Valerie, said.
By Richard Severo and Herbert Mitgang.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TRANSIT-STRIKE (New York) _ As the city opened its emergency
operations center for a possibly crippling strike by transit
workers that could begin at midnight Wednesday, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani said Monday that he would wait 24 more hours before going
to court to try to stop the threatened walkout. By Elizabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-VOLPE (New York) _ After tearfully pleading for mercy
and apologizing to Abner Louima for torturing him in a Brooklyn
police station, Justin Volpe was sentenced Monday to 30 years in
prison by a judge who denounced the former officer for an act of
brutalization that he said also harmed the city as a whole. By
Joseph P. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBINE-VIDEOTAPES (Undated) _ New revelations from videotapes
made by the Columbine shooters. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   WALLSTREET-PAYDAYS (New York) _ Wall Street is overflowing with
holiday cheer: Investment banks have set aside $13 billion to pay
bonuses, up 20 percent from last year. Pay packages above $10
million are no longer rare. Yet among Wall Street professionals
whose incomes still astound the rest of America, the mood has
changed. One top trader bemoans the ``opportunity cost'' of
remaining a financier in the Internet age. (The Marketplace
Column.) By Joseph P. Kahn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
