<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-CMGI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI, COMPAQ TO DEVELOP NET SERVICES FOR SHANGHAI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CMGI Inc. is staking another early claim in the Chinese Internet
market, as it joins with Compaq Computer Corp. to form a joint
venture with a Shanghai Internet firm.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI and Compaq have signed a memorandum of understanding with
Shanghai Information Investment Inc., a venture firm funded by the
Chinese government. SII holds controlling stakes in Internet
backbones and broadband services in Shanghai. Now SII will join
with CMGI and Compaq to create a joint venture that will run a
variety of Internet services in China. The three firms also plan to
invest in attractive Chinese Internet startups, just as CMGI has
invested in dozens of such companies in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   No money has changed hands yet, and Bill White, CMGI's executive
vice president of marketing said that the final shape of the
alliance hasn't been settled. But White said the deal will help
secure the Andover, Mass. company's access to an Internet market
that eventually could become the biggest on earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be successful in China, you need partnerships to help you
negotiate the government and commercial relationships,'' said
White.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup survey taken in September found that only one in 10
Chinese has ever used a computer, and only 14 percent of Chinese
citizens have even heard of the Internet. But that still works out
to about 175 million people, a huge market by any standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is an ideal market for companies to get into,'' said
Steven B. Frankel, an analyst with Adams Harkness &AMP; Hill in Boston.
``You want to be there ahead of saturation.''
</P>
<P>
   This is CMGI's second China deal of the year. In September, the
company gave $350 million in stock for shares of equal value in
Pacific Century CyberWorks Limited of Hong Kong. As with the SII
deal, CMGI will work with Pacific Century CyberWorks to seek out
promising Internet investments in China.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI stock soared $17 9/16 to $211 5/8 on the Nasdaq stock
exchange. Compaq stock was unchanged at $25 1/16 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
