<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT-APEX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot says yes to Apex Supply buy
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot has agreed to buy Atlanta-based Apex Supply
Co., a longtime distributor of plumbing and related products.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot said Monday it would pay cash for Apex's 21 locations
in Georgia, Tennessee and South Carolina. Terms of the deal weren't
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition makes clear Home Depot's intentions to court the
professional builder market. In recent years, the Atlanta-based
retailer has been expanding services to small and medium-sized
contractors to augment its core home improvement business.
</P>
<P>
   With Apex, Home Depot can reach a much larger commercial
customer. For example, Apex sells plumbing products to major
builders of apartment complexes, office buildings and shopping
centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are customers we normally don't see in a Home Depot
store,'' said Andy McKenna, senior vice president of strategic
business development. ``The focus inside the store has been the
smaller contractor, but this enables us to go beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its strength in plumbing, Apex is a major
Southeastern distributor of heating and air conditioning products.
It also sells appliances and cabinets to professional builders.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Wayne Hood of Prudential Securities called the
acquisition a smart move. ``In the total scheme of Home Depot, this
is not a large acquisition, but it allows them to test and
understand the professional market better,'' Hood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first place (professionals) go is a supply house,'' Hood
noted. ``The relationships the supply houses have established with
the professionals are very difficult to break...''
</P>
<P>
   At Apex, such relationships have been developed by the Rodbell
family, who founded the company 50 years ago. The Rodbells will
continue to manage the company but will report to McKenna.
</P>
<P>
   While Apex will keep its name and operate as a subsidiary of
Home Depot, eventually the retailer hopes to incorporate some of
Apex's business into the stores.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Home Depot will be able to fill special orders on
some products faster, and it may stock some Apex products in Home
Depot stores. Large contractors would continue to get their
products directly from Apex, McKenna said.
</P>
<P>
   This is Home Depot's second acquisition of an Atlanta-based
company this year. In June, the retailer bought specialty retailer
Georgia Lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
