<HEADER>
A7779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MEMORY-THEATER-REVIEW     12-13 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMORY-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IF MEMORY SERVES': GEE, MOM, INCEST DID HELP YOUR RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(ms) 
 By WILBORN HAMPTON   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sexual abuse of children would not seem the most
obvious choice of subject for a playwright looking for material for
a rollicking new comedy _ unless, of course, one is a devoted
follower of ``Sally Jessy Raphael,'' ``Oprah'' and the other
confessionals that have become the staple of daytime talk
television.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by the delicacy of the topic, Jonathan Tolins plunges
headlong into those murky waters in ``If Memory Serves,'' a spoof
with serious pretensions about recovered memory and our twin
national penchants for celebrity and the public washing of dirty
laundry.
</P>
<P>
   Tolins, whose ``Twilight of the Golds'' offered a superficial
treatment of a family's latent homophobia a few seasons back,
trains his sights this time on a young man coming to grips with the
possibility that his mother, a famous if faded television star, did
more than kiss him on the forehead when she came to tuck him in bed
at night. Or not. Or does it even matter?
</P>
<P>
   ``If Memory Serves'' ostensibly evolves around the character of
Diane Barrow (aptly cast and ably played by Elizabeth Ashley), once
a household name and face via her '70s sitcom, in which she played
a single parent who successfully juggled a career and motherhood,
but who is now reduced to flogging her workout video and watching
herself in late-night reruns with cold cream on her face. But it is
her son Russell Burke (Sam Trammell) who is the real protagonist.
Russell, who has dropped out of college to find himself (he
actually says, ``I need to figure things out''), ends up in
therapy, where he begins to recall his mother's hitting him in the
head with one of her Emmys and some nighty-night kisses that
weren't all that motherly.
</P>
<P>
   The opening scenes serve as a rather prosaic introduction to
some rather stereotypical characters _ a martini-swilling gossip
columnist (Marilyn Sokol); a performance artist (Melanie Vesey) who
hopes her tale of rape by her stepfather for ``Victims Know More''
will make her famous; Diane's swishy gay secretary (Jeff Whitty);
Diane's current young hunk of a boyfriend (Ron Mathews); and
Diane's hard-drinking ex-husband (Tony Campisi). There is another
son, a married computer freak otherwise out of the picture. There
is also Russell's shrink and an ex-maid (both played by Lynda
Gravatt) whose mysterious departure from the Burke household's
employ in Russell's youth may hold a key to what really happened.
</P>
<P>
   After some stale warm-up banter that is supposed to set a comic
tone, Tolins tries to steer his play into more serious territory.
What is to be said about a culture that uses sexual abuse of
children as entertainment? Is personal scandal acceptable if it
leads to an interview by Barbara Walters or a movie contract?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the play never fulfills its ambition. No sooner
does Tolins sidle up to one of these somber issues than he backs
away with a joke. (As Russell begins to get close to a vital
memory, a vision in which his mother quotes the famous line from
``Tea and Sympathy'' _ ``One day when you look back on this, and
you will ...'' _ dissolves the scene.) Occasionally, the playwright
ventures on even thinner ethical ice in suggesting that Diane
should be forgiven simply because she is a television star and
national icon.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ``If Memory Serves'' is undone by the very standards
it attempts to satirize _ the shallowness of television morality.
If, as the play suggests at one point, discovering the truth
through psychoanalysis provides troubled souls a denouement for
their lives, then the second act for Tolins can only end with a
movie-of-the-week deal on which all can live happily ever after on
the residuals.
</P>
<P>
   The play has been given a smooth staging, and under Leonard
Foglia's sharp direction the action moves fast enough that one
doesn't immediately notice all the potholes and cracks in the
ethical argument over which Tolins is leading the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ashley is still a commanding presence, and she gives the
role of Diane the same vivacity she has always brought to the
stage. Husky-voiced and doe-eyed, tossing her head back to address
the flies as much as any person in her line of vision, Ms. Ashley
presents a larger-than-life star whose main concern about any
scandal is what it will do to her ratings. Trammell is a model of
confusion as Russell. Elsewhere in the generally solid cast, Ms.
Sokol's cameo as a hypocritical Hollywood agent is funny, and
Whitty manages to turn the cliche of Diane's secretary (a young gay
man who likes Judy Garland) into at least a sympathetic caricature.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `IF MEMORY SERVES'
</P>
<P>
   By Jonathan Tolins; directed by Leonard Foglia; sets by Michael
McGarty; costumes by Ilona Somogyi; lights by Russell H. Champa;
sound by Laura Grace Brown; original music by Peter Matz;
production stage manager, Linda Bornes. Presented by the Promenade
Theater, Ben Sprecher and William P. Miller, directors; Charles H.
Duggan, Ostar Enterprises, Jennifer Manocherian, Richard Frankel
and Marc Routh. At 2162 Broadway, at 76th St.
</P>
<P>
   With: Sam Trammell (Russell Burke, Adam Burke), Elizabeth Ashley
(Diane Barrow), Tony Campisi (Stan Burke), Lynda Gravatt (Dr.
Margaret Thurm, Mrs. Kennedy), Ron Mathews (Taylor McDonald),
Marilyn Sokol (Linda Simmons, Helen Menken), Melanie Vesey (Pam
Goldman) and Jeff Whitty (Paul Michael).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
