<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7781 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-NASA-NAT     12-13 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-NASA-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        NASA WHISTLEBLOWER TOOK CONCERNS TO WHITE HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 13 - A NASA space shuttle expert worried for
eight years that one of the agency's centers was putting the
shuttle fleet at risk by failing to clarify and update safety
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Now those worries are getting the highest sort of attention -
from White House investigators. The case is the first in the
agency's history to be filed with the White House Office of Special
Counsel, a body that hears whistleblower claims for federal
agencies. The counsel forwarded the case for President Clinton's
review last week.
</P>
<P>
   Mary D. Harris, an electrical engineer at Johnson Space Center
in Houston, had a dilemma she called a ``Catch-22'': while she
couldn't prove there was a safety hazard in an area called
Electromagnetic Interference, she couldn't find any documentation
to prove otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Electromagnetic interference is a barrage of noise vibrations
caused by radar, radio and other signals. All the shuttle's parts
must be able to withstand the noise vibrations that are floating
around the earth's atmosphere. The problem is similar to the reason
airline passengers are barred from using electronic devices that
might interfere with the airplane's radar and communications.
</P>
<P>
   Harris claimed neither she, nor her colleagues, could prove how
much electromagnetic interference the shuttle could withstand
before a part failed because the tests hadn't been conducted in
years, and much of the documentation about it was missing from
NASA's records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under what category does not knowing fall under? Safe? Or
Unsafe?'' Harris wrote in a memo forwarded to NASA investigators in
June. ``My own personal vote is to put not knowing in the unsafe
category. But I don't make the call.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went outside of NASA and I hollered and I screamed,'' Harris
said in a phone interview from Houston. ``If something goes wrong,
no one can say I didn't do what I was supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA investigators who looked into Harris' claims said in a
written response that some of Harris' arguments were sound, but
concluded at no time was the shuttle in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was worried that the radio signals could threaten the
shuttles' critical pieces - parts such as the computers and engine
components - possibly leading to premature aborting of the mission,
within minutes after launch.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said going to the special counsel was a last resort. As
early as 1989, Harris asked for a computer system to gauge how much
interference the parts could withstand. Two years later, she raised
her concerns to NASA safety officials at JSC, as well as
headquarters, but was never satisfied with their responses.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said she thought officials didn't share her concerns
because she thought they didn't believe conducting EMI tests was a
lucrative investment. Harris said if EMI did cause a launch
failure, ``they will ask me as an EMI expert why I didn't say
anything.'' She added, ``If they think they can survive without [an
EMI test], then remove it from the books and management will take
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't claim anyone had broken a law or rule. But Harris
fretted that NASA made only two EMI assessments of the shuttle
since the 1970s, the most recent after the 1986 Challenger
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   With the introduction of cell phones and satellite
communications, the amount of interference has increased in recent
decades. And the shuttles themselves have changed too.
</P>
<P>
   NASA investigators concluded that despite the uncertainty of its
levels, electromagnetic interference has posed no danger to the
shuttle. They drafted a response and sent it to the White House
counsel this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``In almost 100 flights, there have never been any fundamental
EMI problems,'' said Keith Hudkins, a deputy chief engineer at NASA
who headed an investigation into Harris' allegations. That is, no
shuttle has ever malfunctioned or suffered damage from the radio
waves.
</P>
<P>
   But NASA agreed that the processes to evaluate interference were
lacking. The investigators said new tests should be applied to
future additions of parts, called for updating regulations, and
recommended that an assessment of EMI be made.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response to her allegations, NASA admitted to
faulty record keeping about EMI. Although some decades-old
information appears to be lost, the agency pledged it would improve
its future documentation about EMI.
</P>
<P>
   Before Harris' complaint, ``it wasn't a high priority, there
wasn't pressure either way,'' Hudkins said. ``It is time to do it
again. We want to know the environment around our landing sites and
assure ourselves that the changes are within acceptable limits.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for not conducting tests more often is partly because
finding the effects of interference is no small task. It's easier
for airplanes to be tested for EMI than for a shuttle, whose flight
cannot be exactly replicated in a lab test, Hudkins said.
</P>
<P>
   One change, Hudkins said, could be adding shielding to keep
noise transmission from hurting the part. NASA will also contract
an outside group to fly planes around launch site with receivers to
test frequencies as high as 160 miles high in the environs around
the launch pad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
