<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BAUM-THEATRE-REVIEW- &LR;      12-13 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAUM-THEATRE-REVIEW- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ADAM BAUM AND THE JEW MOVIE': AN ECHO AT FULL VOLUME (AT LEAST) 
</HEADLINE>
 ART- NYT  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(ms) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The curtain opens and the actor Ron Leibman,
impeccably attired for business, is sitting at an
impressive-looking desk working the phone. Braying, bellowing,
howling into the phone _ two phones, at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Ring any bells?
</P>
<P>
   In Daniel Goldfarb's ``Adam Baum and the Jew Movie,'' Leibman's
star turn as Sam Baum, a 1940s movie mogul in denial of his Jewish
identity, will remind many theatergoers of his Tony-winning
portrayal of Roy Cohn, the right-wing lawyer in denial over his
homosexual identity in Tony Kushner's ``Angels in America.'' Both
characters are manipulative, bullying, verbally shrewd and
egregiously self-absorbed. Both have now had their hubris brought
extravagantly to life by Leibman, whose evident delight in testing
the boundary between more than enough and too much makes him
perhaps the most effective scenery chewer on the American stage.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that in ``Angels,'' Roy Cohn was a detail in a
much larger tapestry, and in ``Adam Baum,'' a pointed but
unbalanced comedy that opened for a three-week run at the
McGinn/Cazale Theater on Dec. 12, Sam is really all there is. The
play has two other characters _ Baum's 13-year-old son, Adam, and a
writer named Gar Hampson whom Baum has hired to write a script
about anti-Semitism in America _ but they pale in his presence.
It's Sam who has the wit and the charisma, Sam who has the
interesting conflict, Sam who has the secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Baum, a character based on Samuel Goldwyn, is the kind of
man for whom possessions are power and who offers to share them _
from Egyptian cotton shirts to cashews _ because it gives him
leverage, implies a debt.
</P>
<P>
   There's something just a tad threatening in everything he says
and does; when he gives his son a belly kiss, the desperation of a
father's love is palpable. Teaching Adam (Adam Lamberg), a
sweet-tempered boy prone to being teased in school, to shake hands
properly _ ``Look me in the eye, reach your hand out like a knife,
and then take my hand and shake it one, two, three'' _ he is
passing on a lesson in establishing the upper hand. It's a comic
set piece, but it's strident underneath. For Sam, human relations
are a fierce business.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when they call you names at school,'' he tells his son,
``you look them in the eye, shake their hands, and they will learn
to fear and respect Adam Baum.''
</P>
<P>
   He represents a particular kind of American Jew, the stereotype
that is usually, if inaccurately, called self-hating. An Eastern
European immigrant who believes himself to be assimilated, Sam
either can't or won't hear his own thick accent and won't let his
son wear a yarmulke when he isn't in the synagogue. It's Sam's idea
that Americans _ real, Plymouth Rock-type Americans _ think of Jews
as soft, sensitive intellectuals who are committed to arcane
foreign rituals and determined to remain a tribe in the New World.
He deplores this view and feels that the way for Jews to earn
respect in America is to prove they understand the free enterprise
system and beat the Gentiles at their own game: capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   That is ostensibly why he wants to make a movie about
anti-Semitism _ because Darryl Zanuck, the Gentile head of a rival
studio, is developing his own ``Jew movie,'' ``Gentleman's
Agreement.'' It is why he hires a Gentile to write it _ because he
wants the Jews in it to seem like real Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It is why he forbids Hampson even to mention World War II in his
script, an elephantine omission in 1946, when the play is set. And
it is also why, when Hampson turns in a script full of reverence
for Jewish tradition and portrays anti-Semitism as a national trait
(the president is a Jew-hater), Sam is appalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gar, you have written this script as a Jew and not as a
Gentile,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in his heart of hearts, there is more to Sam's Jewish
identity; this become evident in the second act, which takes place
on the day of Adam's bar mitzvah. As it happens, though, the hidden
part of Sam is the less interesting part. As written by Goldfarb,
who studied with Kushner at Juilliard, it is the antic, striving
Sam Baum that is the most captivating element of this play. And
Leibman takes full advantage as he cajoles Hampson _ with flattery
and insult, cooing and screaming _ to make changes in the script,
and bludgeons his son with affection.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big performance _ too big, probably, for the tiny stage
in this 99-seat house. And certainly too big for his onstage
colleagues to match. As Adam, Adam Lamberg is appropriately cute
and awkward (particularly in his hilariously loud, plaid bar
mitzvah suit that his father loves so much); he's supposed to be
overwhelmed by Sam, and he is. But Hampson is another story; the
irony is that in a play about a Gentile writing about Jews, the
Jewish playwright has missed the boat on his own Gentile character.
</P>
<P>
   Hampson is amusingly clueless; he gives Adam _ oy! _ a hammer
and a wrench as a bar mitzvah gift. Nonetheless determined to write
a ``true'' script, he has done his research on the Old Testament.
But his reverence for the dignity of the Jews is expressed in an
anachronistic tone that is tainted with a contemporary kind of
learned tolerance. He never apprehends that Sam's bullying, his
lording of his material success is an expression of his Jewish
pride. He openly disdains it. He's politically correct, smugly so.
</P>
<P>
   That may be a function of the age of the playwright, who is 26,
but the role isn't helped by the actor Christopher Evan Welch,
whose portrayal of Hampson is awfully slack; the character remains
polite and stammering for too long to suit the drama, too
unresistant to the battering he gets from Sam, too wimpy to possess
the artistic integrity the script attributes to him. (He's supposed
to be a hack, perhaps, but a passionate hack.) And when he finally
gets his dander up in a climactic second-act confrontation with Sam
and his own innate anti-Semitism is exposed, the anger is
manufactured, thin. When Sam tells him, exhausted from their
argument, ``I respect your strength; I do,'' you wonder why.
</P>
<P>
   It's a missed opportunity. The play succeeds as a character
portrait, but for the drama to be fulfilling, both Sam and Leibman
need a stronger foil in Hampson. What is he anyway? Chopped liver?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ADAM BAUM AND THE JEW MOVIE'
</P>
<P>
   By Daniel Goldfarb; directed by Brian Kulick; set by Walt
Spangler; costumes by Elizabeth Hope Clancy; lighting by Kevin
Adams; sound by Aural Fixation; production stage manager, Amy
Patricia Stern. Presented by the Blue Light Theater Company, Peter
Manning, artistic director; Greg Naughton, founder; and Mandy
Greenfield, producing manager. At the McGinn/Cazale Theater, above
the Promenade Theater, 2162 Broadway, at 76th St.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Adam Lamberg (Adam Baum), Ron Leibman (Samuel Baum) and
Christopher Evan Welch (Garfield Hampson Jr.).  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
