<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATS-GA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To-be freshmen testers match U.S. average, but overall average
critically poor
 &HT;    By James Salzer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The state's incoming public college freshmen recorded
a first this fall: they were the first class in University System
of Georgia history to match the national average on the Scholastic
Assessment Test.
</P>
<P>
   First-time freshmen entered the system this fall having scored
an average of 1,016 out of a possible 1,600 on the SAT, the same as
the national average, according to figures released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the statewide average for Georgia high schoolers
who took the SAT this year _ not just those who entered a state
public college _ was 969 this year. That average is the second
lowest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The SAT is used by college officials to help them determine who
gets admitted to their schools.
</P>
<P>
   University officials touted the SAT scores as a sign that
Georgia colleges are getting better-prepared students, including
teens who in the past might have gone out-of-state to school but
are staying because of the HOPE scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   However, other figures showing a drop in SAT scores for incoming
freshmen at two-year colleges suggest those campuses are
increasingly becoming the home for many less-qualified students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clear factor is we are directing underprepared students to
two-year institutions,'' said system spokeswoman Arlethia
Perry-Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year college average dropped from 885 to 879 this fall,
while the system-wide average rose from 1,013 to 1,016.
</P>
<P>
   At Georgia Tech, the average for first-time college freshmen
jumped from 1,296 to 1,303, while at the University of Georgia, it
rose from 1,186 to 1,190, according to University System of Georgia
figures. Georgia State's SAT for incoming freshmen rose from 1,048
to 1,050. In 1991, it was 987.
</P>
<P>
   The average score topped 1,000 for the first time at Valdosta
State University and Georgia College and State University.
</P>
<P>
   The SAT gains came at the same time the number of first-time
freshmen rose 6.9 percent, from 30,093 in the fall 1998 to 32,180
this fall. Total enrollment in the system this fall grew 1.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This data documenting our highest-ever SAT scores and a
burgeoning freshman class demonstrate the success of two very
powerful policies _ the Board of Regents' 1996 decision to raise
the bar with our admissions requirements and the significant impact
of the HOPE scholarship program that keeps the best and brightest
in Georgia,'' said University System Chancellor Stephen Portch.
``Many Georgia high school students have responded to our call for
a higher level of preparation by taking the right courses and
studying hard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Students who graduate high school with a 'B' average are
eligible for HOPE, which pays tuition, fees and some book costs.
However, most students fail to maintain the 'B' average in college
and lose the scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   The SAT scores are good news for Portch, who acknowledged
earlier this month that some four-year schools would not meet the
Board of Regents' mandate to eliminate remedial classes by 2001 for
incoming freshmen who don't meet system admissions requirements.
Thousands of students are still entering the system needing
remedial help.
</P>
<P>
   Incoming freshmen at Clayton College and State University
recorded the largest single-year SAT gain this fall, rising from
943 to 988.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton's Acting President Mike Vollmer attributed the
improvement to the school's decision to implement tougher
admissions standards a year ahead of the 2001 Board of Regents
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``By implementing the 2001 admissions standards a year early,
that has raised the bar at Clayton State,'' Vollmer said.
</P>
<P>
   James Salzer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
