<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRIVACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES MAY FAVOR LAW LIMITING ACCESS TO ACCIDENT RECORDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday resuscitated a Kentucky
privacy statute that prevents the names and addresses of
car-accident victims from being given to chiropractors, auto-repair
shops and other business solicitors.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas statute, with some similarities, is in limbo due to a
state court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, in a brief instruction, told the 6th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Cincinnati to reconsider its decision to strike
down the Kentucky law as an unconstitutional restraint on the right
of businesses to speak freely.
</P>
<P>
   The high court also instructed the 6th Circuit to consider, in
its deliberations, the justices' Dec. 7 ruling that a similar
California law is constitutional. That California statute, designed
to protect the privacy of people arrested, prohibits police from
giving the addresses of arrestees to anyone who plans to sell the
information or use the data to market services to them.
</P>
<P>
   By linking the Kentucky law to the valid California statute, the
justices indicated in their instruction that laws limiting access
to accident records might also be constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling that the Kentucky law is constitutional would bode well
for the 1997 Texas statute, now in legal limbo. The Texas law, like
Kentucky's, would limit public access to the addresses of people
involved in car accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas statute, which has not taken effect due to a
state-court challenge, would require people seeking accident
information to provide the name of a person involved in the
collision as well as the date or location of the mishap. The law is
designed to safeguard the privacy of accident victims and protect
them from being inundated with business solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Daily Newspaper Association and the Texas Press
Association have challenged the law as violating the First
Amendment right of free press.
</P>
<P>
   Travis County District Judge Paul Davis Jr. has enjoined the
state from enforcing the law until he issues a ruling on its
constitutionality. He will hear arguments on the law's validity
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1994 Kentucky law, police may give accident reports
only to victims, their lawyers and their insurers. Media outlets
are permitted to get the reports if they use the information for
its news value only.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers, chiropractors and a publisher challenged the law as
restricting their free speech.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge and the 6th Circuit agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the 6th Circuit rejected arguments from the
law's supporters that it was necessary to protect the privacy of
accident victims. If privacy were truly the statute's goal,
lawmakers would have barred news organizations from having access
to the accident records, the appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   The law's supporters then appealed to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
