<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1999 ON TRACK TO BE 2ND WARMEST YEAR IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This year is shaping up to be the second warmest in
the United States and the fifth warmest in the world, following
last year's record high both nationally and globally, the top
government weather experts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Karl, director of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration's National Climatic data center, said 1999
``continues a trend toward long-term (global) warming,'' This
decade has produced five of the warmest years in the United States,
he said in releasing a NOAA report.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, world temperatures have risen by .06 of a degree
Centigrade or .11 of a degree Fahrenheit per decade in the last
century, the report said. A major warming period lasted from 1910
to 1945, and the current warming trend began in 1976, it added.
</P>
<P>
   Some of 1999's heat occurred last month when parts of the Upper
Midwest recorded temperatures in the high 80s. Alaska experienced
unusual 90-degree temperatures in August. Many parts of the nation
_ Midwest, South and East _ suffered through triple-digits in July
and August.
</P>
<P>
   Despite severe droughts in some parts of the country this summer
and autumn, rainfall is nearly normal nationally in the United
States, the report said. At the end of November, average U.S. rain
and snowfall totaled 30.6 inches _ about an inch below normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half of the year was one of the driest this century,
but then we got some very severe flooding,'' said Jack Kelly, Jr.,
director of the National Weather Service, which is part of NOAA.
Much of the flooding occurred along the East Coast in the aftermath
of several hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this year the United States had a record number of five
Category 4 hurricanes, in which the wind blows between 131 to 155
mph. Hurricanes are ranked from one to five based on wind speed,
with Category 5 (wind blowing more than 155 mph) the strongest.
</P>
<P>
   The year was also notable for 200 tornadoes in January alone. On
May 3 and 4, 74 tornadoes tore through Texas, Oklahoma and Kansas,
killing about 50 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country is vulnerable to extreme weather events,'' Kelly
said. In fact, the United States has more severe weather than any
other country in the world mainly because of the number of
tornadoes that strike here. No other country experiences such a
strong clash between cold air and warm air systems that can produce
severe thunderstorms and tornadoes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   NOAA also released the 15 most dramatic weather-related events
of the century:
</P>
<P>
   _The Galveston (Texas) hurricane in September 1900 in which more
than 8,000 people died.
</P>
<P>
   _The tri-state tornado in March 1925 _ the deadliest such storm
in U.S. history _ which cut a 219-mile swath in Missouri, Illinois
and Indiana, killing 695 people.
</P>
<P>
   _The so-called Dust Bowl of the 1930s, in which drought and wind
caused severe dust storms in the Plains states, prompting hundreds
of thousands of people to move.
</P>
<P>
   _The Florida Keys hurricane of September 1935, a Category 5
storm that killed more than 400 people.
</P>
<P>
   _The New England hurricane of September 1938, which submerged
downtown Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   _The great Okeechobee flood and hurricane of September 1938, in
which a Category 4 storm killed more than 1,800 people in Florida
and another 1,600 in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   _The so-called ``storm of the century'' of November 1950 in
which snow and hurricane-force winds hit the Midwest and East
Coast, killing 383.
</P>
<P>
   _Hurricane Camille in August 1969, a Category 5 storm, which
struck Mississippi with more-than-200-miles-an-hour winds. It
killed 256 people and caused $1.4 billion in damages.
</P>
<P>
   _The ``super tornado outbreak'' of April 1974 in which more than
170 tornadoes hit states from the Great Lakes to Alabama during a
17-hour period. The outbreak killed 315 people and injured 6,142.
</P>
<P>
   _The New England blizzard of February 1978, which paralyzed New
England for a week and brought Boston a record 38 inches of snow.
</P>
<P>
   _The El Ninos of 1982-83 and 1997-98, in which warmer-than-usual
water temperatures in the Pacific Ocean disrupted weather patterns
in the United States, often resulting in stronger storms.
</P>
<P>
   _Hurricane Andrew in August 1992, which was the nation's
costliest storm, hitting heavily populated South Florida. It caused
$25 billion in damages and killed 23 people.
</P>
<P>
   _The ``super storm'' of March 1993, which paralyzed the entire
East Coast from Florida to Maine, killed 79 people and injured more
than 600.
</P>
<P>
   _The great Midwest flood of the summer of 1993 after record
winter snows and spring rains caused severe flooding along with
Mississippi and Missouri Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   _The Oklahoma-Texas-Kansas outbreak of 74 tornadoes on May 3 and
4 of this year, which, among other things, destroyed parts of
Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
the e-mail address jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1903EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7797 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-OBIT-HELLER-3RDTAKE-N     12-13 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HELLER-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: at Yale.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He also wrote a few television plays and, later in the '60s and
early '70s, worked on movie scripts. Among those in which he had a
hand were ``Casino Royale'' (Columbia, 1967) and ``Dirty Dingus
Magee,'' (MGM, 1970), both of them spoofs.
</P>
<P>
   Heller used dialogue from his novel in several adaptations for
the theater. A two-act play, ``We Bombed in New Haven,'' was
produced at the Yale Repertory Theater in 1967 and reached Broadway
the following year for a brief run. ``Catch-22,'' a one-act play,
was produced at the John Drew Theater in East Hampton in 1971.
``Clevinger's Trial,'' based on Chapter 8 of ``Catch-22,'' was
produced in London in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Not until 1974 _ 13 years after publication of ``Catch-22'' _
did he produce another novel, ``Something Happened.'' It was about
alienation in the American business community and it focused on Bob
Slocum, a sad, lackluster careerist with no true friends, dogged by
a feeling of always being trapped.
</P>
<P>
   John W. Aldredge , writing in The Saturday Review, said Slocum
``is haunted by the sense that at some time in the past something
happened to him, something that he cannot remember but that changed
him from a person who had aspirations for the future, who believed
in himself and his work, who trusted others and was able to love,
into the person he has since unaccountably become, a man who
aspires to nothing, believes in nothing and no one, least of all
himself, who no longer knows if he loves or is loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years after ``Something Happened,'' Heller's third novel,
``Good as Gold,'' was published. It was a cynical look at the
workings of the federal government, in which an aide to the
president says, ``Just tell the truth ... even if you have to lie''
and the president himself spends most of his first year in office
writing ``My Year in the White House.'' Into the maw of public
service comes Bruce Gold, an English professor who wants to become
the first ``real'' Jewish secretary of state. The fact that Henry
Kissinger has already served in that capacity does not deter him,
because he feels that Kissinger could not possibly be Jewish, since
he was a party to the war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   R.Z. Sheppard, writing in Time magazine, called the book ``a
savage, intemperately funny satire on the assimilation of the
Jewish tradition of liberalism'' into the American mainstream. ``It
is a delicate subject,'' Sheppard wrote, ``off-limits to non-Jews
fearful of being thought anti-Semitic and unsettling to successful
Jewish intellectuals whose views may have drifted to the right in
middle age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``God Knows,'' published in 1984, made some of the best-seller
lists for a time. It was basically the story of King David told in
the voice of Mel Brooks. Richard Cohen, writing in The Washington
Post, said the book was ``more of a nightclub shtick than a
novel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to see my people as living in a vacuum, not anarchy,
but living in a void of meaning _ even my King David, who despairs
because God doesn't talk to anyone,'' Heller said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, while trying to cope with the dissolution of his 1945
marriage to the former Shirley Held, Heller noticed he had trouble
swallowing, and then found he could not pull a sweater over his
head. The mysterious malady turned out to be Guillain-Barre
syndrome, a life-threatening neurological disease involving partial
paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Certain he was near death, he spent two months in Mount Sinai
Hospital and four months of rehabilitation at the Rusk Institute at
New York University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, he married Valerie Humphries, the nurse who had
helped restore him fully to health at Mount Sinai. He also got
through his illness with the help of his friends, especially Speed
Vogel, a retired textiles executive and former herring taster at
Zabar's specialty-food store, and Mario Puzo, the novelist, who
lent him money after it became known that Heller had let his health
insurance lapse.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of his illness, Heller wrote ``No Laughing
Matter,'' with Vogel. Christopher Lehmann-Haupt, writing in The New
York Times, said he thought the Heller-Vogel collaboration was
``not only richly amusing, it is positively cheering.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Heller published ``Picture This,'' in which he reflects
on such historical figures as Rembrandt, Socrates, Plato and the
American presidents of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rayner, of The Times of London, said that Heller
attacked his main themes _ ``power and intellect are incompatible,
that politicians wage disastrous wars for no good reason ... and
that humanity learns nothing from its mistakes _ and gets away with
it most of the time, for the simple reason that he is funny .... He
refuses to take institutions seriously; or rather ... he takes them
so seriously they become hilarious.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller, a handsome man with a great shock of curly white hair,
enjoyed sampling Chinese food around New York with such friends as
Brooks and Puzo, who were used to his barbed wit and crotchety
ways. Barbara Gelb once described her friend for The New York Times
Book Review:
</P>
<P>
   ``For 20 years now, I have managed to overlook his frequent
sulkiness, his gluttonous table manners and his tendency to growl
No before he even knows what the question is. I have stayed on good
terms with him largely because I relish his aberrant sense of humor
and his skewed way of looking at life _ an outlook he insists has
changed little since he wrote `Catch-22.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my novels, there's concern with the way people use and
misuse language to obscure and confuse and build barriers,'' he
said. ``The way that words are corrupted or the way words
contradict themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Valerie, he is survived by a daughter,
Erica Heller of New York; a son, Theodore of New York, who is a
novelist; and a sister, Sylvia Heller of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Heller's agent, Deborah Karl, said he had completed a novel
called ``Portrait of an Artist as an Old Man,'' to be published
next fall by Simon &AMP; Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   Asked once what his biggest fears were, Joseph Heller replied,
``I fear death, nursing homes and vaccinations.'' But he came to
grips with death, he said, explaining, ``Everyone else seems to get
through it all right so it couldn't be too difficult for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
