<HEADLINE>
JOSEPH HELLER, 76; FAMED FOR WAR NOVEL `CATCH-22' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes excerpt; e and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Heller, whose black-comic novel of World War II,
``Catch-22,'' contributed an enduring phrase to the English
language, died Sunday at his East Hampton, N.Y., home of a heart
attack. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a calamity for American letters,'' Kurt Vonnegut said
Monday, reacting to news of the death of his friend and fellow
novelist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catch-22,'' which draws on Mr. Heller's own experiences flying
60 combat missions as an Army Air Force pilot, encapsulated the
absurdity of war in the form of a supposed military edict of that
name, whereby insane men are excused from combat but the act of
requesting permission not to fight proves one's sanity _ and
fitness to fight.
</P>
<P>
   The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary (1993) defines
Catch-22 as ``a condition or consequence that precludes success, a
dilemma where the victim cannot win.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the book's enduring appeal (it has sold some 10 million
copies since 1961) is its having come to be seen to represent any
individual trapped in a can't-win situation owing to bureaucratic
rule or regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the book remains relevant in so many ways,'' Mr.
Heller said last year, ``because it deals not so much with the war
situation but our societal situation (in) which people are at the
mercy of other people.''
</P>
<P>
   None of Mr. Heller's other books enjoyed the success of
``Catch-22.'' Drawing on writers as diverse as Kafka, Celine, and
Nathanael West, it presents an unrelentingly absurdist vision of
war. Characters bear such names as Major Major, Milo Minderbinder,
and Captain Aardvark. Airmen hire themselves out to bomb their own
base. And its hero, Yossarian, is forthright about his desire ``to
live forever or die in the attempt.''
</P>
<P>
   The book received mixed reviews on initial publication. The
novelist Nelson Algren hailed it as ``the strongest repudiation of
our civilization to come out of World War II.'' But The New Yorker
called it ``a debris of sour jokes, stage anger, dirty words,
synthetic looniness.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether synthetic or natural, that very quality of looniness _
along with its anarchistic rage _ helped make ``Catch-22'' a
central text of the '60s. For many readers, the Vietnam War seemed
like Mr. Heller's vision writ large and all too real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in my book accuses everyone else of being crazy,''
Mr. Heller once said. ``Frankly, I think the whole society is nuts
_ and the question is: What does a sane man do in an insane
society?''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Heller was born on May 1, 1923, in the Coney Island
section of Brooklyn, N.Y. His father was a deliveryman. After
working in the Norfolk (Va.) Navy Yard, Mr. Heller enlisted in the
Army Air Force. He served in Italy and rose to the rank of
lieutenant. ``I was so brainwashed by Hollywood's image of heroism
that I was disappointed when nobody shot back at us,'' he once
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Heller went to the University of Southern California and New
York University under the GI Bill. He earned his BA from the latter
institution in 1948, an MA from Columbia University in 1949, and
spent a year at Oxford University on a Fulbright Scholarship. He
also wrote short stories, several of which were published in The
Atlantic Monthly and Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   After two years teaching English composition at Pennsylvania
State University, Mr. Heller became an advertising copywriter. ``I
didn't want to be in advertising all my life,'' he said, ``or in
any other job . . . and I looked on the writing of a novel as a way
out.''
</P>
<P>
   That novel was ``Catch-22,'' and Mr. Heller spent eight years
working on it. His next novel, ``Something Happened,'' a bleak
satire of business life, took him 13 years. Part of that delay was
attributable to Mr. Heller's writing several plays, screenplays,
and even TV scripts (under the name Max Orange) for the situation
comedy ``McHale's Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Heller published four other novels: ``Good As Gold'' (1979),
``God Knows'' (1984), ``Picture This'' (1988), and ``Closing Time''
(1994), in which Yossarian and several other characters from
``Catch-22'' appear.
</P>
<P>
   He published two nonfiction works: ``No Laughing Matter''
(1986), with Speed Vogel, an account of his harrowing, if
ultimately successful, battle with Guillain-Barre syndrome, a
paralyzing nerve disorder; and ``Now and Then: From Coney Island to
Here'' (1998), a memoir.
</P>
<P>
   He had recently completed the final revisions for his last
novel, ``Portrait of an Artist as an Old Man.'' It is scheduled to
be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Heller leaves a wife, Valerie Humphries, and two children
from his first marriage, Erica Jill and Theodore Michael.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE TERM ``CATCH-22'' ENTERS THE LANGUAGE
</P>
<P>
   (Excerpted from ``Catch-22,'' by Joseph Heller.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean there's a catch?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure there's a catch,'' Doc Daneeka replied. ``Catch-22.
Anyone who wants to get out of combat duty isn't really crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   There was only one catch and that was Catch-22, which specified
that a concern for one's own safety in the face of dangers that
were real and immediate was the process of a rational mind. Orr was
crazy and could be grounded. All he had to do was ask; and as soon
as he did, he would no longer be crazy and would have to fly more
missions. Orr would be crazy to fly more missions and sane if he
didn't, but if he was sane he had to fly them. If he flew them he
was crazy and didn't have to; but if he didn't want to he was sane
and had to. Yossarian was moved very deeply by the absolute
simplicity of this clause of Catch-22 and let out a respectful
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's some catch, that Catch-22,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best there is,'' Doc Daneeka agreed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1912EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
