<SLUG> BC-MA-MANUFACTURING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT HIGHLIGHTS STATUS OF MANUFACTURING IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts' manufacturing output has risen 20
percent since bottoming out in 1992, but the number of jobs in
manufacturing has not returned to the levels reached in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   A report on the state's manufacturing sector released Monday by
MassInsight, a Boston consulting firm, spotlights one aspect of a
state economy in the midst of a dramatic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   The report touted improvements in the manufacturing sector and
said that with its highly educated work force the state has
distinct advantages in attracting or keeping today's cutting-edge
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manufacturers investing in technology have more complicated
work processes _ whether they're in textiles or plastics or in new,
high-tech manufacturing businesses _ and need high-skilled workers
to make their plants go,'' said Williiam Guenther, president of
MassInsight. ``That means places like Massachusetts are back in
business.''
</P>
<P>
   But technology-based increases in productivity have also helped
to restrain job creation after the collapse of the once-dominant
minicomputer and defense industries.
</P>
<P>
   According to MassInsight, the state's manufacturers produced
nearly $33 billion in goods in 1997, the last year for which data
is available. That surpasses production during the peak years, 1987
through 1989. It is a sharp improvement from the state's $27.4
billion production level in 1992, when old-line manufacturers were
in the midst of layoffs and downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   But employment among manufacturers is nowhere near the levels of
the 1980s. The state had 448,300 manufacturing jobs in 1998; in
1982 through 1985, more than 600,000 people were employed in the
goods-producing sector.
</P>
<P>
   And they were good jobs: Manufacturing jobs pay, on average,
about $50,000 annually, compared with about $36,000 earned by other
workers on the state, MassInsight said.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, Guenther noted that manufacturing employment
has stabilized. The decline in payrolls halted in 1996, and
payrolls began rising in 1997 and in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Although Massachusetts has fewer manufacturing jobs than in the
past, Guenther said a trend in which companies locate plants near
the engineers who design and improve them would work to the state's
advantage in the future.
</P>
<P>
   And 450,000 manufacturing jobs ``is a lot of jobs,'' Guenther
said. ``Some people assumed we were going to become an all-service
economy not only here but in the United States. The headline is:
Not so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1913EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
