</P>
<P>
   The book received mixed reviews on initial publication. The
novelist Nelson Algren hailed it as ``the strongest repudiation of
our civilization to come out of World War II.'' But The New Yorker
called it ``a debris of sour jokes, stage anger, dirty words,
synthetic looniness.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether synthetic or natural, that very quality of looniness _
along with its anarchistic rage _ helped make ``Catch-22'' a
central text of the '60s. For many readers, the Vietnam War seemed
like Mr. Heller's vision writ large and all too real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in my book accuses everyone else of being crazy,''
Mr. Heller once said. ``Frankly, I think the whole society is nuts
_ and the question is: What does a sane man do in an insane
society?''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Heller was born on May 1, 1923, in the Coney Island
section of Brooklyn, N.Y. His father was a deliveryman. After
working in the Norfolk (Va.) Navy Yard, Mr. Heller enlisted in the
Army Air Force. He served in Italy and rose to the rank of
lieutenant. ``I was so brainwashed by Hollywood's image of heroism
that I was disappointed when nobody shot back at us,'' he once
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Heller went to the University of Southern California and New
York University under the GI Bill. He earned his BA from the latter
institution in 1948, an MA from Columbia University in 1949, and
spent a year at Oxford University on a Fulbright Scholarship. He
also wrote short stories, several of which were published in The
Atlantic Monthly and Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   After two years teaching English composition at Pennsylvania
State University, Mr. Heller became an advertising copywriter. ``I
didn't want to be in advertising all my life,'' he said, ``or in
