out.''
</P>
<P>
   That novel was ``Catch-22,'' and Mr. Heller spent eight years
working on it. His next novel, ``Something Happened,'' a bleak
satire of business life, took him 13 years. Part of that delay was
attributable to Mr. Heller's writing several plays, screenplays,
and even TV scripts (under the name Max Orange) for the situation
comedy ``McHale's Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Heller published four other novels: ``Good As Gold'' (1979),
``God Knows'' (1984), ``Picture This'' (1988), and ``Closing Time''
(1994), in which Yossarian and several other characters from
``Catch-22'' appear.
</P>
<P>
   He published two nonfiction works: ``No Laughing Matter''
(1986), with Speed Vogel, an account of his harrowing, if
ultimately successful, battle with Guillain-Barre syndrome, a
paralyzing nerve disorder; and ``Now and Then: From Coney Island to
Here'' (1998), a memoir.
</P>
<P>
   He had recently completed the final revisions for his last
novel, ``Portrait of an Artist as an Old Man.'' It is scheduled to
be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Heller leaves a wife, Valerie Humphries, and two children
from his first marriage, Erica Jill and Theodore Michael.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE TERM ``CATCH-22'' ENTERS THE LANGUAGE
</P>
<P>
   (Excerpted from ``Catch-22,'' by Joseph Heller.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean there's a catch?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure there's a catch,'' Doc Daneeka replied. ``Catch-22.
Anyone who wants to get out of combat duty isn't really crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   There was only one catch and that was Catch-22, which specified
that a concern for one's own safety in the face of dangers that
were real and immediate was the process of a rational mind. Orr was
crazy and could be grounded. All he had to do was ask; and as soon
as he did, he would no longer be crazy and would have to fly more
missions. Orr would be crazy to fly more missions and sane if he
didn't, but if he was sane he had to fly them. If he flew them he
was crazy and didn't have to; but if he didn't want to he was sane
and had to. Yossarian was moved very deeply by the absolute
simplicity of this clause of Catch-22 and let out a respectful
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's some catch, that Catch-22,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best there is,'' Doc Daneeka agreed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
