<HEADLINE>
BOSTON, US CHAMBERS SPLIT ON RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Siding with Bay State universities instead of its
own sister organization, the Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce
said Monday it strongly disagrees with an effort by the US Chamber
of Commerce to broaden a law that requires scientists to reveal the
details of federally funded research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seriously concerned that the US chamber's position
would stifle intellectual inquiry and impede the development of new
technologies,'' said Paul Guzzi, president of the Boston chamber.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a new law that allows anyone to file a request under
the Freedom of Information Act to obtain ``all data'' produced by
researchers on federal grants, including those at hospitals and
universities. The act has given citizens access to federal
documents for 22 years, but until now it did not extend to
nongovernment workers.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the law last year. But the White House Office of
Management and Budget later ruled that it applied only to a limited
range of research information, and not to any research conducted
before the law took effect last month.
</P>
<P>
   The US chamber says the OMB illegally narrowed the scope of the
law. Last week, it filed three Freedom of Information requests,
including two directed at Harvard University scientists, that are
designed to provoke a lawsuit over the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Boston chamber criticized that effort, saying the
new law, if interpreted broadly, could force researchers to break
confidentiality agreements with their research subjects or business
partners and add costs as researchers are forced to respond to
repeated request for information.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the group said, the law may discourage
collaboration between industry and university or hospital
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The two chambers of commerce have independent boards and
funding. William Kovacs, a US chamber vice president, said the
Boston group was siding with its own members, which include Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   The law was largely prompted by a Harvard study that linked
increased air pollution to higher death rates and which was cited
by the US Environmental Protection Agency in setting tougher
clean-air regulations. Those rules would cost industry $50 billion
to $150 billion a year, though they have been suspended pending a
review by the courts, Kovacs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's very important to see the data that supports
multibillion-dollar regulations,'' Kovacs said, ``and we don't see
any reason why the Boston chamber would want to keep this secret.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard researchers submitted their data to peer review and
to a review panel funded by both the EPA and business groups. But
releasing it to the public, they have said, would violate
confidentiality agreements with their research subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The US chamber says that confidential information is routinely
withheld during Freedom of Information requests and would not be
released under the new law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 1926EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SYRIA-NYT &LR;      12-13 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SYRIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRIAN FOREIGN MINISTER TAKING A GENTLER MANNER TO TALKS WITH
ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-ISRAEL) 
(ms) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ In his only previous encounter with an Israeli
prime minister, back in 1991, Farouk al-Sharaa waved an old British
poster that identified the Israeli, Yitzhak Shamir, as wanted for
crimes of terrorism. The one time that Sharaa addressed the Israeli
public directly, in 1995, he spoke in an angry tirade.
</P>
<P>
   But now Sharaa, who is 61 and has been Syria's foreign minister
for the last 15 years, is seen as embodying his country's hopes for
a swift peace. On Wednesday in Washington, he will become the
highest-ranking Syrian ever to meet with an Israeli leader, and as
the two sides resume talks for the first time in nearly four years,
Sharaa is expected to present a gentler face than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Sharaa, who left Syria Monday for talks with Israel's current
prime minister, Ehud Barak, has said he is heading for Washington
``serious about making peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The new language appears to reflect broader changes that seem to
have persuaded Syria's president, Hafez al-Assad, that a settlement
with Israel is less a threat than an opportunity. Apart from Assad,
al-Sharaa is seen here as the man who speaks with more authority
than anyone else, and the fact that he will represent Syria in the
talks is regarded as a sign of determination to put the long
Syrian-Israeli conflict to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to peace, there are only two people who really
matter today _ Assad himself and Sharaa,'' said a prominent Syrian
who would speak only on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   A calm, elegant and engaging man who speaks English well,
al-Sharaa was named foreign minister in 1984 in large part,
diplomats here say, because his manner was seen as likely to win
support in the West. His predecessor, Abdulhalim Khaddam, now a
vice president, was known for a hectoring style.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sharaa is generally regarded as among the most able of Arab
foreign ministers. But he has always been a loyalist and has never
allowed his own personality to eclipse that of Assad. Until now,
his only encounters with Israelis have been hostile, reflecting the
deep tensions between the countries.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1991 episode, al-Sharaa was the head of Syria's
delegation to the Middle East peace conference in Madrid, the
American-sponsored gathering that set current peace efforts in
motion. His display of the old British poster came after Shamir's
denounced Syria as a terrorist state.
</P>
<P>
   Many Syrians still describe the confrontation with great pride,
but American officials who had worked overtime to persuade Syria to
attend the gathering regarded it at the time as a major setback.
</P>
<P>
   It was a reminder, they have said, that when it came to the
quest for a Syrian-Israeli peace, the two sides carried so much old
bitterness that they were in effect starting from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sharaa's only direct comments to the Israeli public came four
years later, when peace talks were already under way but mutual
distrust had allowed only scant progress. At the urging of American
officials, who had argued that Syria should make its case directly
to ordinary Israelis, al-Sharaa granted an interview to Israeli
television, becoming the highest-ranking Syrian official ever to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   But the sharp criticism he voiced of Israel and its policies was
widely seen as counterproductive to the peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1998, Shara spoke with bitterness again. Angry at
the fact that the peace talks that broke down in 1996 had not been
reconvened, al-Sharaa criticized the ``ineffective role'' played by
the Clinton administration, which at the time seemed to be giving
low priority to Israeli-Syrian peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States bears a considerable part of the
responsibility of allowing this process to reach a dead end,''
al-Sharaa said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sharaa, who is a Sunni Muslim, was born in 1938 in the
southern city of Dara. He earned a bachelor's degree in English
literature from the University of Damascus in 1963, and later
studied international law at the University of London.
</P>
<P>
   Before being named ambassador to Italy in 1976, he spent 13
years as a manager and official of Syrian Arab Airlines. He was
appointed minister of state for foreign affairs in 1980, and became
foreign minister four years later. Al-Sharaa suffered an aneurysm
this fall, and was taken to Beirut, the Lebanese capital, where he
underwent heart surgery. But he appears to have made a swift
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   And his demeanor has turned particularly upbeat in recent days,
with the decision by the two sides to resume talks in an atmosphere
so optimistic that both Israel and Syria have said a deal could be
reached in a short time.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sharaa was initially seen in the West as more a spokesman
than a decision-maker. As recently as the early 1990s, foreign
visitors who met in small groups with Assad noted that al-Sharaa
tended for the most part to listen in silence or to take notes for
his boss.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, according to well-connected Syrians and
Damascus-based diplomats, al-Sharaa's stature has swelled. He is
one of the few Syrian officials with whom the reclusive Assad, 69,
is believed to meet regularly, instead of merely consulting by
phone. And although al-Sharaa still defers to the president, he now
often completes his boss' thoughts, and has otherwise become a
vocal participant in the discussions with foreign representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Syria and Israel held direct talks, ending in
1996, the Syrian team was led by Walid Moallem, the ambassador in
Washington. Moallem, who is scheduled to leave his post soon, is
generally respected, but the fact that his rank did not regularly
allow him direct access to Assad was seen by some experts as a
factor in slowing the pace of the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, al-Sharaa is described by diplomats here as a man
who truly acts as Assad's right hand.
</P>
<P>
   The first round of talks is expected to be held in Blair House,
the presidential guest quarters across the street from the White
House, and will almost certainly be behind closed doors. In
announcing last week that the two sides would resume direct
negotiations, President Clinton suggested that further discussions
would probably shift to an undisclosed location in the Middle East
after al-Sharaa and Barak returned to their capitals.
</P>
<P>
   But Syrian officials, have insisted that the talks continue in
the Washington area, where they hope the that administration
officials might prove more likely to put pressure on Israel for
compromises on key disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats in Syria say they understand that the State
Department is now seeking a suitable location for further talks
somewhere in the Virginia countryside.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear who might head the Syrian delegation in any
further talks. Other members of the Syrian team that left Damascus
with al-Sharaa Monday included Youssef Shakour, a deputy foreign
minister and former chief of staff of the Syrian Army; Riad
al-Daoudi, the foreign minister's legal adviser, and Maj. Gen.
Ibrahim al-Omar, representing the Syrian Army.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
