<SLUG> BC-CHAMBER-FOIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON, US CHAMBERS SPLIT ON RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Siding with Bay State universities instead of its
own sister organization, the Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce
said Monday it strongly disagrees with an effort by the US Chamber
of Commerce to broaden a law that requires scientists to reveal the
details of federally funded research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seriously concerned that the US chamber's position
would stifle intellectual inquiry and impede the development of new
technologies,'' said Paul Guzzi, president of the Boston chamber.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a new law that allows anyone to file a request under
the Freedom of Information Act to obtain ``all data'' produced by
researchers on federal grants, including those at hospitals and
universities. The act has given citizens access to federal
documents for 22 years, but until now it did not extend to
nongovernment workers.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the law last year. But the White House Office of
Management and Budget later ruled that it applied only to a limited
range of research information, and not to any research conducted
before the law took effect last month.
</P>
<P>
   The US chamber says the OMB illegally narrowed the scope of the
law. Last week, it filed three Freedom of Information requests,
including two directed at Harvard University scientists, that are
designed to provoke a lawsuit over the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Boston chamber criticized that effort, saying the
new law, if interpreted broadly, could force researchers to break
confidentiality agreements with their research subjects or business
partners and add costs as researchers are forced to respond to
repeated request for information.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the group said, the law may discourage
collaboration between industry and university or hospital
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The two chambers of commerce have independent boards and
funding. William Kovacs, a US chamber vice president, said the
Boston group was siding with its own members, which include Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   The law was largely prompted by a Harvard study that linked
increased air pollution to higher death rates and which was cited
by the US Environmental Protection Agency in setting tougher
clean-air regulations. Those rules would cost industry $50 billion
to $150 billion a year, though they have been suspended pending a
review by the courts, Kovacs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's very important to see the data that supports
multibillion-dollar regulations,'' Kovacs said, ``and we don't see
any reason why the Boston chamber would want to keep this secret.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard researchers submitted their data to peer review and
to a review panel funded by both the EPA and business groups. But
releasing it to the public, they have said, would violate
confidentiality agreements with their research subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The US chamber says that confidential information is routinely
withheld during Freedom of Information requests and would not be
released under the new law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
