<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7827 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CROATIA-TUDJMAN-NYT &LR;      12-13 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROATIA-TUDJMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABSENCE OF DIGNITARIES AT HIS FUNERAL IS SEEN AS BOOST TO TUDJMAN'S
PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia _ Croatia's first president, Franjo Tudjman, was
buried Monday in a somber ceremony, mourned by tens of thousands of
the Croats to whom he helped deliver independence and by a
less-than-stellar panoply of foreign dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands lined the streets in a light rain as the funeral
cortege moved from the presidential palace, on one of Zagreb's
hills, to the Mirogoj cemetery, on another. Tudjman's oak coffin,
covered with a Croatian flag, rested on a gun carriage drawn by a
jeep. The ceremony, which had a military cast, was capped by a
Roman Catholic service for this onetime Communist general in Tito's
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The flag was removed from the coffin by a military honor guard
and folded, displaying its red-and-white checkerboard pattern.
Tudjman's widow, Ankica, took the flag, sobbing, and held it
against the black veil in front of her face, hiding her tears.
</P>
<P>
   But given Tudjman's authoritarian rule and his reluctance to
cooperate with the United Nations' tribunal on war crimes in the
former Yugoslavia, the level of representation here by foreign
countries was noticeably low. The few heads of state present
included President Suleyman Demirel of Turkey and the Croat member
of Bosnia's three-member presidency, Ante Jelavic, and there were
heads of government from Hungary, Macedonia, Slovenia and
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Western countries generally sent lower-level diplomats, or _
like the United States _ were represented only by their
ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
   This calculated snub could backfire in the coming parliamentary
and presidential elections and help Tudjman's party, the Croatian
Democratic Union, or HDZ, warned Davor Butkovic, a political
analyst writing in the daily newspaper Jutarnji List. ``Such a
demonstration of distaste for Tudjman will not only strengthen and
unite the voting base of the HDZ, which is anti-European anyway,
but may seriously affect those who are still undecided,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Notes of condolence came from some former colleagues and enemies
including President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, President
Milo Djukanovic of Montenegro and the Bosnian Muslim leader, Alija
Izetbegovic.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman's death and the parliamentary election planned for Jan.
3, which a six-party opposition coalition is expected to win, are
likely to set Croatia in a more Western-oriented, democratic
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Even Tudjman's critics here have praised him for his role in
founding Croatia from the wreckage of Tito's Yugoslavia, and they
say his position in history is secure.
</P>
<P>
   But Tudjman, who was 77 years old, also conspired with Milosevic
to divide Bosnia between them. His army was responsible for one of
the largest and most rapid sieges against an ethnic population in
modern Europe, during the Bosnian war: the expulsion in August 1995
of at least 150,000 Croatian Serbs, driving them into Bosnia and
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman ruled like an autocrat with a single party, after the
model of Tito himself. After 1993, and especially in the period
after his stomach cancer was diagnosed in late 1996, officials say,
he grew increasingly remote, impatient and averse to hearing bad
news.
</P>
<P>
   Jadranko Crnic, the chairman of the Constitutional Court until a
week ago, said it was not proper to criticize Tudjman too harshly
so soon after his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Croatia needs to move in a more democratic direction,''
said Crnic in an interview. ``Everyone in every political party
should accept the idea that there should never again be a president
with as much power as he had under the current constitution.
Everyone should agree that power should flow from the Parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   Crnic remembered how Tudjman criticized him sharply for not
putting his hand over his heart during the playing of the national
anthem _ a gesture here of devotion to Tudjman's ruling Croatian
Democratic Union, not to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I told him as chairman of the court I could favor no
party,'' Crnic said. ``And he was very angry with me. So we kept
our distance from each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats and officials have described Tudjman's
tantrums and obsessions with Western ``plots'' supposedly designed
to undermine Croatia's independence and to keep it out of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Croatian intelligence services have a large role here, state
television is under the control of the ruling party and the
independent press is harassed. But perhaps more important for the
West has been Tudjman's reluctance to cooperate fully with the war
crimes tribunal in The Hague and to hand over indicted individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman also discouraged the Bosnian Croats, who can vote in
elections here, from cooperating fully with the Bosnian Muslims in
the federation that the United States cobbled together before the
Dayton peace accords, which stopped the civil war in Bosnia in late
1995. Tudjman's party has important political support from these
voters in the Croatian diaspora.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential elections should also be held within 60 days of
Tudjman's officially declared time of death, at 11:15 p.m. on Dec.
10. But even Crnic said the constitution is a bit unclear about
whether presidential elections, likely to include two rounds of
voting, must be finished in 60 days or simply called by then.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The opposition, led by the Social Democratic leader, Ivica
Racan, and the Social Liberal leader, Drazen Budisa, has promised
better cooperation with the war crimes tribunal and is being openly
supported by the United States. Budisa is considered likely to be
the main opposition candidate for the presidency, while Racan is
likely to become prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Racan, the former leader of the Communist Party, is highly
respected here as a man with democratic instincts, who supported
elections here in 1990 rather than cracking down with the force of
the party.
</P>
<P>
   But the two opposition leaders have done little to press their
case in the last two weeks, said a former adviser to Tudjman and
political analyst, Slaven Letica. ``The opposition has been doing
nothing and expects to win anyway,'' Letica said. ``They missed the
last five years, doing nothing except negotiating with the
leadership of Tudjman's party, and many of them acquired the same
bureaucratic mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Letica said, he predicts that the opposition parties will
win almost twice as many seats as Tudjman's party, but not enough
for a two-thirds majority that would guarantee constitutional
change. And any new government will inherit a poisoned chalice of
economic recession, high unemployment and taxes, bloated state
industries and a large national debt, requiring painful political
choices to turn the economy around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
