<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7828 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-OBIT-HELLER-TEX     12-13 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HELLER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSEPH HELLER, AUTHOR, COINER OF `CATCH-22,' DEAD AT 76
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Heller, one of this century's most important writers who
died on Sunday of a heart attack at age 76, didn't invent the
satiric novel. But ``Catch-22,'' Mr. Heller's acknowledged World
War II classic published in 1961, may have perfected the form _
and, in its way, forever overshadowed Heller's brilliance as a
novelist.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his five subsequent novels, two autobiographies and
three stage plays had their own literary wonders to offer, but Mr.
Heller was destined to be known almost exclusively for his first
novel.
</P>
<P>
   Even ``Closing Time,'' Mr. Heller's sequel to ``Catch-22's''
tale of bombardier Capt. John Yossarian and his motley associates,
failed to crack the top rungs of national bestseller lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Readers who loved `Catch-22' didn't want the characters
changing even a little,'' said Kenneth Kirkland, a publishing
industry analyst in New York City. ``Joe Heller wrote such a
perfect first book that he didn't leave himself or Yossarian room
to grow with readers after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas novelist/musician Kinky Friedman, a longtime friend, said
Mr. Heller ``has now flown his last mission. He had a lot of
friends, enjoyed a lot of food and had a lot of fun in his life. He
enjoyed his celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Heller, born in Brooklyn to poor Jewish parents, graduated
from high school in 1941 and soon after enlisted in the Army Air
Force. Sent to Corsica during World War II, he flew 60 missions as
a B-25 bombardier before returning to the United States and
attending college on the G.I. Bill. Afterward, he taught college
literature courses before becoming an advertising copywriter for
Time and Look magazines, and serving as promotion manager for
McCall's.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Heller's ambition was to write full time. While still
working at the magazines, he began selling short stories to
Esquire, Atlantic Monthly and other publications. In 1961,
``Catch-22,'' his first novel, was published but gained little
attention from critics or sales in bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   But, in 1962, author S.J. Perelman praised the book in an
interview with the old New York Herald-Tribune. Gradually, word of
mouth and more frequent media attention helped ``Catch-22'' gain a
worldwide audience, particularly on college campuses. Eventually,
``Catch-22'' sold more than 10 million copies and the book's title
entered modern jargon.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Yossarian and other combat fliers faced an odd
military regulation. Anyone crazed by battle fatigue could ask to
be relieved of combat flight duty. But anyone asking to be excused
from dangerous missions had to be sane. Other no-win situations in
the book were also described as ``Catch-22.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, The User's Webster Dictionary defines ``Catch-22'' as ``a
situation in which one is victimized either way, as when an
applicant is refused jobs because he lacks job experience and lacks
experience because he is refused jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Income from the book and appearances on the lecture circuit left
Mr. Heller time to write as he pleased. Fighting writer's block and
a fear of disappointing fans, he wrote plays _ ``We Bombed in New
Haven'' and a stage adaptation of ``Catch-22,'' as well as
``Clevinger's Trial,'' based on scenes from the novel, before
finally publishing ``Something Happened'' in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something Happened,'' a wrenchingly accurate first-person
account of a business executive's life, was brilliantly realized.
Critics swooned, but readers were surprised by the tale's lack of
humor, even humor of a darker nature. ``Something Happened'' didn't
fail completely _ it sold respectably enough to make bestseller
lists _ but, despite its near-unparalleled excellence, it was soon
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Heller kept trying. ``Good as Gold'' in 1979 was a clumsy
attempt to satirize U.S. government in general and Henry Kissinger
in particular; ``God Knows'' in 1984 was a muddled exploration of
biblical history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Mr. Heller was found to have Guillain-Barre syndrome, a
paralyzing disease of the nervous system. The severe illness
required a long convalescence, which he recounted in ``No Laughing
Matter.'' The book included material about Mr. Heller's divorce
from his first wife and the courting of his second, a nurse who was
assigned to his case.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman recalled visiting Mr. Heller in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Radio personality Don ``Imus and I went to see him, and Imus
brought a copy of ``Something Happened'' with him,'' Friedman said.
``Heller looked at ``Something Happened'' and said, `That's my
favorite book of mine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Mr. Heller was back with ``Picture This,'' another
novel that failed to satisfy readers addicted to Yossarian. Word
soon spread through the publishing industry that Mr. Heller was
finally working on a ``Catch-22'' sequel; critics predicted that,
whether written badly or well, the book would sell impressively.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Closing Time'' didn't. A story that transposed Yossarian
and a few other ``Catch-22'' characters to modern-day New York City
and the business rat race there, ``Closing Time'' became considered
the publishing dud of 1994, at least based on low sales. The book
failed to crack any prestigious bestseller list. Critics offered
lukewarm praise, noting the author's apparent certainty that modern
civilization, along with Yossarian &AMP; Co., was pretty much doomed.
</P>
<P>
   While Mr. Heller's health had improved _ he was able to conduct
numerous interviews to publicize ``Closing Time'' _ there was still
a sense, in his public comments as well as his work, that time was
limited.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Mr. Heller published ``Now and Then: From Coney Island
to Here,'' a scintillating autobiography that alternately evoked
chuckles and tears. In the book, Mr. Heller honestly addressed his
perceived deficiencies as a son, husband, father and author, and
the elegiac tone hinted ominously at a writer's public farewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be remembered for his classic books, his dark _ some
would say wicked _ wit and his bright _ some would say sacred _
wisdom,'' Friedman said. ``I say Joseph Heller is brother to
Yossarian.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
