A7829 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TOBACCO-COX     12-13 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Profit cuts of tobacco companies coming from foreign farming
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An alliance of anti-smoking public-health groups says
tobacco farms from Kentucky to Georgia are making less money
because of Big Tobacco's shift to foreign markets not because of
the multibillion-dollar settlement with 46 states.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to be released today by the Campaign for
Tobacco-Free Kids, researchers argue that, even before the national
settlement, the nation's largest tobacco companies started shifting
to overseas farms.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette companies disputed the report and officials said quota
cuts are the cost of litigation. Higher prices, companies say, have
led to dramatic drops in domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
   But the 89-page report, co-sponsored by the American Cancer
Society and the American Heart Association, says farmers are
hurting primarily because business is going abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco litigation is like a drop in the bucket of the
ocean in terms of the current plight of the family farmer,'' Matt
Myers, president-designate of the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids,
said Monday. ``Most of the decline in the use of American tobacco
documented by this report occurred before the tobacco industry's
settlement with the states.''
</P>
<P>
   In two years, Kentucky tobacco farmer Henry West has watched the
basic quota for burley tobacco drop more than 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Like a suburbanite whose home falls in price, a tobacco farmer
who loses quota watches his most valuable asset depreciate. With
federal price supports, farmers can make up to $4,000 an acre.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unfriendly circumstances in this country have contributed
to (Big Tobacco) moving production to other parts of the world,''
West said in an interview Monday. ``I'm sure they don't have that
same attitude in other parts of the world. In fact, they look
forward to the jobs that it creates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take Marlboro, for example. Marlboro made here is more likely
to have our tobacco in it. But Marlboro made in Moscow, or
wherever, is less likely to have our tobacco _ and that takes its
toll.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the nation's biggest tobacco companies agreed to pay
a $206 billion settlement to 46 states. Another $5.15 billion was
set aside to compensate growers over 12 years for an anticipated
decrease in cigarette demand.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the U.S. Justice Department brought suit against
Big Tobacco in an attempt to to recover hundreds of billions of
federal health care dollars spent to treat illnesses blamed on
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the real threat to farmers, claims the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the 6- to 10-percent decline in U.S. consumption, which
we expected to see in 1999 as a result of the settlement, will have
only a small impact on the family farmer because of how much
American tobacco is not used in domestic cigarettes,'' Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   Myers said the purpose of the report, which relied on statistics
from cigarette companies and the U.S. Agriculture Department, was
to underscore the ``hidden changes'' between Big Tobacco and
domestic growers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Philip Morris, the country's largest cigarette maker,
discounts the report.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Pheil, director of communications for Philip Morris USA,
said the company's mix of domestic and foreign tobacco in U.S.
cigarettes has remained at 3-to-1 for years. There's been a
``significant decline'' in consumption since last year's
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The report ``is a manifestation of the anti-smoking forces
trying to drive a wedge between tobacco growing communities and the
tobacco companies,'' Pheil said. But Terry Harper of Georgia, a
fourth-generation tobacco farmer, believes foreign markets are the
root of his problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible,'' Harper said Monday. ``This is our borrowing
power at the bank. That's our asset.'' Three years ago, Harper
invested $70,000 on tractors and barns _ specialized equipment that
can't be used elsewhere on the farm. He uses only about 40 percent
of the equipment today because of decreased demand. West, the
Kentucky tobacco farmer, doesn't smoke. But he can agree with
public-health agencies that children shouldn't light up.
</P>
<P>
   Adults, though, should be free to make up their own minds, he
says. West, like other farmers, are into tobacco for the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what pays our bills,'' West said. ``It's what puts food
on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
