<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-N     12-13 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN FORCES EXPECTED TO SEIZE CHECHEN CAPITAL WITH 10 DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and map are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAKHACHKALA, Russia _ Russian forces advanced to the outskirts
of Grozny Monday, as the senior Kremlin policymaker on Chechnya
predicted that the city would be seized within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's fighting was a fresh indication that the battle for the
Chechen capital has entered a decisive phase even as thousands of
civilians remained trapped in the city.
</P>
<P>
   After a lull of several days, the Russian military resumed
artillery barrages against Grozny. Russian forces had suspended air
and artillery attacks against the city to encourage civilians to
flee. But to keep military pressure on the Islamic militants there,
the Russians now intend to stop the bombardment for several hours a
day and then start up their attacks again.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Vladmir Shamanov, commander of the Western Group of
forces in Chechnya, said the Russian troops had no plans to stage a
frontal assault on the city. But he also disclosed that Russian
soldiers would conduct reconnaissance and commando operations
inside Grozny to help Russian troops infiltrate and occupy the
city.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed that efforts to establish a foothold on the outskirts
of the city were already under way. Russian troops briefly seized
the airport in the Khankala district on the city's edge, but by
Monday night the rebels seemed to have the airfield under their
control, according to reports from the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will try to establish a foothold on the outskirts and get
the civilians out by military transport,'' Shamanov said. ``After
they are out, reconnaissance and other special operations will be
carried out over two or three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the Russian military would be able to
help Grozny's civilians leave the city before its capture.
</P>
<P>
   In the fighting elsewhere in Chechnya, the Russian Air Force
said it had lost one aircraft, but insisted that this was the
result of a mechanical failure. Islamic militants said they had
shot the plane down.
</P>
<P>
   The intensifying conflict has provoked alarm in the West that
many civilian lives will be lost. The Russians have established two
escape routes for civilians to leave the city.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows for sure how many civilians are still in Grozny,
but estimates range up to 50,000. With the city surrounded by
Russian armor and bands of militants roaming the streets, however,
many people appear too frightened to try leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Both Russian officials and the rebels say civilians have been
killed in the fighting _ Prime Minister Vladimir Putin said in
parliament Monday that 68 civilians were killed in recent days _
but each side has blamed the other for the casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Vollebaek, the chairman of the Organization of Security and
Cooperation in Europe and Norway's foreign minister, has begun a
visit to the region to assess the situation. Russia agreed to the
visit last month at a European security conference in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   Vollebaek will arrive on Tuesday here in Makhachkala, the
capital of Dagestan, a small Caucasus republic that borders
Chechnya and is part of Russia. Dagestan was invaded by
Chechen-based Islamic rebels in August, the first blow in what has
become a raging war.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Vollebaek plans to visit Russian-controlled areas
of Chechnya and the neighboring republic of Ingushetiya, where
thousands of refugees are still living in squalid camps, before
returning to Europe to brief the OSCE and NATO on his findings.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely, however, that the Russian government will be
influenced by any Western calls for restraint now that it senses it
has the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage the rebels to surrender, the Russian Parliament on
Monday passed a law providing an amnesty to any rebels who turn
themselves in by Feb. 1. Putin said the move was an important part
of the Kremlin's strategy to prevail in the conflict while limiting
Russian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The fall of Grozny, however, is unlikely to wait that long.
Nikolai Koshman, the Russian deputy prime minister who oversees
Chechnya policy, said he expected Russian forces to capture the
city within seven to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   That estimate may be optimistic; Grozny is a big city and may
contain die-hards. But Shamanov has vowed that the Islamic rebels
in Grozny will not survive the winter.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military has had two basic objectives: isolating the
rebels in Grozny to force their capitulation, and chasing the rest
of the rebel force into the mountains to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces have made steady progress toward both ends.
Grozny appears to be surrounded, and Russian forces have taken key
towns in the south. Urus-Martan has fallen to the Russians, and
Shali has been encircled.
</P>
<P>
   When possible, Russian forces have sought to intimidate towns
into surrendering. At the southern town of Chiri-Yurt, militants
said they were ready to give in, according to reports from
Chechnya. Towns that have become bases of rebel resistance, perhaps
even against the will of many of their inhabitants, have been
pummeled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task was to create an outer circle around Grozny and to
destroy or push the remnants of the bandits to the mountains,''
Shamanov said, using the military's term for the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the number of combatants in the conflict have
varied. The Russian military has refused to say how many of its
troops are involved, but it is believed to exceed 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Igor D. Sergeyev said the rebel force consisted
of 2,000 militants in Grozny and another 2,000 in the south. That
is far fewer than the 15,000 men the rebels were once said to have.
Either way, however, they are badly outnumbered.
</P>
<P>
   There seems little prospect of a political compromise that might
avert Russia's military seizure of Grozny. With an eye to Western
public opinion, the Kremlin has said it is willing to talk as long
as its demands are met: the handover of the Chechen warlords who
led the attack on Dagestan and the release of hundreds of hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a Russian audience, Putin indicated on Sunday that
he did not expect a political solution. ``We have no choice but to
carry this anti-terrorist operation through,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
