<HEADER>
A7834 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-VOUCHER-HNS &LR;      12-13 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-VOUCHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES LET STAND VERMONT'S TUITION-REIMBURSEMENT PROGRAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Refiling for those needing) 
 
STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday cleared the way for
Vermont to keep providing tuition assistance to private, secular
schools, while withholding similar aid from parochial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Religious-school parents had unsuccessfully challenged the state
funding program as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that Vermont's refusal to assist sectarian schools
in the same way it aids other private institutions amounted to
religious discrimination, in violation of the parents' First
Amendment right to practice their religion free of governmental
interference.
</P>
<P>
   But the Vermont Supreme Court, in a decision the federal
justices let stand, ruled that the state's decision to withhold
tuition assistance to parochial schools was required by the
constitutional mandate that government not endorse religion.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. high court's refusal, without comment, to hear the case
neither set a national precedent nor settled the growing political
debate regarding whether states should provide tax breaks, or
``vouchers,'' to parents who send their children to private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of voucher programs, mostly Republicans, view them as
an effective way to give parents greater choice in deciding where
their children are educated.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents, largely Democrats, regard vouchers as an
abdication of government's primary responsibility to use tax
revenue to improve the public school system, not to subsidize
private institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, by declining to hear the case, sidestepped the
opportunity to resolve the constitutional conflict between the
opposing state obligations of ensuring people the right to practice
their faiths freely and of not endorsing religion.
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont parochial-school parents, in their unsuccessful
appeal to the justices, pressed the court to favor the First
Amendment right to free exercise of religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religious expression _ including choosing to educate one's
child in a religious tradition _ has long been valued, not feared,
in our constitutional tradition,'' wrote the parents' lawyer,
William Meub of Rutland, Vt., in a legal brief to the justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed for many low-income parents, choosing how to educate
their children may be one of the few available vehicles for
expressing publicly their beliefs about matters of ultimate
concern,'' Meub added. ``Vermont's unjustified exclusion of
religious schools from its (tuition) program effectively precludes
low-income parents from enjoying the fulfillment and satisfaction
such expression brings.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vermont Attorney General William Sorrell countered that the
First Amendment prohibits states from giving tuition assistance to
religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right to send one's child to a sectarian school does not
include the right to have the government pay for religious
education,'' Sorrell wrote in a brief to the justices. ``The state
has no obligation to subsidize a religious education. On the
contrary, it is barred from doing so by the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the case was a Vermont statute that calls for school
districts in the state either to provide a public high school or
pay the tuition for a student to attend a private, neighborhood
institution.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont's tuition-reimbursement program, which dates back 130
years, is aimed at high school students whose local school
districts do not operate a public high school. State law allows
such school districts to pay tuition for students to attend a
public or private high school.
</P>
<P>
   Of Vermont's 290 school districts, 88 paid tuition for all or
some of their high school students in the 1995-96 school year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Chittenden, Va., School Board authorized that
tuition be paid for students attending private parochial schools,
including Mount St. Joseph Academy, a Catholic high school in
nearby Rutland. But the Vermont education department intervened and
withheld state money to the school district, saying that its
planned tuition payments for parochial schools would be
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Parents of academy students then sued the state, arguing that
its refusal to pay tuition violated their religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   But a state trial court sided with Vermont, ruling that tuition
payments to religious schools would violate the constitutional
separation of church and state. The Vermont Supreme Court agreed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
