<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TRIPP-TRIAL-1STLD-WRI     12-13 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING OPENS ON WHETHER TRIPP WILL STAND TRIAL FOR TAPING
LEWINSKY
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Drops `illegally' from lede.) 
 (ms) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELLICOTT CITY, Md. _ Some of the prosecutors who helped direct
the independent counsel's investigation of President Clinton told a
court hearing Monday that they never promised Linda Tripp immunity
from prosecution in Maryland for taping telephone conversations
with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the three prosecutors said they told Ms. Tripp that if
she turned over the tapes and cooperated with them in investigating
the president's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, they would make it
almost impossible for Maryland authorities to win a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors' accounts came on the first day of a hearing to
determine whether Mrs. Tripp must stand trial here in Howard
County, a suburb of Baltimore, on charges of violating a state law
against secretly recording telephone conversations.
</P>
<P>
   While the impeachment battle has long since been concluded, Mrs.
Tripp remains enmeshed in the drama she helped create. She has been
indicted on two felony counts for which she could face up to 10
years in jail for taping Ms. Lewinsky as the latter talked about
her relationship with the president. Maryland is one of several
states that prohibit tape recording telephone conversations without
the other person's consent.
</P>
<P>
   One of the prosecutors, Jackie Bennett, who had been a deputy
independent counsel, told the court that he had tried to explain to
Mrs. Tripp that the immunity agreement he offered did not bind the
state of Maryland but only the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, he made it clear that it would be
extremely difficult for Maryland to prosecute her because the tape
recordings and everything else connected with them would have been
produced to the independent counsel, Ken Starr, under a grant of
immunity guaranteeing they could not be used against her in any
legal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a constitutional matter we could not prevent Maryland from
bringing a prosecution,'' he said. ``What we could do is make it a
very, very difficult if not insurmountable for the state to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the scenario described by Bennett, the state would have to
demonstrate that it learned of Mrs. Tripp's taping through some
other means than the activities of the independent counsel,
including his report to Congress asserting Clinton had committed
impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp herself was absent for Monday's hearing and is not
expected to be present at any time during the week, even if Ms.
Lewinsky testifies. Her lawyer, Joseph Murtha, Monday asked and
received permission from Judge Diane O. Leasure for Mrs. Tripp to
be absent during the entire hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But Murtha read aloud an affidavit given by Mrs. Tripp in which
she insisted that she only cooperated with Starr's office because
of assurances that she was totally safe from any prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett and another former member of Starr's staff, Stephen
Binhak, both told the court that when Mrs. Tripp first informed the
independent counsel's office in January 1998 that she had made tape
recordings on her home telephone she was concerned that she might
have violated Maryland's laws. Binhak said it was one of the main
topics of conversation when he, Bennett and others from the office
went to Mrs. Tripp's home in Columbia, Md., on Jan. 16 to discuss
taking control of the tape recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Binhak said he explained that the federal government and the
state of Maryland were separate entities and one could not bind the
other. ``I told her we would do all we could to make it an
evidentiary problem for the state of Maryland,'' he said. But, he
added, ``I don't think she was grasping the technicalities. She
believed we would literally just be able to stop the state from
bringing an indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   If the judge rules that the immunity conferred on Mrs. Tripp by
lawyers from Starr's office does not extend to Maryland, state
prosecutors face a second, more daunting hurdle. They will try to
show this week that they and members of the grand jury learned of
Mrs. Tripp's taping through means other than Starr's activities.
</P>
<P>
   If the prosecutors fail to win either argument, they have
acknowledged they will be left with little evidence with which to
bring their case against Mrs. Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett also told the court Monday that in the first few days
after news of the Lewinsky investigation appeared in the media, he
received a frantic telephone call from the elected prosecutor of
Howard County, Marna McLendon, on Jan. 26, 1998. He said Ms.
McLendon told him she was coming under tremendous pressure to
investigate Mrs. Tripp under the state's wiretap laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``She indicated that she was under pressure that was becoming
unbearable to her,'' he said, including much from local Democrats.
``There was political pressure to bring an indictment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
