<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-KNESSET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK OVERCOMES STIFF RESISTANCE IN KNESSET TO TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Giving up war-won land in the Golan Heights for
peace with Syria will be painful, but is a price worth paying,
Prime Minister Ehud Barak insisted Monday before a stormy session
of Israel's parliament as he sought a declaration of support for
the dramatic diplomatic initiative.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Knesset, voting 47-31 with 24 abstentions, gave
its blessing over the talks in Washington Wednesday, the highest
level negotiations in a half century of conflict between the
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our supreme responsibility is to act today so that we will not
dig new rows of graves tomorrow in a conflict that could have been
ended,'' Barak said in a hoarse voice over bursts of angry shouts
from the opposition. He stopped intermittently to glare at hecklers
while the speaker of the Knesset banged a gavel and tried to
restore order.
</P>
<P>
   As Barak spoke some 5,000 Golan settlers and their supporters
demonstrated on a cold, rainy hilltop outside the parliament
building. Later thousands of activists for Peace Now held a counter
demonstration supporting Barak's intiative.
</P>
<P>
   The sincere optimism that seems to have swept through the Middle
East after this breakthrough in the Israeli-Syrian track of the
peace process has been met with the mounting tension within Israel
over whether the Jewish state should give back land that it paid
for with the lives of young soldiers in the 1967 and 1973 Mideast
wars.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that even if Barak can reach a deal with the Syrians,
he will have to work perhaps even harder to sell the deal to his
constituents back home. Barak has reaffirmed a campaign promise
that he would not sign any final peace agreements unless Israel had
a chance to vote on it in a public referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Foreshadowing the challenge he faces, seven members of Barak's
own 68-member coalition voted against the symbolic measure and 19
abstained, including all 17 members of the ultra-Orthodox Shas
party.
</P>
<P>
   Barak dismissed the less-than-overwhelming Knesset endorsement
as a ``temporary stage'' on the way to a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we succeed in bringing before the nation a peace agreement
with Syria that will strengthen Israel's security . . . it will
pass by an overwhelming majority,'' he said in a statement
following the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Legendary hawk and opposition leader, Ariel Sharon, addressing
the Knesset after Barak, fumed that Syrian President Hafez Assad
was a ``dictator whose path was ending'' and accused Barak of
gambling away Israel's security for his own political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel is being asked to pay by giving up strategic assets
while getting nothing in return,'' Sharon added.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was raucous although relatively restrained by Israeli
standards, especially considering the profound issue at hand.
Giving back the Golan Heights where some 18,000 Israelis have lived
for a generation will not be an easy task for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly four years since peace talks collapsed between
Israel and Syria, Barak and Assad have taken a dramatic step
forward by agreeing to resume negotiations _ and holding them on a
higher level than they ever have been in the 51-year history of the
state of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Barak will meet Wednesday and Thursday with Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouk Sharaa, who will be representing the aging and
ailing Assad, 69, who analysts say is anxious to reach a peace deal
to put the nation's affairs in order before his politically
inexperienced son Bashar takes over.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are expected to be grueling. Even though the two sides
are expressing optimism, their final positions seem far apart.
</P>
<P>
   Syria insists that Israel, which captured the strategic Golan
Heights in 1967 and held onto it in bloody fighting in 1973, pull
its troops back to the pre-war 1967 borders which would end at the
northern shores of the Sea of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has publicly balked at such borders as jeapordizing
Israel's military security and access to the Sea of Galilee,
one-third of Israel's water resources.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is demanding that Syria demlitarize its border which is
now heavily fortified with tanks and more than six divisions of
soldiers. Israel is also insisting on establishing early warning
military monitoring posts in the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   A peace agreement between Israel and Syria would likely defuse
the conflict in Lebanon, the last active Arab-Israeli warfront in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has vowed to withdraw Israeli troops from Lebanon by July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
