<SLUG> BC-RENTED-BABY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER RECEIVES 30 MONTHS FOR RENTING BABY TO SMUGGLERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional trim included) 
 
By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Honduran woman who rented her baby for use by
illegal immigrants wanting to pose as a family as they crossed the
Texas border from Mexico was sentenced to 30 months in federal
prison Monday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Melinda Harmon sentenced Susana Clemintina
Espinal, 30, to prison for a year longer than the federal
guidelines recommendation and three years on supervised release.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Doug Davis said he had asked Harmon for the stiffer
penalty because ``Baby Stephanie'' was exposed to significant
danger as she was passed into strangers' hands for use as a
``prop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She (Espinal) didn't know these people, or if they would take
care of the baby or even if she'd get the baby back,'' said Davis.
``This was a 6-month-old, totally helpless baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Espinal pleaded guilty in August to conspiracy to induce
undocumented immigrants to come to, enter or remain in the United
States. Immigrant smugglers paid her $200 to rent the baby for use
by undocumented persons attempting to enter this country in
Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol officials said using infants as ``props'' has
increased as intensive border-control initiatives have made it
harder to slip into the country illegally.
</P>
<P>
   To get their clients into the United States, smugglers pair
unrelated men and women and provide them with an infant so they
appear to be a family.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme is intended to take advantage of a Border Patrol
practice of not charging undocumented immigrants who get caught
with illegal entry _ an offense that may carry prison time _ if
they have a child in their care, said U.S. Attorney Mervyn
Mosbacker.
</P>
<P>
   Agents usually just escort families back across the border,
rather than hold them in detention facilities to await prosecution,
punishment and eventual deportation.
</P>
<P>
   The smugglers _ who charge as much as $2,000 for assisting in
illegal treks across the Texas border _ may have also believed that
a ``family'' would be less likely to arouse the suspicion by
Immigration and Naturalization Service agents, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The smuggling scheme began to unravel in March when Border
Patrol agent Griselda Vidrio in Brownsville noticed a couple
crossing the border with the same baby she had seen earlier that
morning with another couple.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vidrio noticed that the ``mother'' seemed unaccustomed to holding a
baby and had brought only two diapers, one bottle of formula and no
extra clothes.
</P>
<P>
   She said she also recognized a red, beaded bracelet the baby was
wearing and recalled seeing the child with a man who said he and
his baby had survived Hurricane Mitch but that the child's mother
had perished.
</P>
<P>
   When questioned, the couple admitted they were not married and
that the child had been supplied by smugglers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The infant was ultimately taken into custody by INS officials,
who began to search for the parents. Espinal was identified as the
mother after she filed a missing person report with the Houston
Police Department. She stated then that her baby had been
kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   Espinal, convicted previously for possession of crack cocaine,
confessed after INS agents confronted her with pictures of the
child being used by two sets of ``parents,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said she rented ``Baby Stephanie'' to smugglers at
least three times.
</P>
<P>
   The baby is still in custody of Child Protective Services, Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
