<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAULIEU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beaulieu buys two Texas companies
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Carpet maker Beaulieu of America Inc. has entered the
hard surfaces business.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalton, Ga.-based company said Monday it acquired L.D.
Brinkman Co. and Hollytex Inc. of Lewisville, Texas, along with the
parent company, Pro Group Holdings Inc. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisitions will add about $400 million in revenue and
2,500 employees, said Piet Dossche, president of Beaulieu's
residential division. Beaulieu had revenue of $1.5 billion in 1998
with about 11,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas companies will become subsidiaries of Beaulieu.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Brinkman gets Beaulieu into the fast-growing
sector of hardwood floors, laminates, ceramic tiles and vinyl. With
30 locations, Brinkman calls itself the country's largest
floor-covering distributor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This automatically positions us as a total flooring company,''
Dossche said. Brinkman's strongest lines include well-known brands
such as Pergo and Congoleum.
</P>
<P>
   Hollytex adds a high-end carpet line to Beaulieu's portfolio.
Hollytex makes tufted broadloom carpet and rugs for residential and
commercial use at mills in Oklahoma. Its products are distributed
through Brinkman.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held Beaulieu is the fourth-largest maker of carpet
and woven area rugs.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
