<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-IOWA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY'S IOWA PRESENCE LEADS ANALYSTS TO UPRGADE HIS CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa _ Once viewed as a prohibitive underdog in
Iowa, former Sen. Bill Bradley has been pouring resources into this
state in preparation for next month's Democratic presidential
caucuses, betting that a strong showing here will send a powerful
message to party members nationwide that their nomination is truly
up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts had thought that Bradley would have
trouble competing in Iowa against Vice President Al Gore, his lone
rival for the Democratic nomination. Not only is Gore better known,
but he has the support of most of the state's Democratic unions and
top elected officials, vital resources in getting voters to the
caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley has devoted enough time and money to the state to
cause many analysts to upgrade his chances of staying close to Gore
here. Most analysts say Bradley needs to finish only a strong
second here to build momentum for the New Hampshire primary, which
comes one week after the Jan. 24 caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you asked me six weeks ago, I would have said he had no
chance'' of winning, said Arthur Sanders, a professor of politics
at Drake University in Des Moines. ``But he's clearly struck a
chord. Now I'd say he's got a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, more attention has been paid to New Hampshire by the
news media and, to some degree, the campaigns themselves, because
polls show the two men in a dead heat there. By contrast, most
polls have shown Gore well ahead in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   There is a risk for Bradley in fighting all-out for Iowa: If he
raises expectations here and then fails to meet them, he could
deflate his momentum on the eve of New Hampshire. Worried about a
similar situation on the Republican side, Sen. John McCain of
Arizona has avoided Iowa altogether, arguing that he would have no
chance of catching Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bradley campaign has clearly decided that the risk is
worth taking. The campaign has booked about $800,000 in television
advertising time for January, enough to ensure that its commercials
run every day across the state until caucus night, Bradley campaign
aides say. The campaign has already spent about $600,000 on
television advertising in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   After a slow start, the Bradley camp has also made significant
strides in building a field organization, hiring 56 full-time
workers _ to Gore's 70 _ and recruiting volunteer coordinators for
all of Iowa's 99 counties and nearly half of its 2,143 precincts.
In January, the campaign plans to send several hundred volunteers
to Iowa from New Jersey, the state Bradley represented for three
terms in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Bradley plans to spend almost all of
January in Iowa, his aides say, doing the kind of person-to-person
campaigning that Iowans expect from presidential candidates.
Bradley has already spent twice as many days in Iowa this year as
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows their confidence in their ability to run dead even
with the vice president in Iowa,'' said David O'Brien, a former
Clinton administration official and Gore supporter from Cedar
Rapids who is now supporting Bradley. ``They haven't given up on
winning here. And if he stays close, I think it sends a message
that Bradley is more electable.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign officials acknowledge that Bradley is building a
sizable organization here. But they assert that Bradley's mostly
volunteer troops will be no match for Gore's better-financed army
of union and party activists.
</P>
<P>
   And the Iowa caucuses tend to reward the candidates with the
largest field organizations. Unlike primaries, where people can
vote at any time in the privacy of a booth, caucuses are evening
meetings where votes are cast in the open after lengthy debates. As
a result, caucusgoers tend to be only the most loyal party members.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has locked up the big institutions that have proved most
effective at getting those voters to the caucuses. Those include
the state's largest unions, representing auto workers, teachers and
other public employees, and its two Democratic members of Congress,
Sen. Tom Harkin and Rep. Leonard L. Boswell. While Gov. Tom Vilsack
is neutral, his wife has endorsed Gore, as have many of the
Democratic state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has been through Iowa and spent a lot of time with the
people there, not just in the last few months, but the last seven
years,'' said Chris Lehane, Gore's press secretary. ``As a result,
he's developed a tremendous foundation of support in Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   But advisers to Bradley say they believe that Gore's supporters
are unenthusiastic and that his sharp-elbowed attacks on Bradley
are rubbing Iowans the wrong way. They also say Bradley enjoys a
hometown advantage because he grew up in Missouri, and that a
growing number of rank-and-file union members are prepared to buck
their leadership. (Helping push that line is Bradley's Iowa
manager, Dan Lucas, a former AFL-CIO official who has met with 47
union locals in Iowa since joining the campaign last summer.)
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bradley's campaign is reaching out to
disenchanted Democrats, peace advocates, students, independents and
even moderate Republicans, who are allowed to change their
registration on caucus day. And he has been aggressively courting
state and local officials who could give his campaign added
credibility and organizational muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bradley is doing a good job of going after folks that
wouldn't typically go to caucuses,'' said Kim Warkentin, executive
director of the Iowa Democratic Party. ``Everywhere he goes he
draws a huge crowd of people. A lot of it has to do with the
celebrity quality about him. But he's also an honest person who
relates to people one on one, and that's the name of the game in
the caucuses.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's efforts were on display this week in Cedar Rapids when
he made an unusual appeal to crossover voters at the local Rotary
Club, the members of which were mainly Republicans and
independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this room is full of a lot of good Democrats,'' Bradley
said to much laughter. ``But if you're one of those revolutionary
Republicans, if you're one of those open-minded, independent
Republicans and you agree with what I've just said _ think about,
on that caucus night, the one sacrilege of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   As he left, Bradley received a standing ovation. ``I trust this
guy,'' said James Sattler, a 42-year-old Republican who said he
might register Democrat and vote for Bradley, provided he thought
Bush was comfortably ahead in the Republican race. ``He speaks from
the heart. His message is honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Just six hours later, Bradley gave one of his most impassioned
speeches of the campaign to union workers at a Teamsters hall. The
Teamsters leadership has remained neutral in the race. He opened
with several light anecdotes about his days as a star Olympic and
professional basketball player, experiences that his aides say make
him attractive to working-class men. But he quickly turned serious,
calling for policies to help unions organize and punish companies
that violate labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to help working families in this country,
then you have to help unions in this country do the things that
unions do best, which is organize the unorganized,'' Bradley said.
``I want you to know where I'm coming from. I'm on your side.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the candidate received a standing ovation that night,
many political analysts argue that Bradley will have trouble
encouraging large numbers of rank-and-file union members to buck
their pro-Gore leadership. And they say that Republicans like
Sattler are rare.
</P>
<P>
   But the analysts also say Bradley does not have to win in Iowa,
simply stay close to Gore. The question is how close. Many analysts
say Bradley needs to win at least 40 percent of the vote to be
viewed as having succeeded here. And that is a relatively high bar.
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., won 31 percent in 1980, the most
for an insurgent candidate in the last three decades. But even that
was considered a poor showing.
</P>
<P>
   Since the name of the game is beating expectations, Gore's aides
say Bradley should get well over 40 percent, while Bradley's aides
have tried to downplay their chances of getting that much. But at
times, Bradley's supporters cannot resist.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least 40 percent is a good showing,'' said Connie Clarke,
one of Bradley's coordinators in eastern Iowa. ``But I really want
to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
