<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-DEBATE (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Republican front-runner George
W. Bush's challenge in tonight's televised debate with his five
challengers for the GOP nomination will be to defuse concerns about
his intellect and ability to become a world leader. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-PRIVACY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court revives a
Kentucky law that limits the release of motor vehicle accident
reports. The justices tell the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to
restudy the Kentucky case in light of a decision last week that
reinstated a California law limiting commercial access to police
reports. By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-VOUCHER (Washington) _ The Supreme Court clears the way
for Vermont to keep providing tuition assistance to private,
secular schools, while withholding similar aid from parochial
institutions. Religious-school parents had unsuccessfully
challenged the state funding program as unconstitutional. By STEVE
LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   WEATHER (Washington) _ This year is shaping up to be the second
warmest in the United States and the fifth warmest in the world,
following last year's record high both nationally and globally, the
government weather experts say. Tom Karl, director of the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Climatic data
center, says 1999 ``continues a trend toward long-term (global)
warming.'' By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL-TURNOVER (Panama City, Panama) _ President Jimmy
Carter, the man who 22 years ago signed the treaties turning the
Panama Canal over to Panama, on Tuesday bequeaths the American
landmark to the Panamanian government. The United States completed
the canal project in 1914. By SUSANA HAYWARD.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-SHOOTING (Ciudad Acuna, Mexico) _ Mexicans in this border
town are increasingly upset that the authorities across the Rio
Grande in Texas have not charged a man they believe shot one of
three Mexicans who crossed the river to burglarize the man's home
in Del Rio. The issue has polarized people along the border, with
Americans saying their homes often are targets of burglaries and
Mexicans saying the case represents a miscarriage of justice. By
JOHN MacCORMACK. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-SHUTTLE (Undated) _ With its dented fuel line replaced, the
shuttle Discovery is being prepared for a Thursday liftoff on a
mission to repair the idle Hubble Space Telescope. By MARK CARREAU.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE-WASHINGTON (Austin, Texas) _ His picture, similar to the
one on dollar bills, seemed out of place on the local newspaper's
obituary page. But there he was: ``General George Washington,''
dead now for 200 years. ``We thought it would catch the eye,''
chuckled Frank Gibson, a retiree who helped organize a totally
serious church service to commemorate the bicentennial anniversary
of Washington's death in 1799. By JOHN W. GONZALEZ. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   RENTED-BABY (Houston) _ A Honduran woman who rented her baby for
use by illegal immigrants wanting to pose as a family as they
crossed the Texas border into Mexico is sentenced to 30 months in
federal prison. By DEBORAH TEDFORD. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-DIMEL (Houston) _ The University of Houston introduces new
football coach Dana Dimel. By JERRY WIZIG.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-DIMEL-PLANS (Houston) _ Sidebar on what former Wyoming
football coach Dana Dimel's plans are to kick start the University
of Houston on the field and in the stands. By W.H. STICKNEY Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With: FBC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The three Harry Potter books, now
entrenched at the top of the best-seller lists, make delightful
reading for adults and children alike. The stories are the best
fantasy since Alice in Wonderland. The people who want to ban
theses books, contending they promote evil witchcraft, are nuts.
The books don't promote anything but good clean fun. By MARIANNE
MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
