<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-GAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TO REVIEW `DON'T ASK' AS GORE DENOUNCES POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William S. Cohen Monday ordered a
review of military bases to determine how the ``don't ask, don't
tell'' policy on gays is being carried out, while Democratic
presidential frontrunner Al Gore issued a statement saying he would
end the policy if elected president, calling it an ``unacceptable
form of discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was responding to Representative Barney Frank of
Massachusetts, who raised the political stakes Monday by calling on
Gore to go beyond criticizing the policy and to advocate ending it.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the probe, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon
said Cohen shared the concerns of President Clinton, who on
Saturday said that the policy was ``way out of whack,'' having been
used to root out gays and lesbians serving in the military. Bacon
said a spot check of major bases and installations will be
conducted over the next 90 days and the results reported directly
to Cohen.``We are as determined as the president is to see that the
policy is implemented fairly,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   The review comes on the heels of last week's murder conviction
of an Army private at Fort Campbell, Ky. for fatally beating a gay
soldier with a baseball bat, triggering fresh concern over the
treatment of gays and lesbians who, under the administration's
policy, are allowed to serve in the military so long as they keep
their sexual orientation a secret.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, one of only three openly gay or lesbian members of
Congress, jumped into the what has become an election year debate
about the policy, complaining in an interview Monday that Clinton
hadn't gone far enough in his comments and that Gore should speak
out in favor of lifting the ban as has his Democratic rival Bill
Bradley and Hillary Rodham Clinton, a candidate for the US Senate
from New York. None of the GOP candidates for president support
lifting the ban.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Gore, a Vietnam veteran, had urged Clinton not to
accept the ``don't ask, don't tell'' compromise and to issue an
executive order that would lift the ban entirely on gays in the
military, advice that went unheeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's appropriate for him to say what he said
previously, which is `don't ask, don't tell,' not only isn't
working the way it was supposed to, but even it was working the way
it was supposed to, it wouldn't be good enough,'' Frank said. ``He
ought to go a step further and join Hillary Clinton and Bill
Bradley and say it should be abolished altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Gore said in the statement that in light of the
beating death of the soldier at Fort Campbell, ``I believe the
`don't ask, don't tell' policy should be eliminated. Gays and
lesbians should be allowed to serve their country without
discrimination. If I am entrusted with the presidency, I will make
those changes and propose legislation in Congress to eliminate this
unacceptable form of discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   The violatile gays and the military issue had virtually
disappeared from the political radar after President Clinton
abandoned efforts in 1993 to fulfill a campaign promise to lift the
ban on gays in uniforms. But it has bounced back in the past week,
after a military jury at Fort Campbell convicted and sentenced a
private to life in prison for beating a gay infantryman to death
with a baseball bat as the victim slept.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, Gore's rival for the Democratic nomination, supports
gay people serving openly, going so far as to post his position on
his campaign's website. As a New Jersey senator, he supported a
1993 amendment to prevent ``don't ask, don't tell,'' from becoming
law.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the First Lady, campaigning in New York, said the
policy was a political compromise that ``has not worked.'' She
said, ``I don't believe it is ultimately the policy that we should
have in our military.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Saturday with CBS News, the president did not
commit to trying to end the policy, but to making it work. ``What
I'd like to do is to focus on trying to make the policy we
announced back in '93 work the way that it was intended to, cause
it's way out of whack now, and I don't think any serious person can
say it's not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, whose criticism of Gore first came in an interview
Saturday with gay author and columnist Michelangelo Signorile on
the GAYBC Radio Network, Monday said he was disappointed with
Clinton's answer and ``disappointed in the president, because I and
others have been telling him for years what he now acknowledges . .
. that it was not being enforced well.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Bacon said acting Inspector General Donald
Mancuso, who reports directly to Cohen, would decide which bases to
send teams to do the spot checks. ``All of us have read in recent
days the very disturbing charges that have come out of Fort
Campbell, Kentucky. Many people have asked whether the charges made
about Fort Campbell may apply to other installations in the
military,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   C. Dixon Osburn, co-executive director of the Servicemembers
Legal Defense Network, which lobbies on behalf of gays and lesbians
in uniform, however, expressed doubts about the Pentagon's
investigation. He said one question is whether gay people are going
to pariticpate in the review and whether they will be offered
assurances if they report harrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that anti-gay harassment is a problem and they know
what they need to do to fix it, but they are not doing it,'' Osburn
said of Pentagon officials. ``They continue to drag their feet. The
real issue here is we need leadership, not delays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
