<HEADLINE>
MASSMUTUAL IS INTERESTED IN TRAVELERS' CARE DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MassMutual, the Springfield, Mass. insurer, is considering
buying the long-term-care business of Travelers Group, the giant
insurance company that is part of Citigroup Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co. said its
chairman, Thomas B. Wheeler, would retire at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for MassMutual declined to say Monday whether the
company was in talks with Travelers, but he confirmed that
MassMutual was interested in the unit, which sources said was for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard that Travelers is marketing their long-term-care
division,'' said the spokesman, Eustis Walcott. He said MassMutual
had not received a formal proposition from Travelers but that
``when we do, we'll look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   A Hartford, Conn. spokesman for Travelers, Keith Anderson, would
neither confirm nor deny rumors about the company's long-term-care
operations, which provide insurance to groups and individuals
needing constant care in a nursing facility or at home due to
accident, illness, or old age. Anderson declined to say whether the
division was for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of what the unit might fetch were not immediately
available. Long-term care accounts for a tiny portion of Travelers'
core businesses, which include life insurance, annuities, and
property and casualty insurance, and Travelers does not break out
revenues for the segment.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers Life &AMP; Annuity, the main unit of Travelers Group,
expects to earn $660 million for 1999, or about 7 percent of
Citigroup's projected total earnings of $9.2 billion. Travelers was
acquired by New York-based Citicorp in 1998 in a deal that created
the world's largest financial services company.
</P>
<P>
   Walcott said MassMutual, which launched its own long-term-care
business a few months ago, was interested in expanding in that
segment to diversify earnings. He declined to disclose revenues for
the new business. MassMutual is the nation's 11th largest life
insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler is leaving after 37 years at the company. The
63-year-old outgoing chairman, who began his career as a sales
agent, will be succeeded by Robert J. O'Connell, 56, who is
president and chief executive. O'Connell assumed the CEO title from
Wheeler and the president title in January after 9 years at
American International Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Under Wheeler, MassMutual saw its assets under management
increase tenfold, to nearly $200 billion. The company's main
businesses are life insurance, annuities, disability insurance, and
financial management. It owns Oppenheimer Funds Inc., David L.
Babson &AMP; Co Inc., and other asset management firms.
</P>
<P>
   MassMutual, the second-largest insurer in Massachusetts, after
John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co, is owned by its
policyholders. The company has not said whether it will seek to
convert to a public company owned by shareholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
