<SLUG> BC-TV-SPLITUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMED TV COUPLE TO SPLIT UP _ OFF AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEEDHAM, Mass. _ Natalie Jacobson and Chet Curtis, whose
partnership on and off the air has helped define Boston television
news for a generation, announced Monday that they have decided to
separate after almost 25 years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The split creates a situation without precedent in local TV,
since Jacobson and Curtis said they plan to continue working
together as coanchors of the newscasts on WCVB-TV (Channel 5). In
fact, they did so Monday night, looking strained at times but
mostly betraying little sign that anything was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   After the 6 p.m. news, in another unprecedented move, Channel 5
general manager Paul La Camera appeared on-air to tell viewers of
the separation.
</P>
<P>
   For many viewers who have come to view the marriage of ``Chet
and Nat'' as a homey fixture on an otherwise fast-changing TV
landscape, it probably came as a shock. Within an hour after La
Camera's announcement, more than 80 calls had poured in to the
Channel 5 switchboard.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson and Curtis declined Globe requests for interviews, but
earlier in the day, in a statement read to around 100 Channel 5
employees at a staff meeting called by La Camera, the pair called
it ``an amicable and mutual decision.'' They said they remain
``best friends'' who ``care deeply for one another.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement did not explain why they have chosen to separate,
and did not indicate whether they plan to divorce. La Camera and
Channel 5 news director Candy Altman said the couple did not tell
them whether divorce is in the offing or not. Jacobson, 56, and
Curtis, 60, have an 18-year-old daughter, Lindsay Dawn. Curtis also
has two grown children from his first marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, Jacobson and Curtis said that ``this obviously
has not been an easy decision, but we believe it is best for us.''
They called their choice to separate ``intensely personal'' and
said ``we will not make any further public statements.'' They added
that they hope colleagues will not ``feel you have to tiptoe around
us because of this change in our private lives.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came to Jacobson and Curtis, however, their private
lives have often attracted keen public interest, whether it was
major (the birth of their daughter) or minor (a change in
Jacobson's hair style last year). Given that Channel 5 became
Boston's dominant TV news station, in part, by projecting a
``family'' image built around Jacobson and Curtis, a key question
now is how viewers react to the split.
</P>
<P>
   The couple first told La Camera and news director Candy Altman
of their decision last Monday night after the 6 p.m. newscast. In
an interview Monday at Channel 5, La Camera said they opted to
postpone the announcement because the station was focusing on
covering the deaths of six firefighters in Worcester, and believed
it would have been ``inappropriate'' to publicize the separation at
that time.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson and Curtis coanchored several hours of live coverage of
the memorial service and procession for the firefighters last
Thursday, which La Camera cited as proof that ``whatever
difficulties may be occurring in their private lives, is in no way
has spilled over into their work.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they chose to announce their decision to separate
Monday, the couple is apparently still living together in their
Needham home. Curtis is expected to move out by year's end to an
apartment in a Boston suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about marital problems had surfaced when Jacobson
and Curtis showed up at social events without each other. That
speculation intensified in June when Jacobson took a sabbatical
that lasted nearly four months.
</P>
<P>
   La Camera acknowledged that he was aware of the rumors, but he
said he did not question the anchors about them because their work
did not appear to be affected. ``If we had seen any indication in
their work, perhaps we would have,'' said La Camera.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that ``obviously, this must have had something to do
with the sabbatical,'' but he insisted that he still believes
Jacobson primarily took the sabbatical for the reasons she stated
at the time: to spend more time with her daughter and elderly
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never crossed our minds that we were betrayed or misled in
any way,'' said La Camera.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he and Altman offered strong words of personal support
for Jacobson and Curtis. Altman said she is ``saddened and
disappointed, and concerned for them.'' La Camera said his intent
is ``to be as loving and supportive as (I) can,'' adding
emphatically: ``This has nothing to do with ratings.'' He voiced
the hope that Channel 5 viewers will also be ``supportive and
understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   For Channel 5, the months ahead loom as a test of that. The
station has numerous shelfs full of New England Emmys and other
broadcasting awards won with Jacobson and Curtis as their lead
anchors. In the past two years, while maintaining its No. 1
position during the morning, noon, and evening newscasts, the
station has repeatedly lost the 11 p.m. ratings race to rival
WHDH-TV (Ch. 7).
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson and Curtis coanchor the 5 p.m., 6 p.m., and 11 p.m.
newscasts. They anchored the 5 and 6 Monday night, but did not
anchor the 11 p.m. news. La Camera said that had nothing to do with
the separation, but rather reflected their custom during football
season, when Channel 5's broadcast of ``Monday Night Football''
pushes the news into the wee hours.
</P>
<P>
   Their on-air partnership began in 1972, when they started
coanchoring Channel 5's midday newscast. They were married in May
1975. In 1978, each began coanchoring different newscasts with Tom
Ellis. By 1982, though, they were teamed up again on the 6 and 11
p.m. newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond reading and reporting the nightly news, Jacobson and
Curtis have carved out roles as Boston's unofficial First Couple.
They enlarged Channel 5's civic identity by attending numerous
charity affairs, coanchoring everything from the Boston Marathon to
the ``Salute to Symphony'' fundraiser for the Boston Symphony
Orchestra to the Jerry Lewis Labor Telethon to combat muscular
dystrophy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
