<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTHERN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga. Southern hoping for a healthy Peterson
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This isn't the way Adrian Peterson had hoped to
prepare for the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Southern fullback has been forced to spend the last
two days recovering from an assortment of injuries and will be on
crutches until Wednesday, three days before the Eagles meet
Youngstown State in the Division I-AA national championship game in
Chattanooga. Peterson rushed for 183 yards and three touchdowns in
last week's 28-17 semifinal victory over Illinois State, but
sustained a turf toe injury and re-aggravated his injured right
knee.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, the nation's best Division I-AA player is a
mere spectator as the program prepares for its seventh national
title game since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be on the crutches until Wednesday, then we'll take it
from there,'' Johnson said. ``I think he'll be ready to go
Saturday. In fact, I don't think we have enough people to keep him
out of that game.''
</P>
<P>
   The 183-yard performance against Illinois State marked the 29th
consecutive game in his Georgia Southern career that Peterson has
topped 100 yards. He has also surpassed 5,000 career rushing yards
(5,063) and has 71 career rushing touchdowns, including a 161-yard,
two-touchdown performance in last year's 55-43 national
championship game loss to Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, the Walter Payton Award winner as the top player in
Division I-AA, has been a key figure for the Eagles during their
three playoff victories. He has averaged more than 216 yards
rushing in the three wins, including a 333-yard, five-touchdown
performance in the quarterfinal victory over Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   While the health of Peterson remains the team's primary concern,
Youngstown State will have its top back completely healthy for the
title game. Youngstown senior Adrian Brown, a 6-0, 230-pounder,
rushed for 188 yards in leading the Penguins to a 27-24 semifinal
victory over Florida A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the guy,'' said Johnson, referring to Brown. ``We've got
to find a way to stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Eagles' starters are currently healthy for
Saturday's game. Spearheaded by down linemen Voncellies Allen,
Eugene Phillips and Freddy Pesqueira along with linebacker Jason
Neese and cornerback Kiwaukee Thomas, the Eagle defense had its
best game of the playoffs against Illinois State, holding the
Redbirds to slightly more than two yards per carry on 32 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys up front did a great job of stopping the run,''
Johnson said. ``We played hard and ran to the ball. (Illinois State
backs) broke some tackles, but there was always somebody else
there.''
</P>
<P>
   TITLE GAME
</P>
<P>
   _ Who: Georgia Southern vs. Youngstown State
</P>
<P>
   _ What: Division I-AA championship
</P>
<P>
   _ When, where: 2 p.m. Saturday, Finley Stadium, Chattanooga,
Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV, radio: ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
