<SLUG> BC-MA-ONLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS SENATE POSTING BILLS ON THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL CROWLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Massachusetts Legislature became a bit more
Internet-savvy last week. But the state still lags far behind most
other states in letting the public read proposed laws on line.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the state Senate began posting the full text of its
bills on the Internet for the first time. But the House has yet to
follow suit, leaving Massachusetts as the only state where citizens
cannot read all bills for free via computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does seem that in a state that's often called the
birthplace of democracy we should be leaders, not laggards, in
making government accessible to people,'' said Rob Sargent,
executive director of the Massachusetts Public Interest Research
Group.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's move was ordered by Senate President Thomas F.
Birmingham, who has long been more supportive of electronically
posting legislative information for the public than his House
counterpart, House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran. The Senate has made
its daily schedules and summaries of its floor activities available
online for months, and will soon begin asking Senators to file
their bills electronically.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Legislature's Web site provides access to short
summaries and brief legislative histories of pending bills. But
critics say the site pales in comparison to those in other states.
A recent survey by the National Online Legislative Association
ranked the quality of Massachusetts's web site 45th among 50
states. (The site's Internet address is
www.magnet.state.ma.us/legis/).
</P>
<P>
   In the past, reading bills has meant visiting the State House in
Boston or mailing a self-addressed stamped envelope to the
Legislature's document room. To read House bills, citizens must
still visit or write to the document room.
</P>
<P>
   Sources familiar with both the Legislature and the Internet say
there are no techological obstacles to placing all bills online,
although doing so would create some new work for the House and
Senate clerks.
</P>
<P>
   Some speculate Finneran, who does not use a computer, may be
unfamiliar with the Internet's potential. Critics suggest Finneran
is reluctant to open the legislative process to greater scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran did not say Monday whether the House would soon follow
the Senate's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working with the Senate Clerk and the House Clerk
to figure out the most efficient way of doing that,'' Finneran
said. ``When we make this move we don't want to do anything in an
inefficient way and find out we have missed opportunities to do
more and better things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7874 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-GARNETT-COX     12-13 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-GARNETT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dog days for Wolves
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Life after Stephon Marbury has been bleak for the
Minnesota Timberwolves. The team widely regarded two years ago as
an up-and-comer is on a mercurial descent that has crash-and-burn
indicators.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly at the heart of their woes is the departure of
Marbury, the former Georgia Tech guard who forced the Timberwolves
to trade him by threatening to leave when he became a free agent.
To prevent losing him with no compensation, Minnesota moved Marbury
to New Jersey in a three-team trade that brought the Timberwolves
point guard Terrell Brandon from Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   From that March 11 deal to tonight's game against the Hawks at
Philips Arena, Minnesota's record is a disappointing 20-28.
Brandon, a one-time NBA all-star, is being criticized, basically,
for not being Marbury; the sensational Kevin Garnett is frustrated
at his recent play and the overall performance of the team. As a
result, the luster that once shone on the tandem of coach Flip
Saunders and vice president Kevin McHale is dulling. Fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, man,'' said Garnett (averaging 21.3 points, 11
rebounds), whose recent play has followed that of his
underachieving teammates; he had a stretch of 14 straight misses in
a recent game against Golden State. ``When it rains, it pours. I
haven't lost my confidence. Sometimes I might try to do too much. .
. . It ain't easy to deal with this, man. It's all within
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The thoughts in Minnesota seem to hang onto Marbury. He
facilitated the breaking up of him and Garnett, who were bound to
form one of the league's most lethal combinations. By replacing
Marbury with Brandon, the T'Wolves believed the drop-off would not
be noticeable once Brandon got familiar with his new teammates.
</P>
<P>
   After starting 12-7 with Marbury last season, the Timberwolves
of Brandon went 13-18 to end the season. They lost in four games to
San Antonio in the playoffs' first round.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they're 7-10 and all eyes are on Brandon, who signed for
$58.3 million over the next six years, another source of ire in the
cold Minnesota air.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at contracts and go by that, instead of what's
realistic,'' Brandon said. ``If you make the most money, then
that's who you should expect the most. You can never do enough
really. People want more. As teammates, we can't get caught up in,
`Who's fault is it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that Brandon is not up to his previous all-star
level, although he averages 14.8 points and 8.1 assists. It's what
they have _ or have not _ gotten from anyone other than Garnett and
Brandon. The surrounding cast has been inconsistent, from guard
Anthony Peeler to forwards Joe Smith and Malik Sealy to big man
Dean Garrett to rookie Wally Szczerbiak to center Radoslav
Nesterovic.
</P>
<P>
   Which directs more burden toward Garnett.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's (getting to him) a little bit,'' Saunders said. ``That's
natural. (Opponents have) done a better job of taking the ball out
of his hands. Early in the year, when they trapped Kevin, he moved
the ball and we knocked down shots. The last few games, we're not
knocking down shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Said McHale: ``Move the ball earlier, move the ball differently,
see the open guy _ that all comes with getting better. Anybody who
was a good post player went through that. Kevin has to learn how to
deal with it and help get us going.''
</P>
<P>
   It would help if Garnett has someone dependable playing
alongside him, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for Kevin to play well,'' Saunders said, ``the other
guys have to play better. It's that vicious cycle. He wants it so
bad _ that's where his greatest strength is his greatest weakness.
He wants to make it happen so quick. But whether it's golf or
whatever, the harder you swing, the worse your shot is. The harder
you try, the worse you become.''
</P>
<P>
   It can't get much worse for the Timberwolves, who have dropped
five straight and are 2-8 after a 5-2 start. Saunders said the team
is more in need of someone who forces his teammates to play with a
passion and anger than a scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a veteran guy, a John Starks-type guy, who, when
things get really tough, gets in there and takes a stand and says,
`It ends right now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And the decline has hit more than the slumping Garnett and
underappreciated Brandon. McHale and Saunders, a pair of heroes for
a while, have been targets of discord as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, it always comes back to the people at the top,''
Saunders said. ``I see people at grocery stores these days, and
they avoid you like you have the plague. We're all embarrassed
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Garnett: ``From the outside looking in, I know it looks
kind of gloomy. We've still got 65 more games to go. If you give up
now, why play later?''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
