u i BC-PANAMA-CANAL-TURNOVER     12-13 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-TURNOVER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANAMA SEES MIXED MESSAGES IN LOW-KEY CANAL CEREMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ With a mixture of national pride and
nostalgia, this nation receives control of the Panama Canal Tuesday
in a ceremony marking the end the Yankee era begun after the United
States finished the waterway that revolutionized world trade.
</P>
<P>
   But an apparent misunderstanding between the once-close partners
has commenced amid the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The official observance at the giant Miraflores Locks, where
various heads of state will be in attendance, will be devoid of
high-ranking members of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   For many here, the absence takes luster and importance away from
the historic event, set in motion by the 1977 treaties signed by
President Jimmy Carter and Panamanian military strongman Omar
Torrijos to give the canal to Panamanians.
</P>
<P>
   The country of 2.8 million has lived with U.S. bases and
soldiers since the canal was completed in 1914.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, many see it as a slap in the face and lack of respect.
</P>
<P>
   Panamanians wonder if it is an accidental diplomatic gaffe or a
message that the United States is relegating the country to
backwater status now that the military is leaving. Although the
official handover is Tuesday, it doesn't take effect until noon
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Aleman said Monday that relations
with the United States remained excellent but said Panama was
disheartened by the U.S. representation at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latin America, not just Panama, is disappointed. The United
States is missing out on this opportunity. It shows the lack of
(American) diplomatic attention to the region,'' Aleman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main trading partner of the United States is Latin America
and we can't see how they cannot be present at such a historic
event,'' he told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   King Juan Carlos of Spain will attend and so will five Latin
American presidents, including Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton is staying home, and his emissary,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, also canceled late last
week, citing Middle East concerns.
</P>
<P>
   So Carter, hailed here as a champion of human rights who
understood the U.S. military should leave Panama, is the main man.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the U.S. delegation are Transportation Secretary
Rodney Slater and Commerce Secretary William Daley. The
highest-ranking diplomat is Peter Romero, the acting assistant
secretary of state for Western Hemispheric Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Panama, which has been administering the canal this past decade
in a transition that began in 1979, also has been buffeted by
remarks in the U.S. Congress that the country is unprepared to
manage and protect the 50-mile-long channel.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it is offended that many Americans believe a threat
from Communist China is imminent because Panama signed a 20-year
contract with a Hong Kong-based sea ports conglomerate, Hutchinson
Whampoa Ltd., that will control the canal's Atlantic and Pacific
ports. Hutchinson has interests throughout the world, including the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, U.S. Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., said the
agreement with Hutchinson posed a serious threat to U.S. security
and meant China could expand its communist web in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very sad to hear the amount of lies being told at these
congressional hearings. These lies are told over and over again,
and people start to believe them,'' said Aleman, who added that
Rohrabacher was ``not mentally fit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it, but these are ignorant people who don't know
what is going on this country,'' the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
   Aleman added he would like in the coming years to renegotiate
the Neutrality Treaty by which the United States has the right to
intervene militarily should the canal come under any menace.
</P>
<P>
   Panama does not have a military since the U.S. invasion
dissolved the 16,000-strong Panamanian Defense Forces of Gen.
Manuel Noriega 10 years ago. The national police will be in charge
of canal security in the event of any threats, which people here
say is much less with the U.S. troops gone.
</P>
<P>
   But guerrilla activity in neighboring Colombia makes many here
uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no force to defend ourselves against terrorists or
guerrillas filtering in from the Colombian jungle,'' said Jose Luis
Martinez, an accountant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not ready to live without the American soldiers,''
he added, echoing the opinion of many working-class Panamanians who
would have liked U.S. soldiers to stay in the country _ at least
for a while longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
