<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7878 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-MEETINGS-COX     12-13 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEETINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winter meetings produce blockbuster 4-team trade
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ No team in baseball has transformed itself
since season's end like Colorado, a process that continued Monday
with a trans-continental escapade involving four teams, nine
players and all four time zones.
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest winter meetings trade since the days Ted Turner
would rule the hotel cocktail lounge, the Rockies acquired four
more players, including starting pitchers Scott Karl from Milwaukee
and Rolando Arrojo from Tampa Bay. That brings to 15 the number new
players, via trade or free agency, that new Colorado general
manager Dan O'Dowd has acquired since Oct. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team as it stood in the division didn't work,'' said
O'Dowd. ``It didn't work for two reasons. One, there was a bad mix
in the clubhouse; the guys just didn't click. And two, as much as
the club led the league in runs scored, it had back-to-back poor
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that's not an aberration. That's a pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal was not cheap. Colorado had to send third baseman Vinny
Castilla to Tampa Bay as well as catcher Henry Blanco and
right-hander Jamey Wright to the Brewers. But the Rockies also
picked up third baseman Jeff Cirillo and cash in exchange from
Milwaukee as well as infielder Aaron Ledesma from the Devil Rays.
To complete the deal, Colorado sent minor pitcher Justin Miller to
Oakland, which in turn dealt right-hander (and LaGrange native)
Jimmy Haynes to Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The trade was thought to be the biggest at the winter meetings
since the 11-man, three-team extravaganza of Dec. 8, 1977, when
Turner helped concoct the Willie Montanez-John Matlack-Al Oliver
trade between the Braves, Texas and New York Mets. And this one was
almost bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started out being a relatively simple process involving the
Rockies and the Brewers,'' Milwaukee GM Dean Taylor said. ``But it
became complicated because the Brewers were looking for two
pitchers. We felt strongly about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complication was Dan had to go out and acquire a second
pitcher for us. We gave him five names and he went to work on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays later punctuated the day with announcing it had
signed free agent outfielder Greg Vaughn to a multi-year contract,
placing him in the middle of an order that already includes Jose
Canseco, Fred McGriff and Castilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're heading in the right direction with the moves
we made today,'' said Tampa Bay GM Chuck La Mar, whose club is
132-192 in its first two years of existence.
</P>
<P>
   Braves report
</P>
<P>
   GM John Schuerholz meets with two more clubs this morning but
</P>
<P>
   don't anticipate any action. While the Braves are said to have
shown some interest in left-hander Kenny Rogers, San Diego's bid
for second baseman Bret Boone is officially dead and there was no
progress in retaining free agent outfielder Gerald Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a (dollar) number we would consider signing him,''
Schuerholz said, ``and a lot of numbers at which we would be
uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Betemit verdict
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, vice president for major league operations,
expects to issue a ruling on the Adrian Beltre early-signing case
by week's end, when the Los Angeles Dodgers are expected to be
found guilty of signing the third baseman before his 16th birthday.
Alderson anticipates ruling on a similar case involving Braves
prospect Wilson Betemit ``if not by the first of the year, then
very shortly thereafter.''
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence the Braves signed Betemit out of the Dominican
Republic two months before his 15th birthday and 14 months before
clubs are permitted to sign foreign free agents. While Alderson
indicated the Betemit case is not more complicated than Beltre's,
he said, ``It's just at a different part of the pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   With a fully stocked 40-man roster, the Braves could not
participate in Monday's Rule 5 draft and went almost ignored by
other clubs throughout the process. The only player lost from the
system was right-hand prospect Aaron Taylor, who was taken from
Class A Macon by the Seattle organization in the AA Draft. . . .
The New York Yankees rewarded Game 3 World Series hero Chad Curtis
by sending him to Texas in exchange for minor league pitchers Sam
Marsonek and Brandon Knight. . . . Ex-Braves closer Brad Clontz
continued his national tour with his trade from Pittsburgh to
Arizona. The Diamondbacks mark Clontz's fourth organization since
the Braves released him 16 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
