<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7880 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-HELLER-DIES-COX     12-13 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELLER-DIES-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Author's work captured nation's dark mood
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: Moving to (a) General news and (e) Entertainment
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Skube
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He gave our vexations a name.
</P>
<P>
   Every middle manager caught between his bosses and his
subordinates, every wife caught between what her husband says and
what he does, everyone in American life who gets it coming and
going knows what a Catch-22 is even if he couldn't tell you who
Joseph Heller was.
</P>
<P>
   Heller, who died of a heart attack Sunday at age 76, occupied
the amorphous middle ground in American fiction, never really in
and never really out. His name was built with a first novel that
overshadowed everything he subsequently wrote.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Catch-22'' was published in 1961, the '60s had begun only
in the chronological sense. The broader cultural meaning of the
word would not take shape until the number of American ground
forces in Vietnam ballooned and the nation was bitterly divided
over a war the Pentagon but few others believed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catch-22,'' though set in World War II, was one of the first
expressions of irreverence directed at the American military, by
turns cynical and satirical, darkly funny and pessimistic that the
generals knew what they were doing.
</P>
<P>
   Its protaganist, Capt. Yossarian, a bomber pilot who knows his
next mission might be his last, feigns insanity to avoid duty. In
doing so he confronts every soldier's no-win dilemma: Only a crazy
person would want to go into combat, but only the mentally unfit
are excused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in my book accuses everyone else of being crazy,''
Heller once said. ``Frankly, I think the whole society is nuts _
and the question is: what does a sane man do in an insane
society?''
</P>
<P>
   Heller, who flew 60 combat missions in Europe in World War II,
had in mind a regulation from his time in the Army Air Force. He
had planned to call his book ``Catch-18,'' but Leon Uris'
best-selling ``Mila 18'' had come out the previous year and
Heller's publishers were afraid readers would confuse the two.
Heller said he picked the number 22 out of thin air.
</P>
<P>
   The book almost vanished into thin air as well. Except for an
effusive review in The New Republic that called Heller ``one of the
most extravagant talents now among us,'' the hardback edition of
``Catch-22'' mostly annoyed the literary sensibilities of the day.
The Oct. 22, 1961 issue of the The New York Times Book Review said
of it:
</P>
<P>
   ``'Catch-22' has much passion, comic and fervent, but it gasps
for want of craft and sensibility. If 'Catch-22' were intended as a
commentary novel, such sideswiping of character and action might be
taken care of by thematic control. It fails here because half of
its incidents are farcical and fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in ``Books of the Century: A Hundred Years of
Authors, Ideas and Literature,'' the editors of the Times Book
Review acknowledged hasty judgment in a single word: ``Oops!''
</P>
<P>
   Not until ``Catch-22'' came out in paperback in 1963 did it
become a best-seller. By the end of the decade, with the Vietnam
war at full pitch, Heller's humor and contempt seemed to many
Americans to have hit the nail on the head. And the 1970 movie that
was based on the book _ greeted with mixed reviews of its own _
sealed the idea and the phrase into the into popular consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   In his later years, Heller tired of being told he hadn't written
anything as good as ``Catch-22.'' ``I always say, 'Neither has
anyone else','' he told an interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, original as ``Catch-22'' was, many critics believe
his 1974 novel ``Something Happened'' to be equally penetrating as
social commentary. Written in Heller's over-the-top manner, it
satirizes the business world's readiness to crush the spirit of the
individual and presents a view of modern life more contemporary, if
anything, than what's found in ``Catch-22.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon had been put in its place, but the corporation and
its faceless functionaries were another matter. They were, in their
own way, just as ridiculous. It wasn't a world for which Joseph
Heller was suited, and better for him that he wasn't. His friend
Barbara Gelb, interviewing him for the New York Times when
``Something Happened'' came out, observed that he had described
Yossarian (``with shrewd self-knowledge') as ``a crotchety old
fogey of 28.'' Heller himself was a crotchety old-fogey of 51 at
the time, amused by what he regarded as civilian insanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 20 years now,'' Gelb wrote, `` I have managed to overlook
his frequent sulkiness, his gluttonous table manners and his
tendency to growl No before he even knows what the question is. I
have stayed on good terms with him largely because I relish his
aberrant sense of humor and his skewed way of looking at life _ an
outlook he insists has changed little since he wrote Catch-22.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
