<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7885 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-COLUMBINE-VIDEOTAPES-     12-13 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBINE-VIDEOTAPES-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEOTAPES GIVE NEW INSIGHT INTO COLUMBINE KILLERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Skedded earlier as COLO-SHOOTING) 
(lb) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLDEN, Colo. _ Videotapes made by two teen-agers as they
planned a shooting massacre and their suicides at Columbine High
School show them to be filled with hateful rage, hoping to kill 250
people, yet sympathetic to their parents for what they would soon
endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be put through hell once we do this,'' one of
the killers, Eric Harris, said of his parents in the last of
several tapes he made with Dylan Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   And as if to exonerate their parents from any guilt, remorse or
responsibility, Harris quietly quotes Shakespeare: ``Good wombs
have borne bad sons.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities showed the tapes to reporters Monday after Time
magazine reported on them in this week's edition, which was made
available to the media on Sunday. The Denver Rocky Mountain News
reported on the tapes Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Some families of the victims were angered at the Jefferson
County Sheriff's Department for releasing the tapes, along with
surveillance videos from the Columbine cafeteria, where no one was
shot, but the killers are seen walking around students who are
cowering behind overturned desks and chairs.
</P>
<P>
   The pair made three tapes in the weeks leading to the April 20
assault, in which they killed 13 people and wounded two dozen
others before turning their guns on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes form a macabre documentary of the meticulous planning
of the attack, which they called retaliation for what they describe
as years of taunting from friends and relatives because of their
unwillingness to dress and act as others wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Laced with profanity and racial epithets, the tapes reflect two
boys who concluded that they could no longer cope with everyday
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could see all the anger I've stored over the past four
years,'' Klebold says.
</P>
<P>
   ``More rage, more rage,'' Harris said. ``I'm building it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The rage erupted at their school in the Denver suburb of
Littleton, as the two seniors detonated bombs and marched through
the library, where they shot and killed 12 students and a teacher
before turning guns on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Halverson, a spokesman for the Jefferson County Sheriff's
Office, said Monday that the tapes were being shown to reporters
Monday because Time magazine had violated its agreement with
investigators by using direct quotes from the tapes and the
authorities feared ``the potential for sensationalism and the
resulting anguish to the victims' families.''
</P>
<P>
   He said investigators agreed to screen them for Time ``for
background purposes only'' to provide information about the motives
of the killers.
</P>
<P>
   But Diana Pearson, a spokeswoman for Time, said the magazine
made no such agreement nor did the authorities insist on any
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the tapes were shown Monday, neither the families of
the victims nor those of the gunmen had seen the tapes, Halverson
said, adding that arrangements were being made Monday for the
families to view them.
</P>
<P>
   Krista Flannigan, a victim services consultant who has worked
with many of the relatives of the shooting victims at Columbine,
said that she had talked to many of the families Monday and that
some were upset because the tapes were shown publicly before they
had viewed them, but that others were glad the public had a chance
to see the gunmen for what they were.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the homemade tapes, most of them shot in the Harris
home, last more than two hours and were made between March 15 and
sometime just before the shooting began, when the boys spent a
little over a minute saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Harris says: ``I just wanted to apologize to you guys. To
everyone I love, I'm really sorry about all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Klebold adds: ``Just know going to a better place.''
</P>
<P>
   Through much of the tapes, the boys talk extemporaneously about
the frustrations of their lives and their plans for April 20,
against a backdrop of obvious self-loathing and expressed hatred
for all mankind, especially minority groups, whom they belittle
repeatedly with ugly racial epithets.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is society? Just stupid human beings living off each
other,'' says Klebold at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Harris said that after the killings, ``We
need to die, too.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The tapes provide new insight into the most perplexing question
in the aftermath of the shootings: How could two teen-age boys from
comfortable middle-class families have build up so much anger and
rage to shoot innocent classmates at random?
</P>
<P>
   Some of the answer becomes quickly apparent as the two boys,
sitting on easy chairs in the Harris home, take turns talking into
the camera, recalling all the people who they feel slighted,
taunted or mistreated them. The list includes elementary school
classmates, relatives and many of the teen-agers who attend
Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   In acknowledging a pent-up rage to ``get paybacks'' against
perceived enemies, which they said they had been denied by rules
that govern everyday life, they describe how they expect their
crime to ``kick-start a revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it fun to get the respect that we're going to deserve?''
says Harris, who is holding the sawed-off shotgun he would use at
Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   The boys also recount several episodes in which they said their
plans might have been interrupted if their parents had exercised
more curiosity about their activities. Harris is especially lucid
in these moments, leaving the impression that perhaps he wished his
parents, Wayne and Kathy Harris, had interceded.
</P>
<P>
   In one incident, he talks about walking past his mother as he
left home, with the end of a shotgun protruding out of a bag. He
says his mother thought it was his BB gun.
</P>
<P>
   More harrowing for the viewer, however, is a 17-minute visit to
Harris' cluttered bedroom, in which he plays tour guide for Klebold
as cinematographer and interviewer. With exquisite precision and
detail, Harris holds before the camera a virtual arsenal of
weapons, bombs and ammunition that he has concealed on shelves, in
boxes and behind knickknacks.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he indicates a ``bunker'' outside his window where
he claims to be storing mortar grenades, pipe bombs and other
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, my parents never searched my room,'' he tells
Klebold.''
</P>
<P>
   As they're leaving his room, he pretends his mother has just
walked in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks good, son,'' he says, as if to mock her.
</P>
<P>
   A segment taped in Klebold's room also shows a collection of
ammunition, guns and a knife, and in separate sessions in each of
their homes, they taped themselves in dress rehearsals for April
20, trying on their belts and harnesses with loaded weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes also reveal critical differences between the two
teen-agers. While the tapes do not make clear, as reports of the
killing surmised, that Harris was the schemer and Klebold the
follower, it does become apparent that Harris is the deeper thinker
of the two. During much of their philosophical discourse, Harris
introduces most new thoughts, and Klebold builds on them.
</P>
<P>
   It is also during those moments in which Harris, far more than
Klebold, expresses sadness and regret _ hauntingly, at times _ for
what they feel they must do and how he thinks it will affect his
family.
</P>
<P>
   Harris says of his parents: ``My Dad's great, and my mother,
she's so thoughtful. She helps out in so many ways. I wish I was a
sociopath, so I didn't have any remorse for this. But I do. They
are going to go through hell for this. This is going to tear them
apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
