<SLUG> BC-SANFRAN-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEOPHYTES HELP ELECTRIFY MAYORAL RUNOFF IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The two dozen people waiting outside Tom
Ammiano's campaign headquarters at Josie's Cabaret and Juice Joint
piled in when the doors opened like frantic Christmas shoppers,
grabbing stacks of ``Tom for Mayor'' and ``Make History'' bumper
stickers as though they were the last Pokemon toys on earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be 51 on the 20th and this is the first campaign
I've ever wanted to be a part of,'' said Ed McCready, a computer
graphics designer plastering his clothes with yellow and black
``Mayor Tom Ammiano'' stickers.
</P>
<P>
   It has been like this here for six weeks now _ ever since
Ammiano, the president of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors,
forced Mayor Willie Brown into a run-off election on Tuesday with a
last-minute write-in campaign that captured 25 percent of the vote
in a four-way race.
</P>
<P>
   They are both liberals in the nation's most devoutly liberal
bastion, and both have experienced the sting of discrimination.
Brown, 65, is San Francisco's first African-American mayor, and
Ammiano, 58, would become the nation's first openly gay mayor of a
large city if he were elected. But the election battle here has had
little to do with race or sexual orientation. It has been much more
about who best could tackle pressing issues like housing costs, and
who best symbolizes San Francisco's heart and soul.
</P>
<P>
   And by those measures, Ammiano's supporters, many of them young
renters, have sometimes seemed like religious zealots, registering
more than 14,000 new voters, plastering the city with posters and
holding fund-raising rock concerts, comedy shows and wrestling
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such an electrifying event,'' said Molly Berry, 30, a
campaign worker. ``We're open from 9 to 9, and an hour doesn't go
by without at least a dozen people coming in asking to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's supporters, on the other hand, have the money and the
clout. Indeed, to say that the race between Ammiano, a former
teacher and stand-up comic, and Brown, the former speaker of the
State Assembly and one of California's most powerful, experienced
politicians, is a David-and-Goliath battle, only begins to describe
it.
</P>
<P>
   A poll last week by The San Francisco Chronicle shows Brown
leading Ammiano by 20 points, 49 to 29 percent, with 22 percent
undecided. He held an even bigger lead among older homeowners,
those most likely to vote. Still, the same newspaper's polls
wrongly predicted that Ammiano would come in last in the general
election on Nov. 2, with 11 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is taking no chances, amassing a huge campaign fund since
the general election.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six weeks, his campaign has received at least $1.3
million in unregulated, or ``soft money'' from hastily formed
political action committees, in addition to spending $400,000 (a
voter-approved voluntary spending cap) from his general campaign
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano's campaign has received $4,500 in independent spending,
and $250,000 over all.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has received endorsements from California's political
establishment, the small but potentially influential San Francisco
Republican Party, the city's two local daily newspapers, and most
of the city's major labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   He has received $22,600 in contributions from a landlord's group
_ sworn enemies of Ammiano, who has declared ``war on
gentrification'' _ in the form of a contribution to an independent
political action committee, and $200,000 from the Alice B. Toklas
Lesbian and Gay Democratic Club's political action committee, which
spent $175,000 on a television commercial featuring a gay couple
that decides to vote for Brown because of Ammiano's ``out there''
tax proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, whose platform focuses on tenants' rights and creating
a ``living wage'' for all workers, has been endorsed by the Bicycle
Messengers union, day laborers and tenants' rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several days, the California Democratic Party has
recruited legislative staffers from Sacramento to campaign for
Brown, offering them up to four free nights at the Hilton to come
here and walk the precincts. The party put $80,000 into Brown's
campaign in the November election and anticipated spending another
$100,000 in this runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Ammiano's volunteers have never been involved in a
political campaign before, and some have never voted.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, Peter Humphrey, a 35-year-old building
contractor, who said he throws wrestling parties for fun, threw a
``wrestling ball'' for Ammiano in a dark, rented space. A referee
with a grizzled beard wearing a blond woman's wig, shouted out
points as men and women, some dressed in '40s swing clothes,
tussled with strangers on mats. Humphrey asked for donations from
$3 to $250 and collected a total of $391 from the 50 guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even been registered to vote in 10 years,'' said
Humphrey, wearing a red robe over his wrestling trunks. He said he
felt compelled to hold the fundraiser, because ``it's time to look
out for the little guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
