r e BC-BOOKS-HELLER-APPRECIA     12-13 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-HELLER-APPRECIATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELLER'S PRESAGED THE '60S WITH `CATCH-22' 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB GRAHAM  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has to be one of the great openings in modern literature:
``It was love at first sight. The first time Yossarian saw the
chaplain he fell madly in love with him.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the anarchic beginning of Joseph Heller's ``Catch-22''
and set the tone. The phrase entered the language, but more than
that, it caught the spirit of the '60s generation that changed
America.
</P>
<P>
   Heller died of a heart attack Sunday in New York. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ralph J. Gleason, the late Chronicle columnist who
was one of the novel's early champions _ and it needed them _ the
book had ``a pervasive effect on an entire generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The dark, comic, subversive novel, published in 1961, expressed
disillusion with World War II but, uncannily, presaged the mood of
young people who soon would be opposing the war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems reasonable to say that, aside from Bob Dylan and the
Beatles, no single body of work changed how an emerging generation
saw the world as did the vision presented on `Catch-22,''' Gleason
wrote in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Catch-22 is the dilemma of trying to stay sane in an insane
society. The only way to remain sane is to risk being considered
crazy. Here is how Gleason explained it:
</P>
<P>
   ``In Heller's monstrously funny novel, his hero, a World War II
bombardier named Yossarian, asks to be relieved of combat duty
because he is crazy. The medical officer turns him down because of
Catch-22 _ `anyone who wants to get out of combat duty isn't
crazy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yossarian believed that ``the enemy is anybody who's going to
get you killed, no matter what side he's on.'' The medical officer
said, ``That crazy bastard may be the only sane one of us left.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Catch-22'' did not catch on when it was first published in
hardback. The reviews were mixed, some of them openly hostile.
Other reviews, notably by Robert Brustein in the New Republic and
by Nelson Algren in the Nation, saw ``Catch-22'' for the brilliant
work it was, but the book did not take off until it was published
in paperback. It has since become a classic.
</P>
<P>
   Heller was working as an advertising copywriter in the mid-'50s
when he sold the incomplete ``Catch-22'' to Simon &AMP; Schuster on the
basis of 250 pages. It was the first book bought by young editor
Robert Gottlieb, who went on to head the Knopf publishing house and
later was editor of the New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Heller, who was 38 when ``Catch-22'' was finally published, said
in an interview with the Chronicle's Leah Garchik that it took
eight more years for him to achieve financial independence, when
the book was sold to Columbia Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad success didn't happen sooner,'' he told Garchik.
``It's hard to be a writer. Unlike other professions, the longer
one's life is, the more difficult it becomes.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller wrote five more novels, but none of them had the impact
of ``Catch-22.'' The somber tone of his second novel, ``Something
Happened,'' puzzled readers who were expecting another comic
whirlwind. It dealt with the bleak life of a business executive
haunted by a nameless fear. In Heller's view, business was
organized on a pecking order of fear, where everyone is afraid of
the person above and the basic fear is the loss of job security.
</P>
<P>
   Gleason's drumbeating for ``Catch-22'' in his columns in the
'60s had helped the book's phenomenal success in paperback, but
things had changed by the time ``Something Happened'' was published
in 1974 _ Heller was a slow writer. It failed to ignite a
following.
</P>
<P>
   The movie version of ``Catch-22'' was made by director Mike
Nichols in 1971, with Alan Arkin as Yossarian and a screenplay by
Buck Henry.
</P>
<P>
   Yossarian is crazy enough to be alive at the end of the film,
paddling away in a lifeboat, and he is still alive at the end of
Heller's revisiting of the character in a second book, ``Closing
Time.'' In his preface to a 1994 reissue of ``Catch-22,'' Heller
notes that a physician friend in the second novel tells Yossarian:
``Everyone has to go. Everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, Heller writes, ``Yossarian, now 70, will have
to pass away, too. But it won't be by my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Crazy Yossarian is still alive, but Sunday it was Heller's turn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
