<SLUG> BC-FDA-BIOTECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORTERS AND OPPONENTS OF GENE-ALTERED FOOD PROTEST AT HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Ill.) (ms) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ As the Food and Drug Administration had the
last of its three public hearings on bio-engineered food Monday,
hundreds of protesters staged what organizers said was the largest
rally ever in the United States against the use of genetic
engineering in food.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign that scientists might become more active in
defense of biotechnology, about 30 professors and graduate students
from the nearby University of California campuses in Berkeley and
Davis had a demonstration of their own nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these demonstrators were from Berkeley's department of
plant and microbial biology, which last year entered into a
controversial arrangement to receive $25 million in research funds
from Novartis, the huge Swiss drug and agriculture company.
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting protests, which co-existed peacefully outside
the federal building here, reflect the increasing public concern
about genetically altered crops, which have swept largely unnoticed
into American agriculture over the last decade. Because of that
concern, the FDA had hearings in Chicago and Washington last month
to inform the public about its regulations on biotech foods and
seek comment on whether those rules need to be changed. The meeting
here took place under tight security, with everyone required to
walk through metal detectors and to wear identifying badges.
</P>
<P>
   The Novartis contribution, which represents 30 percent of the
microbial biology department's research funds, has caused
dissension both on campus and off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The circumstances in which it is being set up give just too
much space for suspicion that it is tainted by the contribution of
Novartis,'' said Ignacio Chapela, an assistant professor of
microbial ecology who had opposed the Novartis deal, saying it
would undermine the academic integrity of the university.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilhelm Gruissem, a professor of plant and microbial biology
who is chairman of the committee overseeing the university research
financed by Novartis, said scientists retain academic freedom under
the contract with the company.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gruissem who was the main organizer of Monday's
pro-biotech demonstration, united his colleagues behind the name
Coalition of Concerned Scientists. He acknowledged that their
connection to Novartis might weaken their appearance of
independence, but they said they had come of their own accord out
of their concern that the public was not being informed about the
benefits of biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are public sector scientists no matter where the funding
comes from, and we are free to say whatever we want,'' said
Gruissem, who said he has not been in a street protest since his
college days 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists said they fear that a backlash against
agricultural biotechnology could endanger research funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just sit in our offices and watch the debate, we're just
going to suffer,'' said John Taylor, another professor in the
department. He said the Novartis agreement has ``sensitized'' him
and his colleagues to the controversy surrounding biotechnology
foods. ``We get the e-mails about how bad you are,'' he said. ``So
we realize we had to be out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, biotechnology protesters trashed experimental plant
test plots at Berkeley, even though most of the research did not
involve genetic engineering. Nicholas Kaplinsky, a graduate student
at Monday's rally, said he lost a year's worth of research.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Margulis of Greenpeace said it was the largest protest
in this country against bio-engineered food, not counting the ones
at the World Trade Organization meeting in Seattle, which involved
many other issues in addition to biotech. Organizers said the size
of the rally belied the notion that the American public trusted the
FDA.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a kind of belief that the public doesn't care,''
said Chris Desser, coordinator of the Funders' Working Group on
Biotechnology, which represents some foundations concerned about
the issue. ``But an ignorant public is not the same as an apathetic
public. We have found the American public is not apathetic on this.
As they become educated they respond with great concern.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
