<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SPECTER-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SPECTER HEARS MEDICAL WOES
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Laura Winter  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - One had suffered a stroke. Another is facing
possible paralysis. And yet another lost her father. All three told
a senate subcommittee Monday, present mechanisms for protecting
patients don't work.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter (R-Penn.), chairman of the Senate's,
appropriations subcommittee on health convened the hearing in
response to an Institute of Medicine report that said as many as
98,000 patients die because of medical mistakes. Representatives
from the medical industry joined the women in testifying joined the
women in testifying to whether the federal government should get
involved in ensuring quality hospital care.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Medicine released Tuesday a report, entitled
``To Err is Human, Building a Safer Health System.'' In that
report, the authors called upon Congress to create a patient safety
center and to institute mandatory reporting of medical mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   The authors, in their report, argued that only through mandatory
reporting of medical mistakes could the present medical system
improve patient safety. They said without knowing what the
persistent problems are, it would be difficult to come up with
corrective strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nancy Dickey of the American Medical Association said that
while she too would like to see changes in the medical system, she
did not believe a federal government mandate was the right way. She
said she feared that without a guarantee of patient-doctor
confidentiality when repporting mistakes, doctors would shy away
from talking to a federal entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment we would not support a federal mandate,'' Dr.
Dickey said. ``It wold not improve the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would respectfully disagree,'' Specter said. ``I believe
there is a need for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he based his opinion on the fact that the three
women who came to the hearing were examples of how the medical
system had failed.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Artemis, Falls Church, Va., testified that what should
have been a one-time only, $12,000 dollar operation to replace her
hip was a tragic ``comedy of errors.'' In the end Artemis'
insurance company paid $200,000 for the five operations she
endured.
</P>
<P>
   Artemis said when her hip is replaced again, she will have a
50-50 chance of losing the use of her leg. She said she attained
information that her surgeon had been accused of making similar
mistakes before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see changes in the system that will prevent
this so that we don't have to get to the reporting stage,'' Artemis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's Dr. Stanton Smullens, representing the American
Hospital Association, agreed that more should be done in ensuring
patient safety. Smullens, who is also the chief medical officer for
Jefferson Health System, stopped short of saying he supported
legislation that would provide for federal oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Smullens, however, did say making reporting of mistakes
mandatory and protecting patient confidentiality was not
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to be an optimist about health care,'' Dr. Smullens
said. ``The fact that we are here talking about it and analyzing it
will help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
