u a BC-LOUIMA-VOLPE-ART-NYT &LR;      12-13 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-VOLPE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-OFFICER SENTENCED TO 30 YEARS FOR BRUTALIZING HAITIAN
IMMIGRANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 14 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After tearfully pleading for mercy and apologizing to
his victim, Justin Volpe was sentenced Monday to 30 years in prison
for brutalizing Abner Louima in a Brooklyn police station. The
judge denounced the former police officer for an ``unusually
heinous'' crime that had harmed not only Louima but the Police
Department and society at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short of intentional murder, one cannot imagine a more
barbarous misuse of power than Volpe's,'' Judge Eugene Nickerson
said in a packed courtroom in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, as
he sentenced Volpe for a notorious act that drew national attention
and fueled angry charges of police brutality against blacks in New
York City. Louima is black, and Volpe is white.
</P>
<P>
   The former officer's punishment was less than the sentence of
life in prison without parole that the judge could have imposed.
Volpe, 27, could be released after 25 years if he behaves well in
prison, and with credit for the six months he served since
interrupting his trial last May to plead guilty to violating
Louima's civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe was also ordered to pay $277,495 in restitution to Louima,
although Nickerson acknowledged that he would not be able to do so.
Without explaining how he had arrived at the figure, Nickerson
directed Volpe to pay Louima $25 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe admitted that he had violently shoved a broken broomstick
into Louima's rectum in a police station bathroom, inflicting
severe internal injuries on the 32-year-old Haitian immigrant,
because he mistakenly believed that Louima had punched him hard in
the head during a street brawl, knocking him down and causing him
to fear for his life. It turned out that another man had punched
Volpe. ``However frightened and angry he was, Volpe's response was
wildly out of proportion,'' Nickerson said.
</P>
<P>
   In court Monday, Louima described the terror he felt and the
injuries he suffered on the floor of the police station bathroom
where he was assaulted in August 1997. He told the judge of the
psychological pain he later endured because Volpe and his lawyer
suggested that the injuries had come from a homosexual encounter
before his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This big lie,'' Louima said, ``has caused me and my family
incredible pain and emotional suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpe, looking pale and somewhat thinner than his hefty,
muscular figure before he was jailed, and wearing jail clothes that
included trousers that had to be rolled up at the ankles because
they were much too long, told Nickerson, ``I was and still am
ashamed and deeply regretful for what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I betrayed Abner Louima's rights, I betrayed the
city's confidence in police officers, I betrayed myself and my
partner and I betrayed my lawyer.'' The last was a reference to his
not having told his lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg, that he was guilty
until the evidence had become overwhelming at his trial.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently choking up as he stood before the bench, Volpe, who
had been on the force four years when he brutalized Louima and was
dismissed immediately after his conviction, said he had ``come to
realize that this case goes beyond me and Abner Louima.''
</P>
<P>
   Louima showed no emotion as he sat listening in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
