<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-EMERGENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALM IN KHARTOUM AFTER SUDAN'S PRESIDENT DISSOLVES LEGISLATURE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The speaker of Sudan's National Assembly on Monday accused the
country's president, Omar Hassan el-Bashir, of launching a coup
d'etat after el-Bashir dissolved the legislature and imposed a
state of emergency for the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   The parliament speaker, Hassan Turabi, the most powerful
political adversary of the president, accused el-Bashir of
violating the Sudanese Constitution and betraying the ruling
National Congress Party, which controls nearly all of the
legislature's 360 seats and is in turn dominated by Turabi's power
base, the National Islamic Front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will take the case to the grass roots of the National
Congress and decide what to do,'' Turabi said, according to
Reuters. ``If these political matters fail, popular forces will
have to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   But el-Bashir, speaking at a news conference, justified his
pre-emptive political strike as ``a disciplinary measure taken to
restore law and discipline'' in Africa's largest country.
El-Bashir, who donned a military fatigue uniform for the occasion,
promised no drastic steps ``unless there is a violation of the law
or of the state of emergency,'' which was announced on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Sudanese soldiers cordoned off the legislative building
and set up checkpoints around the capital Khartoum, which was
otherwise reported quiet because of Ramadan, the Muslim holy month
of fasting.
</P>
<P>
   James Foley, a State Department spokesman in Washington, said at
the daily briefing that the significance of el-Bashir's measures
was ``really difficult to assess, at least from this distance.``
</P>
<P>
   But Foley added, ``It's important to note that Bashir and Turabi
have engaged in regular power struggles since the regime seized
power in 1989.''
</P>
<P>
   That was when el-Bashir, then an army general, ousted the
country's ruler, Sadeq al-Mahdi, in a military coup supported by
Turabi. El-Bashir set up an Islamic state and banned political
parties.
</P>
<P>
   As rivalry intensified between the two men, Turabi used the
National Assembly to expand his authority and influence.
El-Bashir's dissolution of the legislature in effect tried to
deprive Turabi of his power base.
</P>
<P>
   Clovis Maksud, the Arab League's former ambassador in
Washington, said that by dissolving the National Assembly,
el-Bashir was buying time for three months as well as seeking to
puncture the power that Turabi had amassed as speaker of the
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paradoxically, it might weaken Bashir,'' said Maksud, who now
directs the Center for the Global South at American University in
Washington. ``By establishing his power, he might be losing his
influence.''
</P>
<P>
   El-Bashir has shown concern about the erosion of his own
presidential powers. The legislature on Tuesday was expected to
pass legislation allowing the direct election of Sudan's provincial
governors, in which the president now has a key voice.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, el-Bashir complained that some
provincial governors considered themselves above the government's
control. ``If all governors do that, then we are powerless,''
el-Bashir was quoted by Reuters as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan has been weakened by a 16-year-civil war between the
country's Arab majority and the insurgents in the south who
represent the black, largely Christian minority.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic government has also been increasingly isolated
following Western charges that it has supported terrorism. Last
month, the U.S. Congress passed a law to give food assistance to
the Sudanese insurgents. President Clinton has not yet decided
whether to implement the law, which international aid agencies say
would put their own operations at risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
