<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7908 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-ART-1S     12-13 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI PARLIAMENT NARROWLY SUPPORTS BARAK'S PEACE TALKS WITH
SYRIA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to correct byline)  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT10 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After six hours of impassioned and often raucous
debate _ and just two days before talks begin in Washington _
Israel's Parliament on Monday narrowly endorsed Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's quest for a comprehensive peace settlement with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Israel will have to pay ``a heavy territorial price,'' Barak
acknowledged in an emotional plea for parliamentary support. But
failure to pursue peace with Damascus ``could cost us in blood,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vote of confidence in the prime minister's negotiating plans
passed with 47 votes in favor, 37 against, and 24 abstentions _ a
victory, but far from the strong majority Barak expected. Three
parties in Barak's governing coalition pointedly refused to back
him on Monday night, pointing to potential trouble when a promised
national referendum is held on any final peace pact.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is to meet with Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa of Syria
in Washington Wednesday and Thursday for the highest-level direct
discussions ever held between Syria and Israel. President Clinton
is expected to host the opening and closing sessions of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's appearance in Parliament on Monday was
widely considered his most important appearance since he took the
oath of office there five months ago. Calling this week's
negotiations ``an opportunity that cannot be squandered,'' he
argued that for the first time in its history, Israel has a chance
for a lasting peace with all of its immediate neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Israel's perspective, real peace with Syria and the
Palestinians, if it can be achieved, is the pinnacle of the Zionist
vision,'' he said, ignoring opposition hecklers. ``It is a
revolution. It is a new era in Israel's relations with the Arab
world, and the world at large.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak implicitly conceded that the Golan Heights would be handed
back to Syria in a peace accord, as thousands of residents from the
northern border zone demonstrated angrily outside the Parliament.
The precise boundaries of withdrawal ``will be determined in
negotiations in accordance with the depth of peace and the quality
of security arrangements,'' he said, echoing the formula used by
the late Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, Barak's mentor, in the last
attempt at a settlement with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Sharon, leader of the opposition Likud bloc, followed
Barak to the podium. He predicted that any accord featuring a Golan
withdrawal would go down to defeat in a referendum. He tauntingly
read another statement by Rabin, this one from 1992, that ``it is
inconceivable that even in peace we would descend from the Golan
Heights.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon charged that the government acquiesced to President Hafez
Assad's desire for ``American aid and modern American weapons'' and
President Clinton's hunger ``for a stunning achievement at any cost
before the end of his term in office.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak had praised Clinton in his remarks for his ``personal
involvement and devotion to the cause of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The planned national vote on the Syrian peace accord would be
the first referendum in Israel's history. Lawmakers have yet to
determine how the balloting would be organized, or who will draft
the question that will be put to voters. Israel's attorney-general
rejected an opposition proposal that Arab citizens _ a sixth of the
electorate _ be excluded from the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The vote following Monday night's debate _ a simple yea or nay
response to the peace initiative outlined by the prime minister on
Monday night _ provided the first real test of Barak's coalition
strategy. For Barak's Labor allies, the results appeared worrisome.
He assembled a multiparty government to provide the broadest
possible majority for peace with Syria and the Palestinians, but on
Monday night he was left with an uncomfortably slim plurality.
</P>
<P>
   The second largest faction in Barak's ruling coalition _ the
Sephardic-dominated Shas party _ unexpectedly abstained from the
vote and openly criticized his ``unclear'' negotiating strategy.
Most members of two smaller conservative parties in the government
_ the National Religious Party, backed by settlers in the West
Bank, and Yisrael B'aliya, representing Russian immigrants _ voted
against the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of all three coalition factions then joined Sharon and
other opposition figures outside Parliament in a rally with
protesters from the Golan Heights. ``We feel that the Golan is our
home, and you cannot throw people out of their homes,'' Guy Neuman,
a demonstrator from Qatrin, the largest Golan town, told an Israeli
television interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, anticipating opposition attacks, portrayed himself as a
patriot and career military man who had devoted his life to
Israel's defense. He reminded his audience that he had fought
against the Syrians in the Golan Heights during the 1967 war. ``I
am fully familiar with every valley and every rock in the Golan,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He was accompanied to the Parliament by Nadia Cohen, the widow
of Eli Cohen, an Israeli agent who has executed by Syria in 1965
for espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cohen, who is seeking the return from Damascus of her
husband's interred remains, publicly endorsed Barak's peace
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary interest is Israel's security,'' Barak said. ``The
agreement that we aspire to reach with our Syrian neighbors is one
that will also put an end to our conflict with Lebanon, and will
include diverse and effective systems to preserve security and
peace between our countries at all times. Such an agreement is not
beyond reach.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a meeting earlier on Monday, he told Cabinet colleagues that
while Israel had made no new commitments to Syria before this
week's talks, it ``would not erase'' any promises made in previous
negotiations during the administrations of Rabin and former Prime
Ministers Shimon Peres, and Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Syrians and Israelis have profoundly different recollections of
those past pledges, however.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrians have said the Rabin government was prepared to
withdraw to Israel's 1967 borders _ that is, to the eastern
shoreline of the Sea of Galilee. Israeli negotiators deny making
such a promise. And former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu claims
to have extracted Syrian permission for a permanent Israeli
presence atop Mount Heron, the Golan's high point _ an assertion
dismissed by diplomats in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negotiations with Syria will be difficult and paved with
crises,'' Barak told his Cabinet ministers, according to state
radio reports. ``I have no illusions about the nature of the Middle
East, and I have no doubt that only the overall strength of Israel
will ensure that agreements are honored.``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 2115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GM-NAZI-COMPENSATION-     12-13 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-NAZI-COMPENSATION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM'S OPEL UNIT SAYS IT WILL LIKELY PAY NAZI SLAVE LABORERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The German subsidiary of General Motors
said Monday that it would probably contribute to a fund to
compensate forced laborers in the Nazi era, a move that could make
GM the first American company to accept responsibility for those
abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidiary, Opel, made the statement as lawyers for the
former workers appeared close to a final multibillion-dollar accord
with the German government and industry. An accord would safeguard
the companies from legal claims.
</P>
<P>
   GM bought the German car maker, Adam Opel, more than 60 years
ago. General Motors' long-held view has been that because the
German government took command of Opel factories in the war,
compensation was its responsibility. Opel employed at least 2,000
forced laborers in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Big German companies, which also clung to that view, decided
more than a year ago that they would be wiser to negotiate a
friendly settlement than endure a nightmarish court battle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, the general counsel of GM, Thomas Gottschalk, said
tonight that the company was ``open and seriously willing to
consider participation in the fund,'' but that it was awaiting the
final outcome of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers, the German government and industry are negotiating a
fund of 10 billion marks, or $5.3 billion, participants in the
talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Under a plan that has been floated by Stuart Eizenstat, the
American deputy treasury secretary who is trying to mediate a pact,
GM and up to 200 other American companies with German subsidiaries
would create a separate fund with 1 billion marks, roughly $500
million. German government and industry officials remain adamantly
opposed to a separate American fund, arguing that all companies
that used forced labor should pay into the same effort. It is not
clear how this issue will be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   People on both sides of the negotiations say an overall
agreement could come together in a few days. German officials have
publicly refused to increase their latest offer, a total of 8
billion marks, about $4.1 billion, with 5 billion from industry and
3 billion from the government.
</P>
<P>
   But people close to the negotiations say they are becoming
resigned to paying 10 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a kind of consensus around the 10 billion
number,'' said one person involved in the talks, which involve
American class-action lawyers, Jewish organizations, Washington and
German industry and government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will know within the next 24 hours if it works,'' said Burt
Neuborne, one of the lead attorneys said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, executives at Adam Opel said they are speaking up now
because negotiations are at a crucial stage. ``Now is the moment
when it will be determined whether the negotiations are a success
or not,'' said Bruno Seifert, a spokesman for GM's Opel subsidiary
in Russelsheim, near Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor, which was one of the first companies to be named in
a class-action suit over Nazi-era forced labor, said it is still
considering whether to take part in a fund.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many other American companies have German
subsidiaries that used forced laborers. But people close to the
talks say they have put together a list of nearly 200 companies,
which they are trying to coax into joining the effort.
</P>
<P>
   The American class-action lawyers remain in heated disagreement
with German officials about how that the compensation should be
handled.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Gibowski, a spokesman for the German industry
foundation, has insisted that all companies contribute to the same
fund. As things stand right now, he said, the foundation still
hasn't collected enough commitments from German corporations to
produce the 5 billion marks that business is supposed to
contribute, and the foundation is worried that the number of
companies taking part would diminish if some put their
contributions into other funds. The German government, which has
agreed to the contribution of 3 billion marks. Negotiators are
hoping that additional German companies will join the fund when an
agreement is finally reached, adding to the total compensation.
</P>
<P>
   But ``if there is a separate American fund, then that would lead
to a separate French fund and a separate British fund _ and there
would be nothing left for the German fund,'' said Gibowski.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Ford and General Motors have long admitted that
their German factories used forced labor.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates for former forced laborers, most of whom were
brought to Germany against their will from central European
countries, say that American companies had complicated relations
with their subsidiaries around the war years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were people in charge of the Ford plant during the war
that were promoted to the top levels of Ford in Europe after the
war,'' said Lothar Evers, director of the Nazi Victims' Support
Center, an association in Cologne.
</P>
<P>
   Ford even asked Washington for compensation for a factory that
Allied forces bombed during the war, Evers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can claim damages for buildings that were destroyed by
bombs, it is only fair that people whose lives were destroyed
should be able to seek claims,'' Evers said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated exhortations from the German government, only
about 60 German companies have offered to contribute to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the American Jewish Committee published a list of 257
active German companies that appear to have used forced labor and
have not yet agreed to pay compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Many are small and medium-sized companies, but they also include
Philipp Holzmann AG, a huge construction company that was recently
rescued from bankruptcy by the German government and big big banks.
</P>
<P>
   The battles among groups representing former forced laborers
have been almost as intense as the bargaining with German leaders.
The players include the World Jewish Congress and the Israeli
government as well as a fractious alliance of class-action
attorneys who represent mostly non-Jewish workers in central and
eastern Europe.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The lead class-action attorneys include Neuborne, a professor of
law at New York University; Melvyn Weiss, who battled Swiss banks
over assets owned by Holocaust victims and who represented several
states against the tobacco industry; Michael Hausfeld, a securities
lawyer who led a landmark battle against Texaco over racial
discrimination; and Edward Fagan, who has sued the Swiss banks,
scores of German companies and, most recently, Japanese companies
for wartime actions.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers stand to make tens of millions if not hundreds of
millions of dollars from a settlement, a fact that has generated
animosities among some Jewish groups, and the lawyers have battled
each other in recent days over how hard to bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government, which has been monitoring the talks, has
become increasingly concerned that the attorneys were holding out
for too much money at the expense of aging Holocaust survivors who
are rapidly dying of old age, one lawyer involved in the talks
said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts estimate that 240,000 slave laborers, most of whom were
concentration camp prisoners forced to work in factories, are still
alive today. About half of those people are Jewish. In addition, as
many as two million other people were coerced into various degrees
of forced labor. Most came from Central European countries and
Russia and were not Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Under plans being discussed, a new German foundation would make
money available to victims primarily through bilateral groups that
already exist in most central European nations to pursue claims
against the German government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
