<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7913 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-R-WALLSTREET-PAYDAYS-     12-13 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-WALLSTREET-PAYDAYS-ART-1125(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET RICHES HUMBLE AND WORRY TRADITIONAL WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note) (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.  Graphic  is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 (This article was reported by JOSEPH KAHN, LAURA M. HOLSON and
PATRICK McGEEHAN and was written by Kahn.)  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even by the inflated standards of high finance, Wall
Street is overflowing with holiday cheer this year. Investment
banks have set aside $13 billion to pay bonuses, 20 percent more
than last year, with pay packages above $10 million no longer a
rarity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet among Wall Streeters whose incomes once astounded Middle
America, the mood has changed. One industry veteran bemoaned the
``opportunity cost'' of remaining a financier in the Internet Age.
Others are leaving to join online start-ups, technology companies
and venture capital firms, the pillars of the new economy, where
they sometimes take home more than their old bosses from Day 1 _
and, they say, have more fun.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since Wall Street became the surest
professional path to riches during the frenzied 1980s, those with
the biggest paydays are former investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Like Timothy Weller. He is the talk of the Street, but mostly
because he no longer works there. Last summer, Weller, 34, left
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, where he was a middle-ranking analyst
tracking the telecommunications business, to join Akamai
Technologies, which provides networking services for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai, based in Cambridge, Mass., enticed him to sign on as
chief financial officer by selling him 1.05 million shares, valued
then at $2.63 million, and even lent him the money to buy them.
Gratification was quick: When Akamai went public in October, its
stock soared from $26 to $230. Weller's stake is now worth $240
million.
</P>
<P>
   Few bankers will reap such gains, but many are still taking
their chances on the Internet. One-time masters of the universe say
banking has become prosaic, with the heavy demands no longer
producing unrivaled rewards. Bankers now ogle online entrepreneurs
the way lawyers and accountants once envied Wall Streeters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that investment bankers were at the cutting
edge,'' said Mark Long, who as a banker for Credit Suisse First
Boston helped some of America's hottest Internet companies go
public. ``Today, bankers are just hired guns.''
</P>
<P>
   During a trip last summer to promote the Internet start-up
Intraware to potential investors, Long, 32, accepted his client's
offer to become a vice president, joining shortly before it went
public.
</P>
<P>
   If Intraware does well, Long stands to earn considerably more
than he did as a banker, thanks to stock options. But that is only
one reason he left. ``You get tired of sleeping 45 minutes a
night,'' he said, ``to sell someone else's business.''
</P>
<P>
   With profits for financial firms and bonuses for bankers at
all-time highs, there is certainly no looming crisis on Wall
Street. Even those who leave banking often do so with trepidation,
fearing that inflated Internet stocks could come crashing down.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is more a blow to the psyche. The pressure to earn
Internet windfalls shows up in little ways, as with the rising
stock analyst who says he has lost repeated bidding wars for Upper
East Side apartments and adds, only half in jest, that $10 million
does not buy much of a condo these days.
</P>
<P>
   The online lure is also enhanced by ex-bankers who have changed
careers seamlessly. Jeff Bezos worked on Wall Street until he
founded Amazon.com, and that trend keeps gathering steam. Bezos,
now many times a billionaire, hired a number of other former
bankers and made them Internet retailers. Analysts and deal makers
involved in technology, telecommunications and the Internet readily
change hats and become financial officers or strategic planners at
start-ups, often bringing along former colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Some defectors compete directly with their old firms. At least
three new online investment banks and several Internet
stock-and-bond trading companies, all planning to use the Internet
to steal business from traditional investment banks, are led by
people who learned the business from the inside.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lessin, chief executive of Wit Capital, an online
investment bank, and formerly a top officer at Salomon Smith
Barney, has poached a long list of bankers from Salomon, Merrill
Lynch and other firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I'm a banker but I get to wear casual clothes,''
said Kate Cornish, 28, who left Salomon for Wit a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Especially susceptible are those who are three to five years out
of business school _ on the cusp of devoting a career to a firm,
but young enough to start fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `I want to be a multimillionaire by the time I'm 30,
but if I stay at Morgan Stanley, it may take me until I'm 50,'''
said Joseph Perella, Morgan's head of investment banking.
Americans, he added, want ``instant gratification.''
</P>
<P>
   In reaction, Morgan Stanley has started offering stock to some
newly hired bankers. BancBoston Robertson Stephens, a leading
technology banking firm, has lost 10 bankers to Internet clients
this year. The firm recently took 300 employees to a weekend
retreat to help build esprit de corps and to aid retention, though
firm officials said it was not a response to this year's attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Investment bank recruiters once acted like bouncers, accepting
only the best. Goldman Sachs still finds plenty of eager
applicants, says Peter Kiernan, a senior partner who oversees
hiring from business schools, but now, he said, ``if you expect to
back up a truck and load the top 10 people in a class, you're going
to be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Business school graduates think entrepreneurial jobs are the
wave of the future, Kiernan said. He now tries to persuade people
that they can be entrepreneurs within an investment bank, which can
be a tough sell. ``One thing you don't do is try to sell against
the Net,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Wall Street did not have to try so hard. With the
rapid growth of stocks and bonds and the explosion of mergers,
securities firms were seen as controlling the levers of America's
economy. Investment banking, offering top dollar, consistently
ranked as the No. 1 or No. 2 career choice for top business
graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Popular culture followed the money. ``Wall Street,'' the movie,
and ``Bonfire of the Vanities,'' the novel, created a stereotype of
sharklike bankers and traders whose only obstacle was their own
greed. In the early 1990s, investment banks were seen as the
engines of globalization, financing road projects in China and
privatizing phone companies in Brazil. While corporate America
merged and consolidated, bankers raked in record fees.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet, like an electronic black hole, has stolen all
the gravity. Securities firms seem to have less to do with creating
Internet companies than they did with arranging restructurings or
sending capital abroad. And through the Silicon Valley
looking-glass, Wall Street egos can appear almost humble.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Scott McNealy, chief executive of Sun Microsystems, wrote an
Op-Ed article in The New York Times last summer extolling the value
that entrepreneurs create in the economy and belittling the
``nonjobs'' of bankers. In ``The New New Thing,'' Michael Lewis,
who a decade ago chronicled Wall Street hubris in ``Liar's Poker,''
portrays today's financiers as desperate grovelers who shovel money
at Internet entrepreneurs in hopes of profiting from their creative
instincts.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seem no different. They have pumped up the stocks of
Internet-friendly finance companies so much that a recent survey of
the wealthiest people in finance, compiled by Institutional
Investor magazine, found that the richest financiers often double
as Internet entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab, the founder, chairman and chief executive of the
No. 1-ranked Internet broker, has seen his Schwab stock holdings
soar to almost $5.8 billion, making him the second-wealthiest
person in finance after Warren Buffett. J. Joe Ricketts, chairman
and co-chief executive of Ameritrade, the No. 7 Internet broker,
has stock holdings of almost $2 billion, eclipsing the combined
stock holdings of the leaders of Morgan Stanley, Merrill and
Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, headhunters rarely tried to lure bankers away
from Wall Street. But dot-com fever has changed that. When
Priceline.com decided in June to go after an investment banker to
fill a senior post at a unit it expected to take public shortly, it
asked Cynthia Remec, an executive recruiter, to round up candidates
the same day and set up interviews the next.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Remec frantically phoned 20 bankers to fill this tall order.
Within hours, to her surprise, she found 15 who were eager to hop
the train to Stamford, Conn., Priceline's headquarters, for an
interview. Priceline hired one of them, Anne Maffei, a former
banker at J.P. Morgan, as a senior executive at Webhouse.com, its
grocery-shopping affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers and analysts on the front lines of the new economy
sometimes make especially easy pickings. Though the work hours of
Internet entrepreneurs are legendary, many bankers say the life
compares favorably with the burden of arranging a huge volume of
public offerings and mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like lead oar in `Ben Hur,''' said Bill Burnham, a
top analyst for Credit Suisse First Boston who left to join
Softbank Capital, an Internet-focused venture fund. ``No one works
harder than a tech banker or has less control over his life.''
</P>
<P>
   The lure of stock options is also potent. Thomas Casey, 47, left
as co-head of global telecommunications and media at Merrill Lynch
to head corporate development, among other things, at Global
Crossing, a new telecom company that is building a fiber optic
network for Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the move was a roll of the dice. He left behind a
hefty pay package _ $3 million to $5 million a year at his level.
When he started at Global Crossing, he took a huge pay cut. But he
got options on 2 million shares when the stock was valued at $2 a
share. Those options are now valued at nearly $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Wall Street, you are not going to be so rich that your
children and grandchildren would never have to work again,'' Casey
said. ``But you have that opportunity if you go to a start-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey said money was only one motivation. ``Ultimately, I wanted
to be in a position where I participated directly in creating
something substantial,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, some Wall Street firms are responding aggressively.
Nearly all the big ones have taken stakes in online trading
companies, including an array of virtual stock-trading forums known
as electronic communications networks. Most now allow clients to
buy and sell securities on the Internet. Several analysts predict
that Wall Street's willingness to compete online will slow the
growth of purely online rivals _ and perhaps stem the outflow of
seasoned bankers.
</P>
<P>
   But John Hewitt, a longtime Goldman vice president who helped
execute that firm's efforts to modernize its technology, still sees
the biggest securities firms as being stuck in another era. He
recently left Goldman to become president of Knight/Trimark, which
has used technology and low fees to lure stock-trading business.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, 48, said he long expected to retire as a Goldman
employee. But the more he learned about the Internet, he said, the
more it gnawed at him _ to the point that he raised his hand for
the Knight/Trimark job during a business dinner with Ken Pasternak,
the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Wall Street firms, Goldman included, have become so
successful that they have a vested interest in the status quo,''
Hewitt said. ``The more I thought about it, the more I felt I had
to go somewhere that had a sense of speed and that wasn't afraid of
the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 2119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
