<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL: SURFING (AND SKIING) THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Dec. 19) 
(mk) 
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEARCH FOR THE PERFECT SLOPE
</P>
<P>
   www.skinet.com
</P>
<P>
   Ski resorts have been scrambling to get their own Web sites up
and working, some with more sophistication than others. On the site
for Steamboat, Colo., for example, if your computer is equipped for
audio, you can hear a detailed daily report on conditions. If you
want to see rather than hear about the snow, or lack of it, you may
find a Webcam photo on the home page of your favorite mountain.
Comparison shopping for a resort is trickier, and booking is
probably still best done on the telephone, but there are some sites
that provide a good base of information.
</P>
<P>
   Skinet, with selections from the magazines Ski, Skiing and
Freeze, has an authoritative tone and a lot of useful features. The
home page offers capsules of the articles, and you can click to get
the whole thing. Two of the four when I looked were ``The Old
Farmer's Almanac Predicts Snowy Winter'' and ``Last-Minute
Millennium Deals,'' the latter with links to travel deals. There
are links for forums, chat areas, games and gear.
</P>
<P>
   In the Snow Finder section, you select a state, a Canadian
province or a country and get a report on current snow conditions.
I picked Alaska and got the Alyeska Resort: 30 to 84 inches of
packed powder. Quebec reported no snow this early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING THE SKI MALL
</P>
<P>
   skitown.com
</P>
<P>
   This is more like a big city than a small town, or maybe a giant
mall putting a roof over a host of ski-mountain resort guides.
Browsers will find SkiResortsGuide.com, MountainResortsGuide.com
and a bunch of others all here on the ``premier virtual mountain
resort community on the Internet.'' Skitown lists more than 570
places to slip and slide in the United States and Canada. There are
also sections for real estate around ski towns, a place to exchange
messages with other skiers online or to read or write reviews,
weather reports and forecasts; there are jobs, travel packages and
a newsstand with selections from publications in resort towns. You
can search for ski areas on a map of the United States or Canada or
specify a narrower geographical area _ the Rockies, for example.
There is also an A-to-Z list (which was actually an A-to-Y list)
running from the Afton Alps Ski Area in Minnesota to the Yawgoo
Valley Ski Area in Rhode Island. Information is still sketchy for
some areas, and some links aren't operating yet.
</P>
<P>
   Everything on the Web site seems neatly organized, and it moved
swiftly the half-dozen times I visited on various days and at
various hours, although that may have just been luck. Skitown is
based in Fort Collins, Colo. You can't reserve directly on Skitown,
although there is a form to be filled out that will be passed on to
one of the company's partners.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING A DIFFERENT ROUTE
</P>
<P>
   There are innumerable other ski sites, of course. Of the popular
Web portals I tried, Yahoo is well tuned for skiers. AOL has a
travel section, as does CompuServe, as does GoTo, and MSN links you
to Expedia, also run by Microsoft, which has a ski-vacations
subcategory. Searching ``ski and snow'' on Yahoo brings up a
worldwide directory by region, from which you can get basic
information, updated daily, about European and Southern Hemisphere
resorts as well as those in North America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
