<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIVE CULTURE IN VANCOUVER  
 CHILDREN AT LITERARY SITES  
 BAJA WHALE WATCHING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Questions may be italicized)  
 (af)  
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Please help me find a one-day guided tour of Vancouver that
focuses on the area's native culture. _ Jamie Witter, Bridgeport,
Conn. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In response to a surge of interest in Pacific Northwest
native culture, several Vancouver companies have recently begun to
offer specialized day tours.
</P>
<P>
   West Coast City and Nature Sightseeing offers tours throughout
the year. The four- to five-hour excursion, led by Jeff Watts, a
Nuu-chah-nulth guide, visits the brightly painted totem poles in
the 1,000-acre Stanley Park, as well as the University of British
Columbia Museum of Anthropology, with its vast collection of wood
carvings, totem poles, canoes, ceremonial dishes and jewelry by
Haida, Kwakiutl, Coast Salish and other cultural groups.
</P>
<P>
   The outdoor sculpture area includes two contemporary Haida
houses and a number of totems. The tour, which travels by minibus,
also goes to places used by native descendants; among them is the
Native Education Center, which is built in the style of a long
house. The cost is $29, figured at a rate of $1.48 Canadian dollars
to the U.S. dollar. Information: (604) 451-1600.
</P>
<P>
   Landsea Tours offers a five-hour bus excursion from early May to
mid-October. It visits the totem poles in Stanley Park, a long
house in the Capilano Reserve area north of Vancouver and the
19th-century St. Paul's Mission Church, one of the oldest surviving
mission churches in Vancouver. The $47 price includes a light meal,
and traditional activities, like weaving with cedar bark.
Information: (604) 255-7272.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Spirit Tours has a similar five-hour itinerary for the
same price and during the same time period. Telephone (604)
683-0209, fax (604) 683-6037. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm taking my 5-year-old daughter to England for the first
time this spring and would like to visit some places connected to
children's literature (Beatrix Potter is among the writers who come
to mind). Can you help? _ Lindsey McDonald, Bangor, Maine &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. England is a great place for visiting children's literary
sites, which include museums and attractions devoted to several
authors and their famous characters.
</P>
<P>
   Beatrix Potter, author of the nearly 100-year-old Peter Rabbit
books, lived in the Lake District for some 40 years. Several sites
in this lovely hilly region celebrate her books and her life. At
The World of Beatrix Potter, in Bowness-on-Windermere in Cumbria, a
theater shows biographical videos and there are displays devoted to
Potter's work as a farmer and conservationist.
</P>
<P>
   But the main attraction is the elaborate recreations of scenes
from her books, among them, Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle's kitchen and
Squirrel Nutkin's old oak tree. Between October and April, the
hours are 10 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. daily; until 5:30 in the warmer
months. Admission is $5.25, children $3.25. Information: (44-15394)
88444. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two other Beatrix Potter sites in Cumbria are run by the
National Trust, a British conservation organization. Both are open
from the end of March to the end of October and admission is by
timed tickets. At The Beatrix Potter Gallery, 28 Main Street in
Hawkshead, there are exhibitions of sketches and watercolors that
Potter produced for her own stories.
</P>
<P>
   It is open Sunday through Thursday from 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.
Admission is $4.70, $2.35 for children. Information: (44-15394)
36355. The second site, Hill Top, was Beatrix Potter's 17th-century
home from 1905 until her death in 1943. The small beamed cottage
has been kept as she left it, with her furniture and china all in
place. Admission $6.30, $3.15 for children. The house is in Near
Sawrey, Ambleside. Information: (44-15394) 36269. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 150 miles north of London, in Peak Village, fans of the
author Kenneth Graham and the illustrator E.H. Shepard can visit
the new Wind in the Willows Attraction in Derbyshire. The exhibits
include life-size models of Ratty, Mole and Badger (with sound
effects like Badger's snores), recreations of the meadows, woods
and streams where they cavorted and an interactive display on the
real creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $5.25, children $3.25. Open 10 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.
daily from Oct. 1 until April 1, to 5:30 p.m. during the rest of
the year. Information: (44-1629) 733433.
</P>
<P>
   You can walk through scenes from ``James and the Giant Peach,''
``Matilda'' and other Roald Dahl stories at the Roald Dahl
Children's Gallery at the Buckinghamshire County Museum in
Aylesbury, 35 miles west of London. The gallery, on the A41, is
quite popular and entry is by timed tickets. Hours vary throughout
the year. Admission is $5.65, $3.25 for children. Information:
(44-1296) 331441.
</P>
<P>
   The British Tourist Authority has a free Literary Britain map,
with a section devoted to children's literature. The phone number
in New York is (800) 462-2748, fax (212) 986-1188. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I want to sign up for a whale-watching trip in Baja this
winter. I'm specifically interested in gray whales. Do you know of
an organized tour? _ Raymond W. Fritsch, Columbus, Ohio &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In mid- to late fall, thousands of gray whales migrate from
the Bering Sea to their winter home in the comparatively warm
Pacific lagoons off the Baja Peninsula. January to early April is
whale-watching season, with February considered the optimum month.
Here are two tour possibilities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Natural Habitat Adventures, based in Boulder, Colo. offers
several five-day trips; departure dates include Feb. 15, 18 and 21.
Participants (up to 20 per trip) stay in thatched-roof cabanas
overlooking the San Ignacio Lagoon in the Vizcaino Biosphere
Reserve, and take two daily whale-watching excursions aboard
skiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Other activities include hikes, bird-watching and sea-kayaking.
The cost is $2,295, double occupancy, excluding international air
fare to Loreto. Information: (800) 543-8917.
</P>
<P>
   Oceanic Society Expeditions, in San Francisco, has a nine-day
tour that also goes to San Ignacio Lagoon, which is a prime calving
area for gray whales. On Feb. 18, the group (of up to 28 people)
departs from San Diego aboard a 95-foot motor vessel with 15 double
and triple cabins, shared baths, a library and salon.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to San Ignacio, the boat stops at the San Benitos
Islands, breeding grounds for elephant seals and California sea
lions. Two days are spent at the lagoon. Other stops include Cedros
Island and Ensenada. The cost per person is $1,890. Information:
(800) 326-7491, fax (415) 474-3395.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 2125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7926 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-GAYS-MILITARY-2NDTAKE     12-13 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: training proposals.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Navy's personnel boss, Vice Adm. Daniel T. Oliver, did issue
a Navy-wide memorandum on Oct. 28, sternly reminding commanding
officers that they ``must not condone homosexual jokes, epithets or
derogatory comments, and must ensure a command climate that fosters
respect for all individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum continued: ``Service members should be able to
report crimes and harassment free from fear of harm, reprisal or
inappropriate or inadequate governmental response.''
</P>
<P>
   It then described in detail what the policy does and does not
permit.
</P>
<P>
   When the secretary reissued the policy guidelines in August, the
message drew respect and derision from officers and enlisted
troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, screwing up any homosexual case provides an
excellent opportunity to appear on `60 Minutes,' wrote Col. James
C. Walker, the staff judge advocate for the 1st Marine
Expeditionary Force at Camp Pendleton, Calif. in an e-mail message
sent to commanders outlining Cohen's guidelines. ``My job is to
deny you that opportunity. Call me on all these cases.''
</P>
<P>
   But in another e-mail message circulating at the Marine base at
Twenty-Nine Palms, Calif., one officer wrote to several others:
``Due to the 'hate crime' death of a homo in the Army we now have
to take extra steps to ensure the safety of the queer who has
'told' (not kept his part of the D.O.D. ''don't ask, don't tell''
policy.)
</P>
<P>
   Whoever gets political credit for being first to call for the
policy's elimination, the fact that some of the nation's most
prominent Democrats want it scrapped suggests a major battle ahead
in Congress. Republicans do not support the policy either, but they
generally do not want gays in the military at all.
</P>
<P>
   The process that is leading to the re-examination of the gays in
the military is similar to that which drove Clinton to shift his
position on another sensitive military issue, whether to reopen a
firing range in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago Mrs. Clinton, apparently with her eye on New York
politics and the sizeable Puerto Rican community there, sided with
the governor of Puerto Rico and said the base should be permanently
closed. Shortly thereafter, Gore adopted the same position. Last
month, the president rejected the alternative recommendations of
the Navy and ordered the end of military exercises with live fire
on the base at Vieques.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
