<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7927 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-ART-2N     12-13 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-ART-2NDLDLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI PARLIAMENT NARROWLY SUPPORTS BARAK'S PEACE TALKS WITH
SYRIA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 3rd graf to correct vote in Parliament)  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT10 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After six hours of impassioned and often raucous
debate _ and just two days before talks begin in Washington _
Israel's Parliament on Monday narrowly endorsed Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's quest for a comprehensive peace settlement with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Israel will have to pay ``a heavy territorial price,'' Barak
acknowledged in an emotional plea for parliamentary support. But
failure to pursue peace with Damascus ``could cost us in blood,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vote of confidence in the prime minister's negotiating plans
passed with 47 votes in favor, 31 against, and 24 abstentions _ a
victory, but far from the strong majority Barak expected. Three
parties in Barak's governing coalition pointedly refused to back
him on Monday night, pointing to potential trouble when a promised
national referendum is held on any final peace pact.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is to meet with Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa of Syria
in Washington Wednesday and Thursday for the highest-level direct
discussions ever held between Syria and Israel. President Clinton
is expected to host the opening and closing sessions of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's appearance in Parliament on Monday was
widely considered his most important appearance since he took the
oath of office there five months ago. Calling this week's
negotiations ``an opportunity that cannot be squandered,'' he
argued that for the first time in its history, Israel has a chance
for a lasting peace with all of its immediate neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Israel's perspective, real peace with Syria and the
Palestinians, if it can be achieved, is the pinnacle of the Zionist
vision,'' he said, ignoring opposition hecklers. ``It is a
revolution. It is a new era in Israel's relations with the Arab
world, and the world at large.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak implicitly conceded that the Golan Heights would be handed
back to Syria in a peace accord, as thousands of residents from the
northern border zone demonstrated angrily outside the Parliament.
The precise boundaries of withdrawal ``will be determined in
negotiations in accordance with the depth of peace and the quality
of security arrangements,'' he said, echoing the formula used by
the late Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, Barak's mentor, in the last
attempt at a settlement with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Sharon, leader of the opposition Likud bloc, followed
Barak to the podium. He predicted that any accord featuring a Golan
withdrawal would go down to defeat in a referendum. He tauntingly
read another statement by Rabin, this one from 1992, that ``it is
inconceivable that even in peace we would descend from the Golan
Heights.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon charged that the government acquiesced to President Hafez
Assad's desire for ``American aid and modern American weapons'' and
President Clinton's hunger ``for a stunning achievement at any cost
before the end of his term in office.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak had praised Clinton in his remarks for his ``personal
involvement and devotion to the cause of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The planned national vote on the Syrian peace accord would be
the first referendum in Israel's history. Lawmakers have yet to
determine how the balloting would be organized, or who will draft
the question that will be put to voters. Israel's attorney-general
rejected an opposition proposal that Arab citizens _ a sixth of the
electorate _ be excluded from the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The vote following Monday night's debate _ a simple yea or nay
response to the peace initiative outlined by the prime minister on
Monday night _ provided the first real test of Barak's coalition
strategy. For Barak's Labor allies, the results appeared worrisome.
He assembled a multiparty government to provide the broadest
possible majority for peace with Syria and the Palestinians, but on
Monday night he was left with an uncomfortably slim plurality.
</P>
<P>
   The second largest faction in Barak's ruling coalition _ the
Sephardic-dominated Shas party _ unexpectedly abstained from the
vote and openly criticized his ``unclear'' negotiating strategy.
Most members of two smaller conservative parties in the government
_ the National Religious Party, backed by settlers in the West
Bank, and Yisrael B'aliya, representing Russian immigrants _ voted
against the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of all three coalition factions then joined Sharon and
other opposition figures outside Parliament in a rally with
protesters from the Golan Heights. ``We feel that the Golan is our
home, and you cannot throw people out of their homes,'' Guy Neuman,
a demonstrator from Qatrin, the largest Golan town, told an Israeli
television interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, anticipating opposition attacks, portrayed himself as a
patriot and career military man who had devoted his life to
Israel's defense. He reminded his audience that he had fought
against the Syrians in the Golan Heights during the 1967 war. ``I
am fully familiar with every valley and every rock in the Golan,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He was accompanied to the Parliament by Nadia Cohen, the widow
of Eli Cohen, an Israeli agent who has executed by Syria in 1965
for espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cohen, who is seeking the return from Damascus of her
husband's interred remains, publicly endorsed Barak's peace
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary interest is Israel's security,'' Barak said. ``The
agreement that we aspire to reach with our Syrian neighbors is one
that will also put an end to our conflict with Lebanon, and will
include diverse and effective systems to preserve security and
peace between our countries at all times. Such an agreement is not
beyond reach.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a meeting earlier on Monday, he told Cabinet colleagues that
while Israel had made no new commitments to Syria before this
week's talks, it ``would not erase'' any promises made in previous
negotiations during the administrations of Rabin and former Prime
Ministers Shimon Peres, and Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Syrians and Israelis have profoundly different recollections of
those past pledges, however.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrians have said the Rabin government was prepared to
withdraw to Israel's 1967 borders _ that is, to the eastern
shoreline of the Sea of Galilee. Israeli negotiators deny making
such a promise. And former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu claims
to have extracted Syrian permission for a permanent Israeli
presence atop Mount Heron, the Golan's high point _ an assertion
dismissed by diplomats in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negotiations with Syria will be difficult and paved with
crises,'' Barak told his Cabinet ministers, according to state
radio reports. ``I have no illusions about the nature of the Middle
East, and I have no doubt that only the overall strength of Israel
will ensure that agreements are honored.``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
