</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN OFFICIAL FORESEES LESS DEBT RELIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Japanese finance minister said Monday that he
expected the government to begin trying to gradually wean the
country's shaky economy away from its reliance on public borrowing,
a practice that has made Japan one of the biggest debtor nations.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa's comments, made in an
interview, suggested that the government was keenly aware that its
relentless borrowing was increasingly calling into question its
fiscal responsibility, a criticism that Japan had made of the
United States in years past.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa is one of the nation's most powerful and best-known
politicians, and his comments about government spending came
against the backdrop of mild economic improvement in Japan after
its worst recession since the end of World War II. The remarks may
be a sign that the government is beginning to have faith that the
economy's long-term prospects are improving.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, officials have been wary of publicly describing the
signs of life in the economy over the last year as a recovery. They
have also given little indication of when Japan would stop
borrowing heavily to inject money into the economy, much of it to
build public works projects ranging from extra tunnels and airport
runways to a new Tokyo subway. Such spending has been criticized as
extravagant, wasteful and unlikely to keep the economy going once
the money runs out.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa said he had discussed the matter of a gradual, measured
return to fiscal restraint with Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi on the
phone Monday morning, and that the prime minister seemed eager to
find a way to reassure the public that he was concerned about
Japan's increasing indebtedness and would work to correct it as the
economy regains momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Obuchi wondered how could he say it without giving up the
appearance of the fight against recession,'' Miyazawa said. ``There
is some anxiety about that.''
</P>
<P>
   How widespread the prime minister's concerns are among the
political elite here is unclear. Shizuka Kamei, chief policy
official of the governing Liberal Democratic Party and leader of
one of its largest factions, is an outspoken advocate of government
spending to prop up the economy. Moreover, few politicians are
likely to endorse any meaningful reduction in public spending
before parliament elections, which must be called by September.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Japanese deficit, already the highest in the
industrial world, is expected to reach 10.7 percent of the gross
domestic product by the end of this fiscal year, on March 31, 2000.
The United States, by contrast, is running a surplus estimated at
1.9 percent of its gross domestic product, according to the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, the
Paris-based group of rich nations.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal of fortunes between the two countries is
embarrassing for Japan, which criticized the United States several
times in the 1980s over its budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa's remarks came as executives here indicated more sense
of a recovery. A widely watched business survey by the Bank of
Japan, released Monday, showed that corporate sentiment improved in
the third quarter to its best level in two years. Still, the survey
_ known as the tankan _ contained some mixed signals, notably
evidence that large businesses were cutting capital spending even
more than they had predicted in the second quarter. Such cutbacks
reflect corporate caution about the strength of the recovery.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate report suggesting that the recovery remained
tenuous, the finance ministry said Japan's trade surplus fell for
the ninth consecutive month, largely because of the strength of the
yen. This has made Japan's products more expensive abroad, hurting
the profits of major exporters ranging from Sony and Honda to
Kikkoman, the world's largest producer of soy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament recently approved the government's ninth expensive
attempt to prod the recalcitrant economy into action _ a package of
public spending, loan guarantees, tax breaks and other measures
worth $171 billion if local government spending and lending is
included.
</P>
<P>
   That, coupled with the news that for the first time since World
War II, the government will have to finance more than half of its
budget through bond issues, has raised public sensitivity to the
country's increasing fiscal imbalance, which has swelled total
public debt to more than $5.4 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Magazines and talk shows here have been debating the value of
all of the spending.
</P>
<P>
   But Miyazawa said he thought that tax receipts would start to
rise, perhaps as soon as next year, after declining in five out of
the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax revenues in the next fiscal year may go up,'' he said,
``reflecting some improvement in the business situation as a result
of the restructuring that many companies have undertaken.''
</P>
<P>
   The ministry's tax bureau is substantially less optimistic,
though. The government's efforts to reform the tax system will in
the short term actually reduce what it takes in.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the economy has improved, corporations and
individuals show little sign of increased financial well-being.
Corporate Japan collectively lost money this year for the first
time since the government began gathering data on corporate
performance, according to data compiled by Mikuni &AMP; Co., the
country's only independent credit-rating agency.
</P>
<P>
   And Miyazawa himself, one of the few voices of fiscal restraint
in the top echelons of Japanese government, noted Monday that
consumer sentiment remained uneasy. ``In some ways,'' he said,
``the anxiety is more intense now than it was at the bottom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
