u f BRITAIN'SLARGESTCABLETVF     12-13 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 BRITAIN'S LARGEST CABLE TV FIRM BUYS SWITZERLAND'S TOP OPERATOR  
(ms) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ NTL Inc., Britain's largest cable concern, expanded its
foothold in continental Europe Monday with a $3.7 billion deal to
buy Cablecom Group, Switzerland's leading cable television
operator.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase gives NTL 1.28 million subscribers in Switzerland,
accounting for 53 percent of the cable market there, according to
the two companies. As part of the deal, NTL also will get
Cablecom's SwissOnline subsidiary, one of the most popular Web
sites in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   NTL, a 6-year-old telecommunications company based in New York
that operates mainly in Britain, has gone on a European shopping
spree within the past six months, betting that cable delivery of
entertainment, telephone and Internet services to homes will become
an increasingly important business in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by influential shareholders that include France Telecom
and Microsoft, NTL bought Cable and Wireless PLC's consumer cable,
telephone and Internet units in Britain, as well as France
Telecom's 1G networks and Ireland's largest cable company,
Cablelink.
</P>
<P>
   Those acquisitions, along with the purchase announced Monday,
have put NTL in direct competition with United Pan-Europe
Communications, or UPC, which is based in Amsterdam and has
followed a similar path.
</P>
<P>
   NTL's chief executive, Barclay Knapp, who is from Nebraska, has
pursued a strategy that that combines bundling telephone service,
cable television and Internet access into a single service, much as
AT&AMP;T has sought to do with its acquisition of Tele-Communications
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of our overall European strategy, it is particularly
important to have acquired a network at the very heart of Europe,''
Knapp said in a statement about the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the acquisition would benefit both NTL and
Cablecom because it solidified NTL's position in Europe while it
would make Cablecom more competitive at home.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Sinclair, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in London,
said the deal brought NTL ``one of the best run, competitively and
operationally strong cable companies in Europe at a low price.''
Sinclair, who rates NTL stock as a buy, said the acquisition gave
NTL ``an opportunity to consolidate its position, not just as the
leading UK player but as the most athletic competitor to UPC across
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   While most analysts praised the deal, investors sent NTL's share
price down $6.375, to $113.375, on the Nasdaq stock market.
Analysts said investors were nervous that NTL might have to issue
more shares to finance the acquisition of Cablecom. NTL already has
about $7.7 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   NTL said that Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Chase Manhattan
Bank would finance $2.3 billion of the purchase price and said it
was assessing a number of proposals to finance the balance of the
purchase price. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
