<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY STOCKS SEND NASDAQ INDEX TO ANOTHER RECORD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology stocks continued to power ahead Monday,
pulling the Nasdaq composite index to its seventh record this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in technology shares was led by Internet,
telecommunications and networking stocks. But other market gauges
slipped lower on the day. Trading activity, which usually begins to
tail off as the end of the year approaches, was heavy.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite climbed 37.93, or just more than 1 percent,
to 3,658.17. Since the start of the year, the index has risen by an
astonishing 66.8 percent. Many investors, eager to get in on the
ride, have been recent buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greed meter is running at full tilt,'' said Philip S. Dow,
a managing director in equity research at Dain Rauscher Wessels in
Minneapolis. ``Most of the calls I get are which technology stocks
I should buy. They have nothing to do with what is a good
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulled down by big drops in Hewlett-Packard and the drug makers
Merck and Johnson &AMP; Johnson, the Dow Jones industrial average fell
32.11 points, or 0.3 percent, to 11,192.59. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index also slipped, but by a more modest 1.82 points, or
0.1 percent, to 1,415.22. But the Russell 2000 index of small
company stocks moved higher, rising 3.67 points, or 0.8 percent, to
470.38.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was heavy. On the Big Board, 977.6 million shares
changed hands. Volume on the Nasdaq stock market was 1.55 billion
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm, part of both the S.&AMP; P. 500 and Nasdaq, had a big day.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which has risen fifteenfold this year, gained 26
1-16, to 417 9-16.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in Wal-Mart Stores were rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Monday the company said sales for the week ended Dec. 10 were at
the high end of management's expectations and that same-store sales
for the month are on track to meet the company's internal forecast
of a gain of 5 percent to 7 percent compared with results in the
month a year earlier. Its shares rose 4|, to 67~.
</P>
<P>
   Worries about earnings dragged down Oracle, the world's biggest
maker of database software, which is expected to post results for
the quarter ended Nov. 30 after the market closes Tuesday. Its
stock fell 4~, to 79 13-16.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley A. Nabi, vice chairman of DLJ Asset Management, said
disappointing fourth-quarter results could be particularly damaging
for highflying Internet stocks, and possibly for the overall stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see an ugly bear market on the horizon,'' he said.
``What worries me is that this small group of stocks may
contaminate the whole market. But that isn't going to happen in
what is left of 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks took a pounding, largely on worries that Washington
will renew its efforts to rein in the industry's ability to set
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Merck fell 3 3-16, to 68\. Johnson &AMP; Johnson lost 2 5-16, to 92
1-16. Pfizer was down one-half, to 33[. Bristol-Myers Squibb
dropped 1 9-16, to 66 11-16.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the technology sector, Foundry Networks jumped 26\,
to 304, after the maker of computer-networking gear said its board
had approved a 2-for-1 stock split.
</P>
<P>
   Dow at Dain Rauscher Wessels said market gauges could jump
Tuesday if a report on November consumer prices is friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get a benign reading on consumer prices, we could be off
to the races again,'' he said. ``You could see yields on 30-year
bonds fall down toward the 6 percent level by year-end if that
happens.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
