<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7941 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-LOUIMA-VOLPE-ART-2NDT     12-13 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-VOLPE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the gallery.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What I did not only hurt Abner Louima and his family, but
conjured up the worst fears in people,'' he said. ``This fear was
worse by me being a police officer.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Volpe repeated his earlier statements that another
former officer, Charles Schwarz, had been wrongly convicted by the
jury of helping to torture Louima by holding him down in the
bathroom of the 70th Precinct station house. Volpe repeated his
claim that the officer in the bathroom was Thomas Wiese. In the
past, Volpe had said that Wiese merely watched the attack with the
stick.
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor, Alan Vinegrad, maintained to the judge that
Volpe's statements exonerating Schwarz lacked credibility.
Vinegrad, chief assistant U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, previously
said that there had been more than sufficient evidence to support
the conviction of Schwarz, who faces up to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz plans to appeal his conviction, and his lawyer, Ronald
Fishetti, said Monday that the prosecution should give Volpe a
lie-detector test.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, Wiese and a third former officer, Thomas Bruder, face
trial next month on charges that they conspired to lie to
investigators to persuade them that Schwarz had not taken part in
the torture. Defense lawyers have indicated that they would call
Volpe as a witness for their clients, who deny the charge.
</P>
<P>
   In sentencing Volpe to 30 years, Nickerson reduced a finding by
the U.S. Probation Department that federal sentencing guidelines
mandated that Volpe be sentenced to life in prison without any
chance of parole.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he said, he was taking into account such factors as the
likelihood that the former police officer would have to serve much
of his sentence in ``some form of segregation'' for his own
protection from other inmates _ meaning even harsher punishment. He
lowered the finding to a guideline that called for a sentence of
between 30 years and life. He then imposed the 30 years, without
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a spokesman for the Federal Bureau of Prisons, Dan Dunne,
said that it was too early to say where Volpe would be incarcerated
or what security precautions, if any, would be taken to protect
him.
</P>
<P>
   After the sentencing, Kornberg said he would appeal. He had told
Nickerson that a 20-year-sentence would have been enough. Later he
noted to reporters outside the courthouse _ as Louima's supporters
loudly jeered him in the background _ that another police officer,
Francis Livoti, had been sentenced to seven-and-a-half years for
violating a man's civil rights by killing him with an illegal
chokehold. And Volpe's father, Robert Volpe, a retired city police
detective, said that 30 years was, in effect, as harsh as a life
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Louima said that he hoped the sentence would ``send a clear
message that no one is above the law,'' but the Rev. Al Sharpton,
the New York activist, said after leaving the courthouse that Volpe
``should have been given life.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Rodney, co-chairman of the Haitian-American Alliance,
called the sentence a ``slap on the wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   But Loretta Lynch, the interim U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, said
she accepted the 30-year term as the result of a ``very careful
balancing'' by Nickerson.
</P>
</TEXT>
