<P>
   Telling Time, From Stonehenge On &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Timekeeping, from sundials to wristwatches, is the subject of
the National Watch and Clock Museum in Columbia, Pa., in Lancaster
County, which recently reopened in an expanded building. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The building more than doubles the size of the museum's
exhibition space, to around 25,000 square feet. Money for the
construction came from the National Association of Watch and Clock
Collectors, whose headquarters is in the complex. With more than
13,000 watches, timepieces and clocks, the museum, which was
founded in 1983 and has been expanded several times since then,
traces the evolution from the colossal calendar of Stonehenge to
devices like sundials, hourglasses and oil-lamp and water clocks.
</P>
<P>
   Among the exhibits are a reproduction of a Greek antikythera
(circa 80 B.C.), one of the earliest known mechanically geared
timekeeping devices; six 200-year-old Japanese clocks that divide
the day into 12 hours, 6 hours of daylight and 6 hours of darkness
(the length of the ``hour'' can be adjusted by moving the tile
indicators); and an 11-foot-tall, 8-foot-wide clock with two barrel
organs and 48 animatronic figures that perform on the hour
(soldiers marching through a square, angels, a jester and
skeletons, among others).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hands-on activities and video kiosks supplement the exhibits,
and the museum complex also contains an 80-seat theater that shows
a 10-minute introductory video, as well as a library and research
center. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Watch and Clock Museum, 514 Poplar Street, is open
Tuesday through Sunday. Admission is $6, $5 ages 60 and up, $4 ages
6 to 12. Information: (717) 684-8261. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mexico Backs Down On Car Deposits &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials vowed that they would never back down on their
plan to require a deposit of up to $800 from motorists driving
foreign-registered vehicles into Mexico. But only two days after
the plan went into effect on Dec. 1, they did. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo suspended the plan until further
notice, responding to an uproar raised by Mexicans in the United
States, which included a boycott of Mexican products like Sauza
Tequila and Corona beer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the time being Mexican customs will observe the old
procedure. Travelers who want to drive a vehicle into Mexico past
the 15-mile border zone have two choices. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anybody with a credit card can pay a $16.50 fee for a six-month
multiple-entry permit and must take the car back out of Mexico
before the end of the six-month period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those without credit cards have to buy bonds in dollars from one
of the private companies at each border post. The amount of the
bond depends on the year and model of the vehicle and is determined
by consulting the Blue Book, a listing in the United States of the
value of used cars.
</P>
<P>
   The bond amount varies from $100 to about $600. The companies,
however, charge a commission of as much as half the value of the
bond, which is not returned to the traveler. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cost is much lower for travelers with credit cards,
officials said, because the identification information on the card
is considered adequate to initiate a search for the driver if the
car does not leave Mexico. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The deposit plan sought to address the proliferation of illegal
foreign-made cars in Mexico. Officials said they would revisit the
issue in the first months of next year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mexicans traveling by land into their country are
getting another break from their government. From Dec. 1 to Jan. 10
only, they can bring in up to $300 of goods duty free, instead of
up to $50 worth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julia Preston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To Visit Site on Jordan Call First, Be Cautious &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can now visit the isolated bend of the Jordan River where
many believe that Jesus was baptized by John the Baptist. But there
are a few caveats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First, the area is heavily mined, so visitors must stay on the
paths. You also need to clear your visit with the Israeli army one
week ahead. And if immersion is your goal, the waist-deep waters of
the famous 20-foot-wide stream are less than pristine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Berman, the manager of a company that is developing the
site as a millennial tourist attraction, says the easiest way to
arrange a visit is to call him at (972-51) 511-269 or (972-2)
940-0598 or send a fax to (972-2) 940-0591.
</P>
<P>
   For tour groups he requires the name and passport number of the
leader, the name of the bus company, and the size of the group.
With about seven days' notice, Berman says, he can guarantee
access. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can also get permission from the Israel Defense Forces by
calling (972-2) 530-5511 and providing a fax number where they can
send you a form requesting a visit. Requests are approved once a
week, on Thursday. Approvals, which are usually automatic, will be
faxed back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is a heavily fortified frontier zone with Jordan, so the
experience may seem less than biblical. To get to the baptismal
site, you pass through a gate in an electrified border fence.
Soldiers on both sides of the river, Israelis and Jordanians, are
dispatched to stand guard over visitors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Berman suggests that the time to visit the site is Sunday to
Thursday, 8 a.m. till dusk. There is no admission fee and, so far,
no tourist facilities except for restrooms and a drinking
fountain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, good news from a rival putative baptismal site a few
miles upriver on the Jordanian side: mine clearing there is well
advanced, Jordanian officials report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   William A. Orme Jr. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paris: Toy-filled Department Store Windows &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a tribute to the last Christmas of the 20th century, two big
Parisian department stores a block apart along the Boulevard
Haussmann on the Right Bank are abandoning their haute couture
displays this month for toy-filled windows. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The French puppeteer Jean-Claude Dehix was commissioned by
Galeries Lafayette, at No. 40, and Printemps, at No. 64, to create
dozens of scenes, including, in one Printemps window, a space
capsule filled with teddy bears celebrating the New Year with
champagne and dehydrated caviar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Galeries Lafayette chose the theme Fairies of the World, with
155 puppets and dolls in 25 window displays. Motors animate the
puppets. A white Christmas tree 150 feet high stands under the
Galeries' dome. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Printemps is looking to the future, with Barbies, traditional
French Corolle dolls and German Sigikids starring in scenes ranging
from a messy New Year's Eve party for animatronic dolls and mice to
a flight of a hundred Barbie dolls dressed as queens and
princesses. The windows are in operation from 8 a.m. to 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   In front of all the windows, steps lead to platforms to give
children a better view. The boulevard is most alluring at night,
illuminated by thousands of tiny lights strung in the trees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crowds at the store windows are thinnest early in the morning.
Across the street from the last Printemps window, at 37, rue
Tronchet, is a tearoom called Paul, where tea and cakes make a
fitting conclusion to a holiday stroll. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sylvie Rais
</P>
</TEXT>
