<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-SPYING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAPONS SCIENTIST PLEADS `NOT GUILTY' TO CHARGE OF MISHANDLING
DATA
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for rewriting throughout; story is now complete in 1 take) 
 (sw) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ A former U.S. weapons scientist pleaded not
guilty on Monday to the illegal computer downloading of a vast
trove of nuclear arms data, but a federal magistrate ordered him
jailed pending trial, declaring that the acts he is accused of
represent ``a clear and present danger to the security of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The scientist, Wen Ho Lee, was ordered held behind bars after
all-day proceedings here, where he entered the courtroom smiling
broadly at relatives and dozens of supporters and left to live in a
cell while awaiting a trial that may be months away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plead not guilty,'' Lee responded in a loud, clear voice
after Magistrate Don Sven asked what he had to say about the
59-count indictment returned against him on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations against Lee led to widespread fears of extensive
nuclear spying by the Chinese, though the indictment does not
accuse Lee of spying. He was fired in March from his job at the Los
Alamos weapons laboratory after Energy Secretary Bill Richardson
began an investigation into the accusations spying by Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's hearing produced testimony that Lee's unauthorized
downloading of highly classified data in 1993 or 1994 roughly
coincided with his notice from the Department of Energy that he
might lose his job at the laboratory because of cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   There was also testimony that seven computer tapes containing a
virtual blueprint for much of the country's nuclear arsenal had
been created by Lee, then had vanished _ not turning up despite an
investigation involving about 1,000 witnesses, a review of a
million documents and inquiries by the FBI in Europe and in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, Lee's lawyer, Mark Holscher, said his
client had destroyed the tapes. But he refused to tell questioners
outside the courtroom where or how they had been destroyed, or
whether there was any proof that they had been.
</P>
<P>
   FBI investigators have concluded after a search of Los Alamos
computers that Lee copied information relating to the design,
construction and testing of the most advanced nuclear weapons in
the American arsenal _ data that Lee's former boss said on Monday
was of extraordinary importance.
</P>
<P>
   The former boss, Stephen Younger, said that the material Lee was
accused of compromising could, in the wrong hands, make the United
States missile systems vulnerable to hostile nations, perhaps even
change the global balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very first day I entered the nuclear weapons program it
was made crystal clear to me how important this information was to
national security,'' said Younger, the associate laboratory
director for nuclear weapons. ``We are more aware of anyone else of
the destructive capability of these weapons. It is a sacred trust
to me that we have taken on for the country, and we take that very
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   While he is not accused of espionage, or passing the classified
data to another country, Lee has not explained why he downloaded
the data or what he did with it. A few of the computer tapes he
used have been recovered, but most are unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI special agent, Robert Messemer, testified that the volume
of material downloaded by Dr. Lee would made a stack of paper 134
feet high if printed.
</P>
<P>
   But Holscher pointed out that around that time Lee was also
downloading unclassified data that would have made a stack of paper
over 100 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   And Messemer further acknowledged that an investigation had
developed no evidence that Lee was trying to aid another country.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's supporters have asserted that he is being persecuted
because he is of Chinese descent (he was born in Taiwan). They say
that other, higher-ranking government figures have been guilty of
greater security lapses linked to carelessness, not spying.
</P>
<P>
   Lee could face life in prison if convicted of all charges.
</P>
<P>
   Messemer said that Lee had approached a laboratory employee in a
nonsecured trailer beyond a perimeter fence and asked to use the
employee's computer to download data off a main-frame Los Alamos
laboratory computer. And when Lee was told earlier this year that
he had failed a polygraph test, he began ``massive'' deletions of
classified files he had downloaded, the agent said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking as a counterintelligence person, Dr. Lee's actions
are secretive,'' Messemer said. ``They appear to be clandestine and
nefarious.''
</P>
<P>
   But Holscher emphasized repeatedly in his cross-examination that
Lee had a right to gain access to and use the information that he
copied _ even though there has been no explanation for the
downloading.
</P>
</TEXT>
