<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7957 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-YANKEE-STADIUM-ART-2T     12-13 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKEE-STADIUM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEINBRENNER KEEPS HIS NARROWING OPTIONS OPEN ON A NEW STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last five years, George Steinbrenner has repeatedly
promised he will soon announce where he wants the Yankees to play
when the lease at Yankee Stadium runs out in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he has said he will disclose his choice by opening
day, and sometimes he has said an announcement will come at
season's end. In 1997, he said he would decide whether to stay in
the Bronx or to move to Manhattan or New Jersey after that year's
mayoral election. The following year, he said a decision would come
after the race for governor.
</P>
<P>
   But as Steinbrenner weighs his options, much of the rest of New
York has come to the conclusion that he is really down to only two:
staying in the Bronx in a renovated Yankee Stadium or in a new
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rationale for leaving the Bronx has been eliminated,''
said Mitchell Moss, director of the Taub Urban Research Center at
New York University. ``Now the question is, how do you stay in the
Bronx and keep George happy?''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of building a new ballpark for the team on
Manhattan's West Side has all but evaporated, as has the chance, at
least for now, of shifting the team to New Jersey, many
politicians, urban scholars and New York City and state officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, 69, has spent much of the decade publicly
bemoaning what he says are the high rate of crime in the Bronx,
inadequate parking and nightmarish traffic around Yankee Stadium,
and the failure of Yankee fans to turn out in sufficient numbers
for home games.
</P>
<P>
   But more than 3.2 million people attended games at Yankee
Stadium last season, a record for the team that has won more world
championships than any other. And Gov. George Pataki, who controls
the site on the West Side that has long been considered a potential
future home for the Yankees, has said unequivocally that he wants
the team to remain in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Gargano, chairman of the Empire State Development Corp.,
the state's economic development arm, said the season attendance
figures may prove decisive for Steinbrenner. ``George saw the fans
come out in large numbers, and all indications are that he will
stay in the Bronx,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Tese offered his long-term perspective, predicting that
the Yankees will move to Macombs Dam Park, the city park beside
Yankee Stadium, where a new ballpark might rise. Tese was chairman
of the state development corporation in 1993 when Mario Cuomo, then
the governor, first suggested the West Side to Steinbrenner. ``He's
tried to get into Manhattan for years,'' Tese said, ``but that's
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even Steinbrenner's most ardent ally _ Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani _ talks any longer about what had once been a pet idea:
building a $1 billion enclosed stadium for the Yankees above a
railroad yard on the West Side, between 30th and 33rd Streets and
10th and 12th Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   Without publicly acknowledging that the Manhattan alternative
was dead, the mayor demonstrated his own sense of how far the
political pendulum had swung when he proposed last January to use
the site for a new football stadium to lure the Jets back from New
Jersey. He never mentioned any baseball use of the site when he
made the surprise football proposal in his annual State of the City
address.
</P>
<P>
   Any lingering doubts about the mayor's intentions were erased
during the early morning of Oct. 28, when he stood with
Steinbrenner in the Yankees' clubhouse at the Stadium, basking in
the glow of their 25th World Series victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place becomes even more hallowed ground,'' said the
mayor, a lifelong Yankee fan. ``You think about all the baseball
history made in this place. It means this location becomes even
more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether that meant the Yankees would stay put, Giuliani
said, ``I think they will.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Steinbrenner's spokesman had said he would
decide the Yankees' future once the team's merger with the Nets was
completed. That occurred two weeks ago. Steinbrenner, the Yankees'
principal owner, declined requests for an interview, but through
the spokesman he insisted that all options remained open.
</P>
<P>
   The new stadium saga has spanned 12 years, time enough for
Steinbrenner to hire seven managers, return from a banishment from
baseball, nearly sell 70 percent of the team to Cablevision, beg
the forgiveness of Yogi Berra for firing him as his manager in
1985, play postgame traffic cop to investigate jam-ups on the Major
Deegan Expressway, resuscitate Darryl Strawberry's career and win
three World Series in four years.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The stadium issue turned into a political minefield last year
when the City Council speaker, Peter F. Vallone, who was running
for governor, tried to place a referendum on the November ballot
that would have kept the city from spending money for a new stadium
anywhere but in the Bronx. Aware that polls showed Vallone's
referendum would be approved overwhelmingly, the mayor blocked
Vallone by placing minor revisions to the City Charter on the
ballot, knocking off the stadium referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner stepped into the fray. ``If you single me out,''
Steinbrenner warned Vallone, ``you sure as hell are going to lose
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Many elected officials say now that Steinbrenner and the mayor
failed to build broad public support for the West Side plan. ``I
told Steinbrenner that the West Side had no chance if it's
discussed in a political context,'' said Cuomo, who bemoans the
idea's fate. ``We should have spent a year developing answers to
every legitimate question, then go to the public and discuss it
issue by issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallone is obviously delighted with the outcome. ``The
cockamamie idea to go to Manhattan is dead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It is by no means clear when or how the Yankees' long-range
plans will be resolved. Steinbrenner rarely talks in public about
his intentions, and even the mayor is not saying much these days.
Giuliani's spokeswoman declined several requests to answer
questions about the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Rubenstein, Steinbrenner's spokesman, insists that all
options are still being weighed and says Steinbrenner is also
awaiting a $3 million city-financed study on the Bronx and
Manhattan sites. ``We're still looking at the West Side,''
Rubenstein said. ``It has many pluses.''  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many city and state officials suspect that Steinbrenner intends
to wait everyone out to obtain the best possible deal for his team.
But the risk for Steinbrenner is that he might miss his moment;
some current and former government officials think he already has.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Steinbrenner is more focused on negotiating a new
cable television deal for the Yankees, which would succeed a $486
million contract with the MSG Network that spans 12 years and
expires after next season, according to a business associate.
``He's been saying, `This TV thing has to get done,''' the
associate said.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner could further delay choosing his stadium site _ and
perhaps try to build support for the West Side _ by exercising the
first of two five-year options to extend his current Yankee Stadium
lease, from 2003 to 2007.
</P>
<P>
   But time may not be on Steinbrenner's side. He might have only
one more year to conclude a long-term deal with Giuliani, a
cheerleader who often wears the familiar blue Yankee cap and
jacket. Giuliani is expected to run for the U.S. Senate, and if
victorious he would leave as mayor in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor's decision to seek higher office means the stadium
is no longer on the front burner,'' said Moss of NYU. ``His term is
expiring before the Yankees' lease. The options have been taken
from the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Completing an expensive deal during a Senate race to keep the
Yankees in the Bronx could carry political risks for Giuliani,
political analysts said. But there might be some political
advantage, too, because of the large Hispanic population in the
Bronx, said Norman Adler, a political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a third risk to Steinbrenner's biding his time: The
city's economy cannot stay robust forever, and a recession could
turn munificent public financing for a stadium into an unaffordable
luxury.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner's delays have slowed the Mets' plans to build a new
ballpark next to Shea Stadium. The team unveiled a design for a
$500 million stadium in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets' deal has not advanced very far. ``Nothing has
prevented Rudy from making a deal with the Mets first,'' said City
Councilman Walter McCaffrey, a Queens Democrat. ``It might have
given the city leverage with George Steinbrenner.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Steinbrenner's friends are unsure why he has not decided.
Some speculate that he has been hesitating because he does not want
to be remembered as the traitor who took the Yankees out of the
Bronx; others assume that by not deciding, he somehow keeps his
options open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once, I thought he knew what he wanted,'' said a friend. ``Now
I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
