<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USWEB-USWEB </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 USWeb Ready to Merge With Chicago Firm  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
San Francisco's USWeb/CKS, a Web consulting company, will merge
with Chicago's Whittman-Hart, a business-to-business technology
specialist, in a stock swap that creates an $11.7 billion
full-service Internet firm.
<P>
   Shares of Whittman-Hart plunged $24.75 to close at $54.50 on the
announcement, while shares of USWeb/CKS sank $7.06 to $43.81 amid
concerns that USWeb/CKS already faces the challenge of absorbing
two separate, earlier acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the integration is going to be a challenge,'' said
William Loomis, an analyst with Legg Mason Wood Walker. ``There are
still a lot of unanswered questions. But the concept of a large,
full-service company in this fast-growing market is a very good
one.''
</P>
<P>
   The new company, which has not yet been named, will be the
largest consulting firm in the United States to focus exclusively
on the Internet. The goal is to combine Whittman-Hart's
business-to-business expertise with USWeb/CKS' consumer focus to
handle a broad range of client needs.
</P>
<P>
   USWeb/CKS specializes in Web site development and management of
consumer e-commerce transactions. Its clients include
Williams-Sonoma Inc. and FAO Schwartz. The company merged with CKS,
a technology-oriented advertising agency, a year ago to bolster its
creative services. It moved from Santa Clara to San Francisco's
Multimedia Gulch this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Whittman-Hart is known for developing and managing back-end
operations, including inventory control and supply ordering, for
midsize companies, such as American General Finance and Diners
Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a highly complementary fit,'' said Robert Shaw, the
chief executive and chairman of USWeb/ CKS, who will be chairman of
the new company. ``We can focus our efforts on solving business
problems from the consumer through the supply chain and back
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The merged entity will have more than 8,000 employees and more
than 70 offices in 13 countries. It's headquarters will be in
Chicago, but it will maintain USWeb/CKS's 1,000-member staff in San
Francisco, as well as its Santa Clara and Cupertino offices.
Combined revenues in the third quarter totaled $297 million.
</P>
<P>
   USWeb/CKS shareholders will receive 0.865 shares of
Whittman-Hart for each USWeb/CKS share. That will leave USWeb/CKS
stockholders with 57 percent of the company and Whitman-Hart
investors with 43 percent. The deal is expected to become final in
the spring, pending shareholder and regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bernard, Whittman-Hart's president and chief executive, will
be CEO of the combined business. Whittman-Hart Chief Financial
Officer Bert Young will be CFO, and USWeb/CKS Chief Operating
Officer Robert Clarkson will be COO.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-member board will be composed of four directors from
each company, plus an additional director who has not yet been
selected.
</P>
<P>
   Some securities analysts downgraded their ratings on USWeb/CKS
and Whittman-Hart yesterday, noting that the San Francisco company
is still absorbing CKS and a smaller business-to-business firm,
Mitchell Madison, which it acquired in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, they've got a huge merger with another company,'' said
Drake Johnson, an analyst with Davenport &AMP; Co. who lowered his
rating on USWeb/CKS to ``hold'' from ``accumulate.'' ``That just
complicates the whole process.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Johnson said he expects his concerns to be short term.
``I think the combined entity could be a pretty powerful player in
the Net space going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the expense of USWeb/CKS's earlier acquisitions,
Johnson projected a net loss for USWeb/CKS this year of $203.3
million on &UR;  &LR; revenues of $507.5 million even before yesterday's
announcement. Johnson did not expect USWeb/CKS to become profitable
until the fourth quarter of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Whittman-Hart is profitable. Hambrecht &AMP; Quist analyst Dirk
Godsey is projecting a 1999 net income of $35 million on revenues
of $470 million.
</P>
<P>
   Godsey, who maintains buy ratings on both stocks, called
acquisition-powered growth ``a perfectly good strategy'' that has
been just as successful among Internet professional services
companies as organic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Pending regulatory and shareholder approval, the merger is
expected to be complete in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
