 _ SF CHRON  
 Market Developing Quickly for Digital Photo Printing  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The online photo finishing industry has had a big month.
<P>
   Yesterday, Berkeley's Ofoto launched an e-commerce site,
www.ofoto.com, where digital camera owners can upload images and
arrange to have prints made and sent to friends and family's
doorsteps. It is at least the third company in the Bay Area to
offer such services. And there are sure to be more.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Mountain View's View-based &LR;   &LR; PhotoAccess.com
launched a similar site. And along with 35-employee Ofoto, Redwood
Shores' Shutterfly.com yesterday unveiled its Web finishing
service.
</P>
<P>
   All three companies are trying to cash in on the surging number
of digital cameras on the market and what they hope is the
accompanying desire to make high-quality prints. Digital cameras,
which have been dropping dramatically in price over the past
several months, are expected to be a hot seller this holiday season
and beyond. Some of the cameras cost under $200; others run into
the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation is that this is going to be a big Christmas
for digital cameras, so (Web finishers) have to start getting in
front of the public and the influencers and the resellers now,''
said Alexis Gerard, president of Future Image Inc., a San Mateo
firm that tracks the digital photo market.
</P>
<P>
   While all three Web photo finishers share one strategy _ they
each eschew advertising-based revenue _ each says it outshines the
competition with key differences. Shutterfly emphasizes that it
develops the images itself; PhotoAccess out-sources outsources &LR; 
 &LR; its developing to an ``established'' East Coast processor. And
Ofoto is offering free finishing to its first million customers.
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is whether consumers embrace the virtual
Fotomat idea, stick to the brick-and-morter store or wait until
printer technology advances far enough to produce 35mm-quality
prints at home.
</P>
<P>
   James Joaquin, Ofoto president and CEO, is betting that just
about all photography will shift online.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sharing nature of photography, the fact that it's about
friends and family, is such a natural tie-in with the Web, where
you can purchase and send prints to people,'' he said. ''I think
that the convenience benefit will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
