 _ SF CHRON  
 Andersen Joins Venture Capital Stampede  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Joining the e-commerce investment stampede, management consulting
heavyweight Andersen Consulting said yesterday that it is creating
a venture capital division that plans to invest up to $1 billion in
Internet startups over the next five years.
<P>
   Half the money will come from the consulting firm's profits, the
other $500 million from unidentified VC firms and investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen is headquartered in Chicago but its VC operation will
be based in Palo Alto and headed by Jackson Wilson, previously
managing partner for Andersen's global markets.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen Consulting already has more than 140 venture
investments and alliances with dot-com companies. During Over &LR;   &LR; the
past three years, it has invested $40 million in with &LR;   &LR; several of
them, with impressive results.
</P>
<P>
   Its $3 million investment in Siebel Systems is worth ``north of
$500 million,'' according to Wilson. Andersen also has stakes in
Covation, a joint venture with Bank of America to provide
e-commerce solutions to the health care industry; ChemConnect, the
Internet's largest global chemicals and plastics exchange; and Blue
Martini, which provides merchandising software for online
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided it was time to stop messing around as if this were
a hobby and get really serious,'' said Wilson. Andersen Consulting
Ventures will turn some of its own consultants into full-time
venture capitalists and also hire outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the office in Palo Alto, Wilson plans to open
branches in New York or Boston, Atlanta or Austin, one in Europe
and one in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, Andersen Consulting Ventures expects to have 40
to 50 people investing in and helping manage high-tech ventures.
Andersen hopes to back some of its 62,000 employees who have have
entrepreneurial visions of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson conceded that there are potential conflicts of interest
if its consulting arm is giving advice to a client that competes
with a company Andersen's VC division is backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like other venture capital firms, we don't intend to invest in
companies which compete with each other or our large global 1,000
clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said the company already has firewalls to prevent
conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen Consulting is part of Anderson Worldwide, which also
owns the Andersen accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen Consulting's commitment is impressive but it is hardly
the first consultant or company to barge into VC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is getting into the fray,'' said Jesse Reyes,
director of Venture Economics, a Newark, N.J., research unit of
Securities Data Co. There are easily 200 to 300 companies that do
venture investing, in part to gain access to new technologies as
well as make investment gains. ``I would say Andersen's interest is
more speculative than strategic,'' said Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   This year, venture capital firms have invested close to $40
billion in Internet and other companies. Wealthy individual and
corporate investors have invested billions more. In the third
quarter, Venture Economics reports that corporate investors poured
$724.5 million into 181 companies, led by Intel Corp.'s $123
million investment in 18 private companies.
</P>
<P>
   Several huge new  &LR; VC funds are popping up each week. In the past
two weeks alone, Accel Partners of Palo Alto said it is raising
$600 million for two new funds, including $120 million from a few
dozen top executives and corporations. Draper Fisher Jurvetson of
Redwood City said it is teaming up with a new investment firm
called meVC.com to create a $500 million venture capital fund for
the masses. Individual contributions could be as little as $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   NeoCarta Ventures of San Francisco and Cambridge, Mass.,
announced a new $275 million fund. And two ex-49ers have started
the first Champions Ventures $40 million fund for professional
athletes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
