<SLUG> BC-VOLPE-VOLPE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Prudential Snaps Up Volpe Brown  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Volpe Brown Whelan, a San Francisco investment bank specializing in
public stock offerings for young computer and Internet companies,
announced its sale yesterday to Prudential Securities for an
undisclosed price.
<P>
   The cash purchase, which took effect yesterday, makes privately
held Volpe Brown the latest in a long line of local securities
firms that have sold out amid a white-hot market for
technology-oriented investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimated that Prudential paid $250 million to $300
million for the firm, based on Volpe Brown's projected 1999 revenue
of roughly $115 million and the fact that most securities firms are
being sold for about two times their revenues. That estimated price
is more than twice what the firm was worth two years ago, when
Credit Suisse First Boston bought a 25 percent stake for a reported
$25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential, owned by the giant insurance company of the same
name, is the nation's fifth-largest securities firm, with 6,700
brokers and more than 1.2 million retail account holders. But its
investment banking division is an also-ran, a position it hopes to
change by snapping up Volpe Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe Brown officials said they sold the firm to get access to
Prudential's broad network of brokers and investors.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, as legal barriers between the banking and securities
industries tumbled, San Francisco's big three investment banks,
Montgomery Securities, Robertson Stephens and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist,
all sold out to giant commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   With the latest sale, the only remaining independent investment
banks in San Francisco are the year-old Thomas Weisel Partners,
founded by the former chief executive of Montgomery Securities;
Putnam, Lovell, de Guardiola &AMP; Thornton, which provides research on
and merger advice to securities and money management firms; and a
couple of upstart firms that sell stock principally on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe Brown has led or co-managed 45 public stock offerings this
year, ranking it 26th nationally among investment banks in the
dollar value of its stock offerings, according to CommScan, a Wall
Street data firm. Prudential ranked 20th, with 61 stock offerings
led or co-managed.
</P>
<P>
   The firm is now called Prudential Volpe Technology Group,
combining Volpe Brown's investment banking and research staff with
Prudential's small technology investment banking unit. Senior Volpe
Brown partners, including chief executive Thomas Volpe, will
continue to run the unit, and the new owner will be ``very light
handed'' in overseeing the operation, Prudential chief executive
Wick Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe Brown is cutting an unspecified but ``relatively small''
number of jobs as a result of the takeover, founder and chief
executive Thomas Volpe said. The firm employs about 220 people in
San Francisco, Boston and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   When securities firms are bought, the big danger is losing star
analysts and investment bankers. Prudential is offering bonuses to
staff members who stay with the new firm, officials said, but
defections are still possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fair amount of human capital risk in these deals,''
said Putnam, Lovell analyst Dean Eberling.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe Brown sought a buyer because boutique investment banks are
having a tough time competing against large rivals, Volpe said.
Large firms have big sales staffs that can easily distribute stock
from public offerings to a broad mix of institutional and retail
investors, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``For an independent firm, it gets increasingly difficult,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe and Simmons said they are trying to win more lead-manager
assignments in stock offerings for the new unit. Lead managers,
which coordinate offerings, collect bigger fees than co-managers,
which have fewer responsibilities. So far this year, Volpe Brown
has led only three relatively small offerings, while Prudential has
led 15 offerings, according to CommScan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
