<SLUG> BC-CITRON-CITRON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Ad Agencies Scuttle Planned Union  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Citron Haligman Bedecarre, the largest independent advertising
agency in San Francisco, has called off its planned union with New
York's Euro RSCG Worldwide.
<P>
   The two companies said in February that Euro RSCG, owned by the
conglomerate Havas Advertising of Paris, would buy a majority stake
in CHB.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past 10 months, CHB has shifted its strategy,
deciding to focus on dot-com clients that want a fast-moving,
locally based agency and don't need Euro RSCG's vast international
resources, said Tom Bedecarre, CHB's chairman, in an interview
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about our direction versus their direction,'' said
Bedecarre. ``There's a shift that we think we can take advantage of
by remaining independent.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, Bedecarre described an acquisition as
``inevitable,'' saying his agency needed international capabilities
in order to grow. CHB had held discussions with several suitors
over the years and was eager to be acquired, according to sources.
But the dot-com gold rush changed CHB's priorities.
</P>
<P>
   CHB's billings will hit $200 million this year, about double the
1997 and 1998 numbers, said Bedecarre. Twenty staffers have been
added since February, bringing the agency's total to 85. All of the
growth is attributable to technology clients, which include
Women.com and Goodhome.com, he said.
</P>
<P>
   CHB and Euro RSCG tried for several months to find an
alternative partnership structure, but were unable to come to an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A Euro RSCG executive who declined to be named confirmed
Bedecarre's version of events, saying the split was mutual. ``We've
had discussions over the past several months and finally concluded
that we have too many differences,'' the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the acquisition were never disclosed. The deal was
officially terminated last week and Euro RSCG was expected to make
an announcement soon. Neither party will pay a break-up fee or
other penalty, executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Euro RSCG, meanwhile, is no longer trying to buy a San Francisco
agency that specializes in traditional consumer products, as CHB
did until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company will devote more attention to a San
Francisco offshoot, the recently renamed Aka Euro RSCG. (cq) &LR;   &LR; That
agency, formerly known as Cohn &AMP; Wells, has historically
specialized in direct marketing. ``They're evolving and we're
focusing on them,'' the Euro RSCG source said.
</P>
<P>
   Euro RSCG operates 176 offices in 72 countries. Havas, its
parent, is the fifth-largest advertising company in the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
