<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;     CD Rates Available Online 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Can you recommend an Internet Web site where I can find the best
available yields from bank certificates of deposit?
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Try www.bankrate.com, maintained by Bank Rate Monitor and
Intelligent Life Corp., a publishing company based in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   After you get on the site, you will find a long menu along the
left side of your computer screen. Click on the entry for ``Savings
_ CDs.'' Then, click again to find the best yields nationwide on
CDs with investment periods ranging from one month to five years.
You can scan the 25 best rates for each time period.
</P>
<P>
   The site provides not only the yields but also the minimum
required deposits and how often the interest is compounded.
</P>
<P>
   You can search for the best rates state by state _ for example,
if you only want to do business with banks located in California.
There also are subentries that compare rates entirely within the
Bay Area or any other region that interests you.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this same information appears Mondays on the Data Bank
page of The Chronicle's Business section.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Checking It Out Overseas &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was following the stock of Nielsen Media Research and
suddenly it dropped out of sight. I'm an online investor and don't
know where else to turn for information about this company. Can you
help me?
</P>
<P>
   A: You must not have been following it very closely.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the Dutch publisher VNU made a well-publicized
announcement that it would buy Nielsen _ the New York company
famous for TV ratings _ for close to $3 billion in cash. Nielsen's
stock then stopped trading after the deal was consummated in
October.
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in VNU, you can buy or sell it over the
counter as an American Depositary Receipt _ the form in which
overseas companies are traded on U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   VNU's principal business is the publication of regional
newspapers and mass-circulation magazines. The newly acquired
Nielsen accounts for roughly 10 percent to 15 percent of the
company's $3 billion-plus revenues.
</P>
<P>
   I'd also like to respond to your throwaway line about being an
online investor _ and, therefore, supposedly helpless.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason why you can't do your own investment
research, online or offline. There are countless
securities-research sites online _ such as Yahoo (www.yahoo.com)
and Motley Fool (www.fool.com) _ that will provide you with a
boundless supply of financial news, opinions and data. Also, there
are likely to be abundant investment resources at any large public
library in your area.
</P>
<P>
   There may even be a research section on your broker's Web site.
There certainly is if you deal with one of the more prominent
online brokers, such as Schwab, Fidelity or E-Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Check it out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; When an IRA Is Excluded &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I worked abroad and qualified for the foreign income
exclusion on my tax form. I plan to report a $65,000 salary on
Internal Revenue Service Form 1040 but will exclude all $65,000 _
because it is foreign income _ on Form 2555, leaving a total income
of zero. Am I eligible to make a $2,000 contribution to a Roth IRA?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. You cannot make a contribution of any size to a Roth, nor
can you contribute to any other type of IRA.
</P>
<P>
   According to IRS spokesman Jesse Weller, tax law stipulates that
you may only contribute to an IRA if you have wages or other
personal-service income that cannot be excluded from U.S. taxes.
You had wages, but because they were earned abroad, they are not
taxable here.
</P>
<P>
   If you had U.S.-taxable income from wages and personal services,
you could have made IRA contributions up to the total amount of
that income or $2,000, whichever was less.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
