<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-OUTLOOK </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Breakthrough Year Predicted for Small-Cap Stocks  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Don't hold your breath, but 2000 could be the year when the stocks
of smaller and midsize companies once again outperform the giants.
<P>
   Many market experts have been wrongly predicting such a turn of
events for years. It hasn't happened since 1993, but it has to
happen again sometime _ doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   A few, brave market watchers still think so.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle surveyed nine experts about the stock market
outlook for 2000. A frequent _ though not unanimous _ refrain was
that economic conditions seem ripe for a superior performance by
the market's perennial also-rans.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery of economies around the globe _ especially in Asia
_ should provide grand, new opportunities for lesser U.S. companies
that have been overshadowed by the big-name multinationals. Or so
the reasoning goes.
</P>
<P>
   The experts surveyed by The Chronicle _ market strategists,
financial advisers, money managers, economists, analysts and
publishers _ also focused intently on the prospects for technology
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Even after this year's humongous 60-plus percent gain in the
tech-heavy Nasdaq composite index, scarcely anyone dares suggest
that tech won't lead the overall market again in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks are a different matter. Nearly all the experts
are bothered by what they call the Internet ``bubble'' _ the
multibillion-dollar market values assigned to Internet-related
companies with scant revenues and, in most cases, no earnings.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the survey predicted that the bubble will grow much
bigger in the coming year. Some expect it to burst.
</P>
<P>
   Readers should bear in mind that predicting the stock market is
a perilous exercise at best, and that nothing that follows should
necessarily be accepted as gospel.
</P>
<P>
   When The Chronicle surveyed a panel of experts a year ago, most
of them thought the market would perform weakly during 1999.
</P>
<P>
   They cited such concerns as the global financial crisis, with
its dire threat of deflation (remember?), and the uncertainty over
President Clinton's political fate (ha!). Several thought the
market would go into a sinking spell in November and December as
Y2K and its computer problem loomed.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding all that timidity, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index _ the principal standard of investment performance _ shows a
handsome gain of close to 18 percent so far this year (including
reinvestment of dividends). The blue-chip Dow Jones industrial
average has been even more buoyant, gaining 26 percent year to
date.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the predictions for 2000, edited for space and clarity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Alfred Goldman &LR; , market strategist, A.G. Edwards &AMP; Son, St.
Louis:
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy will remain healthy, with corporate earnings up
about 12 percent. Inflation will remain benign _ maybe 21/2
percent. That will help the stock market, and there also is a
growing global demand for stocks _ more demand than supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The breadth of the market _ the number of stocks doing well _
is going to improve, because a lot of companies will benefit from
economic recoveries in Japan, the rest of Asia, Latin America and
Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My No.1 sector is technology. My favorites are Applied
Materials, Intel and Cisco Systems (which gives you exposure to the
Internet game). They are all dominant factors in dynamic growth
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the retail sector, I like Gap and Wal-Mart. Retail is going
to do well. Consumers are working and making money _ there is low
unemployment _ and Gap and Wal-Mart have proven growth records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would warn against any company that needs to rely on price
increases to grow its earnings, because there is no price
flexibility in this economy. Forget about any commodity-type
company, precious metals, restaurants and supermarkets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Stewart J. Pillette &LR; , Pillette Investment Management, San
Francisco:
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to make the year 2000 different is that the
market will be broadening out. We follow 3,400 companies, of which
85 percent have market capitalizations below $5 billion. Most of
those companies, especially manufacturers, will be major
beneficiaries of a global recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking of stocks like Autodesk, DST Systems, Mitel,
Mohawk Industries, Ashland, Alberto-Culver. And other types of
companies will piggyback on their success: banks, insurance
companies and a host of other service companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest risk in the market right now is the Internet stock
bubble. I'm very worried about that. A few of those companies have
earnings, but Amazon, for example, doesn't have earnings or even a
business plan. People are buying Internet stocks because they are
up, which is not a good reason.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Joe Turner &LR; , money manager, San Ramon:
</P>
<P>
   ``The big opportunity lies in the stocks that have performed
poorly this year. I can see a reversal of this year's roles, where
the big companies, the tech stocks and the Internet stocks _ which
are absurdly overvalued _ pull back and have a year of rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go through the list of stocks that are down significantly this
year, but have quality businesses, good dividend yields,
significant buying of shares by insiders or buying back of shares
by the companies themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some groups that fit this profile include real estate
investment trusts, utilities, managed-care companies, home builders
_ especially those in the manufactured-homes business, such as
Fleetwood, Cavalier and Clayton. Also, brick-and-mortar retailers,
such as Penney, Claire's Stores and Dillards. Then there's
fertilizer, which is really mundane, but there has been tremendous
insider buying. Take a look at Potash and IMC Global.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Gary Schlossberg &LR; , economist, Wells Capital Management, San
Francisco:
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect more gains in the stock market next year, but more
moderate than what we are seeing this year _ probably a gain in the
mid-single digits for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500. There's not enough
earnings momentum to push stocks higher than that, and there
probably will be no help from interest rates, which are likely to
either hold steady or move up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the big, mega-cap growth stocks should continue
to do better than the smaller companies through the better part of
2000. This is not to suggest that you put all your eggs in that
basket, but with more moderate earnings growth overall, investors
place a premium on reliable earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deregulation and restructuring are going to continue to shape
corporate performance _ not only here, but also abroad. Overseas,
they are behind us in restructuring, so overseas stocks could be
more attractive as restructuring comes on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Steve Janachowski &LR; , Brouwer &AMP; Janachowski, Tiburon:
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming a relatively benign economic environment, we're
focused on four major areas: financials, pharmaceuticals,
technology and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financials haven't done particularly well this year because
interest rates have gone up, but new legislation is expected to
free up the financial-service industry to move into profitable new
ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pharmaceuticals will benefit from the aging Baby Boomer
population, while technology is a hot story that will continue, and
telecommunications will benefit by providing infrastructure for the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Todd Bakar &LR; , director of research, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, San
Francisco:
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology has had an awesome year in 1999 _ particularly the
Internet and communications stocks _ but despite the big price
moves, this will continue to be an interesting area going forward.
This is where the innovation is taking place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business-to-business operations on the Internet have been red
hot. A lot of companies in this area have good fundamentals, like
Agile Software, Critical Path, Verisign and Vignette.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another area to watch is mobile communications. Whether your
cellular phone becomes more intelligent, or your pager, or palm
computer, the goal will be to access information, trade stocks,
search up restaurant directories _ to do more things in mobile form
that you've only been able to do at your desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``In wireless, I like Nokia and Motorola. The growth on the
whole cellular and wireless front will remain explosive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Marshall Acuff &LR; , market strategist, Salomon Smith Barney, New
York:
</P>
<P>
   ``The year 2000 will be another up year for the market, but
there are going to be more head winds than there were this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, the market had to contend with rising interest
rates, and we're probably going to see even higher rates during
2000, with the Fed raising them by perhaps another half percentage
point. Another head wind is that profit growth will slow to about 8
percent next year from about 14 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is not whether the market will be up, or how
much, but is it going to broaden out? The leadership has been quite
narrow for some time. I would be more enthusiastic about the
broader market if I thought this would be a strong year for
profits. It looks as though market leadership is going to continue
to be oriented toward bigger-cap growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like biotech companies because their productivity is rising.
Amgen is the company I would go with. It is the industry leader and
is coming forward with important new products next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A second area I like is communications technology. In
bandwidth technology I would go with MCI Worldcom, which seems
underpriced compared to its growth prospects. In wireless, Sprint
PCS seems reasonably priced, while Nokia and Qualcomm seem on the
high side.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Geraldine Weiss &LR; , publisher, Investment Quality Trends
newsletter, La Jolla (San Diego County):
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most overvalued market in history, based on every
measure of historical data we can find, such as dividend yields and
price-earnings ratios.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology sector has been going gangbusters, and I can't
foretell when that will top out. It has been stretched to historic
limits and I would doubt that this will continue into next year _
but nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We follow 350 blue-chip stocks, and more than two-thirds are
down for 1999. They include quality, old-line companies paying
good-sized dividends and selling at low price-earnings multiples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some companies that fit this description include American
Business Products, Bandag, Bergen Brunswick, Hunt Corp., Luby's,
Mercury General, and several utilities: Hawaiian Electric,
Wisconsin Energy and Keyspan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would even recommend Philip Morris. Its price-earnings
ratio is only 10. It just raised its dividend to where it is
yielding 7.4 percent, and its earnings continue strong. It owns
General Foods, Kraft and Miller Brewing. It's a good value even if
you eliminate the tobacco business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Bernard Schaeffer &LR; , president, Investment Research Institute,
Cincinnati:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for another bull market year. I wouldn't be
surprised if we see another 20 percent gain or so for the large-cap
market averages _ the S&AMP;P 500 and the Dow _ and even better than
that in the tech-oriented indexes like the Nasdaq composite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The broader market, as measured by the Russell 2000 index,
might perform pretty much in line with the Dow and S&AMP;P. That would
be quite a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We analyze investor sentiment and its implications for the
market. We base our conclusions on the activity in the options
market, comparing the trading volume of calls and puts. There has
been heavy buying of puts (which give the buyer the right to sell a
security at a fixed price before a fixed deadline). Buying puts is
a strategy based on fear, so we conclude that there is still a
healthy amount of fear in the market. That's a bullish sign,
because it means we aren't yet seeing the blind greed that precedes
a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet stocks are potentially dangerous, however. In many
cases, the support for this sector is a mile wide and an inch deep.
At the first sign of trouble, investors will bail.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
