<SLUG> BC-STANFORD-STANFORD </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Stanford Embraces E-Commerce Curriculum  &HT;     By Carrie Kirby 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Joining the growing group of business schools focusing on the
Internet, Stanford University announced yesterday that it is
opening a research center that will integrate electronic commerce
into the core MBA curriculum.
<P>
   The Center for Electronic Business and Commerce received more
than $20 million in its first round of funding, primarily from
sponsors Charles Schwab, General Atlantic Partners and eBay. The
center will serve as a library for case studies and research, and
will develop e-commerce courses for the business school.
</P>
<P>
   While Stanford doesn't plan to offer a degree specifically in
e-commerce, the university already teaches 11 courses that deal
with online business issues. A class called Electronic Commerce,
completely focused on online business, will be offered for the
first time during the Winter 2000 term.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's announcement comes at a time when MBA students are
flocking to Internet companies and MBA programs are responding with
more e-commerce-related courses. Vanderbilt University in
Nashville, Tenn., started the trend five years ago when it began
offering a concentration in e-commerce. The Massachusetts Institute
of Technology's e-commerce curriculum is the business school's most
popular track.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose State University began offering a certificate in
electronic commerce management this summer, and San Francisco State
University said last month that it will offer a concentration in
e-commerce within its College of Business.
</P>
<P>
   Garth Saloner, co-director of Stanford's e-commerce center, said
the center seeks to be far reaching. ``We really think that
electronic commerce is pervasive. It affects every aspect of what
we teach and do,'' Saloner said.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore the center will serve as a resource for faculty
developing e-commerce case studies for classes in all business
disciplines.
</P>
<P>
   True to Stanford's tradition of working with industry, another
class developed with the new center will allow students to work
directly with Silicon Valley e-commerce companies to examine
problems facing the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Research at the center will take advantage of the Internet's
ability to gather consumer data. For example, one study may examine
how the buying price in an online auction is affected by factors
such as number of bidders, structure and reputation of the auction
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to become a repository for data like that, so
researchers here and elsewhere can analyze what's going on in
electronic commerce,'' Saloner said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
