<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7973 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-SILK-SCHEME-BOS &LR;      12-13 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILK-SCHEME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANGLED WEB LANDS MASSACHUSETTS MAN IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Motivated by a potential gold mine of profits,
scientists have tried and failed for decades to duplicate the
complex genetic coding of spider silk in order to reproduce one of
the world's strongest, softest, and most flexible substances.
</P>
<P>
   So when San Francisco venture capitalist Nigel Fleming saw the
laboratory notes of a Chatham scientist who said he had succeeded,
Fleming was ecstatic. He quit his job, advanced $100,000 of his own
money to complete research, and signed on as chief executive of a
new company to rush spider silk into commercial production. Over
the next three years, he turned over $2.7 million to the scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was to be the crowning glory of my career,'' Fleming said
Monday from his San Francisco office. ``This was the most
extraordinary material in the universe, and we had it.''
</P>
<P>
   The only trouble was that it was all a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   The scientist, Glenn Elion, admitted later that he made up much
of his data in order to solicit money from unwitting investors.
According to court papers filed in connection with a federal
criminal case, Elion fleeced scientists, financiers, family, and
friends of some $3.8 million. He is scheduled to be sentenced
Tuesday in US District Court in Boston on one count of wire fraud
in connection with the case. He faces up to five years in prison
and fines of up to $7.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Elion could not be reached Monday. His lawyer, Robert Goldstein,
declined to comment but indicated he would present mitigating
evidence at the hearing. ``There is more to say about this case,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elion _ who has a doctorate in chemical engineering and is the
nephew of Gertrude B. Elion, who won the Nobel prize for medicine
in 1988 _ owned several companies, including a tiny winery in
Chatham and a biotech start-up, Plant Cell Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, Elion developed the scam as a way
of raising money to participate in another fraudulent scheme based
in Nigeria. The documents said that Elion had received a letter
from a Nigerian man who said he had access to $25 million in US
currency. The currency was coated with a special black substance
for security purposes, the letter stated, and Elion would receive
20 percent of the currency if he would send cash to pay for
removing the black coating.
</P>
<P>
   Elion said he traveled to Nigeria, meeting a man at a hotel who
showed him a box of black-coated bills. He eventually sent at least
$700,000 to advance the scheme, much of it solicited from other
people, court papers say.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain funds for the Nigerians, Elion solicited money from
partners, friends, and family to further what he said was promising
research on producing synthetic spider silk, US Secret Service
agent Sean McCarthy said in court documents. ``Elion stated he felt
that if he told these people the truth, they would be reluctant to
send money,'' McCarthy said.
</P>
<P>
   About that time, Fleming learned of Elion's claims to having
cloned the silk-making gene of the golden-silk spider by inserting
it into bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was amazing stuff,'' said Fleming, who has a doctorate in
clinical biochemistry from Cambridge University and was a lecturer
at Harvard Medical School. ``People have been trying to do this for
20 years. Dupont spent $20 million on it because it's so
potentially commercially lucrative. They said they could build
suspension bridges with it. He showed me a lot of partial data that
was very convincing, very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming helped Elion launch a company to develop and market the
genetically engineered spider silk. The two traveled the world to
raise money, winning pledges of capital from companies in Japan and
elsewhere in Asia, Fleming said. Elion persuaded family and friends
to invest.
</P>
<P>
   He said he began to be skeptical after Elion presented data to
Dupont scientists. Under tough questioning, Elion grew angry and
later sent a bitter, retributive letter, Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, I see that he couldn't face anyone who seriously
questioned his data,'' Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   Agents from the Secret Service and Scotland Yard, meanwhile,
arrested a man running the money-coating scheme and found Elion
among his victims. Elion admitted to investigators that he had been
working for years to profit from the scheme, living for a time in
London, where Fleming thought he was doing research.
</P>
<P>
   Elion's brother ``finally cornered him in a bar and demanded to
know the truth,'' Fleming said. ``That's when we got the news that
this was all a pack of lies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
