<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7980 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-ROBINSON-LADN     12-13 1472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ROBINSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON TO GET FIRST LOOK AT HIS OLD TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He could be bitter but isn't, exactly. He could
second-guess himself, which he does only slightly. He could feel
forlorn, not that he would tell you. Or he might just feel freed
from a world of pressure and expectation he never felt comfortable
in, which he certainly does.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Robinson feels a lot of things as he looks on from across
the country at the Los Angeles Kings he guided for four mostly
frustrating seasons, now flexing muscles like an NHL power in their
first year since he was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson spent four years trying to raise the Kings, and then
they went and grew up without him.
</P>
<P>
   He is now an assistant coach with the New Jersey Devils, and
when the Kings venture into the Continental Airlines Arena tonight,
it will be Robinson's first personal view of his former team since
it ended last season a disappointing 32-45-5, out of the playoffs
and in search of a new coach and direction.
</P>
<P>
   The new coach would become Andy Murray, fresh from coaching at
the high school level, and who is constantly credited for bringing
the Kings intensity and organizational skills, an indirect slap at
Robinson's reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'll tell you what, I'd like to have the team Andy was
given when I was coaching there,'' Robinson said. ``There's seven
or eight new faces on the club that probably would have made a big
difference between us making and not making the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson made the playoffs only once in his four seasons, that
coming in 1998 when the Kings were then promptly swept in the first
round. Still, progress had been made and more was expected last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but guys had career years in '98,'' said Kings
defenseman Rob Blake. ``There were 10 guys who had career years,
and if they don't duplicate it, we don't make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings would never get it going last season. They lost both
goaltenders in the fourth game of the year. Then Blake broke his
right foot. Soon right winger Glen Murray tore his right knee.
Their season was spinning out of control, and there would be no
salvaging it. Others began to underachieve and there were whispers
a passive Robinson was starting to lose control.
</P>
<P>
   Before the last game of the season, Robinson _ who was willing
to stay on _ asked Kings general manager Dave Taylor if he would be
coming back. Taylor, his friend and former Kings teammate who
carpooled with him to games, said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the stupidest thing I ever did,'' Robinson said of
asking Taylor. ``That was a long, friggin'' night.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a proud NHL Hall of Famer, was suddenly out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at pictures of Larry when he took over four years ago
and it's brown hair and a smooth complexion,'' said Kings
defenseman Sean O'Donnell. ``You look at last year and he had more
white hair, a little more wrinkles. It seemed like his four years
here was more like about 10 or 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, the Kings, and management all agree his one downfall
last season was his inability, or refusal, to come down on players
who failed to follow directions and perform as expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the one thing I should have done different was to be
a little harder on them, that's all,'' Robinson said. ``I demanded
hard work and got hard work, but if I were to second-guess myself,
I should have set those standards and stuck by them, no matter who
the person was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of underachievers last year, guys that had great
seasons the year before and I stuck with them, hoping that they
would come back and come through. It's easy to get mad and bench
this guy and that guy, not play this guy _ but these same people
you're benching are the same people who are going to win you games,
so you always keep hoping and hoping, hoping.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson hoped himself right out of a job. He admits it simply
isn't his nature to confront players, to criticize and punish those
who failed to respond. He had played for Scottie Bowman, a stern
taskmaster whose personal style he had never been comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Larry was always big on wanting guys to like him,''
O'Donnell said. ``That's a fine line, because sometimes when you're
a head coach you have to get guys pissed off. Larry didn't seem to
want that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'll never be the way Scottie was when I played.'
Because he hated him. Then you look at the results Bowman's got.
He's always had good teams. There's a fine line being a friend. You
should be able to do it, but the problem is the way players are
nowadays, if they smell they can get away with something, they'll
do it. Unfortunately, Larry kind of got caught up in that. It
wasn't his personality to embarrass somebody or to scream at them
or name them in the media. Things just sort of started landsliding
after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hoping just him telling you to do it was enough. And it
should be enough. It's not Larry's fault. But there are some guys
who need to be told two and three times, and if they still don't
listen, then action needs to be taken, whether it's scratching them
from the lineup, not playing them a couple periods, demoting them
on lines. It's something I don't think Andy hesitates to do. He
keeps everyone on a short leash.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there has been fairly significant personnel changes.
Taylor traded three young players and a first-round draft pick in
the offseason for Ziggy Palffy, Bryan Smolinski, Marcel Cousineau
and a fourth-round pick. Aki Berg is back after a year playing in
Finland and Frantisek Kaberle is over from Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Players injured a year ago _ Blake, Murray, goaltenders Stephane
Fiset and Jamie Storr _ are healthy. Donald Audette, acquired last
December, is back for a full season.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, Smolinski, Murray, Audette and Blake have been the
Kings' top five scorers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different team,'' Taylor said. ``We have the addition
of more speed and more skill. Andy Murray has done a very good job
with the club, but the biggest reason for our turnaround is, if you
look at Bryan Smolinski and Ziggy Palffy, those two players brought
us an additional 53 points at this juncture _ which is quite an
improvement in our team offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said during his tenure with the Kings the
organizational philosophy had always been to develop its young
talent, not to trade or sign for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to stick with our draft choices and not give
away our first draft picks,'' he said. ``That's what we went with,
and that's what I died with.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor insists the philosophy remains, and it was because of it
they were able to trade good young players, get something in return
and still have a strong system. Still, Taylor can appreciate
Robinson's outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he saw me at the draft he said, `Great trade, but a year
too late,''' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   And if Taylor had made the trade and the injured players were
back and the other new additions here, but Robinson still the coach
... would the Kings be doing as well?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an impossible question to answer,'' Taylor said. ``I
believe it was time for a change last year. When I talked to Larry
at the end of the season, I think he felt as much relieved by the
decision we had made.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Blake: ``There's no answer for that. No one knows.
Something had to be done. Things weren't working out the way they
were last year. It's unfortunate that the coach is probably the
easiest guy to go every time. That's usually what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Robinson is doing what he enjoys best _ developing
players. He is usually the last one off the ice after New Jersey
practices, spending extra time with young skaters willing and in
need of learning from one of hockey's greatest players.
</P>
<P>
   Here there is no media spotlight, no one demanding the big
answers, no impending meeting, no schedule to decide, no one
requiring a disciplinarian.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he does not miss the stress naturally incorporated
with being a head coach, but might be willing to try that road
again in the right situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think I'm at the stage of my career now, having been in
the game for so long, I'm looking at just being able to be close to
the young guys and teaching young guys, and passing on what I've
learned and my experiences,'' Robinson said. ``That part of the
game appeals to me more than going back to the grind and day-to-day
tribulations that go with being a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back on it and I'm hurt that I started something I
didn't get to finish. Especially going into the new building, to be
able to at least have one year of being there with it. But then,
that's the way the league goes sometimes. That's the hazards of
this occupation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
