<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7990 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-HOUSTON-DIMEL-HNS     12-13 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOUSTON-DIMEL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Last Friday, when Dana Dimel's car phone rang, the then-Wyoming
football coach figured, correctly, that it had to be good news.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At that time, Dimel was returning home to Laramie, Wyo., from
the Denver airport after a recruiting trip. Earlier that day,
Marshall coach Bob Pruett had changed his mind after signing a
contract to become the University of Houston's new head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that it was a tossup between Bob and me. We were the
only two candidates, and when I heard he had pulled out, I was
hopeful the phone would be ringing soon to bring some good news,''
Dimel said Monday at a news conference introducing him as the
Cougars' new coach.
</P>
<P>
   Dimel, 37, who first was contacted by UH on Nov. 24, three days
after Kim Helton was dismissed after seven seasons, agreed to a
five-year, $600,000-a-year contract plus bonuses and incentives. He
will receive a base salary of $300,000 annually and $300,000 a year
from external revenue sources such as radio-television, apparel,
camps and personal appearances _ about twice Helton's compensation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Dimel can earn bonuses based on team graduation
rates and grade-point averages, bowl appearances, Top 25 rankings,
Conference USA championships and No. 1 C-USA ranking in total
offense and total defense.
</P>
<P>
   UH will pay $200,000 to buy out the remaining two years of
Dimel's contract at Wyoming. UH also owes Helton $600,000 for the
last two years on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Dimel said he intends to implement a controlled passing game
with a 55-percent passing, 45-percent running ratio in play
selection.
</P>
<P>
   The new coach said he expects to complete his staff by Wednesday
and has offered positions to Les Koenning Jr. and Dick Bumpas, who
were Helton's offensive and defensive coordinators, respectively.
Dimel, who held his first players meeting Monday, already has hired
Nevada quarterbacks coach Phil Davis as the Cougars' offensive
coordinator. Helton's staff is under contract until June 1, but
Bumpas and Koenning apparently were the only assistants offered
positions on Dimel's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line coach Clancy Barone and secondary coach Mark
Stoops, both of whom were on Dimel's staff at Wyoming, are
considered possibilities to join him at UH.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Dimel said he has offered a position as an
offensive assistant to former UH quarterback and Heisman Trophy
winner Andre Ware, who said Monday, ``I am still mulling it over.''
</P>
<P>
   University chancellor/president Arthur K. Smith described the
search for Helton's successor _ by Smith and athletic director Chet
Gladchuk _ as ``a stealth operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimel in turn called his plan for next season ``a stealth
offense that is going to strike very quickly, a one-back set mostly
with four receivers and spread out the field combined with a
defensive pressure package. We want to get great speed all over the
field. That comes from recruiting, and that can make a very good
coach out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimel reiterated that he intends to actively recruit the Houston
area and increase the Cougars' recruiting visibility throughout
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked out of the hotel windows Sunday night, saw all those
lights and thought about all the great players there must be living
right out there,'' Dimel said. ``We should be able to bring in some
of them. We will have athleticism, guys who can chase the football
and run with it and catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   That process can begin Wednesday, the initial signing date for
midterm junior-college graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Dimel is a former offensive lineman, like earlier UH coaches
Bill Yeoman and Helton. Dimel's brief NFL career ended in his
rookie year as a Minnesota Vikings free agent after his fifth knee
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an old offensive lineman,'' Dimel said. ``I grind it out.
If I'm on offense or out on the recruiting trail, I'm grinding it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   He had logged 1,700 miles in a rental car recruiting Kansas
junior colleges shortly before he received his second, decisive
call from Gladchuk telling him the Cougars job was his.
</P>
<P>
   During 10 years at Kansas State, including terms as offensive
coordinator and offensive line coach on Bill Snyder's staff, Dimel
helped the Wildcats' rise to one of the country's most successful
programs of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, between 1988 and this season, the Cougars played in
one bowl. That was the 1996 Liberty Bowl after the Helton-coached
Cougars shared the C-USA title, their first conference championship
since a tie for the '84 Southwest Conference crown and one of four
Cotton Bowls under Yeoman. Their best regular-season record during
that time was 7-4 in '96 and '99, which adds up to two winning
seasons in the last nine years.
</P>
<P>
   When hired for his first head coaching job by Wyoming before the
1997 season, Dimel was one of 27 new Division I-A head coaches. Joe
Tiller, with 24 victories at Purdue the next three seasons, is the
only one of the group who has won more since then than Dimel, who
was 23-12 at Wyoming after replacing Tiller.
</P>
<P>
   Dimel grew up in Columbus, Ohio, about a mile from the Ohio
Stadium. His first game as Wyoming's head coach was at Columbus
against the Ohio State Buckeyes, and the Cowboys almost pulled off
an upset in the 1997 season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart of hearts, it was an easy decision to try to take
this program back to be a champion in Conference USA and to compete
with the Big 12 schools,'' Dimel told the crowd of UH staff and
supporters at the Athletics/Alumni Center, ``and I know we will
compete very quickly with the University of Texas (which is on UH
schedules the next three seasons).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get it cranking, no doubt, in my mind. Not to
sound braggadocious, but I don't know anything but win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know that the tradition of this football program
is in the hands of one who cares deeply about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
