<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-GAYS-MILITARY-1STLD-W     12-13 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COHEN ORDERS NEW SURVEY TO DETERMINE TREATMENT OF GAYS IN
MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 9th graf to correct spelling of bludgeoning) (sw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER and KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William Cohen on Monday ordered
spot checks of major military bases around the country to determine
whether gay service members are being harassed and told the
Pentagon inspector general to report back within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore on Monday night called for the outright
elimination of the administration's ``don't ask, don't tell''
policy for gays in the military, saying they should be allowed to
serve openly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gays and lesbians should be allowed to serve their country
without discrimination,'' Gore said in a statement on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore has long argued within the administration for
allowing gays to serve openly, he has not been so forceful publicly
until Monday night. His declaration follows an admission by
President Clinton over the weekend that the current policy toward
gays in the military was ``out of whack,'' but Clinton did not go
so far as to call for the policy to be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks in turn followed comments by his wife, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, who is running for the Senate in New York, that
gays should be allowed to serve openly. Former Sen. Bill Bradley of
New Jersey, Gore's lone rival for the Democratic presidential
nomination, called several weeks ago for gays to be allowed to
serve openly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton complained that the murder of a gay soldier in July
after cruel and persistent harassment showed that the military's
policy for gays was not working. In response to that death, for
which an Army private was convicted of murder last week, Defense
officials hastily put together plans on Monday for a new survey.
</P>
<P>
   The policy prohibits the military from asking about a soldier's
sex life unless there is clear evidence of homosexual conduct, and
it forbids harassing gay and lesbian service members. But the
policy also requires soldiers to leave the service if they
volunteer that they are homosexual or if there is evidence of
homosexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secretary shares the president's determination to make
sure that this policy is executed as fairly as possible,'' said
Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Pvt. Calvin Glover was found guilty of bludgeoning to
death Pfc. Barry Winchell, the gay soldier, in their barracks at
Fort Campbell, Kentucky. During the court-martial, soldiers related
how the gay soldier had been taunted for months with anti-gay slurs
without reprimand by their superiors.
</P>
<P>
   The new Pentagon survey will be conducted by teams under Donald
Mancuso, the acting inspector general, who said in an interview on
Monday that he was told of the new assessment only 30 minutes
before it was announced to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen asked Mancuso to find out what problems exist in
implementing the policy that forbids harassing gay and lesbian
service members but also requires them to leave the service if they
are found to be homosexual. The inspector general said on Monday
that he was given ``full latitude'' to conduct the survey, prepare
the questions and figure out which bases to visit.
</P>
<P>
   For gay and lesbian rights groups the Pentagon announcement was
a disappointment. ``What needs to be done is training to prevent
anti-gay harassment at all levels,'' said Dickson Osborne,
co-executive director of Servicemembers Legal Defense Network.
</P>
<P>
   While saying the survey is a step forward, Osoborne said it
could not succeed because Defense officials failed to promise
confidentiality to service members who come forward to report
harassment to the visiting teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question is can gay people participate in this survey
without getting fired from their jobs, '' he said. ``How do you
trust anyone, especially at a base where an anti-gay murder took
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman, said that the investigators would
pursue those accused of harassment, not the service members who
report that they have been taunted. Under the `don't ask' portion
of the policy, a superior is forbidden to question a service member
about his sexual preference or investigate his private activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be easy to tell from talking to people whether
anti-gay statements or harassment is a regular part of the life of
the post, irrespective of whether the people who are doing the
reporting may happen to be gay or not,'' said Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's aim, he continued, is to ``look at the climate _ if
there was a harassing climate and whether this is condoned by the
command.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the policy was first enacted in 1993, the Pentagon
has yet to institute formal training programs on the policy for all
branches of the services. Following Winchell's murder, Cohen
reissued the guidelines for 'don't ask, don't tell' in August and
asked all the services to submit proposals for training programs,
which they have done. Now that the president asked for a
reassessment of how the policy is followed, the Pentagon will act
quickly on those training proposals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's personnel boss, Vice Adm. Daniel T. Oliver, did issue
a Navy-wide memorandum on Oct. 28, sternly reminding commanding
officers that they ``must not condone homosexual jokes, epithets or
derogatory comments, and must ensure a command climate that fosters
respect for all individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum continued: ``Service members should be able to
report crimes and harassment free from fear of harm, reprisal or
inappropriate or inadequate governmental response.''
</P>
<P>
   It then described in detail what the policy does and does not
permit.
</P>
<P>
   When the secretary reissued the policy guidelines in August, the
message drew respect and derision from officers and enlisted
troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, screwing up any homosexual case provides an
excellent opportunity to appear on `60 Minutes,' wrote Col. James
C. Walker, the staff judge advocate for the 1st Marine
Expeditionary Force at Camp Pendleton, Calif. in an e-mail message
sent to commanders outlining Cohen's guidelines. ``My job is to
deny you that opportunity. Call me on all these cases.''
</P>
<P>
   But in another e-mail message circulating at the Marine base at
Twenty-Nine Palms, Calif., one officer wrote to several others:
``Due to the 'hate crime' death of a homo in the Army we now have
to take extra steps to ensure the safety of the queer who has
'told' (not kept his part of the D.O.D. ''don't ask, don't tell''
policy.)
</P>
<P>
   Whoever gets political credit for being first to call for the
policy's elimination, the fact that some of the nation's most
prominent Democrats want it scrapped suggests a major battle ahead
in Congress. Republicans do not support the policy either, but they
generally do not want gays in the military at all.
</P>
<P>
   The process that is leading to the re-examination of the gays in
the military is similar to that which drove Clinton to shift his
position on another sensitive military issue, whether to reopen a
firing range in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago Mrs. Clinton, apparently with her eye on New York
politics and the sizeable Puerto Rican community there, sided with
the governor of Puerto Rico and said the base should be permanently
closed. Shortly thereafter, Gore adopted the same position. Last
month, the president rejected the alternative recommendations of
the Navy and ordered the end of military exercises with live fire
on the base at Vieques.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
