<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8001 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GOP-DEBATE-NYT &LR;      12-13 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TANGLES WITH MCCAIN OVER CAMPAIGN FINANCING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ In the most spirited Republican debate so
far, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain of Arizona
sparred over McCain's advocacy for overhauling the nation's
campaign finance laws, with Bush declining McCain's offer that the
two take a joint pledge against accepting so-called soft money, or
largely unregulated corporate contributions.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has emerged as the most potent challenger to Bush
for the Republican presidential nomination, told Bush that special
interests were stealing the federal government and that, ``You and
I can stop that tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can commit, as nominees of the party, that we'll have
nothing to do with soft money,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush answered that such a repudiation of soft money would amount
to ``unilateral disarmament'' by giving an advantage to Democrats,
who benefit from donations from labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   Without soft money, Bush said, ``Our Republican Party and
conservative values don't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange underscored McCain's efforts to portray himself as
an insurgent outsider and Bush as the candidate anointed by the
establishment, and it was one of many instances Monday night when
Bush's challengers sought to put him on the defensive or pin him
down in an uncomfortable way.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, a religious conservative, also invited Bush to take
vow: a promise that if Bush became the Republican nominee, he would
choose a running mate who was opposed to legal abortion. Bush did
not do so, saying it would be presumptuous for someone who has not
yet won the nomination to be choosing a vice presidential
candidate. Instead, he said, voters could rest assured that he
would choose a vice presidential candidate who could become
president if necessary, and that that was the most important
criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, whose lackluster performances in previous debates came
under intense scrutiny and criticism, was more assertive and
aggressive this time around, his voice more forceful and his
bearing more confident.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many of the candidates shed some of the tact and
restraint that had defined two forums earlier this month,
precipitating some pungent and occasionally hilarious dialogue as
the subjects ranged far and wide, from gun control and health care
to the vanishing of the family farm and America's trading
relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer and Bush in particular quarreled over that last topic,
with Bauer challenging Bush's support of China's entry into the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will stop allowing China to play us for suckers,'' Bauer
said. ``They dump their goods here, and Iowa farmers are selling
less to China now than they did 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the best way to change that was to make trade with
China even freer, and that China's place in the trade organization
would make it more amenable to fair trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening up Chinese markets is good for Iowa farmers, yessir,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't kept their agreements for 20 years,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates began mixing it up when McCain was asked about
his push to reduce pork barrel spending, and brought up,
unprompted, his opposition to federal subsidies for ethanol, a
corn-based fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Support for ethanol subsidies is a litmus test for candidates in
Iowa, but McCain, apparently seeking to bolster his case that he is
willing to oppose special interests, flatly said he would cut the
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to tell you the things you don't want to hear as well
as what you do want to hear,'' McCain said. ``And everybody here on
this stage, if it wasn't for the fact that Iowa is the first caucus
state, would share my view that we don't need ethanol subsidies.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the first freewheeling moments in the series of
Republican debates, the other candidates jumped on McCain's
statements and, to cheers from the audience in the studio, pledged
their backing for ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support ethanol because it's good for the quality of the
air,'' Bush said. ``It also reduces our dependence on foreign
oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin B. Hatch of Utah said ethanol was ``a renewable
resource that helps farmers, that literally might help us in the
event of another energy crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to the first question, on whether movies and video
games had contributed to school shootings like those at Columbine
High School, the candidates agreed that part of the blame should go
to movies and video games that desensitive children to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We parents should know what our children are watching,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   But they said the real problems were a deterioration of moral
standards and the nation's failure to outlaw abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much focus today on the Dow Jones Industrial
Average and that's fine,'' Bush said. But the focus, Bush said,
should be on ``a problem of the heart in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he would set a moral tone as president that would
give him the clout to take on movie producers and makers of video
games over violence in popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's Republican forum was the third in 11 days to
feature all six candidates for the party's nomination, but it was
the first to take place in Iowa, a pivotal state whose precinct
caucus on Jan. 24 is the opening contest of the primary season. The
first primary, in New Hampshire, comes eight days later.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared to be on much sturdier ground in Iowa than in New
Hampshire, where McCain has pulled ahead of him in several recent
polls. But the publisher Steve Forbes is pouring time and money
into Iowa in the hopes of finishing a strong second to Bush and
proving himself a viable alternative to the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has adopted an unusual, possibly even risky strategy of
ignoring Iowa so that he can focus on New Hampshire, South Carolina
and Arizona
</P>
<P>
   The two previous Republican forums _ in Manchester, N.H., on
Dec. 3, and in Phoenix on Dec. 6 _ were marked by a striking degree
of at least superficial cordiality, with the six candidates
speaking to and about one another in relatively restrained,
respectful terms.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's opponents, still trailing far behind in national
polls, made subtle and sometimes indirect efforts to chip into that
lead by portraying him as someone without the requisite experience,
seriousness or intellectual maturity to lead the country.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush's lackluster, frequently rote performances during those
debates came under exacting scrutiny, dulled the sheen of
inevitability surrounding his candidacy. Journalists and political
analysts examined everything from Bush's cautious adherence to
comments taken from his stump speeches to the curl of his lips,
which struck many observers as a smirk.
</P>
<P>
   Some prominent Republicans and even a few of Bush's foreign
policy advisers conceded that they had been disappointed by the
impression that Bush was making in the debates, which they said did
not do justice to the charm and fluency in policy that he has
projected in less formal settings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
