<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8006 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-DEBATE-COX     12-13 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush, McCain finally show sparks in Iowa debate
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Presidential candidates Gov. George W. Bush
and Sen. John McCain sparred over tax and campaign finance reform
in a Monday night debate that highlighted differences that could
frame the battle for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges came in a debate televised nationally from the Des
Moines Civic Center in the biggest city in the state that will kick
off the presidential season with its Jan. 24 caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who drew criticism for uninspired and uninspiring
performances in previous debates in New Hampshire and Arizona,
wound up in a spirited discussion with McCain when he asked the
senator a question about the relative merits of their tax-cut
plans. Bush, who has avoided cross words about McCain (R-Ariz.),
wound up debating the campaign-finance reform plan that undergirds
many of McCain's positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to get rid of pork in Washington, stop feeding the
hog,'' Bush said, arguing that the best way to limit pork-barrel
spending is to lower taxes, giving government less money to spend.
</P>
<P>
   McCain touched on the tax question but used most of his time to
talk about his call for the end of unlimited soft-money campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny you mention pork,'' McCain told Bush. ``What the
American people need is their money back and they are not going to
get it back until we get it out of the hands of the special
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain asked if all the GOP contenders, including Utah Sen.
Orrin Hatch, publisher Steve Forbes, Alan Keyes and Gary Bauer,
would join him in swearing off soft money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be glad to talk about it,'' said Bush, taking the bait
and making the case that McCain's plan is ``unilateral
disarmament'' because it would not curtail big donations to
Democrats from labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's my worry,'' he told McCain, ``with your plan it's going
to hurt the Republican Party, John.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain also differed on federal ethanol subsidies, the
issue that is keeping the Arizona senator from campaigning here.
Iowa farmers, a powerful political force, like the subsidy program.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said ethanol subsidies come from a dead-end program
backed by special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to tell you that I want to tell you the things you
don't want to hear as well as the things you do want to hear,''
McCain said, drawing boos in the Des Moines Civic Center. ``And one
of those is ethanol. Ethanol is not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said ethanol subsidies should continue because the
agriculture-based fuel ``is good for the air'' and helps reduce
dependency on foreign oil.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is concentrating his campaigning efforts on New
Hampshire, where he now leads Bush in the run up to the Feb. 1
primary, and South Carolina, where Bush has a substantial lead
going into the Feb. 19 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also took heat from Bauer, who challenged him to vow to
choose an anti-abortion rights running mate if nominated. Bush
declined, as he has throughout the campaign. ``I will name somebody
who can be the president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The six candidates also were asked to name a political or
philosophical hero.
</P>
<P>
   Bush named Jesus Christ ``because he changed my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to tell viewers why he choose Christ, Bush said, ``If they
don't know it's going to be hard to explain.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes named John Locke and Thomas Jefferson. Hatch named
Abraham Lincoln and Ronald Reagan. McCain cited ``all of our
founding fathers'' and Theodore Roosevelt. Bauer named and quoted
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
