</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-BRITAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN TO LIFT BAN ON GAYS IN MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GAYS-MILITARY) 
 (af)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain has decided to end the ban on homosexuals in
the armed forces, Defense Secretary Geoff Hoon has said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoon said a new code of conduct would be introduced next year
replacing the current prohibition against gay men and women in
uniform, The Times of London reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the United States military, with its ``don't ask, don't
tell'' policy, the British military flatly bans gays.
</P>
<P>
   The new code will specify that sexual behavior involving on-duty
personnel will be a punishable offense but that sexual orientation
no longer will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone's sexuality is a private matter,'' Hoon said. ``People
are entitled to a private life. A new code of conduct, is,
therefore, the right way of dealing with this question, but I want
to make sure that any solution to this problem does not jeopardize
the effectiveness of the armed forces.''
</P>
<P>
   The Labor government of Prime Minister Tony Blair had been
promising to take such action since September when the European
Court of Human Rights ruled in favor of four gay people dismissed
from the military.
</P>
<P>
   The court said Britain's ban constituted a ``grave
interference'' in private lives.
</P>
<P>
   The Times said the new code would be drawn up in January, but a
Defense Ministry spokesman said no time had been set for ending the
ban.
</P>
<P>
   Most other European nations have permitted gays in uniform since
the Netherlands pioneered the cause in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Hoon will open an armed forces equal opportunities conference in
Birmingham this week, and he said he intended to devote attention
to expanding the recruitment and advancement of women in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to the day when we have a woman general, but,
equally, I don't believe in positive discrimination,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Women in the British armed forces are still barred from
front-line combat roles and are not permitted to serve in the
infantry, armored corps, diving units or submarines.
</P>
<P>
   Hoon did not say if he intended to change that, but he added,
``As women progress through the ranks, they will need to have the
right experience and background to reach the top.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 2240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
