<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8010 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ALBRIGHT-BERGER-ART-2     12-13 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-BERGER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BERGER IN CATBIRD SEAT, ALBRIGHT'S STAR DIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The end of the war in Kosovo was supposed to be a
moment of glory for Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who had
argued passionately for the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in the six months since, Albright has been effectively
eclipsed in foreign affairs by Sandy Berger, the national security
adviser, who has brought his physical proximity to the Oval Office
and his personal relationship with President Clinton to bear on
every foreign policy issue, according to administration officials
and foreign policy experts.
</P>
<P>
   From forging China's entry into the World Trade Organization, to
the unsuccessful battle to win ratification of the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty, to shaping American policy toward Russia's war in
Chechnya, to running Clinton's 11-day trip to Europe, Berger's
presence has been unrelenting.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would argue that Albright has been locked out. The
secretary was at center stage in the Middle East last week when the
Syrian president, Hafez al-Assad, told her during their meeting in
Damascus that he was prepared to resume negotiations with Israel.
Her assistants were quick to note that Assad had told a visitor the
week before that ``nothing can happen until the lady comes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Syrian breakthrough was announced by Clinton, but
Albright was in the spotlight explaining the deal on television,
even though she is less a fixture on the talk shows than she once
was.
</P>
<P>
   But despite what will be continued visibility for Albright this
week as the Middle East peace talks resume in Washington, officials
inside and outside the administration say there is little doubt
about who actually formulates the decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no dispute who runs the show on foreign policy,''
said Ivo Daalder, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, who
is working on a study of the national security council, and who
worked with Berger in the first Clinton term.
</P>
<P>
   Of Albright, he said: ``She remains a participant in the
process. But her weight as secretary of state in the determination
of foreign policy appears less than at any time in the Clinton
administration, including Secretary of State Warren Christopher's
term.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger, a trade lawyer by profession and longtime Washington
political insider, has emerged on top not because of his expertise
in foreign policy, said Daalder.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, what helped him rise so forcefully are his skills as a
hands-on manager, his obsession with finding a consensus among top
officials and the fact that, in this administration, foreign policy
has often been redefined as economic policy advanced through
increased trade.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say Berger emerged the much stronger of
the pair from the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who is seen as a policymaker driven by convictions
with a large human rights concern, persuaded Berger and Clinton of
the need to go to war against the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan
Milosevic, many officials have said. It was a position that the
president and Berger came to much later and more warily than the
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   But once the war began, the White House became the center of
operations, a place that Albright visited for meetings but where
Clinton and Berger held the fort. For the most part, her task was
to work the phones from the state department to try to keep the
NATO foreign ministers on board and fully briefed.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's foreign policy emphasis then shifted away
from Albright's strengths _ the Balkans and Europe _ to China,
Russia, the Middle East and Ireland _ where a special envoy, George
Mitchell, reported to Berger and the president.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Berger was being reinforced by a bigger and
more operational National Security Council than ever before. There
are currently 99 policy assistants at the council _ 35 on loan from
nongovernmental institutions like the Council on Foreign Relations
_ many of them micromanaging issues. A decade ago, there were only
about 70.
</P>
<P>
   On Clinton's recent trip to Istanbul for a meeting of the
Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe, where Russia
was the major topic, Berger briefed reporters every day, a job
often done by the White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   On Russia policy in general, Albright's deputy undersecretary of
state, Strobe Talbott, is the key policymaker, with Berger
increasingly involved, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott, who is the administration's most frequent traveler to
Moscow, writes long memos that are delivered to Albright and Berger
``concurrently and equally,'' an administration official said. The
issues are then resolved at the White House, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary talks frequently with the Russian foreign
minister, Igor Ivanov, but Ivanov, according to administration
officials, is not part of the inner workings of the Russian
government.
</P>
<P>
   On China, Berger has taken the lead, a situation that Albright
has said she believes is a traditional one for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   When China's entry into the World Trade Organization needed to
be pushed, Albright said it was natural that the U.S. trade
representative, Charlene Barshefsky, should be in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's fantastic,'' Albright said. ``She has every detail in
her head; that is her job.''
</P>
<P>
   On the fight with Congress over the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty, Berger was in the catbird seat. He gave the Democratic
leadership the go-ahead to try to win ratification and then
negotiated _ unsuccessfully _ with Republican leaders. Neither
Albright's warm relationship with the chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, Jesse Helms _ a friendship she has
taken great pride in _ nor Berger's political instincts, helped.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty's defeat was a major setback for the administration,
and Berger tried a comeback with two speeches that lambasted what
he called the dangers to the United States of neo-isolationism. But
after receiving poor reviews from the foreign policy establishment
on the grounds that he had been too partisan, Berger dropped the
theme.
</P>
<P>
   Albright had not been given an advance copy of Berger's first
speech, to the Council on Foreign Relations, State Department
officials said. In the interview, she said crisply: ``I write my
speeches and Mr. Berger writes his speeches.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Berger is not the most powerful national security adviser in
recent history _ a status that that still belong to Henry Kissinger
followed by Zbigniew Brzezinski. But he is surely the most
political adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``He instinctively understands Mr. Clinton's needs better than
anyone else,'' Daalder said. ``That makes him absolutely the best
national security adviser for this president, whose involvement in
foreign affairs is episodic and often driven by domestic political
considerations.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger and Albright, who know each other well from Democratic
presidential campaigns and Washington salons, insist that they work
together in seamless coordination.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his office, Berger said that he and the
secretary ``work together as a team as well as any foreign policy
team in the last 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, however, sensitive about their relative positions. He
took care to read in advance a State Department transcript of an
interview that Albright had given to The New York Times a week
earlier, in which a question suggested that Berger had assumed some
of the mantle of secretary of state _ a notion that Berger hotly
disputed.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Albright said, ``As far as I am concerned a strong
national security adviser is very important for a strong secretary
of state.''
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, the emphasis on teamwork is not misplaced,
said Coit Blacker, who was the senior assistant on Russia on the
National Security Council in Clinton's first term and is now a
professor of international relations at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Berger had overtaken Albright because his personality suited the
president, and Albright appeared to have left a vacuum. It is
Berger who has the ease of access to Clinton, an ultimate measure
of clout in any administration.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed in an interview how often she had seen Clinton
one-on-one this year, Albright replied: ``I do not keep track of it
but often what happens is that I see him alone or after a meeting
or I talk to him on the phone. He calls me or I call him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 2243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0461 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8012 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-NCAA-FLASTATE-HNS     12-13 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NCAA-FLASTATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANNY ROBBINS  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Florida State University has asked the NCAA to clarify whether a
Seminoles football player violated NCAA rules when he worked with a
Houston personal trainer last summer and was not required to pay
for the trainer's services.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Minnix, Florida State's associate athletic director for
compliance, was quoted in Thursday's Tallahassee Democrat as saying
he had contacted Steve Mallonee, an NCAA director of membership
services, last week to seek an opinion on whether FSU defensive
lineman Roland Seymour was in violation of NCAA regulations when he
worked in Houston for a month last summer with personal trainer
James Cooper and wasn't required to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Minnix's request occurred after a Dec. 4 story in the Chronicle
reported he had known about the matter in August but had neither
sought an official rules interpretation from the NCAA nor taken any
action regarding Seymour's eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   The story reported that the Seymour case could be considered a
violation of NCAA bylaw 12.1.1.1.6, which states that a
student-athlete loses his or her amateur standing by accepting
preferential treatment, benefits or services as a result of his or
her athletics skill, reputation or payback potential as a
professional athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Minnix, who spent 20 years as an NCAA enforcement representative
and director before coming to Florida State in 1995, said he knew
Cooper did not require payment from Seymour but believed the matter
was not an amateurism issue because Cooper has made similar
arrangements with other high school and college athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper has gained a national reputation as a strength and
conditioning expert and trains dozens of NFL and NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   Seymour, a junior defensive end from New Orleans, entered the
season as one of the top pro prospects at his position but played
in only eight games because of a shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   If the NCAA finds that Seymour's involvement with Cooper was
indeed a rules violation, Florida State would be required to
declare him ineligible. Under those circumstances, he might not be
available for the top-ranked Seminoles' Sugar Bowl matchup with
Virginia Tech. Florida State also might be subject to institutional
penalties for allowing an ineligible player to participate
throughout the season. Forfeits, however, likely would not be
assessed if the school were found to have investigated the matter
thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Minnix did not respond to a message from the Chronicle on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Seymour's relationship with Cooper came to Minnix's attention
when the player was linked to Houston sports agent Carl Poston by a
recruiter for a rival agent last summer. The recruiter contacted
Bill Saum, the NCAA's chief enforcement official for agent issues,
after seeing Seymour and Poston together at a Houston restaurant.
In talking to Saum, the recruiter mentioned Seymour was training
with Cooper and speculated that Poston was paying the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Minnix subsequently was told by Cooper that the trainer had
worked with Seymour for free. Minnix said he concluded Seymour had
not violated NCAA rules, because of Cooper's practice of routinely
providing free workouts for high school and college athletes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Tallahassee Democrat story last week, Minnix said he had
discussed his opinion of the Seymour-Cooper matter last August with
Saum. According to the article, Saum did not disagree with Minnix's
view that Seymour was not in violation of NCAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   Saum said last week he was prohibited by NCAA procedure from
discussing the matter publicly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 2248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991213.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8014 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DEBATE-GOP-KAN &LR;      12-13 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-GOP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN OPPOSES ETHANOL SUBSIDY, SEEKING TO GRAB SPOTLIGHT IN IOWA
GOP DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE and SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Arizona Sen. John
McCain tried to steal the spotlight from Texas Gov. George W. Bush
Monday night by taking a stand very much in keeping with his
maverick image, but in direct opposition to popular sentiment in
Iowa.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the third GOP presidential debate in two weeks, but the first
in Iowa featuring all six candidates, McCain proposed ending the
multimillion-dollar subsidies for ethanol, a corn-based fuel
additive that gives Iowa's hard-pressed farmers another market for
their products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethanol is not worth it,'' McCain said in the nationally
televised debate from the Civic Center in downtown Des Moines. ``It
does not help the consumer. These ethanol subsidies should be
phased out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the GOP front-runner who leads in early Iowa polls,
disagreed. He said use of ethanol is good for air quality. It also
reduces reliance on foreign oil, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Republican candidates agreed with Bush on the
economically dubious practice of converting corn surpluses into
fuel. But McCain's stand, surprising because, on its face, it would
seem to be broadly unpopular in Iowa, was certain to garner
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who chose to not compete in Iowa but to take part in
Monday's debate, has taken the lead in most polls in New Hampshire,
the state that holds the first primary in early February. He has
gained that lead by forging an image as a tell-it-as-it-is,
nontypical politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here on this stage, if it wasn't for the fact that
Iowa is the first caucus state, would share my view that we don't
need ethanol subsidies,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   His answer may prove more popular in New Hampshire, South
Carolina and other early primary states. Iowa's caucus on Jan. 24
will be the first significant political test in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   On another matter, Bush was asked whether he would commit to
nominating an anti-abortion vice-presidential running mate. As he
has in the past, Bush seemed to suggest that he would not.
</P>
<P>
   He said the key would be whether his running mate is qualified,
loyal and ``shares my conservative views.'' But he did not directly
address the abortion question.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates also were asked to address how to fix societal
ills that led to the mass shootings at Columbine High School in
Colorado. Former Ambassador Alan Keyes suggested the key was
outlawing abortion, a move that would ``restore the country's
allegiance to basic moral principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch said he would be a president of integrity
who could approach the entertainment industry in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have the moral power to talk to those people,'' Hatch
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the most important thing was enforcing existing gun
laws, a move that in itself would send a clear message to the rest
of the country and would make the country safer. In Texas, he said,
he worked to appropriate more money to counties so that district
attorneys could prosecute more people who used guns illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to send a signal: Don't be illegally selling guns,''
Bush said. ``Don't be illegally using guns.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain acknowledged that sometimes he doesn't know what his own
children are looking at on the Internet. He said the country must
learn more about the influence of the Internet on children.
Libraries, he added, should have filters on their computers that
make it impossible to log onto sites that promote violence.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a third of the debate was spent by the Republicans
tearing at the Democratic administration for its foreign policy.
McCain and Keyes said President Clinton is not firm enough in
condemning Russian actions in Chechnya. Bush promised a Ronald
Reagan approach promoting a missile defense or muzzling nuclear
threats.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, Steve Forbes and Gary Bauer said the United States is too
subservient to international organizations, such as the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, a former Reagan administration official, jabbed back at
Bush after hearing his criticism about Bauer's hard line on keeping
China out of the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening up Chinese markets is good for Iowa farmers,'' Bush
said, but Bauer replied: ``You believe the Chinese will keep the
agreements. They haven't kept their agreements in 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Civic Center was ringed with police cars and clusters of
Bush and Forbes supporters, who gathered more than an hour early to
ensure backdrops for the television crews on pre-debate telecasts.
Forbes bused in some of his backers and loaded the back of a
mid-sized moving van with literature and give-away day-glow orange
T-shirts and stocking caps.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's face-off had several segments. At one point, the
candidates were allowed to ask each other questions. At another,
questions solicited from audience members were asked. The forum
also featured questions asked from moderators Tom Brokaw, NBC news
anchor, and John Bachman, WHO-TV anchor in Des Moines, directly to
the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Although expectations for Bush were high heading into Monday's
debate, one GOP consultant, Rich Galen, said the governor should be
pleased if he progressed as much between the second GOP debate and
Monday's forum as he did between the first and second face-offs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Bush is on the right track,'' said Galen, a Bush
backer who once ran GOPAC, the political committee headed by former
House Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday, the campaign will shift back to meetings with
small groups of Iowans, a setting where Bush excels, Galen said.
Campaigns have a natural ebb and flow, and McCain's rise in New
Hampshire is part of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew it would get closer,'' Galen said of the GOP
nomination race. ``Bush's campaign is not even concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyn Nofziger, a Forbes backer and veteran of several Ronald
Reagan campaigns, said that Bush needed to go beyond canned
fragments of his speeches and display a great mastery of the
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sticking with the prepared remarks hurt him in the last two
(debates),'' Nofziger said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's debate, Nofziger said, might have entertained political
junkies while passing with little notice among ordinary voters who
will troop to Iowa's caucuses just a month away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably won't be until after New Year's that people notice
these guys,'' he said. ``Right now they're more concerned with
Christmas shopping and the end of the college football season to
bother with politicians.''
</P>
</TEXT>
