<SLUG> BC-MINWAGE-HEARING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING SCHEDULED ON MINIMUM WAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The five-member Industrial Welfare Commission,
which has the authority to raise the minimum wage with or without
approval from the California state Legislature, will hold a public
hearing Wednesday in downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing is the first step in what is expected to be a
yearlong process to decide whether to increase the state's minimum
wage from its current $5.75 an hour. Every two years, the
commission is required to review the current minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Labor organizations and those who support a wage increase say a
dual-income couple can't earn enough money on minimum wage to
escape from living in poverty. Business organizations say an
increase in the minimum wage will lead to layoffs since businesses
can't pass on the higher costs to customers in a competitive world
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes around $40,000 a year to support a family in
California, and clearly the minimum wage is nowhere near that,''
said Sharon Cornu, a spokeswoman for the California Labor
Federation. ``An increase in the minimum wage would reward hard
work and promote prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   While the California Labor Federation petitioned the IWC for the
hearing, Cornu said the organization has not determined how large
of a minimum wage increase it will ask the commission to implement.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone supports an increase in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Julianne Broyles, a lobbyist with the California Chamber of
Commerce in Sacramento, said, ``There are other ways (instead of
raising the minimum wage) to make life more affordable for all
Californians, including making housing more affordable and lowering
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   California's minimum wage will soon become the lowest on the
West Coast. A successful 1996 ballot initiative in Oregon boosted
that state's minimum wage in three steps to $6.50 and hour this
year. In Washington, the minimum wage will increase to $6.50
beginning Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``With other states increasing their minimum wage, there is no
reason for California to be a low-wage state,'' Cornu said.
</P>
<P>
   Broyles, disagreed saying, ``If it's going to be raised it
should be done at the federal level, putting all states on a level
playing field instead of pitting one state against another.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, California's minimum wage is 60 cents higher than the
federal minimum wage of $5.15 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
