<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8017 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-DEBATE-1STLD-WRIT     12-13 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN CHALLENGES BUSH ON HOME-GROWN ISSUE IN IOWA  
 (EDs: Adds quotes from McCain, Bush spokeswoman; edits to
tighten)  
 (For use by New York Times news service clients)   
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Arizona Sen. John McCain denounced federal
subsidies for ethanol in a debate before a belt-corn audience here
Monday, and he issued a pointed challenge to Texas Gov. George W.
Bush to seek an end ``soft money'' donations to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, Bush and the four other Republican presidential hopefuls
met for the first time in this crucial state in a debate that
focused on agricultural issues, morality and trade. Bush and McCain
dominated the 90-minute session, held in advance of the Jan. 24
Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Bush drew applause from the audience of 2,400 Republicans by
backing the federal subsidy for ethanol, a major issue among Iowa
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   McCain defended his stand against ethanol, a gasoline additive
derived from corn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to tell you things you don't want to hear,'' McCain
said. ``And one of those things is (about) ethanol.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has shunned Iowa because of his opposition to the $700
million-a-year ethanol subsidy, which he considers to be a
pork-barrel spending project. In denouncing ethanol, McCain
appeared to be playing the maverick card he has cultivated with
voters in other states, particularly New Hampshire, where polls
show the senator is giving Bush a serious challenge.
</P>
<P>
   McCain drew a few boos and hisses from the Republican crowd for
his statement on the subsidies. He softened the blow a bit by
arguing that as a president promoting free trade, Iowa farmers
would make up for the loss of ethanol-related corn by exporting
more agricultural projects.
</P>
<P>
   China, McCain said, ``will be eating Iowa pork and loving every
mouthful of it when I'm president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was important that the voters of Iowa know where
I stand on the issues,'' McCain told reporters after the debate.
``The farmers of Iowa should want to be off subsidies.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain denied attempting to seek political advantage outside
Iowa through an ``in-your-face'' debate performance in a state
where he is not competing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Florida and said I'm against sugar subsidies,''
McCain said. ``I'll go to Texas if they'll let me in and say I'm
against gas and oil subsidies. Those are the fundamental beliefs
that I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is well ahead of his nearest competitor _ publishing
magnate Steve Forbes _ in Iowa polls, said he supports the ethanol
subsidy ``whether I'm in Iowa or not. ... It's good for the air
(and) it reduces our dependency on foreign oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said Bush was not tailoring his
message to Iowa voters during the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's speaking to America as well as Iowa,'' Hughes said.
``Obviously Iowa is first, but one thing about George W. Bush is he
says the same thing whether he's in the barrio, the chamber of
commerce, or in a debate.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain asked Bush to join him in pledging to end the power of
Washington lobbyists and ``soft money,'' the contributions to
political parties from corporate interests and unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can stop it now,'' McCain said to Bush and the other
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would like to ``talk to you about it sometime.''
When moderator Tom Brokaw of NBC News pressed him for an answer,
Bush said he liked the idea of restricting soft money, but worried
it would hurt the Republican Party if nothing was done to control
the ability of unions to take portions of union-worker wages for
political activity _ most of it benefiting Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We better have paycheck protection or our conservative values
aren't worth a shot,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, a conservative abortion foe and former Reagan
administration official, challenged Bush on trade with China. The
two argued over whether China would live up to trade agreements and
the regulatory framework that goes with China's admission to the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will stop China playing us for suckers,'' Bauer said to
Bush. ``The time for them playing us for suckers will end with my
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he called China ``evil'' and said the Beijing government
is the largest threat to U.S. power in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   As he has in the past, Bush argued that on balance trade with
China is preferable to the hard-line position taken by Bauer
because it opens China to possible democratization and helps the
American economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you something,'' Bush said. ``Opening up the
Chinese market is good for our farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also won applause for his answer to a question posed by the
moderators, Brokaw and local television anchor John Bachman, on
philosophers they admire. After Forbes talked about British
philosopher John Locke and Thomas Jefferson, Bush answered
``Christ, because he changed my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates seemed to agree on one thing: Despite solid
economic prosperity, American morals are in a tailspin and only the
strong moral leadership of a Republican president can straighten
them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president of the United States ought to set a
moral tone in this country,'' Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first thing a president can and should do.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the debate was Alan Keyes, a former State Department
official who called for a ban on abortion. The debate was televised
on the MSNBC cable channel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
