u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-MARINO-N     12-13 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-MARINO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE CRITICISM, MARINO WILL START 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By CHARLES NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ As the airwaves in South Florida crackled with
criticism of the Miami Dolphins, particularly their celebrated
coach and veteran quarterback, Jimmy Johnson said Monday that he
was sticking with Dan Marino for Sunday's home game against San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Dan's our starting quarterback,'' Johnson said without
emotion at the team's practice facility. ``We've been inconsistent
at that position, but we feel like we can improve on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins lost to the Jets, 28-20, on Sunday and have become
a questionable playoff qualifier at 8-5 after a 7-1 start.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's loss, in which Marino was intercepted twice _
once for a touchdown _ and completed just 18 of 39 passes, Johnson
implied criticism of Marino by calling his offense ``hit and miss''
while claiming ``the running game wasn't the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was asked Monday about that veiled criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can just say right now, any time we turn the football over
more than our opponent, that's going to be a negative with me,
however we turn the ball over,'' he said. ``When you've got a tight
ballgame and you turn it over, you're going to have a difficult
time winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that on Aaron Glenn's interception of a Marino pass
early in the fourth quarter _ which he called perhaps the key play
of the game because Miami soon lost its lead _ the Jets were in a
three-deep zone and that Marino ``should have dumped the ball off
to the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino, 38, has been erratic since returning from a neck injury
on Thanksgiving Day against Dallas. He has presided over three
straight losses, and the interception returned 67 yards by safety
Omar Stoutmire in the fourth quarter Sunday was the fifth Marino
turnover this season that has been returned for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said his team played hard, just not effectively enough.
He walked out of his weekly news conference after less than 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly this is a trying time for Johnson, who won two Super
Bowls with Dallas but has been unable to win even a division title
with Miami in four years, quitting in frustration for a few days
after last season. He has been trying without success to remold
Marino, whose immobility and high-risk passing have not produced
the consistency Johnson covets, and their relationship has
suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the Jets' victory, after Marino had been removed
from the game by his coach for inefficiency, the former Dolphins
tight end Jim Mandich told a radio audience, ``Jimmy Johnson and
Dan Marino _ one of these guys is not going to be here next year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
