<HEADER>
A8020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-SHARIF-NYT &LR;      12-13 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-SHARIF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A COURTHOUSE, A SPECTACLE OF HOW THE MIGHTY HAVE FALLEN IN
PAKISTAN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARACHI, Pakistan _ Nawaz Sharif, Pakistan's ousted prime
minister, is a pale and plump man who long ago lost most of his
hair. Under the courtroom's severe fluorescent lights, he often
sits with a slump, his face given over to a grimace.
</P>
<P>
   Two months back, he and his six co-defendants were among the
country's most powerful people. Now they appear pitiful, trying to
face a future that is not what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Since an Oct. 12 military coup, these men have spent most of
their time in solitary confinement. Each time they are brought to
the stately British-era courthouse, they grimly plead for the
return of a few simple pleasures, asking the judge for a
television, a radio and a copy of the Koran. They also say they
want soft mattresses and food that is not slop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am forced to live like a caged animal,'' Sharif complained
once again Monday, describing the 7-by-10-foot stone-floor cell.
</P>
<P>
   His brother Shahbaz, the former chief minister of Punjab
Province, told the judge at a pretrial hearing: ``I am suffering
terrible back pain. I need exercise. It is inhumane.''
</P>
<P>
   Shahid Khakan Abbasi, the former director of the government
airline, said: ``We have not offered our prayers in nine weeks.
Even the Israelis allow their prisoners to say prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   So it goes on, Pakistan's great spectacle of how the mighty have
fallen. But there is no high drama here. People had reason to
expect much more in the way of courtroom theater.
</P>
<P>
   After all, these are onetime members of the ruling elite and
they are accused of conspiring to kill 198 people, hijacking a
jetliner, kidnapping an army general and plotting to wage war
against the state.
</P>
<P>
   Instead there have been weeks of procedural delays in beginning
the trial, which now seems unlikely to start before Dec. 27 at the
earliest.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution seems reluctant to share its evidence. The
defendants contend that is because of a paucity of supply. ``It's
all cooked up,'' Sharif opined of the case against him.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its shortcomings, the case has a riveting story line: a
crowded commercial aircraft was carrying Gen. Pervez Musharraf, the
army Chief of Staff, to Karachi on Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   He was as yet unaware that Sharif had fired him. The plane was
denied permission to land in Karachi. Finally, after some scary
airborne wandering, it was allowed to alight safely with a
near-empty gas tank _ but only after the military had staged a coup
and taken control of the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf, just days after appointing himself Pakistan's ``chief
executive,'' told the nation in a televised speech that Sharif and
his conspirators ``would have forced our plane either to land in
India or crash.'' He added: ``Providence ultimately intervened.
Praise be to Allah that the plane landed safely when barely seven
minutes of fuel was left.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, when the prosecution formally charged the seven
defendants, it turned over summaries of the statements of its own
53 witnesses _ the guts of its case.
</P>
<P>
   The collected stories make a sometimes-convoluted narrative and
one that could alternatively be read as the prime minister's
understandable efforts to head off a military coup after he
exercised his constitutional right to dismiss the army chief.
</P>
<P>
   Memories differ about the timing of events, and it is often
unclear who said what to whom at key moments. But witnesses seem to
agree that Sharif replaced his army chief by 5 p.m. on Oct. 12 and
that within the next 90 minutes the military took control of the
state television station and moved to surround the prime minister's
residence.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, Sharif inquired about Musharraf's flight,
which was due in Karachi at 6:55 p.m. He wanted to divert the
plane, preferably out of the country _ to Muscat, in the United
Arab Emirates. But he was told that the aircraft lacked sufficient
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif then said that the plane might as well land in Karachi or
in nearby Nawabshah, says a statement by Zahid Mehmood, the
director of protocol at Sharif's house.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, there was some discussion about taking Musharraf
into custody. Finally, it was decided that no one should be taken
from the plane or allowed to leave. The flight was to be refueled
and sent on to Muscat.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the plane, things were tense, the statements say.
The general and his aides were in the cockpit, making snap
decisions as instructions from the ground kept changing. As late as
6:53 p.m., the pilot was still being told he could not land in
Pakistan, said an air traffic controller, Manzoor Ahmed.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal ended with a safe landing at 7:48. Musharraf left the
airliner, suddenly confronted with the option of governing this
nation of 140 million people. He decided, as he would say later,
that he viewed this as ``his destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's attorneys _ and some of his political confidantes _
raise questions about the timing of such destiny. Some contend that
a coup had been in the works for months. A few even argue that the
rebellion began as early as 10 a.m. and that the prime minister
fired Musharraf in reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, though, Sharif himself disputed that notion. In a brief
conversation before the hearing, he said, ``The coup began minutes
after the notification was issued'' of the general's dismissal.
``The army knew to head for the TV station and to refuse to allow
the news to be broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the sequence of events on Oct. 12 does not seem of great
interest in Pakistan _ or at least not in the press.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has there been much protest about the solitary confinement
for the prisoners or about the ``protective custody'' of military
officers who were part of Sharif's inner circle on Oct. 12,
including Lt. Gen. Khwaja Ziauddin, the man Sharif had selected to
be his new army chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   In a few moments, court was in session and the famous
co-defendants were taking their turns begging for improved
treatment in the district jail. If they would be allowed
television, they said, they would gladly pay for the sets and leave
them behind as gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, who has been sympathetic to such requests, agreed to
this scheme, but the prosecutor, Raja Quershi, resisted until
finally, exasperated, he proclaimed, ``OK, let them have their
TVs.'' Then later, again nettled by the incessant complaints, the
prosecutor once more crankily relented. ``Yes, OK,'' he said. ``And
they can have their Korans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
