<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ING-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ING'S $10 BILLION BID  _  AND RETRACTION _ PUSHES SHARES OF A
FRENCH BANK UP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: The Netherlands, France, Belgium, Britain)   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Shares in one of the most profitable midsize French
banks, Credit Commercial de France, surged Friday after the ING
Groep, the biggest Dutch financial services group, first made and
then withdrew a $10 billion takeover bid.
</P>
<P>
   ING, which has been on a shopping spree in recent years,
withdrew the bid early Monday after detecting what a spokesman
called a ``lack of enthusiasm'' on the part of Credit Commercial
management.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman, Ruud Polet, said that ``anything may happen now''
and that executives of both banks would see each other on Thursday,
when Credit Commercial's board is scheduled to meet in Paris.
Godfried van der Lugt, the acquisition-minded chief executive of
ING, which holds a 19.2 percent share in Credit Commercial, is a
director.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, in a letter from Van der Lugt to Credit Commercial's
management, ING offered to pay 137.5 euros in cash, or $139.34, a
premium of almost 15 percent to Credit Commercial's closing price
on Friday, valuing the bank at more than $10 billion. ING withdrew
that offer after Credit Commercial's board decided at an emergency
session late Sunday to publish it. Credit Commercial said its board
could not take immediate action, given that ING's offer was made
``suddenly, and without consultation.''
</P>
<P>
   Polet, the ING spokesman, said ING did not view Credit
Commercial's action as a rejection. Rather, it decided to withdraw
the offer because of a ``kind of lack of enthusiasm, a lack of
conviction, that made us think it was not the right moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Trading in shares of Credit Commercial was suspended Monday on
the Paris exchange until two hours after the market opened, and the
stock price surged more than 5 percent within minutes of the
resumption of trading, appearing to reflect a conviction among
investors that ING would sweeten its offer. Shares of Credit
Commercial rose 6.2 euros, or 5.2 percent, to 126 euros. In
Amsterdam, ING fell 0.60 euro, to 56.40 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they expected ING to pursue its courtship of
Credit Commercial, the sixth-largest French bank by assets and one
of the most profitable. Thanks to a strong retail business and the
profitability of a fund unit, Banque de Louvre, Credit Commercial
has reported earnings increases in each of the last 12 years, an
unusual record among French banks. Last month, Credit Commercial
said third-quarter profit rose 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If a renewed bid succeeds, the move would provide another
example of European cross-border bank consolidation, an area ING
has pioneered. In recent years, ING bought Barings of Britain,
Banque Bruxelles Lambert of Belgium and BHF-Bank of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Czepliewicz, a bank analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in
London, said there was ``no fundamental divergence of views''
between the two banks' managements and that he thought the bid
would be renewed. Credit Commercial, a midsize high-quality bank
available for a reasonable price, neatly fits ING's acquisition
pattern and would give it a foothold in the French market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One possible rival bidder, KBC Bancassurance of Belgium, the
second-largest shareholder in Credit Commercial with an 18.2
percent share, said today that it would not make a competing offer.
Swiss Life, the third-largest shareholder with 14.7 percent, said
it would not comment. KBC is a unit of Almanij.
</P>
<P>
   Charles de Croisset, Credit Commercial's chairman and chief
executive, has said in the past that he was open to discussion of a
merger, and in October he reacted to news reports of a possible
takeover bid for the bank by hiring as advisers Rothschild &AMP;
Compagnie and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ING is being advised by
J.P. Morgan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
