<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8113 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     12-13 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROWING THE BOOK AT KOBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If all you want for Christmas is to trade places
with Kobe Bryant, if you'd go to the North Pole and back to be able
to give him your student-loan payment book in exchange for his
black book with Michael Jordan's phone number in it and prom date
Brandy's and fellow adidas client Peyton Manning's, then you really
ought to ask Santa for author Roland Lazenby's latest work, ``Mad
Game.'' Subtitled, ``The NBA Education of Kobe Bryant,'' the
313-page biography is proof that there is no such thing as a
charmed life.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Bryant has a free pass from gravity that's not expected to
expire anytime soon, a $71 million contract with the Los Angeles
Lakers, his own signature sneaker and a rap album that's set for
release in March.
</P>
<P>
   He's like Mike, all right. But as Lazenby's book makes
startlingly clear, Bryant, 21, also is like you and me, tiptoeing
around hostile co-workers and getting blamed for every little thing
that goes wrong on the job and knowing at least one of the smiling
faces he sees every day is trashing him behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   We already knew Bryant was young and headstrong. We knew he was
clean-cut and conscientious and, yes, cocky, sometimes attempting
too much on the court because in his mind no play is impossible to
pull off. Until we got to page 230 of Lazenby's book, though, we
had no idea Bryant ``is a little prick is what he is.''
</P>
<P>
   That fetching description came courtesy of someone Lazenby
identifies only as a longtime Lakers employee. Lazenby's source _
for our purposes he'll heretofore be known as Sore Throat _
unleashes enough vitriol to poison popular opinion on Bryant on
page after page. The source complains that Bryant ``has this
attitude: You may be Shaquille O'Neal but I'm Kobe Bryant. I'm
every bit the player you are plus some.''
</P>
<P>
   Sore Throat also describes how the Lakers assembled for
players-only meetings at various times throughout last year's
truncated season to address Bryant's selfishness on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Tellingly, nowhere is it mentioned whether or not O'Neal's
insistence on shooting off-balance shots while double-teamed or
holding onto defensive rebounds to slow the fast break was likewise
addressed at these gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the allegiance of this unidentified source is so easy to
discern, by the time Lazenby gets around to describing this person
as someone ``close to O'Neal,'' this reader's reaction was, Do you
think????
</P>
<P>
   Bryant sighed after practice the other day when some of Sore
Throat's quotes were read back to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you see what I have to put up with,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   If Lamar Odom is smart he'll go to school on Bryant, and we're
not talking on the court tonight when Odom's Clippers play host to
the Lakers at the Staples Center in the first meeting of the two
phenoms.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, 20, has them all smiling in Clipperville now. It's early
yet. Just wait until Odom delivers a breakout performance in an
All-Star Game and the NBA develops eyes only for him and then we'll
measure the temperature in the Clippers' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't have to be an investigative reporter to deduce the
Lakers were a team divided last year under coach Del Harris and his
replacement, Kurt Rambis. And yet even Bryant was taken aback when
he read the galleys of the book and realized how deep the fissure
was.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash doesn't bother him as much as it baffles him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think whoever was the source of those quotes might have some
serious issues,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the quotes do seem so spiteful as to seem unreal. When
Sore Throat talks about how the one constant in last year's chaotic
season was ``the team's dislike of Kobe'' or that when things go
badly ``it's never Kobe's fault,'' it struck this reader as so
skewed it might as well have been made up.
</P>
<P>
   Lazenby, though, is adamant; he is no Edmund Morris, mixing fact
with fiction in order to buttress a biographical tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a made-up person,'' Lazenby said Monday when reached
at the Virginia Tech campus in Blacksburg where he teaches
journalism classes. ``My source is a very real person who was
reflecting an attitude that was prevalent in the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazenby, who has written a handful of sports books, including
one on the Lakers that was published in 1993, spent months hanging
out with last season's team. The thesis he formed over time, he
said, was, ``Get off Kobe's back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the attitudes I saw infuriated me, too,'' Lazenby
said. ``My point in writing this book was to have the reader say,
`Wow! Look at the attitudes Kobe has had to battle against.''
</P>
<P>
   Those, on top of all the pressures he had to deal with coming to
the NBA straight out of high school and being labeled a knight in
teen-ager's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy being compared to Michael Jordan. When Jordan was
Bryant's age, he wasn't the player who would redefine the game,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant understands he's a work in progress. He's the first one
to admit he has a lot of learning left to do.
</P>
<P>
   In basketball circles his type is called ``coachable.'' Let's
just say there are a lot worse raps.
</P>
<P>
   There's a passage in Lazenby's book in which Sore Throat says of
Bryant, ``When Kobe makes a turnover it totally deflates the whole
team ... because he doesn't make a turnover trying to help the team
win. He makes a turnover out of selfishness.''
</P>
<P>
   The quote was one of a few relayed to Bryant two days after he
committed six turnovers in a loss to Sacramento. He didn't flinch.
He didn't wince. He said matter-of-factly, ``Some of what was said
(in the book) might have had some truth to it.''
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it. In one sentence Bryant owned up to more
missteps than many of his colleagues will in any one season.
</P>
<P>
   Under Phil Jackson, the Lakers have looked more fraternal than
fractious. Bryant, though, continues to proceed cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer he toiled the nights away in a recording studio,
cutting a rap album. Not surprisingly, trust emerged as a recurring
theme in his songs. To read ``Mad Game'' is to better understand
why.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
