<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EURO-AUTO-TRENDS-2TAK     12-13 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-AUTO-TRENDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORT UTILITY VEHICLES RE-ENGINEERED FOR THE OLD WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A typical ad for a Hyundai Galloper reads like a zoology
text: ``Strong and Savage, Lives in Cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Motor and other automakers have introduced such ads to
persuade Europeans to buy an unlikely animal, a native of North
America that has been bred successfully in the Far East and is now
spreading to the narrow lanes and congested cities of Western
Europe: the sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomical gas prices and a tradition of compact cars would
seem to make most of Europe less hospitable than the United States
to sport utilities. Yet Europeans _ to the delight of auto industry
executives but to the dismay of environmentalists and traffic
planners _ are taking to the vehicles in a big way, moving up from
their midget Fiat Cinquecentos and Renault Twingos.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, many of the models sold in Europe, sometimes
modified versions of their trans-Atlantic kin, are smaller and more
fuel-efficient than the behemoths found on American roads. But some
larger models are also attracting buyers.
</P>
<P>
   After several years of relative stability, European sales of the
high-riding sport utilities surged 26 percent last year, four times
the rate of the overall passenger vehicle market, to 464,400. This
year, they are expected to grow another 21 percent, to roughly
564,200, again four times the pace of the overall market.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that number represents only about 3.7 percent of the
total number of new passenger vehicles registered, far lower than
in the United States, where last year sport utilities made up 16
percent of the market. The growth in Europe last year and this year
was fueled by the introduction of new models like the Land Rover
Freelander, the new Honda HR-V and the General Motors Corp.'s
updated Frontera from its Opel division, all smaller than the
standard sport utility and hence better attuned to European roads.
And with virtually every major manufacturer preparing an entry or
already selling one, Europe's flirtation with sport utilities is
expected to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still latent demand in Western Europe for this
thing,'' said Nigel Griffith, an analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI
in London. ``There are still cowboys out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, General Motors replaced its old Frontera, which was
essentially an Isuzu Rodeo for the European market, and sold 25,000
of the new model. This year, it expects to sell 37,000 Fronteras,
which are built at a factory in Britain. In just the first eight
months of this year, Honda Motor sold more than 17,000 HR-V's, its
new sporty, two-door hatchback similar to the CR-V in the United
States, lifting its total European sales of sport utility vehicles
to more than 41,000 _ almost as many as it sold in Europe in all of
last year. And Land Rover, part of the BMW-owned Rover Group, sold
more than 40,000 Freelanders last year, the model's first year.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by such successes, Fiat Auto announced this summer
that it would invest $122 million in a joint venture with
Mitsubishi Motors to build a sport utility at a factory outside
Turin, Italy. Renault of France says that early next year it will
introduce a utility, its first since bowing out of Jeep 12 years
ago when it sold its controlling stake in American Motors to
Chrysler. And Ford Motor is planning a downsized sport utility
vehicle next year that will be more fuel efficient than the
Explorer, its smallest model now, in part to meet the mounting
European competition.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the offerings for the more pampered European
motorists. The Mercedes-Benz unit of DaimlerChrysler had such
success in Europe with its M-class utility, which is assembled in
Alabama mainly for the North American market, that it started
production of the M-class in July at a factory in Graz, Austria. In
Italy, Mitsubishi is manufacturing the Pajero Pinin, an upscale
model that it developed with the Italian design house Pininfarina.
BMW has decided to introduce a European version of its new luxury
X5, which goes on sale in the United States in December.
</P>
<P>
   To outdo them all, Volkswagen plans to trot out its first two
sport utilities by 2002. One, a mid-priced Volkswagen, will be
built at a factory in Slovakia, while a more expensive version that
is part of a joint venture with Porsche will be assembled at the
same factory, then gussied up with a fancy Porsche interior and a
more powerful engine at a factory Porsche is building in Leipzig,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Because European roads are smaller than in the United States and
gas prices higher, automakers have bred a miniature species of
sport utilities for Europe. Honda's new two-door HR-V, for
instance, at 13 feet 6 inches, is 28 inches shorter than the Ford
Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities imported from the United States are trimmed to meet
European tastes and requirements. Chrysler, which imports the
Wrangler and the Cherokee from the United States, and assembles the
Grand Cherokee at the factory in Austria where Mercedes makes the
M-class, builds different seats and a stiffer suspension into its
European cars and installs wipers and lights that conform to
European standards.
</P>
<P>
   Because of high gas prices (in Italy, for example, unleaded gas
can cost more than $4.50 a gallon), many sport utility vehicles in
Europe have diesel engines, since diesel fuel is cheaper. And most
European utilities have 4-cylinder engines, which use less gas than
the V6 or big V8 engines in comparable American models.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the sport utility was dreamed up by
American automakers as essentially a pickup truck with a roof over
the bed and extra rows of seats, and then successfully copied by
Japanese manufacturers. In Europe, by contrast, it was first
popularized by the Japanese, who created the market by introducing
smaller, more economical utility they had designed for congested
Asian cities, and then copied by other automakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese created the market from scratch,'' said Daniel T.
Jones, a professor of auto industry management at the Cardiff
University business school in Wales. ``And everyone piled in behind
the Japanese.''
</P>
<P>
   European automakers like the SUV for the same reason their
American counterparts do: fat cars make fat profits. Yet the
growing competition in Europe, as more and more models flood the
market, has depressed profit margins below those in the United
States. Moreover, small production runs, usually of 30,000 to
40,000 vehicles, prevent the economies of scale that benefit
manufacturers in the United States, where runs are often five to
six times that size.
</P>
<P>
   To keep costs down, Jones said, the Europeans often share
development costs with partners and borrow equipment from existing
models. Thus, the platform for Renault's new sport utility will be
adapted from its highly successful Scenic line of cars. The
mechanical equipment for Fiat's new entry will come from
Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the automakers charge far higher prices in Europe for
the same models they sell in the United States. A Chrysler Grand
Cherokee, for instance, sells for up to 300,000 francs in France,
or more than $46,000, compared with about $35,000 in the United
States. The manufacturers explain the difference by citing
transportation costs, European taxes, and the expense of outfitting
the cars to meet European standards. European consumers don't seem
discouraged from buying.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, so many luxury carmakers are rushing into the market
that a new category of high-priced, high-performance sport utility
vehicle is emerging _ populated with the likes of BMW's X5,
Mercedes-Benz's M-class and Porsche's planned offering _ that is
blurring the very definition of a utility. Thomas Zauber, a BMW
spokesman in Munich, emphasized that ``we don't say sport utility
vehicle, we say sport activity vehicle, as opposed to off-road
varieties.'' BMW, he said, believes that ``the market is beginning
to differentiate, and we believe it's going to grow in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, said Griffith of DRI, ``the market is about a
statement of self-image, what people want to project to other
people, and not just about moving from point A to point B.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you call the vehicles, more and more Europeans are
buying them, and for much the same reasons as their Americans
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got maximum safety, even if going off-road to pick
mushrooms,'' said Mario Roccabella, who drives a Suzuki Vitara, a
small utility. Indeed, Roccabella, a 48-year-old auto salesman in
Rome, got so hooked on his own vehicle several years ago that he
began selling several brands, including Land Rovers, Mitsubishis
and Subarus, and now organizes rallies for S.U.V. owners. Even in
labyrinthine Rome, he said, sport utilities abound, offering
greater vision because of their height, and a relatively smooth
ride ``even though the streets are made of Swiss cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental objections to the vehicles have not yet arisen,
and some countries, like Italy _ now one of the hottest markets _
have even abolished taxes they once levied on off-road vehicles to
discourage their spread, under pressure from automakers as well as
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Some automakers and environmentalists cite the relatively low
market share of sport utility vehicles, their smaller size in
Europe and greater fuel efficiency as reasons an environmental
debate has not erupted in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some European motorists are already griping about sport
utility drivers who hog the road in extremely congested cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it very much the way they look down at you from
so high up,'' said Ann-Henri Le Gouvello, 55, who owns a soup
company in Rambouillet, France, and who uses a four-door
Mercedes-Benz 300GE _ hardly a subcompact _ to drive to Paris or go
hunting near his Rambouillet home. He sniffed at what he deemed
pretentious city dwellers in their showy all-wheel drive vehicles,
saying, ``They use them to drive only in the city, and they never
leave the road with them.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite fears that too many of the vehicles are on the
drawing board, the automakers are accelerating their plans,
pointing not only to growth in Europe but the potential for export.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Reuter, a spokesman for Ford Europe, said its new, smaller
model was designed for North America, Europe and Asia. Volkswagen
expects to sell some of its new Volkswagen and Porsche utilities
abroad; roughly half the 20,000 Porsches it will build will be sold
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never would have done it just for Europe,'' said Griffith
of Standard &AMP; Poor's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
