<HEADLINE>
TOP ATHLETES COUNTDOWN IS A BIG STEP UP FOR ESPN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've watched ESPN's ``SportsCentury'' countdown, your
choices for the century's greatest North American athletes may
differ from the cable network's. But who ranks where is irrelevant
_ except as fodder for amusing debates that go nowhere _ because
the 50 profiles stand as ESPN's most creative work in its 20-year
history. They, not their order, demand attention.
</P>
<P>
   They're packed with surprises (an old friend of Lou Gehrig's
weeping in remembrance), distinguished by balance and enterprise in
finding people who are not the usual interview suspects, and made
memorable by a sensual visual style.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Jack Nicklaus entry. In the five-minute opening
segment, cameras slowly wash over the Scottish links of St.
Andrews, and the Irish course at Turnberry, to convey golf's
ancient history and the meaning of the British Open to Nicklaus.
This storytelling device transports you to where golf began, and
offers an unexpected window into Nicklaus' psychology. ``I like the
old stuff, what was,'' Nicklaus says. Recalling Nicklaus' victory
at the 1970 British Open at St. Andrews, Tom Jarrett, the course
historian, says in a voice made for golf, ``He took off his
pullover, opened his shoulders and slammed a mighty shot onto the
18th hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking forward to Nicklaus' appearance in next year's British
Open at the historic links, the Royal and Ancient Club's Michael
Bonallack says, ``Everyone will have a tingle down the spine. I'll
bet Jack will have a tear in his eye.''
</P>
<P>
   This sort of editorial decision alters expectations for a
television profile. How much more can you know or feel about a
great athlete? More, this series proves.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to open the Nicklaus profile in Scotland is a
reminder of other smart choices, like focusing on races lost by the
hurdler Edwin Moses, not the 122 he won consecutively.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's profile of Jim Thorpe, which opens with a nighttime
tribal Indian dance, is the saddest of the 50 in ESPN's series:
from the schools that wrung the American Indian heritage from
youngsters like Thorpe to his burial in a town he never saw, but
which paid his widow for the right to change its name to his.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe's Olympic and baseball feats are recounted, but serve as
prologue to his being stripped of his 1912 Olympic gold medals for
playing minor league baseball to his slide into obscurity as a
bouncer, ditch digger and movie extra. There is more eloquence in
the people interviewed for this profile than in any other because
of the bittersweet subject. Skip Rozin, a writer, on Thorpe's
post-athletic career: ``Like soldiers who can't deal with
peacetime, here is a man who couldn't live without sports.''
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Grace Thorpe: ``I remember dropping him off for
him to pick up the bus and the bus stop was right in the middle of
the theater and the marquee was right where I dropped him off. I
waved at him and right up there it said, `Jim Thorpe,
All-American.' And that's the last I saw of Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to judge the craft of a ``SportsCentury'' profile is to
compare it to a longer documentary about the same subject.
</P>
<P>
   Take Johnny Unitas. The great Baltimore Colt quarterback was
ESPN's subject earlier this year, and HBO's last week in a
60-minute documentary done with NFL Films as part of its league
deal to continue producing the weekly program, ``Inside the NFL''
</P>
<P>
   Unitas is prickly and unreflective, letting his gridiron feats
speak for a life he says little about. Both works capture Unitas
but the ``SportsCentury'' profile grasps him equally well in less
than half the time. Many of the stories are the same _ his anger at
being cut by the PIttsburgh Steelers, his problems with Coach Don
Shula's hollering style and his late entrance into Super Bowl III
against the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Each features interviews with teammates and opponents but ESPN
shows more enterprise: snaring an assistant coach at Louisville,
where Unitas played; a teammate on the semipro team he played for
after the Steelers cut him; his brother, Leonard, and his sister,
Shirley. Her memory of their widowed mother's philosophy says much
about the man Unitas became. ``If you had a need, it would be
discussed,'' she says. ``If it was a want, she didn't want to hear
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO devotes more time to the beloved place Unitas held in 1950s
and 1960's Baltimore _ sounding very similar to that of the Dodgers
in Brooklyn _ and made generous use of NFL archives. Despite the
league connection, HBO notes Unitas' failed campaign to receive
league disability benefits for an elbow injury suffered in 1968
that has rendered his right thumb and index finger unusable.
</P>
<P>
   The HBO documentary also recalls a macho story of Unitas' being
hammered to the turf in a game against Chicago. His face, upper lip
and nose bloodied, he threw a game-winning touchdown pass. ``That's
no big deal,'' he says. ``I don't throw with my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, neither work discusses his wife or children, and
only ESPN's details his many business failures, including losing
his Colts consulting job because he handicapped for a gambling tip
sheet. ``He was too trusting, that's all,'' says Leonard Unitas.
</P>
<P>
   Now ESPN faces a new test: as the countdown heads to No. 1, it
will be fascinating to see how well-chronicled lives like Muhammad
Ali's, Babe Ruth's and Michael Jordan's can be freshened up. Expect
the unexpected. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
