<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-MEMO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT'S PLATE PILED WITH TOUGH ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In its last term, the Supreme Court breezed through
75 decisions and finished its work on June 23, for the earliest
closing in 30 years. This term, the justices will also decide about
75 cases, but at the rate they are going now they will be lucky to
make it home by next Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   The court began its end-of-year recess Monday, having decided
only two cases since the term began on the first Monday of October.
That compares with an average of more than eight cases the court
had decided by this time in the preceding 10 terms.
</P>
<P>
   Equally telling, the court in recent years has been issuing its
first opinions in the first few days of November. This term, the
first opinions that actually decided cases (there was one earlier
ruling that simply asked the Pennsylvania Supreme Court to advise
the court on a question of Pennsylvania law raised by a pending
case) did not come until Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   But telling of what? Impending gridlock? An obvious possibility.
Sleeping on the job? Emphatically not. Far from shirking its
responsibilities, the court has arguably taken on too much, and is
in the position of a boy with eyes too big for his stomach and too
many desserts piled on his plate. The reason the justices have
decided so few cases is almost surely that they have so many hard,
sharply contested and terrifically important ones on their plate.
</P>
<P>
   Case by case, exercising the discretion that permits them to
turn down 99 cases for every one they decide to hear, the justices
have been constructing a term fit for the millennium, in which many
of the most important principles of constitutional law are up for
review.
</P>
<P>
   FEDERALISM: There are six cases on the docket that address the
validity of the country's essential structural arrangements. The
cases test everything from the states' authority to carry out their
own views of foreign policy to the authority of Congress to make
states accountable for civil rights violations. Three of the
federalism cases have been argued and remain undecided; if the
recent past is a guide, the votes will be very close and the
dissenting opinions bitter.
</P>
<P>
   RACE: It is a safe guess that an unusual case from Hawaii about
an election open only to descendants of the native Hawaiians,
argued in the first week of the term and still undecided, has
struck at least some justices as raising broader questions of
racial preferences in public policy.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION: It is too soon to expect a decision in a case argued
this month that opens the door to revisiting old debates about
government aid to religious schools. Meanwhile, the justices have
agreed to take a new look at organized school prayer, in the
context of students' petitions for God's blessing on public high
school football games.
</P>
<P>
   FREE SPEECH: A Missouri case on whether the $1,000 limit on
campaign contributions is too restrictive of political speech was
argued on the second day of the term and remains undecided as the
election calendar moves forward. A case on the First Amendment
implications of mandatory student activity fees was argued in early
November, as was a case on nude dancing as a form of protected
expression. This month, the court heard a case on federal limits on
indecent programming on cable television, a question that
essentially defeated the justices when they last tried to tackle it
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   DUE PROCESS: A case to be argued next month on whether states
can give grandparents and others the right to petition for
visitation with children who are not their own, over the parents'
objections, raises intriguing questions of due process and parental
rights.
</P>
<P>
   PRISONERS' RIGHTS: If the world knows anything about the current
term, it is that the justices have the opportunity, in an appeal
they accepted last week, to reconsider the 33-year-old Miranda
decision.
</P>
<P>
   While Dickerson vs. United States may be the highest profile
case of the term, it is not necessarily the most challenging, even
in the area of criminal law, for a court that has not displayed any
particular appetite for revisiting Miranda. On the first day of the
term, the justices heard their most important case so far under the
1996 law that limited state prisoners' access to federal courts.
That case remains undecided. A challenge to Florida's continued use
of the electric chair presents an interesting task to a court that
is deeply divided over the meaning of cruel and unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the hard cases are scattered throughout the year _ the
electric chair case will be argued in February _ the term seemed
disproportionately front-loaded. Of the 10 cases argued in October,
most appeared preordained to produce the sharp divisions that,
inferring from the court's delay, they evidently have. But some of
these cases raise issues that have not been conclusively resolved
in more than 200 years of the country's history. That the Supreme
Court has not managed to wrap them up neatly in three months should
be the occasion for neither blame nor surprise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
