<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FASSEL'S RUN ORIGINATED WITH A TIRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ First of all, let's set the record
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to popular belief, the Giants are not undefeated in the
month of December since Jim Fassel became coach. True, they have
won all nine regular-season games in December, but they also lost a
playoff game to the Minnesota Vikings in that month in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 9-0 under any kind of condition _ home games, grass
games, day games, games against losing teams _ is admirable for any
coach, any team. No wonder people overlook that 23-22 loss to the
Vikings in Fassel's first season.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel was asked Monday why his team excels when the weather
gets damp and chilly in the swamplands. He declined to offer any
fanciful full-moon theories, or credit any exotic meteorological or
horoscope factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They only remember what you do in December,'' he recited, a
little ditty suggesting December is generally the month when teams
either qualify for the playoffs or go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time of year is the toughest part of the schedule,''
Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly is for the Giants, with three contenders _ St.
Louis, Minnesota and Dallas _ looming. The Giants can qualify for
the playoffs by winning all three games, which will not be easy,
but at least they have the streak going for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those things written about us, they start believing in
them,'' Fassel said Monday after giving the players a day off after
the 19-17 victory at Buffalo. ``You start to take the field
believing in yourself, but they make it happen,'' he said. ``It's
not just a matter of reading your clips.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he remembered how the streak began, Fassel deliberated
and allowed as how he vaguely remembered something.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first year, we played poorly in one game; I went into the
next zone,'' Fassel just happened to recall. ``This was a time when
you could fold your tents. I went way beyond. It was ugly. But they
responded. So I said, `Hey, maybe I don't have to go there
again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel got it exactly right. It all dates back to Nov. 30, 1997,
when the Giants lost to Tampa Bay, 20-8, and Fassel closed the
locker room. In the next day's paper, Bill Pennington of The New
York Times reported that Fassel had been ``emptying his opinions
and his emotions in a red-faced harangue that threatened the jobs
of starting players on the team's feeble offensive unit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In shouts that filled the Giants' cavernous dressing
quarters,'' Pennington continued, ``Fassel also told the team that
it may have lost its hunger at the worst possible time: in a
playoff hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach did not hide his feelings from the news media after
that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with the way we played the football game,''
Fassel told reporters. ``We're not hitting on any cylinders. There
were mental mistakes, a lack of execution, a lack of
aggressiveness. It was a very disappointing loss.''
</P>
<P>
   After Fassel's outburst, a few defensive players headed off bad
feelings toward the unproductive offensive unit. The coach himself
threatened Danny Kanell with demotion from starting quarterback,
and eventually Kanell and Dave Brown were purged, while the Giants
have not lost a regular-season game in December since. Fassel has
not repeated his diatribe, which he said was totally spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do a lick of calculation,'' Fassel said Monday. ``I
don't act like I'm ticked. They can see it. They can tell if you
are play-acting. I always speak my heart. They're with me too much.
They could get tired of it. They know when I'm mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in his third season, Fassel does not seem to make his
players' eyes glaze when he talks. Percy Ellsworth, one of the
safeties, said he had been wondering, ``What can he say to make me
come out and fight?' Ellsworth found out: ``It was amazing. He came
in both times and was able to rally the troops. I don't know how he
did it, but he knew the exact right things to say and we all came
out fighting. It has to be him. He never gives up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel has faced another offense-defense rift, which he defused
by confronting Michael Strahan, the chief critic. Fassel has once
again shifted quarterbacks, from Kent Graham to Kerry Collins. And
he said Monday that he had more time for the mood of the team
``since I gave up some duties with play calling,'' to Sean Payton,
his quarterbacks coach.
</P>
<P>
   Because the season began late this year, the final game at
Dallas game will take place two days into the new century. The
Giants have not yet played in January under Fassel, but they are
about to find out if the December touch has any carry-over value. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
