<HEADLINE>
FOUR TEAMS SWING NINE-PLAYER TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ In his relatively short tenure as the Oakland
Athletics' general manager, Billy Beane had never held such power
in his hands. ``I can blow this whole thing apart,'' he told
colleagues in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   But Beane was only joking. He had to supply the last piece of
the puzzle Monday, and he was not going to withhold it. He agreed
to trade Jimmy Haynes to the Milwaukee Brewers, and the first
four-team trade in 14 years was complete.
</P>
<P>
   With Beane playing the most crucial though least significant
role in terms of the player he included and the one he got back,
the Brewers, the Colorado Rockies, the Tampa Bay Devil Rays and the
Athletics sent nine players and $1.05 million in various
helter-skelter directions.
</P>
<P>
   The most direct part of the unusual and intricate transaction
had the Rockies trading Vinny Castilla, their good-hitting third
baseman, to the Devil Rays for Rolando Arrojo, a pitcher, and Aaron
Ledesma, a utility infielder. The Rockies also sent Jamey Wright, a
young starting pitcher, and Henry Blanco, a good defensive catcher,
to the Brewers for Jeff Cirillo, a .300-hitting third baseman, and
Scott Karl, a left-handed pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   To secure Haynes as a second starting pitcher the Brewers
wanted, the Rockies gave the Athletics a minor league pitcher,
Justin Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Dan O'Dowd, the Rockies' new general manager, who hit the ground
trading, was the driving force behind the four-team transaction,
and officials of other teams generally credited him with gaining
the most from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Cirillo, whose .326 batting average was fifth best in the
National League last season, and Castilla, who in the past five
seasons has batted better than .300 four times and averaged 38 home
runs and 112 runs batted in, were the best-known names in the
bunch.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays, who seldom have made trades in their two-year
existence, acquired Castilla to bolster one of the American
League's weakest offenses. Later in the day the Devil Rays added to
their lineup, signing Greg Vaughn, a home run hitting free agent,
to a four-year, $34 million contract. The Mets had expressed some
interest in Vaughn but not at that rate.
</P>
<P>
   Castilla and Vaughn, who hit 95 home runs the past two seasons,
join Fred McGriff and Jose Canseco in the middle of the Tampa Bay
lineup. Cirillo will become the cleanup hitter in a Colorado lineup
that O'Dowd has overhauled in an attempt to make it a
multidimensional threat. The general manager previously traded
Dante Bichette, another of the Rockies' sluggers, to Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly,'' Dean Taylor, the Milwaukee general manager,
said, ``Dan and I have been working on the basic structure of this
deal for the better part of six weeks. As we satisfied each other
and expanded the deal to make it work, everyone worked hard to get
it done.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Dowd said the deal began as a three-team trade involving the
Rockies, the Brewers and the St. Louis Cardinals. But that one fell
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tampa Bay had specific interest in Castilla,'' O'Dowd said.
``We knew we had to come up with two pitchers for Milwaukee. We
didn't want to trade the second pitcher ourselves because it would
eliminate the depth that we had worked so hard to acquire with the
Darryl Kile deal. So we went on a shopping spree over the last week
and a half to try to get that second pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal was on and off a dozen times. You have to keep in
mind, Milwaukee, Tampa Bay, the Rockies and Oakland were exploring
other possibilities. As late as last evening, this thing could have
easily not happened.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Dowd engineered the final piece after Taylor gave him a list
of five pitchers the Brewers would consider as the second starter
they wanted. ``Four were unrealistic,'' O'Dowd said without
identifying them. Haynes was the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got the list, we had done our due diligence,'' O'Dowd
said. ``We knew what pitching was available and not available in
the industry. When I got the list, I had already talked to those
clubs. I waited a little bit because I knew Billy was exploring
other options. I didn't want to get into paying that price yet. I
wanted to wait for these meetings. I also didn't want to jump into
something until I knew the other two pieces of the puzzle were
solidly in place. Oakland was the last piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Beane, O'Dowd said, ``really could have done some damage.'' But
he was not about to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relationships are part of making deals,'' Beane said. ``I'm
very close to Danny. It's not a part of a favor bank, but we
weren't going to sit there and blow this entire deal apart just
because we were pig-headed.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, he added, he had planned to trade Haynes somewhere this
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great deal,'' Beane said. ``It was a fun deal to watch
even being somewhat on the periphery. The good thing about being
part of it was knowing what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time four teams joined in one trade was on Jan. 18,
1985. On that day the Brewers traded catcher Jim Sundberg to Kansas
City for catcher Don Slaught and pitcher Frank Wills. Then the
Brewers sent Wills to the Mets for pitcher Tim Leary and Slaught to
Texas for pitcher Danny Darwin and a player to be named, who later
became Bill Hance, a catcher, who never reached the major leagues. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
