<HEADLINE>
BRYANT, ODOM EXPECTED TO SQUARE OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A matchup that existed only on talk radio and in
the occasional newspaper column could become reality tonight. Kobe
Bryant and Lamar Odom, head to head.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers have already begun the debate which young phenom
will be the better player, the Lakers' Bryant or the Clippers'
Odom. But no one figured the two L.A. stars would get a chance to
prove themselves against one another because they played different
positions.
</P>
<P>
   That changed two days ago when Clippers coach Chris Ford moved
his multidimensional rookie from small forward to point guard. Now
Odom and Bryant are likely to guard each other when the Lakers and
Clippers meet tonight for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll be a real interesting matchup,'' Lakers coach Phil
Jackson said. ``I think the Clippers have made a move that's
progressive, it's obviously something where they have to fight (to
end) a losing streak and they're trying to make some changes in a
positive nature. This young man (Odom) looks like he distributes
the ball and is unselfish.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson could play spoiler, though. He said he ``might'' put Ron
Harper on Odom, instead of Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really looking forward to seeing him play,'' Jackson said
of Odom. ``I don't watch college basketball, I'll admit it. I saw
him play one time, it seems like two years ago, in the NCAAs, and I
was impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   No Air in L.A.: Michael Jordan enjoyed watching the Lakers beat
the Detroit Pistons on Sunday from the confines of owner Jerry
Buss' luxury suite. But Jordan said he has no intention of joining
the Lakers for an impromptu workout, as he did with the Chicago
Bulls last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not in any shape, not in basketball condition is what he
told me,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, he's not in shape to keep up with Bryant, his
presumed heir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he wasn't going to come to practice,'' Bryant said.
``We were talking about it the other day, I asked him if he was
going to come to practice. He said, `Hell no.' He said, `I've got
to get in shape.' He doesn't want to chase me around.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Glen Rice, who missed Sunday's game because of an
upper respiratory infection and 102-degree fever, skipped Monday's
practice as well. But Jackson said he hopes Rice will be available
for tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   If not, rookie Devean George might get his second NBA start.
George played only 15 minutes after starting Sunday's game, as Rick
Fox came off the bench to play 37 minutes and score a season-high
20 points. Jackson could start Fox, but seems to prefer keeping his
rotation intact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
