<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA INQUIRES AFTER VIZCAINO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ A day after moving $10.5 million of payroll in
one trade, the Los Angeles Dodgers are hoping to soon move another
significant piece to create more flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves general manager John Schuerholz spoke with
Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone about acquiring utility
infielder Jose Vizcaino for a pitching prospect, several sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides spoke at length about a possible deal during the
general manager's meetings last month and renewed talks at the
winter meetings. As was the case in trading Eric Young, the
financial aspect is key to the Vizcaino deal.
</P>
<P>
   Vizcaino, who wasted away on the bench last season, is slated to
make $3.5 million in 2000. At this point the Dodgers can't absorb
any of Vizcaino's salary in the deal, but that could change
shortly.
</P>
<P>
   An Atlanta official said the Braves like Vizcaino's versatility
as an infielder. He can play second, shortstop or third base, and
is a switch-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Vizcaino is also considered a good clubhouse guy, though the
Dodgers were disappointed he wasn't more of an influence last
season. Part of that was because he struggled in an unfamiliar
backup role and was unhappy. He hit .252 in 94 games.
</P>
<P>
   Two sources said the deal could be put on hold until the Adrian
Beltre case is resolved, noting the Dodgers may need Vizcaino to
play third, second or some combination in a platoon-type situation.
</P>
<P>
   However, even if the teams can't agree on a trade in the next
few days, both sources said the deal would likely be revisited
before or during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Finding Carlos: With Ismael Valdes traded away, it means lefty
Carlos Perez will come into spring training with a spot in the
rotation to lose rather than one to earn. It's a scary thought,
given that Perez was 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA last season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers are in the midst of sending a parade of
representatives to the Dominican Republic to keep a constant eye on
Perez, who has $12.5 million and two years remaining on his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant general manager Bill Geivett, senior vice president
Tom Lasorda and strength and conditioning coordinator Todd Claussen
each visited Perez. Pitching coach Claude Osteen and minor-league
pitching coordinator Jim Benedict are next on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy didn't show up in 1999, but we're optimistic he does
in 2000,'' Malone said. ``We're going to find him and bring him
home. He is in great shape, great attitude. That's the problem last
year. He came in kind of out of shape and overweight.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers don't like what they see from Perez, one option
is to send him to Triple-A Albuquerque. By keeping him in the
minors for two months near the end of last season, it made it so he
couldn't refuse a minor-league assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Malone reiterated what Dodgers chairman Bob Daly
said Sunday about the prospect of signing right-hander Orel
Hershiser to a free-agent contract: ``It's a long shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said Hershiser wants to start, but the Dodgers' need is
in the bullpen. Still, Malone thinks Hershiser will wear a Dodgers
uniform perhaps after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe with all my heart, he will be a Dodger again,''
Malone said. ``He has a lot to offer; quality person, a lot of
ability.''..The Dodgers lost 1996 first-round pick Damian Rolls,
22, and pitcher Adrian Burnside, 22, in the major-league portion of
the Rule 5 draft. Rolls, who played for Single-A Vero Beach last
season, was taken by Kansas City and then traded to Tampa Bay.
Burnside was taken by Cincinnati.
</P>
</TEXT>
