<SLUG> BC-ETHICS-SPENDING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER ETHICS COMMISSION OFFICIAL WANTS TO START COMPANY TO AID
LOBBYISTS IN FILING CAMPAIGN SPENDING REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ Two years after
Missouri campaign contributions and lobbyists' spending were
required to be computerized for easy public consumption, the system
is still not on line and is hindered by glitches that give many
users fits.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now, the Ethics Commission's former head of computer services,
who oversaw development of the long-delayed system, wants to set up
a company to charge lobbyists a fee to help them file their monthly
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mullett, who oversaw the commission's computer services
for nearly six years, abruptly resigned in late October, just as
lobbyists began trying to file their reports by computer.
</P>
<P>
   In a Nov. 1 letter, Mullett requested an Ethics Commission
opinion on whether state law allows him to contract with lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   The irony was not lost on critics of the commission's fruitless
attempts to put information on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just increases my desire to have the whole process turned
over to a different agency,'' said Democratic state Sen. John
Schneider of St. Louis County. ``Filing this information should be
simple enough that you don't need assistance. I hope complications
were not built into the system just so you need assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ethics Commission is scheduled to discuss the request and
issue an opinion today. Ethics Director Chuck Lamb said the staff
has recommended that the commission find Mullett's plan in
violation of state conflict-of-interest laws.
</P>
<P>
   The law prohibits employees from working for a private entity on
projects related to the work they did for the state. But the law
primarily relates to a prohibition on attempts to influence a
government decision. So it may allow the commission some wiggle
room.
</P>
<P>
   Mullett could not be reached Friday or Monday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   His request is the latest wrinkle in the long and twisted
history of the state's efforts to put campaign finance and lobbyist
spending on computer. The legislature enacted a law in 1994 that
required campaign contributions to be computerized beginning in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, it required lobbyists' reports to be filed
electronically beginning in 1998 and for the reports to be on the
Internet by January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Ethics Commission hired a California firm, SDR
Technologies Inc., to develop two kinds of software: One type would
allow campaigns and lobbyists to file information with the
commission; the second would allow the public to search and sort
the information on the commission's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But the process came under fire almost immediately. The Ethics
Commission underestimated the cost, which has grown to more than
$600,000.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors said the bids were rigged in SDR's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider's Senate Judiciary Committee held hearings and the
senator accused Mullett of lacking the expertise to oversee the
system. Mullett insisted that the bids were not written for one
company and his supervisors told Schneider they didn't think
Mullett needed a degree in computer science to oversee the project.
</P>
<P>
   When the software finally arrived in January 1998, it didn't
work.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon sued SDR for failing to
provide a usable product. SDR kept promising to deliver usable
software, but every version it sent was riddled with problems.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was settled last summer after an expert from the
University of Missouri-Kansas City analyzed the software and SDR
agreed to fix the remaining glitches. The first lobbyist filing
software went out last September. But it also has had minor
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The commission began requiring lobbyist reports to be filed
electronically in November. Mike Reid, the commission's compliance
director, said last week that the commission had received about
1,700 filings in November and December.
</P>
<P>
   Most lobbyists are filing successfully, though a few are still
having trouble with the software, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reports are still not available to the public because the
Internet portion of the contract was cut out to save money. The
state contracted with SDR in September to develop a system to put
the information on the commission's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Mullett quit in late October, just as the first filings were
about to start. He said at the time that his decision to leave had
nothing to do with the electronic filing project. He said he was
leaving to take a better job, but declined to identify his new
employer.
</P>
<P>
   In his request to the commission, Mullett argued that his job as
computer manager had no responsibility for regulating lobbyists. He
urged the commission to rule quickly so he could get the business
started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that my inquiry does not spawn numerous attempts
by others to begin a similar type of business,'' Mullett's letter
says.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider said he thought the statutes probably permit Mullett
to start the business. But the request just shows how badly botched
the whole process was.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the software did it right, no one would need assistance,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
