<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-OLDTIMERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PANAMA CANAL CELEBRITY HONORS UNHERALDED WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ The first ship to pass through the Panama
Canal and pretty much every one since have glided through the life
of Cecil Haynes. He was born one year before the canal was
dedicated on Aug. 15, 1914, and has worked for the Panama Canal
Commission for 71 years, starting as an office boy in 1928 ferrying
papers and filling inkwells.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the eve of the symbolic transfer of the canal, Haynes,
86, will assume a special place among the bosses at the reviewing
stand as the oldest and longest-serving worker at the canal, if not
the federal government as well.
</P>
<P>
   Honors have been coming his way for years. The small office
where he works as an inventory management specialist ordering
supplies is lined with photos of him with presidents and generals.
Last month, he was the standard-bearer at the parade celebrating
Panama's independence from Colombia in 1903. He even has his own
Coca-Cola commercial, with a lifetime supply, no less.
</P>
<P>
   The plaudits are puzzling to a man who calls himself ``a little
two-by-four'' among the VIPs. The real honors, he said, should go
the other VIPs _ Very Invisible People like his father and
thousands of fellow West Indian laborers, whose sweat and sinew
carved out the route through stone and jungle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am representing the forgotten workers,'' he said. ``They say
I'm famous. Famous for what? Did I go to the moon? No. This is for
the men who built the canal. Who did something international, with
loss of life. If I am being recognized, it is in their memory. I'm
famous for them.''
</P>
<P>
   He also recognizes them through his memories of an era when
immigrant laborers struggled through bruising days in the field and
dispiriting nights at home. While he and the other blacks lived
crowded together in small rooms they built for themselves inside
larger wooden buildings, American bureaucrats and technicians in
the Canal Zone endured a more leisurely exile with swimming pools,
maids and good schools.
</P>
<P>
   His father, James, arrived in Panama from Barbados in 1904, the
same year the Americans took over construction of the canal. Haynes
recalled stories his father told him of days when he would come
home famished and fatigued, barely able to stay awake to eat, much
less relax after wielding pickaxes and shovels through 10-hour
shifts in drenching rain or blazing sun.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes was born in Gatun City, near the man-made lake traversed
by ships, where his own childhood was humble and hard. Like many
Panamanians who saw the disparities between the Americans and the
locals, he was bothered by the imperiousness of the Americans in
the Zone, the 10-mile strip of land straddling the canal's 50-mile
route. In the Zone, American manners, laws and expectations
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to work for them and keep them in the station they were
accustomed to,'' Haynes said. ``We lived in the Zone, too, but we
were there to help them on the job and off the job. We were not
equals.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked for work when he turned 14, intent on making life
better for himself and his family. He found it as an office boy,
working for $22.50 a month. In the 1940s, he said, labor organizers
from the United States came to Panama and helped bring about better
working conditions, with increased pay and vacations. Yet, for all
the time he put into the job, he was still doing low-level clerical
work when, in 1978, his boss came by to point out that Haynes had
been on the job for a half-century.
</P>
<P>
   All those years inside an office paid off when a public affairs
officer came to him looking for a feel-good feature about his
record service. Haynes went back to his boss.
</P>
<P>
   He was jumped several pay grades, he said, and eventually
promoted to his current job. Things are better now, for himself and
his countrymen. He and his wife, who are childless, sent several
nephews to college. They have a nice home nestled on a cul-de-sac.
He spoke of the past with some reluctance, not wanting to give the
impression that he was ungrateful, but only wanting to remember men
long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think the Americans would realize that mistakes were
made,'' Haynes said. ``Had they only treated us a little better and
given us some recognition in our own country.''
</P>
<P>
   He has received more than his share of recognition from his
countrymen. He is a familiar sight in the pre-dawn hours, as he
waits for the bus to go to work each day. Strangers shout greetings
to him in the street. But he may have less visibility soon. He is
talking about retirement, a puzzlingly foreign idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The papers are in,'' he said. ``My wife wants me to retire.
The minute that comes up, she says that I'm not working anymore.
But, you know, after doing something for so long, just to break it
off like that is difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as difficult as imagining the national milestone would
ever come. He always thought the Americans would rather go to war
than to give up the canal. Now it is being handed over with a
simple ceremony that will not even be attended by President
Clinton, whom Haynes has always wanted to meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't force people to think different,'' was all he would
say the American president's absence.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes talked about his years at a desk as just as important a
contribution to building the canal as the toil of his father's
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something they helped build,'' he said. ``They were
happy and proud about it. They taught me that I should always feel
how they felt, and take as much care of it in their memory. That
remained with me as a boy. That is why I am still here today.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has had his doubts. They come to him whenever he sees the
thick-armed workers at the canal, or the road crews out in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am in an office, shuffling papers,'' he said. ``Over
the years, I came to the point where if I had to do it all over
again, I would not have worked in an office. I'd be out in the
field, where people do things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
