r f BC-KCI-GROWTH-2TAKES-KAN     12-13 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KCI-GROWTH-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KCI POISED FOR GROWTH IN PASSENGERS, AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It took nearly 10
years, but Kansas City International Airport seems to have finally
gotten over the Braniff blues.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1989 collapse of Braniff, the carrier that embarked on
building a substantial hub at KCI, crippled the airport's
operations for several years. The number of flights and passengers
at KCI was sharply reduced, and there was even some talk that
perhaps one of the airport's terminals should be closed because of
the lack of business.
</P>
<P>
   Today KCI is growing again. Passenger traffic has risen steadily
since the mid-1990s, and the number of flights at the airport is
roughly equivalent to what it was when Braniff was operating at its
peak. This year alone, KCI added nonstops to eight new
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Like KCI, airports all over the world are dealing with rising
passenger traffic. And that could lead to trouble spots. Without
significant infrastructure improvements in the next 10 years, the
nation's air traffic system faces the prospect of a sharp increase
in delays and greater backlog, said United Airlines chief James
Goodwin at an aviation conference last week.
</P>
<P>
   While the gridlock common at bigger metropolitan airports is not
a problem here, KCI faces other challenges. It still is not
operating anywhere near capacity, passengers still complain there
aren't enough food and beverage outlets, and morale problems in
recent years caused unusually high turnover at the city's aviation
department.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, aviation observers believe KCI is in good position
to continue growing in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new millennium looks good for your airport,'' said Terry
Trippler, consumer affairs expert for Onetravel.com, an online
travel service. ``You suffered in the early '90s, but the things
that have happened since are finally starting to pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   When airlines acquire more aircraft and look to add flights,
Kansas City usually is considered, one travel agent said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the radar screen, and that's good,'' said Kathy
Sudeikis, vice president of corporate relations at All About Travel
in Mission. ``It's a matter of whether airlines can make it
cost-effective to add flights here.''
</P>
<P>
   KCI is certainly on Southwest Airlines' radar screen. Southwest
has gradually expanded here and is now KCI's dominant carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest, long known as a discount carrier offering short-haul
flights, began changing its strategy several years ago. The carrier
started flying longer routes at higher prices, and Kansas City
became a market that attracted Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Southwest has eight gates and 72 daily departures at KCI,
flying to 21 cities east and west of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest's gradual growth started in 1995, when US Airways
(then known as USAir) substantially reduced its nonstop flights
from KCI. The airline eliminated direct flights to key business and
leisure destinations such as Boston, San Diego, Seattle, Orlando,
Los Angeles and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Other carriers that began filling the void left by the likes of
Braniff and US Airways were Midwest Express and Vanguard Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Midwest Express flew only to Milwaukee when it started service
at KCI in 1989. Now the carrier also offers direct flights to New
York, Boston and San Antonio. In 2000, the airline is dropping KCI
nonstops to Raleigh//Durham, N.C., but is adding service to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City-based Vanguard started operating in December 1994.
After struggling for years financially and operationally, Vanguard
has reached some semblance of stability in recent months and is
flying to key business cities that are the hubs of major carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southwest has fares lower than the majors, but it's Vanguard
that is helping keep prices down in Kansas City,'' Trippler said.
``They seem to have gotten their act together, so that bodes well
for keeping your fares down.''
</P>
<P>
   Trippler said reasonable prices alone draw companies with
offices all over the country to meet in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oftentimes, I'll hear people checking fares saying, `Have you
tried Kansas City?''' he said. ``It still has a reputation in the
travel industry for low fares.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom McKenna, assistant director of marketing for the Kansas City
Aviation Department, said KCI has a better mix of airlines now than
it did eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good balance between the (major) carriers and the
start-up or discount carriers,'' he said. ``Having the low-cost
carriers helps keep the competition going.''
</P>
<P>
   Major airlines such as American, Northwest and United fly only
to their hub cities from KCI, but that also has helped create a
balance, McKenna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airline industry has changed somewhat,'' he said. ``The
majors are now network carriers, with several hubs instead of one
fortress hub.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, each major airline flies to two or three cities (US
Airways flies to four) from KCI. McKenna said that should provide
more opportunities for international travel from KCI. For example,
McKenna said, passengers flying to London have 14 daily one-stop
options from Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the network hubs, you have greater access to the global
marketplace,'' he said. ``And you have a multiple choice of
carriers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
