<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8159 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-AINGE-AZR &LR;      12-13 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AINGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michelle Ainge got the call from her husband before he took the
Suns out for a game against the Dallas Mavericks on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, she realized just how seriously he was
contemplating the unheard of _ giving up a multimillion-dollar
guaranteed contract and abandoning a job he loves because he
believes his family needs him more than a basketball team does.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Danny Ainge did just that, stepping down 20 games
into his fourth season as the Suns head coach, despite a 13-7
record and two more years on his contract after this one.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge, 40, called it a simple choice between a profession he
loves and a family he adores more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of you might think I'm jumping ship,'' Ainge said. ``It's
been hard. I've never quit anything in my life. But I don't really
feel like I'm jumping ship. I believe I'm diving overboard to save
my family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaving a lot of very precious things behind as I dive
overboard to rescue those that mean the most to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there will be speculation that there is more to the
story. That Ainge was frustrated by a team that hasn't played as
well as many anticipated after the acquisition of Penny Hardaway.
That he was forced out. Or that there is something wrong with
somebody in his family.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Ainge said it is what her husband said it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me happy and very proud of him,'' she said. ``He's
giving his family the highest priority, and I know it's really hard
to do. I know how much he loves those guys and basketball and his
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're dying here or something. It makes a
difference to have him at home, and he doesn't want to miss this
time with his family and have regrets later.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge is the father of six children ranging in age from
4-year-old son Crew to 19-year-old daughter Ashlee.
</P>
<P>
   And Ainge, a devout Mormon who lost his own mother to a suicide
when he was a freshman at Brigham Young University, is a devoted
family man. When he took over as head coach, he encouraged players
to bring their families along on road trips whenever there was room
on the club's chartered flights. Ainge once took all six of his
kids along, and many of the team's players often had their children
with them on road trips.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge believed having the families would make it easier for
players. But this season, his own kids were growing at home without
him. And a comment from his second son, 15-year-old Tanner, struck
a chord.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my teenage boys thought that I had been distant, and I
couldn't disagree with that,'' Ainge said, pausing to compose
himself. ``It's been very difficult to find that balance as a coach
that I thought I could, because I was able to do that as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had many conversations with my wife, and she has, by the
way, never, ever pressured me into this decision. This was
something I felt was making a statement to my family _ that they're
more important to me than my career.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're as shocked as anybody that I made this decision. At
the same time, my teenaged sons and daughters and my wife are very
grateful that I made this decision for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Ainge said she and Danny Ainge had many conversations
about the impact of his job on the family, but the call Saturday
still surprised her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sensed this was serious,'' she said. ``He said, `I really
need you to think about this.' I thought, `Whew.' But I thought it
was going to be something he would think about for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ainge called a family meeting Sunday morning to discuss
his decision. And then he called Suns President Bryan Colangelo to
tell him he wanted to meet with him and Suns CEO Jerry Colangelo
that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Colangelo said he sensed something wrong in Ainge's ``body
language and facial expressions'' during the 120-115 Phoenix loss
to the Mavericks as he watched the game on television. When he
learned that Ainge wanted a meeting, he told Bryan ``he's going to
step down.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's just what Ainge did, telling the Colangelos that they
should replace him with assistant Scott Skiles and asking for an
announcement first thing Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After the Suns lost a third straight game in mid November, Jerry
Colangelo said on his weekly show on the team's flagship station,
KTAR-AM, that there needed to be ``a correction'' even after the
team had broken the skid with a victory over Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But Colangelo said at the time that he did not mean a coaching
change.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns won seven straight games, starting with the Chicago
victory. And Colangelo said Monday's coaching shake-up was not ``on
our agenda'' and intended to try and talk Ainge out of resigning
before their meeting Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unequivocably, this has nothing to do with the relationship
between Danny and this organization,'' Colangelo said. ``There's
never been any pressure on him. We all share the same commitment
and passion for winning, so it wasn't anything like that. It's the
first time in my career that I've had a situation where a coach
walked in and said, `I've had enough.' '' ``I think it's the
greatest thing he's ever done,'' said Austin Ainge, Ainge's oldest
son who is a star guard at Gilbert Highland High School and has
accepted a scholarship to BYU. ``I think it's just about the
biggest expression he could show us. He gave up the job he loves.
He gave up the money. He gave up a lot of stuff that's important to
him for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge's kids have grown up with him in the limelight, first as a
player, then a television analyst and then coach. He said he wants
his life to revolve around them now, instead of theirs revolving
around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I've never really known anything different,'' Austin
Ainge said. ``I feel like he's a great dad, and I wouldn't change
my life for anything, nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could tell something was bothering him a little bit, but I
couldn't tell this was coming. He'd come home a little frustrated
after a loss, but he always bounces back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said the decision didn't come down to underperformance
from his team. In fact, he said he would have made the same
decision if the Suns had a 17-3 record instead of 13-7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
