<HEADER>
A8163 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-POLITICS-DEBATE-HNS &LR;      12-13 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, MCCAIN MIX IT UP DURING IOWA GOP DEBATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ The leading Republican presidential
candidates, George W. Bush and John McCain, finally engaged in
rhetorical battle Monday, clashing over a range of issues during
the most animated debate so far between the GOP contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The new aggressiveness among the top contenders comes as the
primary season is fast approaching and the race is tightening with
McCain closing in on Bush, particularly in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who had been criticized for his performance in two
previous debates, came across more relaxed and more willing to mix
it up with his rivals, particularly McCain, who baited the governor
on campaign finance and ethanol subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor, who spoke of Jesus Christ as a prominent
influence in his life, played to more traditional Republican voters
who typically vote in the Iowa caucuses while McCain stressed
themes that appeal to those independent voters who make up a larger
chunk of the New Hampshire electorate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has chosen not to campaign actively in Iowa,
announced to the Des Moines audience that he was going to tell them
some things they did not want to hear and stated flatly that the
federal subsidy for ethanol _ a corn-based fuel additive _ ``is not
worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will not help the consumer,'' McCain said of a product dear
to Iowa farmers. ``Everybody here on this stage, if it wasn't for
the fact that Iowa was the first caucus state, would be sharing my
view.''
</P>
<P>
   The other candidates expressed their disagreement, including
Bush, who said: ``I support ethanol, I support ethanol strongly and
I would support ethanol whether I was here or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush defended ethanol as ``good for the air'' and a way to
reduce dependence on foreign oil.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Bush challenged McCain on taxes, claiming the Arizona
senator's tax cut plan did not help single mothers with incomes of
$40,000 _ a group the governor said would be aided by his tax
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain claimed he could tinker with his tax plan, he
quickly turned his answer into a challenge for Bush to endorse his
centerpiece campaign finance proposals, particularly the ban on
unrestricted donations to political parties, known as soft money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can commit as nominees that we will have nothing to do with
soft money. ... I hope you will make that commitment right here
tonight,'' McCain said to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be pleased to talk about it,'' Bush responded. But the
governor argued that a ban on soft money ``would hurt the
Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that elimination of soft money would still allow labor
unions, which generally support Democrats, to continue to use dues
levied on their members to pay for political campaigns against
Republicans. He called for ``paycheck protection,'' which would bar
unions from using their members' dues for political purposes
against their will.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain countered that Ronald Reagan won the presidency in
1980 when soft money did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   The two men chose different influences when the questions turned
philosophical. When asked which thinker affected him most, Bush
responded that it was Jesus Christ. Pressed to elaborate, Bush
responded, ``If they don't know, it would be hard to explain.''
</P>
<P>
   He then added, ``When you accept Jesus Christ as your savior it
changes your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, however, volunteered a decidedly less religious figure,
saying that former President Theodore Roosevelt was his hero. He
said Roosevelt had taken on some of the prominent powers of the day
and had established the national park system.
</P>
<P>
   The spirited exchanges between McCain and Bush occurred during a
90-minute forum sponsored by WHO-TV in Des Moines and MSNBC, the
cable network that aired the debate nationally. The format was far
more freewheeling, with the moderators allowing the candidates more
leeway to respond to each other and deviate from the questions to
challenge their opponents. Candidates not only responded to
questions posed by the moderators but also queried one another.
</P>
<P>
   The other candidates, magazine mogul Steve Forbes, conservative
activists Alan Keyes and Gary Bauer, and Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch,
were also aggressive in their responses.
</P>
<P>
   But Bauer and Bush mixed it up particularly sharply over
U.S.-China relations. Bauer challenged Bush for his endorsement of
U.S. trade relations with the last Communist power, saying,
``Governor Bush, I will stop allowing China to play us for
suckers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer also challenged Bush to commit to naming a running mate
who was anti-abortion, a commitment the governor has long refused
to make. Bush said he would select a vice presidential candidate
who was loyal to him and who held the same conservative principles.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Hatch referred snidely to Forbes' wealth, and his
willingness to use it for his campaign. When Hatch posed a question
to Forbes, the multimillionaire magazine mogul said, ``that means
hold onto your wallets.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch quickly responded, ``Steve, I couldn't even lift your
wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa forum was viewed as a major test for Bush, who appeared
uncomfortable and rarely deviated from his standard stump speech in
the first two face-offs with his Republican rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the Texas governor's Republican supporters conceded
that Bush, who had little previous experience debating, should have
engaged his rivals earlier in the season to gain more experience
before the primary season begins in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at the Des Moines airport, Bush was asked about his
previous debate performances, if he thought he was overly scripted
and nervous in the encounters in Arizona and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who me?'' he responded. ``What matters is how people vote.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Iowa caucuses just six weeks away on Jan. 24, Bush is
in better shape in this key Midwestern state than in the first
primary state of New Hampshire, where an aggressive campaign by
McCain has catapulted the Arizona senator ahead of Bush, according
to several new polls.
</P>
<P>
   Recent Iowa polls all give Bush a healthy lead, followed by
Forbes, who has waged a high-dollar campaign and is highly
organized in the state. But one recent poll found McCain, who has
largely written off the state, coming in third close behind Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has benefited from a plethora of positive national media
coverage and what many believe were deft performances in the first
two debates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who was scheduled to leave Des Moines right after the
debate, released two new ads Monday that highlight his prisoner of
war experience in Vietnam, including his giving a Christmas sermon
one year for fellow soldiers who were all being held captive in
Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
