<HEADLINE>
BIG BOY CHAIN IS CLOSING KC AREA AND ST. LOUIS RESTAURANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOYCE SMITH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Just nine months
after making a big splash in Kansas City with eight new
restaurants, Big Boy has closed the operations, along with 10 Big
Boys in St. Louis and one in Columbia.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elias Bros., the Warren, Mich.-based parent company of Big Boy,
blamed delays in obtaining city permits that forced them to open
months later than planned. They also had staffing problems and a
drop in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Independence's (Mo.) Big Boy restaurant is not connected with
the Michigan chain and will remain open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our start-up costs started to mount drastically; ultimately
that delayed our return on our investment,'' said Tony Michaels, a
spokesman for Elias. ``We have never run into delays anywhere close
to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Elias purchased the former Shoney's restaurants in October 1998
and began reopening them as company-owned Big Boy operations last
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Elias dealt with several cities, including Kansas City, Overland
Park, Kan., Merriam, Kan., and St. Louis. City officials said
zoning requirements were already in place because most of the
locations were being remodeled.
</P>
<P>
   The Overland Park Big Boy received its construction permit in
just two days and a health department permit in a week, according
to Tim Ryan, codes administrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``From start to finish when the permit was issued, it was 10
days. That's pretty quick for a $100,000 remodel,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said that Overland Park promised a 20-day turnaround time
for an initial plan review and that the city had created a pre-plan
review and one-stop shop, where all questions are answered in one
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having the biggest boom in our history, with nearly $700
million in construction this year,'' Ryan said. ``Even with the
workload, we still turned it around quicker than our established
time frames.''
</P>
<P>
   Merriam officials said Big Boy's plans had been quickly
approved. Independence said that the initial review had been
returned within three days in November 1998 but that three
different departments had questions. Elias did not address those
concerns until late April, and a permit was issued that day.
</P>
<P>
   Elias also blamed its area restaurant closings on falling sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales were as expected at the start, but they did trail off,''
Michaels said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also had problems finding enough help for the
restaurants. Each restaurant had 30 to 50 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoney's had some good help; if they could have kept those
workers, it would have helped,'' said Tom Rhoades of Independence's
Big Boy. ``They were closed down for several months. Finding
workers in Kansas City is tough; we're so successful because we
have experienced employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Elias' area employees were not notified in advance of the Friday
afternoon closing. Michaels said each worker later received a
personal phone call from the company.
</P>
<P>
   The stores are not expected to reopen unless a franchisee takes
over a location.
</P>
<P>
   The Independence Big Boy, which the Rhoades family opened in
1962 on U.S. 40, has complained about customer confusion since the
Michigan chain came to town, and the complaints have continued
after the closings.
</P>
<P>
   Customers are calling Rhoades' operation to ask if it has closed
and what to do about gift certificates belonging to the other Big
Boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they couldn't handle the competition,'' Rhoades said.
``We're still kicking, and hope to maintain that for many years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
