<SLUG> BC-BIZ-RATING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTREPRENEURIAL RATING SLIPS FOR KANSAS CITY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA SIZEMORE LONG  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Despite its
reputation as an entrepreneurial center, the Kansas City area is
losing out to several other cities as a good spawning ground for
small businesses, according to a research firm.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cognetics Inc., a Cambridge, Mass., company that tracks the
activities of 10 million businesses, this year lowered Kansas
City's ranking among the 50 best metropolitan areas to start and
grow a small business to No. 23 from No. 14 a year ago. Inc.
magazine is running the ranking in its December issue.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City business leaders and experts insist Kansas City is a
good place to start and grow a business.
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly 66,000 small businesses in the Kansas City
area, said Matt Gunther, the manager of small-business and
entrepreneurial programs for the Greater Kansas City Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small business is the engine that drives Kansas City,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cognetics based its rankings primarily on the number of start-up
companies reaching at least five employees in the past 10 years;
and the number of young companies _ those 10 years old or younger _
that have grown significantly in the past four years and that have
had a growth index of at least three over the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   A company's growth index is its percentage of employment growth
times its number of added employees.
</P>
<P>
   Cognetics President David Birch said there were no definitive
answers as to why certain cities have dropped in their rankings,
because many of the reasons are subjective and difficult to
measure. The report makes no specific mention of Kansas City's
strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Kansas City, other cities that showed the
sharpest one-year drop in the study were St. Louis, Milwaukee and
Greensboro, N.C. Memphis, Tenn; Baltimore; Houston; and Richmond,
Va., showed the biggest gains.
</P>
<P>
   Birch said some strong patterns had emerged that would indicate
why Kansas City, among other cities, got lower rankings.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he said, the nation's economy has shifted from an
industrial-based economy to a ``knowledge value'' economy.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, perhaps, has not moved quickly enough to meet the
challenges of a knowledge value economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you drive through Kansas City, it definitely has an
industrial flavor to it,'' Birch said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, that was essential, but not now.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he said, Kansas City lacks good research
universities and is not the air travel hub that it could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great research universities are a plus,'' Birch said. ``Places
like the University of California at Berkeley, Stanford University,
Georgia Institute of Technology _ a lot of the cities at the top of
the list have good research universities.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City International Airport is a good airport, Birch said.
``But it is not the hub it should be,'' he added. ``The knowledge
value economy travels by air.''
</P>
<P>
   To its advantage, Birch said, Kansas City does have top-rate
entrepreneurial centers, such as the Kauffman Center for
Entrepreneurial Leadership, part of the Ewing Marion Kauffman
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a fountainhead advocate for entrepreneurs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, it doesn't mean all young businesses or
entrepreneurs feel welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they part of the establishment or not?'' Birch asked.
``Ewing Kauffman certainly was, but are the small entrepreneurs?''
</P>
<P>
   Gunther, of the chamber of commerce, agrees there has been an
ongoing debate on whether small businesses are part of the larger
entrepreneurial community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most definitely they are,'' he said. ``There are a lot of
entrepreneurial programs and centers that help the small
entrepreneur be part of the establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kauffman Center for Entrepreneurial Leadership and the
chamber frequently sponsor programs, seminars and other events that
help small-business owners become part of the big picture, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And while Kansas City is not a major air travel hub, ``our
prices for air travel are among the most reasonable,'' said Pam
Whiting, director of communications for the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is equally important, if not more so, for small
businesses,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And, Gunther and Whiting said, the development of the new
Stowers Institute for Medical Research will help bring Kansas City
in league with other cities who rate for their research institutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
