<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL SKIPS PARTY CONGRESS
</P>
<P>
   Former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, under growing pressure to
disclose his role in campaign financing, missed a congress of his
Christian Democratic Party, and did not offer a reason. Last
weekend Kohl faced the first calls from his party to step down as
honorary chairman because of financing questions. The latest
accusation comes from a French businessman who says his company
gave $44 million to German parties to seal an oil deal, a
suggestion a party leader termed ``absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: ISLANDWIDE COUNCIL MEETS
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bertie Ahern of Ireland, his cabinet and the new
executive of the Northern Ireland Assembly held the first meeting
of the North-South Ministerial Council, set up by the peace
settlement to discuss issues like tourism, the environment and
trade. The two members of the Rev. Ian Paisley's hard-line
Democratic Unionist Party in the Ulster cabinet boycotted the
session.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: PREMIER TO CONFRONT PARLIAMENT
</P>
<P>
   Irritated by Socialists' threats to leave his center-left
coalition, Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said he would force a
political showdown with Parliament after it passes a budget, which
is due this month. He said that he wanted to build a government
strong enough to last until elections in 2001, and that this could
require a cabinet shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN: STIFFER TERMS FOR `HONOR' KILLINGS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate revoked a provision that allows lenient punishment,
typically three to 12 months in jail, for those who kill women
thought to have disgraced their families. The change faces
opposition in the lower house, where members say the current system
deters adultery. At least 25 women are killed each year in such
``honor crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   EAST TIMOR: PRO-INDONESIA MILITIA DISBANDS
</P>
<P>
   The leader of an anti-independence East Timorese militia, Joao
Tavares, said he had ``formally disbanded'' units that have
terrorized refugees in neighboring West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: AUSTERITY AT RAMADAN
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred protested at the office of the Jakarta city
governor to demand that all bars and nightclubs close during
Ramadan, the Muslim month of fasting, which began last week.
Reversing past policy, the government has ordered that state
schools be closed during Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: VIDEO GAMES BANNNED
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has banned six popular games throughout the
country. The prohibition follows an incident in which a student
opened fire in a movie theater in Sao Paulo, killing three people,
and said his action was inspired by the game Duke Nukem. The judge
ordered that game removed from stores, along with Blood, Doom,
Mortal Kombat, Postal and Requiem.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: PRESIDENT IN LEAD
</P>
<P>
   With the ballots half counted, President Joaquim Chissano is
leading his opponent, Afonso Dhlakama, with 53 percent to
Dhlakama's 47 percent. In Parliament, Chissano's ruling party, has
51 percent of the vote, compared with the opposition's 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   NAMIBIA: HAVEN FOR ANGOLAN TROOPS
</P>
<P>
   Angolan armed forces will be allowed to use Namibia for attacks
on rebel positions in southern Angola, the Namibian defense chief
said. For years a stronghold of the rebel group Unita, the
southeast corner of Angola has been fiercely contested recently,
with government troops making inroads.
</P>
<P>
   BOTSWANA: ISLAND WON FROM NAMIBIA
</P>
<P>
   Ending a bitter dispute, the World Court ruled that a tiny
uninhabited island between Botswana and Namibia belongs to
Botswana. The Chobe River island, known as Kasikili or Sedudu,
covers 1.4 square miles and is under water half the year.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: U.S. MISSION
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, the House minority leader, led a
congressional delegation to meet with President Thabo Mbeki and
business and political leaders here. The visit marked the last leg
of a 10-day trip to Africa, including stops in Nigeria and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
