<SLUG> BC-SANFRAN-MAYOR-1STLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEOPHYTES HELP ELECTRIFY MAYORAL RUNOFF IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Subs 9th graf to correct S.F. Chronicle poll results.) 
 (ms) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The two dozen people waiting outside Tom
Ammiano's campaign headquarters at Josie's Cabaret and Juice Joint
piled in like frantic Christmas shoppers, grabbing stacks of ``Tom
for Mayor'' and ``Make History'' bumper stickers as though they
were the last Pokemon toys on earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be 51 on the 20th and this is the first campaign
I've ever wanted to be a part of,'' said Ed McCready, a computer
graphics designer, as he plastered his clothes with yellow and
black ``Mayor Tom Ammiano'' stickers.
</P>
<P>
   It has been like this for six weeks, since Ammiano, the
president of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors, forced Mayor
Willie Brown into a runoff election on Tuesday with a last-minute
write-in campaign that captured 25 percent of the vote in a
four-way race.
</P>
<P>
   They are both liberals in one of the nation's most liberal
bastions, and both have experienced the sting of discrimination.
Brown, 65, is San Francisco's first African-American mayor, and
Ammiano, 58, would become the first openly gay mayor of a large
city if he were elected.
</P>
<P>
   But the election battle here has had little to do with race or
sexual orientation. It has been primarily about who best could
address pressing issues like housing costs, and who best symbolizes
the heart and soul of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   And by those measures, supporters of Ammiano, many of them
tenants, have sometimes seemed like zealots, registering more than
14,000 voters, plastering the city with posters and holding
fund-raising rock concerts, comedy shows and wrestling parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such an electrifying event,'' said Molly Berry, 30, a
campaign worker. ``We're open from 9 to 9, and an hour doesn't go
by without at least a dozen people coming in asking to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's supporters, on the other hand, have the money and the
clout. Indeed, to say that the race between Ammiano, a former
teacher and stand-up comic, and Brown, the former speaker of the
State Assembly and one of California's most powerful, experienced
politicians, has been a David-and-Goliath battle, only begins to
describe it.
</P>
<P>
   A poll last week by The San Francisco Chronicle showed Brown
leading Ammiano by 20 points, 49 to 29 percent, with 22 percent
undecided. Brown held an even bigger lead among older homeowners,
those most likely to vote. Still, the same newspaper's poll was off
by 14 points in predicting Ammiano's showing in the general
election on Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is taking no chances, amassing a huge campaign fund since
the general election.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six weeks, hastily formed political action
committees have spent $1.3 million on Brown's behalf. In addition,
Brown has spent $400,000 (the voluntary spending limit) from his
general campaign fund.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, political action committees have spent $4,500 on
Ammiano's behalf, and he has spent $250,000 over all.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has received endorsements from the state's political
establishment, the small but potentially influential San Francisco
Republican Party, the city's two daily newspapers and most of the
city's major labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   He has received $22,600 from a landlord's group _ sworn enemies
of Ammiano, who has declared ``war on gentrification'' _ in the
form of a contribution to a political action committee. And he
received $200,000 from the Alice B. Toklas Lesbian and Gay
Democratic Club's political action committee, which spent $175,000
on a television commercial featuring a gay couple that decides to
vote for Brown because of Ammiano's ``out-there'' tax proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, whose platform has focused on tenants' rights and on
the creation of a living wage for all workers, has been endorsed by
day laborers, advocates of tenants' rights and the Bicycle
Messengers union.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several days, the California Democratic Party has
recruited legislative staff members from Sacramento to campaign for
Brown, offering them up to four free nights at a hotel to come here
and walk the precincts. The party put $80,000 into Brown's campaign
in the November election and anticipated spending $100,000 in the
runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Ammiano's volunteers have never been involved in a
campaign; some have never voted.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, Peter Humphrey, 35, a building contractor, who
said he has held wrestling parties for fun, held a ``wrestling
ball'' for Ammiano in a dark, rented room. A referee with a
grizzled beard wearing a blond wig, shouted out points as men and
women, some dressed in 1940's swing-dance costumes, tussled with
strangers on mats. Humphrey asked for donations of $3 to $250 and
collected $391 from the 50 guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even been registered to vote in 10 years,'' said
Humphrey, wearing a red robe over his wrestling trunks. He said he
felt compelled to hold the fund-raiser, because ``it's time to look
out for the little guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
