<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-ARRESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. REPORTS ARRESTS OF TERRORISTS PLANNING NEW YEAR'S ATTACKS ON
AMERICANS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration said Monday night that
about a dozen members of a suspected terrorist operation believed
to be planning New Year's attacks on Americans around the world had
been arrested in the Middle East in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said the suspects had links to Osama
bin Laden, the Saudi-born militant who is blamed for the bombing of
two American Embassies in Africa in August 1998
</P>
<P>
   Despite the arrests, the threat remained credible enough that
the State Department issued a terrorism warning over the weekend
advising Americans to stay away from large gatherings and
celebrations in other countries during the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had ongoing intelligence and law enforcement
activities focused on bin Laden for some time,'' the administration
official said. ``We picked up some very credible information about
an operational cell, and we moved on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The official declined to give specific details about who
arrested the suspected terrorists, other than that the arrests were
made in the Middle East, and that the attacks were planned against
Americans celebrating the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon official said Monday night that the authorities
believed they know the location of the planned attacks, but the
official declined to identify the country or countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat was global,'' the administration official said.
``This is really a very sensitive, ongoing investigation. And the
threat has not ended.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department warning cautioned Americans for the period
``up to and through the beginning of the New Year and Ramadan
events and celebrations from now until January 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic holy month of Ramadan began last week.
</P>
<P>
   While the State Department has issued many similar warnings,
this one was unusual because it urged Americans to avoid large
crowds during a period in which people all over the world are
likely to gather at celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   James Foley, a State Department spokesman, said Monday that the
announcement seeks ``to let American travelers know that the U.S.
government has information, specific and credible information, that
terrorist groups have been planning terrorist actions against
American citizens and that this is a worldwide threat.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the warning was not made to prompt the cancellation
of travel plans, but that it ``is connected to the New Year
celebrations and the Ramadan period, and that therefore Americans
need to exercise caution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
