<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8177 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-LOUIMA-VOLPE-1STLD-WR     12-13 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-VOLPE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-OFFICER SENTENCED TO 30 YEARS FOR BRUTALIZING HAITIAN
IMMIGRANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS with new 3rd graf on responses to the sentencing.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT 14 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After tearfully pleading for mercy and apologizing to
his victim, Justin Volpe was sentenced Monday to 30 years in prison
for brutalizing Abner Louima in a Brooklyn police station. The
judge denounced the former police officer for an ``unusually
heinous'' crime that had harmed not only Louima but the Police
Department and society at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short of intentional murder, one cannot imagine a more
barbarous misuse of power than Volpe's,'' Judge Eugene Nickerson
said in a packed courtroom in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, as
he sentenced Volpe for a notorious act that drew national attention
and fueled angry charges of police brutality against blacks in New
York City. Louima is black, and Volpe is white.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence drew sharply mixed reactions. Federal prosecutors
said they accepted it, though they had urged the judge to impose a
life term. Volpe's lawyer and his father both called it too harsh,
while Louima's supporters insisted that it was too lenient. Calling
the sentence appropriate, Police Commissioner Howard Safir said,
``I hope this is a chapter in the history of the NYPD that is
behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   The former officer's punishment was less than the sentence of
life in prison without parole that the judge could have imposed.
Volpe, 27, could be released after 25 years if he behaves well in
prison, and with credit for the six months he served since
interrupting his trial last May to plead guilty to violating
Louima's civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe was also ordered to pay $277,495 in restitution to Louima,
although Nickerson acknowledged that he would not be able to do so.
Without explaining how he had arrived at the figure, Nickerson
directed Volpe to pay Louima $25 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe admitted that he had violently shoved a broken broomstick
into Louima's rectum in a police station bathroom, inflicting
severe internal injuries on the 32-year-old Haitian immigrant,
because he mistakenly believed that Louima had punched him hard in
the head during a street brawl, knocking him down and causing him
to fear for his life. It turned out that another man had punched
Volpe. ``However frightened and angry he was, Volpe's response was
wildly out of proportion,'' Nickerson said.
</P>
<P>
   In court Monday, Louima described the terror he felt and the
injuries he suffered on the floor of the police station bathroom
where he was assaulted in August 1997. He told the judge of the
psychological pain he later endured because Volpe and his lawyer
suggested that the injuries had come from a homosexual encounter
before his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This big lie,'' Louima said, ``has caused me and my family
incredible pain and emotional suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpe, looking pale and somewhat thinner than his hefty,
muscular figure before he was jailed, and wearing jail clothes that
included trousers that had to be rolled up at the ankles because
they were much too long, told Nickerson, ``I was and still am
ashamed and deeply regretful for what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I betrayed Abner Louima's rights, I betrayed the
city's confidence in police officers, I betrayed myself and my
partner and I betrayed my lawyer.'' The last was a reference to his
not having told his lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg, that he was guilty
until the evidence had become overwhelming at his trial.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently choking up as he stood before the bench, Volpe, who
had been on the force four years when he brutalized Louima and was
dismissed immediately after his conviction, said he had ``come to
realize that this case goes beyond me and Abner Louima.''
</P>
<P>
   Louima showed no emotion as he sat listening in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did not only hurt Abner Louima and his family, but
conjured up the worst fears in people,'' he said. ``This fear was
worse by me being a police officer.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Volpe repeated his earlier statements that another
former officer, Charles Schwarz, had been wrongly convicted by the
jury of helping to torture Louima by holding him down in the
bathroom of the 70th Precinct station house. Volpe repeated his
claim that the officer in the bathroom was Thomas Wiese. In the
past, Volpe had said that Wiese merely watched the attack with the
stick.
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor, Alan Vinegrad, maintained to the judge that
Volpe's statements exonerating Schwarz lacked credibility.
Vinegrad, chief assistant U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, previously
said that there had been more than sufficient evidence to support
the conviction of Schwarz, who faces up to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz plans to appeal his conviction, and his lawyer, Ronald
Fishetti, said Monday that the prosecution should give Volpe a
lie-detector test.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, Wiese and a third former officer, Thomas Bruder, face
trial next month on charges that they conspired to lie to
investigators to persuade them that Schwarz had not taken part in
the torture. Defense lawyers have indicated that they would call
Volpe as a witness for their clients, who deny the charge.
</P>
<P>
   In sentencing Volpe to 30 years, Nickerson reduced a finding by
the U.S. Probation Department that federal sentencing guidelines
mandated that Volpe be sentenced to life in prison without any
chance of parole.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he said, he was taking into account such factors as the
likelihood that the former police officer would have to serve much
of his sentence in ``some form of segregation'' for his own
protection from other inmates _ meaning even harsher punishment. He
lowered the finding to a guideline that called for a sentence of
between 30 years and life. He then imposed the 30 years, without
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a spokesman for the Federal Bureau of Prisons, Dan Dunne,
said that it was too early to say where Volpe would be incarcerated
or what security precautions, if any, would be taken to protect
him.
</P>
<P>
   After the sentencing, Kornberg said he would appeal. He had told
Nickerson that a 20-year-sentence would have been enough. Later he
noted to reporters outside the courthouse _ as Louima's supporters
loudly jeered him in the background _ that another police officer,
Francis Livoti, had been sentenced to seven-and-a-half years for
violating a man's civil rights by killing him with an illegal
chokehold. And Volpe's father, Robert Volpe, a retired city police
detective, said that 30 years was, in effect, as harsh as a life
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Louima said that he hoped the sentence would ``send a clear
message that no one is above the law,'' but the Rev. Al Sharpton,
the New York activist, said after leaving the courthouse that Volpe
``should have been given life.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Rodney, co-chairman of the Haitian-American Alliance,
called the sentence a ``slap on the wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   But Loretta Lynch, the interim U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, said
she accepted the 30-year term as the result of a ``very careful
balancing'' by Nickerson.
</P>
</TEXT>
