<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8183 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR &LR;      12-13 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERNIE, BERT, SIR CHARLES AND DANNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J.MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, exactly when did Danny Ainge and Charles Barkley become Big
Bird and Mr. Snuffleupagus?
</P>
<P>
   Barkley blows out his knee and Ainge resigns and suddenly their
voices take on a Muppet-like quality and they chatter on about
family and love and responsibility and I'm wondering if there's
some trend I didn't know about in which washed-up professional
athletes are building mansions on Sesame Street.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge, speaking of his children, said Monday at a news
conference at American West Arena, ``Their lives have revolved
around me for my entire career. I want my life to revolve around
them at this time in my life. It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was no better. After his career-ending injury in
Philadelphia last week, he said, ``I guess the big fella in the sky
wanted me to finish where I started.''
</P>
<P>
   He was subdued. He was respectful. He was _ Lord, no _
``inclusive''.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any sadness in my heart,'' Barkley said. ``You
guys have seen me grow from a boy to a man.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE FUN TO BE BAD
</P>
<P>
   This is the guy who once fulfilled the fantasy of every adult
male in America by slugging Bill Laimbeer. He once spit on a fan.
He vaulted over a scorer's table, breaking computers and knocking
down chairs so he could chase after an officiating crew and scream
at them.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Ainge, about whom Hakeem Olajuwon once said, ``I
know he's a dirty player. He tries to trip me when I'm running.
He's doing it where the referee can't see. But I know what he's
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   And so did the fans of opposing teams, who booed him
mercilessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothered me when it first started,'' Ainge once said. ``But
I've grown to like it.'' As did Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, at his retirement news conference, Sir Charles admitted
that he'd been in the locker room, crying.
</P>
<P>
   Over what? Being a fabulously wealthy man in his 30s who no
longer even needs to ``pretend'' to be in good shape?
</P>
<P>
   I recall a time in the mid-1990s when Ainge launched the
basketball at point-blank range directly into the cranium of Mario
Elie.
</P>
<P>
   I recall a bench-clearing brawl against Detroit in which Barkley
was the first into the fray, with Ainge right on his tail.
</P>
<P>
   Future students of the game will be able to study Ainge artfully
grabbing, bumping and shoving guys when the officials weren't
looking. Or donning an indignant, completely phony ``Who? Me?''
expression when they were.
</P>
<P>
   They will hear Barkley mock the refs who threaten him with
fines, saying, ``You can't control me with money.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, each of these individuals proved to be an
obnoxious, bullying, loudmouth. Sure, that helped the Suns win a
few games. And it certainly entertained the fans.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS SUITS THEM BOTH
</P>
<P>
   But the truth of the matter is, why squander skills like this on
the basketball court when they can be put to better use at the
statehouse?
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fritter away our time contemplating whether
Barkley's name belongs on the Ring of Honor at America West Arena,
we should take immediate steps to have him enshrined in the Dome of
Dishonor at 1700 W. Washington St.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Barkley has spoken of running for governor, but in
his native Alabama. Luckily for us, politicians outside of Arizona
are required to perform some actual work. Here, politics ``is''
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Charles would like that. During his time in Phoenix, Barkley was
the most interesting person in town. Unfortunately, this put him in
direct conflict with the second most interesting person in town,
his boss.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge got less interesting when he became a coach, but he'd
return to his old form in a job that didn't force him to suppress
his best (meaning, worst) instincts. Mayor of Phoenix, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   It's perfect. Danny would be close to his kids. His pal Chuck
would be just down the street. And the two of them could quit
whining like a couple of Elmos in Grouchland.
</P>
<P>
   In this new arena they could spit and throw elbows like the old
days. Mock the opposition. Browbeat people. And best of all, no
refs. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at &QL; 
ed.montini(at)arizonarepublic.com or at (602) 444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
