<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NUKE-SPY-NYT &LR;      12-13 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NUKE-SPY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JUSTICE AND WEN HO LEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Dec. 14:
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors say they have assembled substantial evidence
that Wen Ho Lee, formerly a scientist at the Los Alamos National
Laboratory, illegally copied and removed classified information
describing the design, construction and testing of most major
weapons in America's nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   In view of the case against Lee, his indictment last Friday
seems warranted. At least for now, he has not been charged with the
graver crime of espionage, because evidence is lacking that he
passed these stolen nuclear secrets to China or any other foreign
power.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the publicity, political pressures and accusations of
ethnic stereotyping produced by this case, it is essential that
Lee's right to a fair trial be protected.
</P>
<P>
   The government's case must be vigorously tested, even though
much of the evidence involves nuclear secrets. Federal court
procedures designed for such sensitive cases should make it
possible to explore the evidence without disclosing classified
information.
</P>
<P>
   It is also important that other investigative leads be followed
to determine whether China has obtained American nuclear secrets
and who, if anyone, should be charged with transmitting them.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is accused of transferring hundreds of files containing
nuclear weapons secrets to unclassified computers and removable
computer tapes between 1993 and 1997. Prosecutors allege that some
of those tapes have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Government investigators suspected as early as 1996 that Lee was
mishandling classified information. But for reasons not yet
adequately explained, Energy Department officials failed to remove
him from classified weapons work until late last year. He was
dismissed in March.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, Lee had become the FBI's chief suspect
in a separate, earlier case that involved the possible theft by
China of one of America's most advanced miniaturized weapons
designs, a warhead known as the W-88.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI narrowed its espionage investigation too quickly to
focus on Lee, perhaps because he is a Chinese-American, ignoring
potential suspects at other nuclear facilities where scientists
also had design information on the W-88.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Lee was not involved in giving nuclear weapons secrets
to China, the systematic copying and removal of highly classified
material he is charged with is a serious offense, carrying a
potential penalty of life imprisonment. If a fair trial establishes
his guilt, he should be punished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
