</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GAYTROOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: INVESTIGATING THE ABUSE OF GAY TROOPS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, Dec. 14 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen took the appropriate action
Monday when he ordered the Pentagon's inspector general to conduct
investigations at major military bases to determine the extent of
harassment against gays. But this emergency effort to head off
further viciousness is no long-term solution to a problem that can
only be fixed by allowing gays to serve in the armed forces on an
equal, open basis.
</P>
<P>
   The ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy was a bad compromise when
President Clinton proposed it in 1993 after Congress refused to end
the ban against gays in the military. Now, after five years in
practice, it is a proven failure, as Clinton acknowledged over the
weekend. The intent of the policy was to allow gay people to serve
if they did not disclose their sexual orientation or engage in
homosexual conduct. But the treatment of gays seems to have
worsened. In 1998, nearly twice the number of military personnel
were discharged for homosexuality as in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony at trial about the barracks atmosphere at Fort
Campbell, Ky., where a gay soldier was beaten to death with a
baseball bat, shows how vicious harassment was tolerated for months
and complaints were utterly ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Strict punishment for harassers _ before they kill _ is
obviously needed. But the deeper problem with the policy is that it
encourages anti-gay hatred. The message it sends is that gays are
threats to unit cohesion and unworthy to serve, yet they may be
tolerated so long as they remain closeted. That has proven to be a
recipe for abuse and even resulted in ouster of those who complain
of harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Until Congress and the White House replace this policy with one
that allows gays to serve openly, no amount of clarification can
ensure that gay service members will be protected from violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-99 2355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
