A8188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-TRANSIT-NYT &LR;      12-13 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TRANSIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE MIDNIGHT TRANSIT STRIKE THREAT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, Dec. 14 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a possible transit strike looming after midnight Tuesday,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is warning that a walkout would be
disastrous for New York City's residents and its economy. Strictly
speaking, Giuliani is a bystander in the labor negotiations between
the Metropolitan Transportation Authority, a state agency, and the
transit union.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor is right to step in and assert the city's interest
in a deal. As he notes, a strike would be illegal under the state's
Taylor Law, and it is irresponsible of the union to speak casually
about walking off the job in the absence of a contract. Patient
negotiating will be a more effective tactic for bus and subway
workers seeking better wages.
</P>
<P>
   The latest reports suggest some progress has been made toward
bridging the differences between the MTA and Local 100 of the
Transport Workers Union. They started far apart, however. The union
demanded a wage increase of 27 percent over three years, while the
MTA offered 9.5 percent over four years. But since the MTA agreed
to a four-year, 13 percent increase for workers on the commuter
railroads, it may find it hard not to offer the same package to
subway and bus workers in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The transit workers say they deserve generous raises because an
increase in subway and bus riders has expanded the authority's
revenues. But the extra revenues are needed to help finance the
agency's ambitious capital improvement program over the next five
years. One rule of thumb can give management some flexibility,
however. If workers are willing to increase their productivity
through staffing changes and greater flexibility in assignments,
the agency should be willing to share some of the savings in the
form of increased wages.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem in the current talks is that the union has been
split by bitter internal battles in recent years. Its president,
Willie James, barely won re-election a year ago, and a militant
faction known as New Directions has demanded and won a place at the
bargaining table. Giuliani says this group is responsible for
misleading members into thinking that a strike would not
necessarily be illegal, and would actually help their cause. In
reality, a strike could destroy the union's finances.
</P>
<P>
   By definition there is no good time for a transit strike. But at
the height of a holiday season, and with a millennium New Year's
celebration approaching, a strike right now would be especially
destructive. In most public employee unions, and indeed most
private unions, there is a tradition that talks can continue
without a contract, while wages and benefits continue at the
current level.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides should pledge immediately that if the deadline passes
without a contract at midnight Tuesday night, they will keep
talking and bring in an outside mediator if necessary to avert a
strike. Millions of New Yorkers are counting on them to behave
responsibly. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
