<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-13 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8190 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SCHOOL-ATTENDANCE-     12-13 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-ATTENDANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI SAYS SCHOOLS PADDED ATTENDANCE TO GET MORE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Delivering another blow to Schools Chancellor Rudy
Crew and the New York City Board of Education, Gov. George Pataki
released a report Monday accusing the city's schools of
deliberately inflating attendance figures to get much more state
aid than they deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki attacked the board of education in particular, saying he
agreed with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani that it should be abolished. But
while Pataki said a state investigation had uncovered ``patterns of
widespread, systemic abuse'' in attendance, the report contained no
information about which schools were padding their attendance
rolls, who was responsible and exactly how much the alleged scam
was costing the state.
</P>
<P>
   The state is embroiled in a lawsuit that accuses Pataki and the
legislature of shortchanging New York City schools in distributing
state aid, and Crew joined lawyers for the plaintiffs Monday in
charging that Pataki had issued the report primarily to bolster the
state's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani praised the report, saying, ``What they have
illustrated, aside from the dramatic facts that are in there, is
that this system does not work.''
</P>
<P>
   The report infuriated Crew, who called it a ``political hack
job'' and ``flimsy counterfeit report'' by a governor who wanted to
hide the fact that he had not furnished enough state aid. Crew that
his staff had been working to fix problems with the attendance
system for years but had been hampered by the state's refusal to
provide sufficient funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised that the report contained so little
substance,'' Crew said. ``It is a blatantly political document that
sheds no new light on issues this system has been working toward
improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew, who in the next few weeks is expected to decide whether to
remain on the job for at least another year, said in an interview
that Pataki was trying to ``run me out of here.'' The report on
attendance focuses on general weaknesses in the board of
education's system for tabulating attendance in high schools, and
highlights a handful of particularly disturbing examples. In one
case, a student died unexpectedly in the summer of 1998 but was
kept on his high school's rolls for the entire 1998-99 school year
and was even issued report cards.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that even if city schools were inflating
attendance figures for only 3 percent of students, it could cost
the state $300 million over five years. The state gave New York
City schools $2.2 billion in operating aid this year.
</P>
<P>
   The report complained that the board of education's attendance
system automatically presumed students were present unless they
were marked absent on scan sheets, which are fed into computers
that tabulate daily systemwide attendance. The investigators
charged that at least 40,000 attendance sheets had not been fed
into the computer system since September, meaning that there have
been more than a million instances in which a student was
automatically counted as present.
</P>
<P>
   But board officials said state education policy required them to
take attendance that way. Chad Vignola, counsel to Crew, said the
board had increased monitoring of schools in recent years to ensure
that they report attendance figures honestly. He acknowledged that
the high school attendance system allowed for inaccuracies, but
said the board would replace it early next year with a system that
matched those at the elementary and middle school levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
